{Hello, my dear chess friend! 😊 I’m Angelika Valkova, and I’m thrilled to welcome you to my course, A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4. If you are reading this introduction, that means you’ve already joined the course, and for that, I’m truly grateful! I hope you’ll enjoy this journey as much as I did while creating it. This repertoire was developed together with my friend and coach, GM Gyula Pap, and we’ve put a lot of effort into making it a practical, fighting, and well-structured guide for improving your play against 1.e4. This course is very personal to me because, for most of my career, I played the French and Caro-Kann—openings that often lead to solid, closed structures. But I always felt a gap in my understanding when it came to open positions, and I struggled to navigate those dynamically. That’s why, together with my coach, we decided to expand my repertoire and embrace the Open Game 1.e4 e5. I started playing it myself in OTB tournaments, and this course reflects not just theoretical preparation but real tournament-tested ideas. So, why focus on 1.e4 e5? Because there are almost no top players who haven’t played this at some point in their career. It’s a fundamental part of chess understanding, and the ideas behind it are essential for growth. With this course, we wanted to create a fighting repertoire, full of practical surprises that allow you to set the tone of the game rather than reacting to your opponent’s preparation. For example, against sharp gambits like the King’s Gambit, Vienna, Danish, or Belgrade Gambit, we won’t simply enter wild complications. Instead, we’ll look for solid and counterattacking approaches that put pressure on White. Like my previous course, 1.d4 for Ambitious Chess Improvers, this repertoire is not about tricky but dubious gambits. Every line is backed by deep analysis—so even if you played against Stockfish, the positions would still be solid and playable. But of course, most of us won’t be facing Stockfish! 😉 The other important goal of this course is not just learning moves but also learning different types of positions. I love playing with space and sacrifices, and this opening allows for dynamic ideas right out of the opening! I highly recommend studying this course like a book—going through the material in order. The Quickstarter Chapters are a great way to begin because they introduce the most open and direct positions first, giving you a strong foundation before tackling more complex lines. The course also includes a Priority Lines section, carefully selected by my coach. This section expands on the Quickstarter material with more details and variations. Moreover, it highlights the critical and the most challenging lines. Even if a certain variation feels unlikely to appear in your games, don’t skip it! Every line you study expands your chess knowledge and helps you recognize patterns over the board. Once you’re familiar with the Quickstarters, you can start practicing the repertoire. Through your games, you’ll see which chapters require more attention, depending on what you face most often. While the course can be studied through text, the video content adds an extra layer of understanding. In the videos, I explain the key concepts in a more interactive way, breaking down longer variations, showing alternative ideas, and adding extra explanations that didn’t make it into the text. For example, some lines might be too long to include in the written course, but in the video version, I go through them in detail, explaining key turning points and hidden traps. I truly believe that mastering 1.e4 e5 will transform your chess understanding. It’s not always easy—some tough games are unavoidable—but if you treat those as learning experiences, you will improve significantly. I encourage you to engage with the course forum! There, you can ask questions, share your experiences, and discuss ideas with me and other students. I’ll be checking in regularly, and I’m happy to help! Now, it’s time to begin your journey. Let’s dive into the course and start improving together! See you in the next chapter! 😊} 1. Z0 *

