1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5] Welcome to the first Quickstarter Guide of the course! In this chapter, we are going to look at some romantic, aggressive, and sometimes just rare lines against our repertoire. These lines are especially common in online games, where the shorter time control can make these variations even more dangerous! In general, I would advise you to start with this chapter since here you can learn the most about the essence of 1.e4 e5 and what open game means regarding material, tempo, and development. In the upcoming variations, you can learn: • How to play against the rare 2.Qh5 move. • How to avoid easily the sharp lines of the Danish Gambit. • What are the correct reactions against White's various queen moves in the Centre Game. • What to do if the Bishop's Opening is not transposing to the Italian. • How to surprise White in the Vienna Gambit as early as move 5! • How to counter the King's Gambit with the rare Cunningham Defense. • Why the extra tempo isn't so important in the Reversed Philidor. • In which way you can get a sharp attacking position against the Ponziani.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
