1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening, since it controls the centre in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play. This response to 1.e4 is called the Open Game and you'll see in this chapter that in how many different ways the game can open up and get sharp very quickly.} 2. Qh5 $6 {[%csl Re5,Rf7][%cal Yh5e5,Yh5f7] What could be more aggressive than trying to deliver the Scholar's Mate? 🙂However, the objective value of the move is dubious, since it immediately breaks one of the main opening principles - don't bring your queen into the game too early!} Nc6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6e5] Normal developing move, which is also supporting the [e5]-pawn.} 3. Bc4 {[%cal Rc4f7,Rh5f7] And here we are! Only one move away from the defeat and getting the Scholar's Mate! Fortunately though, this repertoire is not for hyperbullet time control, and in longer time controls where we don't have to premove, we can handle this straightforward threat quite easily. What is important to notice here is that White's main point attack is the [f7]-pawn. This will happen in many other lines as well, and it is logical, since the pawn is not going to go backwards from [e5].} g6 {Addressing the threat with a tempo and forcing the queen to a worse square.} 4. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3f7] Still hoping for a quick win!} Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rc6d4,Rd4c2,Rd4f3,Gg1f3] Defending against the threat with a developing move. Here you already can see the problems with White's opening. The queen already made two moves, and what it is doing currently is nothing else but occupying the [f3]-square, which would be ideal for the [g1]-knight! It is an additional problem that Black is also threatening to win a tempo with ...[Nd4]!} 5. c3 $6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4] Even though White is covering the [d4]-square, they are not doing it with a developing move.} (5. Qb3 $2 {Being too stubborn can lead to huge problems!} Nd4 $1 {Taking with the bishop on [f7] is not the same as with the queen!} 6. Bxf7+ Ke7 7. Qc4 b5 $1 {-+ White's queen has to leave the diagonal, Black is just taking on [f7] with a winning position.}) (5. Ne2 {This is objectively a better and more common move in OTB chess than 5.c3, but there is a rare move which can pretty much take away all the possible danger from the position.} Na5 $1 {White can't escape the trade with their most active piece, the light-squared bishop.} 6. Bb3 Nxb3 7. axb3 d5 {⩱ Black is already better with the bishop pair and more space in the centre.}) 5... Bg7 {Of course, once ...[g6] is played, the bishop belongs to the long diagonal.} 6. d3 Na5 $1 {[%cal Yc4f7] This is my favourite idea in such positions. Without the [c4]-bishop, White's position is simply toothless.} 7. Bb5 {It is logical to try to keep it on the board, but what we see again, is that White is wasting all the time in the world by moving around with their queen and bishop.} O-O {[%csl Ye8][%cal Gd7d5,Yb5e8] In general it is pretty good to castle, but it is even better when the move prepares ...[d5]. 🙂} 8. Bg5 ({White wants to stop d5.} 8. Ne2 $6 {This is too slow.} d5 $1 {∓ Black has the better development, the centre, and also threats like ... [Bg4] for example.}) 8... h6 $1 {In general, it is a very useful move for Black to include, as you will see later in many lines. There are two points behind it. The obvious one is that the bishop can't use the [c1]-[h6] diagonal anymore and well, there is not much on the [e1]-[h4] one. The second one is that when Black wants to strike in the centre with ...[d5], it is possible to completely break the pin with ...[g5] before.} 9. Bh4 g5 $1 {In this particular line it is not much later that the pin is broken and ...[d5] is coming. 🙂} 10. Bg3 {It seems like that White is gaining a tempo on the [e5]-pawn.} d5 $1 {With such an advantage in the development it is not even a question that we are going for complications and want to open the position as much as possible. This is a very important theme in 1.e4 [e5] openings. Once you are better developed, don't worry too much about the material, but try to open the position as quickly as possible, especially if the opponent's king is in the centre!} 11. Bxe5 c6 {Forcing the bishop to a worse square, so after the trade on [e4], our knight can join the game via [c4].} 12. Ba4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Nc4 {[%csl Rb2,Re5][%cal Yc4b2,Yc4e5] Here is the knight! Attacking on [b2] and also on [e5].} 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 $1 {Don't be afraid to trade queens, even when you are down some material! Let's do some math! [Qh5]-[Qf3]-[Qxf6] and [Bg5]-[Bh4]-[Bg3]-[Bxe5]-[Bxf6] that is 8 moves for White, and [Nf6] + [Qxf6], so 2 moves for Black. This is the trade which is currently happening on [f6]! This is 6!!! tempos altogether. If you look at White's position, you can see it. 🙂} 15. Qxf6 Bxf6 {[%cal Rc4b2]} 16. b4 a5 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rg1,Rh1][%cal Rf6a1,Ra5b4] The rook is joining the game, White's position is simply lost here.} *

