1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening, since it controls the centre in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play. This response to 1.e4 is called the Open Game and you'll see in this chapter that in how many different ways the game can open up and get sharp very quickly.} 2. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] This is the so-called MacLeod Attack. White's idea is to push for [d4] and then recapture with the pawn, which sounds like a very sensible plan. The problem is that this idea is too slow, and while White is preparing for it, Black can already strike in the centre!} d5 $1 {There is no reason for delaying this move. The pawn on [c3] stands very well from our perspective, once the queen arrives on [d5], it can't be kicked out with the move [Nc3].} 3. exd5 Qxd5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb1c3]} 4. d4 (4. Nf3 $6 {This is not a great move, since Black can win quite a few tempi against the knight.} e4 $1 5. Nd4 Nc6 $1 6. Nxc6 Qxc6 {White's knight made 3 moves, while Black's only 1! Black already has a very good position, developing the light-squared bishop followed by ... [O-O-O] can be next.}) 4... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4,Ye5d4] Just continuing the development, we shouldn't rush taking on [d4], since it would only open the [c3]-square for the knight.} 5. Be3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4]} (5. Nf3 {The other way to defend the pawn.} Bf5 $1 {The same way as against 5.Be3!} 6. Be2 O-O-O {Black has a strong pressure on [d4] with easy development.}) 5... Bf5 $1 {[%cal Ye5d4,Yf5b1,Yc3d4,Ya1b1,Rf8b4] A rare move, but looks very promising. The idea is that we will eventually take on [d4], and before the knight could come to [c3], we are taking it on [b1], and follow it up with a very unpleasant ...[Bb4]+ !} 6. Nf3 (6. c4 $4 {Kicking the queen and trying to gain some stability in the centre is backfiring here.} Qa5+ 7. Bd2 Qb6 {-+ The pawns on [b2] and [d4] are hanging, White's position is just hopeless.}) 6... exd4 {Executing the idea behind our previous move.} 7. cxd4 (7. Nxd4 {Objectively this is probably a better recapture, but White's position remains tough.} O-O-O {⩱ Black just has the better development in a symmetrical structure.}) 7... Bxb1 $1 {Step 2 accomplished!} 8. Qxb1 Bb4+ {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Yb4e1] White can't really block this check, because then the [d4]-pawn is falling, so the king has to move.} 9. Kd1 O-O-O $17 {We have the better structure and White's king is in the centre. We can't ask more from the opening.} *

