1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening, since it controls the centre in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play. This response to 1.e4 is called the Open Game and you'll see in this chapter that in how many different ways the game can open up and get sharp very quickly.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 (2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. d3.} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. f4 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc1f4]} ({I didn't find the name of this variation, but it looks like that White wants to play the King's Gambit, without it being a gambit. 🙂 Instead,} 3. Nc3 {or 3.Nf3 are more common, but those are just leading to some other lines which I'll show later.}) 3... exf4 {In general, on [f4] we have the two standard options, taking and playing ...[d5] or playing ...[d5] right away. I analysed both, both look fine, but the text move seems to be more ambitious.} 4. Bxf4 d5 $1 {This move is sacrificing a pawn, but this is how you play against inferior lines or moves in 1.e4 e5. You open the position, develop quickly, castle and then good things happen.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bxc7 $6 {It is not good, but the only move which is worth analysing, otherwise White is simply worse.} (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Be2 O-O-O 8. O-O h5 {⩱ Black has a nice advantage here, with clear ideas and more active pieces. ...[Bc5]-...[Nge7] and then ...[f6]-...[g5] is one possible way to continue the game.}) 6... Nf6 {Development is more important than the pawn!} 7. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4e1]} 8. Qd2 Qc5 {[%cal Rf6d5] Preparing the [d5]-square for the knight!} 9. O-O-O Nd5 {[%cal Rd5c3,Rd5c7] Thanks to that loose bishop on [c7], this is already a double attack. Even if we look at this position more generally, the pawn which is missing just opens the file for Black's rooks.} 10. Qe2+ {This was White's idea; otherwise, the position would be just lost. Now at least the [c3]-knight is not pinned anymore.} Be6 {One more developing move.} 11. Ne4 {It almost looks like White is surviving, since next move the bishop could retreat if the queen moved backwards.} Qe3+ $1 {This unexpected trade wins material for Black.} 12. Qxe3 Nxe3 $17 {[%csl Rd1,Re1][%cal Yb4e1,Ye3d1] The [d1] rook is trapped. Black has a clear advantage.} *

