1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4] White wanted to play a gambit, but all of a sudden their queen is in the centre now, giving potentially some nice tempi for Black's development.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5,Re4][%cal Gf6d5,Yf6e4] Excellent developing move, protecting and attacking at the same time, and also forcing White to make a decision with the [e4]-pawn.} 5. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg5d8] This is the most common choice for White, and it is the most logical as well, developing a piece and solving the issue of the [e4]-pawn by tactical means. The only problem with the move is, that Black has a very strong reply. 🙂} (5. exd5 {The most sober choice in the position, White has to admit that they has no opening advantage whatsoever, and just try to equalise the position.} Qxd5 6. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black has zero problems and a slightly better development.}) (5. e5 $2 {A very common move in online games, but it is very bad.} Ne4 {...[Bc5] is a huge threat now!} 6. Be3 Bc5 7. Qd3 Nc6 {⩱ Now you can see the problems with that ambitious 5. e5 move. Black is simply developing and attacking that loose pawn.}) 5... Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Yd5e4,Gf8c5,Yf1b5]} 6. e5 {Ambitious, but White doesn't have pieces to support this ambition.} (6. exd5 Bc5 {The speed of development is the key factor in this position.} 7. Bxf6 {If not this but any queen move, then ...[O-O] and ...[Re8]+ are coming, and White will have very serious problems with finishing the development, and it is not even a question whether they can keep the extra pawn or not. Not. 🙂} Qxf6 $1 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {⩱ Black has many threats (... [Nxd5], ...[Ne4]/...[Ng4]) and will easily regain the missing pawn.}) 6... Bc5 $1 7. Bxf6 (7. Qf4 {doesn't help, because after} Qe7 $1 8. Nf3 h6 $1 9. Bxf6 gxf6 {-+ White is losing the [e5]-pawn.}) 7... gxf6 8. Qxd5 c6 {Winning one more tempo on White's only developed piece.} 9. Qd2 Qe7 $17 {[%cal Rd7e5,Ye8c8,Yc8f5,Yc8g4] We will probably take with the knight on [e5], then develop the [c8]-bishop and castle long with a huge advantage, thanks to our dominating bishops and much better development.} *

