1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. exd5 {This is by far the main move and the one which the aggressive players will choose.} Qxd5 5. cxd4 Nc6 {Black has very easy development in this position. The only issue is our queen on [d5]; we would obviously prefer a knight there, but okay, there is no reason to complain.} 6. Nf3 {This is the correct way to protect the pawn on [d4]. White is also getting closer to castling.} Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4d1,Yc6d4]} 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get a much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} (7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Qc4 {is just a different move order to reach the main line.}) 7... Bb4+ {Black is making standard developing moves.} (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 $4 {This is not so good. 🙂} 9. Bxc6+ {+-}) 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position, we made all the logical developing moves, but now surprisingly Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $3 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square, and if it goes away we have to count on [d5]!. And if we take on [c3] at some moment instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} 9. Bxf3 Qc4 $1 {This is the surprising square, where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight. This position is more often reached via the 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 exd4 4.c3 d5 move order, so it will be examined a little bit further in the Quickstarter about the Scotch.} *

