1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Bc4 {This is sometimes called the Centre Gambit, although it is just a semi-official name at best. It is not too bad, and again gives us the possibility to transpose into more well-known lines at some moment, or try to punish it. Similarly to the concept which I used before, if there is no big upside, I'll try to cut the workload and transpose.} Nc6 (3... Nf6 {would be the way to try and "punish" this line, but it is too much work for too little gain.}) 4. c3 $6 {If White doesn't want to transpose, but it is just very bad.} (4. Nf3 Nf6 $1 {Just transposes to the Scotch Quickstarter.}) 4... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yf6e4] The pawn is hanging on [e4], and it can't be even pushed forward.} 5. cxd4 Nxe4 {White is just down a pawn for no compensation at all, but the next move will just make things worse.} 6. Bxf7+ $2 {Trying to win back the pawn, but it doesn't work out well.} Kxf7 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qd5+ Kg7 9. Qxe4 Bb4+ $19 {...[Re8] and [Re1]+ will clinch the win for Black.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Romantic Lines"]
[Black "Centre Game 4.Qa4/4.Qd3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C22"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[GameId "2160376105639439"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qa4 $6 {White is pretty much playing a reversed Scandinavian with an extra tempo. How bad can it be? Well, reversed openings are very often nothing special, and if you are familiar a little bit with the Scandinavian, you may know that Black most of the time plays with ...[e6] which corresponds to [e3] here to block the bishop's attack on the [f7] or here on the [f2]-square. Here it will not be possible.} (4. Qd3 {A rare move, with the point that it is not closing the bishop on [c1], unlike the main line 4. Qe3, but it allows immediate equality.} d5 $5 {This move is played even more rarely, only once OTB. 🙂 It pretty much solves all the opening problems. The point is that since White most likely will take on [d5], the knight can come to [b4], with not only attacking on [d5], but also on [c2].} 5. exd5 Nb4 6. Qe2+ Qe7 {Black is easily winning back the [d5]-pawn with an equal position.}) 4... Bc5 {[%cal Rc5f2] The bishop is immediately targeting the weakened [f2]-square.} 5. Nf3 d6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Rd7a4] Continuing normal development, with the plan of playing ...[Bd7] in the future.} 6. Nc3 (6. Bg5 Nge7 $1 {is a typical move, and then the pin can be easily stopped with ...f6 .}) 6... Nge7 $1 {This is the main idea to know in this line, it is better to put the knight to [e7], so [Bg5] will not be uncomfortable at all, because Black can break the pin with ...[f6] anytime.} 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O a6 $1 {[%cal Rb7b5] After finishing the development, we can start asking unpleasant questions to White's queen.} 9. Qc4 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge7g6,Yg8h8,Yf7f5,Ya8e8] Black has a much easier position here, with moves like ...[Qd7], ...[Rae8] , ...[Kh8], ...[Ng6] and eventually ...[f5] coming up.} *

