1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qc4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4]} ({A somewhat similar move to} 4. Qd3 {, White is trying to find a better place for the queen than [e3], but [c4] also gives a strange impression, it would be rather the square for the bishop in an ideal world.}) 4... Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Already threatening with ...[d5]!} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Yc3d5] Pretty much the only move for White, in order to stop ...[d5].} Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb4e1,Gd7d5] Pinning the knight, therefore ...[d5] is a threat again!} 6. Bd2 {The fight continues, White breaks the pin, so ...[d5] is stopped again.} O-O 7. O-O-O a5 {[%csl Gb4,Rc4][%cal Ga5b4,Gc6e5,Ge5c4]} ({The two main moves in the position are} 7... Re8 {and 7...d6 . However, I like this move better, with the goal to find out where White's queen will eventually land. Once it is clear, sometimes we can play without ...[Re8] or ...[d6].}) 8. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4,Yg2g4,Yg4g5] This is very logical, White is supporting the [e4]-pawn and preparing to push [g4]-[g5].} Ne5 $1 {Decision time for White, they can keep the queen in the centre, potentially exposed to further tempo moves, or retreat to the more passive [e2]-square.} 9. Qe2 (9. Qd4 d6 $1 {In this case, playing with ...[Re8] wouldn't make much sense, since the e-pawn is protected and the queen is not on [e2], so you can see why it is possible to win some time with 7...a5.}) 9... Re8 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ye8e2,Gd7d5] Once the queen is on [e2], this move comes with great power, and we can be pretty ambitious by trying to play ...[d5] at once without losing time with ...[d6]} 10. Qf2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ye8e1] Going away from the e-file is very logical, and takes away the power of ...[d5] for now.} (10. f4 {White doesn't have enough pieces out, so this move will turn out to be too weakening.} Ng6 11. e5 d6 $1 {And White can't keep their centre together.} 12. Nf3 dxe5 13. fxe5 Bg4 {∓ The [e5]-pawn is very weak.}) 10... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5] We insist on playing with ...[d5]! And we also have to be very fast, because White is ready to start a kingside offensive with [g4]-[g5].} 11. g4 d5 $1 {Against the flank attack the best antidote is to counter in the centre!} 12. g5 d4 $1 {This intermediate move is the key of our concept, and we are doing very well according to my analyses.} 13. Nce2 d3 $1 ({Again a counterattack! It has to be said, that according to the engine,} 13... Nxf3 $1 {is even stronger, but the complications are hair-raising.}) 14. gxf6 dxe2 15. Bxe2 Qxf6 $15 {We can soon start an attack on the queenside, but blockading White's hanging pawns with ...[Ng6] also looks very tempting.} *

