1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3]} Nf6 5. e5 Ng4 {[%csl Re3,Re5][%cal Yg4e3,Yg4e5]} 6. Qe4 {This is much more popular than 6.Qe2, but it is not better at all. :} Ngxe5 $1 7. f4 {White is winning the piece, but Black will get at least 2 pawns and a huge lead in the development for it.} d5 {A nice tempo on the queen.} 8. Qe3 d4 {One more tempo!} 9. Qe4 $2 {This is a mistake, but much more common than [Qe2].} (9. Qe2 Bb4+ {Black is doing extremely well, ...[O-O] is coming followed by ...[Re8], and it is not only compensation but a much better position for Black with a dangerous attack.} 10. c3 Bg4 11. Qd2 Qe7 $1 {The difference in development is decisive.} 12. fxe5 dxc3 13. Nxc3 Rd8 {-+ And White is getting mated or losing a lot of material.}) 9... Qh4+ $1 {Black has a way to prevent losing the knight.} 10. g3 Qg4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yf4e5,Yg4e4,Gg4g6]} 11. Bh3 Qg6 12. Qe2 Bxh3 13. Nxh3 Qg4 $19 {Black is keeping the extra pawn.} *

