1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Yf8b4] A quite refined way of playing, White obviously wants to play with [Nc3], but with this move order they prevent Black to develop the bishop to its most ideal square, [b4], or at least make it less tempting, since there will be no pin now.} Be7 {[%cal Gd7d5] This looks like a pretty good solution, we want to play ...[d5] now, which is quite tough to prevent.} 6. Nc3 (6. c4 $6 {Way too ambitious, White is quite behind in the development for playing like this.} O-O 7. Nc3 Nb4 $1 {Black has to act quickly, this move fits that concept.} 8. O-O-O c6 {With the plan of ...[d5] and opening up the position. White's king is not very safe on the queenside.}) 6... d5 $1 {As usual, if this move is good, Black should have zero problems!} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 {The best move from White, the goal is to achieve equality and not advantage.} (8. Qg3 {This is played pretty frequently, but White already should think about equality, and can't afford moving their queen for the third time.} Ncb4 $1 {White has serious problems with the protection of the [c2]-pawn, since the logical} 9. O-O-O {is pretty much losing right away.} Nxc3 $1 10. bxc3 Nxa2+ 11. Kb2 Nxc3 {-+ White can only take with the king on [c3], but that also doesn't lead to anything good after ...[Bf6]+.}) 8... Qxd5 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ye1c1]} 9. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ge2c3,Gc3a2,Rc3d5] The knight is coming to [c3], to stabilise White's queenside.} (9. Nf3 $6 {Such a normal looking move is already giving Black a serious advantage.} Bf5 {∓ Black finished the development with a tempo, and White has huge problems with protecting the pawn on [c2] and completing the development.}) 9... Bf5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rf5c2] Continuing the development and putting some slight pressure on White.} 10. Nc3 Qd4 {Pretty much every queen move is decent, I like this one, because White can't really trade, since that invites ...[Nxd4] and there are again problems with the [c2]-pawn.} 11. O-O-O O-O-O {The position is equal, if White is not careful we can have ...[Nb4] ideas in the future and gain the upper hand.} *

