1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 {The main and most obvious move for White by far.} Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. f3 $6 {[%csl Re3,Ge4][%cal Gf3e4] This move is asking for ...[d5] to be played!} d5 $1 {Challenge accepted! White has problems with their queen on the e-file.} 9. Qf2 dxe4 {Now, White has to show what they have for allowing ...[d5]-...[dxe4].} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Rd1d8]} ({This is the best way to use the discovered attack on our queen.} 10. Nxe4 {Gives very easy game for Black.} Nxe4 11. fxe4 Bg4 12. Nf3 Qf6 {⩱ Black has the better structure and White has no attack whatsoever.}) 10... Bd7 $1 {Not the most obvious move, but a very important one! Many people went wrong at this moment, which is not so surprising, since this move is basically sacrificing a piece.} 11. Nd5 {[%cal Rg5f6,Rd5f6] More dangerous than accepting the piece sacrifice! White has pretty serious threats on [f6], so this is one of the positions where it is pretty useful to know the theory. 🙂} (11. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 $1 12. Rxd7 Bxc3 13. bxc3 {and here both} e3 {and 13...Qxc3 are winning attacks for Black. 13...e3 14.Qe1 Qe6 -+}) 11... e3 $1 {A very strong intermediate move!} 12. Qh4 Bd2+ $1 {[%csl Rd1] Closing out the rook from the game helps a lot with the defence!} 13. Kb1 Bf5 $1 {[%cal Yf1d3,Gf5c2] One more important move! Preventing [Bd3] and also attacking on [c2], plus helping with the defense in the form of protecting [h7]. Also, if needed, we can play ...[Bg6].} 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxf6 Qd6 $19 {[%cal Gd6f8,Yh4h6] Only move because we have to meet [Qh6] with ...[Qf8]. But this was White's only threat, Black is much better, we can play ...[Nb4] next and White doesn't really have many defensive ideas.} *

