1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 {The main and most obvious move for White by far.} Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Bc4 {The second most popular move in the position, White stops ...[d5] and we also can't take on [e4] for free.} d6 ({The most ambitious move for Black.} 8... Bxc3 {doesn't quite win a pawn.} 9. Bxc3 Nxe4 10. Qf4 $1 Re7 11. Bxf7+ Rxf7 12. Qxe4 {The position is more or less equal.}) 9. f3 {The most common move for White, but somewhat slow, and it is Black whose attack can be more dangerous after a few preparatory moves.} Ne5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Re5c4] Gaining a tempo on the strong bishop is a good start!} 10. Bb3 a5 {[%cal Rb7b5,Ra5a4] Black is the first to start attacking! The ideas with ...[a4] or ...[b5] are already in the air!} 11. a3 (11. a4 {White is trying to completely stop our play, but it is not so easy.} c6 {Preparing the pawn sacrifice with ...[b5]!} 12. Kb1 b5 13. axb5 a4 {Black's attack is extremely dangerous, the files are opening up on the queenside, while at the same time nothing is happening on the kingside.}) 11... Bc5 {Obviously, we are not going to trade this strong bishop on [c3].} 12. Qe1 b5 $1 {Whether White takes on [b5] or not, the files are opening up and Black has great chances for a successful attack.} *

