1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit with} Nc6 {.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 {The main and most obvious move for White by far.} Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Qg3 {The main line, White is sacrificing a pawn, and in return hopes for quick development, connected with some threats against our king.} Nxe4 {The theory supports this move for Black.} 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. c3 {[%cal Gf1d3] White wants to avoid further trades and wins a tempo on the bishop.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gh2h4,Re7h4,Gg1f3] Not only stopping White's [h4]-move, but the bishop itself wants to go to [h4] many times, because the [g3]-square is pretty ideal for the queen, and once it gets attacked, it probably has to go [f3], where originally the knight would like to go.} 11. Bd3 {White is continuing to develop with a tempo.} Bh4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge4e8,Rg3f3] Opening the way back for the rook, and forcing the queen to take away the [f3]-square from the knight.} 12. Qf3 Re8 $17 {[%cal Gd7d6,Rc6e5] White doesn't really have anything for the missing pawn. Black is currently threatening with ...[Ne5], and also can easily continue the development with ...[d6].} *

