[GameId "2160376105930263"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after 2.Nf3 Nf6. Since that it is not a part of this course, starting with this move and not} 2. Nf3 {is not problematic for us, and often can lead to some transpositions.}) 2... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. Nf3 {This is quite an unbelievable move order to me, but it happens quite a lot in online chess and also OTB.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Quickstarter.}) ({4.e5 d5! Important move, but Black is already better after this with ...[Ne4] to follow! 4.c3 Nc6! was already shown as the 'Centre Gambit'.} 3. Nc3 {doesn't have much of an independent value, White can decide where to transpose after} Nc6 4. d3 Bb4) {4.Nf3 Nxe4!} 3... Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Rd7d5] There is no reason not to take this pawn since it is even coming with the threat of ...[d5].} ({Only if you really like the Italian Game, then I suggest you play} 3... Nc6 {instead. But yeah, even then probably take the pawn. 🙂}) 4. Nxe5 (4. Bxf7+ $4 {Just losing, but was tried in many games.} Kxf7 5. Nxe5+ Kg8 $1 {The king is safe on [g8].} 6. Qf3 Nf6 {-+ Black is winning with the extra piece.}) (4. Nc3 {Practically speaking, this is definitely the best try for White. It is called the Boden-Kieseritzky Gambit, but we don't really have to take on [c3] right away, which is good but a little bit messy. Instead, we can play} Nc6 $1 {and just transpose back to a position we can get via the classical Italian Game move order 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.Nc3 Nxe4 , or via the Four Knights Opening, 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bc4 Nxe4 . You can find it in the Scotch Quickstarter.}) 4... d5 $1 {A huge tempo for the development.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3f7]} (5. Nxf7 $4 Qe7 {-+ With the threat of ...[Nc3]+ is the easiest way to win for Black.}) (5. Bb3 $4 {The most common move in the position just gives up material.} Qg5 {∓ Double attack on [e5] and [g2].}) 5... Be6 6. d4 f6 $1 {Basically forcing an endgame, where Black will play with the pair of bishops.} 7. Nd3 dxc4 8. Qxe4 Qd5 9. Qxd5 Bxd5 10. Nf4 Bf7 $15 {[%csl Gf7,Gf8] ...[Nc6] and ...[O-O-O] are our next moves, it is at least a slight edge for Black because of the bishops, but the computer is even more optimistic.} *

