1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after 2.Nf3 Nf6. Since that it is not a part of this course, starting with this move and not} 2. Nf3 {is not problematic for us, and often can lead to some transpositions.}) 2... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} (4. c3 $6 {Too slow, and most likely will lead to a good version of the Italian Game for Black.} d5 $1 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And the move 6.c3?! is completely harmless in the Italian Game.}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} ({Instead,} 4... Na5 {or 4...Bc5 are also good lines for Black.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Yd2b4] White is breaking the pin, so ...[d5] is not working for now.} (5. Bg5 {Very common, but not particularly dangerous. The move fights against ...[d5], but the pin can be broken easily.} h6 $1 6. Bh4 g5 $1 {We haven't castled short yet, so this way of breaking the pin is completely without any risk.} 7. Bg3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 {Black has managed to play ...[d5] and has a great position. The king should castle long in this variation.}) 5... Bxc3 $1 {Certainly not the only move, but regarding our concept, it is pretty much a must.} (5... O-O 6. Nge2 $1 {The knight is ready to recapture on [c3], and it will not be possible to go ...[d5] for a while.}) 6. Bxc3 O-O {[%cal Yd7d5]} ({I like this move order better, playing} 6... d5 {immediately would allow White to play} 7. Bb5 $1 {, which is a little bit annoying.}) 7. Ne2 (7. Nf3 d5 $1 {Works here as well, since White can't win the pawn on [e5], because Black would pin with ...[Re8].} 8. exd5 Nxd5) 7... d5 $1 {There is no need to wait with this move anymore.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Ge5] We reached the position what we wanted, Black has a space advantage in the centre with the pawn on [e5], but White has the pair of bishops, so the game is about even.} 9. O-O Be6 $10 {Black is comfortably equal here, now the threat is to take on [c3] followed by ...[Bxc4], and in case White prevents it, Black can continue with ...[Qd6] and ...[Rad8].} *

