1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after 2.Nf3 Nf6. Since that it is not a part of this course, starting with this move and not} 2. Nf3 {is not problematic for us, and often can lead to some transpositions.}) 2... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} (4. c3 $6 {Too slow, and most likely will lead to a good version of the Italian Game for Black.} d5 $1 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And the move 6.c3?! is completely harmless in the Italian Game.}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} ({Instead,} 4... Na5 {or 4...Bc5 are also good lines for Black.}) 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f4] The most common move. White is already protecting the knight on [c3], and leaves the way open for the f-pawn.} d5 {We don't have to change anything in our plans, this move works well.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Yf3g5,Yg5e6] Developing and keeping the tension in centre. Our bishop is very comfortable on [e6], since we don't have to worry about the [Ng5] idea.} 8. Bxd5 {[%cal Gf2f4] Surprising move at first sight, but it is with a very concrete idea, White can only play for [f4] by taking the knight first.} (8. Nxd5 $6 {Only leads to exchanges.} Bxd5 9. Bxd5 Qxd5 {Black is already slightly more comfortable with more space in the centre.}) (8. Ne4 O-O 9. N2g3 {White really wants to play [Ng5], and it is a serious threat now, since the bishop has only one square available, [c8], which is not fantastic. (( 9.Ng5 Bg4 This is fine for Black.))} Be7 $1 {⩱ The bishop was not doing anything on [b4] anymore, and with this move we don't have to settle for ...[f6], but we can be ambitious and try to play for ...[f5]!}) (8. f4 $2 {doesn't work yet.} Nxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Bc5+ {with trade on [c4] next. 9.Nxc3 Qd4+! 10.Kh1 Bxc4 11.dxc4 Qxc4 12.fxe5 Bxc3 13.bxc3 O-O ∓ White has an awful position with 4 weak pawns.}) 8... Bxd5 9. f4 f6 $1 {A very strong move, which only got popular in the last few years. The main idea is to stay flexible, since castling long can be a much better option in many of the positions.} 10. fxe5 (10. f5 $2 {This is not good, since Black will castle long and even keep the bishop pair, so White will have no attack on the kingside for sure. 🙂} Bf7 $1 11. Kh1 Qd7 {∓ With ...[O-O-O] next, Black is much better.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxd5 (11. d4 Ng6 $1 {The knight has to cover the [f4]-square, so after the trade on [d5], White can't win a tempo with [Nf4].}) 11... Qxd5 12. c3 {[%cal Gb4d6,Yd5d7] This is the precise move order for White, since after ...[Bd6] the queen will not be able to retreat to [d7].} (12. Nf4 Qd7 13. c3 Bd6 14. d4 O-O-O $1 {Black was doing really well in the game Andreikin-Giri.}) 12... Bd6 13. Nf4 Qf7 {[%csl Gf7] Fortunately, the [f7]-square is also pretty nice for the queen. 🙂} 14. d4 O-O-O $1 {[%cal Rd6c5,Rd4e5,Yd8d1] An important trick in this variation!} 15. Qa4 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Yd4e5,Ga4a7] Even after this move, the knight on [e5] is not really hanging} a6 $1 {The last difficult move!} 16. dxe5 Bc5+ $1 {[%csl Rf1]} 17. Kh1 fxe5 $15 {[%cal Rf7f1,Ye5f4] Black is taking back the material with a slightly better position.} *

