[White "Quickstarter Guide: Romantic Lines"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit 5.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C29"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376106053146"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! As it was mentioned before, against [f4], Black either takes and goes for ...[d5] or plays ...[d5] right away.} ({In this particular case} 3... exf4 {can be answered by} 4. e5 $1 {which is a huge tempo for White.}) 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Yd2d4,Rb4c3,Re4c3] We kind of lost a tempo with ...[Bc5], but now we get it back by attacking [c3].} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4d2] Introducing the great threat of [Nxe4], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. a3 {White wants to clarify the situation and does not mind having pawns doubled on the c-file, hoping that this will only strengthen the center. In theory this seems like a good idea, but let's see how it plays out in practice.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gc3d4]} Nc6 10. Bd3 Bg4 {[%csl Gc6,Rd2,Ge4,Gg4] Our minor pieces are simply fantastic here, which cannot be said of the bishop on [d2]. It is also remarkable that once White has managed to stabilize the dark squares, Black plays on the light squares.} 11. O-O {Sets up a brilliant trap!} c4 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3] Fixing the weaknesses on the c-file, and forcing White's bishop to a more passive square.} (11... cxd4 $2 {Already makes White's structure much better, but of course Black wants to take a pawn.} 12. cxd4 Nxd4 $4 13. Nxd4 $1 {Refutes the whole idea.} Bxd1 14. Bb5+ Kf8 15. Ne6+ Ke7 16. Nxd8 {+-}) 12. Be2 O-O $15 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yd8a5,Yf7f6,Re4c3,Ra5c3] The position somewhat resembles a French, and a brilliant one for Black! The [c8] bishop is doing a great job, and we can play standard ideas like ...[Qa5] and attack the pawns on the queen's side or play with ...[f6] and undermine White's center.} *

