1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! As it was mentioned before, against [f4], Black either takes and goes for ...[d5] or plays ...[d5] right away.} ({In this particular case} 3... exf4 {can be answered by} 4. e5 $1 {which is a huge tempo for White.}) 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Yd2d4,Rb4c3,Re4c3] We kind of lost a tempo with ...[Bc5], but now we get it back by attacking [c3].} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4d2] Introducing the great threat of [Nxe4], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. Bb5+ {The most popular move, but White is struggling here as well.} (8. Nxe4 $6 {In online games this move is quite popular, but White is in trouble here.} dxe4 9. Bxb4 cxb4 10. Bb5+ Nc6 $1 11. d5 {White has to try this move, since 11.Ng1 is not very tempting.} exf3 12. dxc6 f2+ $1 {With ...[Qb6] coming against both [Kf1] and [Kxf2], White is in trouble.}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O O-O {[%csl Gc6,Rd4,Re5] The [c6]-knight is unpinned, so White must once again solve problems with their centre.} 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 (11. bxc3 $6 c4 $1 {Basically forcing an opposite-coloured bishop game, where our bishop will be superior.} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {∓ With ...[Bf5]-...[Rb8] and ...[Qa5] to follow, we have easy play against White's weak queenside pawn, while White... has pretty much no play at all.}) 11... Nxc3 {That knight for that bishop??!! Well, Black had other good moves too, but this just guarantees a risk-free edge, so why not?} 12. bxc3 c4 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6e7,Ya7a6,Yb7b5] The bishop is in a big danger, so White must trade.} 13. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Gc8f5,Gd8e7,Re7a3,Rf5c2] White's knight has no good square, while our bishop comes to [f5], combined with ...[Qe7]-...[Rab8]-...[Rb2], and White really struggles to hold the pawns on the queenside.} *

