1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! As it was mentioned before, against [f4], Black either takes and goes for ...[d5] or plays ...[d5] right away.} ({In this particular case} 3... exf4 {can be answered by} 4. e5 $1 {which is a huge tempo for White.}) 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rf3e4,Yd8h4,Gg2g3] This move is taking over as a main line in recent years, White is challenging the [e4]-knight right away, and also prepares against ...[Qh4]+, since it can be answered simply by [g3] now.} Be6 $5 ({Black has 3 main choices in this position instead of this move,} 5... Nc6 {, 5...Nxc3 and the machine's favourite, 5...f5 . All are perfectly playable, but the text move gives White immediate practical problems, and it is also important, that the move is pretty much unknown, I found only 6 games in the database with it. It is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5.Qf3, and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 {⩱ The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qa4+ {Pretty logical move from White, going away from the attack with a tempo.} (8. Qg4 $6 {This is not a good square for the queen, since Black can attack it with atempo, and it is not protecting [e5] either.} Nc6 9. Bb5 h5 $1 {Black is also opening up the rook with this tempo.} 10. Qg3 {The queen has to protect the [g2]-pawn, but also has to defend against ...[Qh4]+.} h4 11. Qg4 Rh6 $1 {White is in danger. ...[Rg6] is coming next.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5] Bringing a new piece into the game is more important now than gaining another tempo.} 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {[%cal Gd2d4,Yd5f3,Ye2f3] Both sides developed normally in the last couple of moves, and now White wants to play [d4], even if it means that they have to give back the pawn, but they will gain the pair of bishops in return.} Bc5+ 12. Kh1 (12. d4 $2 {Unfortunately for White, this is a double pawn sacrifice now. 🙂} Nxd4 $1 13. Nxd4 Bc6 {-+ We are taking on [d4] and then on [e5], winning a pawn.}) 12... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Re5] Stopping [d4] with this little tactical trick gives Black the better chances with the active bishops.} 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 {We are collecting the pawn on [e5] in the next move, and then just bring our pieces to the open e-file.} (13... Bxd4 {Also note,} 14. Qxd4 $4 {blunders the queen to} Bxg2+ {+ -+}) *

