1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4]} d5 {The only good move for Black! As it was mentioned before, against [f4], Black either takes and goes for ...[d5] or plays ...[d5] right away.} ({In this particular case} 3... exf4 {can be answered by} 4. e5 $1 {which is a huge tempo for White.}) 4. fxe5 Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4]} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rf3e4,Yd8h4,Gg2g3]} Be6 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5.Qf3, and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 {⩱ The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4]} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gf4e5,Yf4h4,Gg1f3] Looks like the best square for the queen to me; it supports [e5], helps with [Nf3], and also covers the [h4]-square, so Black's queen can't give an annoying check there.} (8. Qe3 {Besides the main line, this move also keeps the [e5]-pawn protected and prepares for [Nf3]. There is one problem, though: it is not covering [h4]-anymore.} Qh4+ $1 {Pretty much at least equalises on the spot for Black.} 9. Qf2 Qxf2+ 10. Kxf2 Nc6 {⩱ Not only is the [e5]-pawn a problem for White here, but after ...[Nb4], it is also very difficult to do anything with the [c2]-pawn! 9.Qg3 Qe4+ Instead, trading on [g3] is also completely fine for Black. 10.Ne2 Nc6! With at least equal chances since White can't keep the extra pawn. The only thing to avoid is 10...Qxc2?? since that would allow 11.Nc3 , and not only is the bishop hanging, but [Bd3] is a threat as well.}) 8... Nc6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yc6e5,Yc6b4,Rb4c2] The knight is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn, but the idea of playing ...[Nb4] is also very unpleasant for White.} 9. c3 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4][%cal Yc3b4,Yc3d4] A logical move, preventing both ... [Nb4] and ...[Nd4], but it is also a little bit slow, considering that Black is already ahead in the development, and White is yet to develop a minor piece.} (9. d4 {allows} Nb4 $1 {when White already has to find} 10. Kd1 $1 {, since if the queen were to protect the pawn on [c2], it would allow either ...[Be4] or ...[Qh4]+! After the king moves, Black's compensation is obvious, and there are some nice lines after} g5 $1) 9... Be7 10. d4 {Everything looks nice and protected for White, but now comes Black's counterplay.} f6 $1 {Opening up the position with such an advantage in the development is very logical.} 11. e6 $1 {Only move for White!} (11. exf6 $2 {It is not good to open the e-file without any development.} Bxf6 12. Bd2 O-O {∓ ...[Re8] is coming next, while if White would castle long, then the [a2]-pawn is hanging.}) 11... Bxe6 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ye8c8] The position is around equal, but it still looks much easier to play with Black, we can play ...[Qd7], castle long, and then start pushing the h and g-pawns on the kingside, especially if White is castling there.} *

