1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4]} d5 {The only good move for Black! As it was mentioned before, against [f4], Black either takes and goes for ...[d5] or plays ...[d5] right away.} ({In this particular case} 3... exf4 {can be answered by} 4. e5 $1 {which is a huge tempo for White.}) 4. fxe5 Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4]} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rf3e4,Yd8h4,Gg2g3]} Be6 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5.Qf3, and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 {⩱ The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4]} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gf4e5,Yf4h4,Gg1f3] Looks like the best square for the queen to me; it supports [e5], helps with [Nf3], and also covers the [h4]-square, so Black's queen can't give an annoying check there.} (8. Qe3 {Besides the main line, this move also keeps the [e5]-pawn protected and prepares for [Nf3]. There is one problem, though: it is not covering [h4]-anymore.} Qh4+ $1 {Pretty much at least equalises on the spot for Black.} 9. Qf2 Qxf2+ 10. Kxf2 Nc6 {⩱ Not only is the [e5]-pawn a problem for White here, but after ...[Nb4], it is also very difficult to do anything with the [c2]-pawn! 9.Qg3 Qe4+ Instead, trading on [g3] is also completely fine for Black. 10.Ne2 Nc6! With at least equal chances since White can't keep the extra pawn. The only thing to avoid is 10...Qxc2?? since that would allow 11.Nc3 , and not only is the bishop hanging, but [Bd3] is a threat as well.}) 8... Nc6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yc6e5,Yc6b4,Rb4c2]} 9. Nf3 {The most human move, but White already has to be really careful if Black plays correctly here.} Be7 {[%cal Rg7g5,Rg5g4,Ge8g8] Obviously, one of the ideas of the move is to castle, but it also introduces the [g5]-[g4] idea, which is very easy to overlook.} 10. Bb5 $1 (10. Be2 {This move was played in the game Escalante Ramirez-Burke, Dallas 2022, and here, instead of the game continuation, which was ...[O-O], Black could have played even more aggressively.} g5 $1 11. Qg3 h5 {Both ... [h4] and ...[g4] are a threat, so White's next move is pretty much forced, to slow down our pawns.} 12. h3 f5 {∞ Black has huge compensation for the missing pawn.}) 10... O-O 11. Bxc6 $1 {Not an easy move to make, but it is the correct way for White.} (11. O-O $6 {allows} Nb4 $1 12. Ne1 f6 $1 {And Black is clearly better, as White is not ready for the opening up of the game.}) 11... Bxc6 12. O-O f6 $1 {Opening the position for our bishops and rook on [f8].} 13. d4 fxe5 14. Qxe5 Qd7 {[%cal Gd7g4,Ga8e8,Ge7d6,Ge7f6,Rf6d4] Black has a lot of ideas here, basically taking on [f3] and then ...[Bf6] is always an option just to regain the pawn, but keeping the pressure looks even more promising, and we can do that by playing moves like ...[Rae8]-...[Bd6]-...[Qg4]. If everything fails, it will be equal, but White has to be a very good defender for the next few moves.} *

