1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. g3 {This is the Mieses variation; White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally, it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play; it is no different here; Black has quite a few reliable lines.} Bc5 {One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-...[d5].} 5. Nf3 {White is attacking on [e5], and changes the normal setup with [Nge2] in order to stop or delay Black's idea of ...[c6]-...[d5].} d5 $1 {White's plan was a complete failure, ...[d5] works even without ...[c6] in this position.} 6. exd5 {This is the only question White can ask.} (6. Nxe5 $2 dxe4 {∓ White's knight on [e5] is extremely loose.}) 6... e4 $1 {This is the point! The [f3]-knight is struggling to find a good square.} 7. Ng1 {Not ideal, but the alternatives are not better.} (7. Ng5 $2 Bg4 $1 {The knight on [g5] can easily get into trouble.} 8. Ne2 Re8 $1 {It is really difficult to make moves with White here.} 9. h3 $2 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 h6 $1 {Winning the knight on [g5].} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 f5 {-+}) 7... c6 $1 {Excellent move! White lost a lot of time, so we are playing with force here.} 8. d4 $1 {White has to speed up the development in order to avoid a quick loss.} (8. dxc6 $2 Qd4 9. Qe2 Nxc6 {-+ White can hardly move, and ideas like ...[Nb4] and ...[Bg4] are coming, White is already lost according to the engine.}) 8... Bb4 9. dxc6 Nxc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Recapturing and developing with a tempo!} 10. Nge2 Bg4 {[%cal Rg4d1,Rb4e1] Pinning White from both sides.} 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qc8 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Yh2h3,Yc8h3,Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Gf6d5,Gf8e8] With huge positional compensation, we just prevented [h3] and our next moves are ...[Re8]-...[Nd5]-...[Na5]-...[Nc4], occupying all the nice squares with our knights.} *

