1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3.f4 in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. g3.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?.} 3. g3 Bc5 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-...[d5].} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3] The main line. White wants to finish the regular setup of this variation.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Yc6d5] The most ambitious plan for Black, we want to take back on [d5] with a pawn and not with a piece!} 6. O-O (6. d4 {Not really a good idea with the king still in the centre.} exd4 7. Nxd4 d5 8. exd5 Bg4 $1 9. Nde2 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 cxd5 11. Qxd5 Nd7 {∞ White's position is very difficult; their king is staying in the centre for a while.}) 6... d5 7. exd5 {The only way for White.} (7. d3 $6 {Too passive, allows Black to have a good position in many different ways.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. dxe4 a5 {⩱ The endgame is very pleasant, but if you want, you can keep the queens on the board with 9...[Qe7]. We will play ... [Be6] and ...[Na6] next, and White is just struggling with the knight on [e2] and with the light-squared bishop.}) 7... cxd5 8. d4 $1 {Just like this! Otherwise, White just gave up the centre for no reason.} exd4 9. Nxd4 {Everything looks pretty good for White; they managed to castle and blockade our isolated pawn on [d5], and they are ready to develop the dark-squared bishop in the next move.} Bg4 $1 {The key move of the whole variation. We have to provoke some weaknesses or gain some time and try to create active play.} 10. Qd3 (10. f3 $6 {this is the weakening move we were looking for when playing ...[Bg4].} Bd7 {⩱ White weakened the [g1]-[a7] diagonal, the [e3]-square, and closed the bishop on [g2]. With ...[Nc6] and ...[Qb6] to follow, we can put huge pressure on the [d4]-square and all of a sudden it is a very nice IQP-position for Black.}) 10... Bxd4 {[%cal Gb8c6,Yd5d4] Another very important move! Black is giving up the bishop pair in order to speed up the development and make the IQP mobile.} 11. Qxd4 Nc6 {The saying that the queen is the worst blockader is shown here immediately; once it is attacked, it has to go away immediately, and then the IQP can go forward.} 12. Qf4 {This is not a good square for the queen because it blocks the [c1]-bishop's way, but it is nevertheless a somewhat tricky option for White.} (12. Qa4 d4 $1 {There is no need to wait; we can achieve a great position after this move.} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Re8 {⩱ We are improving our position with every move, which can't be said about White since we are keeping busy our opponent with one-move threats.}) 12... Qd7 $1 {[%cal Yd5d4,Gg4h3,Gh3g2] Protecting the bishop, so making ...[d4] available again, and also introducing the ...[Bh3]-...[Bxg2] plan, trading White's most active piece.} (12... d4 $6 {is the move White was waiting for!} 13. Ne4 $1 {Because the queen kept attacking the [g4]-bishop, now we are going to lose the bishop, and be slightly worse.} Nxe4 14. Qxg4 {⩲}) 13. Bd2 {Not a very nice square, but White wants to finish the development somehow.} Rfd8 {...[d4] was already possible, but since White can't prevent it anyway, first, we are activating the rooks.} 14. Rfe1 Rac8 {[%cal Gh7h6,Rd5d4] We can even play ...[h6] next, just to open the back rank and then ...[d4] when it looks the most unpleasant for White.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
