[GameId "2160376106315297"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7]} ({The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. It is not a surprise that this move and} 3. Nf3 {are much more popular than everything else, since allowing ...[Qh4]+, which would force the king to [e2], is not really approved by modern engines and general opening principles.}) 3... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Yc3d5] The main move by far, White is protecting the pawn on [e4], and at the same time also controlling the crucial [d5]-square.} (4. e5 {as in many other different opening lines, it is met by} d5 $1) 4... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Rb4c3,Yf6e4,Gd7d5] A logical developing move, challenging the [c3]-knight and therefore renewing the pressure on the [e4] and [d5]-squares.} ({However, it is just the second most popular one, far behind the also very logical} 4... c6 {. After analysing these options, I didn't find significant difference in their objective value, so I decided to recommend the one which is less explored.}) 5. e5 {This looks like the most challenging move for Black.} (5. Nge2 d5 $1 6. exd5 {White should take with the pawn and not with a piece, since that would open the queen's way to [h4] after trading the [f6]-knight.} f3 $1 {Seriously weakening White's kingside structure and king itself.} 7. gxf3 Nbd7 {∞ Normally White would like to achieve something like this in the King's Gambit, give up some material and attack, but here it is exactly the opposite.}) (5. d3 $2 {This is popular in online games, but it is extremely bad, since it makes ...[d5] so much easier to achieve for Black.} O-O {Basically ...[d5] comes against everything in the next move and Black is clearly better.}) 5... d5 $1 {Just like this! Otherwise, we would be even in trouble.} 6. Bb5+ (6. Bb5+ {The critical test of the variation. Black normally plays} c6 {here, but after} 7. exf6 cxb5 8. fxg7 Rg8 9. Nf3 {White seems to have the advantage, because our pawn structure is less than ideal on the queenside.}) ({•} 6. exf6 $2 {This is really bad.} dxc4 7. fxg7 Rg8 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O Rxg7 {∓ White has lost the bishop pair and the centre and the previous moves. Black will castle long, and is very close to winning.}) ({•} 6. Bb3 $6 Ne4 $1 {White is not in time to take on [d5], because ...[Qh4]+ is a threat.} 7. Nf3 c6 {⩱ Black is comfortably better here, the [b3]-bishop is blocked out of the game.}) 6... Nfd7 $1 {This rare move seems to work very well though! There are some okay, rather a lot of complications, but the machine prefers Black everywhere.} 7. Nxd5 {The only question. Otherwise, Black plays ...[c6] and solidifies the position.} Ba5 {[%cal Rc7c6,Rc6b5,Rc6d5,Gd8h4] The main threat is ...[c6], but ...[Qh4]+ is also in the air. The position is pretty much completely unexplored, there were only 3 OTB games from here on.} 8. Nxf4 {This is the most human move, and the engine's top choice also, but it is not challenging for Black at all.} c6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd7e5] Black is regaining the pawn, with a comfortable position.} 9. Be2 Nxe5 10. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Gd2d4]} c5 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8c6] Not allowing [d4] for White. Black will play ...[Nbc6] or ...[O-O] next and have a nice position.} *

