[PlyCount "18"]
[GameId "2160376106393123"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] This is the main line by far, controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+. Against every other move Black can give the unpleasant check on [h4] and the quickly open the position against White's strangely placed king.} (4. d4 Bh4+ $1) (4. Nc3 Bh4+ $1) 4... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[d5] to follow up ...[Bh4]+ are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 {One of the rare cases when Black can't reply with ...[d5] to this move, since the e-pawn could take two pieces now.} Ne4 $5 {[%cal Re7h4,Gd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe Variation. We are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. O-O {This is the main move by far, and it is really disliked by the computer!} (6. d3 d5 $1 {This is the move to know! The trade would be of course beneficial for Black, and in case the bishop moves away, ...[Bh4]+ is already strong, since the [f7]-square is covered. (( 6...Bh4+ 7.Ke2 Nf2 8.Qd2! Nxh1 9.Qxf4= ∞ This is how the King's Gambit should be played! Down a full rook, the king is in the centre, but White is doing pretty well according to the engine. 🙂))} 7. Bb3 Bh4+ 8. Kf1 Nc5 $1 {The last important move, White had one more trick. } 9. Bxf4 Nxb3 10. axb3 O-O {⩱ If White allows, then we will retreat with the bishop to [e7], but in either case, we will play ... [Nc6]-...[Bg4], putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn, and if White can somehow protect it, we can think about opening up the position with ...[f6].}) 6... d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Yc8g4] Getting some control in the centre with a tempo, and also opening the [c8]-bishop and protecting the [e4]-knight along the way.} 7. exd6 {Hard to say what is the best move for White, but this is the most often played one. At the same time I believe we can already be very happy about the outcome of the opening, the only potential issue, the risky placement of the [e4]-knight is solved, and we will have a knight on [d6] instead of [h5]. A pretty nice upgrade to many of the other lines of the King's Gambit.} ({•} 7. Bb3 $6 {This move also solves the problem with the [c5]-knight, since we can just take this bishop, and keep the extra pawn with ...[g5].} Nc5 8. d4 Nxb3 9. axb3 g5 {∓ White has nothing here, the centre is closed, and our light-squared bishop is very strong.}) 7... Nxd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Rd6c4]} 8. Bb3 Nc6 $1 {I found this move to be the most precise here. The position is good anyways, but it is good to keep the option of ...[O-O-O] and keep White guessing how to develop their play.} 9. d4 g5 $17 {We have a clear extra pawn and a very solid position. It is hard to see from where White's compensation is coming from.} *

