[Black "Reversed Philidor with Be2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376106417700"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. Be2 d5 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] This is the standard move order for White to play the reversed Philidor.} (5. exd5 {This is pretty much the Antoshin Variation of the Philidor Defence, with reversed colours. White will have less space in the centre, but they want to compensate it by attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nxd5 6. O-O Bd6 $1 {This is roughly the only move to know theoretically speaking. Since we know that White's only effective idea is to attack the [e5]-pawn, it looks reasonable to develop the bishop to this square and not to [e7].} 7. Re1 O-O {Black can't complain about the outcome of the opening with more space in the centre.}) 5... Bc5 {The standard square for the bishop in the reversed Philidor.} 6. O-O (6. c3 {Whenever White plays this move, you should just prevent ...[b4]!} a5 $1) 6... O-O 7. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White wants to play [b4], so Black's move shouldn't come as a surprise!} a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5b4,Gc5b6,Gb6a7] Of course, taking away the [b4]-move and making the diagonal longer for the bishop.} 8. b3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gc1b2,Gb3b4] This is the most common move, White is playing for [a3]-[Bb2] and then [b4].} ({•} 8. a3 $6 a4 $1 {That's why the immediate [a3] is inaccurate, now White can't really make progress on the queenside.}) 8... Bg4 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb2c3,Yd5d4,Yg4f3] With their previous move, White weakened their dark squares, especially [c3]. It makes our ...[d4] idea much stronger because the [c3]-pawn last lost its support. The move...[Bg4] looks to increase Black's dark-squared control by looking to trade the bishop for a knight. In this way, white will only have two minor pieces capable of defending the dark squares, and black will have three.} 9. Bb2 Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3,Gd4] Continuing the fight for the [d4]-square and for the dark squares, in general.} 10. Bxf3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rf3] The [f3]-bishop is very bad, so basically we have a 3 vs 2 fight regarding the minor pieces for the [d4]-square.} 11. c4 {[%csl Rb2,Rd2,Rf3] White is not allowing Black to use the [d4]-square, but this move will not improve their own minor pieces.} a4 $1 {[%csl Ga8] Immediately starting active play on the queenside!} 12. bxa4 Qe7 {White is strategically pretty much lost, they have no play, while Black will just double on the a-file, with the goal of collecting both a-pawns from White.} *

