[Black "Reversed Philidor with Bg2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160376106446373"]

1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. g3 (4. Nc3 d5 {And we are transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) 4... d5 {Of course, there is no reason not to play this move.} 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 $6 {This is pretty bad, since Black can already close the diagonal where White wants to put its bishop.} dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Bc5 {⩱}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2b7,Ge1g1,Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] This is the starting position of the 'Richard Rapport Variation'. You can already see a huge upgrade from the regular Philidor setups, that the bishop is on [g2], much more active than on [e2], and it will be also much easier for White to attack the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] Only the 5th move according to popularity, but theory is not yet well-developed in this area. The goal is obvious, we don't want to have any issues with the [e5]-pawn in the future.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge1e5] Putting some pressure on the e-pawn, but it is well-protected.} Bf5 $1 {This is the square I like the most for the bishop in these variations. On [e6] it would be in the way of the rook protecting the [e5]-pawn and also exposed to [Ng5] jumps, while on [g4] White could challenge it with [h3]. On [f5] it is very flexible at the moment.} 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a5 {[%cal Ya5b4] White is looking for some play, so why to allow [b4]?} 10. Nbd2 Qd7 11. Nc4 Rfe8 {The position is certainly playable, but Black by no means is worse here. I like this position with the space advantage, and we still have many improving moves to make, such as ...[h6], ...[a4] or ...[Rad8]. It is also worth mentioning that once our queen is on [d7], ...[Bg4] becomes a serious idea, since White can't challenge it with [h3] anymore, and otherwise the pin can be unpleasant.} *

