1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Bb5 $2 {This line is just bad, but the game is getting very sharp, so Black has to know what to do.} (4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Bf5 {was already mentioned in this QS as the 2.c3 line.}) 4... dxe4 $1 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Re5c6,Gb5e8]} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5]} ({Even though the most frequently played} 5... Qd5 {is also better for Black, there is no way that we should avoid a winning line, even if it is messy.}) 6. Qa4 {[%cal Rb5c6,Ra4c6,Re5c6] White is making the threats on [c6] stronger.} (6. d4 Qxg2 7. Rf1 Bd6 $1 {The first key move of the line, we don't have to be afraid of [Nxc6].} 8. Nxc6 Bd7 $1 {And the second key move! White's position is very bad, because of the weak kingside.} 9. Qa4 a6 $1 {-+ We are not threatening to take anything, but White simply can't move. Eventually, Black is playing ...[Rc8] or ...[Ne7] and wins back material.}) (6. Bxc6+ $2 {This is really bad and very common in online chess.} bxc6 {Now White has to find} 7. Qa4 $1 {just to transpose to the line with 6.Qa4. Everything else is much worse.} Qxg2) (6. Nxc6 $2 {The easiest for Black, there is nothing to know here.} Qxb5 $1 7. Nd4 Qg5 8. g3 Bg4 {-+ White has a horrible position with many weak squares.}) 6... Qxg2 $1 {Black is accepting the challenge, since we have very strong threats on the kingside as well!} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ {Like there are 2 different boards, White is taking everything on the queenside and Black on the kingside, whose strategy is going to succeed?} Kd8 9. Rf1 Bh3 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rg2f1]} 10. Qxa8+ Ke7 11. Kd1 {White's king is running away from the checkmate.} (11. Nc6+ {is a funny line.} Kf6 12. Qd8+ Kg6 13. Ne5+ Kh5 {-+ The king is finally safe from checks, and Black can start collecting material.}) 11... Qxf1+ 12. Kc2 {[%cal Ra8e4] Now the [e4]-pawn is hanging, and our bishop is not doing much on [h3] anyway.} Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4,Ye4e3,Yf5c2] Protecting [e4], and creating the threat to play ...[e3]+ at any moment.} 13. Qd5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd5f7] Qxf7 is a serious threat, but the king can take care of it by himself. 🙂} (13. Nc6+ Kf6 14. Qd8+ Kg6 15. Ne5+ Kh5 {Black's king is safe on [h5]!} 16. Qxf8 e3+ $1 17. d3 e2 {-+}) 13... Kf6 $1 14. Nd7+ (14. Qxf7+ Kxe5 15. Qxf8 Qd3+ {is checkmate in a few moves.}) 14... Bxd7 15. Qxd7 Bd6 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yd7d3] Cutting the queen from the [d3]-square will lead to a painful ...[Qd3]+ from Black.} 16. Qd8+ Kg6 $19 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gh7h5,Yg6h7] Black is completely winning here, one way to finish the development after ...[Qd3]+ is to play ...[h5]-...[Kh7] to protect the rook, and then we can develop the knight.} *

