1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Qa4 {White is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn by pinning the knight on [c6], but also protecting the [e4]-pawn.} Bd7 {The Caro Variation. It is a pawn sacrifice for a lead in development and the initiative.} 5. exd5 ({Pretty much the only move for White.} 5. Bb5 $2 {was tried in a lot of online games, but White is pretty much lost after} a6 $1) 5... Nd4 6. Qd1 {Again the only move as the queen has to guard the [c2]-square.} Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6 {Up to this moment the Caro Variation is pretty forced, now White has a choice. How to protect the pawn on [d5], and how to slow down Black's play in the centre and kingside are the main questions for our opponent.} 8. c4 {Besides protecting the [d5]-pawn, this move also gives a square for the [b1]-knight, which is very important regarding White's development.} Bc5 {This is the most active square for the bishop, and in some cases hitting the [f2]-pawn can be critical. Our goal here is to break up the centre by playing ...[c6], but first is to finish the development.} 9. Nc3 O-O {Now besides the positional idea of ...[c6], we also have stronger threats, such as pushing ...[e4] or attack the [f2]-pawn by playing ...[Ng4].} 10. d3 {White is opening up the diagonal for their bishop and also making ...[e4] much more difficult for Black.} (10. Be2 {White is ready to castle and ...[e4] from Black doesn't look so dangerous, but we have another idea also.} Ng4 $1 {Opening the way for the f-pawn with a tempo.} 11. O-O f5 12. d3 a5 $1 {The rook can join the attack via the 6th rank.} 13. h3 Qh4 {∞ We don't have to retreat with the knight, since taking it would mean a quick loss for White. Black has strong compensation for the pawn. We can play with ...[c6] or ...[e4], and the a-rook can join the game via [a6] or [e8].}) 10... c6 $1 {[%cal Yd8b6,Yd8a5] Typical idea when White protects the pawn with [c4]. Black not only wants to open the long diagonal for the bishop, but now the queen can also go to [b6] or [a5].} 11. Be2 {White would like to quickly castle, but allowing ...[Bg4] is not ideal.} (11. Bg5 {This is the most common move in online chess, but the problem is that Black can break the pin with a tempo!} Qb6 $1 {There are big problems on [b2] and on [f2].} 12. Qe2 Ng4 {∓ White's position is very dangerous.}) 11... cxd5 12. cxd5 (12. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Bb4+ $1 {This is the problem, White can't castle.} 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Qc7 {∓ With moves like ... [Bc6] and ...[Rad8] coming, Black has obviously much more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Bg4 $1 {Black is winning back the pawn with a better position.} 13. Qg3 Bxe2 14. Kxe2 (14. Nxe2 Nxd5 {∓ A clear advantage with a better structure.}) 14... Bd4 $15 {We have time to recover the pawn on [d5]. Black can continue with ...[Qb6], ...[Rac8] and put more pressure on White.} (14... Nxd5 $2 {would be an unfortunate tactical error.} 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bh6 {± White is winning the exchange.}) *

