1. e4 e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye5d4,Ye4d5]} 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4]} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5]} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4]} d5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} 4. Qa4 {White is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn by pinning the knight on [c6], but also protecting the [e4]-pawn.} Bd7 5. exd5 ({Pretty much the only move for White.} 5. Bb5 $2 {was tried in a lot of online games, but White is pretty much lost after} a6 $1) 5... Nd4 6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6 8. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1g1,Yc4d5] The main move by a large margin. White is overprotecting the pawn on [d5] and gets ready to castle.} b5 {A pretty logical try to improve on the main line, which is 8...[e4] and almost exclusively played. The point is that once we play ...[e4], White's queen is going to drop back to [e2] and control the [b5]-square, so we can't insert this move so easily anymore. Eventually, kicking the bishop away from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal can help to regain the pawn on [d5], but even if we just win some space there, it is a good deal for Black.} 9. Bb3 e4 $1 {Of course! We are not waiting for White to play [d3] and be pretty solid.} 10. Qe2 (10. Qg3 {White slows down our development on the kingside?!} Bd6 $1 {Not really! The pawn on [g7] contains some poison.} 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qh6 Rxg2 {-+ Black is completely winning here. Not only did White's queen make a lot of moves, but it was also very badly placed.}) 10... Bd6 {Continuing normal development and the bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 11. d4 {[%cal Gc1g5] Since castling is very risky because of ... [Ng4] ideas, White first wants to develop the bishop to [g5].} (11. d3 {White is using the pin, but there are other things about to happen on the e-file!} O-O 12. dxe4 Bg4 $1 {A great move with a nice tactical point.} 13. f3 Nxe4 {Very nice! Everything is hanging, but nothing can be taken. 🙂 ...[Qh4]+ is Black's threat.} 14. Be3 Re8 {Black has a very dangerous attack.}) (11. O-O $6 {It is not good to castle too early, because from now on White will have to consider ...[Ng4] ideas.} O-O 12. d3 Bg4 $1 {...[Bg4] can be unpleasant as well.} 13. Qe3 Re8 {∓ Black is extremely active and has great chances to attack on the kingside, while White's pieces are just standing on the back rank.}) 11... O-O 12. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Yg5d8] Now White doesn't have to worry about ...[Ng4].} h6 13. Bh4 a5 14. a3 {White will keep their extra pawn for a while, but the bishop on [a2] is going to be very passive.} (14. a4 g5 $1 {This is the right time to include this move. (( 14...bxa4 15.Bxf6! Qxf6 16.Bxa4 is not so clear.))} 15. Bg3 bxa4 $1 {Black has managed to win back the pawn and has a good position.}) 14... Re8 15. O-O a4 16. Ba2 {The bishop is doing nothing else than protecting the [d5]-pawn.} Bg4 {Black has great compensation for the pawn; White can already go wrong in numerous ways in this position.} *

