1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 ({Welcome to the second Quickstarter Guide! After learning the most aggressive lines from White, now it is time to look at all the different versions of the Scotch Game/Gambit.} 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {or 5.Be3 or 5.Nxc6 . The game can go in many different directions in this chapter, it can be sharp but rather slow as well.}) 3... Nf6 {[%cal Gf1b5,Ga2a3,Gh2h3,Gd2d4,Gf1c4] This is the part of the repertoire when it was the most difficult to bring new material and fighting options, since White has numerous ways to completely equalise the game if they want to, and if Black tries something weird, it is usually also bad. 🙂I hope that you will find the material in this chapter interesting, and in my opinion the lines are not only rare, but also perfectly playable. You can learn in this chapter about: • How to get winning chances against the Göring Gambit with a rare queen recapture. • How to get advantage easily against the online favourite, Nakhmanson Gambit. • Why it is good to immediately bring back the queen from [a5] to [h5] in the main line of the Scotch Gambit. • Why 5.e5 [Nd7] could be potentially better than the mainline 5...[Ne4] in the most aggressive version of the Scotch Gambit. • The replies to White's different 5th moves in the Classical Variation with some tricky setups and move orders.} (3... Nf6 {• How you can surprise White with the rare 5...Bc5 6.Be3 Bb4 variation in the} 4. d4 {Scotch. • The way to get an easy equality against the Belgrade Gambit. • What are Black's proper reactions against White's slower 4th moves like 4.a3 , 4.h3 or 4.Be2 . • How to handle the tricky lines in the Spanish Four Knights 4.Bb5 after the rare 4...Bd6 .}) *

