1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. c3 d5 $1 {We don't really have a choice here. As it was shown in the 1st Quickstarter this position can be reached via 2.c3 as well, so better just to transpose there instead of learning two independent lines.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. cxd4 {Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} (6. Nxd4 $6 {puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yg4d1,Rc6d4]} 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} (7. Nc3 {Just another way to reach the tabiya after 9...Qc4.} Bb4 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Qc4) 7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position. We made all the logical developing moves, but now, surprisingly, Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $1 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move, White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square. If it goes away, we have to count on [d5]!, and if we take on [c3] at some point instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} 9. Bxf3 Qc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Rb4c3,Rc4c3] This is the surprising square where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 10. Qb3 {White is further compromising their pawn structure, but the doubled b-pawns will mean an open a-file for the rook.} Qxb3 (10... Qxd4 $4 {Grabbing pawns instead of developing!} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O {+- Black is lost here.}) 11. axb3 {[%csl Ga1,Yb2,Yb3,Yd4][%cal Ga1a7] White's structure is pretty bad for an endgame, but the rook on [a1] has become pretty active.} (11. Bxc6+ {White is making our structure worse, but they have to give up the bishop pair in order to do so.} bxc6 12. axb3 a5 {The tandem of a-pawn and bishop are holding together our queenside pretty nicely, giving our rooks free play.}) 11... Nge7 ({The position is completely equal according to the computer, but this is the type of equality which can turn into a slightly worse position for White seemingly without any reason very soon. 🙂 Of course, the reason for that is that White's structure is clearly worse, which can't always be compensated for by active pieces. If you want, you can trade a lot of pieces and end up in a drawish endgame after} 11... Nxd4 {, but there is no need for that here.}) 12. O-O (12. Be3 O-O-O 13. O-O a6 {Transposes to the main line.}) 12... O-O-O {[%cal Rd8d4,Rc6d4] Black has many other good moves, but it looks logical to finish the development and put pressure on the [d4]-pawn right away.} 13. Be3 (13. d5 $6 {White is trying to simplify the game, but it will not lead to complete equality.} Nd4 14. Rxa7 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxd5 {⩱ Black is better, thanks to White's weak structure on the kingside.}) 13... a6 $132 {[%csl Ya1,Ga6,Gb7][%cal Gb7a6,Gc8b8,Gh8e8,Yc6a7,Ya7c8,Yc8b6] The position is objectively equal but still complex. Black has a couple of easy moves to make, like ...[Rhe8] and ...[Kb8]. The only problematic piece, the [c6]-knight can be improved via [a7]-[c8]-[b6].} *

