1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. c3 d5 {We don't really have a choice here. As it was shown in the 1st Quickstarter this position can be reached via 2.c3 as well, so better just to transpose there instead of learning two independent lines.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. cxd4 {Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} (6. Nxd4 $6 {puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} (7. Nc3 {Just another way to reach the tabiya after 9...Qc4.} Bb4 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Qc4) 7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Bxf3 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move, White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square. If it goes away, we have to count on [d5]!, and if we take on [c3] at some point instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} 9. Bxf3 Qc4 {This is the surprising square where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 10. Bxc6+ {White wants to reach the endgame without doubling their pawns on the b-file.} Qxc6 {[%csl Yd4]} ({More ambitious than the usual recapture} 10... bxc6 {, which normally leads to a pretty equal position. Black has the better structure, but the problem is obviously that the queen has made quite a few moves, taking away time from the development.} 11. Qe2+ Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 O-O-O 13. Be3 Ne7 {If you don't want to remember too much in this 10.Bxc6 line then this is also a perfectly acceptable way to play.}) 11. O-O Ne7 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ge8g8] White has to react quickly here. Otherwise, Black just castles and will have a long-term advantage because of the IQP.} 12. d5 (12. Qb3 a5 $1 {It is useful for Black to wait for the [a3]-move if White wants to get the bishop, since it will take away the [a3]-square from the bishop and sometimes the rook can be activated via [a5] or [a6].} 13. a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 a4 $1 {Black has very nice control over the light squares on the queenside.} 15. Qb4 Nd5 $1 16. Re1+ Kd7 {⩱ clear advantage with the very strong knight on [d5], and the king can walk into safety after we play ... [Rae8].}) 12... Qd7 13. Qb3 (13. Qd4 {with a double attack on [b4] and [g7].} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxd5 {Black has won a pawn, since White can't take on [g7] because of ...[Rg8]. However the king is still in the centre.} 15. Qh4 $1 {This is the most dangerous try from White.} f6 $1 {Preparing to castle either side by protecting the knight.} 16. Ba3 Nf5 17. Qa4+ b5 18. Qc2 O-O-O {The pawn on [b5] weakens our king, but since our queen is so well positioned in the centre of the board White has nothing better than forcing a repetition in this position with [Rfd1] and then [Re1] with an attack on the queen.}) 13... a5 $1 {Preparing to castle next move.} (13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 $1 Qxd5 $4 15. c4 {+- White is winning here. Black won't be in time to castle; with moves like [Ba3] and [Re1], the knight on [e7] is in trouble.}) 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qxd5 $1 {[%csl Ya3,Ga5][%cal Ra3e7,Rc1a3] By including [a3]-...[a5] before taking on [c3], Black has managed to take away the very important [a3]-square from White's bishop.} 16. c4 Qc6 {Keeping the [b7]-pawn protected.} 17. Re1 O-O $1 {The key move of the whole line! Without this, White would have a great position, but now Black is just better with the extra pawn.} 18. Rxe7 $4 {Loses to...} Qf6 $19 {[%cal Rf6a1,Rf6e7]} *

