1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 {The Scotch Gambit! Instead of quickly taking back the material on [d4], White prefers speedy development.} Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking, not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Nc3 {A funny line, which has gained popularity in recent years, mainly in online chess. Black has many good ways to meet it, but I would suggest going in the safest way.} Nxc3 $1 (6... dxc3 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Kf6 9. Re1 {White is hoping for something like this.}) 7. bxc3 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are already two pawns up, so the main goal should be to finish development!} 8. cxd4 d5 $1 {White also wanted to play [d5], so it is the right time to make this move.} 9. Bb5 (9. Bd3 O-O {∓ is an Exchange French or Petrov where White miraculously lost their b-pawn.}) 9... O-O 10. Bxc6 {This is what White normally does, trying to regain the pawn, and frankly, it is tough to see anything better than this.} bxc6 11. Ne5 {[%cal Re5c6]} (11. Re1 {(This is the recommendation of Jonathan Schrantz vampirechicken in his course, Nakhmanson Gambit. He, too, is not very optimistic about White's chances, but he puts some tricks in place in case Black rushes with ...[c5].)} Bb4 $1 {The rook doesn't really have a good square.} 12. Re2 Bg4 {Is just bad for White. 12.Re3 c5! and ...[cxd4] will come with a tempo on the rook in the next move, so White can't win time by [c3]. 12.Bd2 Bd6 ∓ This bishop arrives in its ideal square. In addition, White doesn't have the option of playing [Qd3] and [Ba3], which would be some hope for compensation.}) 11... Bd6 $1 {We could stubbornly hold onto the pawn on [c6], but instead, we can transform our advantage into having a more active position with the pair of bishops, and it is much easier to play like this.} 12. Nxc6 Qh4 13. Ne5 Bf5 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Gf5][%cal Gf8e8,Ga8b8,Rh4e4,Re4c2] Black is clearly better with easy moves, such as ...[Rab8] or ...[Rfe8] to follow. White is on the defensive side, which our opponent obviously will not like after having played the enterprising 6. [Nc3]?!!.} *

