1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 {[%csl Yd5,Ye4,Re8][%cal Rd1d5,Re1e8] The point of the whole variation, Black can't take on [c3] because both the queen and the king are pinned. Black has a wide choice here, with almost all the queen moves being quite okay.} Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses, it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example,} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 {White has to take like this; there are no real alternatives.} (9. Rxe4+ Be6 $1 {This is all you have to know here! Black is ready to castle long next move with the better position.}) (9. Nxd4 Nxd4 $1 10. Qxd4 f5 $1 {White can't take on [e4] with the knight since the rook is hanging on [e1].}) 9... Be6 {Protecting the king from the discovered checks and also preparing to play ...[O-O-O]. White has to react quickly since. Otherwise, Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Bd2 {A decent alternative to the main line. Before committing to [Ng5] or [Bg5], White is asking one more question to Black's queen.} (10. Bg5 $2 {Prevents Black from castling, but not for long.} h6 11. Bh4 Bb4 {Developing with tempo and asking White some questions about the rook.} 12. Re2 g5 {This is also really bad for White, with ...[O-O-O] coming. 12.c3 dxc3 13.bxc3 Be7 ∓ White doesn't really have anything for the pawn.}) 10... Qb5 $5 {Only the 7th most common move in the position, but don't worry, the computer supports it. 🙂 The point is that sometimes the [b2]-pawn can be taken, which is not something the engine would have supported a few years or more ago.} 11. a4 Qxb2 {[%cal Ge8c8] Looks risky, but we are only one move away from castling, so according to the machine, it is possible to take this pawn.} 12. Rb1 Qa2 13. Rxb7 {It looks like that White has a great position, but...} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc8] This shocking move actually puts our king into safety since White can't really bring their pieces closer to the queenside.} 14. Rb1 h6 $17 {[%cal Yh6g5,Re4g5,Rf3g5,Yd1e2,Ge6c4] We even have the time to stop [Ng5] jumps, which were actually White's only real threat. The main problem for White is that they can't even bring their queen out since it can be sent back by ...[Qc4] and ...[Bc4]. Regardless of how good it is, the position is unusual, so there are quite a few examples to check out in the main course.} *

