1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses, it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example,} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 Be6 {Protecting the king from the discovered checks and also preparing to play ...[O-O-O]. White has to react quickly since. Otherwise, Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Neg5 {White is winning back the pawn on [e6].} O-O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rxe6 {So far, we have been following the main line of the 5. O-O variation with thousands of games still played from this position, but now it is time to surprise our opponent.} Qh5 ({Bringing the queen closer to White's king makes a lot of sense since if we look at the main line,} 12... Bd6 13. Bg5 $1 {White is not only developing the bishop with a tempo but also blocks the queen's way to [h5].}) 13. Bg5 (13. Bf4 $4 {This logical developing move immediately gives up a lot of material.} Qf5 {-+}) 13... Rd5 {We don't have a choice, but fortunately, the rook on [d5] is just fine. 🙂} 14. Qe2 ({White is tactically protecting the bishop.} 14. Bh4 Bd6 {With ...[g5]-...[g4] coming, Black is doing well.}) 14... Bd6 $1 {Black is covering the [e8]-square and also attacking on [h2].} (14... Rxg5 $4 {loses the game immediately.} 15. Re8+ $1 Nd8 16. Qe6+ {+-}) 15. Bh4 {The bishop already needed protection, but this is not the right one.} (15. h4 $1 h6 16. Qe4 $1 Rxg5 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Kf1 $1 {Only move for White.} g4 19. Ng1 g3 {∞ Black has great compensation for the exchange.}) 15... d3 $1 {[%cal Rc6d4,Yd4e2,Yd4e6] Freeing the [d4]-square for the knight.} 16. cxd3 g5 $1 {[%cal Yg5g4,Yg4f3,Rc6d4] If Black can chase away the knight from [f3], ...[Nd4] is winning immediately.} 17. Bg3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 g4 $19 {[%cal Yg4f3,Rc6d4] With ...[Nd4] in the next move, Black is winning material.} *

