1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. e5 ({Much more critical and dangerous for Black than} 5. O-O {.}) 5... d5 $1 {As we have seen in many previous variations, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 {Pretty much the only move for White.} (6. exf6 $2 {This is really bad.} dxc4 7. Qe2+ Be6 {-+ White can't do anything against the pawns on [c4] and [d4].}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that, while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7], the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. Bxc6 $2 {If our opponent is anxious about being down a pawn, this move is quite possible to happen, but it just helps Black's task tremendously since we essentially win a tempo because the [e5]-pawn was not hanging anyway.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good; Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 c6 9. Bd3 Bc5 $1 10. Qg4 g6 {∓ White has big problems with defending the [e5]-pawn, since [f4] would make [O-O] not possible for a while.}) 7... bxc6 8. Nxd4 (8. O-O c5 $1 9. c3 dxc3 10. Qxd5 {Even here, Black can keep the extra pawn.} cxb2 $1 11. Bxb2 Nb6 {∓ Protecting the rook and gaining a tempo on White's queen secures Black's advantage.}) (8. Qxd4 {White is not risking giving up the [e5]-pawn.} Be7 9. e6 {(( 9.O-O O-O transposes to another variation of this Quickstarter.))} fxe6 10. Qxg7 Bf6 11. Qg4 Qe7 {∓ With the strong central pawns, Black is clearly better here; if needed it is also possible to castle long after ...[Bb7].}) 8... Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ye5c6] We can take this pawn since all the tactics are working out in our favour.} 9. O-O (9. Bf4 $2 Qf6 10. Bg3 Ba6 {-+ And it is even our opponent who has problems with finishing the development.}) (9. Qe2 Qe7 10. f4 {White is winning back the pawn, but weakening their position a lot and also opening the game more for the bishops.} Ng4 11. Nxc6 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd7 {∓ White has a lot of problems.}) 9... Bd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5][%cal Yd6e5,Ge8g8]} 10. f4 {The only way to stop Black from castling.} Ng4 11. Re1+ (11. h3 Nf6 12. Nxc6 Bc5+ $1 13. Kh2 Qd6 {∓ White's position is very weak and Black is castling on the next move.}) 11... Kf8 $17 {[%csl Gf8,Yg1][%cal Rd6c5,Rc5g1,Rd8h4,Rh4h2] Our king has to stay in the centre, but it is still much safer than White's, which has been weakened by the [f4]-move.} (11... Kf8 {In case of} 12. h3 {, Black has at least 3 ways to achieve a better position,} c5 {followed by ...[Nf6] or, if White allows it, ....[Qh4]! 12...h5!? and 12...Qh4 .}) *

