1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. e5 ({Much more critical and dangerous for Black than} 5. O-O {.}) 5... d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that, while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7], the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {This is by far White's best move since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} Be7 8. Re1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye1e5]} ({A very common move, but not so good, since, as we will see from the main line,} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {works right away, so White doesn't need to protect the [e5]-pawn before that.}) 8... O-O {We can't keep the extra pawn, so it is time to castle.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4f5,Rd4c6,Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} Nb8 $1 {The key move of this variation. Black not only protects the [c6] pawn but also covers the [f5]-square with the [c8] bishop. The knight maneuver of ...[Nf6]-[d7]-[b8] may seem a little strange, but once we play ...[c5] followed by ...[Nc6], we will improve our position greatly. Also, we shouldn't forget about the long-term power of the pair of bishops.} 11. Qf3 {White is preparing against ...[c5], they are ready to put the knight on [f5].} (11. f4 $6 {This looks very logical as White has a majority on the kingside, so they are pushing it forward. However, the problem is that Black can easily stop this idea, and then White is left with an overextended position.} c5 $1 12. Nf3 Nc6 {This is what we wanted to play, and we managed to stop White's [f5]-idea.} 13. Nc3 d4 14. Ne4 Qd5 {⩱ with an excellent position for Black. White's play on the kingside is non-existent, while we can push on the queenside by ... [a5]-...[a4] or with ...[c4]-...[d3]. We will bring the rooks to the b and d-files, and while it is not clear yet where our [c8]-bishop should go, we will simply leave it on [c8] for now until a better square presents itself.}) (11. Nc3 $6 {White is not addressing the threat of ...[c5], so their knight will have to retreat to a passive square now.} c5 12. Nb3 Be6 {⩱ Keeping everything solid, and White's knights are just very restricted here.}) 11... c5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 $10 {[%cal Gb8c6] With the additional trade of minor pieces, White's prospects of kingside play have been heavily reduced. Black will simply finish development and then they can consider pushing their pawns in the centre.} *

