[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2160376106872369"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. e5 ({Much more critical and dangerous for Black than} 5. O-O {.}) 5... d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that, while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7], the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {Definitely the critical line. White can temporarily sacrifice the pawn on [e5].} (9. Qxd4 $6 {It is clear that White is only taking with the queen because they are not sure that 9.Nxd4 is working. Now, both the queen and the knight are misplaced, and Black has very easy play.} O-O 10. Nc3 Nc5 {⩱ We will play ...[Ne6] next and then start pushing our pawns in the centre. White's play is blocked by the knight on [f3].}) 9... Nxe5 $5 ({A rare move. The mainline is} 9... Nb8 {and there is nothing wrong with it, but I like the surprise value and unusual positions that the text move can bring. Now White has 4 ways to attack the knight, and only one of those is good!}) 10. Re1 $6 {The most common and maybe the most natural move in the position, but also a mistake!} (10. Qe2 $2 Qd6 {Protecting the knight and also the [c6]-pawn, which is very important. The knight is now free to move.}) (10. f4 $2 c5 $1 {easily refutes White's aggressive idea.} 11. fxe5 cxd4 12. Qxd4 c5 13. Qd3 O-O {∓ White has won back the pawn, but the [e5]-pawn remains isolated and weak. Black also has very strong bishops and central pawns. It is really tough for White to find any kind of play here, while Black can just improve the position in many different ways.}) 10... f6 $1 ({This is a new move which can lead to a lot of nice attacking lines for Black after 11.f4. In case you don't want to learn those lines, for now,} 10... Qd6 {is also good enough for the advantage.}) 11. f4 Bg4 $1 12. Qd2 (12. Nxc6 $2 {doesn't work.} Qd7 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. Qd2 O-O {-+ White's king is very weak, and they are also very much behind in development.}) 12... O-O $1 {The key move! Of course, it is very hard to find without the help of the machine.} 13. fxe5 fxe5 {We already have 2 pawns for the piece. White's king is exposed, and also their queenside is undeveloped. Black not only has more than enough compensation for the piece but also a winning position.} 14. Nxc6 Bc5+ $1 {One more important intermediate move.} 15. Kh1 Qh4 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Yc6,Rh1][%cal Rf8f2,Rc5f2,Rf2g3,Gc5d6,Ge5e4,Rh4h2] And Black has a winning attack here, White's king is lacking pieces for the defence.} *

