1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 {Since there is also a way to reach this position via 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 , it was not really a question whether 4...Bc5 or 4...Nf6 should be chosen here. 🙂} 5. e5 ({Much more critical and dangerous for Black than} 5. O-O {.}) 5... d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that, while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7], the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {Definitely the critical line. White can temporarily sacrifice the pawn on [e5].} (9. Qxd4 $6 {It is clear that White is only taking with the queen because they are not sure that 9.Nxd4 is working. Now, both the queen and the knight are misplaced, and Black has very easy play.} O-O 10. Nc3 Nc5 {⩱ We will play ...[Ne6] next and then start pushing our pawns in the centre. White's play is blocked by the knight on [f3].}) 9... Nxe5 ({A rare move. The mainline is} 9... Nb8 {and there is nothing wrong with it, but I like the surprise value and unusual positions that the text move can bring. Now White has 4 ways to attack the knight, and only one of those is good!}) 10. Bf4 $1 {The correct way to attack the knight.} c5 $1 {This move makes the line playable for Black.} (10... Ng6 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Qd4 {⩲ It is not much fun for Black, with all the weak dark squares.}) 11. Bxe5 (11. Nb5 $6 {doesn't pose any problems for Black, only makes the queenside structure better.} c6 $1 12. Bxe5 cxb5 13. Bxg7 Rg8 14. Be5 Rg6 {⇆ Black has a huge centre, and our king can even castle long in this line.}) 11... cxd4 12. Bxg7 (12. Qxd4 $6 {allows} c5 {⩱ and Black is castling on the next move, with a slightly better position as the bishops are going to be very strong.}) 12... Rg8 13. Be5 $1 {[%cal Ge5g3] This is the good move from White, intending to meet the ...[Bh3]-threat with [Bg3], and also, in any case the bishop could be very useful on [g3] to stop Black's play on the g-file. If White would take on [d4] with either piece, they would lose an exchange.} (13. Bxd4 $2 Bh3 {∓}) (13. Qxd4 $6 {The 'better' way to lose the exchange.} f6 $1 14. Bh6 Bh3 {⩱ Of course, this is still better for Black.}) 13... c5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc5d4] Of course, we are not going to give up that pawn for free.} 14. Re1 {Bringing a new piece into the game is a very decent move.} Qb6 $132 {[%cal Rb6b2,Gb6g6] Not only attacking [b2], but also covering the 6th rank. In some lines, the queen can also go to [g6]. The position is complex and very unusual. One plan which is good to know is ...[Rg6], followed by ...[Kf8] and ...[Kg8], which could put the king in a safer place.} *

