1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return, they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ... [Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Rd4c6,Ge3c5] The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4]} d6 ({The main line is} 6... Nge7 {with a lot of theory; the text move, although it is the second most popular choice, is much less known. The main point is to delay the development of the [g8]-knight since, against certain moves, it is very effective to develop it on [f6] and attack the [e4]-pawn.}) 7. Bc4 $6 {The most common move in the position, and the main line against 6...[Nge7]. There is a good chance that our opponent is going to play like this. Here, however, the move is very dubious, and it immediately gives Black the upper hand.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Re5c4,Re5g4] Similarly to the absolute main lines of the Scotch, we play with ...[Ne5] and chase away White's bishop from the [c4]-square.} 8. Be2 (8. Bb3 $2 {Remaining on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal is already a serious mistake from White.} Qg6 $1 {White has no way to protect both the [e4] and [g2]-pawn.} 9. O-O Bh3 {-+ winning an exchange.}) 8... Qg6 {[%cal Rg6e4,Rg6g2] Hitting the pawns on [e4] and [g2].} 9. O-O {So far, the moves have been identical to the absolute main line, 6...Nge7 Scotch. The problem for White is that here, with ...[d6] being already played, Black has a very unpleasant continuation, which stops White's main idea, which is [f4], and also forces their bishop into a passive square.} Bh3 $1 {Forcing [Bf3].} ({Instead,} 9... Qxe4 $6 {is very risky, and Black has a better line anyway.}) 10. Bf3 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Gf2f4] Black is very comfortable since [f4] which could cause some problems, is not going to come anytime soon.} Nf6 {Of course! The knight is joining the game to attack the pawn on [e4].} 11. Nd2 (11. Kh1 Bd7 12. Nd2 h5 {⩱ Keeping the options of both short and long castle. White is under pressure and has to watch out for the [e4]-pawn and also for ...[Nfg4] ideas.}) 11... Nh5 $17 {[%cal Re5f3,Rd1f3,Rh3g4,Rg4f3,Yh5g3,Yh5f4] A very nice idea from Black. We want to take on [f3], and then the queen must take it back to protect the [g2]-pawn. Then ...[Bg4] is going to trap the queen!} *

