1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 d6 ({The main line is} 6... Nge7 {with a lot of theory; the text move, although it is the second most popular choice, is much less known. The main point is to delay the development of the [g8]-knight since, against certain moves, it is very effective to develop it on [f6] and attack the [e4]-pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {Definitely looks like the right move for White, developing with a tempo and not allowing Black to comfortably execute the ...[Qg6] and ...[Nf6] plan.} Nge7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ye7c6,Ge8g8] Protecting the knight on [c6] and preparing to castle.} 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 {White is gaining some space in the centre and is ready to meet ...[Qg6] with [f5]!} (9. Bxc6 {Giving up the bishop pair looks unnecessary.} bxc6 10. Nd2 Bb6 {Introducing the ...[c5] idea into the position, but Black's main plan remains ...[Qg6] followed by ...[f5].}) (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc5 {Otherwise, Black would take on [e3] and create a horrible structure for White.} cxb5 11. Bd4 Qg6 {In opposite-coloured bishop positions, king safety is very important, and maybe in the future, it is rather Black who can try to attack White's king.} 12. Nd2 c5 {Chasing the bishop to a more passive square, and with that also ...[f5] can come with a tempo.} 13. Be3 f5 {⇆ Black has zero problems; it is rather White who has to be somewhat careful.}) 9... Bb6 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Yc6d4,Yc3d4,Rd4c5] Protecting the bishop, so that after playing ...[d5] we don't have to worry about [Nxc6]. More importantly, it also prepares to take on [d4] with the knight, and White's recapture of [cxd4] will not win a tempo anymore.} 10. Kh1 d5 $1 {We are getting some light squares in the centre for our pieces.} 11. e5 Qh6 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Rc6e5,Yh6e3] A nice tempo, since ...[Nxe5] is a threat.} 12. Qd2 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Nf5 $132 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black can soon undermine the centre with ...[f6].} *

