1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Ye1c1] Recently, this has been White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Qe2 ({The move orders are very tricky.} 6. a4 {, 6.Nc3 or 6.Qe2 can all transpose into the same position, but we have to be careful not to be tricked into a position which is not part of our repertoire.}) 6... d6 $1 {Being flexible is the key for Black, and this move is excellent for that purpose. Sometimes, we want to play with ...[Qf6] and sometimes with ...[Nge7], depending on White's play, so with this move, we are not showing our cards yet.} 7. Nc3 {[%cal Yd8f6,Rc3d5] Of course, now it doesn't make any sense for Black to play ...[Qf6], since both [b2] and [f2]-pawns are protected, so White could immediately play [Nd5].} (7. Be3 Qf6 $1 8. Nc3 Nge7 {will transpose to the next Quickstarter variation, when White starts with the more common 6.Nc3.}) 7... a5 $1 {We want to attack the knight on [b3], and if White plays [a4] to stop it, we are getting a nice square for our knight on [b4].} 8. Be3 (8. a4 Nb4 $1) 8... a4 {This was our goal, to kick the knight from [b3]!} 9. Nd2 {Now this move is not so awkward since the bishop is already out on [e3].} (9. Bxb6 axb3 10. Be3 bxa2 11. Rxa2 Rxa2 12. Nxa2 Nf6 {The position has simplified quite a bit, and it is clear that we shouldn't really have high ambitions, but we are very solid, and equality is not far away. The goal is to achieve ...[d5] pretty soon.}) 9... Bxe3 {Not allowing White to spoil our structure on [b6].} 10. Qxe3 a3 $1 {This is an important move. If we delay playing ...[a3], then White could play [a3]! themselves, fixing our pawn on a light square. Then, it would be much easier for White to attack the pawn.} 11. b3 Nf6 12. Bb5 O-O 13. Bxc6 $1 (13. O-O {would allow} Nb4 $1 14. Rfc1 Qe7 {⇆ and the knight on [b4] is very annoying.}) 13... bxc6 $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Yd6d5,Yc8f5,Rd5e4,Rf5e4,Re8e4] We will put pressure on the [e4]-pawn in the next moves by playing ...[Re8], ...[d5] and possibly even ...[Bf5].} *

