1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this has been White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 {By far, the most common move for White.} Qf6 ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously, the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gc3d5,Ye2f2] By far, the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5]. Also, [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge1c1] White is continuing the development and preparing to castle long.} d6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ye8c8] Black is doing exactly the same!} 9. O-O-O Bd7 {[%csl Ye6][%cal Gc3d5,Ye7d5,Ye4d5,Rd5c6,Rd5e6] It is better to develop the bishop here than to [e6], since now, after [Nd5], we can comfortably take it with the knight without getting a fork.} 10. f3 (10. f4 Bg4 $1 {is a nice trick from Black, winning the [f4]-pawn.} 11. Qxg4 Bxe3+ 12. Kb1 Bxf4 {⩱}) 10... O-O-O 11. Qd2 {[%csl Gf1] White is opening up the way for the [f1]-bishop.} Bxe3 {It is logical to take now since White is losing some time with the queen.} 12. Qxe3 Qg6 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5] ...[f5] is coming next.} *

