1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this has been White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. a4 {[%cal Ra4a5] White wants to trap our bishop on [b6]!} a5 {We are stopping White's a-pawn, and in case White develops their knight to [c3], we can respond by playing ...[Nb4] to stop [Nd5] threats.} 7. Nc3 Nb4 $1 {Covering the [d5]-square against [Nd5]-ideas.} 8. Bc4 {Since the typical plan of [Qe2]-[Be3] is not available because of the weakness of the [c2]-pawn, White goes for a setup with [O-O], but it can hardly be dangerous for Black.} d6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yd6e5,Gd8h4,Yg8f6] Before playing ...[Nf6], we are stopping [e5]-ideas, and also, we are still keeping the option of developing the queen to [h4] before the knight closes the diagonal.} 9. O-O Nf6 10. Bg5 {The only question for our setup is the pin on our knight.} (10. h3 {gives time for Black to play} h6 $1 {and stop [Bg5].} 11. Re1 O-O 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rxe3 Be6 {with an equal game.}) 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 $1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Ye8g8] Black is using the fact that the king hasn't castled yet!} 12. Bg3 h5 {[%csl Rg3] All of a sudden, there are some issues with the [g3]-bishop.} 13. h3 h4 14. Bh2 g4 $15 {[%cal Rg4h3,Rg4g3] Not only ...[gxh3] but ...[g3]! is a serious threat as well.} *

