1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes their third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {[%cal Gd8h4]} ({This move should already come as little surprise to White since the main line is the intermediate move} 5... Qf6 {. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].}) 6. Bc4 $6 (6. Nc3 Nf6 {transposes to the Four Knights Opening, which will be shown in one of the next variations.}) 6... Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4e4,Rh4f2] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. O-O {This is the most common move, protecting [f2] and also [e4] since we can't take because of the pin.} (7. Qf3 $2 {White replies in kind by defending [f2] and attacking [f7], but now Black can take advantage of the bishop on [c4].} d5 $1 8. Bd3 Nf6 {Putting pressure on [e4] and gaining time is key for Black.} 9. exd5 Ng4 10. g3 Qe7+ {Black has great compensation here, but actually will also take back the material very soon!}) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yf6g4,Rg4f2,Rg4h2] As usual, we are bringing the knight to [f6] in order to attack [e4], and also to have ...[Ng4] opportunities.} 8. Nc3 $2 {[%csl Yc3] Even though the knight is protecting the [e4]-pawn, it is far away from the kingside.} Ng4 $1 {Very unpleasant double attack!} 9. Bf4 (9. h3 Nxf2 {-+}) 9... Nxf2 {It looks like the game is completely over, and it is, but it is better to know that White has one more trick here.} 10. Bxf7+ Kd8 $1 (10... Kxf7 $4 {This would be a huge mistake.} 11. Bg3 {±}) 11. Qh5 {White has nothing better than entering a much worse endgame.} Qxh5 12. Bxh5 Nd3+ 13. Kh1 Nxf4 14. Rxf4 Rb8 $17 {[%csl Yc3,Gc5,Gc6,Gc8,Re4][%cal Yc6b5,Yc6d5] And Black is much better with the pair of bishops and better structure. White is also left with pretty bad minor pieces.} *

