1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. d4 {This is how the Scotch starts, but normally White's next move will tell more about the character of the game. They can just take back and have a relatively 'slower' game, at least compared to the ones after} exd4 4. Bc4 {or 4.c3 .}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes their third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 ({This move should already come as little surprise to White since the main line is the intermediate move} 5... Qf6 {. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the right approach from White. The bishop has to be on [d3] to protect the [e4]-pawn, and they can safely castle on the next move.} Qh4 $1 {[%csl Yb1,Rf3,Gh4][%cal Rh4f2,Rh4h2,Rh4e4] Our play is not changing, we want the queen on [h4] to put pressure on White's position, and it is pretty effective in the absence of the [f3]-knight.} 7. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Rf6g4,Ge8g8] Usual square for the knight, preparing both to attack and also to castle.} 8. Qf3 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gc1f4,Yf3f2]} (8. h3 $6 {White prevents the ...[Ng4]-idea, but gives our light-squared bishop a target.} d6 {Targeting the [h3]-pawn.} 9. Qf3 {White has to protect the pawn on [h3].} Nd7 10. Be3 Ne5 11. Qe2 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 g5 $1 {with both ...[Rg8]-...[g4] and ...[Qf4] being legit ideas, Black is very comfortable.}) {9.Nd2? is immediately losing. 9...Bxh3! 10.Nf3 Qg3 -+ or 10.gxh3 Qg3+ 11.Kh1 Qxh3+ 12.Kg1 Ng4 White is losing their queen or getting checkmated. For instance, 13.Nf3 Qg3+ 14.Kh1 Bxf2 -+} 8... Bd4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yd4e5,Rd4b2,Yc1f4] An unusual move, but once we see that [e5] was a threat and the bishop wanted to go to [f4], it already looks very decent.} 9. c3 Ng4 $1 {A very important intermediate move. Unfortunately, ...[Be5] doesn't work too well.} (9... Be5 10. g3 Qh3 11. Nd2 {⩲ With [Nc4] coming next, there is no really good square for our bishop.}) 10. Bf4 (10. h3 $6 {gives Black's attack a target.} Ne5 11. Qe2 Bb6 12. Be3 g5 $1 {Very strong. The attack can be dangerous.}) 10... Ne5 {Black wants to trade some pieces before retreating their dark-squared bishop.} 11. Qe2 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb6 $132 {Black has managed to get the pair of bishops and has a solid position.} *

