[Black "Four Knights 4.d4 6.Nxc6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C47"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2160376107085370"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move, but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1.e4 [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle because, after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the centre with the [e4]-pawn.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage, they could be slightly better, but since the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one.} 5... Bb4 {is Black's main choice by far; it is very reliable, but all the players from the White side will expect it, and they can achieve a very solid position easily.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines is that White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} (6. Nb3 {Not a particularly bad move from White, but definitely not the one which could challenge the 5...Bc5 line, since now our opponent is forcing the bishop to the 'correct' square.} Bb4 7. Bd3 {Protecting [e4] and preparing to castle.} a5 $5 {Though 7...[d5] was already okay for Black, I like the text move, which was played by my legendary compatriot, GM Romanishin. The point is that if White reacts to this move by} 8. a3 {or 8.a4 , then we can play ...[d5] under better circumstances, and if they don't, then we can push the pawn forward. 8.a4 d5 ⇆ with a nice, fighting position for Black.}) 6... bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bd3 {This is the most popular move for White, and correctly so, they are protecting the centre and preparing to castle.} (7. e5 $6 {This is too ambitious and just weakening for White.} Qe7 $1 {and after} 8. Qe2 {Black can comfortably play} Nd5 {⇆}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gc5d4,Rd4c3,Yf6e4,Ye8e4] Bringing the rook to the game in order to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn. This plan can be and is continued many times with ...[Bd4], targeting one of the main defenders of that pawn.} 9. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8,Yf6][%cal Yg5d8] The most annoying move against our setup, but if we can deal with this pin well, then we are doing very well.} (9. Re1 {White is not only strengthening the pawn on [e4], but threatens to play [e5]!} d5 $1 {This break tends to work well when our opponent's rook is on [e1] since the [f2]-square is weaker and Black already has ...[Ng4]-ideas.} 10. e5 $4 Ng4 {-+ is already losing for White with ...[Qh4] next. 10.exd5 Bg4 Developing with a tempo can't be too bad! 11.Rxe8+ Qxe8 12.Qf1 cxd5= The position is around equal, but White's pieces, especially the queen, are a little bit strange.}) 9... h6 {It is useful to start with this move, just to always have the option of immediately breaking the pin with ...[g5] later.} 10. Bh4 Bd4 {[%csl Rb2,Gf6][%cal Yd4f6,Yd4b2,Ga8b8,Rb8b2] Quite an unusual square for a bishop, but it does a great job of defending and also puts pressure on the queenside, especially when it is combined with ...[Rb8].} 11. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] This move looks the most challenging to me. White is preparing to push [f4].} (11. Qf3 $2 {This is just a blunder.} g5 $1 12. Bg3 d5 {∓ Black is much better because of the ...[Bg4] threat.}) 11... g5 $1 {Very concrete play starts from now on!} 12. Bg3 Bxc3 $1 {After ... [g5], we have to show something, and we are doing so by taking the pawn on [e4]!} 13. bxc3 Nxe4 14. Qh5 {Black's position looks dangerous, but actually, White doesn't have that many pieces to attack.} Qf6 $1 {The queen will be very important for the defence.} 15. f4 $1 ({Without the f-file, White doesn't really have an attack at all.} 15. Rae1 d5 $1 {and White has nothing.}) 15... Nxg3+ (15... Qg6 {pretty much forces the trade of the queens, which would just lead to an equal endgame.}) 16. hxg3 Re7 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ye7f7] The key defensive move. The rook covers the [f7]-square. The game most likely will reach an equal endgame, but for now, Black has an extra pawn.} *

