1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle because, after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the centre with the [e4]-pawn.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage, they could be slightly better, but since the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one.} 5... Bb4 {is Black's main choice by far; it is very reliable, but all the players from the White side will expect it, and they can achieve a very solid position easily.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6] threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} Bb4 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e8,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Yd7d5,Yf6g4,Rg4e3] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...Bb4, and now, once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too. It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects, it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5], once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Bd3 {A decent move; White continues developing.} Nxd4 $5 {A new move, with the aim of creating an imbalanced position.} 8. Bxd4 c5 {[%cal Yd4e3,Rb4c3] This is the point: we are forcing away the bishop from protecting the knight on [c3], so we can create doubled pawns.} 9. Be3 (9. Bxf6 {This is also possible but completely harmless for Black.} Qxf6 10. Qd2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. O-O d6 {Black is completely fine here; we have a backward pawn on [d6], but White's queenside is also very weak.}) (9. Be5 {White keeps the [c3]-square covered for the moment.} Qe7 $1 10. Bf4 c4 $1 {One of the few ways to reach a decent position.} 11. Bxc4 Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 O-O {⇆ Black has decent chances in this position.}) 9... d5 {First, we want to bring the queen into the centre, and then take on [c3].} 10. exd5 (10. e5 {Very ambitious, but also gives good chances for Black.} Ng4 11. Bb5+ Kf8 {((We have to move the king, since 11...Bd7?? would be met by 12.Qxg4 , but in return we have a lot of threats.))} 12. Bd2 d4 13. Ne4 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 {Black is winning the [e5]-pawn.} Qd5 {⩱}) 10... O-O {The ...[d5]-pawn is not running away.} 11. O-O (11. Bc4 {White is trying to keep the extra material.} Bg4 12. Qd3 a6 $1 {when ...[b5] is coming next move against pretty much everything and Black is doing very well.} 13. a4 $2 {This is even losing to} b5 $1 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 {-+ and ...[Qa1] next is winning for Black.}) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qxd5 $132 {[%csl Ya2,Yc2,Yc3,Gd3,Ge3][%cal Gc8f5,Gb7b6] With a double-edged position where White's bishops are quite strong, since the position is open, but Black has the better structure. If at some point we can trade the light-squared bishops, that could easily turn the position into our favour.} *

