1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle because, after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the centre with the [e4]-pawn.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage, they could be slightly better, but since the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one.} 5... Bb4 {is Black's main choice by far; it is very reliable, but all the players from the White side will expect it, and they can achieve a very solid position easily.}) 6. Be3 {White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6] threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} Bb4 {A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...Bb4, and now, once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too. It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects, it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5], once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5...Bb4 main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Bd3 {This is the most common move, and the one which White is going to play if they don't know the theory.} d6 {[%cal Yf6g4,Rg4e3]} ({A tricky moment for us, since} 8... d5 {or 8...O-O are extremely likely to transpose to the main ...[Bb4] lines after White eventually plays [Bg5] and loses a tempo. So, we need something different, and for that reason it is good that the bishop is on [e3] now and not on [c1], since our ...[Ng4] idea can come with a tempo.}) 9. O-O Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rg4e3]} 10. Bf4 (10. Bd2 {will most likely transpose to 10. [Bf4], since after} Qh4 11. h3 Ne5 {⇆ looks way to risky. 11.Bf4 Qf6 transposes to the main line.}) 10... Qf6 {[%cal Rf6f4,Rb4c3,Rf6c3] Targeting the bishop and also the knight on [c3].} 11. Qd2 {[%csl Gc3,Gf4][%cal Yd2c3,Yd2f4]} (11. Ne2 $2 Bc5 {∓ White is in trouble, because not only the [b2]-pawn is hanging, but after taking twice on [f2], we can win material by playing ...[g5].}) (11. Bg3 h5 $1 {With the threat of ...[h4].}) 11... O-O 12. Rae1 Ne5 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8,Yb4a5,Gc8e6,Ye5c4] With a complicated position where Black's chances are quite good. We can bring the rook to [b8], or try ideas with ...[Qe6]/...[Be6] and then ...[Nc4]. Also, taking on [d3] and changing the pawn structure is a completely playable move.} *

