1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle because, after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the centre with the [e4]-pawn.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage, they could be slightly better, but since the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one.} 5... Bb4 {is Black's main choice by far; it is very reliable, but all the players from the White side will expect it, and they can achieve a very solid position easily.}) 6. Be3 {White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6] threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} Bb4 {A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...Bb4, and now, once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too. It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects, it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5], once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5...Bb4 main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Gd4e4,Ge1c1,Yd4c3,Rd4b4] This move is the critical test of the whole 5...[Bc5], 6...[Bb4] line. White is using their extra move Be3 to speed up development and castle long. Also, the queen is doing excellent defensive and attacking role in the centre. The good thing is that it only happened in 8 games! so far.} Qe7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ye7b4,Re7e4,Rf6e4] Protecting the bishop and attacking the [e4]-pawn. Now, White has a wide choice, but in practice they played [O-O-O] in 6 out of the 7 games.} 9. O-O-O (9. e5 $6 {poses zero problems for Black. The only good side of the move is that the pawn is not hanging on [e4] anymore.} c5 $1 10. Qf4 Nd5 11. Qe4 c6 {Already Black is playing for the advantage. White just lost a lot of time with their queen.}) (9. f3 d5 $1 {Using the fact that the king is still in the centre.}) 9... O-O {Taking the pawn on [e4] is not working yet.} (9... Bxc3 $2 10. Qxc3 Qxe4 $4 11. Bc5 {+- and [Re1] in the next move is winning for White.}) 10. Bg5 {[%csl Re7][%cal Yg5e7] The two grandmasters who reached this position as White, both continued with this move, and it is indeed quite normal.} (10. e5 Bxc3 $1 {So the knight can jump to [d5].} 11. Qxc3 Nd5 12. Qd4 Nxe3 {Black is taking back the bishop pair.} 13. Qxe3 Re8 14. f4 d5 {⇆ The break we have to play for is ...[f6]!}) 10... Re8 {Preventing ...[e5] and attacking [e4].} 11. Bxf6 {It is surprising to take immediately, but White had to avoid a tactical trick from Black.} (11. f3 $2 {looks more natural than solving the pin for Black right away.} Bxc3 $1 12. bxc3 Qa3+ 13. Kd2 c5 {∓ Not allowing [Qb4] and the trade, Black will continue with ...[Re6] and attack against White's king. 12.Qxc3 Nxe4! 13.Bxe7 Nxc3 ∓ Black will be up a pawn in the endgame.}) 11... gxf6 {It would be better to take with the queen, but unfortunately the bishop is hanging on [b4].} 12. Bc4 (12. Rd3 Bd6 $1 {Stopping [Rg3] and opening the b-file for the rook. Black's kingside seems to be weak, but it is very difficult to actually attack anything there. White's minor pieces are very passive.}) 12... Qc5 $1 {Black obviously wouldn't mind an endgame.} 13. Qd3 Rb8 14. h4 Qe5 $132 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Yb4c3,Ye5g3,Yd3g3] The queen is well-placed on [e5], sometimes we can take on [c3], but we don't have to rush with it. Black's king is not weaker than White's, since Black can bring more pieces to attack it.} *

