1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle because, after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the centre with the [e4]-pawn.} exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively, it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bc4 {White is strengthening the control over the [d5]-square.} (6. Nxd4 {This line doesn't pose any problems for Black, it just leads to early exchanges.} Nxd5 7. exd5 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O {White didn't manage to get anything out of the opening.}) (6. Bf4 {White has a big threat, but it is very easy to address.} d6 7. Nxd4 Nxd5 {Trading pieces is still available and perfectly good for Black, there is nothing to know here.} 8. exd5 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bf6) {7...O-O! Black can be ambitious with this move. You can find the details in the full course.} 6... O-O {It is always a good thing to castle against a gambit!} 7. O-O Nxe4 {[%csl Gg8]} (7... d6 {is more common, but since we castled, I don't see any issue with taking this pawn.}) 8. Re1 (8. Nxd4 Nf6 $1 {Offering some trades!} 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 $1 10. Bg5 Ng6 {⩱ Black can break the pin with ...[h6] in the next move.}) 8... Nf6 9. Nxe7+ (9. Nxd4 $2 {The only task is to take the correct knight here, which shouldn't be too difficult.} Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bf6 {∓ Black is up a pawn for no compensation.}) (9. Rxe7 $2 {This is not enough for White.} Nxe7 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 d5 {∓ White has no attack, the knight always can defend on [g6], but for now it is not even clear against what it should defend.}) 9... Nxe7 10. Qxd4 {[%csl Gc1,Gc4] White doesn't have anything immediate here, they are playing for long-term compensation with the pair of bishops.} (10. Bg5 {Popular in online games, but not dangerous.} d5 $1 {This is the move to know and not being afraid of [Bxf6].} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 {Our kingside is weakened, but we have two extra pawns for it.} 12. Bd3 Bg4 {∓ Black is up 2 pawns, and it is not clear how White should start their attack.}) 10... d6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Gc8g4]} ({I like this move better than the main line, which is} 10... d5 {, with the idea of restricting the knight on [f3], and ...[Bg4] can't be met by [Ne5] after this.}) 11. Bg5 Nf5 {[%cal Rf5d4,Yf5h4,Yh7h6] Hitting the queen with a tempo and preparing to play ...[h6].} 12. Qf4 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Yf5d4,Yf5h4,Yf5e7] The [f5]-knight is the last problem Black should solve.} g5 $1 15. Qe4 d5 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf5d6] Very important to know this! Now the knight has the [d6]-square, and Black is at least okay.} (15... Ng7 $4 16. Bd3 {+- and Black is lost! This line is a little bit long, but it is quite easy to reach this position if your opponent actually knows the Belgrade Gambit.}) *

