[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2160376107228735"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move, it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 (5. Bxf7+ $2 {A very bad move; White is giving the full centre to Black in hopes of making Black's king weaker.} Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 $1 {White is already on the verge of losing.} 7. Neg5+ Kg8 {White is already on the verge of losing.} 8. d3 h6 9. Nh3 Bg4 {-+ With ...[Qf6], ...[Rd8] and ...[Bd6] to follow, Black has a winning advantage.}) (5. O-O {White is sacrificing a pawn for quick development.} Nxc3 6. dxc3 h6 $1 {With this move, Black is trying to keep the material advantage and play for an advantage. If you feel it is unnecessary to learn these lines, or you feel it is risky, then just play 6...Be7 , when the game is completely equal after 7.Qd5 O-O 8.Nxe5 Nxe5 9.Qxe5 Bf6 .}) 5... d5 {[%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4]} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {∓ Now it is not only the centre, but Black also has the pair of bishops.}) (6. Bb5 $2 dxe4 7. Nxe5 {Doesn't look too bad, but it is already losing for White.} Qg5 $1 {Everything is hanging.} 8. Nxc6 Qxb5 9. Nd4 Qg5 {∓ Black already has the pair of bishops, and White still has no good way to protect on [g2].}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] lines when with Black, we had positions like this and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 8. O-O (8. Bxc6+ $6 {This structure is not a problem for Black, but the bishop pair will be very strong!} bxc6 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 Bg4 {⩱ The pin is very difficult to break, and Black can also continue with ...[f5].}) 8... O-O 9. Re1 {White is preventing ...[f5] by putting additional pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} (9. h3 $6 {Quite a common move for this structure, especially in online games that White wants to prevent ...[Bg4].} Nb4 $1 {Instead, 9...f5 is also good, but this is even more ambitious, after playing ...[f5] White has to retreat their bishop to a very passive square. Note that the knight now covers [d5], which would otherwise been the bishop's choice.} 10. c3 f5 $1 11. Bb1 Nc6 {⩱ Black is obviously better here with more space.}) (9. d3 $6 {White is not challenging our superiority in the centre.} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {⩱ Black is slightly better, and White has already counted on ...[f5]-ideas.}) 9... Bg4 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Gf7f5,Yg4d1] By pinning the knight ...[f5] is again very much a threat for White.} 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 {White wants to win the [e5]-pawn.} Bg6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxe5 {White has won the pawn, but in return, their kingside is seriously weakened, and they are also very much behind in development.} Qh4 {With ...[f5] against pretty much everything in the next move, Black has great compensation.} *

