1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. h3 ({A tricky little move. Basically, White is giving us the honours of 'playing White'. There are many similar moves available for White, and the easiest is to put those lines into two groups. Group 1:} 4. h3 {and 4.a4 Group 2: 4.a3 , 4.Be2 , 4.d3 , 4.g3 .Group 1 moves are useful in the case Black decides to play the 'White side' of the 4.d4 Scotch, and sometimes, with that extra tempo, it is possible to get some advantage. On the other hand, against the moves of Group 2, Black can just play ...[d5] since those moves are not particularly useful for the upcoming reversed Scotch.}) 4... Bb4 $1 {It is important that almost against all the different moves of White at move 4, ...[Bc5] is not good since it allows 5.Nxe5!} 5. Nd5 {Leads to a very equal position.} Nxd5 6. exd5 e4 $1 7. dxc6 (7. Qe2 $6 {White can get into trouble after this!} O-O {⩱}) 7... exf3 8. cxd7+ {This is not good, White should rather be okay with equality.} (8. Qxf3 $1 dxc6 9. Bc4 O-O 10. O-O Qg5 {The position is completely equal.}) (8. cxb7 $2 Bxb7 9. gxf3 O-O {-+ White is pretty much lost here with such a weak kingside.}) 8... Bxd7 9. Qxf3 {White has won a pawn but will have a very tough time finishing development.} O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Re8e1]} 10. Be2 Re8 11. O-O {[%cal Gd2d3] White only needs one move to consolidate, but they are just not in time.} Bc6 12. Qd3 {White's queen has to guard the bishop, but it can only be done by blocking the [c1]-bishop.} (12. Qg4 $2 Re4 13. Qf3 Qe7 {-+ with some unpleasant discovered attack next.}) (12. Qb3 $2 Rxe2 13. Qxb4 Qd5 14. f3 Rae8 {and White can hardly move.}) 12... Qf6 $17 {[%cal Rf6a1,Ga8d8] ...[Rad8] is coming and [b3] is not possible for White.} *

