1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. a3 (4. a3 {Another waiting move, which is called the Gunsberg variation, with the trick of meeting} Bc5 {with} 5. Nxe5 $1 {Luckily for us, it is also preventing 4...Bb4, so we can't mess up our theory here. 🙂}) 4... d5 {This works well, [a3] is not a big deal for White in the Scotch, especially compared to [h3].} 5. Bb5 {This sharp line can happen after many of White's 4th move, but maybe with [a3], it is the most dangerous.} (5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {Pretty much playing as Black again.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 Bg4 {A very easy and safe way for Black to play. You can see that [a3] doesn't help White at all, while [h3] would have prevented this effective setup for Black. ...[Qf6] is next, and Black has a normal game.}) 5... Nxe4 $1 (5... Nxe4 {Since, as you will see,} 6. Nxe5 {is very dubious; there is no reason for refraining from taking this pawn.}) 6. Nxe5 $2 {Critical, but bad. Nevertheless, Black has to know some theory here!} (6. Qe2 Qd6 {is the course, but if you don't want to learn some extra theory, then 6...Nxc3 7.Qxe5 Qe7 is just equal as well.}) 6... Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5e5,Rg5g2] The usual way to deal with the pin on [c6]! 🙂} 7. Nxc6 Qxg2 8. Rf1 a6 9. Nxd5 {A somewhat extreme line, but eventually White will be under attack.} (9. Ba4 Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd7 {-+ White is winning back the piece with the extra pawn.}) 9... axb5 10. Nxc7+ Kd7 11. Nxa8 Kxc6 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gf8c5,Gc8h3,Yh8a8] Even though we are down an exchange, unfortunately for White, the knight on [a8] is not really coming back, so even trading queens is not so comfortable for White, although that would obviously help with defending against the attack.} 12. Qe2 (12. d3 $2 Bg4 13. f3 Ng3 $1 14. hxg3 Bb4+ {with checkmate in a few moves.}) (12. d4 Be6 $1 {The bishop wants to attack from [c4], since it can't be blocked by [d3] anymore.} 13. b3 Be7 {-+ This move is not even against the king... Black just wants and will be up on material after ...[Rxa8].}) 12... Bc5 $1 {[%cal Gh8e8] Preparing to bring the rook to [e8]!} 13. d4 {White has to get some tempo in order to finish development.} Be6 $3 {[%cal Re6c4]} ({The only good move!} 13... Bxd4 14. a4 $1 bxa4 15. Rxa4 {+- is losing for Black.}) 14. a4 (14. f3 Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Bc4+ 16. Ke1 Bxd4 {The rook can't go anywhere.} 17. fxe4 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Rxa8 {∓ Our pawn structure is ideal: the doubled-pawns are very good in defence, it will be tough for White to create a passed pawn on the queenside, while on the kingside, Black can even target White's weaknesses first before pushing the pawns.}) 14... Bb4+ $1 (14... Bc4 $4 {is losing to} 15. axb5+ Bxb5 16. d5+ {+-}) 15. c3 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bxc3+ 17. Bd2 Bc4 $1 {Again, the only move! The line is somewhat difficult, but at least winning for Black.} 18. axb5+ Bxb5 19. Qxb5+ (19. d5+ Qxd5 {-+}) 19... Kxb5 20. Bxc3 Kc6 $19 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Yc6b7,Gb7b5] Black is winning at the end of this chaotic line. White's king is weak, and we also have the plan of ...[b5], ...[Kb7] and taking more material.} *

