1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which, in my opinion, is the most fighting and also much less well-known than the main theoretical lines.} 5. O-O (5. Bxc6 $6 {Similarly to 5.d4, this move just helps Black and makes the bishop on [d6] a completely normal piece by opening up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.} dxc6 6. d4 Bb4 $1 {Maybe the only move which is good to know, but the alternatives are okay as well.} 7. O-O exd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3 {Creating some weak pawns on the queenside.} 9. bxc3 c5 {The position is still around equal, but it looks much more pleasant for Black, with all those pawn weaknesses on White's queenside.}) (5. d4 $6 {A very illogical move and something the [d6]-bishop is really happy about. White is basically opening up a diagonal and the [e5]-square for our silly bishop.} exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 {White's bishop is doing nothing on [b5], and the [d6]-bishop is just about to get active on [e5].} Qe7 {⇆}) 5... O-O {The slower and the less dangerous approach from White. We don't have to worry about [Bg5] or any type of kingside attack after this move, so we will have the time to put our bishop on [d6] to a normal square.} 6. d3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rg5d8] White wants to play [Bg5], which is definitely slightly unpleasant for Black.} h6 $1 {[%cal Yh6g5,Yc1g5] Preventing [Bg5] altogether! Now, White has tried different moves in the practice, which pretty much can all transpose into each other. The main thing is rather to know the setup for Black.} 7. Be3 Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye8e5,Gd6f8,Yd7d5] Our standard regrouping plan we protect the pawn on [e5] and leave the [f8]-square for the bishop, so then we can move our d-pawn and complete development.} 8. a3 {With the goal of having a retreat square for the bishop on [a2].} Bf8 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gd7d6] White has to watch out for ...[d5] as well, not only the more solid ...[d6]. Therefore, in such situations, the most common thing from White is to control the [d5]-square one more time.} 9. Bc4 d6 10. h3 {Useful move against ...[Ng4] or sometimes ...[Bg4].} Be6 {[%cal Gd3d4,Gd6d5] Both sides are finishing development. Now it is about [d4] or ...[d5].} 11. Bxe6 fxe6 $1 {In general, when White is ready to quickly push for [d4], then it is better to take back with the f-pawn.} ({For example, after} 11... Rxe6 12. Nd5 {, Black is definitely not getting ...[d5] anytime soon, and after the usual} Ne7 13. Nxf6+ Rxf6 14. d4 $1 {White is somewhat better.}) 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 (14. Bxd4 $6 e5 15. Be3 c6 {with ...[d5] next.}) 14... c6 $132 {We can play either ...[e5] or ...[d5] in the next move, depending on what White does, and it is just a complicated position with chances for both sides.} *

