1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...Bd6 line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact that our pieces, especially bishops, are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {Sometimes White starts with this move, but the transposition to 5.d3 is very likely, for example} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {.}) 5... O-O 6. a3 {White is waiting for Black to play ...[h6] or ...[Re8], when [g4] would be much more effective. Also, this move creates some squares for the bishop on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} (6. g4 $2 {Shouldn't work without a pawn on [h6] or rook on [e8].} Nd4 $1 {(A typical reply to [g4]. We are attacking at least for a trade two possible attackers from White, and if White takes on [d4], it can quickly open up the position in our favour.)} 7. g5 Ne8 {That's why it is important, that the rook was not on [e8] yet.} 8. Bc4 c6 {⩱ Black will move away the bishop next, and then ...[d5]. White clearly has no attack here.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {In such cases, when [g4] could be dangerous, this is the move to play.} 7. Bc4 c6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Yd7d5,Gd6c5] Continuing the plan, preparing to play ...[Bc7] and then ...[d5] if possible. White has tried quite a few moves in this position, but none seems to pose serious problems for Black.} 8. Nxd4 (8. Bg5 h6 {Since, as we will see, White has no chances to attack us, it is useful to include this move.} 9. Bh4 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Be7 {Solving this issue of the pin, Black has no problems. Next is ...[d6] followed by ...[Be6]. 10.gxf3 opens the g-file for the rook, but there is simply no attack. 10...Be7 Breaking the pin. 11.Rg1 Kh8 ∓ We can play ...[Nh7] or ...[Nh5] anytime, and besides that, we have the option of pushing on the queenside with ...[b5], ...[a5].}) 8... exd4 9. Ne2 Bc7 $1 {We can keep the bishop on this diagonal, since the [d4]-pawn doesn't require protection for now.} 10. Nxd4 d5 $1 {Black is getting huge compensation for the pawn since White's king still hasn't castled, and even on the kingside, it will not be completely safe.} 11. exd5 Bg4 $1 {Bringing out one more piece with a tempo!} 12. f3 Re8+ 13. Ne2 cxd5 14. Bb5 {White is gaining a tempo in order to castle.} Bd7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. O-O d4 {[%csl Yc2,Ye3][%cal Gf6d5,Ga8c8,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] Black has full compensation for the pawn, White has some weak squares and passive pieces, while Black can try a lot of different plans.} *

