1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 After the text move, we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.} 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...Bd6 line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact that our pieces, especially bishops, are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {Sometimes White starts with this move, but the transposition to 5.d3 is very likely, for example} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 {Very logical. White is creating an unpleasant pin and uses the fact that it is not so easy to break it with ...[Be7] since the [e5]-pawn also needs protection.} h6 $1 {It looks strange that Black is creating a target for the [g4]-[g5] advance, but this whole line lies on a very concrete idea.} 7. Bh4 Be7 $1 {Eventually, Black can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected!} ({Instead,} 7... Nd4 {looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.}) 8. Bxc6 {Definitely the test for Black. White is going for the [e5]-pawn.} (8. O-O {Change of plans for White, but of course, the bishop is not ideally placed on [h4], since it can be traded for our bad bishop quite easily.} d6 9. h3 Nh7 {Offering the bishops' trade. Later, the knight can go to [g5] and fight for the centre by challenging the [f3]-knight.} 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {Rerouting the knight to [g6], from where it will support the [e5]-pawn and can sometimes jump to [f4].} 11. d4 Ng6 {Black will play ...[Ng5] next, and it is hard to see anything wrong with this position.}) 8... bxc6 {In case White is not taking on [e5], it is better to have this structure and play ...[d6] next.} 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Re7h4] This is the tactical point of ...[Be7].} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxc6 $1 {Everything would be very easy if not for this intermediate move!} (11. dxe4 Qxe5 12. O-O Rb8 {With ...[d6] and ...[f5] coming, it is White who has to be careful to keep the balance.}) 11... dxc6 12. dxe4 {Quite risky, White can't castle for a while after this move.} (12. Qe2 $1 {The only try for advantage.} Bh3 $1 {Yes, somewhat computerish, but connecting the rooks makes ...[Qb4] a huge threat.} 13. dxe4 Qb4 $1 {and now the queen can't take the knight because of the pin on the e-file.} 14. gxh3 Qxb2 15. O-O Qxc3 {∓ In heavy piece endgames king safety is the most important, well, it is not really a close call at this position. 13.Qxe4 Qf6! Black is fine in all the lines, according to my analyses. You can find many examples in the full course.}) 12... Ba6 $1 {[%cal Ra6f1]} 13. Qd4 Rfd8 {[%cal Rd8d1] Castles for both sides are prevented.} 14. Qe3 f5 {White is able to hold equality according to the computer, but the position is not much fun.} *

