{Welcome to the third Quickstarter Guide of the course! This time, it is the Italian Game which is the topic of this chapter.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 (3... Nf6 {This is the sharpest part of the repertoire. In one case White also wants to play sharp with} 4. Ng5 {, but in the other one, 4.d3 , it is really Black who is inviting complications with 4...d5 .}) 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 {The Polerio Defense.} 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gb5d3,Gd3e2,Gb5a4] Theoretically speaking, here you have to learn the most in the repertoire, and I highly recommend to check out the full course for more lines. Even if you will not get those in your games, there is much to learn there about how to play this type of opening lines. In order to reduce the workload and surprise your opponent there are novelties early on in almost every major line. Normally, people who play the Italian like slow, maneuvering games, which very few people in the world truly understand, and unfortunately your authors are not among them. 🙂 In any case, here you'll not have slow lines. 🙂 What you'll have instead is: • The refutation of the 'Streamers' Gambit in the 4.Qe2 Italian • Lines where White is not going for the main option against 4.d3 d5, therefore not really getting anywhere. • Couple of lines showing why 7.Bb3 is not dangerous against the early ...[d5] variation. • The 'expected lines' in the 7.Bb5 variation, where Black is doing very well, unless White is prepared for the strong 11.Kh1! option.} (7... bxc6 {• Showing why the} 8. Be2 {line isn't dangerous against the Polerio Defense. • A rare line to surprise your opponents instead of entering crazy complications in the 8.Bd3 variation. • An example why it is not good for White to take on [c6] after the 8.Qf3 line.}) *

