1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4]} ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. O-O $6 {[%csl Yc4] This happens quite a lot in online games, but it is not the Berlin Defense 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 when this move actually is the main line. The bishop is much worse on [c4] since Black can play ...[d5] in the next move with a tempo.} (4. Nc3 Nxe4 $1 {is shown in the Scotch Quickstarter.}) (4. d4 exd4 {is the Scotch Gambit.}) 4... Nxe4 {[%cal Gd7d5]} 5. Re1 $2 {The most common move, and a very bad one as well, but in any case, White is already fighting for equality.} (5. Bd5 {wins back the pawn but gives up the bishop pair.} Nf6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 {⩱ Black is already slightly better, and it is also possible to castle long to have a sharper game.}) (5. d4 d5 $1 {Protecting the knight and opening up a diagonal for the bishop first, and later we can take on [d4].} 6. Bb5 exd4 7. Qxd4 Qd7 $1 {We wanted to show this line for this unusual way to break the pin. The queen was stopping the development of the [f8]-bishop, but now it has to go somewhere.} 8. Qa4 Nc5 {⩱ With ...[Be7] and ...[O-O] to follow, Black is clearly better.}) 5... d5 $1 {Winning a huge tempo on the bishop.} 6. Bb5 Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rc5f2] For now we can ignore the defense of the [e5]-pawn, since we have a stronger threat on [f2].} 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. Bxc6 Nxf2 $1 {This is the fastest way to win the game.} 10. Kxf2 Qf6+ $1 {[%cal Rc5d4,Rf6f2,Rf6d4] Black is taking back all the material.} 11. Kg1 Qxd4+ 12. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 13. Kh1 bxc6 $19 {Black is two pawns up and completely winning.} *

