1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Qe2 {White is protecting the pawn on [e4], but in a somewhat unusual way.} ({Either our opponent doesn't want to allow the} 4. d3 d5 {line for Black or just relies on some tricks. The latter is more likely. 🙂}) 4... Bc5 {Developing the bishop to the most active square. There is no reason to play ...[d5] immediately, since the only good part of [Qe2] is that White is prepared for it.} 5. Ng5 $2 {This move looks completely ridiculous; why wait a move and then attack on [f7], when Black can already protect there with castling? However, this is excellent 'content' for streams and YouTube channels, to show some tricks which actually can win the game for you quickly, if Black is not careful, so I expect to see this line online quite often in the future.} (5. Bxf7+ $2 {There is one trick! Tempting, but a very bad move.} Kxf7 6. Qc4+ {White is taking back the bishop, but completely losing the centre.} d5 $1 7. Qxc5 Nxe4 8. Qe3 Re8 {∓ With ...[Kg8] to follow, we will pretty much complete our 'castle' and White not only lost the centre, but the queen on [e3] also looks pretty weird.}) 5... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4c2,Rd4e2] This move completely refutes White's trick. We can ignore the threat on [f7].} (5... O-O 6. Nxf7 Rxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qc4+ {This would be White's trick, and indeed, with the extra exchange, they are better.}) 6. Bxf7+ (6. Qd3 d5 $1 7. exd5 Bf5 {-+ and Black is already winning a lot of material.}) 6... Kf8 {[%cal Rh7h6,Rd4c2,Rd4e2] White has many problems, [e2] and [c2] is hanging, and ... [h6] is also a threat.} 7. Qc4 (7. Qd3 h6 8. c3 hxg5 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Bb3 d5 {-+ White has managed to avoid losing material, but in return they couldn't finish the development.}) 7... Qe7 {[%cal Rh7h6] ...[h6] is threatening to take the bishop on [f7].} 8. b4 Bb6 9. a4 a5 $19 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yh7h6,Yh6g5] We stopped White's desperate tries on the queenside and are about to win material with ...[h6].} *

