1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5] We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Ng5 $6 {[%cal Rg5f7,Yd1f3,Yf3h5] Probably the trickiest among the dubious moves from White! Since our knight is missing from [f6], White is trying to take advantage of it and quickly attack the [f7]-square, just like in the Fried Liver variation. This is definitely a worse version for them, though, since they lost an important tempo by playing [d3].} (6. Bg5 $2 {Really bad! Just helps for Black to protect on [e5] with a tempo!} f6 $1) (6. Bxd5 $2 {Extremely bad! White is giving up the strong bishop for nothing.} Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qd6 {∓ Black can play ...[Bf5]/...[Bg4] next, followed by ...[O-O-O].}) (6. Nc3 {Not a particularly dangerous move, since Black can just continue development without worrying about the [e5]-pawn.} Be6 $1 {With the threat of taking on [c3] and then [c4], creating tripled pawns for White.} 7. Ng5 {This leads to massive simplifications, but White doesn't have anything better.} Nxc3 8. Nxe6 Nxd1 9. Nxd8 Rxd8 10. Kxd1 Na5 $1 {Taking back the bishop with an equal endgame.}) (6. c3 $6 {White wants [Qb3] next and attack on [f7].} Nb6 $1 {The only move to know! Fortunately, it is the move Black wants to play anyway. Now White will have to move the bishop away to [b5] or [b3], and basically instead of the useful [O-O], they lost a tempo with [c3].}) (6. h3 {White should be playing very aggressively, and instead they are just preventing ...[Bg4].} Bf5 {Black wants ...[Qd7] followed by ...[O-O-O].}) 6... f6 $1 {A very important move, there is no more sacrifice on [f7]!} ({In case of} 6... Be7 {,} 7. Nxf7 {is interesting for White!}) 7. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rc4d5] It is pretty easy to go wrong here as Black.} (7. Ne4 $2 Be6 {∓ In this way, White just lost two moves with the knight.}) (7. Qf3 $2 {This fails tactically.} Nd4 $1 8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. Bxd5 Nxc2+ 10. Kd1 Nxa1 {-+}) 7... Bb4 $1 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Ge8g8,Rb4e1] Developing, protecting the knight on [d5] and preparing to castle!} (7... Nxc3 $6 8. Bf7+ $1 Kd7 {(8...Ke7 9.bxc3 ⩲ Black can't take the knight, and [Ba3] is a threat. )} 9. bxc3 fxg5 10. Qg4+ Ke7 11. Qf3 {+- Quite stunning position; White is down a piece, and they can make a quiet move just to protect the bishop, but Black is helpless against the threats of [Ba3]+ and [Bxg5]+.}) 8. Nge4 Be6 {Now everything looks safe for Black.} 9. O-O O-O $10 {Black is at least equal, but with the potential to take over the game, because of the space advantage.} *

