1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re2e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} (6... Bg4 $6 7. h3 $1 {Black has to give up the bishop if they don't want to lose the [e5]-pawn.} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {⩲ In particular, the light-squared bishop is very strong. White has a nice advantage. 7...Bh5 8.g4! Bg6 9.Nxe5 ± And with further exchanges planned, White has nothing to fear as far as the king is concerned; it can still go to the queenside, where it will be perfectly safe.}) 7. O-O {[%cal Gd3d4,Rd4e5] White first castles and keeps the [d4]-option available.} Nb6 $1 {Our knight is not loose anymore on [d5], and we are also gaining a tempo on the [c4] bishop.} 8. Bb5 (8. Bb3 {It is quite problematic to play ...[O-O] in this position, so we have to develop our light-squared bishop and queen and go for ...[O-O-O].} Bg4 {and ...[Nd4] is a threat.} 9. Be3 Qe7 $1 {Followed by ...[O-O-O]. This square may look strange for the queen, but it is pretty standard in these variations. The point is that if the queen would go to [d7], then after [h3]-...[Bh5], the trick of [Nxe5] can work for White, especially if the queen is protected on [e2].}) 8... Bd6 9. d4 {[%csl Yc6,Ye5][%cal Rb5e8,Rd4e5] This is how White should play, putting maximum pressure in our centre.} O-O {We have to finish the development and get out of the pins with our king.} 10. Bxc6 (10. dxe5 {This allows Black to recapture on [e5] without compromising the structure.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Black has no problems, ...[Bf5] is next with an equal position.}) 10... bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5][%cal Gb6d5,Gc8g4,Gf8f3] Well, if only pawn structure would matter, then we could start looking for a new variation. 🙂 Fortunately, this position is much more than that. Black can develop enough counterplay by using the activity of their pieces.} 12. Nxe5 {White is very ambitious. Why block the pawn when they can take it immediately? 🙂} (12. Nbd2 Qe8 {⇆ And Black already has very good play, since White's main idea, which is [Ne4], can be met by ...[Bg4]. Our next moves are very easy, ...[Bg4], ...[Nd5], ...[Qg6], then doubling on the f-file comes, and we are putting a lot of pressure on White's position.}) 12... Qe7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ye7e2]} 13. Re1 Qh4 $1 {[%cal Yd6e5,Ye2e5,Rh4f2] With this body fake, which is what our queen did, we have a threat on [f2] right now.} 14. f4 Ba6 $17 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Re1][%cal Yh4e1] Black has excellent compensation and objectively a much better position.} *

