1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%cal Gf1e1,Rf3e5,Re1e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4] This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines. Black forces White to make a decision: they can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case, it will be easier for us to protect [e5] since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, they can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7]-pawn.} 7. Bb3 {[%csl Gc6]} ({I believe this is easier to handle than} 7. Bb5 {since, after all, the main problem with our position is the [e5]-pawn, which will now be easier because the knight on [c6] can't be pinned.}) 7... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd1,Yf3][%cal Yg4d1,Gd8e7,Ge8c8] Of course! Since the [f7]-square is the problem, not the [e5]-pawn needed protection now, but stopping [Ng5] was crucial. Also, this move perfectly fits into Black's plan, which is ...[Qe7] followed by ...[O-O-O].} (7... Bd6 $4 8. Ng5 $1 O-O 9. Qh5 {+- and White is winning.}) 8. h3 {In order to have [Nxe5] tricks or sometimes just [g4] and go after the [e5]-pawn.} Bh5 9. Re1 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8c8,Yc6e5,Ye7e5] Of course, this is not the ideal position for the queen, but it is not only protecting the pawn on [e5] but also preparing ...[O-O-O], which is very important for Black.} (9... Qf6 $2 {This is not good, because after} 10. g4 $1 Bg6 11. Nc3 {± Black has problems with castling, since [Bg5] is there.}) 10. g4 $6 {Logical to go after the [e5]-pawn, but it is quite weakening.} (10. d4 O-O-O $1 {Black was just in time to castle and pin on the d-file.}) (10. a4 {It looks like the right moment to insert [a4], since Black normally has to reply with ...[a5], and then the knight can still go towards the weakened [b5]-square from [b1].} a5 {This is Black's standard response to [a4]. It is not good to allow [a5]-[a6] .} 11. Nc3 {The knight will have a nice square on [b5], but this slower approach also means that the [e5]-pawn is not in danger. When this is the case, Black is pretty much always fine.} O-O-O 12. Nb5 f6 {⇆ Supporting the centre, but also preparing a ...[g5]-...[g4] expansion on the kingside.}) 10... Bg6 11. Qe2 (11. d4 $6 O-O-O {⩱ and White is not winning anything, but rather losing the [d4]-pawn.}) 11... f6 {Long castle was also possible, Black would have good compensation in those lines as well.} 12. d4 $1 {Otherwise Black just castles long with a better position.} O-O-O 13. dxe5 h5 $1 {Immediately starting the counterplay, which will be dangerous even after the trade of the queens. The variation will be pretty long, but it is not good to stop with down a pawn and with the opponent just trading queens. 🙂} 14. exf6 Qxe2 15. Rxe2 hxg4 16. fxg7 $1 (16. hxg4 $4 Rd1+ 17. Re1 Be4 $1 {Black is winning the game!} 18. Rxd1 Bxf3) 16... Bxg7 {With the bishop taking on [g4], White can avoid the mating attack from Black.} 17. Be6+ Kb8 18. Bxg4 {[%csl Gg4]} Rd1+ $1 19. Re1 Rxc1 $1 {Black is taking back the material.} 20. Rxc1 Bxb2 21. Nbd2 Bxc2 $132 {The position is more or less equal, but with passed pawns on different sides of the board, it is very sharp as well.} *

