1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O Nb6 {This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines. Black forces White to make a decision: they can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case, it will be easier for us to protect [e5] since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, they can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7]-pawn.} 7. Bb5 {[%cal Yb5c6,Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. d4 {Leads to forcing play, which is just fine for Black, but it is not easy, so it is an important line to know.} e4 $1 {We have no other move. Otherwise, we will just lose a pawn, or our structure will be very bad.} 9. Re1 (9. Ng5 O-O $1 {Thanks to this small trick, Black can keep the material balance.} 10. Nxe4 Nxd4 {with complete equality, since White can't take on [d4] because of ...[Bxh2]+. 10.Bxc6 bxc6 11.Nxe4 Bxh2+! Winning back the pawn. 12.Kxh2 Qh4+ 13.Kg1 Qxe4 If anything, I even like Black a little bit more because, with opposite-coloured bishops, the attacks can be more dangerous. White's castled position is also missing a pawn.}) 9... f5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yf5e4] There is no other decent way to protect the pawn on [e4].} 10. Bg5 (10. d5 $4 {just loses a pawn.} Nxd5 {∓ White can't take because of ...[Bxh2]+.}) 10... Qd7 {[%csl Rd7,Re8][%cal Yb5e8]} 11. c4 $1 {White has to find this move in order to pose any problems.} O-O {By going out from the pin, we are threatening to take the [f3]-knight.} 12. c5 $1 {White's moves are much more difficult in this line!} exf3 13. cxb6 {It is much more critical to take here since now, if Black recaptures, the [d5]-threat would still be there.} (13. cxd6 Qxd6 {The position is not so insane anymore.}) 13... h6 $1 {Forcing White's bishop to a worse square, or we can just take it on the next move.} 14. Bh4 f4 $132 {With the threats of ...[g5] and ...[Qg4]. The mess continues, but it is White who has to find very difficult moves.} *

