1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O Nb6 {This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines. Black forces White to make a decision: they can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case, it will be easier for us to protect [e5] since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, they can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7]-pawn.} 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Re1 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re1e5,Rb5e8] By far, the most popular move. White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5] The only way to protect the pawn.} 9. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5] Maximum pressure on the [e5]-pawn!} O-O 10. Bxc6 {White is completely ruining our pawn structure, but what we get in return is the pair of bishops and dynamic potential.} (10. dxe5 {White is not creating doubled pawns on the c-file, but in return, they keep the light-squared bishop.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 fxe5 $1 {By taking with the f-pawn, Black accepts a worse structure and wants to compensate it by active piece play. Having a semi-open f-file for the rook is a good start for that.} 12. Nc3 {The knight is going towards the beautiful outpost on [e4].} Bf5 {Developing and anticipating the knight's arrival on [e4].} 13. Ne4 Bb4 $1 {Before White could stabilise their nice position, we are hitting all of their pieces! Black is fine in all the lines from here.}) 10... bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5] We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. h3 $6 {[%cal Yh3g4,Yc8g4] It is very understandable that White wants to stop all kinds of ...[Bg4]-ideas, but the move is very slow, and it is not developing a piece.} (12. Nxe5 $4 Bxe5 {-+ White can't take back the piece because of back rank problems.}) (12. Nbd2 $6 {The knight is going towards [e4], but even if it reaches it, we have ...[Bg4] and an annoying pin on the other knight.} Bg4 $1 13. Qe2 Bh5 $1 {A nice prophylactic move! Black prepares to play ...[Nd5], and then the queen can't hit our bishop with a tempo in the form of [Qc4]. This move also demonstrates that it is not so easy to improve White's position.} 14. Qe4 Nd5 {⇆ Black has very good play. We can continue with ...[Qf6] and ...[Rae8], and it is still not so easy to mobilise White's queenside.}) 12... e4 $1 {No more blockade on [e4]! Even if we lose this pawn, it opens up the position completely towards White's king.} 13. Ng5 {White obviously can't take the pawn because of the usual ...[Bh2]+.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6f2]} 14. Nxe4 Qg6 {[%cal Rc8h3] Another issue of the [h3] move is that it gives a target for our light-squared bishop.} 15. Kh1 Be6 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1][%cal Ga8d8,Gd8e8] Preparing to bring our last piece into the attack. White is seriously underdeveloped and has a tough defensive task here.} *

