1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O Nb6 {This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines. Black forces White to make a decision: they can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case, it will be easier for us to protect [e5] since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, they can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7]-pawn.} 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Re1 {By far, the most popular move. White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 9. d4 O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. Bg5 {Probably White's most serious try for an advantage, first bringing out the bishop and only then trying to blockade on [e4]. With [Bh4]-[Bg3], it also can be a good defensive piece.} Qe8 {[%cal Ge8g6,Gg6h5] In this type of structure, the queen has nice squares on [g6] or [h5], putting pressure on White's queenside.} 13. Nbd2 (13. Nc3 $2 {is just bad.} Bg4 $1 14. Re3 Qh5 {-+ White is pretty much lost here.}) 13... Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 $1 {Normally, we don't want to give up this bishop so easily, but now we can follow up with ...[e4]!} 15. Nxf3 e4 $1 {[%cal Gb6d5,Ge8g6,Rf8f3] If the knight moves anywhere, the queen comes to [e5], and Black is winning material. White already has to find a couple of difficult moves to save the game.} *

