1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. d3 {White wants to play the 'slow' Italian.} d5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight! Of course, things will not be easy because, in this case, everyone will play like that. Normally, the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 {Basically, the only move for White. The [e4]-pawn is under attack after all.} Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]-pawn. From it, we derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the centre and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins, and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O Nb6 {This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines. Black forces White to make a decision: they can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case, it will be easier for us to protect [e5] since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, they can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7]-pawn.} 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Bxc6+ $1 {This is objectively White's strongest continuation. It still can transpose to less dangerous and previously mentioned lines since [Bxc6] is possible later as well.} bxc6 9. Nxe5 $1 {This is White's point. They are not waiting for ...[f6], but changing the move order and want to pin the bishop. According to the machine, this is White's main try for an objective advantage against the 4...[d5] variation. It is hard to argue with it, but the good thing is that it is very far from common knowledge at this point.} (9. Re1 f6 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 fxe5 {This would be one possible transposition to previously mentioned lines.}) 9... Bxe5 10. Re1 Qe7 {Very few games have reached this position, and here, both 'normal' continuations are quite okay for Black.} 11. d4 (11. f4 Bd4+ 12. Kh1 {It somewhat opens up the king, so we can hope for some counterplay on the f-file.} Be6 13. f5 O-O 14. fxe6 Nd5 {∞ (We don't have to rush by taking on [e6] since the f-file will be opened anyway, but with the text move, we can make White's development more difficult. The difference between this and the strongest 11.Kh1! line is that here, Black has the dark-squared bishop, which is much more active than the light-squared bishop in those lines.)}) (11. Kh1 $1 {A very difficult move to find without serious preparation. White has chances here for the advantage, but as you can see in the main course, with precise play, Black is holding even here.} O-O 12. f4 f6 13. fxe5 fxe5 {This is how the line starts, Black's counterplay should come from the f-file and on the kingside mainly.}) 11... Bxh2+ $1 {We will not have a very bad structure in this line.} 12. Kxh2 Be6 $132 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7,Yh2][%cal Ge8c8,Ge8g8] With a complicated position, Black's structure is not nearly as bad as in some other lines, and also White's kingside isn't perfect. In the next move, Black can castle on either side, depending on their ambition.} *

