1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. d3 ({White's only alternative to} 6. Bb5+ {. The point is that it is still not possible to take on [d5].}) 6... h6 {Sending the knight back to a more passive square.} (6... Nxd5 $4 {is losing to} 7. Qf3 {+-}) 7. Nf3 e4 $1 {One more tempo on the knight; since the [d3]-pawn has to protect the bishop on [c4], it can't take on [e4].} 8. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yd3e4,Ge2c4] White is not only pinning the pawn and therefore protecting the knight, but the queen is also protecting the bishop after [dxe4], so we can't wait and protect on [e4] but have to react.} (8. Nd4 {Black can easily regain the material against this move and keep their lead in development.} Bc5 9. c3 O-O 10. O-O exd3 11. Bxd3 Qxd5 {⩱}) 8... Nxc4 {Black is getting the pair of bishops and the lead in the development for a pawn.} 9. dxc4 Bc5 {[%cal Yf3d4,Yc5d4] The bishop is very active on [c5], and very importantly, it doesn't allow White's knight to jump to [d4].} 10. Nfd2 {[%cal Gd2b3,Rb3c5] The knight was not hanging yet, but it wants to attack the bishop on [c5]. It is White's most common move in both OTB and online chess.} O-O 11. Nb3 {[%cal Rb3c5]} Bg4 $1 {Very important! The queen's only good square is [f1], but it will make short castle impossible for quite a few moves.} 12. Qf1 (12. Qd2 $4 e3 13. fxe3 Ne4 {-+ Black is completely winning with ...[Qh4]+.}) 12... Bb4+ {Another very important move. Black is going away from the attack with a tempo, and if White doesn't want to lose time, then they have to play [c3] and take away that square from the knight.} 13. c3 (13. Bd2 $2 Bxd2+ 14. N1xd2 Re8 {∓ With ...[e3] coming in the next move, Black is much better.}) (13. Nc3 c6 {⩱ White is under big pressure.}) 13... Be7 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ye7f6,Yd7e5,Yb7b5] Looks somewhat surprising to put the bishop on [e7], but the point is that White is not going to castle short, so the bishop's role on [d6] would be limited. It can be more useful from [f6], and also it allows the queen to keep attacking [d5], making ... [b5]-ideas stronger.} 14. h3 Bh5 {[%cal Gh5d1] If White wants to castle long, they have to weaken themselves more.} 15. g4 Bg6 $17 {[%csl Yd3,Yf3][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] The knight has very nice targets on [d3] and [f3].} *

