1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Ba4 $2 {One of the four commonly played moves for White, but it is simply horrible. The bishop is loose on [a4] and Black can immediately take advantage.} h6 9. Nf3 e4 $1 {[%csl Rf3] Winning more time against the knight.} 10. Qe2 (10. Ne5 $4 {This is White's main point with [Ba4]. Now, they attack [c6] with a tempo!} Qd4 $1 {Winning a piece with a double attack.} 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Nxc6 Qc5 {-+ The knight is trapped on [c6].}) 10... Be6 $1 {This is the correct way to block the pin. Since the bishop on [e7] could be potentially taken by White's knight, we can't trap the piece.} 11. Ne5 Qd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rd4a4] White has no choice but to take on [c6].} 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13. Qb5 (13. Nxc6 Qc5 {It is very good that we don't have a bishop on [e7] now.} 14. Qa6 Bc8 15. Qa4 Bd7 {-+ and the knight is lost.}) 13... Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rd4f2,Rd4e5] Attacking not only [f2], but also [e5]!} 14. Qxc6+ Ke7 15. Qb7+ Kd6 $19 {[%cal Rd6e5,Rd4f2] White is either losing the knight or the pawns on [f2] and [g2].} *

