1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 {This looks like the most natural square for the bishop, so it is not a surprise that this move is the most common in the current position.} h6 $1 {We don't have an alternative at this point; we gave up a pawn for time and development, so we should use it!} 9. Nh3 {This looks like an absolutely crazy move, but there is more to it. White puts the knight on a very bad square but does not lose a tempo from the ...[e4] push, which is one of the main parts of Black's counterplay.} (9. Nh3 {They are not afraid of} Bxh3 {because after castling short and playing [Bf3]-[Bg2], the king will be safe. It will be tough to break White on the light squares.}) 9... g5 {I like this move, as it is clearly aimed against the [h3]-knight. White can't castle currently since ...[g4]! would trap the knight, and this slows down White's development on the kingside.} 10. d3 {[%cal Yd3e4,Gc1e3,Gh3g1,Gg1f3] White controls the [e4]-square, opens the diagonal for the bishop, and also prepares [Ng1]-[Nf3], since Black's ...[e4] is not dangerous anymore.} Qb6 {[%cal Yg5g4,Gf8c5,Rb6f2]} ({(After 10 moves, we are already in unexplored territory 1 OTB game! Pretty much everyone plays)} 10... Bg7 {in this position, but keeping the option of playing with ...[g4] and then ...[Bc5] could become the new main line in one day.}) 11. Nc3 {White wants to develop, and this move is also very useful against ...[Bc5] because of [Na4]-threats.} Nb7 {[%cal Gb7c5,Gb7d6]} ({Since the aggressive} 11... g4 {(doesn't work, we just slightly improve our position while keeping the option of playing ...[Bc5] at some moment. Therefore, the usual route for that knight ...[c5]-...[Nc6] is changed. Obviously, the move looks very slow for a position where we are down a pawn, but we already have decent positional compensation with space advantage in the centre, with White's knight being an issue on [h3], and our opponent still has to develop somehow on the queenside.)}) 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. dxe4 {[%cal Ge1g1,Yd1g4] Now White wants to castle since ...[g4] is not trapping the knight anymore because it can be just taken.} Be6 {And Black has an excellent position with ...[Rd8] coming.} (13... Be6 {It is important that White can't play} 14. O-O {. Let's see why.}) 14. O-O $4 Rd8 15. Qe1 g4 $19 {Black is winning the knight.} *

