1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 h6 9. Nf3 e4 {[%csl Rf3] This is the issue with the knight on [f3] — Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d4,Rd4e5,Rd4f2] We have the huge threat of ...[Qd4] now, attacking the knight and [f2] as well.} 11. O-O Qd6 {Continuing to gain time against White's loose knight and also eyeing the [h2]-pawn!} 12. Ng4 $2 ({Not much better than} 12. Nc4 $4 {White loses control from the [g4]-square with this trade.} Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Ng4 $1 {White already has no defence here.} 14. g3 Nxf2 15. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qd4+ 17. Kg2 Qxc4 {-+ Black is just up an exchange, and White's king remains weak.}) (12. d4 $1 {White has to give back the pawn to secure equality.} Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 O-O {The position is more or less equal. Black surely has no problems.}) 12... Bxg4 $1 13. Bxg4 h5 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Rf6g4] With ...[Ng4] coming next, Black's queen is really well-placed on [d6].} 14. Be2 (14. Bh3 Ng4 $1 15. g3 Nxf2 $1 16. Rxf2 h4 $1 {Black's attack is very dangerous.}) 14... Ng4 15. g3 (15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. g3 Qe6 $1 {Black has the time to castle long and then just win the game on the h-file.}) 15... Nxh2 $1 16. d4 {[%cal Gc1f4] White opens up the bishop with a tempo, it should help the defence.} (16. Kxh2 Bxf2 $1 17. Rxf2 h4 {-+ Black's attack is decisive.}) 16... exd3 {[%cal Rd6g3]} 17. Bf4 {White brings the bishop with a tempo, so White is not losing the game on [g3].} Qe6 $1 {[%cal Rd3e2,Rh2f1]} 18. Re1 {It looks like that White is escaping with this move.} O-O-O $1 19. Kxh2 (19. cxd3 Qh3 {-+ With ...[Ng4] or ...[h4] next, Black is winning.}) (19. Bxd3 Qxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Nf3+ {+ -+ just wins for Black.}) 19... dxe2 20. Qxe2 Qxe2 21. Rxe2 Rd1 $19 {[%cal Rd1a1] White didn't get checkmated, but they will lose in the endgame instead.} *

