1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 h6 9. Nf3 e4 {This is the issue with the knight on [f3] — Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 11. c3 {[%cal Rb2b4,Yc3d4] White is preventing ...[Qd4] and also introducing the [b4]-idea into the position.} O-O ({Black is doing very well in the main line as well, which is} 11... Bd6 {, but I prefer the text move, which 'prevents' White from going to lines with [f4] since it would be weird to protect a knight which is not hanging and stop [O-O] possibilities.}) 12. b4 $6 {Not as much as with 12.d4, but White is weakening their position with this move since it is not just a piece for free.} (12. d4 $2 {Very suspicious. Once White plays [c3], the knight will not be stable at all on [d3].} exd3 13. Nxd3 Bb6 14. O-O Re8 {White has very unpleasant pressure on their position.}) (12. O-O Qc7 $1 13. d4 exd3 14. Nxd3 {This is not ideal for White; the pawn should be on [c2] to protect the knight.} Bd6 {Attacking [h2] with tempo is pretty important.} 15. g3 Bh3 16. Re1 Rad8 {Setting up the X-ray on the queen. White is under a lot of pressure.}) 12... Bd6 13. f4 (13. d4 {Has similar problems to those shown a move before, and ...[b4] also weakened the queenside even more.} exd3 14. Nxd3 Nc4 15. O-O Nd5 {Just by occupying the weak squares, Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn.}) 13... exf3 14. Nxf3 Re8 $1 {[%cal Rc8a6] With the threat of ...[Ba6].} 15. O-O (15. bxa5 $2 Ba6 16. d3 Bc5 $1 {White can't castle, and the extra piece they have is definitely not doing anything.}) 15... Qe7 $1 {[%cal Re7e2] The [e2]-bishop is obviously much more valuable than the [a5]-knight.} 16. Bd3 Qc7 $1 {Just a nice illustrative line showing White's queenside doesn't matter at all.} 17. bxa5 Bg4 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Gc7,Gd6,Ge8,Gf6,Gg4][%cal Rd6h2,Yd6c5,Rf6h5] It seems like that Black is up a piece or two, and the engine's -3 evaluation confirms that.} *

