1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here; there are many continuations with around equal value, and I tried to choose a more human one.} Rb8 {Bringing the rook into play and renewing the threat on the [b5]-bishop.} 9. Bxc6+ $2 {White is taking another pawn, but Black's lead in development is going to be even more serious, and the position is opening up for the bishops.} Nxc6 10. Qxc6+ Nd7 $1 {[%cal Rd8g5] We even win a tempo by blocking the check!} 11. d3 {White is protecting the knight and trying to have some control in the centre.} (11. d4 {A good try from White, trying to gain some time to finish development, but Black shouldn't be interested in this pawn!} exd4 $2 {would be a very bad move, just giving White extra time to finish their development.} 12. O-O {∞ Things are already far from clear here. 11...Be7! 12.Nf3 Rb6 13.Qa4 O-O Black is just so much better developed that we don't have to count the pawns at all. 14.O-O Bb7 15.Nxe5 Nxe5 16.dxe5 We are down 3 pawns, but the game is over. 16...Rg6! 17.f3 Bxf3! 18.Rxf3 Qd1 + -+ Black is winning a lot of material.}) 11... Be7 $1 12. Ne4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yf7f5] This is the main move, but putting the knight in the way of the f-pawn is dubious.} Rb6 13. Qa4 (13. Qc4 {Not a better place for the queen. It will not prevent ...[O-O] because Black can kick it away with tempo.} Ba6 $1 14. Qa4 f5 {∓}) 13... f5 14. Ng3 O-O $19 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc8b7,Gb6g6,Rg6g2] ...[Rg6] and ... [Bb7] are coming. White is having huge problems on the kingside.} *

