1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here; there are many continuations with around equal value, and I tried to choose a more human one.} Rb8 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yd3f5,Yg5e4] This is the main move. In case of a trade on [e4], White wants to take back with the bishop. Also, in general, we already saw that ...[f5] is a very dangerous idea for Black. Thus, the bishop tries to fight against it.} Bd6 {[%csl Yf3,Rg3][%cal Yd6g3] Besides being a developing move and preparing ...[O-O], the bishop also targets the [g3]-square, highlighting the fact that White's queen doesn't really have a lot of squares to go to.} 10. Nc3 {The most common move in the position, but it already gives a big advantage for Black.} (10. O-O Bg4 $1 {The queen doesn't really have a good square. On [g3], it would be on the diagonal of the bishop, while on [e3] it could be attacked by ...[Nd5].}) 10... Bg4 $1 11. Qe3 (11. Qg3 {It looks extremely risky to put the queen into the dark-squared bishop's diagonal.} e4 12. Qe3 {For now, White is avoiding material losses because of the pin on the e-file.} O-O 13. Ngxe4 Re8 {∞ Black is down 2 pawns, but has huge threats, like simply taking on [e4] and then ...[f5].}) 11... Nd5 $1 {This is the problem with the [e3]-square for the queen! Obviously, our opponent doesn't want to create a massive centre for us by taking on [d5].} 12. Nxd5 (12. Qg3 {Not a blunder!} f5 $1 13. Ne6 Qf6 $1 {The knight is trapped on [e6].}) (12. Nxd5 Qxg5 $4 {Falling for the trick. Ne4 Qe7 Nxd6+ Qxd6 Qxg4 ± and White is much better with the extra pawn.}) 12... cxd5 {[%csl Yd3,Gd5,Ye3,Ge5,Yg5]} 13. Qxa7 {The queen goes away from the awkward [e3]-square and creates some threat on [f7].} Be7 $1 {Protecting on [f7] by creating a counter-threat.} 14. Nf3 e4 15. Ne5 Be6 16. Be2 Bd6 $19 {White is likely to lose the knight on [e5] or some other material very soon.} *

