1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 ({The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line'} 3. Bb5 {, which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5]-pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].}) {(In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...Bc5 is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3.Bb5, such as the Marshall or the Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.)} 3... Nf6 ({This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular} 3... Bc5 {would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano. Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone. Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].}) 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least.}) 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that, they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 Nd5 {Attacking the knight on [g5] and freeing the way for the f-pawn.} ({This is clearly the main line for Black since, for example,} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there, according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yd6e5,Gf7f5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line. Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here; we are building on ...[f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Re1 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Yd3f1,Rf3e5] Attacking on [e5], and sometimes it can be very important that the bishop can retreat to [f1].} (11. Nc3 $2 {Allows ...[f5] for free.} f5 12. Be2 e4 13. Nd4 Be5 {Forcing the knight further away from the kingside.} 14. Nb3 Qh4 $1 15. g3 Qh3 {With ideas like ...[f4] or ...[Nf4], Black's attack is extremely dangerous. For example} 16. Nxa5 {loses to} Nf4 $1 17. gxf4 Bxf4 {-+ or 17.Bf3 Rf6 -+ and ...[Rh6]-...[Qxh2] is game over.}) 11... Bg4 {[%cal Gf7f5] A relatively rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on [e5].} ({However,} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally, I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. h3 {By far the most common and most logical, White wants to break the pin, and unfortunately, they can.} Bxf3 (12... Bh5 $6 {Unfortunately, it doesn't work because White has the very strong} 13. Bf5 $1 {± and when needed, they can just break the pin by playing [Bg4] without weakening the kingside at all.}) 13. Qxf3 f5 $1 {[%cal Re5e4] As usual, if we can play ...[e4] for free, then Black is just better.} 14. Bxf5 (14. Bf1 e4 15. Qd1 Bc7 {With ...[Qd6] and ...[Rae8] coming, Black's position is much easier to play.}) 14... Qe7 {[%cal Rg7g6] Covering the [e6]-square, so now ...[g6] is a big threat.} ({On} 14... g6 $2 {, White has} 15. Be6+ {with a winning position. White has a couple of options here: they can either sacrifice the bishop for a few more pawns or try to save it but lose even more time. You can check out the full course for more details. I'll just show one line here which looks normal from White.}) 15. Qg4 $2 {[%cal Gf5e6] Going out from the pin. Also, White has the check on [e6] once the bishop is attacked.} Qf6 $1 16. Be6+ Kh8 {[%cal Rf6f2] Even though White gained a tempo for organising some defence, it is still not possible.} 17. Rf1 Nf4 {[%cal Rf4e6]} 18. Bb3 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yb3,Yc1] The pieces on the queenside are completely out of the game.} h5 19. Qf3 e4 $19 {[%cal Gd6h2,Rf4h3,Ga8e8] Black's attack is decisive.} *

