1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these positions was deemed very promising for White, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous.Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin Endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on [e5], which can be defended in innumerable ways. Against slower moves, like 5.h3 or 5.d3, Black can just play ...[f6], with the plan of ...[c5], ...[Ne7]-[c6], and in case White later wants to play for [d4] what else?, then they will have to trade the doubled pawns on the c-file.} (5. d4 {White could go for the endgame right away, but there are many possible ways to get a slightly improved version of it, so I will rather show one of those lines in more detail.} exd4 6. Nxd4 {is not ideal now, because of} c5 {and White will have to take back with the king on [d1] instead of the rook. 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 7.Nxd4 Bd7 Fortunately, Black's setup is going to be the same almost everywhere!}) 5... Qd6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7g4,Ye8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes it possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. d4 {White can gain an extra tempo compared to 5.d4 exd4 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 lines because of the extra move [O-O], but as you will see, it means pretty much nothing since it is an endgame without any concrete lines.} exd4 7. Qxd4 {Let's see what White can do with that extra tempo.} (7. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {This is what I like about ...[Qd6]! We can comfortably continue the development behind the queen.} 8. e5 $2 {Just a bad, weakening move! Additionally, Black's queen is forced to a better square.} Qg6 {∓}) {8.Nc3 O-O-O 9.Be3 Nh6 The knight is great there, supporting ...[f5] and going towards [g4]. 10.f3 f5 The main idea is to open the position; Black is doing well with the bishop pair.} 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] (The bonus compared to the Berlin endgame! It is a very significant one, which is worth much more than a tempo lost here or there. While in that opening 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.O-O Nxe4 5.d4 Nd6 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7.dxe5 Nf5 8.Qxd8 Kxd8 the king is staying in the centre and it is not so easy to connect the rook, here, it is not a problem for Black at all.)} 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Be3 Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye8e4] White can obviously develop in quite a few different ways, putting the bishop on [f4] or the knight to [d2], but Black's setup is good against all of those things. Ideally, White would like to push their majority on the kingside, so having the rook targeting the pawn which could be a passed pawn later is quite useful.} 11. Rfe1 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gg6e5,Ye5c4,Ye5g4] The knight is going to [g6], from where later it can go towards [e5] and [c4]/[g4]. Instead, ...[Nf6] would be less good since after [f3], the knight is somewhat passive on [f6].} 12. Rad1 Ng6 13. f3 h5 $1 {[%csl Gd7,Gf8][%cal Gb7b6,Ga6a5,Yc8b7] The last move of Black's setup. Gaining some space on the kingside and making it more difficult for White to do anything there. Sometimes, ...[h4] followed by ...[Rh5] is also possible. Pretty much in all endgame lines in the Exchange Ruy Lopez Black should go for this setup. The computer likes to evaluate these positions as slightly better for Black, which is rather unusual. White's position seems quite normal, and apart from the gain of space on the queenside, it is hard to find anything more concrete for Black. I think the assessment is due to long-term prospects, thanks to the bishop pair and the fact that if White starts to do anything, it will only make their position worse.} *

