1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these positions was deemed very promising for White, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous.Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin Endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on [e5], which can be defended in innumerable ways. Against slower moves, like 5.h3 or 5.d3, Black can just play ...[f6], with the plan of ...[c5], ...[Ne7]-[c6], and in case White later wants to play for [d4] what else?, then they will have to trade the doubled pawns on the c-file.} (5. d4 {White could go for the endgame right away, but there are many possible ways to get a slightly improved version of it, so I will rather show one of those lines in more detail.} exd4 6. Nxd4 {is not ideal now, because of} c5 {and White will have to take back with the king on [d1] instead of the rook. 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 7.Nxd4 Bd7 Fortunately, Black's setup is going to be the same almost everywhere!}) 5... Qd6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7g4,Ye8c8]} 6. Na3 {[%cal Rc4e5,Ga3c4,Rc4d6] This is the main test of the 5...[Qd6] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy, and in some cases, they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. Nc4 {The most human move, the knight was not blocked out, so they can bring it to [c4] with a tempo. This position was still reached in 36 games, but now we go into really rare waters.} (7. c3 $6 {allows} Qd3 $1 {The knight is just misplaced on [a3] now.} 8. Qc2 Qxc2 9. Nxc2 Ne7 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Ng6 {⩱ Black is extremely solid, with great chances to attack or undermine White's centre.}) 7... Qe7 (7... Qe6 {is the main move, but I didn't like it so much. The text move is risky because it gives a free move to White instead of attacking the knight. However, I couldn't find anything which would refute this extremely rare move.}) 8. d4 {The most aggressive move.} (8. b3 {It can't be the refutation, too slow.} Be6 9. Ba3 c5 $6 10. c3 {⩲ with [d4] next. 9...Qf7! 10.Bxf8 Qxf8 ∞ and Black is ready to castle in the next move.}) 8... Be6 $1 {Everything else is very bad according to the engine, but okay, we want long castle, and now we could develop with a tempo.} 9. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4,Re5][%cal Ye2c4] Black has to do something with the pawn on [e5].} (9. Na5 O-O-O $1 {And we have castled! The computer approves, and I like this position for Black.}) 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 {White's main threat is actually not taking on [e6] but preventing castling!} Bxc4 $1 (10... O-O-O $2 {This is not only extremely dangerous, but even losing according to the engine.} 11. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 12. Na5 $1 {With [Qxa6] next, Black's position is shaky and bad.}) (10... Bd7 $2 11. Bf4 O-O-O 12. Nb3 {+- Once White can use their knight for the attack, it is already over.}) 11. Qxc4 Qxe4 $1 {What Black is doing looks extremely risky, but the next move is ... [O-O-O]! It's not so easy to find anything for White here.} 12. f3 {This is the human move, but Black is just better here with the extra pawn.} (12. Bf4 $3 {White has to find this insane move in order not to be worse, and it is basically a forced draw but a very long variation.} Qxf4 {You can find in the full course more details on how White can achieve the draw here.}) 12... Qd5 $1 13. Re1+ Kf7 $17 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8d6,Yg8e7] The king is actually very safe on [f7], and we have a clear way of finishing the development with ...[Bd6] and ...[Ne7]. Mikkelsen-Bedia, Serpukhov 2004.} *

