[Black "Deferred Cozio 5.Bb3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C70"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376108146269"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5] The 3... [Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6]. What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6] and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack. So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay. After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7], there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often, we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7] because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Bb3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5,Yg5f7] White is targeting the [f7]-pawn, and they have ideas like [Ng5], so this is a dangerous sideline.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ya4,Gc6][%cal Ra4e8] Since White already moved the bishop for the 3rd time, and even more importantly, they removed it from pressuring the [c6]-knight, we can afford to go for ...[d5] this early.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 {White has to act very quickly; otherwise, Black can easily be better with the space advantage in the centre.} 7. O-O {[%cal Gf1e1,Rf3e5]} Bg4 $1 {By pinning the knight, we make it very difficult for White to attack or win the [e5]-pawn without weakening their kingside with [h3]-[g4].} 8. Re1 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re5c6,Yc6d8] We shouldn't forget that the [e5]-pawn is actually hanging now because then the knight can take with a discovered check on [c6], winning back the material with having an extra pawn.} Be7 $1 {No discovered check on the e-file!} 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 {White is weakening the kingside, but there is simply no other way to challenge our position.} Bg6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Nb4 {[%csl Rg1,Yg4,Yh3] This looks like an excellent Marshall Attack for Black! Black has good compensation for the pawn, since White's kingside is very weak.} *

