1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. d4 {Quite logical. Since Black didn't attack White's centre, White immediately tries to get a space advantage.} exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 {[%cal Ge7c6,Rc6d4] After the trade, we can speed up our development.} 7. Qxd4 Nc6 {White has a lot of options now, but none seem to be very dangerous for Black.} 8. Bxc6 {This is the most common move from White, going into a Berlin-type of endgame.} (8. Qd3 Bc5 $1 {followed by ...[O-O], ...[d6] and Black eventually wants to play ...[f5].}) (8. Qe3 {If White decides to move the queen, this looks like the square to go to. Black's bishop wants to go to [c5] in general, but now it is prevented.} Bd6 $1 {Not as awkward as in the Spanish Four Knights. 🙂 Here, we can quite easily develop our other bishop by playing ...[b5] and ...[Bb7] so that the dark-squared bishop can even stay on [d6].} 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Re8 {Both sides are developing normally. Black should put pressure on the [e4]-pawn to compensate for having slightly less space.} 11. f4 {This was played in Warmerdam-Demchenko, chess.com 2020; while it is clear that [f4]-[e5] is a plan for White, it is just exposing our opponent too much at this moment.} b5 $1 12. Bb3 Na5 {Taking White's bishop on [b7], followed by ...[Bb7], offers Black a good game.}) 8... dxc6 $1 (8... bxc6 {We could try this move, but after} 9. Nc3 {, it is tough to continue developing since White's queen is attacking on [g7].}) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {It is a pretty decent Berlin for Black. Not that I know too much about the Berlin in general, but easy development with the bishops and bringing the king to the queenside is not always available for Black.} 10. Be3 Be6 11. Nd2 (11. O-O a5 {Of course, there are many other moves, but pushing the queenside pawns and slowing down White's central advance are key in the Berlin. Now, there was no time for ...[Kd7]-...[Re8] since White had [Rd1]+.} 12. Nc3 Kc8 {After ...[b5], the king can go to [b7].}) 11... Kd7 {[%cal Ga8e8,Yd7c8] If possible, bringing the rook [e8] and then ...[Kc8] is a nice regrouping for Black.} 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Nb3+ Kc8 $10 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Re6b3,Gh7h5,Gf7f5,Yb7b6,Ya6a5] Black is extremely solid, and White has some problems with the [e4]-pawn.} *

