1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. Nc3 {I struggled against this move the most. White is making it very difficult to play for ...[d5], and also, once the knight goes to [d5], it is not so easy to deal with it. Besides these things, White also didn't give up on the [d4]-idea, so Black has to be ready for a lot of things.} d6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Yc6a5,Ya4b3,Ra5b3] By protecting the pawn on [e5], Black is ready to go after White's bishop with ...[b5] and then ...[Na5].} 6. O-O (6. d4 $6 {Strangely enough, this is the second most popular move from White, but this is just not good.} b5 $1 7. Bb3 Nxd4 $1 {White's bishop on [b3] can easily get into danger.} 8. Nxd4 exd4 {And White can't take on [d4] because ...[c5]-...[c4] is winning a piece. White can, of course, try other moves, like [Qh5] or [Qf3], but you can check out in the full course that, even there, Black is better.} 9. Nd5 c5 {∓}) (6. d3 $6 {Just allows immediate equality for Black.} b5 $1 7. Bb3 Na5 {In such cases, when White is losing the bishop, they should try to go for quick [d4], which will be difficult after just playing [d3].}) 6... Rb8 {Not a huge surprise that this move was only played once before. Probably the most mysterious move of the whole repertoire, but it is just crucial not to allow White to play [Bd5] with a tempo in some lines, so we can continue the development with ...[Ng6].} (6... Ng6 7. d4 b5 8. Bb3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bd5 $1 {Otherwise, we would be completely fine, but now it will not be possible for Black to advance ...[c5]-...[c4] with tempo. That's why 6...Rb8 is good for Black.} Rb8 11. Bc6+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd4 {± White is clearly better here; they have targets on the queenside, and [f4] is already possible as well.}) (6... b5 7. Bb3 Na5 8. d4 $1 Nxb3 9. axb3 {⩲ (And Black has two pawns hanging e5 and [b5] and is also seriously behind in development.)}) 7. Re1 {Probably the most human move, waiting for ...[Ng6] and only then playing [Nd5].} (7. d4 {It is highly unlikely that White will go for this if they know about that ...[c5]-...[c4] trick. Nevertheless, the line is quite interesting with a pawn sacrifice.} b5 8. Bb3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Qf3 $1 Be6 {White can prove enough compensation here, but nothing more. You can check out a few possible lines in the course.}) 7... Ng6 8. Nd5 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gd2d4] The knight is very strong on [d5], and it also allows White to play for [c3]-[d4].} Be7 9. d4 (9. c3 O-O {Instead, ...[Bg4] would do nothing since there is no pawn on [d4].} 10. h3 {White wants to go for [d4] without allowing ...[Bg4].} f5 {⇆ Since it is not possible to play for ...[d5], Black is using the other break, which is similarly possible because the knight was not developed to [f6] but [e7]-[g6].}) 9... Bg4 $1 {[%cal Yg6h4,Yb7b5,Rc6d4] Black is getting good counterplay here, with ...[Nh4] and after that ...[b5], ...[Nxd4] threats.} 10. c3 Nh4 $132 {Black is creating some weaknesses on the kingside. The position is very unclear and completely untested.} *

