1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4]} Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} 8. Nc3 {This is the most common option for White.} d5 $1 ({We have to strike in the centre right away!} 8... O-O 9. O-O {would just make our position clearly worse.}) 9. exd5 (9. e5 {allows Black to develop comfortably.} Bg4 $1 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxc6+ $1 {So they can take back on [f3] with the queen.} bxc6 12. Qxf3 O-O {⇆ With ...[f6] coming next, Black has good chances.}) (9. O-O {Similarly as in the line with 9.exd5, Black has to be careful with the move order.} Bxc3 $2 10. exd5 $1 Qxd5 11. Bb3 $1 {The queen can't go to its ideal square on [h5], because of [Bxf7]+!}) (9. exd5 {dxe4! Ng5} O-O {Qh5 h6 Nxf7 We are a pawn up, so we can decide when to return the material. Rxf7} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 {Qxg6 Qxd4= White can take the pawn on [e4] or [c6], but with the pair of bishops we are fine.}) 9... Bxc3+ $1 {An unusual move order, but we have to force White to take back on [c3].} (9... Qxd5 $2 {This automatic move is a pretty serious mistake.} 10. O-O Bxc3 11. Bb3 $1 {This is the difference from 9...[Bxc3]+. White does not have to take on [c3] immediately, and the ideal square for our queen is not available now.} Qh5 $4 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Ne5+ {+-}) {11...Qf5 is of course better, but the queen is misplaced on [f5] as well. 12.bxc3 ±} 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. O-O (11. Qe2+ Qe6 $1 12. d5 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 b5 $1 {And Black is not losing a piece.}) 11... O-O 12. Bb3 (12. h3 {allows} Na5 $1 {and White can't kick the queen with [Bb3].}) 12... Qh5 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc8g4] With ...[Bg4] or, if prevented, then with ...[Na5] next, Black has a decent game. There is one dangerous move to know here.} 13. Ba3 $2 {It would be winning if it wasn't bad.} Bg4 $1 (13... Rd8 $4 {It is just losing, since} 14. Ne5 $1 Qxd1 15. Bxf7+ Kh8 16. Nxg6+ hxg6 17. Raxd1 {+- is a completely winning endgame for White.}) 14. Bxf8 Nh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f3,Rg4f3,Rh5f3] White can't protect [f3] at all.} 15. Bxf7+ $1 {Avoids more serious material losses.} Qxf7 16. Ng5 $1 Bxd1 17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Rfxd1 Kxf8 $15 {White has a rook and pawn for the two knights, which is not quite enough, but they definitely can fight for the draw.} *

