1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5] Black is protecting the pawn on [e5] and ...[d5] is already possible in the next move.} 6. d4 {White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 {Would just transpose to Quickstarter variations, which start with 5.O-O [Ng6] 6.c3 [d5].}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre. Otherwise, we are just worse.} 8. Bd2 {A rare but tricky line, played amongst others by GMs Wesley So and Peter Svidler.} O-O $1 (8... Bxd2+ {This looks much more logical than castling, but it gives White the extra option of castling on the queenside!} 9. Qxd2 O-O 10. Nc3 {⩲ This looks like a pretty bad position, with [h4]-[h5] coming.}) 9. O-O (9. d5 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b5 {White should decide whether to put the bishop on [b3] or [c2].} 11. Bb3 Nce5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O {f4 is already a big threat, so Black has to act quickly.} a5 $1 14. f4 a4 {⇆ Black is just in time to avoid a very passive and bad position.}) ({11.Bc2 Nce5 12.Nxe5 Nxe5 13.O-O f5! Challenging White in the centre. 14.exf5 d6= With ...[Bxf5] next, Black is completely fine.} 9. Bxb4 Nxb4 10. Qd2 Qe7 $1 {Followed by ...[d5]!}) 9... Bxd2 10. Qxd2 (10. Nbxd2 d5 $1 {With similar moves to follow as in the main line.}) 10... d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4] This move is the key for Black! Opening up the bishop and not allowing White to gain too much space in the centre.} 11. Bxc6 (11. exd5 Nce7 $1 {It is better to take with the knight on [d5]!}) 11... bxc6 12. e5 {Our structure is not good on the queenside, but we are not playing for an endgame, but an attack on the kingside!} f6 $1 13. Qc3 Nf4 $132 {Black is in excellent shape, and in case White takes the pawn...} 14. Qxc6 $2 Bd7 15. Qc5 Bb5 $19 (15... Bb5 {This is already lost for White.} 16. Rc1 {and 16.Re1 drop an exchange with 16...Nd3}) (15... Bb5 {On} 16. Rd1 {, Black can simply play} Be2 {and, since White cannot allow ...[Bxf3], this line also wins an exchange for Black.}) *

