1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. Re1 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Re1e5,Yd7d5,Ye4d5] This move is very good against ...[d5] but doesn't help much with [c3]-[d4].} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5] Especially against slower moves, like [h3], [d3], [c4] or [Re1], it is good to develop the bishop to [c5], where it is more active compared to [e7].} 7. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4]} Nh4 $1 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rh4f3,Yd2d4,Yf3d4] The knight from [g6] sometimes can even fight against the [d4]-break!} 8. d3 {If White has to play like this, it already means that Black is fine.} O-O $10 {[%cal Gd7d6,Yf7f5] Black can play ...[d6] next and then prepare to play ...[f5].} *

