1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The most common move, White is pushing for [d4] right away.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5] It is extremely rare that Black can play ...[d5] so early in the Ruy Lopez. And it is not even bad! This is all possible because the main defender of the [e5]-pawn is not the [c6], but the [g6]-knight.} 7. exd5 (7. d3 {Complete success for Black. When I say that if nothing happens after ...[d5], then we are good, then I'm talking about such moves.} Be7 {We can just complete our development without any problems.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Bb3 Qd3 $1 {We must force the bishop to [c2] before allowing [d4], since then the bishop is not going to control the crucial [d5]-square and also will not put pressure on [f7].} 9. Bc2 (9. Ng5 $2 {It is good to know that this move is not working.} Be7 $1 10. Nxf7 $2 Rf8 {∓ The knight is trapped on [f7]. 10.Bxf7+ Kf8 11.Bxg6 White has to take in order not to lose a piece. 11...hxg6 12.Qf3+ Bf5 -+ It is important to keep a piece on [d3] and block White's queenside. 12.f4 Bc5+ 13.Kh1 Bg4 -+ White is playing without their queenside, so it is not surprising that Black is completely winning here.}) 9... Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8e6] This is the right square for the queen, keeping the bishop's diagonal open and also allowing ...[O-O-O].} 10. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5] Now, White threatens [d5], winning space in the centre and forcing the knight to a passive square, but we want to castle long anyway, so it is easy to deal with this threat.} Be6 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8] The line continues in the course, but Black has already equalised here, with ...[O-O-O] in the next move.} *

