1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4]} d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5]} 7. exd5 (7. d3 {Complete success for Black. When I say that if nothing happens after ...[d5], then we are good, then I'm talking about such moves.} Be7 {We can just complete our development without any problems.}) 7... Qxd5 8. d4 {This is the most common move from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rg4d1] Putting pressure on the knight and the [d4]-pawn while also preparing to castle long.} 9. dxe5 (9. Nbd2 {White wants to take back on [f3] with the knight.} exd4 $1 10. Qe1+ Be7 11. Nxd4 Bd7 {Black has no problems.}) (9. Bb3 Bxf3 $1 {We should go for an equal endgame; retreating with the queen would be pretty dangerous. (( 9...Qd7?! 10.h3! Bxf3 11.Qxf3 ⩲ White is better with the strong bishop on b3.))} 10. Bxd5 Bxd1 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Rxd1 O-O-O 13. Be3 Bc5 {We can double on the d-file, or just take on [d4] and create an isolated pawn; the chances are equal. 11.Rxd1 O-O-O! Giving up [f7] for [d4]. 12.Bxf7 exd4 13.cxd4 Nxd4 14.Nc3 Ne2+= Taking the [c1]-bishop and completely equalising the game.}) 9... O-O-O $1 {Finishing the development. We can win back the [e5]-pawn later.} (9... Bxf3 {Practically speaking, it is a very decent move since most of the time, White will take back with the queen, which already leads to a better position for Black.} 10. gxf3 $1 {This is the risk Black takes. If White knows this move, it can get somewhat unpleasant.} Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ngxe5 12. Bf4 {⩲ This is the much-improved version of the endgame for White, compared to 10.Qxf3? Qxf3 11.gxf3 Ngxe5 ⩱}) 10. Qxd5 Rxd5 11. Bb3 (11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nbd2 {and} Nf4 $5 {is an interesting alternative to the main line; Black decides to play down a pawn, but with substantial compensation in the form of the bishop pair and a strong knight on [d3]. 12...Bxf3 13.Nxf3 Nxe5 14.Nxe5 Rxe5= The king on [b7] will protect all of our weaknesses, so again, what White has is a symbolic advantage in a drawish endgame.}) 11... Bxf3 $1 12. gxf3 Rxe5 13. Bxf7 Bd6 {[%csl Yf3,Yh2][%cal Gh8f8,Ge5h5,Rg6h4] With so many weaknesses on the kingside, White having an extra pawn is not too concerning as Black has excellent compensation in exchange. This was played in the game Gormally-Sadhwani, chess.com 2022.} *

