1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. Nxc6 dxc6 (8... bxc6 {is also possible, but who likes to play against the Berlin Endgame?}) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Black is just extremely solid, and it is very tough for White to push the majority on the kingside.} 10. Nd2 Re8 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ge7f8] The king goes to [f8]!} 11. Bb3 Ke7 12. Kh1 Kf8 $132 {[%cal Ya6a5,Yb7b5] With a very complicated endgame and chances for both sides.} *

