1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Be3 {[%cal Rd4c6] Npw, [Nxc6] is a threat, so we have to react.} Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Qg5 $1 {Not only protecting the bishop, but if White is not careful, we can quickly win the game.} 10. Bxc5 (10. Nc3 $4 {covers the [e2]-square but not [f3]!} Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Nh4 {-+ With a double attack on [g2] and [f3].}) (10. g3 $6 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 c5 $1 {This is another trick, but White can escape here by finding some extremely difficult moves.} 12. Qxg7 b5 {White has to find} 13. Na3 {here, and then the position is somewhat complicated. It is not an easy move, though.}) 10... Qxc5 {We already traded two pairs of minor pieces, which is good, given that we have less space.} 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bb3 d6 $10 {[%cal Gc8e6] We will play ...[Be6] next, with a more or less even position.} *

