[GameId "2160376108523112"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6,Yf3e5]} ({The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5. Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to} 3. Bc4 {or other lines, but overall, it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.}) 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} 5. O-O Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yg6e5,Gd7d5]} ({Here, we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4] White is preventing the trade on [d4] since we don't want to give such strong central pawns to our opponent.} O-O 9. Be3 Nce5 $1 {[%cal Re5c4,Re5g4,Gd7d5] Black wants to create counterplay with ...[Ng4] or ...[Nc4].} 10. Nd2 d6 {[%cal Re5g4] White has to defend against ...[Ng4] now.} 11. h3 Qh4 {[%cal Rc8h3] Black has good counterplay on the kingside.} 12. f4 {Entering some crazy lines, but if this works, White is just much better.} Bxh3 $1 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Nf5 Qg5 $1 {Without this, Black is just lost.} 15. Qe2 Bxg2 {Collecting the third pawn for the piece.} 16. Qxg2 Bxe3+ 17. Nxe3 Qxe3+ 18. Qf2 Qg5+ {[%csl Rg1,Gg8] We shouldn't trade queens; our king is much safer.} 19. Kh1 Rad8 {With equal chances, according to the engine. Anything is possible in this position.} *

