1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Qf3 $6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg1f3] Clearly a dubious move, the queen is occupying the square where normally the [g1]-knight wants to go, and well, such an opening principle like 'bring the queen into the game, and put her into an awkward square' is yet to be invented. This variation is called the Napoleon Opening, named after the French Emperor, who was an avid chess player.} Nf6 {This move pretty much destroys White's dreams, who was dreaming about 3. [Bc4] and 4. [Qxf7] checkmate ideas. :} 3. g4 $2 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yg4g5,Yf1c4,Yc4f7,Yf3f7] Extremely stubborn, White is not giving up on their original idea, and tries to kick the knight from [f6] and deliver checkmate.} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Re4,Ge5,Gf6,Rg4][%cal Yf6e4,Yf6g4,Yc8g4] This is how unsound opening play should be punished! White is playing for dreams, while Black is playing for the centre.} 4. exd5 Bxg4 5. Bb5+ {Trying to confuse Black and somehow save the [d5]-pawn.} Nc6 $19 {[%csl Rd5] Black is just developing with every move, and with ... [Qxd5] to follow, it will be a clear extra pawn for us after just 6 moves into the game.} *

