1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Qf3 $6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg1f3] Clearly a dubious move, the queen is occupying the square where normally the [g1]-knight wants to go, and well, such an opening principle like 'bring the queen into the game, and put her into an awkward square' is yet to be invented. This variation is called the Napoleon Opening, named after the French Emperor, who was an avid chess player.} Nf6 {This move pretty much destroys White's dreams, who was dreaming about 3. [Bc4] and 4. [Qxf7] checkmate ideas. :} 3. Bc4 c6 {[%cal Yc6d5,Gd7d5] With the idea of pushing ...[d5] and gaining complete control over the centre.} 4. Nc3 {[%cal Yc3d5] White has to stop the [d5]-idea, and finally make a normal developing move.} (4. g4 $4 {This desperate idea of hitting the knight with [g5] and then giving a checkmate on [f7] is even worse than before, because our pawn on [d5] will be protected now.} d5 $1 {-+ Again this break, and White's position is collapsing, since ...[Bxg4] is coming with tempo.}) 4... b5 {Gaining space on the queenside, and keeping an option like ...[b4] in reserve. When there will be a direct battle for the centre, such a move really can hurt White, since the [c3]-knight will have to leave to a much more passive square.} (4... d5 $5 {I really wanted to make this move work, but unfortunately there is one issue.} 5. exd5 e4 $1 {This is the point, if White would take this pawn, then the pin with ...[Qe7] is really unpleasant.} 6. Qe2 cxd5 {Everything looks great, but White has a tactical trick.} 7. Bxd5 $1 Nxd5 8. Qb5+ {With this check, White is getting back the piece.} Nc6 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Bd6 {∞ Black has full compensation for the pawn, but of course this line is not needed if we have simpler and better ways.}) 5. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3] White has to defend against the unpleasant ...[a4] idea.} 6. a4 {More direct and worse way to save the bishop. White is forcing a move, which Black wanted to play anyways, sooner or later.} b4 7. Nce2 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc3e4,Yc3d5] The knight is not controlling anymore the important central squares [e4] and [d5].} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] So it is a great time for us to occupy the centre!} 8. exd5 {Not a horrible move if White follows it up correctly.} cxd5 9. d4 {Without this move White would have no part of the centre.} e4 10. Qg3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Black has many good ways to play here, to me the easiest is to play ... [g6]-[Bg7] and ...[Ba6], all our pieces are active and we have a space advantage in the centre.} *

