y unpleasant.} 6. Qe2 cxd5 {Everything looks great, but White has a tactical trick.} 7. Bxd5 $1 Nxd5 8. Qb5+ {With this check, White is getting back the piece.} Nc6 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Bd6 {∞ Black has full compensation for the pawn, but of course this line is not needed if we have simpler and better ways.}) 5. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3] White has to defend against the unpleasant ...[a4] idea.} 6. a4 {More direct and worse way to save the bishop. White is forcing a move, which Black wanted to play anyways, sooner or later.} b4 7. Nce2 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc3e4,Yc3d5] The knight is not controlling anymore the important central squares [e4] and [d5].} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] So it is a great time for us to occupy the centre!} 8. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd3e4] White is stabilising in the centre.} Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Re4][%cal Gd7c5,Yc5e4,Yc5b3] A nice pawn sacrifice from Black! It is of course not the only way, but it is nice to get a feeling for such moves, when the opponent is playing weird lines or some passive moves, we can punish them very early on!} 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gg3g7] With this move White is trying to cause some discomfort in Black's development, but it is almost needless to say, that the computer would completely ignore it and give up the [g7]-pawn for some tactical complications.} g6 {I like this move much better, though. We already established an advantage in the centre, so we don't really need adventures at this moment.} (10... Bd6 {The computer pretends that [Qg3] did nothing. 🙂} 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qh6 Rxg2 13. Ng3 Nc5 {∓ (And Black is doing well, although the position remains a little bit messy of course only for the human-eye!.)}) 11. Nf3 Nh5 $17 {A queen trade is coming very soon, and then we can simply develop with [Bb7] and secure our advantage with the strong central pawns.} *

