y unpleasant.} 6. Qe2 cxd5 {Everything looks great, but White has a tactical trick.} 7. Bxd5 $1 Nxd5 8. Qb5+ {With this check, White is getting back the piece.} Nc6 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Bd6 {∞ Black has full compensation for the pawn, but of course this line is not needed if we have simpler and better ways.}) 5. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3] White has to defend against the unpleasant ...[a4] idea.} 6. a3 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ya3b4,Yb5b4,Yb3a2] This is the better way to do it, since this move also addresses the potential [b4] idea, at least for the moment.} d6 {This move may look like a little bit modest, especially after seeing the previous couple of moves, but the idea is very strong, [Nbd7]-[Nc5] and hitting the important bishop on [b3], and also putting more pressure on White's centre.} (6... Bc5 $5 {This move is also good, but the knight will be even stronger on [c5]!}) 7. Nge2 Nbd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd7c5] Continuing the way to the [c5]-square.} 8. d4 $6 {Looks logical, putting a pawn to the centre and even preventing ...[Nc5], but the problem with the move that it is not closing the [f1]-[a6] diagonal.} Ba6 $1 {[%csl Re2,Rf1][%cal Ya6f1,Yb5b4] The next is ... [b4], and White can't really keep their centre together.} 9. O-O b4 10. axb4 axb4 $17 (10... axb4 {And wherever the knight goes, because of the pin on the f1-a6 diagonal, White is losing a pawn. For instance,} 11. Nb1 exd4 {∓}) *

