y unpleasant.} 6. Qe2 cxd5 {Everything looks great, but White has a tactical trick.} 7. Bxd5 $1 Nxd5 8. Qb5+ {With this check, White is getting back the piece.} Nc6 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Bd6 {∞ Black has full compensation for the pawn, but of course this line is not needed if we have simpler and better ways.}) 5. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3] White has to defend against the unpleasant ...[a4] idea.} 6. a3 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ya3b4,Yb5b4,Yb3a2] This is the better way to do it, since this move also addresses the potential [b4] idea, at least for the moment.} d6 {This move may look like a little bit modest, especially after seeing the previous couple of moves, but the idea is very strong, [Nbd7]-[Nc5] and hitting the important bishop on [b3], and also putting more pressure on White's centre.} (6... Bc5 $5 {This move is also good, but the knight will be even stronger on [c5]!}) 7. Nge2 Nbd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd7c5] Continuing the way to the [c5]-square.} 8. d3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] The bishop will be good on [g7], and the [g6]-pawn can support ...[f5] ideas in the future.} 9. O-O Bg7 10. h3 {[%cal Yh3g4,Yc8g4] Normally White should play this move with the queen on [f3], because after a move like [Ng3] or [Be3], ... [Bg4] can be really unpleasant to face.} O-O $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5b3,Yc8e6,Yb5b4] With a very comfortable position for Black, it is hard to say what White should do here, while we have crystal clear moves to play, such as ...[Nc5] and ...[b4], and also ...[Be6].} *

