[GameId "2160376108711535"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Qh5 $6 {[%csl Re5,Rf7][%cal Yh5e5,Yh5f7] This move is a better version of 2. [Qf3], since it is also attacking on [e5], therefore Black can't just respond with 2...[Nf6]. The variation goes by many different names, I'll go with the Kentucky Opening, since it looks like that the first published game of this line was played there. It was famously played by Hikaru Nakamura even in classical games, but nevertheless, the objective evaluation of the line remains dubious.} Nc6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6d4,Yc6e5] Normal developing move, which is also supporting the [e5]-pawn.} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yh5f7] And here we are! Only one move away from the defeat and getting the Scholar's mate! Fortunately though, this repertoire is not for hyperbullet time control, and in longer time controls where we don't have to premove, we can handle this straightforward threat quite easily.} (3. Bb5 $2 {White wants to take the knight and then the [e5]-pawn, but it fails to the most natural move in the position.} Nf6 {∓ Developing with a tempo, and once the queen retreats, we can gain another tempo on the bishop by playing... [Nd4], so White's opening strategy completely failed.}) 3... g6 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yf3f7] One more chance to blunder on [f7]! On a more serious note, at least White managed to force the Black knight to [c6], which is not a great achievement by itself, but what we saw in the original 2. [Qf3] lines, the very strong ...[c6]-[d5] idea is at least not on the table yet.} Nf6 {[%csl Rc2,Rf3][%cal Gc6d4,Yd4c2,Yd4f3] Protecting against the mate with a developing move! We don't need anything better than that! Also, since the [e5]-pawn is not under attack anymore, we have immediate ...[Nd4]-ideas to take over the initiative.} 5. d3 $2 {White is not addressing Black's plan!} Nd4 {[%csl Rc2,Rf3][%cal Yd4f3,Yd4c2] Of course!} 6. Qd1 d5 $1 {White lost a lot of time in the opening with the queen, so it is time for Black to seize the initiative.} 7. exd5 b5 {Opening the position and gaining tempos wherever we can!} 8. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3] The [b3]-bishop is again in danger.} 9. c3 (9. a4 $6 {this is far from ideal now, Black can completely ruin White's queenside structure.} Nxb3 10. cxb3 Qxd5 {∓ The material is equal, but Black has the pair of bishops, the better development, and White has the worst structure. 🙂}) 9... a4 $1 {[%csl Ga8] Thanks to the a-pawn, even the rook from [a8] is getting very active!} 10. cxd4 axb3 11. Qxb3 (11. dxe5 Rxa2 $1 {-+ Is a lovely tactical trick, Black is winning a lot of material.}) 11... Qxd5 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Yg1,Yh1] Sometimes people are afraid to trade queens when they are on the attack, or they have the initiative, but we shouldn't forget that it is very possible to have strong attacks even without queens, and it is more important to keep the flow going with or without queens. Also, here it is a nice bonus, that we are trading White's only developed piece.} 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. dxe5 {The dust has settled, White is up 2 pawns, and... completely lost.} Nb4 {[%csl Ga8,Rc2,Gc8,Rd3,Gf8][%cal Yb4c2,Yb4d3] Black is extremely active and there are many weaknesses in White's camp.} 14. Na3 Nxd3+ {One pawn is back.} 15. Ke2 Nxc1+ 16. Rxc1 b4 $19 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Yf8h6,Yc8a6,Ya8a2] We will take back the second one on [a2], and will have a crushing position with the monster bishops.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 1.e4 e5 - Unusual Second Moves"]
[Black "Unusual Second Moves - 2.Qh5 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C20"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2160376108740208"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Qh5 $6 {[%csl Re5,Rf7][%cal Yh5e5,Yh5f7] This move is a better version of 2. [Qf3], since it is also attacking on [e5], therefore Black can't just respond with 2...[Nf6]. The variation goes by many different names, I'll go with the Kentucky Opening, since it looks like that the first published game of this line was played there. It was famously played by Hikaru Nakamura even in classical games, but nevertheless, the objective evaluation of the line remains dubious.} Nc6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6d4,Yc6e5] Normal developing move, which is also supporting the [e5]-pawn.} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yh5f7] And here we are! Only one move away from the defeat and getting the Scholar's mate! Fortunately though, this repertoire is not for hyperbullet time control, and in longer time controls where we don't have to premove, we can handle this straightforward threat quite easily.} (3. Bb5 $2 {White wants to take the knight and then the [e5]-pawn, but it fails to the most natural move in the position.} Nf6 {∓ Developing with a tempo, and once the queen retreats, we can gain another tempo on the bishop by playing... [Nd4], so White's opening strategy completely failed.}) 3... g6 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yf3f7] One more chance to blunder on [f7]! On a more serious note, at least White managed to force the Black knight to [c6], which is not a great achievement by itself, but what we saw in the original 2. [Qf3] lines, the very strong ...[c6]-[d5] idea is at least not on the table yet.} Nf6 {[%csl Rc2,Rf3][%cal Gc6d4,Yd4c2,Yd4f3] Protecting against the mate with a developing move! We don't need anything better than that! Also, since the [e5]-pawn is not under attack anymore, we have immediate ...[Nd4]-ideas to take over the initiative.} 5. c3 $6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4] Even though White is covering the [d4]-square, they are not doing it with a developing move.} Bg7 6. d3 Na5 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ya5c4] This is my favourite idea in such positions. Without the [c4]-bishop, White's position is simply toothless.} 7. Bb5 {It is logical to try to keep it on the board, but what we see again, is that White is wasting all the time in the world by moving around with their queen and bishop.} O-O {[%cal Gd7d5] In general it is pretty good to castle, but it is even better when the move prepares ...[d5]. 🙂} 8. Bg5 ({White wants to stop d5.} 8. Ne2 d5 $1 {∓ Black has the better development, the centre, and also threats like ... [Bg4] for example.}) 8... h6 {Asking some questions from the bishop.} 9. Bh4 $6 ({Principled, but not working well.} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 {⩱ Black effortlessly achieved a better position thanks to the pair of bishops, and to ideas like ...[c6]-[d5] or ...[Bg7]-[f5].}) 9... g5 {The pin is broken anyways.} 10. Bg3 {But it looks like that White gains a tempo on the [e5]-pawn!} d5 $1 {With such an advantage in the development it is not even a question that we are going for complications and want to open the position as much as possible.} 11. Bxe5 (11. exd5 $2 {This move has a very easy refutation.} Bg4 12. Qe3 Qxd5 {-+ Both the bishop on [b5] and the pawn on [g2] is hanging, White can pretty much resign here.}) 11... c6 {Forcing the bishop to a worse square, so after the trade on [e4], our knight can join the game via [c4].} 12. Ba4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Re5][%cal Yc4b2,Yc4e5] Here is the knight! Attacking on [b2] and also on [e5].} 14. Bxf6 {A sad necessity.} Qxf6 $1 {Again a nice example that we shouldn't be afraid of trading queens, even though we are down a pawn for the moment.} 15. Qxf6 (15. Qe2 {Can be met by the very strong} Qf4 $1 {and ... [Qc1] is not an easy threat to stop without dropping material.}) 15... Bxf6 16. b4 a5 $19 {[%csl Ya1][%cal Ya8a4,Ra5b4,Yf6a1,Gf8e8] The rook is joining the game, White's position is simply lost here.} *

