[White "1) 1.e4 e5 - Unusual Second Moves"]
[Black "Unusual Second Moves - 2.Qh5 #3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C20"]
[PlyCount "38"]
[GameId "2160376108772977"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Qh5 $6 {[%csl Re5,Rf7][%cal Yh5e5,Yh5f7] This move is a better version of 2. [Qf3], since it is also attacking on [e5], therefore Black can't just respond with 2...[Nf6]. The variation goes by many different names, I'll go with the Kentucky Opening, since it looks like that the first published game of this line was played there. It was famously played by Hikaru Nakamura even in classical games, but nevertheless, the objective evaluation of the line remains dubious.} Nc6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6d4,Yc6e5] Normal developing move, which is also supporting the [e5]-pawn.} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yh5f7] And here we are! Only one move away from the defeat and getting the Scholar's mate! Fortunately though, this repertoire is not for hyperbullet time control, and in longer time controls where we don't have to premove, we can handle this straightforward threat quite easily.} (3. Bb5 $2 {White wants to take the knight and then the [e5]-pawn, but it fails to the most natural move in the position.} Nf6 {∓ Developing with a tempo, and once the queen retreats, we can gain another tempo on the bishop by playing... [Nd4], so White's opening strategy completely failed.}) 3... g6 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yc4f7,Yf3f7] One more chance to blunder on [f7]! On a more serious note, at least White managed to force the Black knight to [c6], which is not a great achievement by itself, but what we saw in the original 2. [Qf3] lines, the very strong ...[c6]-[d5] idea is at least not on the table yet.} Nf6 {[%csl Rc2,Rf3][%cal Gc6d4,Yd4c2,Yd4f3] Protecting against the mate with a developing move! We don't need anything better than that! Also, since the [e5]-pawn is not under attack anymore, we have immediate ...[Nd4]-ideas to take over the initiative.} 5. Ne2 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye2d4] White is developing and stopping the ...[Nd4] idea.} (5. Qb3 $2 {The most stubborn continuation from White! Just not giving up on creating one-move threats! I played like this more than a couple of times in my childhood, and well, opponents failed to blunder the [f7]-pawn. 🙂} Nd4 $1 {The punishment is coming for moving around with the queen, instead of developing.} 6. Bxf7+ Ke7 {And White can't keep that [f7]-bishop for long.} 7. Qc4 b5 {-+ With an extra piece for Black.}) 5... Na5 $5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ya5c4] Was played only in 8 OTB games, but looks very logical to take that light-squared bishop.} 6. d3 {Probably this is the best move for White, since even if the bishop is traded on [c4], the pawn will be a decent replacement regarding the fight against Black's [d5]-move.} (6. Bd3 {This is the only way for White to keep the bishop on the board, but it is extremely awkward.} Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. b4 {White wants to prepare the [c4]-square for the light-square bishop with this move.} Nc6 9. a3 d5 $1 {∓ (With great difficulties White managed to keep the light squared bishop on the board along the way it became a very bad piece, since it had to leave the [a2]-[g8] diagonal but lost all the coordination and the fight for the centre.)}) (6. Bb3 {Allows Black to immediately execute the ...[d5] idea.} Nxb3 7. axb3 d5 8. d3 h6 $1 {⩱ Not even allowing any kind of [Bg5] very slightly unpleasant idea. Black has the pair of bishops and the centre, [Bg7] and [O-O] is coming very soon with a pleasant position.}) 6... Bg7 {Instead of this move, Black took on [c4] in all 4 OTB games, but we don't have to hurry with that move, the bishop still can't escape.} 7. Nbc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc3d5] Natural move, increasing the control over the [d5]-square.} O-O 8. h3 (8. Bg5 {This move fails to impress.} h6 $1 {Our typical reaction against [Bg5].} 9. Bh4 c6 {⩱ With ideas like ...[g5] followed by [d5] are coming.}) (8. h4 {White is attempting a direct attack, but Black's position is extremely safe and solid, it is not even easy for the pawn to reach the [h5]-square.} d6 {Introducing the ...[Bg4] idea into the position.} 9. Ng3 {White is trying to support [h5], but simply there is not enough space for their pieces now.} Bg4 10. Qe3 c6 {∓ With ...[d5] looming, White is in a serious trouble.}) 8... d6 9. Bg5 {This is how the 4 OTB games went, the move is nothing special, but it is hard to find anything better for White.} h6 $1 {As usual!} 10. Be3 c6 {[%cal Yc6d5,Gd6d5,Yc6b5,Gb7b5] Supporting the [d5] or the [b5] push!} 11. a4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yc4a2] Once this move is played, then it is time for us to take the bishop on [c4], before it could retreat to [a2].} Nxc4 12. dxc4 Be6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ye6c4] Black is finishing the development with a tempo.} 13. b3 {It looks like that White's position is pretty solid, but actually, Black has so many tempting choices here, that it was hard to pick a main line.} Rc8 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yd6d5,Yc4d5,Yc6d5,Yc8c2] A clever waiting move, the rook will be very useful on the c-file which will be opened after our break with [d5].} ({•} 13... d5 $5 {This move was working right away, but we put some fire into it with ...[Rc8] first.}) ({•} 13... Nxe4 $5 {A great tactical idea, leading to a quite nice position for Black.} 14. Nxe4 f5 15. N4c3 f4 16. Bd2 d5 {∞ Quite an amazing position, Black is down a piece, but the huge centre is at least a compensation for it.}) ({•} 13... Ne8 $5 {With the idea of playing for ...[f5] is also very typical for this pawn structure.}) 14. O-O (14. O-O-O $6 {It is very dangerous to play like this.} Qc7 {∓ Black's position has enormous dynamic potential, with ...[d5] or ... [a6]-[b5] coming, White's king is in a big danger, the queen move just put some more pressure to the [c2]-square.}) 14... d5 $1 {There is no reason to delay this break anymore.} 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. exd5 e4 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rc2,Gg7][%cal Gg7a1,Gc8c2] The key move, Black's pieces are getting alive, while White's position is very loose.} 17. Nxe4 Bxd5 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Qg3 Rxc2 $15 {[%csl Ra1,Rb3,Gd5,Re2,Gf6][%cal Yf6a1,Yd5b3,Yc2e2] The bishops are very strong, and a lot of pieces are hanging in White's camp.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 1.e4 e5 - Unusual Second Moves"]
[Black "Unusual Second Moves - 2.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C20"]
[PlyCount "16"]
[GameId "2160376108818034"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. c3 $6 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] This is the so-called MacLeod Attack. White's idea is to push for [d4] and then recapture with the pawn, which sounds like a very sensible plan. The problem is that this idea is too slow, and while White is preparing for it, Black can already strike in the centre!} d5 $1 {There is no reason for delaying this move. The pawn on [c3] stands very well from our perspective, once the queen arrives on [d5], it can't be kicked out with the move [Nc3].} 3. exd5 ({•} 3. Nf3 $6 {The inventor of the line, MacLeod liked to play this move, but Black can achieve a nice advantage by simple means.} dxe4 4. Nxe5 {The knight is pretty insecure in the middle of the board.} Qe7 $1 {A very precise move, not allowing White to play [d4], because then after the en passant, the pin on the e-file will be deadly.} 5. Nc4 Nc6 6. Be2 Bf5 {⩱ After very natural developing moves, we have a nice space advantage in the centre, and very easy follow-up play in the form of [O-O-O], [Nf6] and since most probably White is going to castle short, we will start pushing our h-pawn very soon as well.}) ({•} 3. d3 {A very sad move, White is already admitting the opening went wrong.} dxe4 {There are many other moves and setups here, but this one is very easy and leads to a slightly better position for Black.} 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bc5 {Developing with a tempo.} 6. f3 a5 {⩱ A very useful move for this structure, stabilizing the bishop, gaining some space on the queenside. Even though the position is without queens, there is an interesting idea for Black, to play ...[f5] and ...[Nf6], with the idea that White's king can't castle anymore, and the [c3]-move weakened quite a few light squares.}) 3... Qxd5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb1c3]} 4. Nf3 $6 {A very provocative move, inviting our pawn to [e4].} e4 $1 {It is coming with a tempo, so it looks very good for Black.} 5. Nd4 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Offering a trade is also a tempo, since the other side has to react to it.} 6. Nxc6 Qxc6 7. d3 {White has to undermine the [e4]-pawn, otherwise our opponent is just left with a serious space disadvantage.} exd3 {We shouldn't be too unhappy about this exchange, because White can't take back with the bishop, because of the pawn on [g2].} 8. Qxd3 Bd7 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gg8f6,Gf8c5] The position is symmetrical, where the value of time and development is extremely important, and Black is doing amazingly in that regard. The next moves are ...[O-O-O], ...[Bc5] and ...[Nf6], White has a very difficult task in order to stay in the game, not even talking about reaching a decent position.} *

