1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. c3 $6 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] This is the so-called MacLeod Attack. White's idea is to push for [d4] and then recapture with the pawn, which sounds like a very sensible plan. The problem is that this idea is too slow, and while White is preparing for it, Black can already strike in the centre!} d5 $1 {There is no reason for delaying this move. The pawn on [c3] stands very well from our perspective, once the queen arrives on [d5], it can't be kicked out with the move [Nc3].} 3. exd5 ({•} 3. Nf3 $6 {The inventor of the line, MacLeod liked to play this move, but Black can achieve a nice advantage by simple means.} dxe4 4. Nxe5 {The knight is pretty insecure in the middle of the board.} Qe7 $1 {A very precise move, not allowing White to play [d4], because then after the en passant, the pin on the e-file will be deadly.} 5. Nc4 Nc6 6. Be2 Bf5 {⩱ After very natural developing moves, we have a nice space advantage in the centre, and very easy follow-up play in the form of [O-O-O], [Nf6] and since most probably White is going to castle short, we will start pushing our h-pawn very soon as well.}) ({•} 3. d3 {A very sad move, White is already admitting the opening went wrong.} dxe4 {There are many other moves and setups here, but this one is very easy and leads to a slightly better position for Black.} 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bc5 {Developing with a tempo.} 6. f3 a5 {⩱ A very useful move for this structure, stabilizing the bishop, gaining some space on the queenside. Even though the position is without queens, there is an interesting idea for Black, to play ...[f5] and ...[Nf6], with the idea that White's king can't castle anymore, and the [c3]-move weakened quite a few light squares.}) 3... Qxd5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb1c3]} 4. d4 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4,Ye5d4] Just continuing the development, we shouldn't rush taking on [d4], since it would only open the [c3]-square for the knight.} 5. Be3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4]} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ye5d4,Yf5b1,Yc3d4,Ya1b1,Gf8b4,Yb4e1] A rare move, but looks very promising. The idea is that we will eventually take on [d4], and before the knight could come to [c3], we are taking it on [b1], and follow it up with a very unpleasant ...[Bb4]+ !} 6. Nf3 (6. c4 $4 {Kicking the queen and trying to gain some stability in the centre is backfiring here.} Qa5+ 7. Bd2 Qb6 {-+ The pawns on [b2] and [d4] are hanging, White's position is just hopeless.}) 6... exd4 {Executing the idea behind our previous move.} 7. cxd4 (7. Nxd4 {Objectively this is probably a better recapture, but White's position remains tough.} O-O-O {⩱ With better development for Black, the next moves are ...[Bc5], ...[Nf6] and ...[Rhe8], so just centralising our forces, and in the meantime White somehow has to solve the problem of the [g2]-pawn, which slows down the development of our opponent.}) 7... Bxb1 $1 {Step 2 accomplished!} 8. Qxb1 Bb4+ {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Yb4e1] White can't really block this check, because then the [d4]-pawn is falling, so the king has to move.} 9. Kd1 O-O-O $17 {[%csl Rd1,Rd4][%cal Yb4c5,Yc5d4,Gg8f6,Gh8e8] We have the better structure and White's king is in the centre, we can't ask more from the opening.} *

