1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. c3 $6 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] This is the so-called MacLeod Attack. White's idea is to push for [d4] and then recapture with the pawn, which sounds like a very sensible plan. The problem is that this idea is too slow, and while White is preparing for it, Black can already strike in the centre!} d5 $1 {There is no reason for delaying this move. The pawn on [c3] stands very well from our perspective, once the queen arrives on [d5], it can't be kicked out with the move [Nc3].} 3. exd5 ({•} 3. Nf3 $6 {The inventor of the line, MacLeod liked to play this move, but Black can achieve a nice advantage by simple means.} dxe4 4. Nxe5 {The knight is pretty insecure in the middle of the board.} Qe7 $1 {A very precise move, not allowing White to play [d4], because then after the en passant, the pin on the e-file will be deadly.} 5. Nc4 Nc6 6. Be2 Bf5 {⩱ After very natural developing moves, we have a nice space advantage in the centre, and very easy follow-up play in the form of [O-O-O], [Nf6] and since most probably White is going to castle short, we will start pushing our h-pawn very soon as well.}) ({•} 3. d3 {A very sad move, White is already admitting the opening went wrong.} dxe4 {There are many other moves and setups here, but this one is very easy and leads to a slightly better position for Black.} 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bc5 {Developing with a tempo.} 6. f3 a5 {⩱ A very useful move for this structure, stabilizing the bishop, gaining some space on the queenside. Even though the position is without queens, there is an interesting idea for Black, to play ...[f5] and ...[Nf6], with the idea that White's king can't castle anymore, and the [c3]-move weakened quite a few light squares.}) 3... Qxd5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb1c3]} 4. d4 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4,Ye5d4] Just continuing the development, we shouldn't rush taking on [d4], since it would only open the [c3]-square for the knight.} 5. Nf3 (5. dxe5 $2 {White is trying to simplify, but the [c3]-move is really hurting our opponent, because of the weakness of light-squares, especially [d3].} Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Bg4+ 7. f3 O-O-O+ {Very energetic development from Black, we don't have to hurry taking back the pawn on [e5].} 8. Ke1 Bf5 {∓ White doesn't have a single developed piece, and if they want to hang on to the [e5]-pawn, by playing [f4], then we can simply undermine it by...[f6]! and if the e-file also opens up, White's king will be in extreme danger.}) 5... Bf5 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ye5d4,Yf5b1,Ya1b1,Yc3d4,Gf8b4,Gb4e1]} ({Even though} 5... Bg4 {also looks very tempting, I believe those lines after} 6. Be2 {are not so clear, while this idea of targeting the [b1]-knight seems pretty strong in this variation as well.}) 6. Be2 {Here we are at crossroads, we have a choice between two promising lines, with very different characteristics.} (6. dxe5 {Going for the endgame with an uncastled king will again bring nothing good for White.} Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 8. Nbd2 Nge7 {⩱ With ideas like ...[Ng6]-[Ngxe5] and then ...[Bc5] coming, Black is clearly in the driver's seat.}) 6... exd4 {This is our alternative option, where basically we are taking a pawn by force.} 7. cxd4 Bxb1 $1 {Of course! Just before the knight could come to [c3].} 8. Rxb1 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 {Now White can block the check, but they still can't avoid losing the [d4]-pawn.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O-O 11. O-O (11. Rd1 {This move doesn't help either, not only the [a2]-pawn is hanging, it is probably even better just to go for the [d4]-pawn since we are at the same time also completing the development.} Nge7 {∓ The idea of...[Nf5] and then taking on [d4] looks unstoppable.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 {Black won a pawn, have a perfect structure, so this position looks very good. However it has to be said, that since we castled to opposite sides, and for White it is much easier to push the pawns on the queenside, there is some decent compensation for the pawn.} 13. Qc2 Nf6 $15 {I believe objectively Black should be slightly better, but White has practical chances.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
