[White "1) 1.e4 e5 - Unusual Second Moves"]
[Black "Unusual Second Moves - 2.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[GameId "2160376108940918"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. g3 $2 {Was played in quite a big number of games, but nevertheless it is pretty bad.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Yd5h1] Of course! The difference compared to the 2...[d5] line is that our queen will recapture on [d5] with a tempo!} 4. Nd2 {[%csl Yg2,Rg3,Yh3][%cal Gf1e2] Philidor-type of opening play from White, but the move order is far from ideal, and also the bishop normally goes to [e2], which would be quite problematic here because the pawn is already on [g3].} (4. exd5 $2 {Leads to a really miserable position for White.} Qxd5 5. Qf3 Qa5+ {We are not trading that awkward queen on [f3].} 6. Nc3 Nf6 {∓ With ... [Bb4] and ...[Nd4] coming, Black is much better.}) 4... dxe4 {Clarifying the situation in the centre is the most straightforward way to reach an advantage in this position.} (4... f5 $5 {If you are in an aggressive mood, this move is worth trying!}) 5. dxe4 (5. Nxe4 {This move offers us to take more central control with tempo. We are not going to reject this offer!} f5 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bd6 8. Nf3 O-O {⩱ We can conclude that the opening was a success for Black, who achieved a nice space advantage in the centre. It is useful to play...[Kh8] in such positions, when our f-pawn is not on [f7] anymore, and otherwise we have some typical attacking ideas like ... [Qe8]-[h5].}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Rf2][%cal Ga7f2] The bishop is fantastic on this diagonal, it is already targeting a potential weak pawn in White's camp, [f2].} 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. Ngf3 O-O {The games is progressing logically, both sides are developing their forces.} 8. O-O a5 {[%csl Ga4,Ga7][%cal Yc5a7,Ya5a4] Making the [g1]-[a7] diagonal a little bit longer for the bishop, gaining space on the queenside, this is a very typical, useful move for this structure.} 9. c3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd1c2,Yc2e4,Yd2b3,Yd2c4,Yc1g5] White wants to play [Qc2], in order to free their [d2]-knight from its defensive responsibilities.} (9. a4 {Looks like a logical, almost automatic move, but it doesn't help with the development.} b6 $1 {↑ The bishop is coming very quickly to [a6], and we will follow it up with ...[Ng4], White is already in danger.}) 9... a4 $15 {[%csl Ra2,Rd3,Rf2][%cal Yb7b6,Yc8a6,Yf6g4,Yh7h6,Yc8e6] With gaining more space on the queenside Black achieves a very comfortable position. We have a lot of ideas here, we can try to play ... [b6]-[Ba6]-[Ng4] and put pressure on the [f2]-pawn, but if we want to keep an eye on the [a2]-pawn and put our bishop to [e6], that is also possible, just it is good to play ...[h6] first, to avoid any [Ng5] annoying jumps from White.} *

