[White "1) 1.e4 e5 - Unusual Second Moves"]
[Black "Unusual Second Moves - 2.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C20"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376108969591"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. a3 {Not a horrible move, but somewhat strange. 🙂 Jorden Van Foreest played like this twice, so it deserves some coverage. White's idea is to play [c4] and basically get into an English opening.} d5 $1 {The easiest, we don't want any kind of English opening.} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 {Even though this move is coming with a tempo, and we don't have the usual [Bb4], it would be hard to say that White tricked us, because he spent a tempo on playing [a3], which is. .. not a very useful move. 🙂} Qe6 $1 {We are basically playing the Centre Gambit with opposite colours. Even though we are down a tempo, since we are Black, White managed to use those moves for playing [a3], and even worse, [d3], so the [f1]-bishop can't go out to [b5].} 6. Nf3 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Exactly like this. We are really playing a Centre Gambit!} 7. g3 O-O-O 8. Bg2 Nd4 {[%cal Gd7c6] Putting the knight to a very nice square and opening the [c6]-square for our bishop.} 9. O-O Nxf3+ {Either forcing White's bishop to an awkward square, or trading the light-squared bishop on [g2], which regarding roles in the attack and defence is White's most important piece.} 10. Qxf3 (10. Bxf3 Ne7 {↑ We have many ideas here, putting the other knight to [d4], trading the bishops by playing ...[Bc6] at some moment, and most importantly, marching with our h-pawn and attack White's king!}) 10... Bc6 11. Qe3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Kb8 $132 {[%cal Yh7h5,Yh5h4,Gg8e7,Ge7f5] We have a position with mutual chances, but Black can be very optimistic about the attacking chances on the kingside.} *

