1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. Be3 {This move was played twice by TOP-GM Levon Aronian. The idea, similarly to 3. [a3], is to play [c4] very soon, and transpose the game into English waters.} d5 $1 {Still no weird transpositions for us! 🙂} (3... Nf6 4. c4 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 {(This was played in the game Aronian-Grischuk lichess 2020, and the position resembles a lot to the one, which we usually get after ) 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.e4 Bb4 5.d3 .}) 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1] Thanks to this move we are not losing any time with the queen.} 6. Nf3 Nge7 {[%csl Gd4,Re3][%cal Ye7f5,Yf5d4,Yf5e3]} ({Instead,} 6... Nf6 {(was played in the game Aronian-Paravyan lichess 2020, which is also completely fine for Black, but I like the idea to go towards the [d4]-square with the knight.)}) 7. Be2 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4] Occupying a central square with the knight can't be too bad.} 8. Bd2 (8. O-O $6 {Allows some very favourable transformation of the position for Black.} Bxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Nxe2+ 10. Qxe2 Bg4 {⩱ Black already has the better structure, and the pin on the [f3]-knight is also very unpleasant.}) 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ng6 $10 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gg6f4]} (9... Ng6 {Black is at least comfortable if not better here, for instance} 10. Qd2 {If White wants to be flexible with castling, and control the [f4]-square, they can be punished by a spectacular move!} Bh3 $1 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Bxg2 13. Qe3+ $1 {White has to find a couple of only moves in order to not lose on the spot.} Kd7 14. c4 $1 Qf5 15. Rg1 Rhe8 {∓ With ...[Bf3] or ...[Rxe2]+ ...[Bf3] and ...[Re8] to follow, Black has a huge advantage.}) *

