[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376109014649"]

1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Yf6d5,Gd7d5] Preparing to push ...[d5] in the next move.} 4. f4 $6 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gf1e2,Ge1g1] As we will see, thanks to the inclusion of the moves: [Nc3]-[Nc6], this logical continuation is not working well at all for White.} exf4 {In general [f4] requires a reaction from Black, if we just allow our opponent to play [Nf3] and then finish the development, then we'll have less space, and potentially White can develop a dangerous play on the kingside, either by playing [f5], or taking on [e5] and using the semi-open f-file. The most obvious reaction from us is to take on [f4] and in the vast majority of cases follow it up with ...[d5]! and the other one is to play ...[d5] right away.} 5. Bxf4 d5 $1 {Very important, we are continuing the fight for the centre.} 6. Nxd5 {The only 'point' of this move if White is going for the [c7]-pawn, otherwise it is just helping with our development.} Nxd5 7. exd5 Qxd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc8f5,Gf8c5] We have a much better development, White should already fight for the equality here.} 8. Bxc7 {This brave but rather greedy move can be the point of White's previous play.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Rg1][%cal Gc5g1] Castling to the kingside is not so realistic for White after this move.} 9. Qf3 Qd7 {[%csl Rc2,Rc7,Rf3][%cal Yd7c7,Yd4f3,Yd4c2,Gc6d4] Of course, we are not interested in the queen trade now, and even though we are going backwards, we are gaining a tempo on the bishop, and also the queen on [f3] will be exposed to ...[Nd4] ideas.} 10. Bf4 O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e1] Now...[Re8] check is also a threat.} 11. O-O-O {[%csl Rc1,Yf1,Yf3,Yf4,Yg1,Yh1] Even though castling normally means some kind of safety for the king, if we take a closer look, we can see that White's pieces are located on the kingside, not really providing any help for the defense.} Nd4 12. Qh5 Bb6 $19 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2,Rf4][%cal Yd4c2,Gd7a4,Ya4f4,Ya4a2,Gc8e6] With an already winning position for Black. The ...[Qa4] move will be extremely unpleasant to meet, the pawns on [c2] and [a2] are weak, and the only developed minor piece, the [f4]-bishop, is very loose and therefore a tactical target.} *

