1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Yf6d5,Gd7d5] Preparing to push ...[d5] in the next move.} 4. g3 ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 $1 {Transposes to the Scotch Four Knights game.}) ({•} 4. g4 $6 {The move breaks some opening principles, but it was played by strong GM, Shevchenko in 2021, so we can have a brief look at it.} h6 $1 {Preventing [g5], which was pretty much the only idea behind White's previous move.} 5. Bg2 Bb4 {The game of GM Shevchenko continued with 5...[Bc5], but the text move looks more logical, by pinning the knight we are introducing the [d5]-break into the position.} 6. Bd2 {(6.h4 White insists on playing for [g5] and then recapture with the pawn, but this approach is creating a lot of weak squares behind those pawns. 6...d6 (6...d5 is also good, but this one is even easier, the main goal is anyway to hit the [g4]-pawn. ) 7.g5 hxg5 8.hxg5 Rxh1 9.Bxh1 Ng4 Once the situation clarified a little bit on the kingside, it is not clear what White managed to achieve, since our opponent wanted to push back the very knight, which just landed on [g4]. 10.Bf3 (10.f3 Bc5! Important, but not difficult tactical point. 11.fxg4 Bxg1 ∓ Our next moves are ...[Be6]-[Kd7]-[Qh8] and play against White's very weak kingside. ) 10...Qd7 ↑ The next move is ...[Bc5] and forcing White to take on [g4], and with that giving us the pair of bishops and slightly better endgame. )} Bxc3 {Not a must, but an easy way to achieve a slightly better position.} 7. Bxc3 d5 {Unfortunately for White, they have to waste a tempo for the loose pawn on [g4].} 8. h3 Be6 {⩱ ...[Qe7] and [O-O-O] is coming, Black's play is much easier with the central space advantage.}) 4... d5 $1 {There is absolutely no reason to delay this move.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 {We have to make a decision with the the [d5]-knight now, and in most cases I prefer not taking on [c3] and give the semi-open b-file for White's rook. Unless there are some concrete reasons which forces Black to take on [c3], I tried to be consistent with this approach, when White develops the bishop to [g2].} Be6 7. Nf3 (7. Nge2 $2 {This is a serious mistake, White will castle short, and for the king's defense, the knight is very much needed on [f3]!} Qd7 8. O-O O-O-O {∓ With ...[h5]-[h4] and eventually ...[Bh3] coming, it really feels like that we are attacking the Sicilian Dragon. 🙂}) 7... Qd7 {There are other ways for Black, but I like this ambitious setup with [O-O-O] coming.} 8. O-O (8. Ng5 {It is important that this move is not an issue as long as we have} Bg4 $1 {with a tempo!}) 8... O-O-O {It looks much easier to attack with Black than with White in this position.} 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. c3 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ya2a4] White is trying to create counterplay on the queenside.} f6 {[%csl Gc6,Ge5][%cal Yf6e5,Yg7g5,Yh7h5,Gd7h7] Very useful improving move, now we don't have to be worried about the [e5]-pawn anymore, and it also opens the 7th rank for the queen, which can be important later.} 11. b4 Kb8 $40 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7f5,Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] I like Black's chances a lot here, our attack is very obvious, while White still has to work a lot to find targets in our position.} *

