1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. d3 {A very modest line, called the Leonardis variation. White obviously can't really fight for an opening advantage after such a move, but things can get interesting against certain responses.} Nc6 {All three natural moves for Black are fine here, besides my choice there is 3...[d5] and 3...[Nf6].} ({•} 2... d5 {This is of course fine, but here we can see the advantage of 2. [d3] over 2. [c3], the knight can jump to [c3]!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {In any case, it is not a big deal for Black, since we can pin this knight.} Bb4 5. Bd2 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc6 7. f4 Nge7 {∞ The position is around equal, but I wanted something more against 2. [d3].}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {This is the most popular move, but I didn't like it, because it allows one of the very few proactive ideas for White after 2. [d3].} 3. f4 $5 exf4 4. Bxf4 {With an interesting position, in such cases I would prefer to have my other knight developed, because if} d5 {now, then} 5. e5 $1 {is coming with a tempo.}) 3. f4 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc1f4] I didn't find the name of this variation, but it looks like that White wants to play the King's Gambit, without it being a gambit. 🙂} (3. Nf3 Nf6 {This position is analysed under the 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d3 Nf6 move order.}) 3... exf4 {As usual, on [f4] we have the two standard options, taking and playing ...[d5] or playing ... [d5] right away. I analysed both, both look fine, but the text move seems to be more ambitious.} 4. Bxf4 d5 $1 {Just like this!} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bxc7 $6 {It is not good, but the only move which is worth analysing, otherwise White is simply worse.} (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Be2 O-O-O 8. O-O h5 {⩱ Black has a nice advantage here, with clear ideas and more active pieces. ...[Bc5]-[Nge7] and then [f6]-[g5] is one possible way to continue the game.}) 6... Nf6 {Development is more important than the pawn!} 7. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4e1]} 8. Qd2 Qc5 {[%csl Rc3,Rc7][%cal Gf6d5,Yd5c3,Yd5c7] Preparing the [d5]-square for the knight!} 9. O-O-O Nd5 10. Qe2+ {This was White's idea, otherwise the position would be just lost. Now at least the [c3]-knight is not pinned anymore.} Be6 {But we can just develop again!} 11. Ne4 {This is the best move according to the engine, but it also doesn't help.} (11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {(11...Nd4! is even stronger according to the computer, but if you don't remember the details it can get somewhat tricky, so I like the text move better. )} 12. c4 Qd7 13. Bg3 O-O {∓ Nd4 is a threat, and we also want to play ...[b5], [Rfd8]-[Rac8] and attack White's king, which currently doesn't really have any defenders.}) 11... Qe3+ $1 {This unexpected trade wins material for Black.} 12. Qxe3 {White must take, since otherwise we take on [e2] and then collect the bishop on [c7].} Nxe3 $17 {[%csl Rd1,Re1][%cal Yb4e1,Ye3d1] The [d1] rook is trapped, Black has a clear advantage.} *

