1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Ne2 {This modest and unusual developing move with the knight is called Alapin's Opening. I believe it is already quite clear at this moment, that his idea of 1.e4 c5 2.c3!? is much more dangerous for the Black players than this particular line. Having said that, it was played by the likes of Ivanchuk, Rapport or Van Foreest, so it is definitely not a mistake, just not the most ambitious play from White.} Nc6 ({I find this move the most consistent with our repertoire. If, for example, we would play} 2... Nf6 {, then after} 3. d4 $5 {we should learn some new lines, which I don't see as a necessity.}) 3. f4 $6 {This move gives a very strange impression, the knight begs to be on [f3] and not on [e2] in such cases.} Bc5 {Since we learned how to react on [f4], by taking + immediately playing ...[d5], it is time to break the rule. 🙂 In this particular case ...[d5] is again a great move, but taking on [f4] and improving White's knight would be dubious from us. I chose the text move, because the bishop looks very good in that diagonal and if White continues in the same spirit, the game can end very quickly.} 4. Nbc3 (4. fxe5 $2 {White is falling for the trap.} d6 $1 {Bringing more pieces into the game!} 5. exd6 {(5.d4? Looks logical, but just losing material. 5...Qh4+ 6.Ng3 Bxd4 -+ (6.g3 Qxe4 -+ With double attack on the rook and the [d4]-pawn. ))} Qh4+ 6. Ng3 Bxd6 {This was a hidden point of playing ...[d6]! Now the knight on [g3] is in trouble.} 7. Qf3 Nd4 8. Qd3 Nxc2+ 9. Qxc2 Bxg3+ {+ -+ And Black is continuing the attack with equal material on the board.}) 4... d6 {[%csl Re2,Ge5][%cal Yd6e5] Stabilising the centre, and White has not much to show against the bishop on [c5].} 5. d3 (5. Na4 {A logical try, White is getting rid of the strong bishop, but Black can transform the advantage.} Bg4 6. fxe5 Qh4+ 7. g3 Qh5 8. Nxc5 dxc5 {∓ ...[Bf3] and then ...[Qxh2] or ...[Nxe5] is coming, White is close to losing.}) 5... a5 $15 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gf7f5,Gg8f6] Securing the [g1]-[a7] diagonal for the bishop, we can play ...[f5] and [Nf6] next, with a very serious initiative.} (5... a5 {•} 6. f5 g6 $1 {Undermining the [f5]-pawn.} 7. Ng3 Qh4 8. Nd5 Kd8 $1 {∓ It is not a big deal, since White has problems with development, and their position is just falling apart on [f5].}) (5... a5 {•} 6. g3 f5 7. Bg2 Nge7 $1 {In this particular case it is better to develop the knight here and not to [f6], since if White ever wants to open the long diagonal with [exf5], the knight can take back on [f5].} 8. fxe5 {It is hard to find another way of developing for White, since they simply can't castle short.} dxe5 9. Bg5 {Preparing [Qd2] and [O-O-O].} h6 $1 {Gaining the bishop pair.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qd2 O-O {⩱ White's dark-squares are very weak, and it is also quite easy to attack their king on the queenside.}) *

