1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Ne2 {This modest and unusual developing move with the knight is called Alapin's Opening. I believe it is already quite clear at this moment, that his idea of 1.e4 c5 2.c3!? is much more dangerous for the Black players than this particular line. Having said that, it was played by the likes of Ivanchuk, Rapport or Van Foreest, so it is definitely not a mistake, just not the most ambitious play from White.} Nc6 ({I find this move the most consistent with our repertoire. If, for example, we would play} 2... Nf6 {, then after} 3. d4 $5 {we should learn some new lines, which I don't see as a necessity.}) 3. Nbc3 {If White doesn't want to transpose to the Scotch game, then this move is the best try.} ({•} 3. d4 {Now this move is not a problem, we are simply transposing to the Scotch game.} exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5) ({•} 3. Ng3 $2 {This move is simply very bad, moving the same piece again, and completely ignoring Black's idea.} d5 4. d3 h5 $1 {A nice idea with a little tactical help. (5.Nxh5 can be answered by 5...dxe4! and White can't take back on [e4], because after the queen trade, the knight is dropping on [h5]. And if White can't take back on [e4], then we simply managed to exchange a central pawn for a flank pawn, and also our rook on [h8] became active. )} 5. h4 g6 {⩱ Playing ...[d4] and [Be7] looks like a tempting follow-up for Black, but there are many ways to play, White so far misplaced a knight, and lost space in the centre.}) ({•} 3. g3 $2 {Doesn't look very bad, but it is! White simply can't afford such slow moves after already playing one of those with [Ne2].} d5 $1 {Of course! White is seriously worse after 3 moves!} 4. Bg2 dxe4 5. Bxe4 Nf6 {( Instead 5...Bh3 is an interesting idea, which is worth knowing, but even that one is not needed here. )} 6. Bg2 Be6 {∓ With ...[Qd7], [O-O-O] and then [h5]-[h4] to follow, Black is dominating. ( 4.Nbc3 This is not better. 4...dxe4 5.Nxe4 Bg4! 6.Bg2 Nd4 7.N4c3 Qd7 ∓ Black has a huge advantage. )}) 3... Nf6 {We are still ready to transpose into the Scotch, and well, that would be the best choice for White too.} 4. g3 $2 {Allowing ...[d5] and immediately giving Black a very nice position.} d5 $1 5. exd5 {Relatively the best, but the alternatives are really awful.} ({•} 5. Bg2 $2 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Bh3 $1 {∓ Making it tricky for White to castle short.}) ({•} 5. d3 $2 dxe4 $1 {Going for a much better endgame.} 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bg4 {-+ White is collapsing, ...[Bf3]-[Nd4]-[O-O-O] is coming.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 Be6 7. O-O Nxc3 {Since, as I said before, I don't like taking on [c3] and giving the b-file for White. 🙂 Seriously speaking, there was nothing wrong with just continuing with ...[Qd7], but the concrete reason here is that I like this option even more, because if White is not taking with the knight, then there is ...[Bd5] and we can trade the main defender of the king.} 8. bxc3 (8. Nxc3 Qd7 {⩱ We have seen similar positions before, ...[O-O-O] and then the h-pawn is coming, Black's king is much safer.}) 8... Bd5 $15 {[%cal Yd5g2,Yd8d5,Ge8c8] We will trade, and then long castle with the usual attacking ideas to follow.} *

