1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Bb5 {The Portuguese Opening, not a very popular one, and understandably so. It looks like that White is attacking the shadow of the [c6]-knight.} c6 {Looks like the most logical, and this move questions White's whole concept.} 3. Bc4 $6 {Provoking ...[d5], which... we wanted to play anyway.} d5 4. exd5 cxd5 5. Bb5+ (5. Bb3 {This is a very bad version of the Bishop's opening. Black has a lot of time to stabilise the centre.} Nc6 6. d3 Nf6 7. Bg5 Be6 {⩱ White has no compensation for giving up the centre.}) 5... Nc6 {Finally ...[Nc6] is coming, but White lost the centre along the way. 🙂} 6. d4 exd4 ({One of the possible options.} 6... Qb6 $5 {or 6...e4!? also look very good.}) 7. Qxd4 (7. Ne2 $4 {This was played by World Nr.1 Magnus Carlsen on lichess in 2021 against GM Sanal. ( The transposition is amusing, they reached this position via the 1.e3 e5 2.Ke2 d5 3.Ke1 c5 4.d4 Nc6 5.Bb5 exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Ne2 move order. 🙂 It has to be said that White's position is a little bit better in our case, since castling is still possible. )} Qa5+ {+ -+ It was played and Black went on to win the game.}) 7... Nf6 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. O-O O-O {Now we are winning a tempo, because the knight on [c6] is no longer pinned.} 10. Qh4 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7f5,Ge7g6] Very strong move, highlighting the fact that White's queen is struggling to find a comfortable square. Black is extremely active and has a comfortable advantage.} *

