1. e4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1h5,Gf1c4,Ye4d5] The most popular first move and, in the vast majority of the cases, the choice of the players who are new to the game, since it can lead to open positions and there are many tricks, traps, which are very tempting to try out.} e5 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5] Our choice against 1. [e4]. This is the most classic way to respond to the King's pawn opening since it controls the center in the same way White just did. It is an 'evergreen' opening, as it has been, is, and will always be popular at all levels for its solidity and richness of play.} 2. Bb5 {The Portuguese Opening, not a very popular one, and understandably so. It looks like that White is attacking the shadow of the [c6]-knight.} c6 {Looks like the most logical, and this move questions White's whole concept.} 3. Ba4 d5 {We will have to take back with the queen on [d5], but it is not a problem at all.} 4. Nc3 $6 {The most common move in the position, but Black has many good antidotes to it.} ({•} 4. d3 $6 {White agrees to go for a clearly worse endgame at move} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Nf6 7. f3 Nbd7 {⩱ With the bishop on [f1] it wouldn't be so horrible, but now after ...[Nc5] and ...[a5] White will have issues with that piece also.}) ({•} 4. Nf3 $4 {Losing material.} dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qa5 $1 {Wins a piece!} 6. Qh5 g6 7. Qg5 f6 {-+}) ({•} 4. Qe2 $2 {Not a good move, White will have no control in the centre with pawns, so Black can develop initiative very easily.} dxe4 5. Qxe4 Bd6 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Qh4 e4 $1 {The problems are starting for White.} 8. Ng5 O-O 9. O-O h6 $1 {A very nice move, showing the complete lack of harmony in White's camp.} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Re8 12. Qd3 {(12.Qf3 Qh4 -+ Is picking up the [a4] bishop. )} a5 {The awkward position of the bishop+queen and the lack of development is -4 in the computer's language. 🙂} 13. a3 Na6 14. Bb3 {White is saving the bishop but losing more time.} Nc5 15. Qf3 Nxb3 16. cxb3 Qh4 17. g3 Bg4 {-+ White's position is hopeless here, the question is whether they will get mated with or without queens.}) 4... a5 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7b5,Ga5a4,Ya4b3] I like this move the most, we are threatening to trap the bishop!} 5. a3 {Pretty much the only move, the alternative leads to a very weird position for White.} (5. Bb3 $6 d4 6. Nce2 a4 $1 {We are forcing the bishop to [d3].} 7. Bc4 b5 8. Bd3 Na6 9. Nf3 Bd6 {∓ White's position doesn't look good, and we will just continue with moves like... [Nf6] and [Nc5].}) 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 {With a tempo!} 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {White's knight made 3 moves, our knight 1, it is a good trade for us!} 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. d3 Nd7 $36 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Ge8c8] Black can castle both sides, will probably play ... [Bd6], and already have the ...[Nc5]-threat in the position.} *

