1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. f4 $2 {This is the Halász Gambit, a pretty dubious opening variation.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4] We can simply protect our extra central pawn.} 4. Nf3 d5 $1 {Creating more presence in the centre and also making the [f5]-square available for our pieces.} 5. e5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yc8f5,Yg8h6,Yh6f5]} Bc5 6. a3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Yc6b4,Yb4d3,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] This is the most common move in the position, White wants to develop with [Bd3] and don't want to allow the ...[Nb4] move, and also [b4]-[b5] can be an idea for White.} ({•} 6. Bd3 {White can start with this move as well, but then they have to be ready for ...[Nb4].} Nh6 7. O-O O-O {∓ With ...[f6] or ...[Nb4] on the next move.} 8. Ng5 {It's not dangerous as Black has, for example,} Bf5) ({•} 6. Bb5 {Trying to win back the pawn on [d4] is not good when combined with a weakened [g1]-[a7] diagonal.} Nge7 7. Nxd4 {With the pawn on [f2], it could be a game.} a6 $1 {Forcing some favourable trades.} 8. Bxc6+ Nxc6 {Black wants to trade the knight on [d4], so the [a1]-[g7] diagonal will open.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {-+ Black is pretty much winning here, ...[O-O] followed by ...[f6] or ...[a5] followed by ...[Ba6] are good options. (9.Be3 Qh4+ 10.g3 Qh3 -+ White kind of solved the dark square problems, and now they are losing on the light squares with ...[Bg4] coming. )}) 6... Nh6 {Very comfortable square for the knight, it can jump to [f5] and in case we want to play with a quick ...[f6], we can take back simply with the queen, since the knight is not blocking the way from [e7].} 7. b4 Bb6 8. Bd3 (8. b5 {This wouldn't help much, White is regaining the pawn, but their position will be full of weaknesses.} Ne7 9. Nxd4 Nef5 {-+ With threats like ... [Qh4]+, White is losing here.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O f6 $17 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yf6e5] Undermining White's only trump in the position, the kingside majority. Black keeps the extra pawn, and is much better.} *

