1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4] White wanted to play a gambit, but all of a sudden their queen is in the centre now, giving potentially some nice tempi for Black's development.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5,Re4][%cal Gf6d5,Yf6e4] Excellent developing move, protecting and attacking at the same time, and also forcing White to make a decision with the [e4]-pawn.} 5. e5 $2 {This move is very bad, White will have a lot of concrete problems to solve.} Ne4 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8c5,Gc5f2] ...[Bc5] is a huge threat now!} 6. Be3 Bc5 7. Qd3 Nc6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yc6e5] Now you can see the problems with that ambitious 5. [e5] move, Black is simply developing and attacking that loose pawn.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {White is trying to catch up in the development, but the weakness of the [e5]-pawn remains.} Bxe3 10. Qxe3 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Re8 $17 {[%csl Re5] In the next move, or after ...[Bg4], the [e5]-pawn is going to fall.} *

