1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4] White wanted to play a gambit, but all of a sudden their queen is in the centre now, giving potentially some nice tempi for Black's development.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5,Re4][%cal Gf6d5,Yf6e4] Excellent developing move, protecting and attacking at the same time, and also forcing White to make a decision with the [e4]-pawn.} 5. exd5 {The most sober choice in the position, White has to admit that he has no opening advantage whatsoever, and just try to equalise the position.} Qxd5 6. Qxd5 Nxd5 7. Nf3 Nd7 $10 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc8f5,Ge8c8,Yc5d3] The position is certainly even at this point, but if someone has to be careful it is White, thanks to the [c3]-move, which weakens the [d3]-square and gives Black's minor pieces some clear target.} *

