1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4] White wanted to play a gambit, but all of a sudden their queen is in the centre now, giving potentially some nice tempi for Black's development.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5,Re4][%cal Gf6d5,Yf6e4] Excellent developing move, protecting and attacking at the same time, and also forcing White to make a decision with the [e4]-pawn.} 5. Bg5 $6 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg5d8] This is the most common choice for White, and it is the most logical as well, developing a piece and solving the issue of the [e4]-pawn by tactical means. The only problem with the move is, that Black has a very strong reply. 🙂} Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yd5e4,Gf8c5,Yf1b5,Yc7c6] Excellent move! Renewing the threat of ...[dxe4], overprotecting the knight on [f6], and very importantly, making the [f1]-bishop useless, since a move like [Bb5] can be simply neutralised by ...[c6].} (5... dxe4 {This doesn't lead anywhere, or maybe to a small White edge.} 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nd2 {Now the pawn is hanging on [e4], because of the pin.} Bf5 8. Ne2 $1 {⩲ With [Ng3] to follow, White will regain the material with a slightly better development and the option of ruining our structure with [Bxf6].}) 6. exd5 {White accepts the pawn, but even after this move our opponent is very far from equality.} ({•} 6. Qxd5 {A funny move, but Black has different good responses.} Nxd5 7. Bxd8 Nb4 $1 {I like this the most.} 8. cxb4 Bxb4+ 9. Nc3 Kxd8 {⩱ Thanks to the pair of bishops Black is already slightly better in this endgame.}) ({•} 6. e5 $2 {This was played in the only OTB game which reached this position, but it simply doesn't work.} Bc5 $1 7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qxd5 c6 {There are many good moves for Black, but it is good to win another tempo on the queen.} 9. Qd2 Qe7 {∓ We will probably take with the knight on [e5], then develop the [c8]-bishop and castle long with a huge advantage, thanks to our dominating bishops and much better development. ( 7.Qf4 The only square where the queen can protect the [e5]-pawn, but it will not help for long. 7...Qe7! 8.Nf3 h6! 9.Bxf6 gxf6 -+ The [e5]-pawn is lost, Black has a winning position. )}) 6... Bc5 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Ye1,Rf1,Rg1,Rh1][%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e8] The speed of development is the key factor in this position.} 7. Bxf6 (7. Qh4 $2 {Basically on any queen move, ...[O-O] and [Re8]+ is coming.} O-O 8. Bd3 {And if we are not blundering [Bxh7]+ now, then we will have a huge advantage.} h6 $1 9. Bxf6 Nxf6 {-+ With ...[Qxd5] and ... [Re8]+ check coming, Black is pretty much winning here.}) 7... Qxf6 $1 {Even though we will have to trade the queens, which looks like an achievement for White, our advantage in the development will be still very significant.} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Gc5,Gc8,Gf6][%cal Yc8f5]} 9. Bb5+ (9. Bc4 $2 {White can't keep their extra pawn for long.} Ne4 $1 {∓ The [f2]-pawn is falling.}) 9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 $36 {[%csl Rd5,Re1,Rf2][%cal Gf6g4,Gh8e8,Yg4f2,Ga8d8,Gd7c8] White always develops a piece and then trades it, so it looks like that our opponent is doing nothing with the development. 🙂 But now the time of trades is over, we will bring the rooks into the centre, take the pawn on [d5], and have a clear edge.} *

