1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. exd5 (4. cxd4 $2 {White insists on playing with less material, and well, now I see no reason not to accept this gift.} dxe4 {The difference is visible compared to taking on [c3] on move 3, now both sides have easy development, just Black has an extra pawn. 🙂} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Be7 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 {∓ Both sides have more or less finished developing, and Black comfortably keeps the extra pawn.}) 4... Qxd5 5. cxd4 {We have very easy development in this position, the only issue is our queen on [d5], we would obviously prefer a knight there, but okay, there is no reason to complain.} Nc6 6. Be3 $6 {As we will see later, White can also protect the [d4]-pawn by tactical means, so this move is just too passive now, allowing Black to take over the initiative.} Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nf6 {We have no issues with development whatsoever.} 8. Nf3 Qa5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ya5c3,Yf6e4,Yf6d5]} ({Very precise, keeping the initiative.} 8... Bg4 {This looks very tempting, but it allows} 9. Be2 $1 {and after} Qa5 10. O-O {White doesn't mind giving up the [c3]-pawn, since we are not taking it with check, so our opponent can use that time to create dangerous counterplay. In fact, in this particular position, the computer already prefers White.}) 9. Qb3 ({The better square for the queen.} 9. Qc2 $6 {Inviting ... [Bf5] ideas.} O-O $1 {⩱ A smart waiting move, the idea is that if White goes [Be2], then we go for ...[Bf5], and if our opponent goes to [d3] with the bishop, then we can play ...[Bg4]! White is under pressure in this position.}) 9... O-O 10. Bc4 {White is not interested in allowing ...[Be6].} Qh5 $1 {A very cool move! Putting the emphasis to the other side of the board.} 11. O-O Bd6 $15 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4,Rh2][%cal Gc8g4,Gc6a5,Ya5b3,Ya5c4,Gf6g4] With ...[Bg4] or ...[Ng4] coming on the kingside and ...[Na5] on the queenside, Black keeps the better chances.} *

