1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. exd5 (4. cxd4 $2 {White insists on playing with less material, and well, now I see no reason not to accept this gift.} dxe4 {The difference is visible compared to taking on [c3] on move 3, now both sides have easy development, just Black has an extra pawn. 🙂} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Be7 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 {∓ Both sides have more or less finished developing, and Black comfortably keeps the extra pawn.}) 4... Qxd5 5. cxd4 {We have very easy development in this position, the only issue is our queen on [d5], we would obviously prefer a knight there, but okay, there is no reason to complain.} Nc6 6. Be3 $6 {As we will see later, White can also protect the [d4]-pawn by tactical means, so this move is just too passive now, allowing Black to take over the initiative.} Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nf6 {We have no issues with development whatsoever.} 8. a3 {White is solving the issue of the pin, but losing more time along the way.} (8. Nge2 {White is preparing to play [a3], and they want to replace the knight on [c3] with another knight, so our queen will be again under attack.} Bg4 9. a3 Bxe2 {This looks like a nice solution, we are gaining some time by not allowing White to have another knight on [c3].} 10. Qxe2 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 O-O {⩱ Besides the worst structure, White has also problems with finishing the development, and our idea is to improve our worst piece, the [c6]-knight by bringing it to [f5], and then play ... [Rfe8] to put more pressure on the [e3]-bishop.}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Bg4 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gf6,Gg4] All the pieces are coming to the game.} 10. Nf3 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Re3][%cal Gf6d5,Yd5e3,Yd5c3,Ge8c8,Ya5c3,Gh8e8] With ideas like ... [Nd5] and [O-O-O] to follow, Black is clearly in the driver's seat here.} *

