1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3,Gf1c4,Gg1f3,Ge1g1] The Danish Gambit. White's idea is to sacrifice a pawn or pawns and provide quick development for the minor pieces. Not a bad idea, such play was very common and successful before opening theory existed.} d5 {In a way, an economical choice, but that is never the first or second consideration in this repertoire. The point is simply that I don't want to give White the game they want. They want to sacrifice material, quickly develop, attack, so play a very sharp game. This move doesn't allow it at all.} ({According to the computer, both} 3... dxc3 {and 3...Qe7 are stronger continuations, but again, those are certainly not refutations, and even though we can reach let's say, a -0.30 position, but the game remains complicated and White has play. It is a matter of taste, of course, but I believe the text is a very good practical choice.}) 4. exd5 (4. cxd4 $2 {White insists on playing with less material, and well, now I see no reason not to accept this gift.} dxe4 {The difference is visible compared to taking on [c3] on move 3, now both sides have easy development, just Black has an extra pawn. 🙂} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Be7 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 {∓ Both sides have more or less finished developing, and Black comfortably keeps the extra pawn.}) 4... Qxd5 5. cxd4 {We have very easy development in this position, the only issue is our queen on [d5], we would obviously prefer a knight there, but okay, there is no reason to complain.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {This is the correct way to protect the pawn on [d4].} Bg4 {[%csl Rd1,Rd4][%cal Yg4d1,Yc6d4,Yd5d4] Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 7. Be2 $1 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and don't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} Bb4+ (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 $4 9. Bxc6+ {+- is the simple tactical point behind 7. [Be2].}) 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position, we made all the logical developing moves, but now surprisingly Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $1 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square, and if it goes away we have to count on [d5]!. And if we take on [c3] at some moment instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} 9. Bxf3 Qc4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yc4f1,Re1g1,Yb4c3,Yc4c3] This is the surprising square, where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the c3-knight. This line is discussed in more detail in the Scotch Gambit chapter via the 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 exd4 4.c3 d5 move order.} *

