1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Bc4 {This is sometimes called the Centre Gambit, although it is just a semi-official name at best. It is not too bad, and again gives us the possibility to transpose into more well-known lines at some moment, or try to punish it. Similarly to the concept which I used before, if there is no big upside, I'll try to cut the workload and transpose.} Nc6 ({The way to try to punish White's choice starts with} 3... Nf6 {, where White's only good move is actually} 4. Nf3 {, (all the rest 4. [Bg5], 4. [Qxd4] or 4. [e5] are very dubious and Black has the advantage everywhere. After) 4.Nf3 there is ... [Bb4]+ or [Nxe4]. Both are interesting, but in my opinion we don't have to learn so much against such a rare line.}) 4. c3 $6 {If White doesn't want to transpose, but it is just very bad.} (4. Nf3 {By far the best move for White.} Nf6 $1 {And we transpose to the Scotch Gambit.}) 4... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yf6e4] The pawn is hanging on [e4], and it can't be even pushed forward.} 5. cxd4 Nxe4 {White is just down a pawn for no compensation at all, but the next move will just make things worse.} 6. Bxf7+ $2 Kxf7 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qd5+ {White is regaining the piece and losing the game.} Kg7 9. Qxe4 Bb4+ $19 {[%csl Re1,Re4][%cal Gh8e8,Ge8e1] ...[Re8] and [Re1]+ will clinch the win for Black.} *

