1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qa4 $6 {White is pretty much playing a reversed Scandinavian with an extra tempo. How bad can it be? Well, reversed openings are very often nothing special, and if you are familiar a little bit with the Scandinavian, you may know that Black most of the time plays with ...[e6] which corresponds to [e3] here to block the bishop's attack on the [f7] or here on the [f2]-square. Here it will not be possible.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Rf2][%cal Yc5f2,Ye4e3] The bishop will be very strong on this diagonal, since the e-pawn definitely can't move back to [e3].} 5. Nf3 (5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nge7 {is just another way to reach the mainline.}) 5... d6 6. Bg5 {Normally this move is coming with a pin on the knight, which stands on [f6], and here we can use this in our favour.} Nge7 $1 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gf7f6,Yg5d8] In the future we can neutralise this pin by playing ... [f6] and and later maybe ...[f5] will also be an idea.} 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O-O {Just as in the Scandinavian, White is opting for [O-O-O], and at the same time, sets up a small 'trap'.} f6 $1 ({The easiest solution, not allowing any activity for White.} 8... Bxf2 {This is fine according to the computer, but the game gets crazy.} 9. e5 $1) 9. Bh4 Kh8 {[%cal Ra2g8] The [a2]-[g8] diagonal has been weakened, so it makes a lot of sense to remove the king from there.} 10. Bd3 (10. Qc4 {Trying to find a better place for the queen, but it is still not easy to see where it is exactly.} Qe8 {⩱ Removing the queen from the d-file, and preparing moves like ...[Ng6] and ...[Be6], followed by an attack on the queenside.}) 10... a6 $17 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc8e6,Gb7b5] And Black has a clear advantage, White's main problem is their queen, which is not only misplaced, but also will help Black to gain tempi for the queenside attack.} *

