1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qd3 ({A rare move, but not so bad. White's point is that in the main line, which is} 4. Qe3 {, the queen will be very often misplaced once Black's rook is coming to [e8], so it has to move again. From [d3] it can solve the protection of the pawn, and will not be pinned after Black's ...[Re8].}) 4... d5 $5 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5][%cal Gc6b4,Yb4c2,Yb4d5] This move is played even more rarely, only once OTB. 🙂 It pretty much solves all the opening problems. The point is that since White most likely will take on [d5], the knight can come to [b4], with not only attacking on [d5], but also on [c2].} 5. exd5 (5. Qxd5 {Allows easy equality and slight initiative for Black.} Qxd5 6. exd5 Nb4 7. Bb5+ {White has to be precise. (7.Na3 Nxd5 ⩱ Because of the misplaced knight on [a3], Black is already slightly better here. )} Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Kxd7 9. Kd1 Nxd5 {The computer holds it for White, but it is not very easy and pleasant. We are going to play ...[Rd8] followed by ...[Kc8], [Nf6], [Bc5], [Rhe8] and see how our opponent can handle it.}) 5... Nb4 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5][%cal Yb4d5,Yd8d5,Yb4c2,Yb4d3] White is not able to keep their extra pawn.} 6. Qe2+ ({•} 6. Qe4+ {We can simply meet it with} Qe7 $1) ({•} 6. Qe3+ $6 {is even more inaccurate, White will have to lose one more tempo for protecting the pawn on [c2].} Be7 $1 {⩱}) 6... Qe7 7. Na3 Nxd5 $10 {[%csl Ra3] Black is very comfortable, and White has some issues to solve because of the knight on [a3].} *

