1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qc4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4]} ({A somewhat similar move to} 4. Qd3 {, White is trying to find a better place for the queen than [e3], but [c4] also gives a strange impression, it would be rather the square for the bishop in an ideal world.}) 4... Nf6 {Already threatening with ...[d5]!} 5. Bg5 $2 {A bad move, as White doesn't have any good move against ...[h6].} h6 {White is losing the pair of bishops or allowing ...[d5], both are very bad news for our opponent.} 6. Bh4 (6. Bxf6 Qxf6 {⩱ Black has the bishop pair and White has no compensation for it.}) 6... g5 {Breaking the pin and thus preparing ...[d5].} 7. Bg3 d5 {The position is opening up for Black, while White has almost no development.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yf1,Yg1,Yh1][%cal Gc8e6,Gd8e7,Gf8g7] With ...[Be6], [Bg7], [Qe7] coming, the computer is already saying decisive advantage for Black!} *

