1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qc4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4]} ({A somewhat similar move to} 4. Qd3 {, White is trying to find a better place for the queen than [e3], but [c4] also gives a strange impression, it would be rather the square for the bishop in an ideal world.}) 4... Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Already threatening with ...[d5]!} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Yc3d5] Pretty much the only move for White, in order to stop ...[d5].} Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb4e1,Gd7d5] Pinning the knight, therefore ...[d5] is a threat again!} 6. Bd2 {The fight continues, White breaks the pin, so ...[d5] is stopped again.} O-O ({If you would like to create immediate havoc, I can recommend you the move} 6... b5 $5 {. It leads to a very interesting game, where Black has great compensation for the pawn. However, since we can achieve a good position with much simpler means, I prefer the text move. 🙂}) 7. O-O-O a5 {[%csl Gb4,Rc4][%cal Ga5b4,Gc6e5,Ge5c4] The two main moves in the position are 7...[Re8] and 7...[d6]. However, I like this move better, with the goal to find out where White's queen will eventually land. Once it is clear, sometimes we can play without ...[Re8] or ...[d6].} 8. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4,Yg2g4,Yg4g5] This was played in both games which reached this position, and it is very logical, White is supporting the [e4]-pawn and preparing to push [g4]-[g5].} Ne5 $1 {Decision time for White, they can keep the queen in the centre, potentially exposed to further tempo moves, or retreat to the more passive [e2]-square.} 9. Qd4 d6 {In this case, playing with ...[Re8] wouldn't make much sense, since the e-pawn is protected and the queen is not on [e2], so you can see why it is possible to win some time with 7...[a5].} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8,Gc3d5] The pin looks pretty unpleasant at first sight, especially with [Nd5] coming, but we can deal with it.} h6 $1 {Very useful, once the bishop goes to [h4], we will always have the opportunity to play ...[g5], if White has some big threat.} 11. Bh4 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb4c5] We are creating the threat of ...[Bc5]! by covering our queen on the d-file.} (11... Bc5 {Unfortunately this was not that clear right away.} 12. Qxc5 $1 {A strong sacrifice from White!} dxc5 13. Rxd8 Rxd8 14. Nd5 {∞ Both [f6] and [c7] are hanging, the position is very complicated.}) 12. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gd5f6,Gh4f6]} ({This is the question, obviously.} 12. Kb1 $2 {If White would play a standard prophylactic move, then we can use a nice tactical trick.} Bc5 $1 13. Qd2 Nxe4 {-+ is winning a pawn, because the bishop on [h4] is unprotected.}) 12... g5 {[%csl Gd5,Rf1,Rg1,Rh1] It may look scary to play this move in front of our king, but let's not forget that White's most active piece the [d5]-knight is about to be traded, and all the other pieces of White are watching the game from the back rank.} 13. Nxf6+ (13. Bg3 Nxd5 $1 {Of course! We are trading that strong knight.} 14. exd5 Re8 {And the engine already gives a clear edge for Black, White's pieces are simply not taking part in the game, and our opponent can't really create a dangerous attack neither.} 15. h4 Bc5 16. Qc3 Ng6 {∓ We are threatening to take on [h4], and will win the game there, where White wanted to attack us.}) 13... Qxf6 14. Bg3 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg3e5,Gd4d7] Bxe5 is a threat, so we will have to strengthen the knight on [e5].} Bc5 {A nice intermezzo, it is useful to send the queen back to [c3], because then [b5]-[b4] can come with a tempo.} 15. Qc3 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb7b5,Yb5b4,Yb4c3]} Rfe8 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4]} (15... Rfe8 {The plan is ...b5-b4 and Black is in an excellent shape.} 16. h4 {It is quite important that this move is not working for White.} gxh4 $1 17. Bxh4 Qf4+ 18. Kb1 Bxg1 {-+ And the [h4]-bishop is falling. A pretty unusual way to win a piece. 🙂}) *

