1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qc4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4]} ({A somewhat similar move to} 4. Qd3 {, White is trying to find a better place for the queen than [e3], but [c4] also gives a strange impression, it would be rather the square for the bishop in an ideal world.}) 4... Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Already threatening with ...[d5]!} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Yc3d5] Pretty much the only move for White, in order to stop ...[d5].} Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb4e1,Gd7d5] Pinning the knight, therefore ...[d5] is a threat again!} 6. Bd2 {The fight continues, White breaks the pin, so ...[d5] is stopped again.} O-O ({If you would like to create immediate havoc, I can recommend you the move} 6... b5 $5 {. It leads to a very interesting game, where Black has great compensation for the pawn. However, since we can achieve a good position with much simpler means, I prefer the text move. 🙂}) 7. O-O-O a5 {[%csl Gb4,Rc4][%cal Ga5b4,Gc6e5,Ge5c4] The two main moves in the position are 7...[Re8] and 7...[d6]. However, I like this move better, with the goal to find out where White's queen will eventually land. Once it is clear, sometimes we can play without ...[Re8] or ...[d6].} 8. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4,Yg2g4,Yg4g5] This was played in both games which reached this position, and it is very logical, White is supporting the [e4]-pawn and preparing to push [g4]-[g5].} Ne5 $1 {Decision time for White, they can keep the queen in the centre, potentially exposed to further tempo moves, or retreat to the more passive [e2]-square.} 9. Qe2 Re8 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ye8e2,Gd7d5] Once the queen is on [e2], this move comes with a great power, and we can be pretty ambitious by trying to play ...[d5] at once without losing time with ...[d6]} 10. Qf2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ye8e1] Going away from the e-file is very logical, and takes away the power of ...[d5] for now.} (10. f4 {Logical move, we are not controlling the centre with pawns, so White is trying to push back our pieces. Fortunately, along the way, they will weaken their centre way too much.} Ng6 11. e5 d6 {And White can't keep their centre together.} 12. Nf3 dxe5 13. fxe5 Bg4 {∓ The [e5]-pawn is going to fall very soon.}) 10... c6 {[%cal Gd7d5] We insist on playing with ...[d5]! And we also have to be very fast, because White is ready to start a kingside offensive with [g4]-[g5].} 11. g4 d5 $1 {Against the flank attack the best antidote is to counter in the centre!} 12. g5 d4 $1 {This intermediate move is the key of our concept, and we are doing very well according to my analyses.} 13. Bf4 Nh5 {Forcing White to give up that very important dark-squared bishop.} 14. Bxe5 (14. Rxd4 Qe7 $1 {∓ White's position is extremely loose, and ...[Bc5] is a very serious threat.}) 14... Rxe5 {Now the [g5]-pawn is hanging with a check, White has two options to protect it.} 15. h4 ({This is the worst one, because even though it is a tempo, it weakens the e-pawn.} 15. f4 $6 Re8 16. Nge2 Qe7 {And no matter how White takes the pawn on [d4], our opponent is clearly worse.} 17. Rxd4 {( • 17.Nxd4 Bxc3 18.bxc3 Qa3+ 19.Kb1 Rxe4 ∓ The material is equal, but White's king and structure is much weaker. ) ( • 17.Qxd4? Bg4! ∓ (Some of White's pawns or all of them are going to fall very soon.))} Bc5 {∓ Winning the exchange.}) 15... Re8 $1 {Black had many moves of equal value according to the engine, but this looks pretty good to me, the rook was strange on [e5], and now it is back to control the back rank.} 16. Nge2 b5 17. Nxd4 Qb6 {White is up a pawn, but the dark squares are pretty weak in their camp. But the main thing in the position is that we have opposite-side castling, so king safety is the most important, and while White's attack is pretty much stopped by the knight on [h5], Black is just about to start its offensive by pushing the 'a' and b-pawns.} *

