8] or ...[d6].} 8. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4,Yg2g4,Yg4g5] This was played in both games which reached this position, and it is very logical, White is supporting the [e4]-pawn and preparing to push [g4]-[g5].} Ne5 $1 {Decision time for White, they can keep the queen in the centre, potentially exposed to further tempo moves, or retreat to the more passive [e2]-square.} 9. Qe2 Re8 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ye8e2,Gd7d5] Once the queen is on [e2], this move comes with a great power, and we can be pretty ambitious by trying to play ...[d5] at once without losing time with ...[d6]} 10. Qf2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ye8e1] Going away from the e-file is very logical, and takes away the power of ...[d5] for now.} (10. f4 {Logical move, we are not controlling the centre with pawns, so White is trying to push back our pieces. Fortunately, along the way, they will weaken their centre way too much.} Ng6 11. e5 d6 {And White can't keep their centre together.} 12. Nf3 dxe5 13. fxe5 Bg4 {∓ The [e5]-pawn is going to fall very soon.}) 10... c6 {[%cal Gd7d5] We insist on playing with ...[d5]! And we also have to be very fast, because White is ready to start a kingside offensive with [g4]-[g5].} 11. g4 d5 $1 {Against the flank attack the best antidote is to counter in the centre!} 12. g5 d4 $1 {This intermediate move is the key of our concept, and we are doing very well according to my analyses.} 13. Nce2 (13. gxf6 {This is not really critical.} dxc3 14. Bxc3 Qxf6 {∓ We have the better structure and the better development, White didn't achieve anything.}) 13... d3 $1 ({Again a counterattack! It has to be said, that according to the engine,} 13... Nxf3 $1 {is even stronger, but the complications are hair-raising.}) 14. gxf6 dxe2 15. Bxe2 Qxf6 $15 {[%csl Re4,Rf3][%cal Ge5g6,Gg6f4,Ya5a4,Ya4a3] We can soon start an attack on the queenside, but blockading White's hanging pawns with ...[Ng6] also looks very tempting.} *

