1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. e5 $2 {It is important to know how to react against this aggressive move, but since White is neglecting development, we are in an excellent shape.} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3,Re5][%cal Yg4e3,Yg4e5] Obviously White saw this move coming, their main idea lies in the fact, that if Black captures the pawn on [e5], then the knight can be pinned.} 6. Qe2 (6. Qe2 {This is the less common move, but maybe the more important to know. Now, White would be right in the case of} Ngxe5 $2 7. f4 $1 {pinning the knight, and Black doesn't have enough compensation in that case.}) 6... d6 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc8g4,Ye5d6,Ye2e8] Looks surprising at the first sight to allow White to take a pawn with a check, but not only we didn't have any other good move, it is just a pawn sacrifice, and we will gain a huge lead in the development.} 7. f3 {[%cal Rh4e1] This move is quite weakening and also takes away the [f3]-square from the knight.} Nh6 (7... Ngxe5 {was already more than enough compensation for the piece according to the engine, but it looks somewhat unnecessary to enter those lines now.}) 8. Bxh6 {Looks tempting, but White can't spoil Black's structure.} Qh4+ {The queen could be very unpleasant on [h6].} 9. g3 Qxh6 10. exd6+ Be6 {We are again much ahead in the development, so pretty much the only move or idea for White to stay in the game is to give back the material and go for the endgame.} 11. d7+ Kxd7 12. Qd2+ {White manages to trade queens, but it is obviously not enough for equality.} Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Re8 $17 {[%csl Ye1,Ge6,Gf8][%cal Ye6a2,Gf8c5,Gd7c8] Black keeps a clear advantage with the pair of bishops, and there are also many weak squares in White's camp.} *

