1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. e5 $2 {It is important to know how to react against this aggressive move, but since White is neglecting development, we are in an excellent shape.} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3,Re5][%cal Yg4e3,Yg4e5] Obviously White saw this move coming, their main idea lies in the fact, that if Black captures the pawn on [e5], then the knight can be pinned.} 6. Qe2 (6. Qe2 {This is the less common move, but maybe the more important to know. Now, White would be right in the case of} Ngxe5 $2 7. f4 $1 {pinning the knight, and Black doesn't have enough compensation in that case.}) 6... d6 $1 {[%csl Re8,Gg4][%cal Gc8g4,Ye5d6,Ye2e8] Looks surprising at the first sight to allow White to take a pawn with a check, but not only we didn't have any other good move, it is just a pawn sacrifice, and we will gain a huge lead in the development.} 7. h3 (7. exd6+ Be6 {∞ ( White is already in a pretty serious trouble here, and the engine recommends moves like 8.Nf3 to give back the pawn, but somehow try to finish the development. In that case, we can simply reply with 8...Qxd6 followed by ...[O-O-O] having a nice advantage anyway. )} 8. dxc7 $4 Qxc7 {-+ We will castle long, and then we can attack on [c2] with ...[Nb4] or on [f2], by playing ...[Bc5], White is lost here according to the engine.}) 7... Ngxe5 $1 {As we will see, it is not even a real sacrifice, White is so undeveloped, that we can regain material very-very soon.} 8. f4 {[%cal Rh4e1,Gd8h4] This weakens the [e1]-[h4] diagonal, and indeed all three games which reached this position continued with ...[Qh4]+, but we have even better than that.} Nd4 {[%cal Rd4e2,Rd4c2]} 9. Qe4 {The only move to keep the pin and the [c2]-pawn protected.} c5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4,Rd4c2] By protecting the knight on [d4], we keep the pressure on the [c2]-pawn.} 10. fxe5 {White is taking the piece and even have a way to deal with the tempting ...[Bf5]!} d5 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Re4][%cal Ye4c2] White's queen can't protect the [c2]-square after this move, so we are winning a lot of material.} (10... Bf5 $4 {Would be a losing mistake.} 11. Bb5+ $1 {This intermediate moves turns the tables.} Ke7 12. Qxb7+ {+-}) 11. Qf4 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 $19 {[%csl Rd1] Black is up on material and White's king is also much weaker, the game is pretty much decided.} *

