1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. e5 $2 {It is important to know how to react against this aggressive move, but since White is neglecting development, we are in an excellent shape.} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3,Re5][%cal Yg4e3,Yg4e5] Obviously White saw this move coming, their main idea lies in the fact, that if Black captures the pawn on [e5], then the knight can be pinned.} 6. Qe4 Ngxe5 $1 ({This is the correct move, even though} 6... d5 {is much more popular. We will get excellent compensation for the piece. 6...d5 7.exd6+ Be6 8.Ba6! Thanks to this nice move, the variation is far from clear.}) 7. f4 {White is winning the piece, but Black will get at least 2 pawns and a huge lead in the development for it.} d5 {[%cal Rd5e4] The first nice tempo.} 8. Qe3 {This is also possible, but it doesn't look like that provoking ...[d4] helps White's chances.} d4 9. Qe2 ({This is a must now.} 9. Qe4 $2 {After this move, White can't even win the piece on [e5].} Qh4+ 10. g3 Qg4 11. Bh3 Qg6 12. Qe2 Bxh3 13. Nxh3 Qg4 {-+ Black saves the pieces and keeps the extra pawn.}) 9... Bb4+ {[%cal Ge8g8] This check is a novelty, but not a shocking one. 🙂 White can't really block the check in a good way, so it means that their king will stay in the centre.} 10. Kd1 (10. c3 $2 {Fails to} Bg4 $1 11. Qd2 Qe7 12. fxe5 dxc3 13. Nxc3 Rd8 {-+ And White is getting mated or losing a lot of material.}) 10... O-O 11. fxe5 Re8 {And Black has huge play for the piece. According to the computer it is already winning..} 12. Bf4 d3 $1 {Making White's king more open.} 13. Qxd3 (13. cxd3 {With ...[Bg4] and ...[Nxe5] is coming Black is much better.} Qd4 {∓}) 13... Qf6 $19 {Quite a pretty move. 🙂 Of course, White can't take it because of the mate on [e1].} *

