1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Yf8b4] A quite refined way of playing, White obviously wants to play with [Nc3], but with this move order they prevent Black to develop the bishop to its most ideal square, [b4], or at least make it less tempting, since there will be no pin now.} Be7 {[%cal Gd7d5] This looks like a pretty good solution, we want to play ...[d5] now, which is quite tough to prevent.} 6. c4 $6 {Very ambitious, but also very risky. If White can finish the development they could hope for a better position with the space advantage in the centre, but Black will not allow it.} O-O 7. Nc3 Nb4 $5 {Black has to act quickly, this move fits that concept.} 8. O-O-O ({Instead} 8. Rc1 {is clearly worse.} Ng4 $1 {Black continues with the aggressive play!} 9. Qf3 f5 10. exf5 Ne5 11. Qe4 Bc5 {↑ With ...[d6] or ...[Re8] coming next, White has an unpleasant defensive task here.}) 8... c6 {[%cal Yd7d5] With the idea of playing ...[d5] next, and open the position for White's king.} 9. e5 (9. a3 a5 $1 {The inclusion of these moves doesn't change much in the position, White pretty much never can take the knight on [b4], because it opens the a-file and Black will have good chances to deliver checkmate there.}) 9... Ng4 {Just forward!} 10. Qg3 d5 $13 {[%csl Rc1]} (10... d5 {And Black has an excellent position with great attacking chances. For instance, if} 11. Nf3 Bc5 12. a3 a5 {Our typical reaction, we refuse going backwards!} 13. Bg5 Bxf2 14. Bxd8 Bxg3 15. Bg5 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. axb4 axb4 {Quite an instructive position, White is up a piece after a semi-forcing line, but our opponent is completely lost here, because Black's activity is very dangerous without the queens as well.}) *

