1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Yf8b4] A quite refined way of playing, White obviously wants to play with [Nc3], but with this move order they prevent Black to develop the bishop to its most ideal square, [b4], or at least make it less tempting, since there will be no pin now.} Be7 {[%cal Gd7d5] This looks like a pretty good solution, we want to play ...[d5] now, which is quite tough to prevent.} 6. Nc3 d5 $1 {Black completely solves the opening problems with this move.} 7. exd5 ({Pretty much the only move.} 7. e5 $4 {This is simply losing material for White.} d4 $1 8. Qg5 dxc3 {A huge tempo.} 9. Bxc3 Qd5 10. Rd1 Qe6 {-+ And Black is completely winning with the extra piece.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Qg3 {[%cal Rg3g7] This is played pretty frequently, but White already should think about equality, and can't afford moving their queen for the third time.} Ncb4 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rb4c2] Attacking on [c2] is a much stronger threat than [Qxg7]. White has a lot of ways here to protect the pawn on [c2], but none of those is enough for equality.} 9. Nxd5 ({•} 9. Qxg7 $4 {is just a blunder.} Bf6 $1 {-+ We protect the rook with a tempo, and will collect the [a1]-rook in the next couple of moves.}) ({•} 9. Bd3 {Not a challenging move at all, we can achieve an edge just by securing the advantage of the bishop pair.} O-O 10. Nge2 Nxd3+ 11. Qxd3 Nb4 $1 {Still problems with the [c2]-pawn!} 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. O-O-O Bf5 {-+ Black is winning a pawn and has a huge advantage.}) 9... Qxd5 10. Bxb4 (10. Qxg7 $2 {Looks like a better attempt than the previous one, because we don't have ...[Bf6] with a tempo, but it's still losing. 🙂} Nxc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1 12. Qxh8+ Bf8 {-+ ...[Be6] and long castle is coming, the difference between the king safety is decisive.}) 10... Qe4+ $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge4b4] Very precise, on ...[Bxb4]+ White can play [c3] with a tempo, but once the queen will take on [b4], that move is not available for White, because of the hanging pawn on [b2].} 11. Ne2 Qxb4+ 12. Qc3 Qb6 $17 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Re7b4,Yb6f2,Ge7f6] Generally, when there are no central pawns on the board, the bishop pair is dominating even more, since there is no way to close the position. It is a nice bonus that we have some additional threats in this position.} *

