1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Yf8b4] A quite refined way of playing, White obviously wants to play with [Nc3], but with this move order they prevent Black to develop the bishop to its most ideal square, [b4], or at least make it less tempting, since there will be no pin now.} Be7 {[%cal Gd7d5] This looks like a pretty good solution, we want to play ...[d5] now, which is quite tough to prevent.} 6. Nc3 d5 $1 {Black completely solves the opening problems with this move.} 7. exd5 ({Pretty much the only move.} 7. e5 $4 {This is simply losing material for White.} d4 $1 8. Qg5 dxc3 {A huge tempo.} 9. Bxc3 Qd5 10. Rd1 Qe6 {-+ And Black is completely winning with the extra piece.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5 {The best move from White, the goal is to achieve equality and not advantage.} Qxd5 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ye1c1] Now [O-O-O] would be very nice for White, but unfortunately the [a2]-pawn is hanging, so still precision is required from our opponent.} 9. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ge2c3,Gc3a2,Rc3d5] The knight is coming to [c3], to stabilise White's queenside.} (9. Nf3 $6 {This move could trick us, that it is a developing move, but in reality it doesn't do anything, not helping with [O-O-O] and also not challenging the queen on [d5].} Bf5 {∓ Black finished the development with a tempo, and White has huge problems with protecting the pawn on [c2] and completing the development.}) 9... Bf5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rf5c2] We are just continuing the development, equalising so easily with Black is not something to complain about.} 10. Nc3 (10. Nf4 {This should be also good enough for equality, with the idea of preparing [Bd3].} Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. Bd3 Rhe8 {I would take Black here, but of course White should be able to maintain equality.}) 10... Qd4 {Pretty much every queen move is decent, I like this one, because White can't really trade, since that invites ...[Nxd4] and there are again problems with the [c2]-pawn.} 11. O-O-O O-O-O $10 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc6b4,Yb4c2,Yf5c2] The position is equal, if White is not careful we can have ...[Nb4] ideas in the future and gain the upper hand.} *

