1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. f3 $6 {[%csl Re3,Ge4][%cal Gf3e4] This move is asking for ...[d5] to be played!} d5 $1 {Challenge accepted!} 9. Qf2 (9. Qg5 $6 {The queen is not really finding a good square.} h6 $1 10. Qh4 {(10.Qg3 Bd6! By breaking the X-ray on the d-file, now we can safely collect the [e4]-pawn. 11.Qf2 dxe4 12.fxe4 Nxe4 13.Nxe4 Rxe4 14.Bd3 Re8 ∓ A clear extra pawn and big advantage for Black. )} d4 {Gaining space in the centre and preparing to launch on attack on the queenside.} 11. Nce2 a5 {→ All White's pieces are stuck on the kingside, so our attack should be pretty dangerous in the absence of defenders.}) 9... dxe4 (9... d4 {is also interesting, but taking on [e4] is the real test of White's play.}) 10. Bg5 {[%cal Rd1d8]} ({This is the best way to use the discovered attack on our queen.} 10. Nxe4 {Now we have a very easy position.} Nxe4 11. fxe4 Bg4 12. Nf3 Qf6 {⩱ We created an isolated weak pawn on the e-file, and White doesn't have any compensation for it.}) 10... Bd7 $1 {Not the most obvious move, but a very important one! Many people went wrong at this moment.} ({•} 10... Qe7 $2 {Happened in a lot of games, and it is not clear what the Black players missed here, since the position is pretty bad by force.} 11. Nd5 $1 Qe5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. fxe4 {+- Our position is very weak.}) ({•} 10... Bd6 {This is a decent move, but White is fine after} 11. Qh4 $1 {∞}) 11. Nd5 {[%cal Rg5f6,Rd5f6] White has pretty serious threats on [f6], so this is one of the positions, where it is pretty useful to know the theory. 🙂} e3 $1 {A very strong intermediate move!} 12. Qh4 Bd2+ $1 {[%csl Rd1] And one more! Closing out the rook from the game.} 13. Kb1 Bf5 $1 {[%cal Yf1d3,Gf5c2] Preventing [Bd3] and also attacking on [c2] + helping with the defensive in the form of protecting [h7], and also if needed we can play ...[Bg6].} ({Just as an interesting note, we could have also played} 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd8 Raxd8 {and our position is so dominating that the engine gives the edge for Black, despite being down a queen.}) 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxf6 Qd6 $19 {[%cal Gd6f8] Only move because we have to meet [Qh6] with ...[Qf8]. But this was White's only threat, Black is much better, we can play ...[Nb4] next and White doesn't really have many defensive ideas.} *

