1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Re4] A pretty rare move, but was played quite a few times by GM Nepomniachtchi, so it is good to have some knowledge here. White is sidestepping from the [d5]-threat, but at the same time they are not protecting the pawn on [e4], but rather rely on some compensation with the pair of bishops.} Bxc3 {Definitely the test of White's setup.} 9. Bxc3 Rxe4 $1 ({The more ambitious move.} 9... Nxe4 {is also possible, but after} 10. Bc4 $1 Re7 11. Bxf7+ {White is taking back the pawn, the position however remains completely fine for Black.}) 10. Qg3 {[%csl Gc3,Rg7][%cal Gc3g7,Gg3g7] This is White's idea, to have a focal point on [g7] for the attack, and it is obvious that the bishop on [c3] is very strong. The question is whether it is enough for a full pawn.} d5 {[%cal Ye4e6,Ye6d6,Gd5d4]} ({The choice for Black was between} 10... d6 {and the text move. This looks better because it threatens with ...[d4] and closing the long diagonal, and if White is preventing that and kicking back the rook, then it can go to the nice [d6]-square, which would be of course not available if we put a pawn there.}) 11. f3 {In all of his 4 games in this line, Nepomniachtchi opted for this move. White simply can't allow Black to push [d4].} Re6 {[%cal Ge6d6] The rook is going to [d6].} 12. Ne2 Rd6 {[%cal Gd5d4] The threat of [d4] is renewed!} 13. Nd4 ({Probably the best try, but White doesn't have enough for the pawn.} 13. Qf4 d4 $1 14. Nxd4 Nd5 {Very nice play from Black, taking away all the activity from White.} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 {∓ This was played in Nepomniachtchi-Anand, St.Louis 2017, where Anand converted his advantage to a full point.}) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bf5 15. h4 {White is desperately looking for some play, but it is not there.} Qd7 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2][%cal Gd7a4,Ga8e8] With the cheeky threat of ...[Qa4].} 16. Qf2 h5 $17 {Stops all the play on the kingside, Black is clearly better with the extra pawn.} *

