1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Bc4 {The second most popular move in the position, White stops ...[d5] and we also can't take on [e4] for free.} d6 ({The most ambitious move for Black. Instead,} 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nxe4 {is also possible, where after} 10. Qf4 Re7 11. Bxf7+ Rxf7 12. Qxe4 {we can get an equal but complicated position.}) 9. Nf3 {This move is protecting on [e4] by tactical means, and looks like a better move than 9. [f3], so will be probably the main line in the future.} Be6 {[%csl Gc4] Continuing the development and trading White's strongest piece, the [c4]-bishop.} (9... Bxc3 $6 10. Bxc3 Nxe4 11. Rhe1 Bf5 {(11...Re7 12.Ne5!)} 12. Qf4 {∞ And White is doing pretty well.}) 10. Bxe6 Rxe6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rb4c3,Yf6e4,Ye6e4] There are no more tactical tricks connected with the [f7]-square, so the [e4]-pawn is in danger again.} 11. Ng5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rg5e6,Gg5e4] Played exclusively in OTB chess, which is not a surprise, it is not only protecting the pawn, but also gains a tempo on the rook.} Re8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gh7h6] ...[h6] is coming, so the pawn on [e4] is still an issue.} 12. f4 {This move is pretty much saying that White is not going to move their knight away from [g5], but have more aggressive intentions.} h6 13. h4 {Everything looks good for White, the [e4]-pawn is protected and the knight can't really be taken now, because the attack on the h-file would be very dangerous.} Qc8 $17 {[%cal Gc8g4,Rd6d5,Rd5d4] The problem with White's position is that we can simply ignore the knight for now, and maybe take it later. 🙂 Our opponent has no progressive ideas here, Black on the other hand can continue with ...[Qg4], but ...[d5]-[d4] also looks pretty dangerous. We also have the [h3]-square under control now, so White has to watch out for ...[hxg5] as well, since it can't be followed up by [Qh3] anymore.} *

