1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Qg3 {The main line, White is sacrifising a pawn, and in return hopes for quick development, connected with some threats against our king.} Nxe4 (8... Rxe4 {is an interesting alternative, but the text move is in an excellent shape according to the theory.}) 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. Bf4 $6 {Besides the main line, this move is also pretty logical, since White wants to gain a tempo by attacking the pawn on [c7].} Qf6 $1 {A very important move! Now, White is not going to take on [c7] with a tempo, which actually means that they can't take there at all.} (10... d6 $6 {This materialistic move would allow White very decent compensation for the pawn.} 11. Bd3 Re8 12. Nf3 {→}) 11. Nh3 (11. Bxc7 $4 d6 $1 {The bishop is trapped on [c7]!} 12. Bxd6 {(12.Ne2 Bf5 -+)} Qh6+ $1 {Because of the weak back rank, Black is picking up the bishop.} 13. Kb1 Bxd6 {-+}) 11... d6 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd3e4,Gh3g5,Gf4g5] It still looks like that White is getting quite a few tempi for organising some counterplay.} Nd4 $1 {This extremely strong move pretty much refutes the 10. [Bf4] line. The rook is untouchable because of the fork on [e2].} 13. Kb1 (13. Bg5 {This doesn't change much.} Qe6 {∓ The pawn is hanging on [a2] and ...[Rg4] is also coming.}) 13... Ne2 14. Qf3 {[%csl Re2,Re4][%cal Gf3e2,Gf3e4] With multiple double attacks ( 14...Rxf4 15.Nxf4 Nxf4 16.Qe4! it looks like that White is doing very well.)} Ba3 $3 {An unpleasant surprise, introduced to the practice by Spanish Super-GM, Vallejo Pons.} 15. Bc1 {White is not getting mated, but Black can simplify to a completely winning endgame.} ({•} 15. c3 {Will probably end with a checkmate for Black pretty quickly.} Nxc3+ $1 16. Kc2 (16. bxc3 Qxc3 {-+ With mate in one or two moves.}) 16... Rb4 {Black is completely winning, let me show you a pretty line.} 17. bxa3 Rb2+ 18. Kxb2 (18. Kc1 Nxa2#) 18... Na4+ $1 19. Kb3 Qb2+ 20. Kxa4 Bd7+ 21. Ka5 Qb6#) ({•} 15. bxa3 {This was played by Nepomniachtchi against Vallejo, and after a forced sequence of moves, Black reached a completely winning position.} Nc3+ 16. Kc1 Nxa2+ {Taking one more pawn for free, since the king can't go to [d2].} 17. Kb1 (17. Kd2 Qc3#) 17... Nc3+ 18. Kc1 Bxh3 {The bishop is hanging on [f4], so White has no choice but to take the rook on [e4].} 19. Bxe4 Bxg2 $1 {Winning back material.} 20. Qxg2 Qxf4+ 21. Kb2 Nxe4 {-+ Nepomniachtchi-Vallejo Pons, Moscow 2007 Black has a knight and 3 pawns for the rook, which is a decisive material advantage, and we haven't even talked about White's king yet.}) 15... Qxf3 16. gxf3 Re7 {Slightly better than ...[Re8], since sometimes the [f7]-pawn may need protection Ng5-[Bc4].} 17. Ng5 Nxc1 {The knight can be exchanged for the [d3] bishop. This is very important because White has no time for [bxa3].} 18. Rxc1 Bc5 {Black's pieces are not hanging anymore, but the extra pawn is still there.} 19. Rce1 {White is looking for some play on the e-file, taking the [h7]-pawn wouldn't help much, since they would lose the [f2]-pawn in return.} (19. Bxh7+ Kf8 {-+ ...[g6] is a threat, so White can't protect on [f2].}) 19... Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Bd7 $19 (20... Bd7 {Using White's weak back rank, Black is stopping all the counterplay on the e-file. For instance,} 21. Re7 Re8 {-+}) *

