1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Qg3 {The main line, White is sacrifising a pawn, and in return hopes for quick development, connected with some threats against our king.} Nxe4 (8... Rxe4 {is an interesting alternative, but the text move is in an excellent shape according to the theory.}) 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. c3 Be7 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gh2h4,Re7h4,Gg1f3] Not only stopping White's [h4]-move, but the bishop itself wants to go to [h4] many times, because the [g3]-square is pretty ideal for the queen, and once it gets attacked, it probably has to go [f3], where originally the knight would like to go.} 11. Bd3 Bh4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge4e8,Rg3f3] Opening the way back for the rook, and forcing the queen to take away the [f3]-square from the knight.} 12. Qf3 Re8 {There is no reason why would White have compensation for the missing pawn.} 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qh6 Ne5 {[%cal Re5g4] The queen will be kicked out from [h6], or the bishop has to retreat into a passive square.} 15. Be2 d6 $19 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gh4f6,Gf6g7,Gc8f5] With a huge advantage for Black.} *

