1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge4][%cal Yb8c6] This is the starting position of the Centre Game. White achieves some superiority in the centre thanks to the [e4]-pawn, but the price for it is that the queen had to be involved early in the game, and it can be easily attacked by Black's minor pieces.} (3. Nf3 {This move has no independent value in our case, since we will just transpose back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit. In case you would like to try to punish White for changing the move order and first playing [d4], then you can look into} Bc5 {or even more into 3...Bb4+ . I did that, but since there was no significant gain, just studying more theory, where the positions can get pretty sharp, it was not appealing to me. 3...Nc6 And we are back to the Scotch Game or Scotch Gambit.}) 3... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc6d4] Of course, this move is very tempting and good.} 4. Qe3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4,Ge3g3] The most common move from White, by far. It leaves the [c4]-square available for the bishop and most often White wants to move their queen to [g3], against Black's ...[Re8] idea in the future.} Nf6 ({The most logical move from Black, the second most popular after this one is} 4... d6 {, but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid of White's [e5]-idea.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1,Yf6e4,Yd7d5] Now this move comes with a pin on the knight, so there is no reason not to play it, it also puts indirect pressure on the [e4]-pawn and helps with a potential ...[d5]-break.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge1c1] Pretty much exclusively played in this position, White breaks the pin and prepares for [O-O-O].} O-O 7. O-O-O {Both sides castled, and to the opposite side! So, the play will be very concrete here, there is no time to waste, we have to attack either in the centre, or maybe on the queenside.} Re8 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ye8e3,Rf6e4,Re8e4,Gd7d5] Extremely logical move, attacking the [e4]-pawn and using the awkward situation of the [e3]-queen.} 8. Qg3 {The main line, White is sacrifising a pawn, and in return hopes for quick development, connected with some threats against our king.} Nxe4 (8... Rxe4 {is an interesting alternative, but the text move is in an excellent shape according to the theory.}) 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. c3 Be7 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gh2h4,Re7h4,Gg1f3] Not only stopping White's [h4]-move, but the bishop itself wants to go to [h4] many times, because the [g3]-square is pretty ideal for the queen, and once it gets attacked, it probably has to go [f3], where originally the knight would like to go.} 11. Nf3 {[%cal Yf3h4,Gf1d3]} ({Preventing Black's ...Bh4 ideas.} 11. f4 {This move weakens the light-squares so much, that an exchange sacrifice on [e4], will not be even a real sacrifice, because of the power of our bishop.} d5 12. Bd3 Bf5 $1 {The bishop will be a beast on [e4].} 13. Nf3 Qd7 {White scored 0-9 in OTB games from this position.} 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Rhe1 Bg6 {With the threat of ...[Qf5].} 16. Qh3 Bf5 17. Qg3 f6 {∓ And very soon ...[Na5]-[Qa4] will be very tough to meet for White.}) 11... Ra4 {[%cal Ra4a2] Was played only once, but looks like a very strong move. The rook moves away from [Bd3] or [Ng5] tempo moves, and also attacks the pawn on [a2] while still controlling the 4th rank.} 12. Bd3 (12. Kb1 $2 {There is no time for this, since after} d5 $1 {-+ Both ...[Bf5] and ...[Rg4] is a threat.}) 12... d5 {[%cal Re7d6,Rd6g3]} ({With the threat of ...Bd6.} 12... Rxa2 13. Ng5 {∞ is surprisingly not so clear, but we don't have to rush with taking the pawn.}) 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 $17 {[%csl Ra2,Ga4][%cal Ga4g4,Ga4a2,Gh7h6] The rook on [a4] is extremely well-placed, and White didn't manage to achieve the counterplay they were looking for. We can develop our own play, but one move which could be useful to make is ...[h6], since it solves the problem of the back rank, and in case of ...[Be6], [Ng5] will not be an issue.} *

