[Result "*"]
[ECO "C24"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160376110309029"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. f4 $2 {This is called the Greco Gambit Greco played it in 1620!, and it is a very, very dubious line for White. It is a very bad version of the King's Gambit, where the annoying ...[Qh4]+ will be supported by the knight on [e4].} Nxe4 {Besides the obvious ...[Qh4]+, Black also has the threat of simply playing ...[d5] and ask White where is the compensation for the missing pawn.} 4. d3 Qh4+ {Not surprisingly, this move is a problem for White again.} 5. g3 Nxg3 6. Nf3 Qh5 {The computer prefers ... [Qh3] a little bit to this move, but it is much more practical to react on the same way to 4. [d3] and 4. [Nc3] if in both cases it gives advantage to us.} 7. Rg1 d5 $1 {Instead of ...[e4], now ...[exf4] will keep our material advantage here, this move is preparing for it.} (7... e4 $4 {This would be a huge mistake now.} 8. dxe4 Nxe4 9. Qe2 {And Black is just losing here.} d5 10. Rg5 $1 {+-}) 8. Bxd5 exf4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh5d5] Gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop on [d5]!} 9. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yb4e1,Gh5d5,Ge8g8] One more tempo, as the bishop on [d5] is hanging again. Also, Black is ready to castle, while White's king is exposed in the centre.} 10. Bxf4 Qxd5 11. Rxg3 {White has won back a pawn, but it is not nearly enough.} O-O $17 {[%csl Re1,Gg8][%cal Gb8c6,Gf8e8] Black is cleary better with the extra pawn and safer king.} *

