1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. f4 $2 {This is called the Greco Gambit Greco played it in 1620!, and it is a very, very dubious line for White. It is a very bad version of the King's Gambit, where the annoying ...[Qh4]+ will be supported by the knight on [e4].} Nxe4 {Besides the obvious ...[Qh4]+, Black also has the threat of simply playing ...[d5] and ask White where is the compensation for the missing pawn.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc3d5,Yd7d5]} ({Maybe somewhat better than} 4. d3 {, but it is really just a bad line for White either way.}) 4... Qh4+ 5. g3 Nxg3 {[%cal Rh4h1] This basic tactical idea works very well for Black.} 6. Nf3 {[%cal Rf3h4]} Qh5 $1 {This move we have to know though, connected with the idea which is coming in the next move. We are already two pawns up at this moment, so if we can safely finish the development, then we are just much better.} (6... Qh3 $6 {Strangely enough, after this move White is even better!} 7. Rg1 {The difference compared to the main line, that now [Rxg3] is a threat which is coming with a tempo on our queen.} Nf5 8. fxe5 {⩲ White is very active, and we are way behind in the development.}) 7. Rg1 e4 $1 8. Rxg3 exf3 9. Rxf3 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf3e3,Gd1h5]} ({We shouldn't blunder the queen to a discovered check, but we want to develop anyway.} 9. d4 Bb4 $1 {And Black has no problems with finishing the development.}) 9... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Re7,Yf3][%cal Ge2e7,Yh5f3] White is trying to keep our king in the centre, but since the rook on [f3] is also hanging, we can continue the development.} O-O $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge7h4,Gb8c6,Gd7d6] White has nothing to show for the missing pawn.} *

