1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. Nf3 $6 {This is a very strange move order, but it happens from time to time.} Nxe4 {[%cal Yd7d5] There is no reason not to take this pawn, since it is even coming with the threat of ...[d5], only if you really like the Italian Game, then I suggest you to play 3...[Nc6] instead. 🙂} 4. Nxe5 {[%cal Rc4f7,Re5f7] Unfortunately for White, the seemingly dangerous threat on [f7] is met with a move which is a tempo for Black.} ({•} 4. Bxf7+ $4 {Just losing, but was tried in many games.} Kxf7 5. Nxe5+ Kg8 $1 {And White is not taking back the knight, and neither giving checkmate, so they are just down a piece.} 6. Qf3 Nf6 {-+}) ({•} 4. d4 $2 d5 5. Bb3 exd4 6. Qxd4 Be6 7. O-O Nc6 {∓}) ({•} 4. d3 $6 {If the bishop would be on [f1] now, instead of [c4], then it is a reversed Petrov's game. 🙂 And funnily enough, it would be better for White to have the bishop there, because now Black will have the possibility to gain the pair of bishops and secure a slight edge.} Nc5 $1 5. Nxe5 d5 6. Bb3 Nxb3 7. axb3 Bd6 {⩱ Black is comfortably better with the pair of bishops.}) ({•} 4. Nc3 {Practically speaking, this is definitely the best try for White. It is called the Boden-Kieseritzky Gambit, but we don't really have to take on [c3] right away, which is good, but a little bit messy. Instead, we can play} Nc6 {and just transpose back to a position we can get via the classical Italian Game move order, or via the Scotch Four Knights Game, which is actually analysed in our course here.}) 4... d5 $1 5. Be2 {[%cal Yd8g5,Ye5g4] This modest move is White's best probably, our opponent is at least prepared for the ... [Qg5] idea.} ({•} 5. Bb3 $2 {The most common move in the position is just a tactical error.} Qg5 $1 {∓ With a double attack on [e5] and [g2], Black is winning material.}) ({•} 5. Qf3 {Let's not blunder checkmate and then we are fine!} Be6 6. d4 f6 $1 {Basically forcing an endgame, where we will play with the pair of bishops.} 7. Nd3 dxc4 8. Qxe4 Qd5 9. Qxd5 Bxd5 10. Nf4 Bf7 {⩱ ...[Nc6] and [O-O-O] are our next moves, it is at least a slight edge for Black because of the bishops, but the computer is even more optimistic.}) 5... Bd6 {[%cal Rd6e5]} ({On} 5... Qg5 {, White has} 6. Ng4 {which is not so clear, so I suggest just to continue the development and play like we are with the White pieces in a symmetrical pawn structure.}) 6. d4 Nd7 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Ge4][%cal Ge8g8,Gd8h4,Gf7f5] This is basically the Petrov's Defence, where we are playing as White, and 'Black' lost a tempo by playing [Bc4]-[Be2].} *

