1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4,Re5][%cal Ge2e4,Ye4d5,Ge2e5] Protecting the pawn on [e4] and also discouraging ...[d5], since the queen also puts an X-ray on the [e5]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%csl Re2][%cal Rc6d4,Yd4e2] The most obvious move, and it comes with the threat of ...[Nd4], which is not something White would like to allow and move the queen again. The knight also protects the [e5]-pawn, making ...[d5] a possibility.} 4. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4,Yc6d4] Addresses the threat of ... [Nd4], but allows our favorite break, ...[d5]!} (4. Nf3 {This move is the most common one here, and after our move it will just transpose to another chapter.} Bc5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) 4... d5 $1 {Black is already taking over here.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5] We have a nice development, and space advantage thanks to the [e5]-pawn, so if White is not doing something quickly, they are just worse.} 6. d4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd4e5] Challenging the [e5]-pawn is White only idea in this position.} Be6 $1 {A very important new move, and probably the reason why 4...[d5] is not popular at all, since finding this move OTB with the following idea is pretty difficult, to say the least.} 7. dxe5 Ndb4 $3 {Brilliant move! All the tactics are working for Black, and now we can see the point of ...[Be6], it was a crucial point for this move to work, that we have tactical ideas against the [c4]-bishop.} 8. cxb4 Nd4 {[%csl Gc2,Gc4][%cal Ge2c2,Ge2c4,Rd4e2] The queen has to protect both the [c2]-square and the [c4]-bishop.} 9. Qd3 (9. Bb5+ {doesn't help much.} c6 $1) 9... Bf5 {[%cal Rf5d3,Yd4c2] ...[Nc2] check is coming!} 10. Qd2 Nc2+ 11. Ke2 Qh4 $36 {[%csl Re2][%cal Rc2a1,Rh4c4,Ga8d8] A lot of things are hanging for White, Black is just much better here.} *

