1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4,Re5][%cal Ge2e4,Ye4d5,Ge2e5] Protecting the pawn on [e4] and also discouraging ...[d5], since the queen also puts an X-ray on the [e5]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%csl Re2][%cal Rc6d4,Yd4e2] The most obvious move, and it comes with the threat of ...[Nd4], which is not something White would like to allow and move the queen again. The knight also protects the [e5]-pawn, making ...[d5] a possibility.} 4. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4,Yc6d4] Addresses the threat of ... [Nd4], but allows our favorite break, ...[d5]!} (4. Nf3 {This move is the most common one here, and after our move it will just transpose to another chapter.} Bc5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) 4... d5 $1 {Black is already taking over here.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5] We have a nice development, and space advantage thanks to the [e5]-pawn, so if White is not doing something quickly, they are just worse.} 6. d4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd4e5] Challenging the [e5]-pawn is White only idea in this position.} Be6 $1 {A very important new move, and probably the reason why 4...[d5] is not popular at all, since finding this move OTB with the following idea is pretty difficult, to say the least.} 7. dxe5 Ndb4 $3 {Brilliant move! All the tactics are working for Black, and now we can see the point of ...[Be6], it was a crucial point for this move to work, that we have tactical ideas against the [c4]-bishop.} 8. Bxe6 (8. Na3 {The best move according to SF, but practically speaking it is pretty easy to handle.} Bxc4 9. Nxc4 Nd3+ 10. Kf1 Qd5 {With very obvious moves, Black is getting great play for the pawn.} 11. Ne3 Qe4 12. Nc2 Qc4 13. Ne3 Qa6 14. Nf3 O-O-O {∞ With ...[Bc5] and ...[Rhe8] coming next, Black is at least fine, but in a practical game it just looks awful for White.}) 8... Nd3+ $1 {[%csl Re1] And White has big problems with their king.} 9. Kd1 ({•} 9. Kd2 $4 {Blunders the queen.} Nf4+ {+ -+}) ({•} 9. Kf1 $4 Nxc1 10. Qc2 fxe6 11. Qxc1 Qd3+ 12. Ne2 O-O-O {Even though White is up a pawn, they can hardly move here.} 13. Na3 Bxa3 14. bxa3 Rhf8 {-+ We can take back the pawn on [e5] anytime, White is completely lost here with such weak king and passive pieces.}) 9... fxe6 {[%cal Rd3f2,Rd3f4,Rd3b2] A lot of discovered checks are in the air, so White has to go out from the d-file or cover the king somehow.} 10. Nd2 (10. Kc2 $4 {Allows Black to win in a spectacular fashion!} Ndb4+ $1 11. Kb3 {(11.cxb4 Nd4 + -+ Wins the queen and the game. )} Qd5+ 12. Ka4 a6 13. cxb4 b5+ 14. Ka3 Bxb4#) 10... Qd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rd5g2,Ge8c8] For only one pawn, Black achieves a very dominating position.} 11. Ngf3 O-O-O {Putting the king into safety, and bringing the rook into the game!} 12. Kc2 g5 {[%cal Rg5g4,Gf8g7,Gf8c5]} (12... g5 {Not giving much time for White to relax. 🙂 Black has fantastic compensation for the pawn, which basically we can take back anytime we want. A possible line goes like,} 13. Nb3 Be7 14. Bxg5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Rhg8 {All of our pieces are very active.} 16. Ne4 Nf4 {⩱ We will take back the pawns with a clearly better position.}) *

