1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. f4 $6 {[%csl Gc4,Gf1] In the spirit of the Vienna Game, but with the bishop out there on [c4].} exf4 $1 {Don't change a winning team! As usual, immediately ...[d5] or first ...[exf4] and then ...[d5] is our reaction to [f4].} 5. Nc3 {White is preventing ...[d5], so what we have to do now, is to prepare to play it anyway!} Bb4 {By pinning the knight, we make ...[d5] available again.} 6. Bxf4 O-O {...[d5] was already working, but since White can't prevent it, I prefer castling first, and then open the position.} 7. Nge2 (7. Nf3 $2 {is even worse.} d5 $1 8. exd5 Re8+ $1 {∓ And White's king is going to be in a lot of trouble.}) 7... d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bxd5 {It is not a move White wants to make, but there is simply nothing better.} (9. Bd2 $2 {Trying to keep the bishops on the board is too slow.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bc5 {And White can't castle anymore.} 11. d4 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qe4 13. Rf1 Bh3 {-+ Black is winning material.}) 9... Qxd5 {The [g2]-pawn is hanging, so White can't even try to get greedy and take on [c7].} 10. O-O Qd7 $15 {[%csl Gb7,Rg2][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gb7g2] With the idea of developing the bishop via ... [b6]-[Bb7] and putting pressure on the long diagonal.} *

