1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. f4 $6 {[%csl Gc4,Gf1] In the spirit of the Vienna Game, but with the bishop out there on [c4].} exf4 $1 {Don't change a winning team! As usual, immediately ...[d5] or first ...[exf4] and then ...[d5] is our reaction to [f4].} 5. Bxf4 (5. Nf3 $6 {White is saying that there is time to develop before taking back on [f4], but unfortunately it is not really true.} d5 {I find it the easiest, the computer is saying that 5...[g5]! is even stronger, but why to weaken ourselves, if this move is also good enough for an advantage?} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 8. Bxd5 {White has to give up the pair of bishops, otherwise they remain down a pawn.} Qxd5 9. Bxf4 O-O-O {⩱ Black is clearly better with the pair of bishops, and our attack is also going to be the more dangerous one, ...[f6], followed by ...[g5]-[h5] is very strong.}) 5... d5 $1 {[%cal Yf8b4,Yc8g4] We really need this move after ...[exf4], to fully activate our position.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f4] White is already in trouble here, the machine can't find anything which is even close to equality.} 7. Qe2+ {[%csl Rc7,Gg2][%cal Ge2g2,Yc4d5,Yf4c7] White is protecting the [g2]-pawn, so maybe in a good day they can grab a pawn on [c7].} Be6 8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Bxc7 {Not a good move, but White didn't really have anything much better available.} (9. Nc3 Qa5 10. Nf3 {Allows a nice tactical trick for Black! (10.O-O-O O-O-O -+ It is unclear how can White protect the pawn on [a2], and even if they could, ...[Bb4] is very strong for Black. )} Ba3 $1 11. Bxc7 {Pretty much forced, but doesn't help White.} Qxc7 12. bxa3 Nd4 $1 {More tactics are coming!} 13. Qd2 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Rc8 {∓ White is struggling with the safety of their king, and the pawn structure is also far from ideal.}) 9... Rc8 {[%cal Rc8c2] A new piece is coming with a tempo.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5] Finally some development from White, and also with a tempo!} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4e1] It has been quickly neutralised.} 11. Bg3 Nd4 {[%cal Rd4c2,Rd5g2,Rb4c3,Rc8c3] White has to protect a lot of squares, and it all should be done by the queen.} 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Nxd5 ({Trying to simplify, but it doesn't work. The same goes for every other move.} 13. Nge2 Nxe2 14. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bxd5 16. Kxe2 Rxc2+ {+ -+ And Black is taking a lot of pawns, while White's king is still weak.}) 13... Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Rxc2+ 15. Ke3 Bxd5 {[%cal Rd5g2]} 16. Kxd4 Bxg2 $19 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rg1e2,Rg1f3,Rg1h3] Since the knight would hang everywhere if it moves, White can't even get 2 pieces for the rook.} *

