1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Yd2b4] White is breaking the pin, so ...[d5] is not working for now.} Bxc3 $1 {Certainly not the only move, but regarding our concept, it is pretty much a must.} (5... O-O 6. Nge2 $1 {The knight is ready to recapture on [c3], and we are not getting to play ...[d5] anytime soon. The position is obviously completely fine for Black, but the goal is to play a different type of game and structure.}) 6. Bxc3 O-O {[%cal Yd7d5]} ({I like this move order better, playing} 6... d5 {immediately would allow White to play} 7. Bb5 $1 {, which is a little bit annoying.}) 7. Ne2 d5 $1 8. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Ge5] We reached the position what we wanted, Black has a space advantage in the centre with the pawn on [e5], but White has the pair of bishops, so the game is about even.} 9. O-O Be6 {[%cal Yd5c3,Ye6c4] Preparing to take on [c3] and then on [c4].} 10. Bd2 Qd6 11. Re1 ({•} 11. Nc3 $6 {Leads to a slightly worse endgame for White.} Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bxc4 13. dxc4 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Rfd8 {⩱ Black has a much easier time to create a passer on the kingside, then White on the queenside.}) ({•} 11. Ng3 f5 $1 {Cutting the [g3]-knight out of the game.}) 11... Rad8 $10 {Black is at least equal, but I like our chances with the more space.} *

