.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Yd2b4] White is breaking the pin, so ...[d5] is not working for now.} Bxc3 $1 {Certainly not the only move, but regarding our concept, it is pretty much a must.} (5... O-O 6. Nge2 $1 {The knight is ready to recapture on [c3], and we are not getting to play ...[d5] anytime soon. The position is obviously completely fine for Black, but the goal is to play a different type of game and structure.}) 6. bxc3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Gc3d4]} ({This move can lead to sharper games then} 6. Bxc3 {.}) 6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd2,Gd5,Ge5] Nice centre vs the bishop pair is the theme of the game here.} 8. Nf3 {The most logical move in the position.} Bg4 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yg4d1]} 9. O-O Qd6 $132 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8c8,Gd6e5]} (9... Qd6 {A new move in this position, we want to castle long and then start playing against White's king. Since there were no games for this position, I'll just show a line which the computer considers best for White, otherwise it is already advantage for Black!} 10. Qe2 O-O-O 11. h3 {(11.Qe4?! f5! 12.Qxd5 Qxd5 13.Bxd5 Rxd5 ⩱ Black is more active and White's structure is worse. )} Bh5 12. Qe4 Bg6 13. Qg4+ f5 14. Qg3 {This unusual queen maneuver keeps the equality for White.} f4 15. Qg4+ Kb8 16. Rfe1 Rhf8 {⇆ Computer is saying zeros, but obviously there is a lot of play left in the position.}) (9... Qd7 $2 {When the knight is not on [f6], and our [g4] bishop can be potentially unprotected, we have to watch out for tactics.} 10. h3 $1 Bh5 {The best move would be 10... [Bxf3], but that is something what we really don't want to play.} 11. Nxe5 $1 Bxd1 12. Nxd7 Bxc2 13. Nc5 {+-}) *

