1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Yd2b4] White is breaking the pin, so ...[d5] is not working for now.} Bxc3 $1 {Certainly not the only move, but regarding our concept, it is pretty much a must.} (5... O-O 6. Nge2 $1 {The knight is ready to recapture on [c3], and we are not getting to play ...[d5] anytime soon. The position is obviously completely fine for Black, but the goal is to play a different type of game and structure.}) 6. bxc3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Gc3d4]} ({This move can lead to sharper games then} 6. Bxc3 {.}) 6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd2,Gd5,Ge5] Nice centre vs the bishop pair is the theme of the game here.} 8. Qf3 {[%cal Rc4d5,Rf3d5] Tempting move, but not a particularly good one. It is better to develop the knight first, and then castle.} (8. Ne2 {A normal developing move, but we can also employ our setup without any problems.} O-O 9. O-O Be6 10. Ng3 {The knight is going towards [e4]. (10.Rb1 Simply can be met by 10...b6=)} Qd7 11. Ne4 b6 {Preventing [Nc5], Black has a normal position, our next move is most likely going to be ...[Nde7] with the goal of trading the light-squared bishops.} 12. Ng5 {This is not a problem at all, we can even answer with a tempo move.} Bg4) 8... Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5] Easily solving the problems.} 9. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3g7,Gg1f3] If we should castle short, then White's play is pretty reasonable, since they can follow up the play with [Nf3]. But we have much better!} (9. Rb1 {White is threatening to take the [b7]-pawn. Or maybe not?} O-O $1 {(9...b6 10.Bb5! wouldn't have been ideal, but the pawn is not hanging! )} 10. Rxb7 $4 Na5 {White's structure is horrible after the trade on [c4].} 11. Rb1 Nxc4 12. dxc4 Nb6 {-+ With ...[Bxc4] coming next, Black has a huge advantage.}) 9... Qd6 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ge8c8,Yf7f5,Yh7h6,Yg7g5] We can castle long and White's queen will be on the way of Black's pawn avalanche.} 10. Qxg7 $2 {Opening the g-file for Black.} O-O-O $17 {[%csl Re1,Rg7][%cal Gh8g8] With ...[Rhg8] or ...[h5]-[Rdg8] to follow, White is in a serious trouble for only one pawn.} *

