1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bg5 {Very common, but not particularly dangerous. The move fights against ...[d5], but the pin can be broken easily.} h6 $1 6. Bh4 $6 {Certainly more ambitious than taking on [f6], but the move will only bring problems for White.} g5 $1 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Ge8g8] We haven't castled short yet, so this way of breaking the pin is completely without any risk.} 7. Bg3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yg3d2,Rd5c3,Rb4c3] The bishop should rather be on [d2] than on [g3].} 9. Nge2 Be6 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 ({•} 11. Nxc3 $2 {Leads to mass exchanges and a horrible endgame for White.} Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxc4 13. dxc4 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Ke7 {∓ This position should be technically winning for Black, White's structure is awful.}) ({•} 11. Bxd5 Qxd5 12. Nxc3 Qd4 {⩱ With long castle and attack on the kingside to follow, Black has an excellent position.}) 11... Qd6 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gd5f4,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] Black is much better. ...[O-O-O] is next, and our king is perfectly safe, while White will have to defend against a dangerous attack after ...[h5]-....[h4]. ...[Nf4] is also interesting for Black, since if White takes it, the g-file opens up.} *

