.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bg5 {Very common, but not particularly dangerous. The move fights against ...[d5], but the pin can be broken easily.} h6 $1 6. Bh4 $6 {Certainly more ambitious than taking on [f6], but the move will only bring problems for White.} g5 $1 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Ge8g8] We haven't castled short yet, so this way of breaking the pin is completely without any risk.} 7. Bg3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yg3d2,Rd5c3,Rb4c3] The bishop should rather be on [d2] than on [g3].} 9. Nge2 Be6 10. Bb5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg3e5,Yb5e8] Trying to create some job for the [g3]-bishop, but we can easily protect the pawn on [e5].} Nf4 {[%csl Gf4] The knight is superb on [f4].} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[%csl Gb4,Rc6,Rc7,Ge6,Gf4] Our structure is somewhat damaged, but the activity of our minor pieces provide more than enough compensation for it.} 12. O-O h5 {Who stands better, should attack!} 13. f3 h4 14. Bf2 Rg8 $15 {[%csl Ge6,Gf4][%cal Gd8e7,Ge8c8] Black is very active, it is extremely hard to do anything with the knight on [f4], since once it is taken, it will open the g-file for the rook, and if it is not taken, it attacks so many squares in White's camp. Our king can remain in the centre, but a plan of ...[Qe7] followed by long castle is also very playable.} *

