1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Bg5 {Very common, but not particularly dangerous. The move fights against ...[d5], but the pin can be broken easily.} h6 $1 6. Bxf6 Bxc3+ $1 {Important intermezzo, we are ruining White's structure a little bit before the knight could arrive to [e2].} 7. bxc3 {[%csl Yc2,Yc3]} Qxf6 8. Ne2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge1g1] This is the correct square for the knight, White's only active idea is [f4] in this position.} d6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge8c8] Obviously we can't really play for ...[d5] anymore, so we are just continuing the development, and staying flexible, keeping both short and long castle available.} 9. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4]} ({White is ready to go for f4 in the next move.} 9. d4 {This is the other move which is frequently played in practice, but it is much less dangerous than playing for [f4] right away.} Qe7 $1 {An X-ray attack on the [e4]-pawn, forcing White to make a decision.} 10. O-O {If White just continues developing, they will remain with a rather bad structure here. (10.Bd3 O-O 11.O-O and before White could try to go for [f4], we play... 11...f5= Black has no problems at all. )} exd4 11. Nxd4 O-O {(11.cxd4 Qxe4 ⩱ And White can't take advantage of the e-file, since we are castling in the next move. )}) 9... Na5 $1 {[%cal Ra5c4] We will have to play ...[g5] at some moment, but this knight jump will give us a much better version.} (9... g5 $6 {This is the most common move, but it allows White to keep the bishop active.} 10. Bb5 $1 Bd7 11. c4 O-O-O 12. Nc3 {⩲ And White has good chances for a queenside attack.}) 10. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} ({•} 10. f4 $2 {This move is nothing without the bishop's pressure on the [f7]-square.} Nxc4 11. dxc4 Bd7 {∓}) ({•} 10. Bb5+ {It is not a pin anymore, so the bishop is just going to be very passive on this diagonal.} c6 11. Ba4 g5 {Stopping [f4].} 12. d4 h5 {⇆ With the plan of playing ...[h4] and then ...[Kf8]-[g7]. It is hard to find constructive ideas for White.}) 10... g5 $13 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Yg5f4,Ye5f4] This is a much improved version of ...[g5], White can't really use the light-squared bishop for anything. It even blocks the b-file for the rook.} (10... g5 {One possible line goes} 11. d4 {Trying to look for play in the centre, but Black is very quick to finish the development.} Bd7 12. dxe5 Qxe5 $1 {With long castle coming very soon, Black is in a good shape. 12...dxe5 would allow 13.Qd5!}) *

