1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Nf3 {[%cal Yf3e5,Ge1g1] The most popular move among Top players, White is preparing to meet ...[d5] by putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn, and our opponent is also aiming for a quick castle.} d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c3,Rb4c3] We are threatening to win a pawn on [c3], but White can ignore it, and instead go for rapid development.} 7. O-O $1 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rc4d5] As we will see, that pawn on [c3] is poisoned for the moment.} (7. Bd2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 Bg4 {transposes here.}) 7... Bxc3 (7... Nxc3 $2 {This is very bad, because White can recapture with a tempo on [c3].} 8. bxc3 Bxc3 9. Ng5 $1 {This is the point of White's play, there are big problems around our king.} Bxa1 {(9...O-O 10.Qh5 +-)} 10. Bxf7+ Ke7 11. Ba3+ Kf6 12. Qf3+ Bf5 {(12...Kxg5 13.Bc1+ Kh4 14.Qg3)} 13. Ne4+ $1 Kxf7 14. Qxf5+ Ke8 15. Qe6+ Ne7 16. Rxa1 {+- And Black is completely lost, as we pretty much can't do anything with our king.}) 8. bxc3 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Yd8d6,Ge8c8]} ({Still keeping the option of castling long!} 8... Nxc3 $2 {This way of taking the pawn is also unplayable.} 9. Qe1 $1 Nd5 10. Ba3 {+- Our king stays in the centre, White has a winning advantage according to the computer.}) 9. Re1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge5c6,Re1e8] The threat is to take on [e5] and then win back the queen with a discovered check via [c6].} ({•} 9. Bd2 Qd6 $1 {Transposes to the 5. [Bd2] [Bxc3] 6. [bxc3] [d5] line.}) (9. d4 {White is trying to open the position while our king is still in the centre.} O-O $1 {(This positional and most likely temporarily pawn sacrifice is solving Black's problems.)} 10. dxe5 Nb6 11. Be2 Re8 {∞ Black's pieces are very active and White has numerous weaknesses, such as the [e5]-pawn, and pretty much all the pawns on the queenside.}) 9... O-O {In general, I like to castle long in this type of pawn structures, since then we can develop an attack quite nicely with moves like ...[f6]-[g5]-[Nf4]. But unfortunately it was not possible in this concrete position.} (9... Qd6 $6 10. Ba3 $1 {A very strong move.} Qxa3 11. Bxd5 {⩲ We have problems with the [e5]-pawn.}) 10. Bd2 {Basically, White slightly tricked us with this move order, since they are pretty much playing the 5. [Bd2] line, where we castle long, but here it was not possible. It is not a big deal though, Black's position is very solid, just we can't be as ambitious as in the lines with ...[O-O-O].} Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8e5,Yh2h3,Yg4h5,Yg2g4,Yh5g6] Supporting the [e5]-pawn is a good way to take away the power of the [h3]-[g4] ideas from White.} 11. h3 Bh5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5,Ge8e5] We can safely retreat with the bishop, since the [e5]-pawn is well protected.} 12. Rb1 {[%csl Rb7,Gg2][%cal Yb1b7,Gg2b7] A nice point of [bxc3] systems, that the rook can use the b-file. Here I'm not too worried though, normally these things are much more unpleasant when there is a bishop on the long diagonal for White.} a6 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Yc4b5] Very precise move, not even allowing White to play [Bb5], after the eventual ...[Nb6] or ...[Rb8].} 13. Qe2 (13. a4 Rb8) (13. Rxb7 $2 Nb6 $1 {⩱ White is going to lose that greedy rook!}) 13... h6 $10 {One more nice improving move, anytime White tries [g4]-[Nh4] in the future, we can simply retreat with the bishop to [h7], and also opening the back rank is not a bad thing.} *

