1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f4] The most common move, White is already protecting the knight on [c3], and leaves the way open for the f-pawn.} d5 {We don't have to change anything in our plans, this move works well.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Bxd5 $6 {Was played in quite a large number of games, it is hard to see why White has to give up this bishop, since the [c3]-square was already protected.} Qxd5 8. O-O Qd7 $1 {With the idea of putting the bishop to the long diagonal.} 9. f4 {White has to challenge the centre, but it just makes the long diagonal, and especially the [g2]-square even weaker.} b6 10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. Ng3 O-O $15 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gc8b7] With ...[Bb7] coming next, Black is clearly better with the strong bishops.} *

