1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f4] The most common move, White is already protecting the knight on [c3], and leaves the way open for the f-pawn.} d5 {We don't have to change anything in our plans, this move works well.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Yf3g5,Yg5e6] Developing and keeping the tension in centre. Our bishop is very comfortable on [e6], since we don't have to worry about the [Ng5] idea.} 8. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4g5,Yg5e6] White wants to attack our bishop in an unusal way, but in the meantime releases the tension over the [d5]-square, so we can easily move the bishop once it is attacked.} O-O ({Instead} 8... Be7 {is the most popular move, and it is good, but we don't have to hurry with it, since [Ng5] would rather help us.}) 9. N2g3 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ge4g5,Ye6f5,Yf5g4,Ye6c8] White really wants to play [Ng5], and it is a serious threat now, since the bishop has only one square available, [c8], which is not fantastic.} (9. Ng5 {Achieves nothing, as we simply go to} Bg4 {and the knight looks silly on [g5].}) 9... Be7 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Ge7g5] The bishop was not doing anything on [b4] anymore, and with this move we don't have to settle for ...[f6], but we can be ambitious and try to play for ...[f5]!} 10. Qh5 f5 $1 {We are giving up the pair of bishops, but gaining a lot of space in the centre.} 11. Ng5 Bxg5 12. Bxg5 Qd7 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5,Gf5,Rg5,Rh5,Rg3][%cal Gd5b4,Ga8e8] White's pieces on the kingside, especially the knight on [g3] is really misplaced.} (12... Qd7 {One possible line is} 13. Bd2 Ndb4 {Trading White's pair of bishops.} 14. Bxe6+ Qxe6 15. Bxb4 Nxb4 16. Qd1 {White has to go back to defensive mode.} c5 {So the knight can go back to behind the pawn, on [c6].}) *

