1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f4] The most common move, White is already protecting the knight on [c3], and leaves the way open for the f-pawn.} d5 {We don't have to change anything in our plans, this move works well.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Yf3g5,Yg5e6] Developing and keeping the tension in centre. Our bishop is very comfortable on [e6], since we don't have to worry about the [Ng5] idea.} 8. Bxd5 {[%cal Gf2f4] Surprising move at the first sight, but it is with a very concrete idea, White can only play for [f4] by taking the knight first.} (8. f4 $2 {This is a move what White has to play, just it is too early at this moment.} Nxc3 $1 9. Nxc3 {(9.bxc3 Bc5+ 10.Kh1 Bxc4 11.dxc4 Qxd1 12.Rxd1 f6 ∓ With a horrific endgame for White. )} Qd4+ $1 10. Kh1 Bxc4 11. dxc4 Qxc4 12. fxe5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 O-O {∓ White has an awful position with 4 weak pawns.}) 8... Bxd5 9. f4 f6 $1 {A very strong move, which only got popular in the last few years. The main idea is to stay flexible, since castling long can be a much better option in many of the positions.} (9... O-O {This is the main line, but now White can get a decent position. For example,} 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. f5 $1 f6 12. Ng3 {∞ This is what White wants! Gain space on the kingside, then put the knight to [e4], and maybe later start attacking Black's king.}) 10. f5 $2 {[%csl Gf5] White gains space on the kingside, but our king is not even there yet!} Bf7 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gf7] We can keep the bishop pair and then go for long castle.} 11. Kh1 Qd7 12. Ne4 O-O-O {[%csl Gc8][%cal Yg7g6] Our king is completely safe on [c8], and the next goal is to undermine White's structure on the kingside by playing ...[g6].} 13. a3 Be7 14. b4 {White is trying to create some play, but it is just very slow.} g6 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Yg6f5]} 15. b5 {We have been following the game Tabatabei-Nihal, 2021 chess.com.} Nd4 $17 (15... Nd4 {An improvement over the aforementioned game, with already a decisive advantage for Black, according to the engine.} 16. fxg6 Bxg6 {...[f5] is coming and White can't take on [f6].} 17. Nxf6 Bxf6 18. Rxf6 Bh5 {-+ Winning the knight on [e2]. 16.Nxd4 Qxd4 17.Qg4 Trying to create something with the [fxg6]-discovered check. 17...Be6! Closing the diagonal. 18.fxe6 Qxa1 -+ Black is just an exchange up.}) *

