1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3]} ({The Bishop's Opening. In modern practice, especially among the elite players, this move order is used in order to avoid the ultra solid and well analysed Petrov's Defense, which happens after} 2. Nf3 Nf6 {. By delaying the development of the [g1]-knight, White will keep the opportunity to push for [f4] and only then develop the knight to [f3].}) 2... Nf6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yg1f3,Rf6e4,Yd7d5] The most logical answer from Black, taking advantage that White didn't attack our central pawn with 2. [Nf3], we have the time ourselves to attack the [e4]-pawn and support the ...[d5]-break, which, similarly to many other variations of this repertoire, will be a main idea for us.} 3. d3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] By far the main and best move for White to protect the [e4]-pawn this way.} (3. d4 exd4 4. Nf3 {White wants to play the dangerous Urusov Gambit, but we will sidestep that with} Nc6 $1 {and transpose to the Scotch Gambit chapter.}) ({In case of} 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 Nc6 {, the game transposes to this line.}) 3... Nc6 ({Black has a pretty wide variety of different setups here,} 3... c6 {is especially popular among the players who want to play the Petrov's Defence, since if after the text move White is playing} 4. Nf3 {then we are in the Italian Game, which is not part of a normal Petrov repertoire. We don't have such problems, so we can just continue with our usual move.}) 4. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yd7d5] The main move, White is controlling the [d5]-square. Now Black is at a crossroads again, having three, pretty much equally good options.} ({•} 4. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the Italian Game.}) ({•} 4. c3 $6 {Way too slow.} d5 $1 {We can break in the centre without any problems.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 $1 {And we just transposed to the Italian Game, by a somewhat unusual move order. 🙂}) 4... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd7d5,Yb4e1] By pinning the knight, Black is reinforcing the idea of ...[d5]. I found this move the most consistent with the repertoire.} (4... Na5 {is another interesting line, but the positions after for example} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. Qd3 {are not so easy to play. White's pawns are controlling the position very well, I have seen Nakamura winning many games with White in such structures.}) ({The third line is} 4... Bc5 {, but it would have the flavor of the Italian game, and as you will see later in the course, we will not really have any games in a 'slow' Italian.}) 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f4] The most common move, White is already protecting the knight on [c3], and leaves the way open for the f-pawn.} d5 {We don't have to change anything in our plans, this move works well.} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Yf3g5,Yg5e6] Developing and keeping the tension in centre. Our bishop is very comfortable on [e6], since we don't have to worry about the [Ng5] idea.} 8. Bxd5 {[%cal Gf2f4] Surprising move at the first sight, but it is with a very concrete idea, White can only play for [f4] by taking the knight first.} (8. f4 $2 {This is a move what White has to play, just it is too early at this moment.} Nxc3 $1 9. Nxc3 {(9.bxc3 Bc5+ 10.Kh1 Bxc4 11.dxc4 Qxd1 12.Rxd1 f6 ∓ With a horrific endgame for White. )} Qd4+ $1 10. Kh1 Bxc4 11. dxc4 Qxc4 12. fxe5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 O-O {∓ White has an awful position with 4 weak pawns.}) 8... Bxd5 9. f4 f6 $1 {A very strong move, which only got popular in the last few years. The main idea is to stay flexible, since castling long can be a much better option in many of the positions.} (9... O-O {This is the main line, but now White can get a decent position. For example,} 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. f5 $1 f6 12. Ng3 {∞ This is what White wants! Gain space on the kingside, then put the knight to [e4], and maybe later start attacking Black's king.}) 10. fxe5 (10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. fxe5 Nxe5 {is transposing to the main line.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxd5 ({•} 11. Nf4 Bf7 {Another good point of 9... [f6] is that the bishop has [f7]-available.} 12. d4 Nc6 13. Re1+ Be7 {⩱ Black is castling next, and White is struggling to equalise here, because of the weakness of the [d4]-pawn.}) ({•} 11. d4 Ng6 $1 {The knight is controlling the [f4]-square, so after the trade on [d5], White can't kick out our queen by [Nf4].} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nf4 Nxf4 14. Bxf4 O-O-O {The position is around equal, but the opposite side castling gives chances for both sides to win this game.}) 11... Qxd5 12. c3 {[%cal Gb4d6,Yd5d7] This is the precise move order for White, since after ...[Bd6] the queen will not be able to retreat to [d7].} (12. Nf4 {Allows the queen to retreat to [d7].} Qd7 13. c3 Bd6 14. d4 O-O-O $1 {A very nice move, played by Anish Giri in a very important tie-break game of the FIDE Grand Prix, against GM Andreikin.} 15. Qb3 (15. dxe5 $4 Bc5+ {+ -+}) 15... Ng6 16. Ne6 Rde8 17. d5 Nf8 {∓ Giri played great up to this moment, and he has a clear advantage since White couldn't solve the development and the only active piece is just being traded, or it has to go back.}) 12... Bd6 13. Nf4 Qf7 {[%csl Gf7] Fortunately, the [f7]-square is also pretty nice for the queen. 🙂} 14. d4 O-O-O $1 {We are just in time to finish the development with this little tactical trick.} 15. Qa4 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Yd4e5,Ga4a7]} ({Even after this move, the knight on e5 is not really hanging.} 15. dxe5 $4 Bc5+ {+ -+}) 15... a6 16. dxe5 (16. Qb3 Nc4 {⩱ With ...[Rde8] or ...[Rhe8] coming next, Black is simply more active here.}) 16... Bc5+ $1 {[%csl Rf1] Making the [f1]-rook unprotected allows Black to regain the material.} 17. Kh1 fxe5 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gd8,Gf7]} (17... fxe5 {Black has better pieces, and the only move which is more or less okay for White here is} 18. Rf3 $1 {which is anything but easy to find. However,} exf4 19. Bxf4 Qd5 {⩱ is definitely at least slightly better for Black.}) *

