1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. Bc4 {After this move we are most likely transposing to another variation and therefore chapter.} Nc6 ({The most practical choice, but if you want to be very principled, I believe the line} 3... Nxe4 $1 {is the easiest way to reach equality for Black.} 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 {and here instead of the craziness which starts with} Nc6 6. Nb5 $1 {, Black has 5...Be7 and according to my analyses, no problems at all.}) 4. f4 $6 ({The only move which avoids transposition to some other variation, but it is very dubious.} 4. d3 Bb4 {transposes to the Bishop's Opening.}) (4. Nf3 Nxe4 $1 {is analysed via the Four Knights move order.}) 4... Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yd7d5] This small tactical trick already gives a clear advantage for Black.} 5. Nxe4 {As usual, this move doesn't challenge us at all.} d5 6. Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 exf4 {With a healthy extra pawn, and no problems with our development, we can be very optimistic here.} 8. Nf3 Bd7 $17 {[%cal Gd8f6,Ge8c8] With ...[Qf6] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is in a serious trouble.} *

