1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. Bc4 {After this move we are most likely transposing to another variation and therefore chapter.} Nc6 ({The most practical choice, but if you want to be very principled, I believe the line} 3... Nxe4 $1 {is the easiest way to reach equality for Black.} 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 {and here instead of the craziness which starts with} Nc6 6. Nb5 $1 {, Black has 5...Be7 and according to my analyses, no problems at all.}) 4. f4 $6 ({The only move which avoids transposition to some other variation, but it is very dubious.} 4. d3 Bb4 {transposes to the Bishop's Opening.}) (4. Nf3 Nxe4 $1 {is analysed via the Four Knights move order.}) 4... Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yd7d5] This small tactical trick already gives a clear advantage for Black.} 5. Bxf7+ {We are yet to see a single line, where this desperate intermediate move helps White chances.} Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 $1 {Black rules the centre.} 7. Ng5+ Kg8 {Our king is perfectly safe, it is rather its colleague, which has to be worried about some attack.} 8. d3 exf4 9. Bxf4 Qe7+ 10. Ne2 Bg4 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8e8] White can't castle and we are ready to bring the rook to [e8], White has big problems.} *

