1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. Bc4 {After this move we are most likely transposing to another variation and therefore chapter.} Nc6 ({The most practical choice, but if you want to be very principled, I believe the line} 3... Nxe4 $1 {is the easiest way to reach equality for Black.} 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 {and here instead of the craziness which starts with} Nc6 6. Nb5 $1 {, Black has 5...Be7 and according to my analyses, no problems at all.}) 4. f4 $6 ({The only move which avoids transposition to some other variation, but it is very dubious.} 4. d3 Bb4 {transposes to the Bishop's Opening.}) (4. Nf3 Nxe4 $1 {is analysed via the Four Knights move order.}) 4... Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yd7d5] This small tactical trick already gives a clear advantage for Black.} 5. Nf3 {This is the best move relatively speaking, but the machine is not impressed at all.} Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ye1g1,Re7c5,Rc5g1,Ye7e1] The key move of the line, pretty much refuting the whole idea from White, since our opponent can't castle, because it would drop the bishop on [c4].} 7. b4 {[%cal Yb4c5,Ye7c5,Ge1g1] Covering the [c5]-square and preparing for [O-O] looks like an interesting try from White, but we shouldn't be afraid of some ghost threats.} ({•} 7. O-O $4 Qc5+ {+ -+}) ({•} 7. Qe2 {With down a pawn, White goes into the endgame. Something clearly went wrong for our opponent.} exf4 $1 8. Bxf4 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 d6 {∓ With a clear extra pawn for Black.}) 7... exf4+ $1 8. Kf2 {[%cal Gh1e1,Ge1e8] Re1 is coming with big power, but it is just one move too late.} Qf6 $19 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] White can't stop ...[Be7] followed by castle, so there is not much our opponent can do here to compensate for the material deficit.} *

