1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. a3 {Mengarini's Opening. A fun little move, with the idea of offering Black to play White's side of the Scotch game. 🙂 A relevant variation to compare here is going like this: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 Qh4 this move is not considered to be entirely correct, because of the following continuation, 5.Nc3 Bb4 6.Be2 Qxe4 7.Nb5! and Black is experiencing problems with protecting the pawn on [c7]. It could be exactly the same here with reversed colors, just White played this extra move of [a3], which stops the annoying ...[Nb4] move at the end of the same line. 🙂 If we understand this, and just don't play ...[d5] here right away, we should be fine with everything else.} Nc6 $1 {The simplest, with most likely transposing to a Four Knights Game.} 4. Bc4 $6 ({Doesn't work well, for already well known reasons.} 4. Nf3 d5 {transposes to the Four Knights.}) 4... Nxe4 $1 5. Nxe4 d5 {Black is already fighting for the advantage.} 6. Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 8. d3 h6 $15 {[%cal Gf8g8,Ge8g8,Gf7f5]} ({A very precise move order,} 8... O-O {looked obvious, but after} 9. Qh5 $1 {we have to weaken our position a little bit, since} h6 $4 {is losing to} 10. Bxh6 $1 {. Now castle is coming next, and then ...[f5], with a superior central control, Black has a comfortable edge.}) (8... h6 9. Qh5 {This move fails to do anything now, since after} Nd4 $1 {the queen has to retreat to [d1], to protect the [c2]-pawn.}) *

