1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. d4 {White is playing in the spirit of the Centre Game, which most of the time will just lead to a transposition to that chapter, but there is one line, where there could be a significant difference.} exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 5. Qd3 {When we reach this position from the Centre Game move order, then the knights are or [b1] and [g8] still, and we can play ...[d5]! with a good game. Fortunately, that move works here as well, but it is undoubtedly an improved version for White.} (5. Qe3 Bb4 {is the main line of the Centre Game.}) 5... d5 $1 6. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yg5d8,Ge4d5] Instead of taking the pawn on [d5], White is rather continuing the development and putting more pressure on our position.} d4 $1 {This very strong move solves our opening problems completely, and Black is even going to be better after this move.} 7. Nd5 {[%cal Yg5f6,Yd5f6] Everything looks pretty good for White, but now comes the surprise, with a remarkable tactical point at the end!} (7. Bxf6 {Probably, objectively better than 7. [Nd5], but still not enough for equality.} gxf6 $1 {Not allowing 8. [Nd5] to be a tempo on our queen, and the once the bishop goes to [g7], kingside castling will still be very safe for Black.} 8. Nd5 f5 $1 {⩱ A nice undermining move, our next moves are ...[Bg7]-[Be6] and short castle with good play thanks to our strong bishops.}) 7... Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4d5,Rb4d3] It is very logical to challenge that strong [d5]-knight with a tempo.} 8. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 9. c3 {[%cal Rd3b5,Rc3b4,Rc3d4] But now it looks like that Black has serious problems, the bishop is hanging, if it leaves the [e1]-[a5] diagonal, then the [d4]-pawn is falling.} (9. c3 {On} Bc5 {, which is protecting the pawn, there is} 10. Qb5+ $1 {winning the bishop, and on 9...Ba5 there is simply 10.e5!}) 9... dxc3 $1 {The point behind our previous play, we are 'blundering' the bishop on [b4].} 10. Qb5+ {[%csl Yb4][%cal Rb5e8,Rb5b4] It looks like that we are losing the bishop, and the game.} (10. Qxd8+ {Leads to a pawn down endgame for White.} Kxd8 11. O-O-O+ Ke8 12. bxc3 Bxc3 {⩱ White has only minimal compensation for the lost pawn.}) 10... Nd7 $3 {[%cal Rc3b2,Rb2a1] It is very easy to miss this fantastic resource. The threat of ...[cxb2]-[bxa1Q] is so strong, that we don't even have to care about our queen.} 11. Qxb4 (11. Bxd8 $4 cxb2+ 12. Qxb4 bxa1=Q+ 13. Ke2 Kxd8 {-+ And Black is up a full rook.}) 11... cxb2 {One more intermezzo.} 12. Qxb2 Qxg5 $17 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg5g7,Ge8g8] Black is up a healthy pawn.} *

