1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. d4 {White is playing in the spirit of the Centre Game, which most of the time will just lead to a transposition to that chapter, but there is one line, where there could be a significant difference.} exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 5. Qd3 {When we reach this position from the Centre Game move order, then the knights are or [b1] and [g8] still, and we can play ...[d5]! with a good game. Fortunately, that move works here as well, but it is undoubtedly an improved version for White.} (5. Qe3 Bb4 {is the main line of the Centre Game.}) 5... d5 $1 6. Nxd5 Nxd5 7. exd5 Nb4 {[%cal Rb4c2] There is no way for White to keep the extra pawn, since the knight attacks not only [d5] but also [c2].} 8. Qe4+ Qe7 $1 {[%cal Rb4d5,Rb4c2] An instant equalizer. Black is taking back the pawn on ...[d5] with a very good position.} *

