1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. d4 {White is playing in the spirit of the Centre Game, which most of the time will just lead to a transposition to that chapter, but there is one line, where there could be a significant difference.} exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 5. Qd3 {When we reach this position from the Centre Game move order, then the knights are or [b1] and [g8] still, and we can play ...[d5]! with a good game. Fortunately, that move works here as well, but it is undoubtedly an improved version for White.} (5. Qe3 Bb4 {is the main line of the Centre Game.}) 5... d5 $1 6. Bf4 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gf4c7,Yc3b5] This is the main move for White, our opponent is eyeing at the [c7]-pawn and wants to play [Nb5] next. The following moves are pretty forcing, and the game will eventually lead to a balanced endgame.} (6. exd5 Nb4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 $1 {Because of the weakness of the [c2]-pawn, White can't keep the extra pawn on [d5], therefore we at least have a comfortable equality.}) 6... d4 7. Nb5 {[%cal Rf4c7,Rb5c7]} Bb4+ {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4a5,Ga5c7] The bishop from [a5] is going to be a key defender of the [c7]-pawn.} 8. c3 dxc3 $1 {[%cal Rc3b2] The ...[cxb2] threat is very strong, so we don't have to be afraid of [Nxc7]+.} 9. Qxd8+ ({•} 9. bxc3 Ba5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Transposes to the main line.}) ({•} 9. Nxc7+ $4 Qxc7 $1 10. Bxc7 cxb2+ 11. Ke2 bxa1=Q {-+ With decisive material advantage.}) 9... Kxd8 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8c7,Gb4a5,Ga5c7] The king and the bishop will solve the protection of the [c7]-pawn.} 10. Bxc7+ {This is the only moment when White can grab this pawn without major problems, but Black will comfortably regain the missing pawn, and have a good endgame.} Ke7 11. bxc3 (11. Nxc3 $2 {This is just a blunder.} Nxe4 {∓ Black is already clearly better.}) 11... Bc5 {[%csl Yb5,Yc7,Ye4][%cal Rf6e4] The [e4]-pawn is hanging, and White's coordination is also not ideal, so our opponent can't hold onto the extra pawn for long.} 12. e5 ({•} 12. Bd3 a6 $1 {Black regains the pawn and secures an equal position.} 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Bxd4) ({•} 12. f3 a6 $1 {Immediately regaining the material.} 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Bxd4 {Black has no problems at all, maybe later we can be even optimistic with our queenside majority.}) 12... Ne8 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ra7a6,Ye8c7] White has problems with the [c7]-bishop, pretty much the only way is to give a check on [d6], but then the pawn will be weak there.} 13. O-O-O {[%cal Gd1d6,Gc7d6] Supporting the [Bd6]-idea.} a6 14. Bd6+ Nxd6 15. exd6+ Kd8 16. Nc7 Ra7 $10 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc5d6] With ...[Bxd6] coming in the next move, Black is regaining the material.} *

