1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. d4 {White is playing in the spirit of the Centre Game, which most of the time will just lead to a transposition to that chapter, but there is one line, where there could be a significant difference.} exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 5. Qd3 {When we reach this position from the Centre Game move order, then the knights are or [b1] and [g8] still, and we can play ...[d5]! with a good game. Fortunately, that move works here as well, but it is undoubtedly an improved version for White.} (5. Qe3 Bb4 {is the main line of the Centre Game.}) 5... d5 $1 6. Bf4 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gf4c7,Yc3b5] This is the main move for White, our opponent is eyeing at the [c7]-pawn and wants to play [Nb5] next. The following moves are pretty forcing, and the game will eventually lead to a balanced endgame.} (6. exd5 Nb4 7. Qe2+ Qe7 $1 {Because of the weakness of the [c2]-pawn, White can't keep the extra pawn on [d5], therefore we at least have a comfortable equality.}) 6... d4 7. Nb5 {[%cal Rf4c7,Rb5c7]} Bb4+ {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4a5,Ga5c7] The bishop from [a5] is going to be a key defender of the [c7]-pawn.} 8. c3 dxc3 $1 {[%cal Rc3b2] The ...[cxb2] threat is very strong, so we don't have to be afraid of [Nxc7]+.} 9. Qxd8+ ({•} 9. bxc3 Ba5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Transposes to the main line.}) ({•} 9. Nxc7+ $4 Qxc7 $1 10. Bxc7 cxb2+ 11. Ke2 bxa1=Q {-+ With decisive material advantage.}) 9... Kxd8 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8c7,Gb4a5,Ga5c7] The king and the bishop will solve the protection of the [c7]-pawn.} 10. bxc3 (10. O-O-O+ Bd7 11. bxc3 Ba5 {is another way to reach the position in the main line.}) 10... Ba5 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ga5c7,Gd8c7] We solved the problems with the [c7]-pawn.} 11. O-O-O+ Bd7 12. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4]} ({The only good way to protect the pawn.} 12. e5 $2 {is very bad.} Ne4 {∓ With the pawns on [f2] and [c3] hanging, White is in a horrible shape.}) 12... a6 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd1d8] Forcing a trade on the d-file, and therefore removing all the pressure which is on our king currently.} 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Ba4 {White can't avoid the draw here, if Black wants to continue, it is possible in different ways, but the position is objectively equal.} 15. Rd3 Bb5 16. Rd1 Ba4 $10 ({Black can continue playing by} 16... Re8 {or 16...Nd7 , the position is pretty complex there.}) *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
