[White "4) Vienna Game"]
[Black "Vienna Game - 3.f4 d5 4.exd5 Nxd5 5.fxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C29"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2160376111169218"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. exd5 {Not a very popular move, if your opponent is prepared, they will pretty much never play like this, but nevertheless it is not so bad.} Nxd5 {[%cal Rd8h4]} ({Not the only good move for Black,} 4... e4 {or 4...exf4 (are also good lines, but those are transposing to territories which we are not playing for example in the King's Gambit so it looks more logical to continue in an independent way here.)}) 5. fxe5 {Looks extremely risky, but happened in quite a few games, so deserves some coverage.} (5. Nxd5 $6 {Strangely enough, this move is the most popular in this position. It poses absolutely zero problems for Black, and it is actually White who already has to fight for the equality.} Qxd5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Be2 Nxe5 {Black's moves are not particularly difficult.} 9. O-O Bc5+ 10. Kh1 Nxf3 11. Bxf3 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 O-O {⩱ With a serious advantage in the development, Black is playing for the advantage here.}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 (6. dxc3 $2 Qh4+ $1 {White can't block the check with 7. [g3], because ...[Qe4]+ is picking up the rook.} 7. Kd2 Nc6 {⩱ For only one pawn, White's king is staying in the centre. We will play ...[Bg4] and ...[O-O-O] with a nice advantage.}) 6... Qh4+ {[%csl Re1] White still can't block this check, so this line looks anything but fun for White.} 7. Ke2 (7. g3 $2 Qe4+ 8. Kf2 Qxh1 9. Nf3 {White is trying to trap the queen by playing [Qe2] and [Bg2] in the next moves, but it is just too slow.} Nc6 $1 10. Qe2 Bg4 11. Bg2 Qxh2 $1 {Giving back some material, but still keeping an extra exchange.} 12. Nxh2 Bxe2 13. Kxe2 Nxe5 {-+ Black is completely winning.}) 7... Bg4+ {Instead of immediately taking back the missing pawn, it is much better to finish the development first.} (7... Qe4+ $2 {Many games continued with this move, but it just helps White.} 8. Kf2 Qxe5 9. Nf3 Qa5 10. d4 {⩲ Our queen made a lot of moves, and in the meantime White managed to stabilise the position, and with moves like [Bc4]-[Rb1]-[Re1] coming up, the engine already prefers White.}) 8. Nf3 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6e5] Of course, we wouldn't mind taking back the pawn with the knight! 🙂} 9. Qe1 {A very original way of playing, it still can transpose back to the main line, but normally White has a different idea.} Qh5 $1 {[%csl Re1,Re2]} (9... Qxe1+ $6 {It is again a very instructive mistake, to be greedy instead of keeping White's pieces in awkward positions.} 10. Kxe1 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nxe5 12. d4 {⩲} Nxf3+ $2 13. Kf2 Nh4 14. Rb1 {± White is down a pawn, and is much better! The bishops are fantastic in this position.}) 10. Kd1 {[%csl Yd1,Ye1] This position is more funny than good for White. 🙂} (10. d4 O-O-O 11. Kf2 f6 $1 {transposes to this line.}) 10... Bxf3+ 11. gxf3 Qxf3+ 12. Be2 Qd5 $15 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Ge8c8,Gc8b8] With [O-O-O] and then [Kb8] coming so we are not going to blunder any check on the light squares Black is definitely preferable here, with the much safer king.} *

