1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. d3 $6 {White is inviting big complications with this move, which I believe is better to avoid and to be simply better in a calm position. 🙂} Nxc3 (5... Qh4+ {This is the start of a very messy line, which is playable for both sides.} 6. g3 Nxg3 7. Nf3 $1 {Makes the line possible to play for White.} Qh5 8. Nxd5 Nxh1 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Bg4 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. d4 $1 {∞ At the end of this chaotic line, the only good move for Black is} f6 $1 {which is equal according to the computer, but yeah, we simply don't need this.}) 6. bxc3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Re5][%cal Yc3c4,Yf8b4] Isolating the [e5]-pawn and potentially causing some problems on the dark squares in White's position, and of course not waiting for White to play [d4] themselves.} 7. Nf3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gd3d4] This is how White should play, they lose a pawn, but at least there will be a chance to play [d4], and finish the development.} ({•} 7. Bb2 $6 {Looks awkward, and it is bad indeed.} dxc3 8. Bxc3 Nc6 {∓ ...[Bc5] is coming next, once the knight goes to [f3], ... [Bg4] is pretty much an instant reply from us, and we are also going to castle soon, which can't be said about our opponent.}) ({•} 7. cxd4 $2 {This just invites trouble.} Qxd4 8. Rb1 Bb4+ {A clever check, we will see the point of it at the end of the line.} 9. Bd2 Bc5 10. Qe2 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qa4 {∓ Now thanks to ...[Bb4]+ forcing White's bishop to [d2], there are too many pieces on the second row for the queen to protect the [a2]-pawn.}) ({•} 7. c4 $6 {A pretty bad positional move, White is just going to be very weak on the dark squares.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Qe7 {⩱ And White already has serious problems how to protect the pawn on [e5].}) 7... dxc3 {There is no reason for us not to take here.} 8. Be2 ({Equally popular to} 8. d4 {in OTB chess, but this feels way too passive for this position.}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O Qd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Yc2c4,Gc8e6,Ge8c8] Thanks to the pawn on [c3], our queen is very stable and strong on [d5]. In most of the games, Black played 9...[Bc5]+ and castled short, but it is even more ambitious to castle long, and the king is going to be very safe there, since if anywhere, only on the kingside could have White hoped for some play, thanks to the space advantage provided by the pawn on [e5].} 10. Kh1 h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5,Gc8e6,Rf3g5] This move is just very thematic against [Ng5] ideas, and even though 10...[Be6] works as well, I still like it better.} 11. Qe1 {[%cal Re1c3,Ge1g3]} Bb4 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb4c3] Simply keeping our extra pawn.} 12. Qg3 {It looks like that White was just in time to create some threats, but since we are castling longside, we are not worried about our g-pawn at all.} Be6 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8] If White takes on [g7], they will have to face a very strong attack. Otherwise, they are just down a pawn without compensation in any means.} *

