1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. d3 $6 {White is inviting big complications with this move, which I believe is better to avoid and to be simply better in a calm position. 🙂} Nxc3 (5... Qh4+ {This is the start of a very messy line, which is playable for both sides.} 6. g3 Nxg3 7. Nf3 $1 {Makes the line possible to play for White.} Qh5 8. Nxd5 Nxh1 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Bg4 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. d4 $1 {∞ At the end of this chaotic line, the only good move for Black is} f6 $1 {which is equal according to the computer, but yeah, we simply don't need this.}) 6. bxc3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Re5][%cal Yc3c4,Yf8b4] Isolating the [e5]-pawn and potentially causing some problems on the dark squares in White's position, and of course not waiting for White to play [d4] themselves.} 7. Nf3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gd3d4] This is how White should play, they lose a pawn, but at least there will be a chance to play [d4], and finish the development.} ({•} 7. Bb2 $6 {Looks awkward, and it is bad indeed.} dxc3 8. Bxc3 Nc6 {∓ ...[Bc5] is coming next, once the knight goes to [f3], ... [Bg4] is pretty much an instant reply from us, and we are also going to castle soon, which can't be said about our opponent.}) ({•} 7. cxd4 $2 {This just invites trouble.} Qxd4 8. Rb1 Bb4+ {A clever check, we will see the point of it at the end of the line.} 9. Bd2 Bc5 10. Qe2 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qa4 {∓ Now thanks to ...[Bb4]+ forcing White's bishop to [d2], there are too many pieces on the second row for the queen to protect the [a2]-pawn.}) ({•} 7. c4 $6 {A pretty bad positional move, White is just going to be very weak on the dark squares.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Qe7 {⩱ And White already has serious problems how to protect the pawn on [e5].}) 7... dxc3 {There is no reason for us not to take here.} 8. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf1c4] White has a nice pawn-centre to compensate for the missing pawn, or at least that is what they are hoping. 🙂} Qd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Yf1c4] This is just a great square for the queen in these lines, and we very importantly stopped [Bc4] from White!} 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gd3e4] If we are sleeping, White is going to play [Qe2] followed up by [Bc4] or [Be4] and suddenly our queen has to leave [d5], and White will have some play.} (9. Be2 {Very slow.} Nc6 10. O-O Be6 {With normal developing moves, Black is achieving a winning position.} 11. Be3 O-O-O {∓ We are much better on both sides of the board, on the kingside we can play with ...[h6]-[g5], but what is even more effective, is to play on the queenside using the ...[Ba3]-[Bb2] idea, and White is pretty much stalemated there.}) 9... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Rc6d4] But we are not sleeping! In case of [Qe2], the pawn is just falling on [d4].} 10. Be3 (10. Rb1 {With the idea of hitting the queen from [b5].} Nb4 $1 11. a3 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 b6 $1 {We are giving back the pawn, but our advantage remains. The bishop on the light squares is going to be the best piece on the board.} 13. Qxc3 Ba6 {∓ With ...[Be7] and [O-O] to follow, Black is clearly better.}) 10... h6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6] Preparing to play ...[Be6] without worrying about [Ng5] at any moment.} 11. Rb1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb1b5,Gb5d5] White wants to challenge our queen on [d5].} Nb4 ({This is the easiest, simply blocking the rook's way to b5.} 11... Be6 {also works for tactical reasons, but it is not needed.}) 12. O-O Be6 $17 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Yb4d3,Ge8c8,Gf8e7] Most likely we will be able to keep the extra pawn on [c3], but even if not, we can just take the bishop on [d3], and claim the advantage with our pair of bishops.} *

