1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rc3e4]} ({This is White's alternative to the normal} 6. d4 {, and it is quite a tricky one! White is attacking the knight on [e4], and also putting the minor pieces on [f2] don't work for Black.}) 6... Bf5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4,Rc5f2] Developing and protecting the knight looks like the way to go for Black, with keeping all our threats.} ({•} 6... Bf2+ {This is the most popular move, but White is pretty okay after this.} 7. Kd1 Nxc3+ 8. bxc3 Bb6 9. d4 {∞ I would still take Black here, but it is pretty complicated.}) ({•} 6... Nf2 $4 {is a big blunder because White will get 2 pieces for the rook, since the knight is trapped on [h1].} 7. d4 $1 Nxh1 8. dxc5 {+-}) 7. d4 {White finally plays this move, and ...[Bb4] would be still a good response, but since the queen is not covering the [d4]-pawn now, I like ...[Bb6] even more.} Bb6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yb6d4,Yb8c6]} 8. Be3 Nc6 {[%cal Yc6d4,Yb6d4,Gf5g4,Rg4e2] Increasing the pressure on the [d4]-pawn, and at some moment ...[Bg4] can be really unpleasant for White.} 9. O-O-O O-O $15 {[%cal Yf7f6,Gd8e7,Ge4c3,Ye7a3] With moves like ...[Qe7] preparing to make ...[f6] or ...[Nxc3] a stronger threat, coming up, White's position is really tough to play here.} *

