1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rc3e4]} ({This is White's alternative to the normal} 6. d4 {, and it is quite a tricky one! White is attacking the knight on [e4], and also putting the minor pieces on [f2] don't work for Black.}) 6... Bf5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4,Rc5f2] Developing and protecting the knight looks like the way to go for Black, with keeping all our threats.} ({•} 6... Bf2+ {This is the most popular move, but White is pretty okay after this.} 7. Kd1 Nxc3+ 8. bxc3 Bb6 9. d4 {∞ I would still take Black here, but it is pretty complicated.}) ({•} 6... Nf2 $4 {is a big blunder because White will get 2 pieces for the rook, since the knight is trapped on [h1].} 7. d4 $1 Nxh1 8. dxc5 {+-}) 7. Nd1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd2d3] A very cheeky move from White! They want to play [d3] and trap our knight in the middle of the board.} (7. d3 $6 {We have a very nice way to counter this move.} Bf2+ 8. Kd1 Bb6 $1 {And our knight is tactically protected on [e4].} 9. dxe4 dxe4+ 10. Nd2 e3 {∓ Winning back the piece with a much better position.}) 7... Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4f3,Ge4g5,Gg5e6] By pinning the knight on [f3], the bishop provides a way back for the knight, via [g5]-[e6].} 8. d3 (8. Ne3 {White is challenging our bishop, but we can protect it, and maybe involve the [h8]-rook in the game as well.} h5 $1 9. c3 {Preparing to play [d4], but Black is so much better developed, that we can even meet it with a sacrifice. (9.d3 Bb4+ 10.Kd1 Nc6! -+ is a pretty nice position, White is pinned everywhere. )} Nc6 $1 10. d4 Bxd4 11. cxd4 Nxd4 {-+ And White is completely lost.}) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Ng5 {[%csl Rc1,Rd1,Ge6,Rf1][%cal Gg5e6] It looks like that White achieved something by gaining the pair of bishops, but in fact, our knight is going to be really strong on [e6], and White has a lot to do in order to activate those pieces in the back rank.} 10. Qf5 (10. Bxg5 $2 {Greedy and bad!} Qxg5 11. Qxd5 Nd7 12. c3 O-O-O {∓ Black has huge play for the missing pawn, which in the machine's evaluation is already a winning advantage.}) 10... Ne6 {[%cal Re6d4] One more tempo, since ...[Nd4] is very unpleasant.} 11. c3 g6 12. Qf3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White is one move away from stabilising the position, and having a good game.} d4 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Rd1,Re5,Rf1][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6e5] Very strong move, isolating the [e5]-pawn, and keeping White's minor pieces passive.} 13. Qxb7 {White takes a pawn, but it will not help much with the major problems their position have.} Nd7 {[%csl Re1][%cal Rd7e5,Re8g8,Gf8e8] We are going to castle, very soon regain the pawn on [e5], and then start attacking White's king.} *

