1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one. By far the main and most expected move from White.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Yd2d4,Rb4c3,Re4c3] We kind of lost a tempo with ...[Bc5], but now we get it back by attacking [c3].} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4d2] Introducing the great threat of [Nxe4], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} (7. Qd3 $6 {Looks very strange.} O-O 8. Bd2 Bf5 {White walked into it by playing [Qd3].} 9. Qe3 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 c5 $1 {⩱ Now we will attack the dark squares, playing moves such as ...[Nc6] and ...[Qa5].}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gc3e4] Not the most popular, but probably the most solid option for White.} Nxd2 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Since we are attacking the dark squares in the center, it makes a lot of sense to exchange this bishop.} 9. Qxd2 cxd4 $1 ({This is the most precise move order.} 9... Nc6 {allows White a thematic pawn sacrifice shown in this illustrative line.}) 10. Nxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Rc6e5] Continuing to put pressure on White's centre.} 11. Qf4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gf4d4]} (11. Nxc6 $2 {A huge positional mistake, which improves Black's structure.} bxc6 12. O-O O-O {∓ White is much worse due to the weak [e5]-pawn.}) 11... O-O 12. Nxc6 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf4b4] Now this move is completely different, because our bishop on [b4] is hanging.} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 bxc6 14. O-O Be6 $10 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2,Rc3,Gd3,Re5][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Gh7h6,Gd8g5] The position is around equal. Black has the better structure, but White's bishop is stronger. If we can exchange queens, then we are in a very good situation, but there is still a long way to go.} *

