], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} (7. Qd3 $6 {Looks very strange.} O-O 8. Bd2 Bf5 {White walked into it by playing [Qd3].} 9. Qe3 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 c5 $1 {⩱ Now we will attack the dark squares, playing moves such as ...[Nc6] and ...[Qa5].}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gc3e4] Not the most popular, but probably the most solid option for White.} Nxd2 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Since we are attacking the dark squares in the center, it makes a lot of sense to exchange this bishop.} 9. Qxd2 Nc6 {This continuation allows White a thematic pawn sacrifice, which is mainly used in the French Defense.} 10. a3 Ba5 11. b4 $1 {With this sacrifice, White is stabilizing the centre.} cxb4 12. Ne2 bxa3 13. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Ge1g1] White is not better, but it has a normal game with a strong center and fairly good minor pieces.} *

