1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one. By far the main and most expected move from White.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Yd2d4,Rb4c3,Re4c3] We kind of lost a tempo with ...[Bc5], but now we get it back by attacking [c3].} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4d2] Introducing the great threat of [Nxe4], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} (7. Qd3 $6 {Looks very strange.} O-O 8. Bd2 Bf5 {White walked into it by playing [Qd3].} 9. Qe3 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 c5 $1 {⩱ Now we will attack the dark squares, playing moves such as ...[Nc6] and ...[Qa5].}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. a3 {White wants to clarify the situation and does not mind having pawns doubled on the c-file, hoping that this will only strengthen the center. In theory this seems like a good idea, but let's see how it plays out in practice.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gc3d4]} (9. Bxc3 {The bishop looks very strange on [c3].} O-O 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O Bf5 {⩱ It is not clear how White should continue, if they take [c5], we can always respond with ...[Nxc3] and create a very ugly structure. Otherwise Black just increases the pressure with moves like ...[Rc8], ...[Re8] and ...[Qb6].}) 9... Nc6 10. Bd3 Bg4 {[%csl Gc6,Rd2,Ge4,Gg4] Our minor pieces are simply fantastic here, which cannot be said of the bishop on [d2]. It is also remarkable that once White has managed to stabilize the dark squares, Black plays on the light squares.} 11. O-O {Sets up a brilliant trap!} c4 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3] Fixing the weaknesses on the c-file, and forcing White's bishop to a more passive square.} (11... cxd4 $2 {Already makes White's structure much better, but of course Black wants to take a pawn.} 12. cxd4 Nxd4 $4 13. Nxd4 $1 {Refutes the whole idea.} Bxd1 14. Bb5+ Kf8 15. Ne6+ Ke7 16. Nxd8 {+-}) 12. Be2 (12. Bxe4 {It does not lose material, but neither is it sufficient for equality.} dxe4 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 Bg6 {⩱ White's position is pretty loose on the kingside, sooner or later ...h5 can be quite dangerous.}) 12... O-O $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf7f6,Gd8a5,Re4c3,Ra5c3] The position somewhat resembles a French, and a brilliant one for Black! The [c8] bishop is doing a great job, and we can play standard ideas like ...[Qa5] and attack the pawns on the queen's side or play with ...[f6] and undermine White's center.} *

