1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one. By far the main and most expected move from White.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Rd8h4] This is the old main line, a very logical developing move, which prevents the dangerous ...[Qh4] ideas.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re4f2] By having the threat of ...[Nf2], we are pretty much provoking [d4], which looks counterintuitive, but once it is played, we can pin the knight on [c3]!} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Yd2d4,Rb4c3,Re4c3] We kind of lost a tempo with ...[Bc5], but now we get it back by attacking [c3].} 7. Bd2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4d2] Introducing the great threat of [Nxe4], taking advantage of the fact that our [b4]-bishop is unprotected.} (7. Qd3 $6 {Looks very strange.} O-O 8. Bd2 Bf5 {White walked into it by playing [Qd3].} 9. Qe3 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 c5 $1 {⩱ Now we will attack the dark squares, playing moves such as ...[Nc6] and ...[Qa5].}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd4][%cal Gc5b4,Rc5d4] Excellent move! Not only does it protect the bishop on [b4], but it also attacks White's center!} 8. Bb5+ {The most popular move, but White is struggling here as well.} (8. Nxe4 $6 {Now this move is not nearly as effective as without ...[c5], and Black is even going to be better here.} dxe4 9. Bxb4 cxb4 10. Bb5+ {(10.Ng1?! is extremely passive. 10...O-O 11.Bc4 Nc6 12.c3 bxc3 13.bxc3 So far we have followed a blitz game, Andreikin-Kramnik 2010. The former world champion somehow lost this game, but it has nothing to do with the opening. 🙂 13...Qc7! -+ With the threat of ...[Nxe5]. This position is just awful for White. )} Nc6 $1 11. d5 {White's best try, but even this fails.} exf3 12. dxc6 f2+ $1 {This intermezzo gives Black a nice edge, since White can't take the pawn.} 13. Kf1 Qb6 {∓ or 13.Kxf2?? Qb6 + -+}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O O-O {[%csl Gc6,Rd4,Re5] The [c6]-knight is unpinned, so White must once again solve problems with their centre.} 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 (11. bxc3 $6 c4 $1 {Basically forcing an opposite-coloured bishop game, where our bishop will be superior.} 12. Bxc6 {White has to take, otherwise our knight moves, and we trap the bishop with ... [a6]-[b5].} bxc6 {∓ With ...[Bf5]-[Rb8] and ...[Qa5] to follow, we have easy play against White's weak queenside pawn, while White... has pretty much no play at all.}) 11... Nxc3 {That knight for that bishop??!! Well, Black had other good moves too, but this just guarantees a risk-free edge, so why not?} (11... c4 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bb4 Re8 14. Nd2 {And White is quite okay.}) 12. bxc3 c4 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6e7,Ya7a6,Yb7b5] The bishop is in a big danger, so White must trade.} 13. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 {[%csl Ra3,Rc2,Rf3][%cal Ga8b8,Gc8f5,Gd8e7,Ye7a3,Yf5c2] White's knight has no good square, while our bishop comes to [f5], combined with ...[Qe7]-[Rab8]-[Rb2], and White really struggles to hold the pawns on the queenside.} *

