1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rf3e4,Yd8h4,Gg2g3] This move is taking over as a main line in recent years, White is challenging the [e4]-knight right away, and also prepares against ...[Qh4]+, since it can be answered simply by [g3] now.} Be6 $5 ({Black has 3 main choices in this position instead of this move,} 5... Nc6 {, 5...Nxc3 and the machine's favourite, 5...f5 . All are perfectly playable, but the text move gives White immediate practical problems, and it is also important, that the move is pretty much unknown, I found only 6 games in the database with it. It is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5. [Qf3], and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 {Asking the knight on [e4] one more time is a waste of time for White.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $1 {The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Qg3 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 {⩱ With ...[Qa5] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is under big pressure.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line, only reached in 3 games so far. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qa4+ {Pretty logical move from White, going away from the attack with a tempo.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5] Bringing a new piece into the game is more important now than gaining another tempo.} (8... Bc6 9. Qf4 $1 {⩲ And White tricked us, because the move we would like to play here is 8...[Nc6], but it is not legal.}) 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {[%cal Gd2d4,Yd5f3,Ye2f3] Both sides developed normally in the last couple of moves, and now White wants to play [d4], even if it means that they have to give back the pawn, but they will gain the pair of bishops in return.} Bc5+ 12. Kh1 (12. d4 $2 {Unfortunately for White, this is a double pawn sacrifice now. 🙂} Nxd4 $1 13. Nxd4 Bc6 {-+ We are taking on [d4] and then on [e5], winning a pawn.}) 12... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Re5] Stopping [d4] with this little tactical trick gives Black the better chances with the active bishops.} 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Gd4][%cal Gf8e8] We are collecting the pawn on [e5] in the next move, and then just bring our pieces to the open e-file.} (13... Bxd4 {Also note,} 14. Qxd4 $4 {blunders the queen to} Bxg2+ {+ -+}) *

