t is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5. [Qf3], and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 {Asking the knight on [e4] one more time is a waste of time for White.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $1 {The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Qg3 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 {⩱ With ...[Qa5] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is under big pressure.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line, only reached in 3 games so far. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qe3 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge3e5,Gg1f3]} ({Together with} 8. Qf4 {, this move looks like the most normal reaction from White, keeping the [e5]-pawn protected, and also supporting the knight's development to [f3].}) 8... Qh4+ $1 {Pretty much at least equalises on the spot for Black.} 9. Qg3 (9. Qf2 $6 Qxf2+ 10. Kxf2 Nc6 {⩱ Not only the [e5]-pawn is a problem for White here, but after ...[Nb4] it is also very difficult to do anything with the [c2]-pawn!}) 9... Qe4+ {Eventually we are going to get an endgame, and this version seems to offer Black better chances to play for the advantage.} (9... Qxg3+ {Also completely fine, Black is regaining the pawn on [e5] without problems.} 10. hxg3 Nc6 11. Nf3 O-O-O 12. c3 Re8 13. d4 f6) 10. Ne2 Nc6 (10... Qxc2 $4 {Ambitious, but losing. 🙂} 11. Nc3 {+- Bd3 is an unpleasant threat now, Black is on the verge of losing.}) 11. d3 Qxe5 12. Qxe5+ Nxe5 {Black has zero problems, and for the moment, has the more active pieces.} 13. Bf4 Bb4+ $1 {We have to make sure that on ...[Ng6] White can't play [Bxc7], and this intermediate check does exactly that.} 14. Nc3 Ng6 15. Bg3 (15. Bxc7 $4 {is losing material.} Rc8 16. Bg3 Rxc3 {-+}) 15... O-O-O $10 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5c6,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] There is a lot of play left, and Black's kingside majority seems to be more mobile, than White's on the queenside, so we can be pretty optimistic here.} *

