t is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5. [Qf3], and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 {Asking the knight on [e4] one more time is a waste of time for White.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $1 {The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Qg3 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 {⩱ With ...[Qa5] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is under big pressure.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line, only reached in 3 games so far. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Ge5,Gh4][%cal Gg1f3,Gf4e5,Gf4h4] Looks like the best square for the queen to me, it supports [e5], helps with [Nf3] and also covers the [h4]-square, so Black's queen can't give an annoying check there.} Nc6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yc6e5,Yc6b4,Yb4c2] The knight is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn, but the idea of playing ...[Nb4] is also very unpleasant for White.} 9. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Gc3b4] A logical move, preventing both ... [Nb4] and ...[Nd4], but it is also a little bit slow, considering that Black is already ahead in the development, and White is yet to develop a minor piece.} Be7 10. d4 {Everything looks nice and protected for White, but now comes Black's counterplay.} f6 $1 {Opening up the position with such an advantage in the development is very logical.} 11. e6 $1 ({Only move for White!} 11. exf6 $2 {Extremely risky, and objectively bad.} Bxf6 12. Bd2 O-O 13. O-O-O {This was the only way for White to avoid having their king in the centre, but it gives back the extra pawn and the king will still not be safe.} Bxa2 {∓}) 11... Bxe6 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] The position is around equal, but it still looks much easier to play with Black, we can play ...[Qd7], castle long, and then start pushing the 'h' and g-pawns on the kingside, especially if White is castling there.} *

