t is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5. [Qf3], and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 {Asking the knight on [e4] one more time is a waste of time for White.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $1 {The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Qg3 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 {⩱ With ...[Qa5] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is under big pressure.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line, only reached in 3 games so far. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Ge5,Gh4][%cal Gg1f3,Gf4e5,Gf4h4] Looks like the best square for the queen to me, it supports [e5], helps with [Nf3] and also covers the [h4]-square, so Black's queen can't give an annoying check there.} Nc6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yc6e5,Yc6b4,Yb4c2] The knight is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn, but the idea of playing ...[Nb4] is also very unpleasant for White.} 9. d4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd4e5,Gc1d2,Gd2e3,Ge1c1] White is stabilizing the centre, and also introduces options such as [Bd2]/[Be3] and then [O-O-O], which may be a quicker way to put the king into safety than going for [O-O].} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c2] This is the only problem with White's previous move, it is not trivial at all to protect the pawn on [c2].} 10. Kd1 {[%csl Gc2,Rd1][%cal Gd1c2] The only move, but now the king stays in the centre, which is offering long-term compensation for Black.} ({•} 10. Qd2 $4 Qh4+ 11. Kd1 Qg4+ 12. Ne2 Be4 {-+ And White is losing the game on the [c2]-square.}) ({•} 10. Qf2 $4 Be4 $1 {And ...[Nc2]+ is coming next, or White can get into other type of trouble as well.} 11. Bb5+ c6 12. Ba4 {White saves the pawn on [c2], but losing the bishop on [a4].} Qa5 $1 {-+ Because of the different discovered checks, White is losing the bishop on [a4].}) 10... g5 $5 {[%cal Rg5f4] Very aggressive, which completely fits the way we want to play here. White again has to move with the queen, but it is not clear to where, all squares have some problems.} 11. Qf2 {[%csl Gd4,Gg2][%cal Gf2d4,Gf2g2,Gc2c3,Gf2f7] Looks like a decent square for the queen, it protects two key pawns, where a sacrifice could happen, and it is not in the way of developing the bishops or the knight to [f3].} Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ge8c8] Black is continuing the standard developing plan and prepares to castle long, while also addressing White's main idea.} 12. c3 $2 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gb2e5] White built a very strong pawn chain, and if Black should retreat now to [c6] with the knight, White would have the time to consolidate and be even better according to the machine.} (12. Bxg5 $4 {Drops a piece.} Qg4+ 13. Nf3 {The line continues, because White is going to get four pawns for the piece, but as we will see at the end, it will be not enough.} Bxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Qxg5 15. Qxb7 Rd8 16. Bb5+ c6 17. Bxc6+ Nxc6 18. Qxc6+ Rd7 {-+ White's king is simply too weak, the extra piece is much more important here than the pawns.}) 12... Qa4+ $1 {[%cal Ra4d1] The refutation of White's try.} 13. b3 Bxb3+ 14. axb3 Qxb3+ $1 {This is the important move! We are not going for the rook yet!} (14... Qxa1 $2 15. cxb4 {+-}) 15. Ke2 Qxc3 $19 {[%cal Gc3d3,Gb4c2,Rc3a1] White can't defend against both ...[Qd3]-[Nc2]+ and ...[Qxa1] threats, so our opponent is losing a lot of material here.} *

