2. Qe4 Qd7 {( The computer gives 12...Bd5 with a repetition, but we can continue with this move. )} 13. Qxb7 Bd5 14. Qb5 Bc6 15. Qc4 O-O-O {with compensation.}) 9... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Yg7g5,Yg5g4] Obviously, one of the ideas of the move is to castle, but it also introduces the [g5]-[g4] idea, which is very easy to overlook.} 10. Bb5 $1 O-O (10... g5 {Still playable, but White is fine here.} 11. Qf5 Be6 12. Qe4 {and now} g4 $2 {is not good, because White has} 13. Nd4 $1 {±}) 11. Bxc6 {Not an easy move to make, but it is the correct way for White.} (11. O-O $6 {allows} Nb4 $1 12. Ne1 f6 $1 {∞ And Black is clearly better, as White is not ready for the opening up of the game.}) 11... Bxc6 12. O-O f6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Ge7][%cal Gf8f1] Opening the position for our bishops and rook on [f8].} 13. d4 fxe5 14. Qxe5 Qd7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rc6f3,Ge7f6,Ga8e8,Gd7g4] Black has a lot of ideas here, basically taking on [f3] and then ...[Bf6] is always an option just to regain the pawn, but keeping the pressure looks even more promising, and we can do that by playing moves like ...[Rae8]-[Bd6]-[Qg4]. If everything fails it will be equal, but White has to a very good defender for the next few moves.} *

