1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. f4 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd8h4] In the style of the King's Gambit, but obviously this move is much safer, since thanks to the knight on [f6], the weakened [e1]-[h4] diagonal is not really an issue, at least right away, for White.} d5 $1 {The only good move for Black! But, it shouldn't come as a surprise, since we have seen many times before, that against [f4], we take and then play ...[d5] or we play ...[d5] right away. Now the first option doesn't work at all, since [e5] is a huge tempo for White, so we go with the other one.} 4. fxe5 {By far the main and most expected move from White.} Nxe4 {[%cal Rd8h4] Already with the threat of ...[Qh4]+.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rf3e4,Yd8h4,Gg2g3] This move is taking over as a main line in recent years, White is challenging the [e4]-knight right away, and also prepares against ...[Qh4]+, since it can be answered simply by [g3] now.} Be6 $5 ({Black has 3 main choices in this position instead of this move,} 5... Nc6 {, 5...Nxc3 and the machine's favourite, 5...f5 . All are perfectly playable, but the text move gives White immediate practical problems, and it is also important, that the move is pretty much unknown, I found only 6 games in the database with it. It is basically a gambit line, since we are giving up a pawn for quick development and in order to create some threats.}) 6. Nxe4 {The only reasonable move from White, our opponent's goal was to force us to make a decision regarding our knight on [e4] by playing 5. [Qf3], and even though we ignored to make a decision, White can't just do the same, because then the queen is just oddly placed on [f3].} (6. d3 $6 {Asking the knight on [e4] one more time is a waste of time for White.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $1 {The position is already quite difficult for White, they have the worst structure, and problems with the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Qg3 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 {⩱ With ...[Qa5] and ...[O-O-O] to follow, White is under big pressure.}) 6... dxe4 7. Qxe4 {[%csl Re4] The starting position of the line, only reached in 3 games so far. We have to use the vulnerable position of White's queen, and the weakness of the pawns on [c2] and [e5] to create counterplay.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd5e4] A good start, putting the bishop to a very active square with a tempo.} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Ge5,Gh4][%cal Gg1f3,Gf4e5,Gf4h4] Looks like the best square for the queen to me, it supports [e5], helps with [Nf3] and also covers the [h4]-square, so Black's queen can't give an annoying check there.} Nc6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yc6e5,Yc6b4,Yb4c2] The knight is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn, but the idea of playing ...[Nb4] is also very unpleasant for White.} 9. Nf3 {The most human move, but White already has to be really careful if Black plays correctly here.} (9. b3 {With the idea of playing [Bb2] and [O-O-O].} Nb4 $1 {Very strong counterplay against the [c2]-pawn.} 10. Kd1 g5 {Black has at least enough compensation here for the pawn. The computer is showing many lines as a quick draw by repetition as best for both sides, but there are a lot of alternatives, the position is just unclear, where we have the options to castle short after ...[Bg7] or castle long after ...[Qd7], while our opponent's king is shaky on [d1].} 11. Qf5 Be6 12. Qe4 Qd7 {( The computer gives 12...Bd5 with a repetition, but we can continue with this move. )} 13. Qxb7 Bd5 14. Qb5 Bc6 15. Qc4 O-O-O {with compensation.}) 9... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Yg7g5,Yg5g4] Obviously, one of the ideas of the move is to castle, but it also introduces the [g5]-[g4] idea, which is very easy to overlook.} 10. Be2 {This move was played in the game Escalante Ramirez-Burke, Dallas 2022, and here instead of the game continuation, which was ...[O-O], Black could have played even more aggressively.} g5 11. Qg3 (11. Qf5 Be6 12. Qe4 g4 {-+ is a disaster for White, the knight has to retreat to [g1], and just ...[Qd7], ...[O-O-O] and ...[Bf5] is coming with a decisive advantage for Black.}) 11... h5 {Both ... [h4] and ...[g4] are a threat, so White's next move is pretty much forced, to slow down our pawns.} 12. h3 f5 {We have one more pawn to involve in the game. 🙂} 13. exf6 Bxf6 {Black has huge compensation. We want to continue with ...[Qe7] and ...[O-O-O] and White has to be really precise to stay in the game.} *

