1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. Nf3 $6 {[%cal Rf3e5] White is attacking on [e5], and changes the normal setup with [Nge2], in order to stop or delay Black's idea of ...[c6]-[d5].} d5 $1 {White's plan was a complete failure, ...[d5] works even without ...[c6] in this position.} 6. exd5 ({•} 6. Nxe5 $2 dxe4 {∓ White's knight on [e5] is extremely loose.}) ({•} 6. Qe2 {White can stabilize the position on [e4] with this move, but it was not the intention by playing 5. [Nf3].} Re8 {The easiest way. ( In case you are looking for some immediate punishment of White's play, then 6...Nc6 7.O-O Bg4!? looks promising, but I couldn't find advantage for Black if White plays correctly there, so decided just to recommend a slightly better line where we don't really have to know a single move, we are just developing normally. )} 7. d3 c6 8. O-O h6 $1 {A typical, useful move for Black, we don't have to count on [Bg5] ideas from White anymore.} 9. h3 a5 10. a4 Na6 {⩱ With more space in the centre, Black is at least slightly better here.}) 6... e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Rf3][%cal Ye4f3] This is the point! The [f3]-knight is struggling to find a good square.} 7. Ng5 $2 {Makes it relatively easy for Black to develop a strong initiative.} Bg4 8. f3 (8. Ne2 Re8 $1 {White is under huge pressure, and the loose position of the knight on [g5] doesn't help either.} 9. h3 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 h6 $1 {The knight is lost!} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 f5 {-+}) 8... exf3 9. Bxf3 Re8+ {The king is staying in the centre.} 10. Kf1 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 (11. Qxf3 $2 {is even worse, keeping the knight awkward on [g5], and allowing ...[Nbd7]-[e5] with a tempo.} Nbd7 12. d3 Ne5 13. Qg2 Qd7 {-+ White is pretty much lost here with such king.}) 11... Nxd5 $17 {The material is equal, but we have the much safer king and better development.} *

