1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. d3 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1,Gg1e2] Played a few times by GM Rauf Mamedov, the strongest player who is using the Mieses variation regularly. Depending on Black's next move, White can still opt for [Nf3] or [Nge2].} c6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd7d5,Gc6d5] Preparing to play ...[d5] and recapture with the pawn.} 6. Nf3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4,Gf3] If White doesn't want to react on our ...[d5], then it is better to have the knight on [f3] then on [e2], since it is much more active on this square. The move also sets up a trap, which is quite easy to blunder.} (6. Nge2 d5 {is going to transpose to the 5. [Nge2] [c6] lines.}) 6... d5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] The d5-pawn is protected by tactical means.} 7. O-O dxe4 ({Going for an equal endgame is what I prefer here, in case you are more ambitious, you can try} 7... Re8 {, but I was not completely happy with} 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Bg5 {, of course it is perfectly fine for Black, just my suggested move looks easier to play for me.}) 8. Nxe4 (8. Nxe5 {is also very level.} Re8 9. Bf4 exd3 10. Nxd3 Bf8 {We can play with ...[Bf5]-[Nbd7]-[Qb6], the comp is saying that is equal, which is surely true, but the knight on [d3] looks very strange.}) 8... Nxe4 9. dxe4 Qxd1 {Keeping the queens with ...[Qe7] or [Qc7] is also good.} 10. Rxd1 f6 $10 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga7a5,Gb8d7] The endgame is equal, but there is a lot of play left.} *

