1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. d3 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1,Gg1e2] Played a few times by GM Rauf Mamedov, the strongest player who is using the Mieses variation regularly. Depending on Black's next move, White can still opt for [Nf3] or [Nge2].} c6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd7d5,Gc6d5] Preparing to play ...[d5] and recapture with the pawn.} 6. Nf3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4,Gf3] If White doesn't want to react on our ...[d5], then it is better to have the knight on [f3] then on [e2], since it is much more active on this square. The move also sets up a trap, which is quite easy to blunder.} (6. Nge2 d5 {is going to transpose to the 5. [Nge2] [c6] lines.}) 6... d5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] The d5-pawn is protected by tactical means.} 7. Nxe5 {White accepts the challenge!} Bd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rd4c3,Yd5e4] The key move, attacking both knights and therefore putting more pressure on the [e4]-pawn too.} 8. f4 {[%csl Re1,Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gd3e4,Rd4g1] White keeps everything protected, but makes the king quite unsafe with this move.} Re8 {[%cal Re8e1] The threat is not necessarily ...[Bxe5], but just by bringing a new piece, we are putting more pressure to White's position.} 9. Ne2 {White would even like to force ...[Bxe5], so their king could castle.} Bb6 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Rb6g1] We will take back the material at some moment, for now it is much more important to keep the king in the centre.} 10. h3 {[%cal Yf6g4,Yh3g4] It was not easy to make a useful move for White, this one at least stops ...[Ng4] or sometimes ...[Bg4] ideas.} dxe4 $1 {This is not the first or last time in the course, that we see that even after the trade of the queens, the king in the centre can be very vulnerable, once the position is opened up.} 11. dxe4 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Re8e4,Rf6e4] Trading White's most active piece, and attacking the [e4]-pawn along the way.} 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 {[%cal Re8e4,Rf6e4]} 14. e5 Rad8 {[%csl Gb6,Rd1,Gd7,Gd8,Ge8,Gf6][%cal Rd7h3,Rd8d1] Nice intermezzo, Black already completely mobilised the pieces, while White is struggling with the king.} 15. Ke1 Nd5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Yf7f6,Rd5b4,Rd7f5] Black has huge play here, we can target the [c2]-pawn by playing ...[Nb4], and ...[f6] with the idea to break up the center also looks like a strong move.} *

