1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3] The main line, White wants to finish the regular setup of this variation.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc6d5] The most ambitious plan for Black, we want to take back on [d5] with a pawn and not with a piece!} 6. O-O (6. d4 {This move doesn't work nearly as well as after 3...[c6], since now it is not the queen which is coming to [d4], and also Black castled in the meantime, which provides an opportunity for an immediate strike in the centre.} exd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 {White already has to be very careful here.} 8. exd5 Bg4 {One more tempo!} 9. Nde2 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 cxd5 11. Qxd5 Nd7 {∞ White's position is very difficult, their king is staying in the centre for a while.}) 6... d5 7. d3 $6 {[%csl Gd3,Re2,Ge4] As I said earlier, if White doesn't want to react on our ...[d5] move, it is much better to put the knight to [f3]. Just look at this [e2]-knight now, it can't even move!} dxe4 $1 {Playing similarly to the lines where the knight is on [f3], with the difference that it will end up as a better position for us. 🙂} 8. Nxe4 (8. dxe4 Qe7 $1 {No trades now! White's pieces are struggling with the lack of space.}) 8... Nxe4 9. dxe4 (9. Bxe4 {Will not make the knight on [e2] any better, but at least we will have a space advantage as well. 🙂} Bh3 10. Bg2 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qd5+ 12. Kg1 Nd7 {⩱ With ...[f5] coming very soon, Black is clearly better.}) 9... a5 $15 {[%csl Re2,Rg2][%cal Gc8e6,Gb8a6]} ({The endgame is very pleasant, but if you want, you can keep the queens on the board with} 9... Qe7 {. We will play ...[Be6] and ...[Na6] next, and White is just struggling with the knight on [e2] and with the light-squared bishop.}) *

