1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3] The main line, White wants to finish the regular setup of this variation.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc6d5] The most ambitious plan for Black, we want to take back on [d5] with a pawn and not with a piece!} 6. O-O (6. d4 {This move doesn't work nearly as well as after 3...[c6], since now it is not the queen which is coming to [d4], and also Black castled in the meantime, which provides an opportunity for an immediate strike in the centre.} exd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 {White already has to be very careful here.} 8. exd5 Bg4 {One more tempo!} 9. Nde2 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 cxd5 11. Qxd5 Nd7 {∞ White's position is very difficult, their king is staying in the centre for a while.}) 6... d5 7. exd5 cxd5 8. d4 $1 {Just like this! Otherwise White just gave up the centre for no reason.} exd4 9. Nxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Gg1][%cal Gc1g5,Gc1e3] Everything looks pretty good for White, they managed to castle, blockade our isolated pawn on [d5] and they are ready to develop the dark-squared bishop in the next move.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4d1] The key move of the whole variation. We have to provoke some weaknesses or gain some time and try to create active play.} 10. Nf3 {Removing the blocker in an IQP position is usually not a recipe for success.} Nc6 {[%cal Yc6d4] Black has firm control over the [d4]-square now, and can play ...[d4] at any moment.} 11. Bg5 {Putting some pressure on the [d5]-pawn. However, Black will push [d4] anyway.} (11. h3 Be6 {⇆ With moves like ...[Qd7]-[Rfe8] and later ...[Ne4] coming, Black is very active and has good chances in a double-edged position.}) 11... d4 12. Ne4 Be7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 $10 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8e8] White has failed to block the pawn on [d5], it is now much stronger on [d4], and all of Black's pieces are quite good, so we need not worry. We can continue with moves like ...[Rc8] and ...[Re8].} *

