1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 ({The so-called Vienna Game. Not nearly as popular as} 2. Nf3 {, but a very decent variation. Depending on Black's reply, White can choose from different setups in the next move, such as playing 3. [f4] in the style of the King's Gambit, or a slower game with 3. [g3], but the normal 3. [Bc4] will also be available, even though with great chances to transpose to some other opening, most likely to the Bishop's Opening.}) 2... Nf6 {The most common response from Black, just a standard developing move, and depending on which line White chooses, we can decide if we want to play with the knight on [c6] or play with ...[c6]!?. After 2. [Nf3] we don't have this luxury, because our opponent immediately attacks the [e5]-pawn, which we have to protect by playing 2...[Nc6].} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3] This is the Mieses variation, White would like to calmly develop their pieces and then play with [f4] at some moment. Since White is playing slowly, normally it means Black should have a lot of different ways to play, it is no different here, Black has quite a few reliable lines.} (3. Nf3 {has no independent value, it transposes back to 2. [Nf3] openings.} Nc6 {And we are in the Four Knights Game.}) 3... Bc5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] One of the main moves for Black, as I mentioned earlier in the course, I only like to play with ... [d5] and taking on [c3] with the knight, if that is clearly the way to go, but when there are alternatives, I usually prefer those.} ({So why not} 3... c6 $2 {I don't like that White has} 4. d4 $1 {, stopping our plan. This is one of the points behind ...[Bc5], that it controls the [d4]-square.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {And now it would be great to play ...[Nc6].}) 4. Bg2 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5] After castling, the next step is to play in the centre with ... [c6]-[d5].} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3] The main line, White wants to finish the regular setup of this variation.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc6d5] The most ambitious plan for Black, we want to take back on [d5] with a pawn and not with a piece!} 6. O-O (6. d4 {This move doesn't work nearly as well as after 3...[c6], since now it is not the queen which is coming to [d4], and also Black castled in the meantime, which provides an opportunity for an immediate strike in the centre.} exd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 {White already has to be very careful here.} 8. exd5 Bg4 {One more tempo!} 9. Nde2 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 cxd5 11. Qxd5 Nd7 {∞ White's position is very difficult, their king is staying in the centre for a while.}) 6... d5 7. exd5 cxd5 8. d4 $1 {Just like this! Otherwise White just gave up the centre for no reason.} exd4 9. Nxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Gg1][%cal Gc1g5,Gc1e3] Everything looks pretty good for White, they managed to castle, blockade our isolated pawn on [d5] and they are ready to develop the dark-squared bishop in the next move.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4d1] The key move of the whole variation. We have to provoke some weaknesses or gain some time and try to create active play.} 10. Qd3 ({•} 10. Qd2 Bxd4 {transposes.}) ({•} 10. f3 $6 {this is the weakening move, we were looking for when playing ...[Bg4].} Bd7 {⩱ White weakened the [g1]-[a7] diagonal, the [e3]-square, closed the bishop on [g2], with ...[Nc6] and ... [Qb6] to follow, we can put huge pressure on the [d4]-square and all of a sudden it is a very nice IQP-position for Black.}) ({•} 10. Nde2 {Was played by GM Adhiban against Kramnik a few years ago, but not particularly challenging for Black.} Qd7 {Both preventing [h3], and getting out of a potential pin in case of [Bg5].} 11. Bg5 Ne4 $1 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd7 Nxd7 14. Rfe1 f5 15. Rad1 Nb6 {With ...[Rac8] coming next, Black has no problems at all.}) 10... Bxd4 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd5d4] Another very important move! Black is giving up the bishop pair in order to speed up the development and make the IQP mobile.} 11. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gd5d4] The saying that the queen is the worst blockader is shown here immediately, once it is attacked it has to go away immediately and then the IQP can go forward.} 12. Qf4 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Yc1f4,Yf4g5] This is not a good square for the queen, because it blocks the [c1]-bishop's way, but it is nevertheless a somewhat tricky option for White.} Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gg2,Gg4][%cal Gd7g4,Yd5d4,Yg4h3,Yh3g2] Protecting the bishop, so making ...[d4] available again, and also introducing the ...[Bh3]-[Bxg2] plan, trading White's most active piece.} (12... d4 $6 {is the move White was waiting for!} 13. Ne4 $1 {Because the queen kept attacking the [g4]-bishop, now we are going to lose the bishop, and be slightly worse.} Nxe4 14. Qxg4 {⩲}) 13. Re1 (13. Bd2 {Not a very nice square, but White wants to finish the development somehow.} Rfd8 {...[d4] was already possible, but since White can't prevent it anyway, first we are activating the rooks.} 14. Rfe1 Rac8 {↑ We can even play ...[h6] next, just to open the back rank and then ...[d4] when it looks the most unpleasant for White.}) 13... Bh3 $1 {[%csl Gg2] Trading the light-squared bishops will make the light squares weaker in White's camp.} 14. b3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 d4 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gf6d5] The IQP is moving forward, making the nice [d5]-square available for the knight or for the queen.} 16. Ne2 ({Not ideal, but there is no better.} 16. Ne4 $4 {is already losing for White.} Nxe4 17. Rxe4 f5 18. Re1 Nb4 {-+}) 16... Rad8 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd8d4] Bringing a new piece and supporting the [d4]-pawn.} 17. Bb2 Qd5+ 18. Qf3 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Ya2,Yc2,Re2][%cal Ya5a2,Gc6e5,Gf8e8] Black is very active, White can have problems with protecting the pawns on [a2] and [c2] or at least that will keep their pieces very passive and our opponent also has to watch out for ...[Ne5] ideas, when if the queen leaves the long diagonal, and we can give a ...[Qd5] check, it could be pretty unpleasant.} *

