{19...bxc6?? Allows too many checks for White. 20.Qxc6+ Kf8 21.Qh6+ Kg8 22.Qxg5+ Kf8 23.Qh6+ Ke7 24.Qd6+ Ke8 25.Qc6+ It is a draw.} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. d4 $6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rh4e1] The Villemson Gambit. White is occupying the centre with their pawns, but the problem with the move is that 2. [f4] also weakened the [e1]-[h4] diagonal, so White's king is exposed to unpleasant checks.} Qh4+ {Of course! We are not waiting for [Nf3] and allow White's king to castle later.} 4. Ke2 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Ge2f2,Gg1f3,Gf1c4,Gh1e1,Gf2g1] White's idea is to play [Nf3] and then put the king to [f2], develop the light-squared bishop, play [Rf1] or [Re1] and then after [Kg1], the king would be completely safe. Of course, in the meantime, Black will also make some moves.} (4. Kd2 $2 {This is the alternative, but the king stands much worse in this square.} Qf2+ 5. Ne2 Nf6 6. Kd3 {Yes, White's position is that bad, that the king has to protect the pawn on [e4].} f3 7. Nf4 Nc6 8. c3 d5 $1 {-+ Opening up the position with a winning advantage for Black.}) 4... d5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc8g4] Opening the position against the king in the centre is not a bad idea! We are also intending to meet [Nf3] with ...[Bg4] now!} 5. e5 {Keeping the position closed looks logical, but White has other problems, too, they are down a pawn for example...} Bg4+ 6. Nf3 Nc6 {Putting some pressure on the [d4] and [e5]-squares while preparing to castle long.} 7. Bxf4 {White should try to take back the material, but the problem is that their king will be too active. 🙂} Bxf3+ 8. Kxf3 Nh6 $1 {Threatening to win the queen with ...[Qg4]+} 9. Qd2 (9. Bxh6 $2 {is just losing because of} Nxd4+ $1 10. Ke3 Bc5 {-+ With many unpleasant checks to follow, White is just lost here.}) 9... g5 $1 {Playing very energetically should work against a king which is on [f3].} 10. Be3 {White should protect the [d4]-pawn.} Nf5 {It is hanging again.} 11. g4 Bc5 $1 {And again! 🙂} 12. gxf5 ({•} 12. c3 {Doesn't help.} Nxe5+ 13. dxe5 Nxe3 {-+}) ({•} 12. Bxg5 $4 {Even though it is a tempo on the queen, Black is just giving checks and the game can end with a nice mate.} Nfxd4+ 13. Kf4 Ne6+ 14. Kf5 {White has to protect the [g5]-bishop.} Ncd4+ 15. Kf6 Be7#) ({•} 12. dxc5 $2 Nxe5+ 13. Ke2 Qxg4+ 14. Kf2 Qf3+ {+ -+ Black is winning back the material.}) 12... Nxd4+ 13. Bxd4 Qe4+ $1 14. Kg3 Bxd4 {Everything is hanging is White's position.} 15. Bb5+ c6 16. Re1 Qh4+ 17. Kg2 Bxb2 $19 {And we are winning material in the most unexpected way. 🙂} (17... Bxb2 {•} 18. e6 Bxa1 19. Qxd5 O-O $1 {-+ The king is safe and Black is winning more material.}) (17... Bxb2 {•} 18. Qxd5 Qxe1 19. Bxc6+ Kf8 $1 {The only winning move, but it is enough.} 20. Qd6+ Kg8 $1 {-+ No more checks, Black is completely winning.}) *

