1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. d4 $6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rh4e1] The Villemson Gambit. White is occupying the centre with their pawns, but the problem with the move is that 2. [f4] also weakened the [e1]-[h4] diagonal, so White's king is exposed to unpleasant checks.} Qh4+ {Of course! We are not waiting for [Nf3] and allow White's king to castle later.} 4. Ke2 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Ge2f2,Gg1f3,Gf1c4,Gh1e1,Gf2g1] White's idea is to play [Nf3] and then put the king to [f2], develop the light-squared bishop, play [Rf1] or [Re1] and then after [Kg1], the king would be completely safe. Of course, in the meantime, Black will also make some moves.} (4. Kd2 $2 {This is the alternative, but the king stands much worse in this square.} Qf2+ 5. Ne2 Nf6 6. Kd3 {Yes, White's position is that bad, that the king has to protect the pawn on [e4].} f3 7. Nf4 Nc6 8. c3 d5 $1 {-+ Opening up the position with a winning advantage for Black.}) 4... d5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc8g4] Opening the position against the king in the centre is not a bad idea! We are also intending to meet [Nf3] with ...[Bg4] now!} 5. exd5 {White is at least taking back the material this way, but of course the difference between the kings should provide Black a clear edge.} (5. Nf3 Bg4 $1 6. exd5 Nd7 {transposes.}) 5... Bg4+ 6. Nf3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gd8e8,Re8e2] Black has a couple of good alternatives, but I like the fact, that after this move we can castle any moment we want, and bring the rook into the play.} 7. Bxf4 {The only question, White will be at least up a pawn for the moment.} (7. c4 {White can try to hold onto material equality in this way, but their king will remain very weak.} O-O-O 8. Kd3 Qf6 {∓ It's hard to say how White should develop here, while Black has a very easy way, with moves like ...[g5]-[Bg7]-[Ne7]-[Nf5]-[Rhe8] and putting enormous pressure on White's position.}) 7... Bxf3+ $1 {[%cal Rh4f4] Forcing the king to [f3].} 8. Kxf3 Bd6 $1 {We have to play fast, and not allow White to stabilise their position.} 9. Bxd6 (9. Qe2+ {will not improve White's position much, and we can also cover this check with a developing move.} Ne7 10. Bxd6 cxd6 {And White can't keep the extra pawn.} 11. Qe4 Qh5+ 12. Qg4 Qxd5+ 13. Qe4 Qh5+ 14. Qg4 Qa5 {∓ White's king is still on [f3], and the material balance is restored.}) 9... Qh5+ $1 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Yg2g4,Rh5d1] Very important intermezzo! We will not only expose White's position even more, but also taking back the pawn along the way.} (9... cxd6 $6 {This line just shows that one inaccurate and automatic move can let the whole advantage slip away.} 10. Qd2 {⩲ The computer already prefers White!}) 10. g4 Qxd5+ 11. Kf2 Qxd6 $17 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Yh7h5,Yg8f6,Ge8c8] Black has a huge advantage, we will castle long and start an attack against White's king.} *

