1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nc3 $6 {[%cal Rh4e1]} ({This variation is the Mason Gambit, the problems are similar like in the} 3. d4 {line, White is allowing ...[Qh4]+, but at least our opponent develops a piece now.}) 3... Qh4+ {Again, there is no reason not to give this check.} 4. Ke2 {[%cal Gg1f3]} d5 $1 {[%cal Yg1f3,Gc8g4] This move is the key once again, meeting [Nf3] with ...[Bg4] is crucial for Black.} 5. Nxd5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7] The game is getting sharp, White also has some threats now.} (5. Nf3 $2 {inaccurate move order from White!} Qe7 $1 {...[Bg4] is also good, and would just transpose to 5. [Nxd5], but this is even better, now White can't take on [d5], because of ... [Qxe4]+.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. e5 d4 {-+ With ...[Nc6] or ...[Nd5] coming next, White is completely lost here.}) 5... Bg4+ {This is logical, we are developing with a check.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc6d4,Yc6e5]} ({The alternative is} 6... Bd6 {, which is more materialistic and clearly worse than the text. We go for the attack and don't care about the rook on [a8].}) 7. Nxc7+ {White has to take some material, otherwise Black is just attacking for free.} ({•} 7. d4 $2 {Instead of the rook, White goes for the [f4]-pawn.} O-O-O 8. Bxf4 Nf6 $1 {This very strong move highlights the weakness of White's central pawns.} 9. Bg3 Qh6 {-+ White is completely lost, our opponent can't keep the centre together.}) ({•} 7. c3 $2 O-O-O {∓ The attack will continue with material equality. We can consider moves like ...[f5] or ...[Nge7] next.}) 7... Kd8 8. Nxa8 Ne5 {[%cal Re5f3,Yg2f3,Rg4f3,Rh4h5] The threat is to take twice on [f3] first with the knight and then win White's queen by playing [Qh5]+. Now you can also see why we played ...[Kd8] in the previous move and not [Kd7], if we go along with the line we are threatening with and on ...[Qh5]+, White plays [Kg2]-[Qxd1], then at the end of the story there is [Bb5] discovered check and White is taking our queen with a winning position.} 9. h3 {[%cal Re5f3,Gh3g4]} (9. h3 {White is preventing our idea, since they want to meet} Nxf3 {with} 10. hxg4 $1) 9... Bh5 $1 ({Instead} 9... Bxf3+ {only leads to a perpetual, but our position is much better here.}) 10. d4 {With this move White is forcing Black to win the queen, and well, why not?} Nxf3 11. gxf3 Bxf3+ 12. Kxf3 Qh5+ {[%csl Rd1][%cal Rh5d1]} 13. Kg2 Qxd1 14. Bd3 Qh5 (14... f3+ $4 {Would trap our own queen. 🙂} 15. Kh2 {+-}) 15. Bxf4 Ne7 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gg7g5,Ge7g6,Gg6h4,Gg6f4] White doesn't even have enough material for the queen, and we also have a very effective way of continuing the game with ...[g5]-[Ng6]-[Nf4] and White's king will remain in danger.} *

