1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nc3 $6 {[%cal Rh4e1]} ({This variation is the Mason Gambit, the problems are similar like in the} 3. d4 {line, White is allowing ...[Qh4]+, but at least our opponent develops a piece now.}) 3... Qh4+ {Again, there is no reason not to give this check.} 4. Ke2 {[%cal Gg1f3]} d5 $1 {[%cal Yg1f3,Gc8g4] This move is the key once again, meeting [Nf3] with ...[Bg4] is crucial for Black.} 5. Nxd5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7] The game is getting sharp, White also has some threats now.} (5. Nf3 $2 {inaccurate move order from White!} Qe7 $1 {...[Bg4] is also good, and would just transpose to 5. [Nxd5], but this is even better, now White can't take on [d5], because of ... [Qxe4]+.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. e5 d4 {-+ With ...[Nc6] or ...[Nd5] coming next, White is completely lost here.}) 5... Bg4+ {This is logical, we are developing with a check.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Yc6d4,Yc6e5]} ({The alternative is} 6... Bd6 {, which is more materialistic and clearly worse than the text. We go for the attack and don't care about the rook on [a8].}) 7. Nxc7+ {White has to take some material, otherwise Black is just attacking for free.} ({•} 7. d4 $2 {Instead of the rook, White goes for the [f4]-pawn.} O-O-O 8. Bxf4 Nf6 $1 {This very strong move highlights the weakness of White's central pawns.} 9. Bg3 Qh6 {-+ White is completely lost, our opponent can't keep the centre together.}) ({•} 7. c3 $2 O-O-O {∓ The attack will continue with material equality. We can consider moves like ...[f5] or ...[Nge7] next.}) 7... Kd8 8. Nxa8 Ne5 {[%cal Re5f3,Yg2f3,Rg4f3,Rh4h5] The threat is to take twice on [f3] first with the knight and then win White's queen by playing [Qh5]+. Now you can also see why we played ...[Kd8] in the previous move and not [Kd7], if we go along with the line we are threatening with and on ...[Qh5]+, White plays [Kg2]-[Qxd1], then at the end of the story there is [Bb5] discovered check and White is taking our queen with a winning position.} 9. Qe1 {This is the most common move, White is not going to lose the queen here, but should enter an endgame where they will soon be down on material as well.} Nxf3 10. Qxh4+ (10. gxf3 $4 {Would still lose the queen.} Bxf3+ {+ -+}) 10... Nxh4+ 11. Ke1 g5 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Gf4][%cal Gg5f4,Yd8b8] We have time to pick up the knight on [a8], the most important for now is to stabilise our kingside, so White will not be able to create counterplay.} 12. d3 Kc8 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gc8b8,Gb8a8] The knight is trapped on [a8].} 13. Bd2 (13. g3 {White is trying to create some play on the kingside, and undermine our strong [f4]-pawn.} Nf3+ 14. Kf2 Bc5+ 15. Kg2 Ne1# {Oops.}) 13... Kb8 14. Bc3 f6 15. Nb6 axb6 $17 {[%csl Ra1,Rh1][%cal Gf8e7,Gg8h6] We are going to finish the development with ...[Be7] and ...[Nh6], and will have a clear advantage with the minor pieces, since it is not clear where White's rooks can find some play in the near future.} *

