1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7] The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. After studying the previous lines and worse moves for White, we can understand that one of the ideas of the move is to prepare a square for the king on [f1], so it shouldn't stand awkwardly on [e2] and stop the development of almost White's whole army. Otherwise the move is also very useful against Black's typical central break, ...[d5], and it also puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. e5 $2 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge5f6] Very logical, immediately challenging the knight on [f6], but fortunately it doesn't work too well.} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc8g4,Rd5c4] By now we can say that our first reaction against White's [e5] move should not to be to move the attacked piece, but to counterattack with ...[d5]! and acquire presence in the centre and also open the light-square bishop.} 5. Bb3 ({•} 5. Bb5+ c6 6. exf6 {This is a slightly improved version of 5. [exf6], because the queen will be able to take a few pawns on the queenside.} cxb5 7. Qe2+ Be6 8. Qxb5+ Nc6 9. Qxb7 Nd4 {-+ Really just slightly improved. 🙂 It is not clear how White will defend the pawn on [c2].}) ({•} 5. exf6 $2 dxc4 6. Qe2+ Be6 {-+ This position is awful for White, the bishop pair will dominate the game.}) 5... Bg4 {Developing with a tempo can't be too bad.} 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. d3 Bxf3 $1 {[%cal Rd8h4] Preparing ...[Qh4]+ and winning some material.} 8. Qxf3 Qh4+ {[%csl Rh1]} (8... Qh4+ {White is losing the rook on h1, or the whole kingside if they prefer to play with} 9. g3 fxg3 {.}) 9. Ke2 Ng3+ 10. hxg3 Qxh1 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Rh1c1]} 11. Nd2 ({•} 11. Bxf4 c6 {Protecting [d5].} 12. Nc3 {White has no choice. Even though they are down an exchange, they have to sacrifice more to get closer to Black's king.} Qxa1 13. Nxd5 Bb4 $1 {Threatening mate in one and also preparing to castle.} 14. Nxb4 O-O {-+ White doesn't have enough play for being two exchanges down.}) ({•} 11. Qxd5 Qh5+ {11...[Qxc1] is even better, but this is safer. Protecting [f7] with tempo, and then eventually protect [b7].} 12. Kd2 c6 {-+ White is down an exchange for no compensation.}) 11... Nc6 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8] O-O-O is coming next, Black is much better and up an exchange.} *

