1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7] The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. After studying the previous lines and worse moves for White, we can understand that one of the ideas of the move is to prepare a square for the king on [f1], so it shouldn't stand awkwardly on [e2] and stop the development of almost White's whole army. Otherwise the move is also very useful against Black's typical central break, ...[d5], and it also puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. Qe2 $2 {[%csl Re8][%cal Yd7d5,Ye4d5,Ge2e8] This move is aimed against ...[d5], but White can't prevent it for long, and then the queen will be just misplaced on [e2].} Bb4 $1 ({Very clever move by the comp!} 4... Bc5 {is also good obviously, but then with} 5. Nf3 {White can win some time because [d4] is a threat.}) 5. e5 {Now we don't have the usual ...[d5]! to counter this move, but we can take advantage of the queen's placement on [e2].} O-O $1 {[%cal Rf8e8,Re8e1]} 6. c3 {We have two pieces hanging now, but we are not going to move them. 🙂} d5 $1 {With some delay, but against [e5], ...[d5] is still coming.} 7. Bb3 Nc6 $1 {Development over material!} 8. cxb4 Re8 {All of our pieces are coming into the game, while White's extra pieces are just standing in the back rank.} 9. Nf3 Nxe5 10. O-O {White managed to castle, but the assault continues.} (10. Nxe5 {White is two pieces up at the moment, but Black is starting to regain material with the next move.} Bg4 $1 {The queen has to go and can't protect the knight on [e5].} 11. Qf2 Rxe5+ 12. Kf1 Ne4 {Four pieces are attacking White's king, which doesn't have much of a help.} 13. Qd4 Qh4 {-+ Black has many threats, the simplest is ...[Ng3]+.}) 10... Bg4 11. Qxe5 (11. Qd1 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Bh3 {-+ Once the queen is coming to [g5], the game is over.}) 11... Rxe5 12. Nxe5 Qd6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1] White has enough material for the queen, but they are not in time to use that material.} 13. d4 Qb6 14. Rxf4 Re8 $19 {And White can't keep their position together.} (14... Re8 {•} 15. Nxg4 Re1+ 16. Rf1 Rxf1+ 17. Kxf1 Nxg4 {-+ White is doing fine materially speaking, but there is no help for the king, so the queen+knight should win the game. ( • 15.Kh1 Going away from the diagonal, so defending against ...[Rxe5]. 15...g5! Black is forcing away the rook, and wins the [d4]-pawn. 16.Rf1 Be2! Forcing the rook to a worse square. 17.Re1 Rxe5! 18.dxe5 Qf2 19.Bd2 Bf1 -+ And White has to resign. )}) *

