1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7] The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. After studying the previous lines and worse moves for White, we can understand that one of the ideas of the move is to prepare a square for the king on [f1], so it shouldn't stand awkwardly on [e2] and stop the development of almost White's whole army. Otherwise the move is also very useful against Black's typical central break, ...[d5], and it also puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Yc3d5] The main move by far, White is protecting the pawn on [e4], and at the same time also controlling the crucial [d5]-square.} (4. d3 $6 {White wants to take back the pawn on [f4].} d5 $1 {Opening up the position for our pieces, and also defending the [f4]-pawn along the way.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 {A very clever move by the engine! The point is that we are provoking [c3], so White can't develop their knight there anymore, and also weakening the light squares in White's position, which is very important since the only way to take back the pawn on [f4], will be via [Bxd5] and [Bxf4], so White will have to trade the light-squared bishop.} 7. c3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bxd5 Qxd5 10. Bxf4 Be6 {⩱ Black has a pleasant edge with the pair of bishops, ...[c5]-[Nc6] can be our next couple of moves. We also set a small trap, the [c7]-pawn is not hanging because it is defended by ...[Qc5]+ picking up the bishop.}) 4... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Rb4c3,Yf6e4,Gd7d5] A logical developing move, challenging the [c3]-knight and therefore renewing the pressure on the [e4] and [d5]-squares. However, it is just the second most popular one, far behind the also very logical 4...[c6]. After analysing these options, I didn't find significant difference in their objective value, so I decided to recommend the one which is less explored.} 5. Nge2 {[%csl Gc3,Ye2,Gf3][%cal Ge2c3,Ge2f3] White is ready to replace the knight on [c3], but still it looks like some sort of concession, since the knight's best and most active square is obviously on [f3].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re2] Excellent move, the whole idea works, because of White's unfortunate knight on [e2].} (5... Nxe4 {This looks very strong, but the computer already slightly prefers White, after the strong,} 6. O-O $1 O-O 7. Nxf4 {∞ And White has excellent compensation on the semi-open f-file.}) 6. exd5 (6. Nxd5 $4 {This move is just a disaster for White, it does nothing else than clearing the Black's queen's way towards [h4].} Nxd5 7. Bxd5 Qh4+ 8. Kf1 (8. g3 fxg3 9. Nxg3 Bg4 {-+ The queen is trapped on [d1]!}) 8... f3 {Making the king even more open.} 9. gxf3 Bh3+ 10. Kg1 Nd7 {→ Black has a completely winning attack according to the computer, and it is hard to argue.}) 6... f3 $1 {[%csl Re1] Destroying White's kingside structure, so the king will be not safe, even if it manages to castle.} 7. gxf3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Rb6c4,Rb6d5] With the idea of ...[Nb6] and taking back the missing pawn on [d5].} 8. d3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd3c4] By protecting the bishop in advance, White is preparing to meet ...[Nb6] with [Bg5]! so they may keep the extra pawn on [d5].} (8. d4 {This is the best move according to the machine, but here it is very simple to take back the material and have the better chances for Black.} Nb6 9. Bb3 Nfxd5 {We regained the pawn, and will keep the better chances thanks to our better structure and safer king.} 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bd6 {⩱ ( 9.Bb5+ Doesn't help much. 9...Bd7 And the [d5]-pawn will fall anyway. )}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gf6d5] Now Black is threatening to take the pawn on [d5], so it is time for White to pin our knight!} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg5d8]} Be7 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Rf6d5] By neutralising the pin, we are again threatening to take on [d5].} 11. Bxf6 ({This is the only way to keep the extra material.} 11. Nf4 {has a tactical problem.} Nfxd5 $1 {And the knight is defending the bishop on [e7].} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 {∓}) 11... Bxf6 {[%csl Rc4,Gc8,Re2,Gf6,Rg1] We have excellent play for the missing pawn, in fact the computer already gives a pretty significant edge for Black. Let's see a few examples, how the game can possibly continue.} 12. Kh1 c6 $1 {Opening up the position for our bishops.} 13. dxc6 Nxc4 $1 {Gaining the pair of bishops, and also that [c4]-bishop was just about the get more active.} 14. cxb7 {With this intermediate move, White will be even up 2 pawns for the moment.} (14. dxc4 bxc6 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 {⩱ With ...[Bf5] and ...[Rab8] coming, we will put White's queenside under fire.}) 14... Bxb7 15. dxc4 Rc8 16. Qd3 Be5 $15 {With the threat of ...[Qh4], so White is basically forced to take on [d8], and then we reach a very instructive position, which I would suggest you to analyse yourself somewhat further, to see how strong the bishops are in an open position.} *

