1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7] The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. After studying the previous lines and worse moves for White, we can understand that one of the ideas of the move is to prepare a square for the king on [f1], so it shouldn't stand awkwardly on [e2] and stop the development of almost White's whole army. Otherwise the move is also very useful against Black's typical central break, ...[d5], and it also puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Yc3d5] The main move by far, White is protecting the pawn on [e4], and at the same time also controlling the crucial [d5]-square.} (4. d3 $6 {White wants to take back the pawn on [f4].} d5 $1 {Opening up the position for our pieces, and also defending the [f4]-pawn along the way.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 {A very clever move by the engine! The point is that we are provoking [c3], so White can't develop their knight there anymore, and also weakening the light squares in White's position, which is very important since the only way to take back the pawn on [f4], will be via [Bxd5] and [Bxf4], so White will have to trade the light-squared bishop.} 7. c3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bxd5 Qxd5 10. Bxf4 Be6 {⩱ Black has a pleasant edge with the pair of bishops, ...[c5]-[Nc6] can be our next couple of moves. We also set a small trap, the [c7]-pawn is not hanging because it is defended by ...[Qc5]+ picking up the bishop.}) 4... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Rb4c3,Yf6e4,Gd7d5] A logical developing move, challenging the [c3]-knight and therefore renewing the pressure on the [e4] and [d5]-squares. However, it is just the second most popular one, far behind the also very logical 4...[c6]. After analysing these options, I didn't find significant difference in their objective value, so I decided to recommend the one which is less explored.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Rd5,Re4,Gf3] This is the more active square for the knight, however it doesn't do much about the critical [e4] and [d5]-squares in the centre, and Black can take advantage of it.} O-O 6. O-O Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5] Typical and very strong!} 7. Nxe4 (7. Nd5 {The idea of White is to force our bishop to the awkward [d6]-square, and while it still seems to be good for Black, I like how Black met this move in practice all the time.} c6 $1 {With this small tactical trick, we keep our development fluent.} 8. Nxb4 Qb6+ 9. d4 Qxb4 10. Bd3 d5 11. Bxf4 Bf5 {∓ With a very solid extra pawn for Black. ( 9.Kh1 Doesn't change much, Black will be able to play ...[d5] anyway. 9...Qxb4 10.d3 d5 11.Bb3 Nf6 ∓)}) 7... d5 8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. d3 Bf5 {Simply continuing the development, since we should have made some really awkward move to protect on [f4] anyways.} 10. Bxf4 Bxe4 11. dxe4 Qxe4 12. Bxc7 Na6 $36 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Ra6c7] The position is equal, but White still has to solve some problems with their coordination to be comfortably equal.} *

