1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf1,Rf7][%cal Yd8h4,Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Gc4f7] The Bishop's Gambit. One of the two main moves for White. After studying the previous lines and worse moves for White, we can understand that one of the ideas of the move is to prepare a square for the king on [f1], so it shouldn't stand awkwardly on [e2] and stop the development of almost White's whole army. Otherwise the move is also very useful against Black's typical central break, ...[d5], and it also puts pressure on the [f7]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Yd7d5,Ge8g8] This is the main line for Black, there are many alternatives as well, but I liked those much less. The goal of ...[Nf6] is clear, we are attacking the [e4]-pawn, helping with the ...[d5]-break, and also getting one move closer to castling, which is never a bad thing against the King's Gambit.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Yc3d5] The main move by far, White is protecting the pawn on [e4], and at the same time also controlling the crucial [d5]-square.} (4. d3 $6 {White wants to take back the pawn on [f4].} d5 $1 {Opening up the position for our pieces, and also defending the [f4]-pawn along the way.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 {A very clever move by the engine! The point is that we are provoking [c3], so White can't develop their knight there anymore, and also weakening the light squares in White's position, which is very important since the only way to take back the pawn on [f4], will be via [Bxd5] and [Bxf4], so White will have to trade the light-squared bishop.} 7. c3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bxd5 Qxd5 10. Bxf4 Be6 {⩱ Black has a pleasant edge with the pair of bishops, ...[c5]-[Nc6] can be our next couple of moves. We also set a small trap, the [c7]-pawn is not hanging because it is defended by ...[Qc5]+ picking up the bishop.}) 4... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Rb4c3,Yf6e4,Gd7d5] A logical developing move, challenging the [c3]-knight and therefore renewing the pressure on the [e4] and [d5]-squares. However, it is just the second most popular one, far behind the also very logical 4...[c6]. After analysing these options, I didn't find significant difference in their objective value, so I decided to recommend the one which is less explored.} 5. e5 d5 $1 {Just like this! Otherwise we would be even in trouble.} 6. Bb5+ (6. Bb5+ {The critical test of the variation. Black normally plays} c6 {here, but after} 7. exf6 cxb5 8. fxg7 Rg8 9. Nf3 {White seems to have the advantage, because our pawn structure is less than ideal on the queenside.}) ({•} 6. exf6 $2 {White is losing the whole centre and the pair of bishops after this unfortunate capture.} dxc4 7. fxg7 Rg8 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O Rxg7 {∓ Black will castle long, and is very close to winning.}) ({•} 6. Bb3 $6 {White is hoping to get the [d5]-pawn once the [f6]-knight moves, but Black can create a strong counter threat.} Ne4 $1 {With ...[Qh4]+ in the air, White is obviously not in time to take on [d5].} 7. Nf3 c6 {And now we are just stabilising on [d5], cutting the [b3]-bishop out of the game.} 8. Qe2 Bf5 9. O-O O-O 10. Nd1 {With the idea of [d3] and taking back the pawn on [f4].} Be7 {Preparing the [c5]-square for the knight, the bishop could be extremely weird out there, once the knight blocks its way back.} 11. d3 Nc5 12. Bxf4 a5 $1 {∓ Black's pieces are much more active and the threat of ...[a4]! is also not easy to meet.}) 6... Nfd7 $1 {This rare move seems to work very well though! There are some okay, rather a lot of complications, but the machine prefers Black everywhere.} 7. Nxd5 {The only question, otherwise Black plays ...[c6] and solidifies the position.} Ba5 {[%cal Rc7c6,Rc6b5,Rc6d5,Gd8h4] The main threat is ...[c6], but ...[Qh4]+ is also in the air. The position is pretty much completely unexplored, there were only 3 OTB games from here on.} 8. e6 {[%cal Yf7e6,Gd1h5] Not really worse than the other moves in the position, but it is a very unlikely move from a human.} Qh4+ $1 ({White's idea was to meet} 8... fxe6 {with} 9. Qh5+ {, I would rather avoid that and force White's king to move.}) 9. Kf1 (9. g3 {Fortunately it doesn't work, but not so obvious why.} fxg3 10. exd7+ Bxd7 11. Bxd7+ {(11.Qe2+ Kd8 -+ Also wins for Black, as ... [g2] is coming. )} Kxd7 12. Kf1 {The only way to prevent ...[g2], but now Black can take back the knight on [d5] and have a big advantage.} g2+ $1 13. Kxg2 Qg5+ 14. Kf2 Qxd5 {-+}) 9... fxe6 10. Qe2 O-O {There are other good options for Black, I tried to find the safest solution and suggest it to you.} 11. Nf3 Qd8 12. Qxe6+ Kh8 {White is facing a lot of threats, like ...[c6] or ...[Nc5], they have only one move not to be losing here.} 13. b4 $1 a6 $1 {It is very important to know this move!} (13... Bb6 $2 14. Ne7 $1 {With the threat of [Ng6]+, Black is in a big trouble here. For example,} Re8 15. Ng6+ hxg6 16. Qh3+ Kg8 17. Bc4+ Kf8 18. Bb2 {+- And Black is getting checkmated.}) 14. bxa5 ({•} 14. Bd3 Nc5 $1 {∓}) ({•} 14. Bc4 Nb6 $1 {∓}) ({•} 14. Be2 Nc6 $1 15. bxa5 Nde5 {-+ Trapping the queen!}) 14... axb5 $15 {[%cal Gd7f6] With ...[Nf6] coming next, White has no activity anymore and is just worse.} *

