lot of complications, but the machine prefers Black everywhere.} 7. Nxd5 {The only question, otherwise Black plays ...[c6] and solidifies the position.} Ba5 {[%cal Rc7c6,Rc6b5,Rc6d5,Gd8h4] The main threat is ...[c6], but ...[Qh4]+ is also in the air. The position is pretty much completely unexplored, there were only 3 OTB games from here on.} 8. b4 {Definitely the most challenging move for Black.} c6 $1 {[%csl Re5] A key move! Otherwise, White can keep the pawn on [e5] and has the advantage.} (8... Bb6 $2 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Nf3 {±}) 9. bxa5 (9. e6 {Almost everything is hanging. 🙂} Ne5 $1 10. Nxf4 O-O {∞ Black's king is much safer, therefore we can be very optimistic about the future.}) {10.exf7+ Kxf7 11.Nxf4 (11.Qh5+? g6! -+) 11...Re8 And it is again Black, who has the initiative. 12.Be2 Bb6 ∓ White's king is in a lot of trouble. ( 12.bxa5 Nd3+ 13.Kf1 Re1+ 14.Qxe1 Nxe1 15.Bc4+! This was White's point, but Black also has some idea. 🙂 15...Ke8 16.Kxe1 Qd4 ∓ Three pieces are hanging for White, Black will be up on material. )} 9... Nxe5 $1 {[%cal Rc6b5,Rc6d5] The pawn is more important than the pieces, since White can't save both of those anyway. But the pawn on [e5] could have been protected.} ({•} 9... cxd5 10. Qh5 O-O 11. Nf3 {± White keeps the [e5]-pawn and the better position.}) ({•} 9... cxb5 10. d4 $1 Qxa5+ 11. c3 {± Again White is much better, Black has no centre at all.}) 10. Nxf4 {[%cal Gd2d4] White didn't only remove one of their pieces from the fork, but also threatens to play [d4].} Qd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4f4,Rd4a1,Rc6b5]} (10... cxb5 {is also playable, but this move gives an advantage for Black.}) 11. Ba3 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ga3f8] Keeping Black's king in the centre looks like a tempting option for White.} (11. Nh5 O-O $1 {Finally our king is in safety. (11...Qxa1?? This is way too greedy! 12.Nxg7+ Kd7 13.d4 +- This could end very badly for Black. )} 12. Ba3 Ng4 13. Nh3 cxb5 14. Bxf8 Qe5+ 15. Kf1 Kxf8 {∓ Black is down an exchange, but White's king is weak, their piece coordination is awful, while our play is very easy with ...[Nc6]-[Bf5]-[Re8] coming.}) {12.c3 White is protecting the rook on [a1] with a tempo, but still can't keep all the material. 12...Qh4+ 13.g3 Qe4+ 14.Qe2 Bf5! -+ The last precise move! (14...Qxh1?? Would lead to a funny draw. 15.Qxe5 Qxg1+ 16.Bf1! f6 17.Qe7 Rf7 18.Qe8+ Rf8 19.Qe7=)} 11... Qxf4 12. Be2 Qe4 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Re4g2] Not so easy to address the attack on the [g2]-square.} 13. d4 $1 {This tactical solution looks like the best try from White, but Black can switch plans now.} Nc4 $1 {[%cal Rc4a3] White can't keep the dark-squared bishop on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal, so Black will be able to castle.} (13... Qxg2 14. dxe5 Qxh1 15. Qd4 Qd5 16. Qc3 {∞ This is a big mess, where White has chances.}) 14. Bc1 (14. Bc5 b6 {∓}) 14... O-O ({Would be still early, giving White some activity.} 14... Qxg2 15. Bf3 Qg6 16. Ne2 Qd6 17. Qd3 {∞}) 15. Nf3 Re8 $15 {[%csl Ra5] Black has a solid advantage with the better pawn structure.} *

