1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rf1,Yf4][%cal Gc1f4] White is occupying the centre with their pawns and also plans to take with the bishop on [f4] in the next move. The only possible problem with this move is that it neglects our ...[Bh4]+ idea. If White takes that seriously, then they have to move the bishop from [f1] and prepare the [f1]-square for the king.} Bh4+ $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ye1d2,Ye1e2] This is the idea behind 3...[Be7], we are forcing White's king to a less than ideal square.} 5. Ke2 {[%cal Gc1f4] The most common move, White is ready to play [Bxf4] in the next move.} d5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc8g4] Opening the way for the bishop to [g4] and also in case White takes the pawn on [d5], the e-file is opening for their king.} 6. e5 {Better than taking the pawn, but still a very sad position for White.} (6. exd5 Bg4 7. Bxf4 Nf6 8. c4 {White keeps an extra pawn, but that's all the positives that can be said about our opponent's position.} O-O {→ With a huge attack for Black.} 9. g3 Nh5 $1 {And Black is already winning some material.}) 6... Bg4 7. Bxf4 f6 $1 {[%csl Re2] Very thematic play, opening the centre for the king in the middle.} 8. g3 fxe5 9. Bxe5 Bf6 $17 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge8g8] The position is pretty even, the only difference is that Black can castle, and White can't. 🙂} *

