1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rf1,Yf4][%cal Gc1f4] White is occupying the centre with their pawns and also plans to take with the bishop on [f4] in the next move. The only possible problem with this move is that it neglects our ...[Bh4]+ idea. If White takes that seriously, then they have to move the bishop from [f1] and prepare the [f1]-square for the king.} Bh4+ $1 {[%cal Ye1d2] This is the idea behind 3...[Be7], we are forcing White's king to a less than ideal square.} 5. Kd2 {It sounds extremely weird, but White is planning to move the king to the queenside, playing [c4] and [Kc2].} Be7 {The bishop has done its job, it is time to retreat and prepare for ...[Nf6].} 6. c4 {Clears the [c2] square for the king.} Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O {So far, Black has developed normally.} 8. Kc2 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] White's position doesn't look too bad, they have a strong centre and they are just about to take back the pawn on [f4].} b5 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] A fascinating idea from the machine. White's king will not be safe on the queenside, and Black will start attacking White's center as well.} 9. Bxf4 d5 $1 {[%cal Rb5c4,Rd5e4] Stockfish is strong! The material is not important, as long as the files and diagonals are open around White's King.} (9... bxc4 10. d5 $1 {It closes and controls the center, and White is more or less okay here.}) 10. exd5 (10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 f5 $1 {∓ One more break. But White is not getting a break. 🙂}) 10... c6 {[%cal Rb5c4,Rc6d5,Gc8f5] Black has compensation for the pawn with fantastic play on the queenside. Both White's king and centre are under pressure.} *

