1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gd2d4,Gc1f4] White is saying that without the ...[d5] option, ...[Bh4]+ in itself is not such a big deal, and otherwise [d4] and [Bxf4] is coming.} Bh4+ 5. Ke2 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4] White is completely right! Without ...[d5] it is a pretty okay position, but we can do it even as a pawn sacrifice. Kinda, since we are up a pawn currently.} 6. Nxd5 Bg4 {[%csl Gg4,Gh4][%cal Rh4e1,Rg4d1] Quite unusual, but effective placement of our bishops.} 7. d3 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gc1f4] The best move from White, giving some stability to the centre.} ({•} 7. Nxf4 $2 Qd4 $1 8. g3 (8. d3 $4 {Not so good...} Qf2#) 8... Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Qxf4 10. gxh4 Nc6 {∓ White's position looks very bad.}) ({•} 7. h3 $2 Bxf3+ 8. gxf3 g5 $1 {∓ The next move is ...[c6] and White has not much besides a weak king in the centre.}) 7... Nf6 $1 {Just bringing new pieces into the game, not being concerned if we will be down a pawn for a while or not.} 8. Nxf4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] New piece and new threats are coming into the game.} 9. Be3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ge3d4]} (9. c3 $6 {Covers the [d4]-square, but much more importantly weakens the [c2]-[d3]-[e4] chain, which is the main defensive line of White's position.} Qe7 {∞} 10. g3 g5 11. Bh3 Bxf3+ 12. Kxf3 gxf4 13. gxh4 Ne5+ 14. Ke2 Rd8 {-+ And eventually White falls apart on [d3].}) 9... g5 {[%csl Rf4] Our pieces are in the game, it is time to push the pawns and create some concrete threats.} 10. Nh3 Bxf3+ 11. gxf3 g4 {[%csl Re2] We are getting closer to White's king.} 12. Ng1 Qe7 {[%csl Re2,Rf1,Rg1,Rh1][%cal Ge8c8,Gh7h5,Gf6d7,Gd7e5] We are going to castle long in the next move, and continue putting pressure on White's position.} *

