1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gd2d4,Gc1f4] White is saying that without the ...[d5] option, ...[Bh4]+ in itself is not such a big deal, and otherwise [d4] and [Bxf4] is coming.} Bh4+ 5. Ke2 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4] White is completely right! Without ...[d5] it is a pretty okay position, but we can do it even as a pawn sacrifice. Kinda, since we are up a pawn currently.} 6. Nxd5 Bg4 {[%cal Rh4e1,Rg4d1] Quite unusual, but effective placement of our bishops.} 7. d4 {The most common move in OTB chess, but it is too ambitious. Both the [d4]-pawn and especially the [e4]-pawn will be very loose.} Nf6 {Targeting the [e4]-pawn.} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. c3 {White tries to stabilise the center a bit.} Nd7 10. Qd2 g5 $17 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4][%cal Ge8c8,Yh8e8] With moves like ...[O-O-O]-[c5]-[Rhe8] coming next, White will struggle a lot to keep their position together.} *

