1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. d3 $6 {[%cal Gc1f4] Very slow, and allows ...[d5].} d5 $1 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Yc4,Gf4][%cal Gd5f4,Yc4d5,Yb1c3,Yb2c3] It is a nice bonus for Black, that the knight is protecting the pawn on [f4] with this recapture, and White can only take that pawn back, by either giving up their light-squared bishop or compromising their structure with [Nc3]-[Nxc3].} 7. Bxd5 {White is taking back the pawn, even though by losing the pair of bishops our opponent can't claim full equality anyways.} Qxd5 8. Bxf4 g5 $1 {Especially not after this very strong move!} 9. Bg3 (9. Bxc7 $2 {Loses a lot of material.} g4 10. Nc3 {( • 10.Nfd2 Qxg2 11.Rf1 Bh4+ 12.Bg3 Qxh2! -+) ( • 10.Bxb8 gxf3 -+)} Qe6+ {+ -+}) 9... g4 {[%cal Rd5g2]} 10. Nc3 ({Otherwise the g2-pawn is falling.} 10. Nh4 Qd8 $1 {-+}) 10... Qe6+ 11. Ne5 f6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Re6e1] White will have some compensation, but certainly not enough for a full piece.} 12. O-O fxe5 13. d4 Rf8 14. Bxe5 Na6 $17 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge8c8] ...[Bd7] and [O-O-O] is coming very fast.} *

