1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. d3 $6 {[%cal Gc1f4] Very slow, and allows ...[d5].} d5 $1 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Yc4,Gf4][%cal Gd5f4,Yc4d5,Yb1c3,Yb2c3] It is a nice bonus for Black, that the knight is protecting the pawn on [f4] with this recapture, and White can only take that pawn back, by either giving up their light-squared bishop or compromising their structure with [Nc3]-[Nxc3].} 7. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Ge8c8,Ge8g8] There was nothing wrong with castling short, Black already has a very comfortable position, but this move order is a little bit more ambitious and flexible, White has to count on ...[O-O-O] sometimes.} 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {White's structure is weakened, and we can even transform this advantage by taking the strong [c4]-bishop.} Na5 $1 10. Bb3 Nxb3 11. axb3 O-O (11... g5 $5 {May be objectively better than, ...[O-O], but it is 10 times more complicated, which is very unnecessary at this moment, since we have a good position already.} 12. h4 h6 {⩱}) 12. Bxf4 a5 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga5a4,Ga8a6,Ya6h6] Against White's unusual structure on the queenside, we have the way to create a passed pawn by playing ...[b5]-[a4], and our rook can also join via the 6th rank in case it is needed.} *

