1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. d3 $6 {[%cal Gc1f4] Very slow, and allows ...[d5].} d5 $1 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Yc4,Gf4][%cal Gd5f4,Yc4d5,Yb1c3,Yb2c3] It is a nice bonus for Black, that the knight is protecting the pawn on [f4] with this recapture, and White can only take that pawn back, by either giving up their light-squared bishop or compromising their structure with [Nc3]-[Nxc3].} 7. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Ge8c8,Ge8g8] There was nothing wrong with castling short, Black already has a very comfortable position, but this move order is a little bit more ambitious and flexible, White has to count on ...[O-O-O] sometimes.} 8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Bxf4 Bg4 10. Bxc7 (10. Nc3 {Doesn't really ask any questions, we are just protecting the pawn on [c7], and have a very comfortable game.} Qd7 11. h3 Bh5 {Obviously not giving up the pair of bishops for no reason. 🙂} 12. Qd2 O-O {⩱ If instead 12...O-O-O , then maybe 13.Nb5! could have posed some problems, but now Black is simply better with the pair of bishops, we will play moves like ...[Kh8], ... [Rae8]-[Bd8] and don't mind any trades which doesn't involve our bishops.}) 10... Qc5+ {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rc5c7,Rc5g1] Putting the X-ray to the bishop with a tempo.} 11. d4 ({A sad necessity, White has to go for a worse endgame.} 11. Kh1 $2 Nd4 $1 {Double attack on [c2] and [c7].} 12. c3 Nxf3 13. gxf3 Bh3 {-+ And Black is winning material.}) 11... Nxd4 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc5c7]} 12. Qxd4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd4g4]} Bxf3 {The bishop was hanging on [g4], so some precision is required here, but we can keep our bishops on the board.} 13. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 14. Kh1 Bc6 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6][%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e8,Yc5g1,Yc6g2] Without central pawns to restrict them, our bishops are beasts here.} *

