1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. Nc3 $2 {Pretty common and very bad! White is falling for one of the most basic tricks of the 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Rd7d5] We can take this pawn and regain the piece with ...[d5].} 6. Bxf7+ {White does this most of the time, realising the something went wrong, our opponent tries to compensate it with this idea of weakening our king, but castling artificially with [Rf8] and [Kg8] is not so time-consuming for Black.} (6. Nxe4 d5 $1 {This is very easy for Black, we can even keep our extra pawn on [f4].} 7. Bxd5 {(7.Bb5+ Doesn't change anything. 7...c6 8.Bd3 dxe4 9.Bxe4 We have many good moves here, but stopping White from castling looks reasonable. 9...Bh4+ 10.Kf1 Be7 ∓ And when it is needed, we can simply protect the [f4]-pawn by playing ...[Bd6]. )} Qxd5 8. d3 Bf5 {∓ If the knight moves away, we can consider playing by ...[g5] and then castling long at some moment, keeping our material advantage.}) 6... Kxf7 7. Ne5+ {[%csl Rh8][%cal Yf7g8] A little bit more tricky than capturing on [e4] right away, because now the king has to block the rook's way to [f8].} (7. Nxe4 Rf8 $1 {Preparing to hide the king on [g8].} 8. O-O Kg8 {∓ With ...[d5] and ...[Nc6] coming in the next moves, Black is simply up a pawn for no compensation.}) 7... Kg8 8. Nxe4 d6 $1 {[%csl Re4,Re5][%cal Yd6e5] Very precise, we are going to force back White's knight one by one.} 9. Nf3 d5 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yd5e4] The d-pawn is doing a nice job!} 10. Nf2 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] White's previously active knights in the centre lost their power pretty quickly.} Nc6 11. d4 g5 $19 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5,Gh6][%cal Ge7f6,Gc8f5,Gh7h6,Gh6f4] We are super solid, ...[Bf5]-[Bf6] are our next moves, we can solidify the position with ...[h6] anytime we want, and our king is just perfectly safe.} *

