1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. d3 {Objectively speaking this move is not so bad, but was only seldomly played, I guess because of the fear of ...[Bh4]+.} d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4] The typical counterattack! We already saw it many times with the knight on [f6] attacked by the pawn on [e5], this is a much rarer but not less effective way for Black here as well.} (6... Bh4+ {In fact, this move is not so effective!} 7. Ke2 Nf2 8. Qd2 $1 Nxh1 9. Qxf4 {∞ This is how the King's Gambit should be played! Down a full rook, the king is in the centre, but White is doing pretty well according to the engine. 🙂}) 7. dxe4 {The best move according to the machine, White is taking back the material, but at the same time they have to enter a slightly worse endgame.} dxc4 8. Qxd8+ Bxd8 9. Bxf4 O-O 10. Na3 c3 $5 ({There was nothing wrong with} 10... Be6 {, but we would like to be down a pawn, if the means a horribly weak structure for White.}) 11. bxc3 Nd7 $15 {The knight is going to [c5] and maybe later to [e4], it is not so easy to look at White's position without feeling some pain in the stomach.} *

