1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. d3 {Objectively speaking this move is not so bad, but was only seldomly played, I guess because of the fear of ...[Bh4]+.} d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4] The typical counterattack! We already saw it many times with the knight on [f6] attacked by the pawn on [e5], this is a much rarer but not less effective way for Black here as well.} (6... Bh4+ {In fact, this move is not so effective!} 7. Ke2 Nf2 8. Qd2 $1 Nxh1 9. Qxf4 {∞ This is how the King's Gambit should be played! Down a full rook, the king is in the centre, but White is doing pretty well according to the engine. 🙂}) 7. Bb3 Bh4+ $1 {[%csl Rb3,Gd5] Now we give this check, since the [d5]-pawn cuts out the [b3]-bishop from the game, so it is not so easy to sacrifice an extra rook for White. 🙂} 8. Kf1 (8. Ke2 $4 Nf2 9. Qe1 {(9.Qd2 Nxh1 10.Qxf4 Be7 -+ There is nothing for White here, since the [f7]-square is covered. )} Bg4 $1 {-+ Protecting the [h4]-bishop by pinning the knight, Black is completely winning, we are taking material very soon. 9...Nxh1?? Would be a bad error! 10.Qxh4 ⩲}) 8... Nc5 {Even though we can't win material, we will get the pair of bishops, and White's king stays in the centre for now.} 9. Bxf4 Nxb3 10. axb3 O-O $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh4e7,Gb8c6,Gc8g4] If White allows, then we will retreat with the bishop to [e7], but in either case, we will play ... [Nc6]-[Bg4], putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn, and if White can somehow protect it, we can think about opening up the position with ...[f6].} *

