[e4].} 6. d3 {Objectively speaking this move is not so bad, but was only seldomly played, I guess because of the fear of ...[Bh4]+.} d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4] The typical counterattack! We already saw it many times with the knight on [f6] attacked by the pawn on [e5], this is a much rarer but not less effective way for Black here as well.} (6... Bh4+ {In fact, this move is not so effective!} 7. Ke2 Nf2 8. Qd2 $1 Nxh1 9. Qxf4 {∞ This is how the King's Gambit should be played! Down a full rook, the king is in the centre, but White is doing pretty well according to the engine. 🙂}) 7. Bb3 Bh4+ $1 {[%csl Rb3,Gd5] Now we give this check, since the [d5]-pawn cuts out the [b3]-bishop from the game, so it is not so easy to sacrifice an extra rook for White. 🙂} 8. Kf1 (8. Ke2 $4 Nf2 9. Qe1 {(9.Qd2 Nxh1 10.Qxf4 Be7 -+ There is nothing for White here, since the [f7]-square is covered. )} Bg4 $1 {-+ Protecting the [h4]-bishop by pinning the knight, Black is completely winning, we are taking material very soon. 9...Nxh1?? Would be a bad error! 10.Qxh4 ⩲}) 8... Nf2 {Many times this move is just a blunder especially with the king on [f1], since we cannot rely on the pin with ...[Bg4]!, since we take the rook, but in return we lose 2 minor pieces.} 9. Qe1 {[%csl Gf1,Re2][%cal Yf1e2]} Nxh1 10. Qxh4 Qxh4 11. Nxh4 $16 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gf1g1,Gg1h1] The knight is trapped, and White is much better.} *

