1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Ye4c3,Gb1c3,Gd2c3,Gc1f4] Probably the best move for White, but was played only in 3 OTB games, showing that this territory is completely unexplored. The move itself is extremely counterintuitive, it looks like that White's play should be about gaining tempi and attack the knight on [e4], and instead of it, all of a sudden White is offering a trade! But what a subtle one! We shouldn't forget that if this trade happens on [c3], Black's knight made 3 moves and White's one only 1! It is 2 extra moves disappearing from the board, and also White would recapture with the d-pawn on [c3], opening up the way for the [c1]-bishop, so White is really gaining a lot of time with this exchange.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4] As many times before, this move is the key for Black. Speeding up the development, and not caring about the material and giving easy play for White with 6...[Nxc3].} 7. Bxd5 {The only problem with ...[d5] was, that it is actually hanging. :} (7. exd6 $2 {is just a disaster for White.} Nxd6 8. Bb3 Bh4+ {∓ The king remains in the centre, and Black also keeps the extra pawn.}) 7... Bh4+ {[%csl Re1] Our standard idea, forcing White's king to move.} 8. Ke2 Nf2 {[%cal Rf2d1,Rf2h1]} 9. Qe1 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Rg4e2] As usual, this is the move which is very unpleasant for the king on [e2].} 10. g3 $1 {[%cal Ge1f2,Gg3h4] A lot of pieces are hanging, we have to be very precise.} (10. Bxb7 Nd7 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 {White is up on material, but Black's pieces are super active.} 12. Rf1 Nxe5 $1 13. Rxf2 O-O {→ White is up a rook, but the computer doesn't see any defense for White. The best line runs like} 14. Kf1 Nxf3 15. gxf3 Bh3+ 16. Kg1 Re8 17. Ne4 Re6 18. Qe2 Rg6+ 19. Kh1 Bxf2 20. Qxf2 f5 21. d3 Bg2+ 22. Qxg2 Rxg2 23. Kxg2 fxe4 24. dxe4 g5 {-+ And now it is Black who is up material. 🙂}) 10... fxg3 11. hxg3 Nxh1 (11... Bxg3 $2 12. Rg1 $1 {± And our bishops became vulnerable.}) 12. gxh4 {[%csl Rh1] We are going to lose the knight on [h1], so the material balance is not in our favour, therefore we have to look for some concrete and fast play!} c6 $1 13. Be4 (13. Bb3 Qd4 $1 14. Qxh1 Nd7 {∓ With ...[Nxe5] coming, Black is in an excellent shape.}) 13... O-O 14. Qxh1 f5 $1 {[%csl Re2,Gf8] Trying to involve more pieces in the game, and open the position for White's king.} 15. exf6 (15. Bd3 b5 $1 {∓ Keeping the White's pieces stuck by not allowing [Bc4]-[d4], and planning to play ...[Nd7]-[Nxe5]!}) 15... Nd7 $3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7c5,Gd7f6,Rf6e4,Rc5e4] Fantastic move, again not caring about the number of pawns, but with the goal to challenge White's main defender, what holds together the position, the [e4]-bishop! 15...[Qxf6] or 15...[Rxf6] would just lose time in that regard.} 16. fxg7 (16. d3 Nxf6 {-+ With the bishop on [e4] falling, White's whole position is collapsing.}) 16... Rf7 $17 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yd7e5,Re5f3,Gd8b6,Ga8e8] Black has a huge attack, and in the next moves even the [a8]-rook is going to join the game.} *

