1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Ye4c3,Gb1c3,Gd2c3,Gc1f4] Probably the best move for White, but was played only in 3 OTB games, showing that this territory is completely unexplored. The move itself is extremely counterintuitive, it looks like that White's play should be about gaining tempi and attack the knight on [e4], and instead of it, all of a sudden White is offering a trade! But what a subtle one! We shouldn't forget that if this trade happens on [c3], Black's knight made 3 moves and White's one only 1! It is 2 extra moves disappearing from the board, and also White would recapture with the d-pawn on [c3], opening up the way for the [c1]-bishop, so White is really gaining a lot of time with this exchange.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4] As many times before, this move is the key for Black. Speeding up the development, and not caring about the material and giving easy play for White with 6...[Nxc3].} 7. Bxd5 {The only problem with ...[d5] was, that it is actually hanging. :} (7. exd6 $2 {is just a disaster for White.} Nxd6 8. Bb3 Bh4+ {∓ The king remains in the centre, and Black also keeps the extra pawn.}) 7... Bh4+ {[%csl Re1] Our standard idea, forcing White's king to move.} 8. Kf1 {This is the best for White, but the least challenging to find the moves for Black.} Nxc3 {[%csl Rd1] Now, since the queen is not protected on [d1], we can go for this trade, and use the pin on the d-file.} (8... Nf2 $4 {is still losing.} 9. Qe1 Nxh1 10. Nxh4 {+-}) 9. dxc3 c6 $1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Rd8d1] The bishop can't go away.} 10. Nxh4 cxd5 11. Nf3 Nc6 $1 {We will get excellent compensation for the missing pawn, thanks to our safer king, better structure and to the opposite coloured bishops since we can effectively attack on the light squares.} (11... g5 $4 {Would be a huge mistake if we are so concerned about the material.} 12. h4 $1 {±}) 12. Bxf4 O-O 13. Kf2 Bf5 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2,Rf2][%cal Gf5e4,Gf7f6,Ga8e8,Gd8a5,Ga5a4,Yf5c2,Ya4a2] Black has excellent play, the computer even slightly prefers our position, despite being down a pawn. We will put the bishop on [e4], and then play ...[f6] putting White under fire. We also have positional ideas, like ... [Qa5]-[Qa4] and once again, attacking the light-squares in White's camp.} *

