1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. Bd5 $5 {[%cal Rd5e4,Yd7d5] Quite an interesting move and idea. White is attacking our knight and physically stopping us from our favourite ... [d5] move.} Ng5 {[%cal Gd7d6] Our position with the knight on [g5] looks a little bit strange, but the undermining idea of ...[d6] is coming very soon, so everything is just fine.} (6... Bh4+ 7. Kf1 Nf2 {We don't have any pieces to support this idea.} 8. Qe1 {± White is going to win material here.}) 7. d4 d6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yd6e5]} (7... Ne6 {is an interesting alternative, but undermining White's centre looks like the most reliable way of playing.}) 8. Bxf4 dxe5 9. dxe5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gd1d5] White must spoil their structure, since the bishop on [d5] needs protection.} c6 {Forcing an equal endgame, where I would rather take Black.} 10. Bxc6+ {White is winning a pawn temporarily, but we are taking it back on [e5].} Nxc6 11. Qxd8+ {Once again, a must for White, since otherwise they are not winning back the piece on [g5].} Bxd8 12. Bxg5 Bxg5 {With this trade, Black is winning back the pawn on [e5].} 13. Nxg5 Nxe5 $10 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8d7,Gf7f6,Ge8c8] The position is equal, but it is asymmetrical, so there is a lot of play left, and we don't have to worry much, since we have a bishop in a position, where the play is going to progress on both sides of the board.} *

