1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. Bd5 $5 {[%cal Rd5e4,Yd7d5] Quite an interesting move and idea. White is attacking our knight and physically stopping us from our favourite ... [d5] move.} Ng5 7. O-O d6 {[%cal Yd6e5] The key idea to undermine White's space advantage in the centre and make the [d5] bishop loose.} 8. Nxg5 Bxg5 9. exd6 O-O {We can afford this move, before White would start checking us on the e-file, because the bishop on [d5] is unprotected.} 10. dxc7 {With this move, White is falling for a small trap.} (10. d4 {is better.} Qxd6 11. Nc3 Nc6 {But Black is extremely comfortable here as well.} 12. Bxc6 {The only way to take back the pawn.} Qxc6 13. Bxf4 Be7 $1 {By keeping the bishops, even though maybe not better, but Black is at least having the better side of equality.}) 10... Qxd5 11. cxb8=Q Qd4+ {Stopping White's [d4]-move!} 12. Kh1 Rxb8 $15 {[%csl Gg5,Gd4][%cal Gb8e8,Gc8d7,Gd7c6] With ...[Bd7]-[Bc6] and ...[Rbe8] coming, Black has a nice advantage with very active pieces.} *

