1. e4 e5 2. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ye5f4,Gd2d4] The ever-popular King's Gambit! It was the most popular opening until the end of the 19th century against 1...[e5]. White has many dangerous lines in case Black does not know the theory. The idea is to gain full control of the center once Black takes the pawn on [f4], and if possible to castle quickly and put pressure on the f-file.} exf4 ({My choice is to accept the gambit, and not the increasingly popular} 2... d5 {, which keeps the game away from the chaos which can easily happen in the King's Gambit.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yf3h4,Rd8h4] The King's Knight's Gambit. The most popular move for White, it develops the knight to its most natural square, and also stops the annoying ...[Qh4]+.} Be7 {[%cal Re7h4,Yg8f6,Yf6e4,Yf6g4]} ({The Cunningham Defense. This modest looking bishop move has two ideas, one is to give a check on h4, and the other one is that depending on White's response, Black will have different squares available for the g8-knight not only h5, which is pretty much the only good square in case of} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {.}) 4. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge1f1,Gc4d5,Yd7d5] Controlling the [d5]-square and preparing the [f1]-square for the king in case of ...[Bh4]+ is the main line for White.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Here, I recommend switching plans, since if White can put their king to [f1], all the ideas with ...[Bh4]+ followed up by ...[d5] are much less dangerous. With the text move, we are asking a question about the [e4]-pawn, and White answered it incorrectly many times in the practice.} 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye7h4,Yd7d5] This rare move is the Euwe variation, we are placing our knight in a central square instead of ...[h5] and [g4]... where the knight is definitely safer, but also more passive. The justification of the line lies in the fact, that we can often gain tempo on the [c4]-bishop by playing ...[d5] and the ...[Bh4]+ threat is also in the air, making it not so trivial for White to harass our knight on [e4].} 6. O-O {This is the main move by far, and it is really disliked by the computer!} (6. Qe2 $2 {Aggressive, but very easy to meet.} d5 $1 7. exd6 {If White wouldn't take, they already have to count on ...[Bh4]+ as well.} Nxd6 8. Bb3 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. d4 g5 {-+ White just lost a very valuable tempo with [Qe2], which is misplaced there now, and Black will continue with simple development, like ... [Bf6]-[Re8]-[Bf5].}) 6... d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Yc8g4] Getting some control in the centre with a tempo, and also opening the [c8]-bishop and protecting the [e4]-knight along the way.} 7. exd6 {Hard to say what is the best move for White, but this is the most often played one. At the same time I believe we can already be very happy about the outcome of the opening, the only potential issue, the risky placement of the [e4]-knight is solved, and we will have a knight on [d6] instead of [h5]. A pretty nice upgrade to many of the other lines of the King's Gambit.} ({•} 7. Bb3 $6 {This move also solves the problem with the [c5]-knight, since we can just take this bishop, and keep the extra pawn with ...[g5].} Nc5 8. d4 Nxb3 9. axb3 g5 {∓ White has nothing here, the centre is closed, and our light-squared bishop is very strong.}) ({•} 7. Be2 {Very passive for the King's Gambit standards.} c6 {Introducing ...[Qb6]+ idea to the position.} 8. d3 {White can't really bother our knight with this move.} Qb6+ $1 {White can't move the king because of ... [Nf2]+.} 9. d4 {And suddenly our knight on [e4] is very safe and stable.} g5 10. c4 Be6 {∓ With a clear extra pawn for Black.}) 7... Nxd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Rd6c4] The knight even takes back with a tempo!} 8. Bb3 Nc6 $1 {I found this move to be the most precise here. The position is good anyways, but it is good to keep the option of ...[O-O-O] and keep White guessing how to develop their play.} 9. d4 g5 $17 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5][%cal Gg5f4] We have a clear extra pawn and a very solid position. It is hard to see from where White's compensation is coming from. Let's see a few examples of how the game could continue from here.} (9... g5 {•} 10. Nc3 O-O {Yes, this is not our usual pawn position when we castle, but the king is going to be pretty safe there, the [f4]-pawn is nicely restricting White's play.} 11. h4 {A logical try, trying to loosen Black's kingside. (11.Nd5 Bg4 12.c3 Kh8 ∓ And Black is very solid, now that the king is on [h8], we can meet 13.g3 with 13...Rg8 and 13.h4 with 13...f6!)} h6 $1 {We don't want to move our pawns from [g5] and [f4]!} 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. Nd5 Bg4 {With ...[Nf5] coming next, White has to take the time to strengthen the centre.} 14. c3 Kg7 $1 {Not only moving out from the diagonal of the [b3]-bishop, but also making moves like ...[Rh8] possible! White's king is not at all safer in this position than Black's one.} 15. Nxf4 {This is one of the top choices of the engine, but there is not nearly enough compensation for White. (15.Qe1 Bf5! Not the only good move, but a pretty deep trap from SF. 🙂 16.Nxe7 Nxe7 17.Nxg5 It looks like that we just blundered our most important pawn, but here comes the point of the machine. 17...Ng6! 18.Nf3 Bd3 19.Rf2 Ne4 ∓ And the rook is trapped on [f2]. )} gxf4 16. Bxf4 f5 {∓ The game is not over, we still have some defensive task ahead, but we are clearly favourites with White having only a pawn for the piece.}) (9... g5 {•} 10. g3 {This move definitely would have more power, if our king would be on [g8] already. It still wouldn't be good, but now we just castle long, and it looks like that White is just weakening their own king.} Bh3 $1 {Developing with a tempo and getting closer to ...[O-O-O].} 11. Re1 Qd7 12. d5 O-O-O $1 {Quite a nice way to exploit White's weak king, and the fact that their pieces are just watching the game on the queenside.} 13. dxc6 Qxc6 14. Rxe7 {One more piece!} Nf5 {-+ But the next couple of moves will not be easy for White.}) (9... g5 {•} 10. c4 {Trying to do something in the centre looks like a decent try, since White has a majority there, but without the support of pieces, those pawns can become very weak.} Bg4 $1 11. d5 {(11.c5 Nf5 -+ The [d4]-pawn is falling. )} Ne5 12. c5 Nf5 {-+ Black is simply playing around the pawns, and it is not clear what White achieved, besides a hanging pawn on [c5].}) *

