[White "6) Ponziani Opening And Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.Be2 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 5.e5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2160376113250046"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. Be2 {This opening goes by the name of Inverted Hungarian Opening, because of the resemblance of the Hungarian Defense, which starts by the moves 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Be7 . A very modest choice, as it is not really possible to play for an advantage in such a way.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] Continuing the development and attacking the [e4]-pawn.} 4. d4 $6 {[%csl Yd4,Ye2] The only independent way for White if they don't want to transpose to the Four Knights Game or to some reversed Philidor. However, the text move is pretty dubious and it is strange to immediately start active actions after the slow 3. [Be2].} ({•} 4. Nc3 d5 {transposes to the Four Knights game.}) ({•} 4. d3 d5 {is transposing to 3. [d3] [Nf6] 4. [Be2] [d5].}) 4... exd4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] We accept the pawn, and since [e4] is still under attack, it is not so easy for White to take it back.} (4... Nxe4 5. d5 $1 {This is what we should avoid. White is gaining space in the centre and recapturing the pawn on [e5].}) 5. e5 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rg4e5,Rc6e5] Attacking the e-pawn again, now on [e5].} 6. O-O (6. Bf4 $2 d6 $1 {This strong move secures the extra pawn for Black.} 7. Bb5 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Ngxe5 9. Bxe5 Bd7 {-+ Black is keeping the extra material, and can quickly finish the development with ...[Qe7] and ...[O-O-O].}) 6... Be7 ({We have time to take on e5. For now, it is better just to continue the development and prepare to castle.} 6... Ngxe5 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. Qxd4 {∞ would give White compensation for the pawn.}) 7. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gf3e5,Yh2h3] White protects the pawn on [e5] and has the threat of playing [h3]!, kicking our knight to a very bad square.} (7. Nxd4 Ngxe5 {White does not have much (if anything) for the pawn here.} 8. f4 Ng6 9. f5 Nge5 10. Nc3 d5 {⩱ With a clear extra pawn for Black.}) 7... d6 $1 {[%cal Yg4e5] Undermining White's centre, and protecting the d-pawn in case exchanges are happening on [d6].} 8. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yb5e8] By pinning the knight on [c6], White is fighting for the [d4] and [e5]-squares. The problem is that this bishop moves for a second time in the opening, indicating the [e2] square is an inferior square for this piece.} (8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bh4 O-O {⩱ Because of the discovered check on [h2], White can't take back the pawn on [d4], and is clearly worse.}) 8... Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxe5 $6 dxe5 10. Nxe5 O-O $1 {(10...Qd6 is also good, but this move is even stronger according to the engine. )} 11. Bxc6 {(11.Nxc6 is even worse. 11...bxc6 12.Bxc6 Rb8 13.b3 Ba6 14.Re1 Bb4 15.Re4 Qf6 -+ The bishops are extremely strong in such an open position. )} Qd6 $1 {This is the point, Black is getting the pair of bishops or an extra pawn.} 12. Nxf7 Qxc6 13. Ne5 Qd5 {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, because of the bishop pair and space in the centre.}) 9... dxe5 10. Bxe5 {[%cal Re5g7,Re5d4,Rb5c6] White is regaining the material, but will have to concede the bishop pair for it.} (10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bxe5 {We could hang on to the extra pawn by playing ...[Bf6] here, but it is so much better to allow White to take on [g7] and open the g-file for us. 🙂} c5 12. Bxg7 Rg8 13. Be5 Qd5 14. Bg3 Bb7 15. f3 O-O-O {-+ And the h-pawn is going to start running with a probably decisive effect.}) 10... Qd5 {This leads to a safe, but small advantage for Black. The 'mathematically stronger' 10...[Bd7] is a good alternative.} (10... Bd7 11. Bxd4 {(11.Bxc6 Bxc6 12.Qxd4 Qxd4 13.Bxd4 O-O-O ∓ Black is much better in this endgame, no central pawns mean that the bishops are going to rule the board. )} Nxd4 {I guess this is the moment where most people would finish the calculation as Black is winning material, but the computer shows that it is not so easy.} 12. Qxd4 Bxb5 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14. Re1 Bd7 15. Nc3 a5 $1 {The only move which keeps the advantage for Black!} 16. Rad1 Ra6 17. Qxh7 Rg6 {⩱ Black is better, but White has practical chances, and that's why in the end I preferred 10...[Qd5]. But honestly speaking, if you ever get to the position after 10. [Bxe5], then maybe it is worth seriously considering 10...[Bd7] since that has the bigger upside, and it is extremely unlikely that White will go for this piece sacrifice in the mainline.}) 11. Bxc6+ Qxc6 12. Qxd4 f6 13. Bg3 O-O $15 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7] With a typical bishop pair advantage for Black in an open position.} *

