1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. g3 {The Konstantinopolsky opening, on the way of becoming the Richard Rapport variation. 🙂 Basically the move is the same as 3. [d3] regarding our repertoire, so more details are going to be analysed there.} Nf6 4. d3 (4. Nc3 d5 {And we are transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) 4... d5 5. Nbd2 $6 {This move is bad, and it was already shown in the first chapter that when the bishop is going to [g2] and Black can respond with a timely ...[dxe4], then White is struggling a lot.} (5. exd5 Nxd5 {transposes here.}) 5... dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Bc5 {Transposes to the 1.e4 e5 2.d3 Nc6 3.g3 d5 4.Nd2 dxe4 line.} *

