[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2160376113319680"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1c2] Jobava has played like this many times, and there are two ideas behind this move. Firstly, if allowed, White can gain some space on the queenside with an early [b4]-move. Secondly, the queen can go to [c2] to protect the pawn on [e4], without committing their [b1]-knight to [d2]. Since there are a lot of transpositions and very similar positions with the 4. [Be2] lines, here we will focus on the lines where White plays with [Qc2], and in the [Be2] lines, all the other possibilities.} d5 {[%cal Rd5e4] This is obvious and coming with a tempo, so we don't have to be afraid of [b4].} 5. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4,Yc1g5,Ya2a4,Yb1a3] By protecting the pawn this way, White keeps the options of playing by [Bg5] or [a4]-[Na3] at some moment. Both of those are rare and not perfect plans, though.} ({•} 5. Qa4 {Was played in a few games, but it is not clear what White achieves after the simple} Bd7 $1 {When the queen most likely has to go back to [c2] right away.}) ({•} 5. Nbd2 {The most popular move in the position, and a transposition to 4. [Be2] lines is extremely likely.} a5 {Preventing [b4]!} 6. Be2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O {Transposes to 4. [Be2] [d5].}) 5... a5 $1 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ya5b4,Gf8c5,Gc5b6,Gb6a7,Gc5f2] A key move, stopping [b4], and also preparing a nice diagonal with some retreat square for the dark-squared bishop. We are at crossroads again, White can play with or without [a4].} 6. a4 {This is how Jobava plays this system, even though the games are mainly from shorter time controls. The main point is really just to have a standard setup and avoid heavy theory.} Bc5 7. Be2 h6 {[%cal Yc1g5,Yh6g5]} ({Not a must at all, but we are playing this move anyway at some moment, and it looked to me that since White hasn't castled yet,} 7... O-O 8. Bg5 {could be mildly annoying, since the ...[h6]-[g5] ideas are more risky for Black.}) 8. O-O O-O {It is really tough for me to say what White should do in this position. Just ' waiting' with the white pieces after 8 moves doesn't look like the correct answer.} 9. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5] The knight is going towards [b5]. It is debatable how strong it will be there, as it can be driven back by ...[c6] in the future.} (9. h3 {A useful move, now the rook is free to go from [f1], since ... [Ng4] is not an issue anymore.} Be6 10. Re1 {(10.Na3 Re8 transposes to 9. [Na3] )} d4 $1 {Obviously 10...[Qd7] or 10...[Re8] are also good moves, this is just a different plan, which also can be very effective. The move is very well-timed, once White's rook was looking for some play on the e-file, we are just closing the centre, and want to play on the queenside.} 11. Na3 {( • 11.c4?? A horrible move. 11...Nd7 -+ With ...[Bb4]-[Nc5] and then ...[f5] coming, White is much worse. ) ( • 11.cxd4 Bxd4 ∓ With clear edge for Black, because of the multiple weak squares on the queenside, such as [b4], [b3] or [c5]. )} Nd7 12. Nb5 Bb6 {Preparing the ...[c5]-square for the knight.} 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Bf4 Rc8 {⩱ ...[Nb4] and ...[Nc5] is coming, Black has huge pressure on the queenside.}) 9... Re8 {Black is making the standard improving moves.} 10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Yf6g4] White has to cover the [g4]-square, so the rook from [f1] can join the game and don't have to protect against ...[Ng4].} Be6 {You can't really go wrong if you are just developing your pieces to normal squares against the Philidor.} 11. Nb5 Qd7 12. Re1 $2 {Jobava had this position 3 times, he won all the games, but the position is already lost!} (12. d4 {The engine's top choice, but even this looks pretty bad for White.} Bb6 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nxe4 15. Nd4 Bf5 {⩱ White is having problems with the weak e5-pawn and different discovered attacks on the queen.}) 12... dxe4 $1 {Closing the centre before going for the kingside attack.} 13. dxe4 Bxh3 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rc5g1,Rd7h3,Rf6g4] White is lost after this sacrifice.} 14. Nxc7 (14. gxh3 Qxh3 {...[Qg3]+ or ...[Ng4] is coming.} 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Qg3+ 17. Kf1 Rad8 {-+ And ... [Ng4] is going to be decisive on the next move.}) 14... Bxg2 $1 (14... Qxc7 {is also good, but this is just a very pretty line.}) 15. Nxe8 (15. Kxg2 Qg4+ $1 {(15...Qxc7 -+ With a pawn up for Black. )} 16. Kh2 Bxf2 {-+ With a winning attack.}) 15... Qh3 {[%cal Rh3h1]} 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 {White is up a full rook, but getting checkmated.} 17. Nh2 Qg3 $19 {[%cal Rg2f3,Rg3g2] A spectacular win!} *

