1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1c2] Jobava has played like this many times, and there are two ideas behind this move. Firstly, if allowed, White can gain some space on the queenside with an early [b4]-move. Secondly, the queen can go to [c2] to protect the pawn on [e4], without committing their [b1]-knight to [d2]. Since there are a lot of transpositions and very similar positions with the 4. [Be2] lines, here we will focus on the lines where White plays with [Qc2], and in the [Be2] lines, all the other possibilities.} d5 {[%cal Rd5e4] This is obvious and coming with a tempo, so we don't have to be afraid of [b4].} 5. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4,Yc1g5,Ya2a4,Yb1a3] By protecting the pawn this way, White keeps the options of playing by [Bg5] or [a4]-[Na3] at some moment. Both of those are rare and not perfect plans, though.} ({•} 5. Qa4 {Was played in a few games, but it is not clear what White achieves after the simple} Bd7 $1 {When the queen most likely has to go back to [c2] right away.}) ({•} 5. Nbd2 {The most popular move in the position, and a transposition to 4. [Be2] lines is extremely likely.} a5 {Preventing [b4]!} 6. Be2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O {Transposes to 4. [Be2] [d5].}) 5... a5 $1 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ya5b4,Gf8c5,Gc5b6,Gb6a7,Gc5f2] A key move, stopping [b4], and also preparing a nice diagonal with some retreat square for the dark-squared bishop. We are at crossroads again, White can play with or without [a4].} 6. Be2 ({More flexible than} 6. a4 {, White can opt for that move later also, but keeping ideas like [b3]-[a3] and then playing for [b4] is White's main idea here.}) 6... Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga7f2] The bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5 $6 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Re4d5,Yg5d8] This move is one of the advantages of starting with an early [c3] and protecting the pawn with [Qc2], so the knight is not blocking the bishop on [d2].} dxe4 {A straightforward way to deal with the pin on the [h4]-[d8] diagonal. We are preparing to play ...[h6] on the next move.} 9. dxe4 h6 10. Bh4 g5 $1 {Works without any issues. Let's not forget that in principle we are 'White' here, so we can afford more aggression than usual.} 11. Bg3 (11. Nxg5 $2 {This is nothing, White has no pieces to attack with.} hxg5 12. Bxg5 Qd6 {-+ The attack is finished, Black is up a piece. 🙂}) 11... Nh5 12. Nbd2 Qf6 $15 {[%cal Gh5f4,Gc8e6,Ga8d8] Black is more active here. We should finish development with ...[Be6] and ...[Rad8] and then consider ...[Nf4]. Alternatively, taking on [g3] and then following it up with ...[h5]-[h4] is also tempting.} *

