1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1c2] Jobava has played like this many times, and there are two ideas behind this move. Firstly, if allowed, White can gain some space on the queenside with an early [b4]-move. Secondly, the queen can go to [c2] to protect the pawn on [e4], without committing their [b1]-knight to [d2]. Since there are a lot of transpositions and very similar positions with the 4. [Be2] lines, here we will focus on the lines where White plays with [Qc2], and in the [Be2] lines, all the other possibilities.} d5 {[%cal Rd5e4] This is obvious and coming with a tempo, so we don't have to be afraid of [b4].} 5. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4,Yc1g5,Ya2a4,Yb1a3] By protecting the pawn this way, White keeps the options of playing by [Bg5] or [a4]-[Na3] at some moment. Both of those are rare and not perfect plans, though.} ({•} 5. Qa4 {Was played in a few games, but it is not clear what White achieves after the simple} Bd7 $1 {When the queen most likely has to go back to [c2] right away.}) ({•} 5. Nbd2 {The most popular move in the position, and a transposition to 4. [Be2] lines is extremely likely.} a5 {Preventing [b4]!} 6. Be2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O {Transposes to 4. [Be2] [d5].}) 5... a5 $1 {[%cal Yb2b4,Ya5b4,Gf8c5,Gc5b6,Gb6a7,Gc5f2] A key move, stopping [b4], and also preparing a nice diagonal with some retreat square for the dark-squared bishop. We are at crossroads again, White can play with or without [a4].} 6. Be2 ({More flexible than} 6. a4 {, White can opt for that move later also, but keeping ideas like [b3]-[a3] and then playing for [b4] is White's main idea here.}) 6... Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga7f2] The bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 ({White is continuing to play in the reversed Philidor fashion.} 8. a4 h6 {transposes back to 6. [a4] [Bc5] lines.}) 8... h6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gh6g5,Yf3g5] Very standard and useful move for Black, anytime we want to go ...[Be6], we don't have to worry about [Ng5] anymore.} 9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Yd5d4,Yd4c3] This is what White normally does when they are not committing to an early [a4]. The idea is to play for [b4]. From our perspective it is good to know that once the b-pawn has moved, our [d4]-idea is usually stronger, because of the weakness of the [c3]-pawn, or rather that White can't replace it with another pawn after ...[dxc3], so the [d4]-square can be an issue for our opponent.} (9. a3 $6 {Looks 'faster' than [b3]-[a3] and then [b4], but in fact it is a serious positional error.} a4 $1 {And White can't move the b-pawn anymore without weakening the structure, since we will take with en passant all the time.}) 9... Re8 {Black is still improving the position and making useful moves.} 10. a3 Ba7 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yd5d4,Yc3d4,Gc2c5,Yc5b6,Yd2c4] A very deep move, which at first sight looks rather strange. The point is connected with ...[d4] - first, after we play that move and White takes it, our bishop is not attacked on [c5]. Then, if we would put the bishop to the more natural [b6]-square, then it could be sometimes attacked with [Nc4], which is crucial in one of the lines.} 11. b4 ({•} 11. Bb2 {When the bishop goes to [b2], the ...[Nh5] idea with hitting the [f4]-square is very strong.} dxe4 12. dxe4 Nh5 {⩱ And the knight reaches [f4], since} 13. g3 Bh3 14. Rfd1 Nf6 {∓ Makes things even worse for our opponent.}) ({•} 11. Rb1 {White wants to play [b4] and recapture with the a-pawn.} Nh5 {...[Nf4] is an unpleasant threat.} 12. Re1 d4 $1 {This is a position where it is really good that our bishop is on [a7], since [Nc4] can't come with a tempo.} 13. cxd4 {(13.Nc4 b5 And the knight can go home. )} Nxd4 $1 {And now it is very good that the bishop is not on [c5], because it would be simply hanging. 🙂} 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Rf1 Nf4 {⩱ And Black has a nice edge with the very active pieces.}) 11... axb4 12. cxb4 (12. axb4 $4 {Just a big blunder.} Bxf2+ 13. Rxf2 Rxa1 {-+}) 12... Bb6 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Rc6b4,Ga8a1,Yd5d4] Opening the a-file for the rook, and we are definitely not planning to play ...[d4] anymore, since White has already created a weakness on that square.} 13. Bb2 Nh5 {[%cal Rh5f4] Provoking some weaknesses in White's camp.} 14. g3 {Better than allowing the knight to [f4].} Nf6 $15 {[%csl Rg4,Rh3][%cal Yc8h3,Yf6g4] White has weakened the light squares on their kingside with [g3], and now ideas like ...[Bh3]-[Ng4] look particularly dangerous.} *

