[GameId "2160376113422083"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. Be2 d5 5. exd5 {This is pretty much the Antoshin variation of the Philidor Defence, with reversed colours. White will have less space in the centre, but they want to compensate it by attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nxd5 6. O-O Bd6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Gc6e5] Since we know that White's pretty much only play is to attack the [e5]-pawn, it looks reasonable to develop the bishop to this square and not to [e7].} (6... Bc5 $6 {is just a blunder.} 7. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 8. d4 Bd6 9. dxe5 Bxe5 10. Re1 {± Bf3 is a huge threat.}) 7. Re1 (7. d4 {White is trying to equalise the game on the spot, but this move is not enough for that goal.} exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O $1 {The knight is not hanging because of the discovered check on [h2].} 10. Rd1 Qe7 {⩱ Even though the pawn structure is symmetrical, Black's pieces are more active, so White still has to solve some issues before claiming equality here.}) 7... O-O 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ge2f1,Gc4e5,Ge1e5] White is bringing the pieces to attack the [e5]-pawn, but it is already well protected.} (8. c3 a5 $1 {No [b4] from White!}) 8... Re8 {[%cal Ge8e5] More protection to the [e5]-pawn.} 9. Bf1 a5 10. c3 h6 {Both sides are just making slow, improving moves.} 11. a4 Bd7 {[%csl Ge5] Black has comfortably finished their development, and it is hard to see how White should continue.} 12. Nc4 (12. Ne4 Bf8 {⩱ The knight is not really well-placed on [e4], Black can consider playing with ... [f5] very soon.}) 12... Qf6 $10 {Black is really comfortable here, we will bring the rook to [d8], and then maybe even looking for a good way to start playing for ...[f5].} *

