1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. Be2 d5 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] This is the standard move order for White to play the reversed Philidor.} Bc5 6. O-O ({•} 6. c3 a5 $1 {As usual, [c3] is best met by the immediate ...[a5], not allowing [b4].}) ({•} 6. exd5 Nxd5 $1 {Even though against the Antoshin variation we put the bishop to ...[d6], it is completely fine on [c5] too, because there is no [Nxe5] trick, since the knight on [d2] is blocking the [d4] possibility.}) 6... O-O 7. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White wants to play [b4] and by this point, our answer should be routine for you! 🙂} a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5b4,Gc5b6,Gb6a7] Of course, taking away the [b4]-move and making the diagonal longer for the bishop.} 8. h3 {[%cal Gf1e1,Yf6g4,Gh3g4] White is playing a waiting game without moving the queen.} h6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Yf3g5] We are also making the typical waiting/ improving moves.} 9. Re1 Be6 10. Bf1 {[%cal Re4d5,Gf3e5,Ge1e5] White is putting some pressure on the [e5]-pawn, but it is very easy to deal with.} (10. exd5 Bxd5 11. Nf1 {We have many possibilities here, White is playing very slowly.} Re8 12. Be3 Bd6 {Avoiding the trade looks reasonable, since White's minor pieces are struggling with the lack of space.}) 10... Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8e5]} ({And the e5-pawn is safe again!} 10... dxe4 {I would like to show this very interesting plan from the machine.} 11. dxe4 g5 $1 {First, Black closed the centre, and now starts on offensive on the kingside.} 12. Nh2 Kh7 {With ...[Rg8] and ...[g4] to follow, Black has certain attacking chances.}) 11. exd5 Bxd5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Ge8e5,Gc6e5] We have to take with the bishop in this instance in order to keep the ...[e5] pawn defended. Taking with the knight would be more natural.} 12. Qc2 a4 $15 {[%csl Ya2][%cal Gc5f8,Gb7b5,Yd5a2] Black is definitely better with an advantage in space. White's rook is also passively defending the [a2]-pawn at the moment. We can further improve our position by playing moves such as ...[b5], ...[Bf8] and ...[Rb8].} *

