1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. Be2 d5 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] This is the standard move order for White to play the reversed Philidor.} Bc5 6. O-O ({•} 6. c3 a5 $1 {As usual, [c3] is best met by the immediate ...[a5], not allowing [b4].}) ({•} 6. exd5 Nxd5 $1 {Even though against the Antoshin variation we put the bishop to ...[d6], it is completely fine on [c5] too, because there is no [Nxe5] trick, since the knight on [d2] is blocking the [d4] possibility.}) 6... O-O 7. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White wants to play [b4] and by this point, our answer should be routine for you! 🙂} a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5b4,Gc5b6,Gb6a7] Of course, taking away the [b4]-move and making the diagonal longer for the bishop.} 8. b3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gc1b2,Gb3b4] This is the most common move, White is playing for [a3]-[Bb2] and then [b4].} ({•} 8. a3 $6 {would be a very inaccurate way to start this plan, because of} a4 $1) ({•} 8. Qc2 {Anytime White goes for this move, it will transpose to 4. [c3] lines.} h6 {transposes to 4. [c3] [d5].}) ({•} 8. a4 {Here the chances are also pretty high to transpose into 4. [c3] territory, since where else White's queen would go than [c2]?} h6 9. exd5 {This direct approach is an extra possibility for White, but it is just what the computer likes, Philidor players normally don't play like this.} Nxd5 10. d4 {Trying to equalise the game, and while White is not far from it, it can be hardly called an achievement.} exd4 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qf6 {The position is about equal, it looks like a small edge for Black because of the more active pieces though, our next moves are ...[c6] and ...[Rd8].}) 8... Bg4 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb2c3,Yd5d4,Yg4f3] With their previous move, White weakened their dark squares, especially [c3]. It makes our ...[d4] idea much stronger because the [c3]-pawn last lost its support. The move...[Bg4] looks to increase Black's dark-squared control by looking to trade the bishop for a knight. In this way, white will only have two minor pieces capable of defending the dark squares, and black will have three. 🙂} 9. Bb2 ({•} 9. h3 {Plays into our hands, we don't mind the trade on [f3] at all.} Bxf3 10. Bxf3 d4 11. c4 {(11.cxd4? Qxd4 -+ White is just losing a pawn. )} a4 12. bxa4 Be7 {⩱ We will recover the pawn with [Nd7]-[Nc5]/ [Nb6]-[Nxa4] and have a big positional advantage.}) ({•} 9. a3 d4 10. cxd4 {(10.c4 White tries to keep the queenside closed, and basically transpose to some kind of reversed KID structure. Our play is clear, the [d4]-pawn provides us space advantage on the queenside, so we have to prepare for ...[b5] and open that side of the board. 10...Bc8! ⩱ Just very instructive, but obviously not the only good move. We don't want to trade this bishop for White's awful [e2]-bishop, on the other hand we would like to transfer our knight from [f6] to [c5], so it makes a lot of sense to get this bishop out of the way first. )} Bxd4 11. Rb1 {(11.Nxd4 Qxd4! It is an important move, so we don't have problems with the [g4]-bishop. )} Bc5 {⩱ Our structure is clearly better, and White also has to deal with a couple of weak squares.}) 9... Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3,Gd4] Continuing the fight for the [d4]-square and for the dark squares, in general.} 10. Bxf3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rf3] The [f3]-bishop is very bad, so basically we have a 3 vs 2 fight regarding the minor pieces for the [d4]-square. It is therefore not a surprise that in both OTB games which reached this position, White rather decided to keep the centre closed.} 11. c4 a4 $1 {[%csl Ga8] Immediately starting active play on the queenside!} 12. bxa4 Qe7 $17 {[%cal Ga8a6,Gf8a8,Gc5a3,Gf6d7] White is strategically pretty much lost, they have no play, while Black will just double on the a-file, with the goal of collecting both a-pawns from White.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani Opening And Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.d3 Nf6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160376113512198"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. g3 (4. Nc3 d5 {And we are transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) 4... d5 {Of course, there is no reason not to play this move.} 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 $6 {Just very bad, and will transpose to the chapter where 2. [d3] is discussed.} dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Bc5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5 {transposes to 2. [d3] [Nc6] line.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2b7,Ge1g1,Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] This is the starting position of the 'Richard Rapport Variation'. You can already see a huge upgrade from the regular Philidor setups, that the bishop is on [g2], much more active than on [e2], and it will be also much easier for White to attack the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] Only the 5th move according to popularity, but theory is not yet well-developed in this area. The goal is obvious, we don't want to have any issues with the [e5]-pawn in the future.} 7. O-O O-O {And now we are mainly left with the games of GM Rapport as reference.} 8. Re1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge1e5] Putting some pressure on the e-pawn, but it is well-protected.} Bf5 $1 {This is the square I like the most for the bishop in these variations. On [e6] it would be in the way of the rook protecting the [e5]-pawn and also exposed to [Ng5] jumps, while on [g4] White could challenge it with [h3]. On [f5] it is very flexible at the moment.} 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a5 {[%cal Ya5b4] White is looking for some play, so why to allow [b4]?} 10. Nbd2 Qd7 11. Nc4 Rfe8 $10 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf5g4,Ga5a4] The position is certainly playable, but Black by no means is worse here. I like this position with the space advantage, and we still have many improving moves to make, such as ...[h6], ...[a4] or ...[Rad8]. It is also worth mentioning that once our queen is on [d7], ...[Bg4] becomes a serious idea, since White can't challenge it with [h3] anymore, and otherwise the pin can be unpleasant.} *

