1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. g3 (4. Nc3 d5 {And we are transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) 4... d5 {Of course, there is no reason not to play this move.} 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 $6 {Just very bad, and will transpose to the chapter where 2. [d3] is discussed.} dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Bc5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5 {transposes to 2. [d3] [Nc6] line.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2b7,Ge1g1,Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] This is the starting position of the 'Richard Rapport Variation'. You can already see a huge upgrade from the regular Philidor setups, that the bishop is on [g2], much more active than on [e2], and it will be also much easier for White to attack the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] Only the 5th move according to popularity, but theory is not yet well-developed in this area. The goal is obvious, we don't want to have any issues with the [e5]-pawn in the future.} 7. O-O O-O {And now we are mainly left with the games of GM Rapport as reference.} 8. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Gb2c3,Ga1b1] White is challenging our knight, and in case of a trade the b-file is opening up for the rook.} Nxc3 {As I said in previous chapters, whenever possible, I like to avoid this kind of structure with the bishop in [g2]. There is nothing wrong with these positions, it is just a matter of taste. Here, Black had the opportunity to play with ...[Nde7], and it is quite good. However, White can also play [Nc3] with the inclusion of the moves [a3]-[a5], and then we better take on [c3] than allow White's knight to [b5], so it is probably best to adopt the same solution against this line as well.} 9. bxc3 Bf5 $1 {The bishop goes to the usual square in this system!} 10. Rb1 Rb8 {The pressure on the b-file is minimal. One of the reasons that Black takes [c3] in this line is that White has already committed to a very early [d3]. Playing [d4] is one of White's main ideas in this structure, but now it would be accompanied with the loss of a tempo.} 11. Ng5 Qd7 12. Ne4 Bg4 $1 {Provoking [f3] by White or they will have to move the queen to an awkward-looking square.} 13. f3 Be6 $15 {[%cal Re6a2,Gd6e7,Gb7b6] Black is very comfortable here. There is almost no pressure on the queenside, and in all other parts of the board we are doing very well.} *

