1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf1e2,Gg2g3] A very solid move, a favourite of GM Baadur Jobava. White doesn't want to get any advantage out of the opening, they just want to get a playable game, most of the time also in the case of Jobava aiming for a reversed Philidor Defense setup with moves like [Be2]-[Nbd2]-[Qc2], etc. In the last couple of years Richard Rapport started to play these systems with developing the bishop to [g2], with similar goals like the other setup, get a game without memorizing a lot of lines.} Nf6 {[%cal Yd7d5,Gf6d5] Since White is not putting any pressure on our position at all, we can just prepare and play ...[d5] in the next move, essentially playing as 'White' but with a tempo down obviously, if we compare it to the normal Philidor theory.} 4. g3 (4. Nc3 d5 {And we are transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) 4... d5 {Of course, there is no reason not to play this move.} 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 $6 {Just very bad, and will transpose to the chapter where 2. [d3] is discussed.} dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Bc5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5 {transposes to 2. [d3] [Nc6] line.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2b7,Ge1g1,Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] This is the starting position of the 'Richard Rapport Variation'. You can already see a huge upgrade from the regular Philidor setups, that the bishop is on [g2], much more active than on [e2], and it will be also much easier for White to attack the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] Only the 5th move according to popularity, but theory is not yet well-developed in this area. The goal is obvious, we don't want to have any issues with the [e5]-pawn in the future.} 7. O-O O-O {And now we are mainly left with the games of GM Rapport as reference.} 8. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Rapport's favourite move. White is aiming for [b4], and also wants to weaken the [b5]-square along the way.} (8. d4 {This was never played before, but it is useful to know that we can't be too ambitious here.} exd4 {We just have to enter a symmetrical and equal position. (8...e4?! 9.Ng5! And our position is pretty loose. 9...f5 10.f3 exf3 11.Qxf3 ⩲)} 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Nb4 $1 11. Na3 Be7 {Black is completely equal here, without any problems.}) 8... a5 {There is still no reason to allow [b4].} 9. Nc3 Nxc3 {Even though it is of course not a must to take on [c3], but it looks like the easiest solution, not to allow White's knight to [b5].} (9... Nde7 10. Nb5 $1 {This is the point of starting with 8. [a3]!, now the knight is pretty unpleasant on [b5], and White can play for [d4] immediately.} Ng6 11. d4 exd4 12. Nfxd4 {⩲ White is definitely better here.}) 10. bxc3 {Here ...[a4] and ...[h6] were played against Rapport, which are of course fine, but we don't have to change our usual setup in these lines.} Bf5 11. Rb1 {[%cal Rb1b7]} Rb8 {Black is just very solid.} 12. Nd2 Qd7 $10 {[%cal Gf5g4,Gb7b6,Gf8e8] At this point, Black has many moves available. For example, playing ...[b6] will ease the pressure on the b-file. The computer says the position is equal, but practically the position looks easier for black to play with the better structure.} *

[Event "A Black Repertoire for Ambitious Chess Improvers: Fighting 1.e4"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani Opening And Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Ponziani - 3.c3 d5 4.Bb5 dxe4 5.Nxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2160376113585929"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Bb5 $2 {This line is just bad, but the game is getting very sharp, so Black has to know what to do.} dxe4 $1 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Re5c6,Gb5e8] This was White's idea behind 4. [Bb5], they are not only regaining the pawn, but there is another attack on the [c6]-knight.} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5]} ({Even though the most frequently played} 5... Qd5 {is also better for Black, there is no way that we should avoid a winning line, even if it is messy.}) 6. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Rc1g5] Protecting the knight and attacking the queen.} Qxg2 7. Rf1 Bd6 $1 {The first key move of the line, we don't have to be afraid of [Nxc6].} (7... Nge7 8. d5 {+-}) 8. Nxc6 (8. Qh5 {Allows Black to consolidate.} g6 9. Qh4 Nge7 10. Qf6 Rf8 {-+}) 8... Bd7 $1 {And the second key move! White's position is very bad, because of the weak kingside.} 9. Nxa7 (9. Qa4 a6 $1 {-+ We are not threatening to take anything, but White simply can't move. Eventually, Black is playing ...[Rc8] or ...[Ne7] and wins back material.}) 9... c6 $1 {[%csl Ge8] The most precise, we sacrifice a pawn for our king's safety.} (9... Rxa7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 11. Qh5 {is also better for Black, but not so simple.}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Be2 Nf6 $17 {[%csl Re1,Ge8][%cal Gd7h3,Yf6g4,Ge8g8,Rg2h2] The difference between king safety and piece activity should be decisive here.} *

