1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Bb5 $2 {This line is just bad, but the game is getting very sharp, so Black has to know what to do.} dxe4 $1 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Re5c6,Gb5e8] This was White's idea behind 4. [Bb5], they are not only regaining the pawn, but there is another attack on the [c6]-knight.} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5]} ({Even though the most frequently played} 5... Qd5 {is also better for Black, there is no way that we should avoid a winning line, even if it is messy.}) 6. Qa4 {[%cal Rb5c6,Ra4c6] White is making the threats on [c6] stronger.} (6. Nxc6 $2 Qxb5 7. Nd4 Qg5 8. g3 Bg4 {-+ is disastrous for White.}) 6... Qxg2 $1 {Black is accepting the challenge, since we have very strong threats on the kingside as well!} 7. Rf1 $2 {This is too slow. White is keeping the threats, but now Black has time to consolidate.} Bd6 $1 {An important developing move.} 8. Nxc6 (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Ke7 10. Qxa8 Bh3 {-+ Winning a lot of material for Black.}) 8... a6 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ya6b5] Once we are getting the light-squared bishop, the rook on [f1] is going to be in big trouble.} 9. Nd4+ axb5 10. Qxa8 Ne7 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Ra8,Rb1,Rc1][%cal Ge8g8,Gc8h3,Ge7g6,Gg6e5] A very instructive line! White is a rook up, Black has just made a developing move to prepare castling, and White is absolutely lost. The reason is that the extra material for White is so far behind in development.} *

