1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Bb5 $2 {This line is just bad, but the game is getting very sharp, so Black has to know what to do.} dxe4 $1 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Re5c6,Gb5e8] This was White's idea behind 4. [Bb5], they are not only regaining the pawn, but there is another attack on the [c6]-knight.} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5]} ({Even though the most frequently played} 5... Qd5 {is also better for Black, there is no way that we should avoid a winning line, even if it is messy.}) 6. Qa4 {[%cal Rb5c6,Ra4c6] White is making the threats on [c6] stronger.} (6. Nxc6 $2 Qxb5 7. Nd4 Qg5 8. g3 Bg4 {-+ is disastrous for White.}) 6... Qxg2 $1 {Black is accepting the challenge, since we have very strong threats on the kingside as well!} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ {Like there are 2 different boards, White is taking everything on the queenside and Black on the kingside, whose strategy is going to succeed?} Kd8 9. Rf1 (9. Qd5+ {This line goes for a very bad endgame for White.} Bd6 10. Nxf7+ Ke7 11. Qg5+ Qxg5 12. Nxg5 Nf6 {-+ Black is down a pawn, but with a winning position. The difference in piece activity is too great. For now, ...[h6] is a threat to trap the knight and we have many moves such as ...[Ba6]-[Kd7]-[Rae8]-[Rhf8] to play, with complete domination.}) 9... Bh3 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rg2f1] We allow White to take our rook with a check, since the [f1]-rook can't be protected.} 10. Qxa8+ Ke7 11. Kd1 {White's king is running away from the checkmate.} (11. Nc6+ {is a funny line.} Kf6 12. Qd8+ Kg6 13. Ne5+ Kh5 {-+ The king is finally safe from checks, and Black can start collecting material.}) 11... Qxf1+ 12. Kc2 {[%cal Ra8e4] Now the [e4]-pawn is hanging, and our bishop is not doing much on [h3] anyway.} Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4,Ye4e3,Yf5c2] Protecting [e4], and creating the threat to play ...[e3]+ at any moment.} 13. Qd5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd5f7] Qxf7 is a serious threat, but the king can take care of it by himself. 🙂} Kf6 $1 14. Nd7+ (14. Qxf7+ Kxe5 {And Black is just up a piece, since} 15. Qxf8 {allows forced checkmating lines after} Qd3+ {+ -+}) 14... Bxd7 {We have to take now since the d-pawn is not pinned, so ...[Kg5] is not that advisable.} 15. Qxd7 Bd6 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yd7d3] Cutting the queen from the [d3]-square will lead to a painful ...[Qd3]+ from Black.} 16. Qd8+ Kg6 $19 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gh7h5,Gg6h7,Gg8f6] Black is completely winning here, one way to finish the development after ...[Qd3]+ is to play ...[h5]-[Kh7] to protect the rook, and then we can develop the knight.} *

