rook can't be protected.} 10. Qxa8+ Ke7 11. Kd1 {White's king is running away from the checkmate.} (11. Nc6+ {is a funny line.} Kf6 12. Qd8+ Kg6 13. Ne5+ Kh5 {-+ The king is finally safe from checks, and Black can start collecting material.}) 11... Qxf1+ 12. Kc2 {[%cal Ra8e4] Now the [e4]-pawn is hanging, and our bishop is not doing much on [h3] anyway.} Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4,Ye4e3,Yf5c2] Protecting [e4], and creating the threat to play ...[e3]+ at any moment.} 13. Na3 {The most common move in the practice, but it is relatively easy to refute.} f6 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7] Once our king reaches [f7], it is going to be pretty safe, especially compared to White's king.} 14. Nc6+ Kf7 15. Nd4 Qd3+ {[%csl Ra1,Rc1] Blocking out the [c1]-bishop and the [a1]-rook from the game.} 16. Kb3 Bg4 {[%cal Rg4d1] ...[Bd1]+ is very unpleasant.} 17. Nac2 c5 18. Qd5+ Kg6 19. f3 {Just to stop ...[Bd1] for the moment.} exf3 20. Ne1 Ne7 $19 {And Black is completely winning, with or without the queens on the board.} *

