1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. d4 $2 {A very bad move, but pretty popular in online chess.} dxe4 $1 {By the most obvious moves we are going to get a clearly better endgame.} 5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {[%csl Yc3,Rd1,Ye5][%cal Gb1c3,Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Gc8f5,Ge8c8] After a few trades, we can see that the position appears to be almost level. However, Black has a few small advantages in this position. Our knight can easily attack White's weakness on [e5], we can cover our own weak pawn with ...[Bf5], and most importantly, White's has lost their castling rights. Black will probably finish development with ... [O-O-O] and gain another tempo.} Bf5 8. Be3 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6]} 9. Nd2 O-O-O $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7c6,Yc6e5] With ...[Nc6] coming next, White has great chances to lose a pawn very early on.} *

