[PlyCount "42"]
[GameId "2160376113749776"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Qa4 {[%csl Yc6,Ge4][%cal Yf3e5,Ga4e4] White is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn by pinning the knight on [c6], but also protecting the [e4]-pawn.} ({•} 4. d3 Nf6 {transposes here.}) ({•} 4. exd5 Qxd5 {And our queen is doing very well on [d5].} 5. d4 Bf5 {transposes here.}) 4... Bd7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yc6d4,Rd7a4] The Caro Variation. It is a pawn sacrifice for a lead in development and the initiative.} 5. exd5 {Pretty much the only move for White.} Nd4 {[%cal Rd7a4,Rd4c2]} 6. Qd1 {Again the only move as the queen has to guard the [c2]-square.} Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 (7. gxf3 $2 Qh4 8. d3 O-O-O {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, because of White's ruined structure and weak king.}) 7... Nf6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1][%cal Yf6d5,Ge5e4] Up to this moment the Caro Variation is pretty forced, now White has a choice. How to protect the pawn on [d5], and how to slow down Black's play in the centre and kingside are the main questions for our opponent.} 8. c4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc4d5] Besides protecting the [d5]-pawn, this move also gives a square for the [b1]-knight, which is very important regarding White's development.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Yf2][%cal Gc7c6,Gc5f2] This is the most active square for the bishop, and in some cases hitting the [f2]-pawn can be critical. Our goal here is to break up the centre by playing ...[c6], but first is to finish the development.} 9. Nc3 O-O {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge5e4,Gf6g4,Gg4f2] Now besides the positional idea of ...[c6], we also have stronger threats, such as pushing ...[e4] or attack the [f2]-pawn by playing ...[Ng4].} 10. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White is ready to castle and ...[e4] doesn't look so dangerous from Black, but we have another idea also.} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rg4f2,Rc5f2,Gf7f5] Opening the way for the f-pawn with a tempo.} 11. O-O (11. Ne4 Bd4 12. h3 Nh6 {∞ Next is ...[f5], giving huge initiative for Black.}) 11... f5 {[%cal Ge5e4] The threat is ...[e4].} 12. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4]} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6g6,Gg6h6] The rook can join the attack via the 6th rank.} 13. h3 Qh4 {[%csl Gg4,Gh4] We don't have to retreat with the knight, since taking it would mean a quick loss for White. Black has strong compensation for the pawn. We can play with ...[c6] or ... [e4], and the a-rook can join the game via [a6] or [e8].} 14. Nb5 (14. hxg4 $4 {is pretty much losing on the spot.} fxg4 15. g3 {Relatively the best, but White is losing material here as well.} gxf3 16. gxh4 fxe2 17. Nxe2 Bh3 {-+ (15.Qe4 Leads to a mate in 5 for Black. 15...Bxf2+ 16.Rxf2 Qxf2+ 17.Kh2 g3 + -+)}) 14... e4 $1 {Black is continuing very aggressively, rightly so!} 15. Qf4 exd3 16. Bxd3 Rae8 $1 {Our last piece is joining the attack, and White's position is very difficult. Our last move also sets a nice trap.} 17. Nxc7 $2 Re4 $1 {Black is crashing through by activating the [f8]-rook with this sacrifice.} 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. hxg4 Rxf4 20. Bxf4 g5 21. Be5 e3 $19 {And it is a checkmate or a lot of material for Black.} *

