, as it concedes time to Black, neglecting development.} Bxc6 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6][%cal Rc5f2,Rc6g2]} 12. Qg3 {The strong idea of [Bh6] is saving White from getting into big trouble.} e4 {[%csl Ye1][%cal Gf8e8,Ge4d3] Trying to open up the position for White's king.} (12... Nh5 $5 13. Qg5 Qxg5 14. Bxg5 Nf4 {∞ Also gives excellent compensation for Black with very active minor pieces.}) 13. Bh6 $1 {[%cal Ge1c1,Rg3g7] Not only threatening mate, but also preparing to castle queenside.} Nh5 14. Qe5 $6 {[%cal Re5c5,Re5h5] It leads to some crazy lines, all of which end favorably for Black.} Bd4 $1 {Sacrificing the knight, which was only defending [g7].} 15. Qxh5 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Yc3,Ye1,Yf2,Yh6][%cal Rd4c3,Rf6f2,Yg7h6] White is under attack everywhere!} 16. Bd2 g6 {Forcing the queen to a worse square, before starting to take material.} 17. Qe2 (17. Qg4 Qxf2+ 18. Kd1 e3 {∓ Taking back the piece with a much better position, since} 19. Be1 {is losing to ...[Qxb2], while 19.Bc1 Bxc3 and the bishop can't be taken back, because of [Ba4] mate.}) 17... exd3 18. Qxd3 Bxf2+ {[%csl Ye1][%cal Ge8e1,Gd8d1] Black managed to open the files in the centre. White's king is in big troubles.} 19. Kd1 Rfd8 20. Nd5 {White is trying to close the d-file, and it doesn't look so bad.} Rxd5 $1 {With this sacrifice, Black is opening the c-file.} 21. cxd5 Ba4+ 22. Kc1 (22. Ke2 Re8+ {+ -+ White has to give up a lot of material.}) 22... Bd4 $17 {[%csl Ya1,Rc1,Yf1,Yh1][%cal Rd4b2,Ga8c8] Down a full rook, but once the rook is coming to [c8], Black is going to retain the material and more.} *

