1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Qa4 {White is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn by pinning the knight on [c6], but also protecting the [e4]-pawn.} ({•} 4. d3 Nf6 {transposes here.}) ({•} 4. exd5 Qxd5 {And our queen is doing very well on [d5].} 5. d4 Bf5 {transposes here.}) 4... Bd7 {The Caro Variation. It is a pawn sacrifice for a lead in development and the initiative.} 5. exd5 {Pretty much the only move for White.} Nd4 6. Qd1 {Again the only move as the queen has to guard the [c2]-square.} Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 (7. gxf3 $2 Qh4 8. d3 O-O-O {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, because of White's ruined structure and weak king.}) 7... Nf6 {Up to this moment the Caro Variation is pretty forced, now White has a choice. How to protect the pawn on [d5], and how to slow down Black's play in the centre and kingside are the main questions for our opponent.} 8. Bc4 {The main move by a large margin. White is overprotecting the pawn on [d5] and gets ready to castle.} ({•} 8. d3 $2 {Stops ...[e4] but gives back the pawn right away.} Bg4 9. Qg3 Qxd5 {∓ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black has a space advantage and more active pieces.}) ({•} 8. h3 $6 {White stops ...[Bg4] ideas, but there were more important things to do in the position.} Bc5 {(8...c6!? Continuing in gambit-style is also possible according to the computer. )} 9. Bc4 e4 10. Qg3 Qe7 $1 {∓ Black will castle long and the [g7]-pawn is too dangerous to take since it will open the g-file for us. The queen on [g3] is also misplaced, exposed to ...[Bd6] or ...[Nh5] ideas.}) ({•} 8. d4 $6 {White is trying to speed up the development for the pieces on the queenside, the problem with the move that it fails to keep the extra pawn.} exd4 9. Bg5 Be7 {...[Nxd5] tactics are in the air, because the knight is protecting the bishop on [e7].} 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nxd5 $1 {Secures a slight edge for Black.} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. cxd4 Bc6 {⩱ White has an IQP, which is well blockaded, there is no active play to compensate for it, so Black can be very optimistic here.}) 8... b5 {A pretty logical try to improve on the main line, which is 8...[e4] and almost exclusively played. The point is that once we play ...[e4], White's queen is going to drop back to [e2] and control the [b5]-square, so we can't insert this move so easily anymore. Eventually, kicking the bishop away from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal can help to regain the pawn on [d5], but even if we just win some space there, it is a good deal for Black.} 9. Bb3 (9. Be2 $6 {Was tried in practice, but doesn't make too much sense.} Bd6 {White can't prevent both ...[e4] and ...[Bg4] so they are already in trouble.} 10. h3 {(10.d3 Bg4 11.Qe3 Nxd5 Black regains the pawn with the space and development advantage. 12.Qg5 Qxg5 13.Bxg5 Be6 ⩱)} e4 $1 11. Qe3 O-O {White's position looks bad, and it is bad. 🙂} 12. c4 Re8 13. O-O c6 {↑ With huge activity for Black. It can be instructive if you try out a few lines for White here, just to see how easily such positions can collapse.}) 9... e4 {Of course! We are not waiting for White to play [d3] and be pretty solid.} 10. Qg3 $2 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Yg3g7] Ugly, but it can happen easily, since apparently White slows down our development on the kingside.} Bd6 $1 {Not really! The pawn on [g7] contains some poison.} 11. Qxg7 Rg8 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Rg8g2] White is only moving around with their queen, while Black's rook is coming to the second rank.} 12. Qh6 Rxg2 $19 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Gg2,Yh6][%cal Gd8e7,Ge8c8] Black is completely winning here. Not only White's queen made a lot of moves, it is also very badly placed.} *

