 [g3] is also misplaced, exposed to ...[Bd6] or ...[Nh5] ideas.}) ({•} 8. d4 $6 {White is trying to speed up the development for the pieces on the queenside, the problem with the move that it fails to keep the extra pawn.} exd4 9. Bg5 Be7 {...[Nxd5] tactics are in the air, because the knight is protecting the bishop on [e7].} 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nxd5 $1 {Secures a slight edge for Black.} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. cxd4 Bc6 {⩱ White has an IQP, which is well blockaded, there is no active play to compensate for it, so Black can be very optimistic here.}) 8... b5 {A pretty logical try to improve on the main line, which is 8...[e4] and almost exclusively played. The point is that once we play ...[e4], White's queen is going to drop back to [e2] and control the [b5]-square, so we can't insert this move so easily anymore. Eventually, kicking the bishop away from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal can help to regain the pawn on [d5], but even if we just win some space there, it is a good deal for Black.} 9. Bb3 (9. Be2 $6 {Was tried in practice, but doesn't make too much sense.} Bd6 {White can't prevent both ...[e4] and ...[Bg4] so they are already in trouble.} 10. h3 {(10.d3 Bg4 11.Qe3 Nxd5 Black regains the pawn with the space and development advantage. 12.Qg5 Qxg5 13.Bxg5 Be6 ⩱)} e4 $1 11. Qe3 O-O {White's position looks bad, and it is bad. 🙂} 12. c4 Re8 13. O-O c6 {↑ With huge activity for Black. It can be instructive if you try out a few lines for White here, just to see how easily such positions can collapse.}) 9... e4 {Of course! We are not waiting for White to play [d3] and be pretty solid.} 10. Qe2 Bd6 {Continuing normal development, and the bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 11. d4 {Since castling is very risky because of ... [Ng4] ideas, White first wants to develop the bishop to [g5].} O-O 12. h3 {Instead of pinning the knight on [f6], White is stopping Black's main attacking ideas by controlling the [g4]-square.} a5 {A useful move to make. Perhaps on a good day, the rook can join the attack via [a6].} 13. a3 Kh8 {Like Bobby Fischer did against the Maróczy-setup, Black is aiming for ...[g5]!} 14. O-O g5 {The firepower is there to attack!} 15. Bxg5 {White accepts the pawn sacrifice, but it opens the g-file for Black.} Rg8 {Should the bishop move, ...[Bxh3] is already a problem for White.} 16. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3g5,Ge3h3]} ({The question, of course, is how can Black break through.} 16. f4 exf3 17. Bxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxf3 Qh4 {-+ Black's attack continues without sacrificing anything.}) 16... Bxh3 {Not an easy move to find without the help of the engine. 🙂} 17. Bxf6+ {White is winning a piece.} Qxf6 18. Qxh3 Rxg2+ {Black sacrifices everything!} 19. Kxg2 (19. Qxg2 Rg8 20. Qxg8+ Kxg8 {-+ Although White is doing very well material-wise, they simply cannot use it because their king is so weak, and Nd2 is met by ...Qg5 . White can try many moves here, but the evaluation starts at -5.}) 19... Rg8+ 20. Kh1 Rg4 {The only winning move! Black wins the queen with ...[Rh4] next. White can't really take the rook.} 21. Qxg4 Qh6+ 22. Kg2 Qh2# {With only two pieces left, Black manages to mate White.} *

