 in the position.} Bc5 {(8...c6!? Continuing in gambit-style is also possible according to the computer. )} 9. Bc4 e4 10. Qg3 Qe7 $1 {∓ Black will castle long and the [g7]-pawn is too dangerous to take since it will open the g-file for us. The queen on [g3] is also misplaced, exposed to ...[Bd6] or ...[Nh5] ideas.}) ({•} 8. d4 $6 {White is trying to speed up the development for the pieces on the queenside, the problem with the move that it fails to keep the extra pawn.} exd4 9. Bg5 Be7 {...[Nxd5] tactics are in the air, because the knight is protecting the bishop on [e7].} 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nxd5 $1 {Secures a slight edge for Black.} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. cxd4 Bc6 {⩱ White has an IQP, which is well blockaded, there is no active play to compensate for it, so Black can be very optimistic here.}) 8... b5 $5 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yf3e2,Ye2b5,Rb7b5] A pretty logical try to improve on the main line, which is 8...[e4] and almost exclusively played. The point is that once we play ...[e4], White's queen is going to drop back to [e2] and control the [b5]-square, so we can't insert this move so easily anymore. Bothering the bishop from the queenside can help to regain the pawn on [d5], but even if we just win some space there, it is a good deal for Black.} 9. Bb3 (9. Be2 $6 {Was tried in practice, but doesn't make too much sense.} Bd6 {White can't prevent both ...[e4] and ...[Bg4] so they are already in trouble.} 10. h3 {(10.d3 Bg4 11.Qe3 Nxd5 Black regains the pawn with the space and development advantage. 12.Qg5 Qxg5 13.Bxg5 Be6 ⩱)} e4 $1 11. Qe3 O-O {White's position looks bad, and it is bad. 🙂} 12. c4 Re8 13. O-O c6 {↑ With huge activity for Black. It can be instructive if you try out a few lines for White here, just to see how easily such positions can collapse.}) 9... e4 $1 {Of course! We are not waiting for White to play [d3] and be pretty solid.} 10. Qe2 Bd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yd6h2] Continuing normal development, and the bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 11. d4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] Since castling is very risky because of ... [Ng4] ideas, White first wants to develop the bishop to [g5].} ({•} 11. O-O $6 {It is not good to castle too early, since from now on White has to count on ...[Ng4] ideas.} O-O {(11...Ng4!? is already interesting at this moment. 12.h3 Nh2 Quite exotic, but works according to the engine. 🙂 )} 12. d3 Bg4 13. Qe3 Re8 {∓ Black is extremely active and has great chances to attack on the kingside.}) ({•} 11. d3 {White is using the pin, but there are more things about to happen on the e-file!} O-O 12. dxe4 Bg4 $1 {A great move with a nice tactical point. (12...Nxe4 13.Be3 ∞)} 13. f3 {(13.Qd3 Nxe4! 14.O-O f5 ↑ ...[Qh4] is coming next, White will have a tough time to defend the king. )} Nxe4 $1 {Very nice! Everything is hanging, but nothing can be taken. 🙂} 14. Be3 Re8 {→ White is pinned with a weak king, it doesn't look good for our opponent.}) 11... O-O 12. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4,Yf6g4,Yd7g4] Instead of pinning the knight on [f6], White is stopping Black's main attacking ideas by controlling the [g4]-square.} a5 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6g6,Ga5a4] A useful move to make. Perhaps on a good day, the rook can join the attack via [a6].} 13. a3 Kh8 $1 {Like Bobby Fischer did against the Maróczy-setup, Black is aiming for ...[g5]!} 14. O-O g5 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Gf6,Gf8] The firepower is there to attack!} 15. f3 {[%cal Gf3g4] White is stopping [g4], and it looks like that we may have exposed ourselves too much on the kingside.} g4 $3 {[%csl Ra1,Ga8,Rb1,Rb3,Rc1,Gd6,Gd7,Gd8,Gf6,Gf8] Black has 4 more pieces which can join the attack, so we have plenty of room to even sacrifice a few. 🙂} 16. fxg4 (16. fxe4 Nxe4 $1 17. Qxe4 Re8 18. Qd3 Qh4 {-+ The g-file is about to be opened, and White's king is about to be checkmated.}) 16... Nh5 $3 {[%cal Rf8g8,Rg8g2,Yh5g3] All that matters is the open g-file. 🙂} 17. gxh5 Rg8 $19 {[%cal Rd7h3,Rd8h4] There is no defence for White, Black's attack is too strong.} *

