1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Rf3e5,Gf3d4] By far the most common move. White is developing with a tempo and gets one move closer to castling.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yc6e5,Yf3d4,Yf3e5] Covering the same central squares as White did with [Nf3], and protecting the pawn on [e5].} 3. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The Ponziani Opening. White wants to build a strong centre by playing [d4], but for now the pawn on [c3] is taking away the square from the knight, which allows Black to strike first in the centre.} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yd8d5]} ({The main line is} 3... Nf6 {, but I don't mind having the queen on [d5] because it can't be kicked away by the knight jumping on [c3].}) 4. Qa4 {[%csl Yc6,Ge4][%cal Yf3e5,Ga4e4] White is not only attacking the [e5]-pawn by pinning the knight on [c6], but also protecting the [e4]-pawn.} ({•} 4. d3 Nf6 {transposes here.}) ({•} 4. exd5 Qxd5 {And our queen is doing very well on [d5].} 5. d4 Bf5 {transposes here.}) 4... Bd7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yc6d4,Rd7a4] The Caro Variation. It is a pawn sacrifice for a lead in development and the initiative.} 5. exd5 {Pretty much the only move for White.} Nd4 {[%cal Rd7a4,Rd4c2]} 6. Qd1 {Again the only move as the queen has to guard the [c2]-square.} Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 (7. gxf3 $2 Qh4 8. d3 O-O-O {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, because of White's ruined structure and weak king.}) 7... Nf6 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1][%cal Yf6d5,Ge5e4] Up to this moment the Caro Variation is pretty forced, now White has a choice. How to protect the pawn on [d5], and how to slow down Black's play in the centre and kingside are the main questions for our opponent.} 8. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d5,Ge1g1] The main move by a large margin. White is overprotecting the pawn on [d5] and gets ready to castle.} ({•} 8. d3 $2 {Stops ...[e4] but gives back the pawn right away.} Bg4 9. Qg3 Qxd5 {∓ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black has a space advantage and more active pieces.}) ({•} 8. h3 $6 {White stops ...[Bg4] ideas, but there were more important things to do in the position.} Bc5 {(8...c6!? Continuing in gambit-style is also possible according to the computer. )} 9. Bc4 e4 10. Qg3 Qe7 $1 {∓ Black will castle long and the [g7]-pawn is too dangerous to take since it will open the g-file for us. The queen on [g3] is also misplaced, exposed to ...[Bd6] or ...[Nh5] ideas.}) ({•} 8. d4 $6 {White is trying to speed up the development for the pieces on the queenside, the problem with the move that it fails to keep the extra pawn.} exd4 9. Bg5 Be7 {...[Nxd5] tactics are in the air, because the knight is protecting the bishop on [e7].} 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nxd5 $1 {Secures a slight edge for Black.} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. cxd4 Bc6 {⩱ White has an IQP, which is well blockaded, there is no active play to compensate for it, so Black can be very optimistic here.}) 8... b5 $5 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yf3e2,Ye2b5,Rb7b5] A pretty logical try to improve on the main line, which is 8...[e4] and almost exclusively played. The point is that once we play ...[e4], White's queen is going to drop back to [e2] and control the [b5]-square, so we can't insert this move so easily anymore. Bothering the bishop from the queenside can help to regain the pawn on [d5], but even if we just win some space there, it is a good deal for Black.} 9. Bb3 (9. Be2 $6 {Was tried in practice, but doesn't make too much sense.} Bd6 {White can't prevent both ...[e4] and ...[Bg4] so they are already in trouble.} 10. h3 {(10.d3 Bg4 11.Qe3 Nxd5 Black regains the pawn with the space and development advantage. 12.Qg5 Qxg5 13.Bxg5 Be6 ⩱)} e4 $1 11. Qe3 O-O {White's position looks bad, and it is bad. 🙂} 12. c4 Re8 13. O-O c6 {↑ With huge activity for Black. It can be instructive if you try out a few lines for White here, just to see how easily such positions can collapse.}) 9... e4 $1 {Of course! We are not waiting for White to play [d3] and be pretty solid.} 10. Qe2 (10. Qg3 $2 {Bad, but can easily happen, since seemingly White's slows down our development on the kingside.} Bd6 $1 {Not really! The pawn on [g7] contains some poison.} 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qh6 Rxg2 {-+ Black is completely winning here, White is only playing with the queen.}) 10... Bd6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yd6h2] Continuing normal development, and the bishop is very strong on this diagonal.} 11. d4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] Since castling is very risky because of ... [Ng4] ideas, White first wants to develop the bishop to [g5].} ({•} 11. O-O $6 {It is not good to castle too early, since from now on White has to count on ...[Ng4] ideas.} O-O {(11...Ng4!? is already interesting at this moment. 12.h3 Nh2 Quite exotic, but works according to the engine. 🙂 )} 12. d3 Bg4 13. Qe3 Re8 {∓ Black is extremely active and has great chances to attack on the kingside.}) ({•} 11. d3 {White is using the pin, but there are more things about to happen on the e-file!} O-O 12. dxe4 Bg4 $1 {A great move with a nice tactical point. (12...Nxe4 13.Be3 ∞)} 13. f3 {(13.Qd3 Nxe4! 14.O-O f5 ↑ ...[Qh4] is coming next, White will have a tough time to defend the king. )} Nxe4 $1 {Very nice! Everything is hanging, but nothing can be taken. 🙂} 14. Be3 Re8 {→ White is pinned with a weak king, it doesn't look good for our opponent.}) 11... O-O 12. Bg5 (12. O-O $2 {This move is still bad.} Ng4 $1 {Black's attack is very dangerous.} 13. h3 {(13.g3 f5 ∓ With ... [Qe8]-[h5] coming, Black is in great shape. )} Nh2 $1 14. Re1 Qh4 {The next is to push the f-pawn till [f3]. 🙂} 15. Qxe4 $2 {loses to} Rae8 {-+}) 12... h6 13. Bh4 (13. Bxf6 {With the potential idea of going for long castle, but the king is not much safer on that side of the board, with Black's pawns already about to launch an attack there.} Qxf6 14. Nd2 Rae8 15. O-O-O Qg6 {∞ With both ...[a5]-[a4] and ...[f5]-[f4] coming, Black is in an excellent shape.}) 13... a5 {[%cal Ra5a4,Yg7g5,Rf6d5] Threatening to play ...[a4] with the [d5]-pawn losing its protection, so after an eventual ...[g5] we can simply regain the material with ...[Nxd5].} 14. a4 g5 $1 {[%cal Rf6d5] This is the right time to include this move.} (14... bxa4 {Would be somewhat inaccurate, because of} 15. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 16. Bxa4 {And Black still has to work to get back the [d5]-pawn.}) 15. Bg3 bxa4 16. Ba2 (16. Bxa4 Bxa4 17. Rxa4 Qd7 18. Ra1 Nxd5 {⩱ With ...[f5] coming next, Black is quite significantly better here with the strong centre.}) 16... Rb8 $15 {[%cal Rb8b2,Yf6g4,Gd7g4,Yf6h5] Black has a nice position. After White castles, our ideas include starting to push the f-pawn. This can be prepared by ...[Ng4] immediately or alternatively and maybe even better is to play ...[Bg4] and then ...[Nh5], so besides ...[f5], we also have the possibility to go for ...[Nf4].} *

