[White "7) Scotch Gambit 5.O-O And Rare 5th Moves"]
[Black "Göring Gambit - 4.c3 d5 5.exd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "54"]
[GameId "2160376114409246"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 {As it was mentioned in the Centre Game chapter, we can also reach this position by playing 2. [d4], so our choice should be the same. Instead of accepting the material, we should play ...[d5]!} d5 $1 5. exd5 (5. Bd3 {The only somewhat decent alternative to 5. [exd5], but of course by playing in such a modest way, White cannot hope for much from the opening.} Bg4 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e5 Nd7 9. Bb5 dxc3 10. Nxc3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {⩱}) 5... Qxd5 6. cxd4 (6. Nxd4 $6 {Puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4f3,Rg4d1,Rc6d4] Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 7. Nc3 {This is quite a long and forced line where Black is completely fine and it is White should know a few things to be safe.} Bxf3 (7... Bb4 $5 {In case you don't want to learn the line with 7... [Bxf3], then this move gives good chances to transpose into 7. [Be2] main lines.}) 8. Nxd5 (8. gxf3 $6 Qxd4 9. Be3 Qb4 {⩱ White has no compensation for the pawn.}) 8... Bxd1 9. Nxc7+ Kd7 10. Nxa8 Bh5 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc6d4] White is temporarily up an exchange and a pawn, but since the knight from [a8] most likely will be trapped it is White who has to be very precise here in order to avoid trouble.} 11. d5 (11. Bb5 $2 {Allows Black to collect the knight on a8 without any complications. 11...Nf6! 12.O-O Bd6 ∓}) 11... Nd4 {[%cal Rd4c2]} 12. Bd3 Bg6 $1 {[%cal Rd4c2] A key move for Black, making sure that ...[Nc2] will be a threat again.} 13. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Rd4c2]} 14. Kd1 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3a7] White's idea now is to play [Be3] and take on [a7], enabling the knight to come back from [a8]. Therefore our task is to maintain the knight on [d4].} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh6f5,Gf5d4]} 15. Be3 Nhf5 16. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] The only move for White to stay in the game. The threat is [g4] and then taking the pawn on [f7] after the trade on [e3].} Nxe3+ (16... Bd6 $2 17. g4 $1 {±}) 17. fxe3 Nf5 18. Rf3 Bd6 {[%cal Rh8a8]} 19. e4 Rxh2 $5 20. Rc1 (20. exf5 {Probably also good enough to make a draw.} Rh1+ 21. Kc2 Rxa1 22. fxg6 fxg6 23. Rf7+ Kc8 24. Rxg7 Rxa2 25. Rg8+ Kd7 26. Rg7+ Kc8) 20... Rh1+ 21. Kd2 Bb4+ {Black will win a piece, but the game will remain very complicated, with mutual chances.} 22. Kc2 Nd4+ 23. Kd3 Rxc1 24. Rxf7+ (24. Kxd4 $4 f6 {-+ Black is taking the knight on [a8], and winning the game.}) 24... Ke8 25. Rxb7 Rd1+ 26. Kc4 Bd6 27. Rxa7 Be5 $13 {With the draw as the most likely result. Black is not risking much here, since ...[Rc1]+ and ...[Rd1] is available as a perpetual.} *

