[White "7) Scotch Gambit 5.O-O And Rare 5th Moves"]
[Black "Göring Gambit - 4.c3 d5 5.exd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2160376114462495"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 {As it was mentioned in the Centre Game chapter, we can also reach this position by playing 2. [d4], so our choice should be the same. Instead of accepting the material, we should play ...[d5]!} d5 $1 5. exd5 (5. Bd3 {The only somewhat decent alternative to 5. [exd5], but of course by playing in such a modest way, White cannot hope for much from the opening.} Bg4 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e5 Nd7 9. Bb5 dxc3 10. Nxc3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {⩱}) 5... Qxd5 6. cxd4 (6. Nxd4 $6 {Puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4f3,Rg4d1,Rc6d4] Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position. We made all the logical developing moves, but now, surprisingly, Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $1 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square, and if it goes away we have to count on [d5]!, and if we take on [c3] at some moment instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} (8... O-O-O $6 9. O-O Qa5 10. Be3 {⩲}) 9. Bxf3 Qc4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc4f1,Ge1g1,Yb4c3,Yc4c3] This is the surprising square, where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 10. Qb3 {White is further compromising their pawn structure, but the doubled b-pawns will mean an open a-file for the rook.} Qxb3 (10... Qxd4 $4 {is way too greedy, and will most likely result in a quick loss for Black.} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O {+-}) 11. Bxc6+ {White is making our structure worse, but they have to give up the bishop pair in order to do so.} bxc6 12. axb3 a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4] The tandem of the a-pawn + the bishop are holding together our queenside pretty nicely, giving our rooks free play.} 13. O-O ({•} 13. Bf4 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Ne7 {⩱ The most relevant weakness in the position is the [d4]-pawn, which we will attack by doubling on the d-file and playing ...[Nf5].}) ({•} 13. Be3 Ne7 14. Ke2 f6 {⩱ Black's position is more pleasant, we can play moves like ...[Kf7], ... [Rab8]-[Rhd8] and start attacking White's weaknesses on [b3] and [d4].}) 13... Ne7 {Black has no problems, and it is White who has to be careful to maintain the balance.} 14. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rd2] The key towards equality lies in the trade of the bishops. If White manages to trade our [b4]-bishop, then our opponent will also have some targets to attack.} Nf5 15. Rfe1+ Kd7 16. Red1 Rhb8 $10 {The position is equal, but still far from draw.} *

