1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 {As it was mentioned in the Centre Game chapter, we can also reach this position by playing 2. [d4], so our choice should be the same. Instead of accepting the material, we should play ...[d5]!} d5 $1 5. exd5 (5. Bd3 {The only somewhat decent alternative to 5. [exd5], but of course by playing in such a modest way, White cannot hope for much from the opening.} Bg4 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e5 Nd7 9. Bb5 dxc3 10. Nxc3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {⩱}) 5... Qxd5 6. cxd4 (6. Nxd4 $6 {Puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4f3,Rg4d1,Rc6d4] Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position. We made all the logical developing moves, but now, surprisingly, Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $1 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square, and if it goes away we have to count on [d5]!, and if we take on [c3] at some moment instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} (8... O-O-O $6 9. O-O Qa5 10. Be3 {⩲}) 9. Bxf3 Qc4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc4f1,Ge1g1,Yb4c3,Yc4c3] This is the surprising square, where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 10. Qb3 {White is further compromising their pawn structure, but the doubled b-pawns will mean an open a-file for the rook.} Qxb3 (10... Qxd4 $4 {is way too greedy, and will most likely result in a quick loss for Black.} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O {+-}) 11. axb3 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3,Rd4][%cal Ga1a7] White's structure is pretty bad for an endgame, but the rook on [a1] has become pretty active.} Nge7 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3,Gc6,Rd4][%cal Ge7c6] The position is completely equal according to the computer, but this is the type of equality which can turn into ⩱ seemingly without any reason very soon. 🙂 Of course, the reason for that is that White's structure is clearly worse, which can't always be compensated for by active pieces.} (11... Nxd4 {This move pretty much makes a draw on the spot, but I don't see any need to go for this.} 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Rxa7 Bc5 14. Ra8 Rxa8 15. Bxa8 Nf6 16. O-O O-O 17. Bb7 Nxb3 {With so little material on the board, the draw is very likely.}) 12. O-O (12. Be3 O-O-O 13. O-O a6 {transposes.}) 12... O-O-O {[%cal Rd8d4] Black has many other good moves, but it looks logical to finish the development and put pressure on the [d4]-pawn right away.} 13. Be3 ({•} 13. d5 $6 {White is trying to simplify the game, but it will not lead to complete equality.} Nd4 14. Rxa7 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxd5 {⩱ Black is better, thanks to White's weak structure on the kingside.}) ({•} 13. Bxc6 $6 {Another try to equalise on the spot, but this also fails.} Nxc6 14. d5 Na5 15. Ra4 c5 $1 16. dxc6 Nxc6 {⩱ White managed to get rid of one weakness, but the doubled b-pawns are staying on the board.}) 13... a6 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Ga6,Gb7][%cal Gb7a6] Very good move, since our a-pawn is not loose anymore, and it seriously reduces the role of the open a-file.} 14. Ra4 {[%cal Ra4b4,Rd4d5] White has [d5]-ideas, so it is time to remove the bishop into safety.} (14. Rfd1 Rhe8 15. Ra4 Bd6 {transposes.}) 14... Bd6 $10 {The position is objectively equal, but I believe Black has the much easier side of it, with the better pawn structure. Let's see a few possible continuations.} (14... Bd6 {•} 15. Rd1 Rhe8 16. g3 Kb8 17. Kf1 Na7 $1 {Again this knight maneuver is the way to make progress with Black.} 18. Be2 Nac8 19. Raa1 Nb6 {⩱}) (14... Bd6 {•} 15. g3 Kb8 16. h4 Na7 $1 {⇆ A typical idea which is worth knowing. The knight is going to [b6], and when possible, to [d5] in order to blockade the isolated pawn.}) (14... Bd6 {•} 15. Ne4 h6 $1 {There is no need to rush, and we are taking away the possibility of any [Ng5] jumps in the future.} 16. Rc1 (16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. dxc5 Rd3 {⩱ White can't really use their bishops, but Black can attack the weak pawns!}) 16... Rhe8 17. Kf1 Kb8 {With quite a few ideas for Black, like pushing ...[f5], or attacking on [d4] by playing ...[Nf5], and of course the standard ...[Na7]-[b5] or ...[Na7]-[c8]-[b6] plans are also available.}) *

