1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. c3 {As it was mentioned in the Centre Game chapter, we can also reach this position by playing 2. [d4], so our choice should be the same. Instead of accepting the material, we should play ...[d5]!} d5 $1 5. exd5 (5. Bd3 {The only somewhat decent alternative to 5. [exd5], but of course by playing in such a modest way, White cannot hope for much from the opening.} Bg4 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e5 Nd7 9. Bb5 dxc3 10. Nxc3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {⩱}) 5... Qxd5 6. cxd4 (6. Nxd4 $6 {Puts zero pressure on Black, who already has the better development.} Nf6 7. Be3 Bd7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is already better.}) 6... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4f3,Rg4d1,Rc6d4] Pinning the knight and therefore putting more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 7. Be2 {This is a much better way to protect the pawn on [d4] than [Be3], since it also prepares for castling at the same time, and doesn't allow Black to get much superior pawn structure with the doubled f-pawns.} Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {This is the critical position. We made all the logical developing moves, but now, surprisingly, Black has only one good move.} Bxf3 $1 {This move takes away the dangerous dynamic possibilities from White. On any other move White would castle and our position would be very unpleasant, because our queen can't really find a good square, and if it goes away we have to count on [d5]!, and if we take on [c3] at some moment instead of moving the queen, then the idea of [c4] is tough to stop.} (8... O-O-O $6 9. O-O Qa5 10. Be3 {⩲}) 9. Bxf3 Qc4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc4f1,Ge1g1,Yb4c3,Yc4c3] This is the surprising square, where our queen feels comfortable, preventing White from castling and exerting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 {[%csl Ga7,Gb7,Gc7] More ambitious than the usual recapture 10...[bxc6], which normally leads to a pretty equal position.} (10... bxc6 11. Qe2+ Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 O-O-O 13. Be3 Ne7 {Many games have been played from this position, which is equal. If you don't want to remember too much in this line then this is also a perfectly acceptable way to play.}) 11. O-O Ne7 {[%csl Rd4,Re8][%cal Ge8g8] White has to react quickly here, otherwise Black just castles and will have a long-term advantage because of the IQP.} 12. d5 Qd7 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Rd7a4] The queen has to keep the [a4]-square under control, to avoid [Qa4]+.} 13. Qd4 {[%cal Rd4b4,Rd4g7] The only active moves from White are connected by attacking our [b4]-bishop.} Bxc3 14. bxc3 (14. Qxc3 $2 O-O {∓ And White is losing the [d5]-pawn for no compensation.}) 14... Qxd5 {[%csl Re8] We won a pawn, but our king is still in the centre.} 15. Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4e7] The best try from White in order to keep our king in the centre.} ({•} 15. Qxg7 $4 {Fortunately White can't take here.} Rg8 16. c4 Qc6 {-+}) ({•} 15. Qb4 c5 $1) ({•} 15. Qe3 Qe6 $1 {A huge tempo for Black!} 16. Qc5 O-O 17. Qxc7 Nd5 {⩱ Even though White has regained the pawn, Black's structure is superior and very importantly,} 18. Qxb7 $4 {doesn't work, because} Rfb8 {-+ Traps the queen!}) 15... f6 16. Ba3 (16. Re1 $4 {Doesn't stop castling, because of the weak back rank.} O-O-O {-+}) 16... Nf5 17. Qa4+ b5 18. Qc2 O-O-O $10 {[%csl Gd5]} (18... O-O-O {The pawn on b5 weakens our king, but since our queen is so well positioned in the centre of the board White has nothing better than forcing a repetition in this position.} 19. Rfd1 Qe6 20. Re1 Qd5) *

