r too much in this line then this is also a perfectly acceptable way to play.}) 11. O-O Ne7 {[%csl Rd4,Re8][%cal Ge8g8] White has to react quickly here, otherwise Black just castles and will have a long-term advantage because of the IQP.} 12. Qb3 a5 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6g6] It is useful for Black to wait for the [a3]-move if White wants to get the bishop, since it will take away the [a3]-square from the bishop and sometimes the rook can be activated via [a5] or [a6].} 13. a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5,Gc4,Gd5] Black has very nice control over the light squares on the queenside.} 15. Qc2 (15. Qb4 $6 Nd5 $1 16. Re1+ Kd7 17. Qb1 g6 {⩱ Black has a clear advantage with the very strong knight on [d5], and the king can walk into safety after we play ... [Rae8].}) 15... O-O {[%cal Gb7b5] ... [b5] is a very strong positional threat now.} 16. c4 b5 17. Be3 (17. c5 $4 Qd5 {∓ is a positional K.O. for White.}) 17... bxc4 18. Rfc1 Nd5 19. Qxc4 Qd6 $10 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rc4a4,Rc4c7] Black's knight is very strong, but White should be able to hold the balance here.} *

