1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Nxd4 $6 {This is not a good move. It is a mix between the Scotch Game and the Scotch Gambit, but it is better to go with either of those than to play this weird line.} Nxe4 $1 {Of course! There is no reason not to take a free pawn in the centre.} 6. O-O (6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qd5+ Kg7 9. Nxc6 {White is winning back the pawn, but they have to give up the bishop pair along the way, and Black will also have an extra pawn in the centre.} Qe8 $1 {Forcing White to trade into an endgame.} 10. Qe5+ Qxe5 11. Nxe5 Bb4+ 12. c3 Bc5 13. O-O d6 14. Nd3 Bb6 {⩱ Black is clearly better with the pair of bishops.}) 6... d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rd5c4,Gd5e4] Developing with tempo and stabilizing the knight on [e4].} 7. Bb5 Bd7 {I couldn't find any dangerous move for White from this position.} 8. Re1 ({•} 8. c4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bxb5 10. cxb5 Nc5 {The knight will be excellent on [e6].} 11. Nc3 c6 {⩱}) ({•} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Re1 Be7 10. f3 Nd6 11. Qe2 {There are many good plans here for Black, what I like most is} c5 12. Nb3 Nf5 13. Nxc5 O-O {∓ Where Black gives back the pawn, but thanks to the [f3]-move, White's king is not safe.}) 8... Qf6 $1 {[%cal Rf6f2,Rf6d4,Ge8c8]} 9. Be3 O-O-O $17 {[%csl Gd5] With a healthy extra pawn for Black.} *

