1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Ng5 $6 {This is not quite the Fried Liver Attack, which is a very respectable line. The inclusion of the moves [d4]-[exd4] greatly favours Black, since as we will see, it makes an early ...[Qe7]+ possible.} d5 6. exd5 Qe7+ $1 7. Kf1 ({Of course, not ideal, but White doesn't have better.} 7. Qe2 $2 Qxe2+ (7... Nb4 $1 {is even better according to the engine, but we don't need to study this position in detail.}) 8. Kxe2 Nb4 9. a3 Nbxd5 {∓ Black has a healthy extra pawn. (9.Na3 Bg4+ 10.f3 Bh5 ∓ With ...[O-O-O] coming in the next move. (9.d6? Nxc2 10.Nxf7 b5! -+ Black is winning a lot of material. ))}) 7... Ne5 8. Qxd4 Nxc4 9. Qxc4 {[%csl Gc8,Rf1,Gf8] White has won a pawn, but their king is in the centre and Black also has the pair of bishops.} h6 10. Nf3 Qc5 {[%csl Rd5] Showing White that the [d5]-pawn is pretty vulnerable!} 11. Qe2+ (11. Qxc5 Bxc5 {White has big problems here, they can't even equalise, despite being up a pawn.} 12. c4 Bf5 {∓ Black is clearly better. Next is ... [O-O-O] and ...[Rhe8], and we can undermine White's centre with ...[c6] or ...[b5] if needed.}) 11... Be7 12. Be3 (12. c4 {This move does not protect the pawn on [d5], since the [c4] pawn is pinned!} Nxd5 $1) 12... Qxd5 13. Nc3 Qe6 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Ge8g8] Black is better, with the safer king and also the pair of bishops.} *

