1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Nc3 {A funny line, which gained popularity in the recent years, mainly in online chess. Black has many good ways to meet it, but I would suggest to go in the safest way.} Nxc3 (6... dxc3 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Kf6 9. Re1 {is what White is hoping for.}) 7. bxc3 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are already two pawns up, so the main goal should be to finish development!} 8. cxd4 d5 ({On} 8... O-O 9. d5 {is somewhat unpleasant, so it was time to insert this move.}) 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6 {This is what White normally does, trying to regain the pawn, and frankly, it is tough to see anything better than this.} bxc6 11. Ne5 Bd6 $1 {We could stubbornly hold onto the pawn on [c6], but instead we can transfrom our advantage into having a more active position with the pair of bishops, and it is much easier to play like this.} 12. Nxc6 Qh4 13. Ne5 Bf5 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Gf5][%cal Gh4e4,Re4c2,Ga8b8,Gf8e8] Black is clearly better with easy moves, such as ...[Rab8] or ...[Rfe8] to follow. White is on the defensive side, which our opponent obviously will not like after having played the enterprising 6. [Nc3]?!!.} *

