1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Nc3 {A funny line, which gained popularity in the recent years, mainly in online chess. Black has many good ways to meet it, but I would suggest to go in the safest way.} Nxc3 (6... dxc3 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Kf6 9. Re1 {is what White is hoping for.}) 7. bxc3 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are already two pawns up, so the main goal should be to finish development!} 8. cxd4 d5 ({On} 8... O-O 9. d5 {is somewhat unpleasant, so it was time to insert this move.}) 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6 {This is what White normally does, trying to regain the pawn, and frankly, it is tough to see anything better than this.} bxc6 11. Re1 {This is the recommendation of Jonathan Schrantz vampirechicken in his course, Nakhmanson Gambit. He, too, is not very optimistic about White's chances, but he puts some tricks in place in case Black rushes with ...[c5].} Bb4 {Causing some confusion in White's camp and moving away the bishop from the [e7]-square, where it was under attack.} ({•} 11... c5 $2 {This would be a serious mistake and what White was waiting for with [Re1].} 12. Ba3 $1 {White is winning back the pawn.}) ({•} 11... Bd6 {Obviously a fine move, but Black is not getting ...[c5] yet.} 12. Qd3 {With the plan of [Ba3].}) 12. Bd2 ({•} 12. Re3 c5 $1 {With the point, that} 13. c3 {can be met by} cxd4 $1 {gaining a tempo on the rook.} 14. cxd4 a5 {⩱ White has nothing, just a struggle for the draw.}) ({•} 12. Re2 {Not ideal, allows Black to develop with tempo.} Bg4 13. Qd3 Qf6 {∓ With the threat of taking on [f3].}) 12... Bd6 {This bishop arrives in its ideal square. In addition, White doesn't have the option of playing [Qd3] and [Ba3]!} 13. Rb1 c5 $17 {Black gets rid of the doubled pawns and has excellent winning chances thanks to the extra pawn.} *

