1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. Nc3 $6 {Similarly to the previous move, this funny knight jump is available for White, but it brings nothing good.} dxc3 8. Bxd5 Be6 $1 {The key move of the line. We don't have to enter any kind of mess to have the upper hand.} (8... f5 9. Ng5 {⇆}) 9. Bxe4 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 cxb2 11. Bxb2 {[%csl Gb2,Gd1,Ge4] White has some advantage in the development to compensate for the missing pawn, but in any case, our opponent is just fighting for equality here, nothing more.} f6 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Gf6,Gg7][%cal Yb2f6,Yf3g5,Yf3e5,Ge8f7] Very nice move, restricting the bishop on [b2] and the knight on [f3], while also preparing a safe square for the king on [f7].} 12. Bc3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7] White is looking for counterplay against the [b7]-pawn.} (12. Re1 Kf7 13. Bc3 Bc5 {∓ With ...[Bb6] next if needed, Black is safely up a pawn.}) 12... Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] This position was quite heavily tested in correspondence chess, and this move was almost exclusively Black's choice. The plan is to protect the pawn on [b7] by playing ...[O-O-O].} 13. Rab1 O-O-O 14. Nd4 {Since the pawn on [b7] is hanging if our knight would move, White can create doubled c-pawns for Black.} Re8 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 {It is not a clean extra pawn, but it is obvious that White has a long fight ahead to make the draw from here.} *

