1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Yd4c3,Rd1d5,Ye4c3,Re1e8] The point of the whole variation, Black can't take on [c3], because both the queen and the king are pinned. Black has a wide choice here, with almost all the queen moves being quite okay.} Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 ({White has to take like this, the alternatives are much worse. For instance,} 9. Rxe4+ $2 Be6 10. Nxd4 O-O-O $1 {With a very unpleasant pin on the d-file!} 11. Be3 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Ba3 $1 {Spectacular and strong!} 13. Qb1 Bd6 {⩱ And Black is clearly better with the very strong bishops!}) 9... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8] Protecting the king from the discovered checks, and also preparing to play ... [O-O-O]. White has to react quickly, since otherwise Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Bg5 $2 {[%cal Rg5d8,Ye8c8] Prevents Black from castling, but not for long.} h6 $1 11. Bh4 Bb4 {[%cal Rb4e1] Developing with tempo and asking White some questions about the rook.} 12. Re2 ({•} 12. c3 {This is the better move according to the machine, but hard to see any compensation for White even after this.} dxc3 13. bxc3 Be7 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 {∓ With ...[O-O] coming next, Black has a nice extra pawn.}) ({•} 12. Nxd4 $4 Bxe1 {-+}) 12... g5 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] Making ...[O-O-O] available again.} 13. c3 {White is trying to create some complications.} ({•} 13. Nf6+ Ke7 {-+ Black is winning a piece.}) ({•} 13. a3 Be7 14. b4 Qd5 15. Bg3 O-O-O {-+ Black keeps the extra pawn without any problems.}) ({•} 13. Bg3 O-O-O {-+}) 13... dxc3 14. bxc3 Be7 15. Bg3 g4 {[%cal Ge8c8] The knight has to go to an awkward square if White wants to stop ...[O-O-O]. And they have to.} 16. Nh4 O-O $19 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ga5h5] With ...[Qh5] coming next, our king is perfectly safe, but the same can't be said about the knight on [h4].} *

