1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Yd4c3,Rd1d5,Ye4c3,Re1e8] The point of the whole variation, Black can't take on [c3], because both the queen and the king are pinned. Black has a wide choice here, with almost all the queen moves being quite okay.} Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 ({White has to take like this, the alternatives are much worse. For instance,} 9. Rxe4+ $2 Be6 10. Nxd4 O-O-O $1 {With a very unpleasant pin on the d-file!} 11. Be3 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Ba3 $1 {Spectacular and strong!} 13. Qb1 Bd6 {⩱ And Black is clearly better with the very strong bishops!}) 9... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8] Protecting the king from the discovered checks, and also preparing to play ... [O-O-O]. White has to react quickly, since otherwise Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Bd2 $5 {A decent alternative to the main line. Before committing to [Ng5] or [Bg5], White is asking one more question to Black's queen.} Qb5 $5 {[%cal Rb5b2] Only the 7th most common move in the position, but don't worry, the computer supports it. 🙂 The point is that sometimes the [b2]-pawn can be taken, which is not something the engine would support a few years or more ago.} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 {[%csl Ga5,Rb5] The queen would be much better placed on [a5] here, as you could see in the 10. [Bg5] lines. Here there is one key difference, which makes the line pretty okay for White.} Bc5 (12... Bb4 $2 {It would be a mistake to react the same way as with the queen on [a5].} 13. Nxd4 $1 {Here is the difference! With the queen on [a5] we just ignore this move and take the rook on [e1], but now our queen is hanging.} Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bxe1 15. Qxg7 {± And White is much better, since our king is very weak.}) 13. a4 (13. c4 $5 {This was also tried in a few games.} dxc3 14. a4 Qa5 15. bxc3 O-O 16. Rb1 a6 17. Nxc5 Qxc5 18. Rxb7 Na5 {The position is around equal, but there is still a lot of play left.}) 13... Qa5 14. Qd3 {A tricky way to prevent ...[O-O].} Bb4 (14... O-O $4 {Would allow} 15. Nf6+ $1 gxf6 16. Rxe6 {And White's attack is decisive.} fxe6 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Qxh6+ Kg8 19. Qg6+ Kh8 20. Bxf6+ Rxf6 21. Qxf6+ Kg8 22. Qxe6+ {+-}) 15. c3 ({This is a must, since} 15. Re2 {would allow} g5 $1 {with ...[O-O-O] to follow.}) 15... dxc3 16. bxc3 Be7 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8] The computer is pretty optimistic about White's chances to equalize here, but a pawn is a pawn so we shouldn't be too unhappy with this position.} *

