1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Yd4c3,Rd1d5,Ye4c3,Re1e8] The point of the whole variation, Black can't take on [c3], because both the queen and the king are pinned. Black has a wide choice here, with almost all the queen moves being quite okay.} Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 ({White has to take like this, the alternatives are much worse. For instance,} 9. Rxe4+ $2 Be6 10. Nxd4 O-O-O $1 {With a very unpleasant pin on the d-file!} 11. Be3 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Ba3 $1 {Spectacular and strong!} 13. Qb1 Bd6 {⩱ And Black is clearly better with the very strong bishops!}) 9... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8] Protecting the king from the discovered checks, and also preparing to play ... [O-O-O]. White has to react quickly, since otherwise Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Bd2 $5 {A decent alternative to the main line. Before committing to [Ng5] or [Bg5], White is asking one more question to Black's queen.} Qb5 $5 {[%cal Rb5b2] Only the 7th most common move in the position, but don't worry, the computer supports it. 🙂 The point is that sometimes the [b2]-pawn can be taken, which is not something the engine would support a few years or more ago.} 11. a4 Qxb2 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] Looks risky, but we are only one move away from castling, so according to the machine it is possible to take this pawn.} 12. Rb1 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Qb4 14. Qd3 Be7 15. Rab1 Qc4 {After trading the queens, the king will be safe in the centre.} 16. Bxe7 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Kxe7 18. Rxb7 Rhc8 {⩱}) 12... Qa2 13. Rxb7 {It looks like that White has a great position, but...} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc8] This shocking move actually puts our king into safety, since White can't really bring their pieces closer to the queenside.} 14. Rb1 h6 $17 {[%cal Gh6g5,Re4g5,Rf3g5] We even have the time to stop [Ng5] jumps. Since you probably do not play with such a king often, let's see some lines to illustrate that there is no real danger to Black.} (14... h6 {•} 15. Bf4 {Probably the best try from White, opening up some space for the queen. [Ne5] is also an option, with the point of trading Black's main defender, the [c6]-knight.} Qxa4 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 {Now Black's king looks more vulnerable, but still, there are not many white attackers.} Rd5 $1 18. Ra1 Qc6 {(18...Qc4 Would allow White to relocate the knight to [f3]. 19.Nd2! Qb5 20.Nf3 This is quite messy. )} 19. Bxd4 Bb4 20. c3 Rhd8 {Black has completed development with an extra pawn.} 21. Rxa7 Rxd4 22. cxd4 Bxe1 23. Qxe1 Rxd4 {∓ The position has greatly simplified, Black's king is definitely not in danger.}) (14... h6 {•} 15. a5 {White can protect this pawn, but it will not help with the position of their queen.} Be7 {∓ Black can use the [d5] and [c4] squares for the heavy pieces.}) (14... h6 {•} 15. Qe2 {It is quite important that this natural move is not working for White.} Qc4 $1 {White's queen is forced back to [d1].} 16. Qd1 Qxa4 {-+ The queen is locked on [d1].}) *

