1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {A very common move, but objectively speaking not really challenging if Black knows what to do against it. On the other hand, it is very safe for White, so finding a combative response wasn't easy here.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Yd4c3,Rd1d5,Ye4c3,Re1e8] The point of the whole variation, Black can't take on [c3], because both the queen and the king are pinned. Black has a wide choice here, with almost all the queen moves being quite okay.} Qa5 ({This is the main line, and according to my analyses it is the one which can provide the most winning chances for Black. For example} 8... Qf5 {is also very safe for Black, but if White wants, they can make a draw there pretty effortlessly.}) 9. Nxe4 ({White has to take like this, the alternatives are much worse. For instance,} 9. Rxe4+ $2 Be6 10. Nxd4 O-O-O $1 {With a very unpleasant pin on the d-file!} 11. Be3 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Ba3 $1 {Spectacular and strong!} 13. Qb1 Bd6 {⩱ And Black is clearly better with the very strong bishops!}) 9... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8] Protecting the king from the discovered checks, and also preparing to play ... [O-O-O]. White has to react quickly, since otherwise Black is just up a pawn.} 10. Neg5 {[%cal Rg5e6] White is winning back the pawn on [e6].} O-O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rxe6 {So far we have been following the main line of the 5. [O-O] variation with still thousands of games played from this position, but now it is time to surprise our opponent.} Qh5 $5 ({Bringing the queen closer to White's king makes a lot of sense, since if we look at the main line,} 12... Bd6 13. Bg5 $1 {White isn't only developing the bishop with a tempo, but also blocks the queen's way to [h5].}) 13. Qe2 Bd6 $1 {[%cal Rd4d3,Yc2d3,Yc6d4,Yf3d4,Yh5h2,Ge2d3,Gd6h2,Rd8d3] It is clear now that we tricked White since, as I said earlier, 12...Bd6 should be met by 13.Bg5! , while now we were able to transfer the queen to the kingside. We have also introduced the threat of ... [d3]! in the position, since no matter how White takes that pawn, it has a tactical refutation.} 14. h3 {White is avoiding the tricks with [d3], and also it is good to have the h-pawn safely protected.} (14. Bd2 d3 $1 15. Qxd3 Bxh2+ {+ -+ (15.cxd3 Nd4 -+)}) 14... Rde8 {Seemingly there is no threat, but actually almost everyone has fallen into this trap.} 15. Bd2 $2 (15. Qc4 {This is the engine's recommendation, but only one game went like this in practice.} Qf5 $1 16. Rxe8+ Rxe8 {With a pleasant position for Black.}) 15... Ne5 $1 {The tactics are working out in Black's favour.} 16. Rxe8+ (16. Nxd4 Qxe2 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 {is the same as 16. [Rxe8].}) 16... Rxe8 17. Nxd4 Qxe2 18. Nxe2 Nc4 $1 {[%cal Rc4d2,Re8e2] White has to give back the material.} 19. Be3 Nxb2 $17 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2,Gc4][%cal Gb2c4] Black has a clear advantage. White's queenside structure is very weak, and our knight will be very strong on [c4].} *

