1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. Bxc6 $2 {If our opponent is anxious about being down a pawn, this move is quite possible to happen, but it just helps Black's task tremendously, since we essentially win a tempo, because the [e5]-pawn was not hanging anyway.} bxc6 8. O-O $2 {We will not allow White to transpose to the 7. [O-O] [Be7] lines because now we can play the ambitious 8...[c5], holding on to our extra pawn.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4]} 9. c3 dxc3 10. Qxd5 {[%cal Rd5a8]} ({Even though this comes with a tempo, we also have an intermediate move!} 10. Nxc3 c6 $1 {∓ And our centre is safely protected.}) 10... cxb2 $1 11. Bxb2 Nb6 $1 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Gb6a8,Rd8d5] Protecting the rook and gaining a tempo on White's queen secures Black's advantage.} 12. Qe4 (12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {∓ Looks like a Berlin, where White's queenside magically disappeared.}) 12... Qd5 $17 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gc8b7,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Ge8c8] Black is clearly better, with options to castle on either side of the board.} *

