1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. Bxc6 $2 {If our opponent is anxious about being down a pawn, this move is quite possible to happen, but it just helps Black's task tremendously, since we essentially win a tempo, because the [e5]-pawn was not hanging anyway.} bxc6 8. Nxd4 (8. Qxd4 Be7 {(8...Bc5!? (is an equally good move maybe even slightly better according to the engine but since we can anyway get the text position via a different move order,) 8...Be7 seems to be the logical choice here. )} 9. O-O O-O {transposes here.}) 8... Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ge5c6,Rd4c6] We can take this pawn, since all the tactics are working out in our favour.} 9. O-O ({•} 9. Bf4 $2 Qf6 10. Bg3 Ba6 {-+}) ({•} 9. Qe2 Qe7 10. f4 {(10.O-O c5 11.Nb3 Bg4 12.Qd2 Qd6 ∓ With ...[O-O-O] coming on the next move, Black comfortably keeps the extra pawn. )} Ng4 11. Nxc6 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 {White has managed to win back the pawn, but their king is very open, and the position is ideal for our pair of bishops.} Bd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. fxe5 O-O-O {-+ The [e5]-pawn is very likely to fall.}) 9... Bd6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Developing, protecting the knight on [e5] and getting one move closer to castling.} 10. f4 {The only way to stop Black from castling.} Ng4 11. Re1+ ({•} 11. h3 Nf6 12. Nxc6 Bc5+ 13. Kh2 Qd6 {∓}) ({•} 11. Nxc6 Qh4 $1 {With a huge attack for Black, ...[Bc5] and ...[Ba6] are coming.}) 11... Kf8 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Yf2f4,Rd6c5,Rc5g1,Rd8h4] Our king has to stay in the centre, but it is still much safer than White's, which has been weakened by the [f4]-move.} 12. h3 c5 13. Nc6 (13. hxg4 {White is taking back the pawn, but will have a very bad position.} cxd4 14. Qxd4 Bxg4 15. Qxd5 h5 {∓ The rook can come into the play by ...[Rh6] and Black is just much better with having the pair of bishops.}) 13... Qh4 $1 {We are already quite deep in a rare line, but probably it is not the time to stop, when we are just sacrificing a piece. 🙂} 14. hxg4 Bxg4 15. Qd2 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd2e1] White has to keep the rook protected.} Bxf4 16. Qf2 Bg3 17. Qxc5+ Bd6 18. Qf2 Qh2+ 19. Kf1 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1][%cal Rd7b5,Rb5f1] The key move, the bishop is coming to play via [b5].} 20. Nd4 Bg3 21. Nf3 $1 {[%cal Rf3h2]} Bb5+ 22. Re2 Bxe2+ 23. Kxe2 Re8+ $17 {With strong defence, White has managed to stay in the game. However, not only is their king now weak, Black also has a slight material advantage.} *

