1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. e6 $6 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge8g8] Before Black could castle, White is trying to open up the position and keep our king in the centre. The idea is not bad, but it is not working.} fxe6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rd4e6,Gd1h5,Rh5e8] Now you can see the point of ...[e6], that the knight is attacking both [e6] and [c6]-pawn with a tempo, but the problem is that our usual way of protecting [c6] will also protect the pawn on [e6].🙂} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Ge6][%cal Gb8c6,Gc8e6]} 11. Re1 $6 {It is not a good idea to be materialistic here. Even though White will get back the pawn, they will be seriously behind in development.} O-O $1 (11... Qd6 $6 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qh6 {∞ And the position is not so clear.}) 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Rxe6 Bc5 $1 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1][%cal Rc5f2,Rf8f2] White is going to be on the defensive side now.} 14. Re2 (14. Be3 d4 15. Bd2 Qd5 {∓}) 14... Qf6 $17 {[%cal Rf6b2,Rf6f2,Gb8d7,Ga8e8] With pressure on [f2] and [b2] and ...[Nd7]-[Rae8] to follow, Black is just much better.} *

