1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. e6 $6 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge8g8] Before Black could castle, White is trying to open up the position and keep our king in the centre. The idea is not bad, but it is not working.} fxe6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rd4e6,Gd1h5,Rh5e8] Now you can see the point of ...[e6], that the knight is attacking both [e6] and [c6]-pawn with a tempo, but the problem is that our usual way of protecting [c6] will also protect the pawn on [e6].🙂} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Ge6][%cal Gb8c6,Gc8e6]} 11. Qh5+ {With this check White can weaken a few squares on our kingside.} g6 12. Qe2 {[%cal Rd4e6,Rf1e1,Re1e6]} ({•} 12. Qh6 $6 {Prevents Black from castling, but it is easy to kick out the queen from [h6].} Bf8 13. Qe3 Qf6 14. Re1 Bc5 15. c3 O-O {-+ Black is completely winning with the extra pawn.}) ({•} 12. Qe5 $2 {Fails to} Bf6 {-+}) 12... c5 {At some moment we have to give back the pawn, and if we do it now we can develop with tempo.} 13. Nxe6 Qd6 {[%cal Rd6e6,Rc8e6]} 14. Re1 Nc6 {If the [e6]-knight moves, then we can simply castle and have a nice position with the pair of bishops, and if not, then we will just trade into the endgame.} 15. Nc3 Qxe6 16. Qxe6 Bxe6 17. Rxe6 Kd7 $15 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc6d4,Rd4c2,Rb4c2,Ge7f6,Ga8b8,Gh8e8] All of our pieces will soon be very active, and our centre is mobile. White is very far away from doing anything with their kingside majority at the moment.} *

