1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. c3 $5 {[%cal Gc3d4] A very interesting move, instead of taking back on [d4], White wants to speed up the development by bringing the knight to [c3] and then target our [d5]-pawn!} dxc3 {We have to react, [cxd4] is not something we want to allow for free.} 9. Nxc3 a6 $1 {The other option is 9...[Nb6], but this one not only looks completely fine for Black, it was played by Peter Leko, who is one of the leading theoreticians in the world.} 10. Bxc6 {White is forced to take as otherwise the [e5]-pawn falls, or Black will keep the [d5]-pawn.} ({•} 10. Bd3 $2 Ndxe5 {-+}) ({•} 10. Ba4 $2 Nb6 $1 {If we had played 9...Nb6 , then White should have played 10.a4! a5 11.Be3! to target our knight on [b6] and then regain the pawn on [d5]. This is not possible now.}) 10... bxc6 11. Nd4 {[%cal Rd4c6] White has to continue aggressively and pose problems for Black before they have a chance to castle.} (11. e6 $2 {Was played by GM Kosteniuk, but it simply doesn't work at all. Even if White captures the pawn on [e6], they will remain a pawn down.} fxe6 12. Nd4 Nb8 {∓}) 11... Nb8 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] White's idea is to push the pawn to [f6]!} c5 ({Instead} 12... O-O 13. f5 Bc5 {is also possible, but the game can get extremely sharp, so we will just follow how GM Leko played this line. 🙂}) 13. Nb3 {[%cal Rd1d5,Rc3d5] White gains a tempo on our [d5]-pawn, and if we would protect it, then the dangerous [f5] will happen.} c4 $1 {Forcing White to enter a complicated endgame.} ({•} 13... c6 14. f5 {⇆}) ({•} 13... d4 14. Qf3 $1 c6 15. Ne4 {⩲ White is even better here, with such a dangerous play on the kingside.}) 14. Qxd5 {[%cal Rd5a8,Rd5c4] Neither side will have a choice in the next few moves.} ({•} 14. Nd4 $2 c5 15. Nc2 d4 {∓ The pawns are too strong.}) ({•} 14. Nd2 $2 Nc6 {-+}) 14... Qxd5 15. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} cxb3 16. Nxc7+ Kd7 17. Nxa8 Bc5+ $1 {[%cal Ra8b6,Yc5b6] Very important intermezzo, stopping the knight's way back via [b6].} 18. Kh1 Bb7 {[%cal Rb7a8] The knight is trapped, Black will have 2 pieces for the rook.} 19. Rd1+ Kc8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gb7g2] So far we have been following the game Beerdsen-Leko, Germany 2023, where 19...[Kc6] was played and Black eventually won the game. However it looks more logical to put the king on [c8], since then it will not block the bishop's diagonal and the knight can also develop to the [c6]-square.} 20. Bd2 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga1c1,Rc1c8] Rc1 is a threat now, so we have to be careful before taking the knight.} Ba7 $1 21. Rac1+ Nc6 22. axb3 Bxa8 $132 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gh8d8,Gc8b8,Gh8e8] We have a very complicated position on the board. Materially speaking, White is doing fine with a rook+2 pawns vs the minor pieces, but their b-pawns are doubled and Black's bishops are extremely strong. If White can't activate their kingside majority, Black will have a long-term advantage. Our next ideas should be to remove the king from the pin and bring the rook into play.} *

