1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1e5,Yb5c6,Yb7c6,Yf3d4]} ({A very common move, but not so good, since as we will see from the main line,} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {works right away, so it is not needed from White to protect the [e5]-pawn before that.}) 8... O-O {We can't keep the extra pawn, so it is time to castle.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rd4f5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gc8f5,Yc6c5,Yb8c6] The key move of this variation. Black not only protects the [c6] pawn, but also covers the [f5]-square with the [c8] bishop. The knight maneuver of [Nf6]-[d7]-[b8] may seem a little strange, but once we play ...[c5] followed by [Nc6], we will improve our position greatly. Also, we shouldn't forget about the long-term power of the pair of bishops.} 11. f4 $6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Rf4f5] This looks very logical as White has a majority on the kingside and so they are pushing it forward. However, the problem is that Black can easily stop this idea, and then White is left with an overextended position.} c5 $1 12. Nf3 Nc6 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yc8f5] This is what we wanted to play, and we managed to stop White's [f5]-idea.} 13. Nc3 d4 14. Ne4 Qd5 $15 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gf8d8,Gc8f5,Gc8b7,Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gc5c4] With an excellent position for Black. White's play on the kingside is non-existent, while we can push on the queenside by ...[a5]-[a4] or with ...[c4]-[d3]. We will bring the rooks to the b and d-files, and while it is not clear yet where our [c8]-bishop should go, we will simply leave it on [c8] for now until a better square presents itself.} *

