 Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rd4f5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gc8f5,Yc6c5,Yb8c6] The key move of this variation. Black not only protects the [c6] pawn, but also covers the [f5]-square with the [c8] bishop. The knight maneuver of [Nf6]-[d7]-[b8] may seem a little strange, but once we play ...[c5] followed by [Nc6], we will improve our position greatly. Also, we shouldn't forget about the long-term power of the pair of bishops.} 11. Nc3 $6 {White is not addressing the threat of ...[c5], so their knight will have to retreat to a passive square now.} c5 12. Nb3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rd1d5]} ({•} 12. Nf3 {The [f4]-[f5] plan is not on the table for a while.} Be6 13. Bf4 Nc6 {⩱ With ...[Rb8] coming next, Black is already slightly better.}) ({•} 12. Nde2 d4 13. Ne4 Nc6 14. Bf4 Bg4 $1 {A nice move to stop any [N2g3]-[Qf3] etc. ideas, connected with some kingside play.} 15. h3 Bh5 {⩱}) 12... Be6 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Rc3] Keeping everything solid, and White's knights are just very restricted here.} (12... d4 $2 {This push is quite committing, so we have to be careful when to do it. The main things to look at are White's knights, for example if one of those is on [e2] in a very passive position, then ...[d4] is almost always good, the other thing which is even more important, since we want to follow up this move with ...[Qd5], that whether White has the intermediate [Qf3] or not.} 13. Qf3 $1 c6 14. Ne4 Qd5 15. Qg3 {→ And finally White has some serious play against our king.}) 13. f4 {[%cal Rf4f5,Ye6f5,Yc3d5] With the idea of [f5] and then taking on [d5].} c6 14. Na4 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3][%cal Gd8b8,Gb8b5,Gb5b4] White is struggling with bad pieces and our next idea will be to activate the queen via [b8].} *

