1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1e5,Yb5c6,Yb7c6,Yf3d4]} ({A very common move, but not so good, since as we will see from the main line,} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {works right away, so it is not needed from White to protect the [e5]-pawn before that.}) 8... O-O {We can't keep the extra pawn, so it is time to castle.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rd4f5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gc8f5,Yc6c5,Yb8c6] The key move of this variation. Black not only protects the [c6] pawn, but also covers the [f5]-square with the [c8] bishop. The knight maneuver of [Nf6]-[d7]-[b8] may seem a little strange, but once we play ...[c5] followed by [Nc6], we will improve our position greatly. Also, we shouldn't forget about the long-term power of the pair of bishops.} 11. Qf3 {[%cal Gd4f5,Yc6c5] White is preparing against ...[c5], they are ready to put the knight on [f5].} (11. Qh5 {This will most likely transpose.} c5 12. Nf3 $2 {There is simply no play on the kingside, so White is just misplacing the knight. (12.Nf5 Bxf5 13.Qxf5 Qd7 Transposing again. )} Nc6 {Black has ideas to play ...[Qd7]-[f5]/[g4] trade the queens and play a much better endgame with the bishop pair.} 13. Ng5 {is easily refuted by} Bf5 $1) 11... c5 (11... Qd7 {is an interesting alternative with the goal of playing ...[c5] and not allowing the knight to jump to [f5].}) 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1][%cal Gb8c6] With the additional trade of minor pieces, White's prospects of kingside play have been heavily reduced. Black will simply finish development and then they can consider pushing their pawns in the centre.} 14. Qxd7 ({•} 14. Qh5 $6 Qe6 15. f4 g6 {⩱ No [f5], and it is now Black's turn to push the pawns after ...[Nc6].}) ({•} 14. Qf3 $6 Nc6 15. c3 Rae8 {∓ With ...[Bd8] and maybe ...[f6] to follow, and the [e5]-pawn can be easily in trouble.}) 14... Nxd7 15. Nc3 c6 $10 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gf8e8,Gf7f6,Ga7a4] Black has comfortably equalised here. White doesn't really have any active ideas other then [f4]-[f5], but not only would that weaken their position, it can always be stopped by Black playing ...[f5]. In their turn, Black can play ...[a5]-[a4] to gain some space on the queenside and also the move ...[c4] can open up some squares for our minor pieces.} *

