1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Qxd4 $6 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3] It is clear that White is only taking with the queen because they are not sure that 9. [Nxd4] is working. Now both the queen and the knight are misplaced, and Black has very easy play.} O-O 10. Nc3 Nc5 $15 {[%cal Gc5e6,Gc8b7,Gd8d7,Yc6c5,Yd5d4] We will play ...[Ne6] next and then start pushing our pawns in the centre. White's play is blocked by the knight on [f3].} *

