1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {Definitely the critical line, White can temporarily sacrifice the pawn on [e5].} (9. e6 $6 fxe6 10. Nxd4 Nb8 {transposes here.}) 9... Nxe5 $5 ({A rare move. The mainline is} 9... Nb8 {, and there is nothing wrong with it, but I like the surprise value and unusual positions that the text move can bring. Now White has 4 ways to attack the knight, and only one of those is good!}) 10. Qe2 $6 {[%cal Re2e5] This was never played in an OTB game, and indeed, it looks pretty easy to handle this.} Qd6 {[%csl Gc6,Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Gd6c6] Protecting the knight and also the [c6]-pawn, which is very important. The knight is now free to move.} 11. f4 (11. Bf4 $6 f6 {And if White wants to take back the pawn immediately, they are just losing the game.} 12. Re1 O-O 13. Bxe5 fxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Rxe5 Bf6 {-+}) 11... Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f6] The knight is going to [f6].} 12. Re1 Bd7 {Seemingly it does nothing about short castle, but actually it covers the [e8]-square, which makes a trick possible.} 13. h3 (13. Nc3 $4 O-O $1 {This is the point of ...[Bd7], White can't take the bishop now.} 14. Qxe7 Rae8 {-+}) 13... Nf6 14. Nc3 Kf8 $17 {[%cal Ga8e8,Yh7h5,Yh5h4,Gh8h6,Gh6g6] Now there is no mate on [e1], so we can't castle and give up the bishop. However, ...[Kf8] is also not too bad, and we can play ...[Re8] next. The [h8]-rook can be developed on the h-file after ...[h5]-[h4].} *

