. Now White has 4 ways to attack the knight, and only one of those is good!}) 10. Re1 $6 {Maybe the most natural move in the position, but also a mistake!} f6 $1 ({A new move! Black tried} 10... c5 {, 10...Qd6 and 10...Ng6 in practice, but as you will see, the text is much stronger.}) 11. f4 {Probably because of this move, Black was avoiding ...[f6] so far in practice. If we have to move the knight now, then we are in big trouble, since the pawn on [c6] is hanging.} (11. Nc3 {Too slow.} Bd7 $1 {The knight is free to go now, since the [c6]-pawn is protected.} 12. f4 Ng6 13. f5 Ne5 14. Qh5+ Kf8 {∓ Even though Black didn't manage to castle, the king will be completely safe on [f8], since the knight on [e5] is so strong, that White can't really attack around it. We can support that knight by playing ...[Bd6] next, and also kick back the queen by playing ...[Qe8].}) 11... Bg4 $1 12. Qd2 (12. Nxc6 {Doesn't work.} Qd7 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. Qd2 O-O {-+ White's king is very weak, and they are also very much behind in the development.}) 12... O-O $1 {The key move! Of course, it is very hard to find without the help of the machine.} (12... c5 $2 {This is the human way, but after} 13. fxe5 cxd4 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Qxd4 {± White has a much better position.}) 13. h3 {Even though it forces the bishop back, it further weakens White's king.} Bd7 {[%csl Rg1]} 14. fxe5 fxe5 15. Rxe5 (15. Nf3 Rxf3 $1 {Eliminating the main defender of the king.} 16. gxf3 Bc5+ 17. Kh2 Qh4 {-+ White is getting checkmated.}) 15... Bd6 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7][%cal Rd6h2,Rd7h3,Gd8h4,Rf8f1] Since White's pieces on the queenside are undeveloped, Black can attack the White king with more pieces.} 16. Re3 (16. Re1 Qh4 {-+}) 16... Qf6 $1 {[%cal Rf6f1]} 17. Nf3 Bxh3 $1 {Black is breaking through.} 18. gxh3 Bc5 $19 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gf6g6,Rc5g1,Rf6f3] White is going to lose a lot of material in the next few moves.} *

