1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 $1 {As we have seen in the previous chapters, meeting [e5] with ...[d5]! is a crucial idea.} 6. Bb5 ({Pretty much the only move for White, the alternatives are very bad. •} 6. exf6 $2 dxc4 7. O-O {(7.Qe2+ Be6 -+)} Qxf6 8. Re1+ Be6 {-+ Black is completely winning with 2 extra pawns.}) ({•} 6. exd6 $2 Bxd6 7. Nxd4 $4 {White would like to take back the pawn, but instead they will just lose their queen.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bb4+ {+ -+}) 6... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rc6e5,Yf6e4,Yf2f3,Yf3f4]} ({The alternative to the main line, which is} 6... Ne4 {. Our line is getting more and more popular since it seems to be easier to play. One of the key differences between the moves is that while the knight is more active on [e4], it can be exposed to White's kingside play with potential tempo-gaining moves like [f3] and a later [f4]. On [d7] the knight is more modest, but it immediately puts pressure on the [e5]-pawn and also breaks the pin on the [c6]-knight.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] This is by far White's best move, since the [e5]-pawn is not hanging yet, because of the pin, White can just continue the development and take back the pawn later.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Taking on [d4] too early is not good, Black has a couple of ways to gain the upper hand.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {(8.Bxd7+ Bxd7 9.Qxd4 Bf5 ∓ Black will finish the development and then push the centre with ...[c5]-[d4]. )} c6 9. Be2 {(9.Bd3 Bc5 10.Qf4 Qe7 -+ or 10.Qg4 g6 ∓ The [e5]-pawn is in a big trouble. )} Bc5 10. Qg4 g6 11. Qg3 Bd4 12. f4 f6 {∓ White has trouble with castling.}) 7... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] We are continuing the development and getting ready to castle.} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {Definitely the critical line, White can temporarily sacrifice the pawn on [e5].} (9. e6 $6 fxe6 10. Nxd4 Nb8 {transposes here.}) 9... Nxe5 $5 ({A rare move. The mainline is} 9... Nb8 {, and there is nothing wrong with it, but I like the surprise value and unusual positions that the text move can bring. Now White has 4 ways to attack the knight, and only one of those is good!}) 10. Bf4 $1 {The correct way to attack the knight.} c5 $1 ({This move makes the line playable for Black.} 10... Ng6 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Nxe7 Nxe7 13. Qd4 {⩲ It is not much fun for Black, with all the weak dark squares.}) 11. Bxe5 cxd4 12. Bxg7 {It looks like that Black is losing a pawn, but things are far from clear.} (12. Qxd4 $2 {allows} c5 $1 {⩱ And Black is castling on the next move, with a slightly better position as the bishops are going to be very strong.}) 12... Rg8 13. Be5 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Yc8h3,Ge5g3] This is the good move from White, intending to meet the ...[Bh3]-threat with [Bg3], and also in any case the bishop could be very useful on [g3] to stop Black's play on the g-file.} (13. Bxd4 $2 {This move simply blunders an exchange.} Bh3 $1 14. g3 c5 15. Be5 Bxf1 16. Qxf1 Qd7 {∓ We are not going to castle long, but instead have the plan of ...[Rg6], ...[Kf8]-[g8] to bring our king into safety.}) 13... c5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] Of course, we are not going to give up that pawn for free.} 14. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gd5] Immediately attacking our strong centre looks like the critical try.} (14. c3 $6 {Undermining our centre and bringing the knight into the game is logical, but this is not the correct way to do so.} dxc3 {And unfortunately for White, the point, which was to take with the knight is not working, because of} 15. Nxc3 d4 $1 16. Ne4 Qd5 {-+}) 14... Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g8,Gg8g6] Getting closer to the 'ideal' castle position, by playing ...[Rg6] and ...[Kg8] at some moment.} 15. Qh5 {[%cal Rh5h7] Now this is a much better move than on the previous move as ...[Rg5] does not work as well for Black.} Rg6 {[%cal Gf8g8] Stopping [Qh6]+, and also preparing ...[Kg8].} (15... Rg5 $6 16. Qxh7 Bf5 $4 {is just losing now.} 17. Qh8+ Rg8 18. Bg7+ {+-}) 16. Qxh7 {[%csl Rh7] It looks like that we are in a lot of trouble, but White's queen can be potentially misplaced, which will give Black a decent position.} Bf6 $1 {Qh8 was a huge threat.} 17. f4 $1 {The only move for White!} ({•} 17. Re1 $2 Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf6 $1 19. Re1 Bg4 {-+ White's misplaced queen, combined with a mating attack gives Black a decisive advantage.}) ({•} 17. Bxf6 $4 Qxf6 {-+ And Black is completely winning, since} 18. Nd2 {fails to} Qg5 $1 {picking up a piece. Otherwise we just want to play ...[Ba6] and ...[Rh6] to trap the queen on [h7]!}) 17... Bf5 {[%cal Rg6g2] With the threat of ...[Rg2].} 18. Qh5 Bg4 ({We don't necessarily have to repeat, but it looks like a normal way at this point. Alternatively, we can try} 18... Be4 {or even 18...Bxe5 with wild positions.}) 19. Bxf6 (19. Qh7 Bf5 {is just a draw.}) 19... Qxf6 20. Qxd5 Re8 {And Black has a very dangerous compensation, which in reality should end in a draw, if White manages a position where White's moves are definitely more difficult to find. 🙂} 21. Nd2 Re2 22. f5 $1 Rg5 23. h4 $1 Rh5 24. Ne4 $1 Qxh4 $10 (24... Qxh4 {And after finding 3 only moves in a row, White can give a perpetual check now.} 25. Qd6+ Kg7 26. Qe5+ Kf8 27. Qd6+ Kg7) *

