1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Rd4c6,Ye3c5] The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. Nb5 $6 {[%cal Rb5c7] Played in a lot of games, but it is very dubious. Our [c7]-square is indeed vulnerable, but White gives up a lot in order to attack it.} Bxe3 7. fxe3 {[%csl Re3,Re4] The structure is already pretty bad for White.} Qh4+ {Very unpleasant check.} 8. Kd2 {Very rarely played, but according to the engine it is not much worse than the main line.} Kd8 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8c7] Now it is especially not a big deal to move with our king, since White has already done the same.} 9. Qf3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4]} 10. N1c3 a6 $1 {Great move! Black can immediately go on the counterattack.} 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 d5 $1 {This is the point behind 10...[a6]. Black immediately attacks White's centre.} 13. exd5 (13. Re1 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Qh6+ $1 {And White's king is in trouble.} 15. Kc3 Nd5+ 16. Kd3 Re8 {-+}) 13... Re8 $1 {[%cal Rh4g5,Rh4h6] Creating the threats of ...[Qg5] and [Qh6] is much more important than taking the [d4]-pawn.} 14. g3 {[%cal Gf3f4] Now White can block the checks with [Qf4].} Qxd4+ 15. Bd3 Bg4 16. Qf4 Qxf4+ 17. gxf4 Ke7 $15 {[%csl Rd5,Rf4][%cal Ga8d8,Ge7f8] With a nice endgame for Black. White has more pawn islands and a couple of weaknesses already.} *

