1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. Nb5 $6 {[%cal Rb5c7] Played in a lot of games, but it is very dubious. Our [c7]-square is indeed vulnerable, but White gives up a lot in order to attack it.} Bxe3 7. fxe3 {[%csl Re3,Re4] The structure is already pretty bad for White.} Qh4+ {Very unpleasant check.} 8. g3 Qxe4 {[%cal Re4h1]} ({The alternative} 8... Qd8 {is equally popular, but the text is just much more forcing and gives Black a very good position.}) 9. Nxc7+ (9. N1c3 {A slightly tricky move order, since it tempts us to take on [e3]. However, should just take the rook and transpose to the main lines.} Qxh1 10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 Nf6 12. Qd6 Qf3 {And we transposed to the lines with 9. [Nxc7]+ [Kd8].}) 9... Kd8 10. Nxa8 Qxh1 11. Qg4 {[%cal Rg4g7] Attacking [g7] is too slow in this position.} Nge7 $1 {[%csl Ra8] The pawns on the kingside don't really matter, since if Black can develop quickly, the knight on [a8] will be lost.} 12. Nc3 {[%cal Ge1c1]} ({White is preparing to castle long.} 12. Qxg7 Rg8 13. Qxh7 Qf3 14. Qd3 Nb4 15. Qb3 Ned5 {-+ And Black is winning.}) 12... Ne5 $1 {[%cal Re5g4,Re5f3] This is the way to refute the 11. [Qg4] line.} 13. Qa4 {[%cal Ra4a5,Ra4a7]} (13. Qxg7 $2 {This is still very easy for Black.} Nf3+ 14. Kf2 Rg8 15. Qxh7 Ng5 {-+}) 13... Nf3+ {Our king is under attack, and the only way to win is to take the pawn on [h2]! 🙂} 14. Kf2 Nxh2 $1 {Of course, the main thing is not the pawn, but preventing White from castling long.} 15. Be2 {White has to give up the rook, so temporarily our queen and knight on [h2] will be out of play.} (15. Qa5+ b6 16. Qxa7 Qf3+ 17. Kg1 Qxg3+ 18. Bg2 Nf3+ 19. Kf1 Nd2+ 20. Kg1 Nc4 {-+ And our king is perfectly defended.}) 15... Qxa1 {[%csl Ra1,Rh2]} 16. Qa5+ b6 (16... Ke8 $4 17. Nc7+ Kf8 18. Qb4 $1 {+- And White is winning with the threat of [Nd5].}) 17. Qxa7 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh8h6,Gh6a6] The only winning move! The rook's defense is much needed on the 6th rank.} 18. Qxb6+ Ke8 19. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6,Yb6d8,Ye8f8] With a mate in two threat - [Nd6]+ followed by [Qd8].} Rh6 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yh6d6]} (19... Rh6 {Now} 20. Nd6+ {would do nothing, since Black can sacrifice the exchange and still be up on material.}) 20. Nc7+ Kf8 21. Ne6+ {White has to continue giving checks, otherwise they have nothing for the rook.} fxe6 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8f7]} ({The king needs the f7-square!} 21... Rxe6 $4 22. Qd8# {would be unfortunate for Black.}) 22. Qd8+ Kf7 23. Nd6+ Kg6 {[%cal Gg6h7] The king is running to [h7], where it will be completely safe.} 24. Qe8+ Kh7 {[%csl Gh7]} 25. Ne4 {[%cal Re4g5] One last threat with [Ng5] checkmate!} (25. Bd3+ Nf5 26. Nxf5 Rf6 $1 {Pinning the knight, and the queen alone can't do anything.} 27. Qxh5+ Kg8 28. Qe8+ Rf8 {-+ Since the knight is pinned, White has run out of checks and must resign.}) 25... Rg6 $19 {Finally, Black's king reached safety, and they soon converted the material advantage in Edelmann-Marczell, ICCF corr. 2002.} *

