1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. Nb5 $6 {[%cal Rb5c7] Played in a lot of games, but it is very dubious. Our [c7]-square is indeed vulnerable, but White gives up a lot in order to attack it.} Bxe3 7. fxe3 {[%csl Re3,Re4] The structure is already pretty bad for White.} Qh4+ {Very unpleasant check.} 8. g3 Qxe4 {[%cal Re4h1]} ({The alternative} 8... Qd8 {is equally popular, but the text is just much more forcing and gives Black a very good position.}) 9. Nxc7+ (9. N1c3 {A slightly tricky move order, since it tempts us to take on [e3]. However, should just take the rook and transpose to the main lines.} Qxh1 10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 Nf6 12. Qd6 Qf3 {And we transposed to the lines with 9. [Nxc7]+ [Kd8].}) 9... Kd8 10. Nxa8 Qxh1 11. Qd6 {[%cal Rd6c7,Rd6f8]} ({Both Qc7 and Qf8 are a threat now.} 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Qd6 Qf3 {transposes to 11. [Qd6] [Nf6] 12. [Nc3] [Qf3].}) 11... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gd8e7]} ({Much better than} 11... Nge7 {as it keeps the e7-square available for our king. Our knight is also much more active on f6.}) 12. Nd2 $2 {The most common move in the position, and while White achieves a winning position against 11...[Nge7] with it, here it is pretty much losing.} Ne8 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ye8c7] No more [Qc7] checks!} 13. Qf4 Qxh2 14. O-O-O Qh6 $1 {[%csl Ra8] Chasing White's queen is very annoying for our opponent, since all endgames are easily lost because of the knight on [a8].} 15. Qxf7 Qxe3 {[%csl Gc6,Gd8,Ge8] We can safely take a few pawns, since our king is perfectly protected by the knights.} 16. Kb1 Qxg3 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Yh7h1] We can also develop the rook by pushing the h-pawn.} 17. Ne4 Qg4 18. Nc3 h5 $19 {[%cal Yh5h1,Gh8h6,Gh6f6] Black is just winning here, White can't really create any threats.} *

