1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. c3 d6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf6g6,Gg8f6]} ({The main line is} 6... Nge7 {with a lot of theory; the text move, although it is the second most popular choice is much less known. The main point is to delay the development of the [g8] knight, since against certain moves it is very effective to develop it on [f6] and attack the [e4] pawn.}) 7. Nc2 {Quite passive but the knight would stand pretty well on [e3], defending against the ...[f5] and ...[d5] breaks.} Bd7 {We don't have to rush by taking on [e3] since the structures with doubled c-pawns are fine for us.} 8. Nd2 (8. Bxc5 dxc5 9. Nd2 O-O-O 10. Qe2 Nge7 {∞}) 8... O-O-O 9. Be2 Bxe3 10. Nxe3 Qe5 $10 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gh8e8] Black has good play against the [e4]-pawn.} *

