1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. c3 d6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf6g6,Gg8f6]} ({The main line is} 6... Nge7 {with a lot of theory; the text move, although it is the second most popular choice is much less known. The main point is to delay the development of the [g8] knight, since against certain moves it is very effective to develop it on [f6] and attack the [e4] pawn.}) 7. Bc4 $6 {The most common move in the position, and the main line against 6...[Nge7]. There is a good chance that our opponent is going to play like this. Here however, the move is very dubious and it immediately gives Black the upper hand.} Ne5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Re5g4,Re5c4] Similarly to the absolute main lines of the Scotch, we play with ...[Ne5] and chase away White's bishop from the [c4]-square.} 8. Be2 Qg6 $1 {[%cal Rg6e4,Rg6g2] Hitting the pawns on [e4] and [g2].} 9. Nb5 {This does not solve White's problems, but at least White is trying to complicate the game.} Qxg2 10. Rf1 Bxe3 11. Nxc7+ $1 {Otherwise Black would just protect the [c7]-pawn with a winning position.} Kd7 $1 {[%cal Rd7c7] We have to gain a tempo on the knight, so White has no time for [fxe3].} 12. Nxa8 Bf4 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Ge5,Gf4,Gg2] We are down an exchange, but the knight on [e5] and the bishop on [f4] are completely dominating White's position.} 13. Qa4+ Ke7 14. Nc7 {[%cal Rc7d5] White can retain the extra material, but it will not help to neutralise our very active pieces.} Nf6 {Preventing [Nd5]+.} 15. Nd2 Bg4 $17 (15... Bg4 {Stopping our opponent from castling long, Black has great chances here; one possible continuation is} 16. Qb5 Rc8 17. Qxb7 Kf8 18. Rd1 Bh3 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 g5 {-+ Despite being quite seriously up on material, White can hardly move their pieces.}) *

