1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7d5,Yf7f5] This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 {This is the Classical Variation, immediately asking White what they want to do with that [d4]-knight.} 5. Be3 {The traditional main line for White is developing the bishop and also threatening to take on [c6] with tempo, so Black would lose the [c5]-bishop.} Qf6 {[%cal Rf6d4,Rc5d4,Rc6d4] Still asking the same question from White, what to do with the [d4] knight?} 6. c3 d6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf6g6,Gg8f6]} ({The main line is} 6... Nge7 {with a lot of theory; the text move, although it is the second most popular choice is much less known. The main point is to delay the development of the [g8] knight, since against certain moves it is very effective to develop it on [f6] and attack the [e4] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rd4c6,Rb5c6] Definitely looks like the right move for White, developing with a tempo and not allowing Black to comfortably execute the ...[Qg6], ...[Nf6] plan.} Nge7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ge7c6,Ge8g8] Protecting the knight on [c6] and preparing to castle.} 8. O-O ({Instead, both} 8. Nxc6 {and 8.Bxc6 are possible, but since White is castling anyway, I'll look at those options a move later.}) 8... O-O 9. f4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Yf6g6,Yf4f5] White is gaining some space in the centre and is ready to meet ...[Qg6] with [f5]!} Bb6 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Yc6d4,Yc3d4,Rd4c5] Protecting the bishop, so that after playing ...[d5] we don't have to worry about [Nxc6]. More importantly, it also prepares to take on [d4] with the knight and White's recapture of [cxd4] will not win a tempo anymore.} 10. Kh1 d5 $1 {We are getting some light squares in the centre for our pieces.} 11. e5 Qh6 {[%cal Rc6e5,Yh6e3] A nice tempo, since ...[Nxe5] is a threat.} 12. Qd2 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Nf5 $132 {[%csl Gb6,Gf5][%cal Yf7f6]} (13... Nf5 {Black is doing very well, one possible line is} 14. Bf2 f6 $1 15. Nc3 fxe5 16. dxe5 Bxf2 17. Rxf2 d4 18. Ne4 Ne3 {⩱}) *

