1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {[%cal Rb3c5,Gb1c3,Gc1g5,Gc1e3,Gd1e2,Ye1c1] Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 {[%csl Gb6]} ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Bd3 {This is not common or particularly dangerous for Black, since it prepares [O-O]. One of the main ideas of the [Nb3] lines for White is to castle long and, if possible, attack Black's king.} d6 $1 {A flexible move; before developing our knight, we keep the option of ...[Qh4].} 7. Nc3 (7. O-O Qh4 $1 {The queen is very unpleasant on [h4] for White.} 8. Nc3 Nf6 {⇆ With ...[Ng4] coming next, Black already has pretty decent play.}) 7... Nge7 {Playing ...[Qh4] was also possible, but with White still keeping the option of castling long, it looks less convincing. Instead, we are just continuing our development, and we put the knight on [e7] in order to support the [d5] and [f5]-breaks.} 8. O-O O-O $10 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yf7f5,Rf5e4] Black is completely fine. We are going to play ... [f5] very soon and challenge White's superiority in the centre.} *

