1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1e3]} ({The move orders are very tricky.} 6. a4 {, 6.Nc3 6.Qe2 all can transpose into the same position, but we have to be careful not to be tricked into a position which is not part of our repertoire.}) 6... d6 $1 {[%cal Yd8f6,Yg8e7] Being flexible is the key for Black, and this move is excellent for that purpose. Sometimes we want to play with ...[Qf6] and sometimes with ...[Nge7], depending on White's play, so with this move we are not showing our cards yet.} 7. Nc3 ({•} 7. a4 {We can just transpose, but normally White is not making this move, since Black has maybe even better replies, like 7...[Be6] for example.} a5 {transposes here.}) ({•} 7. Be3 Qf6 8. Nc3 Nge7 {transposes here.}) 7... a5 {[%csl Rb3,Gb4][%cal Ya5a4,Ya4b3,Ya2a4,Yc6b4] We want to attack the knight on [b3], and if White plays [a4] to stop it, we are getting a nice square for our knight on [b4].} 8. Nd5 {[%cal Ya7b6,Rd5b6,Yc7b6] Since we moved our a-pawn, there is no comfortable way to take back on [b6] now, so White wants to spoil our pawn structure.} a4 $1 (8... Ba7 {is also completely fine, but here we are playing for even more than just equality.}) 9. Nxb6 (9. Nd2 Bc5 {And now the whole idea of [Nd5] is gone.} 10. Nf3 {With ...[O-O] to follow, Black has a much easier development.} Nge7 {⩱}) 9... cxb6 {[%csl Yb6,Yb7]} 10. Nd2 Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e8,Yd6d5] Our structure is pretty bad, but we have a serious lead in development, which is very difficult to neutralise for White.} 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] And White has problems with the [e4]-pawn.} 13. O-O Re8 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Re8e2]} 14. Qd3 Bg4 $17 {[%csl Yd2,Yd3,Ye4][%cal Gg2e4,Gd3e4,Gd2e4] It is tough to move anything for White, since they have to protect the pawn on [e4], while [exd5] is met by ...[Be2]! winning the exchange.} *

