1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ra5b6] White wants to trap our bishop on [b6]!} a5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4,Yb1c3] We are stopping White's a-pawn, and in case White develops their knight to [c3], we can respond by playing ...[Nb4] to stop [Nd5] threats.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1e3] White is keeping the option of playing with 8. [Be3] or 8. [Bg5] before developing the knight to [c3].} d6 $1 {A good multipurpose move! We don't want to bring the knight to [f6] yet, since then White's bishop could go to [g5], and it is too early for ...[Nb4].} 8. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5] White is ready to jump with the the knight to [d5], which obviously should be addressed.} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gd5][%cal Gb4d5] An excellent square for the knight, since it can't be easily attacked. The knight not only covers the [d5]-square, but also puts some pressure on White's queenside.} 9. g3 $6 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] A logical way to develop, since the queen is blocking the light-squared bishop's way, but it is just too slow, and Black can take over the initiative.} Nf6 10. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {Forcing the queen to an awkward square or provoking a weakness.} 11. f3 (11. Qd2 $6 O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Re1 Qd7 {-+ It is quite surprising, but the engine is already saying that Black is winning. They can't really finish the development without weakening the position or having problems with the [e4]-pawn.}) 11... Be6 $17 {[%csl Yg2][%cal Rb6g1] White is not able to castle short, and the bishop on [g2] is not active either.} *

