t play} dxe4 $1 {And White has no follow-up.}) (14... c6 {•} 15. Nc5 Qe7 {Forcing matters, but playing slower with 15...[Qc7] and then ...[Rad8] is also okay.} 16. Nxe6 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Qxe6 {∞ With the idea of playing ...[Qe5] next, controlling the dark squares.}) (14... c6 {•} 15. Kb1 {Typical and useful move after castling long.} Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Qc7 {⇆ Controlling the [f4]-square and preparing to play ...[Rad8].}) (14... c6 {•} 15. Be2 {A pretty normal move, White is finishing the development and have the big threat of [f4].} Bxe3 (15... g6 $5 {is also good, preventing [f4].}) 16. Qxe3 Qc7 $1 {Controlling the [f4]-square, where the knight can jump in the next move.} 17. e5 $1 {Preventing ...[Nf4].} c5 $1 {Nice pawn sacrifice from the engine!} 18. Nxc5 {(18.Qxc5?! Qxe5 ⩱ White's kingside is overextended, but the bigger problem is that the c-file has opened up, so White's king can get into danger. )} Rac8 19. Nxe6 fxe6 {∞ Black has full compensation for the pawn, there is nice pressure on the c-file, while the rook from [f8] supports ...[Nf4]. (19.Nb3 Na2+! Wins back the material. 20.Kb1 Nxc3+ 21.Qxc3 Qxc3 22.bxc3 Rxc3 ⇆ The position remains complex, both sides have quite a few weaknesses. )}) *

