1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. f4 {[%cal Rb6g1,Ge4e5,Gc3d5] Very ambitious, but also pretty risky, since White weakens the [g1]-[a7] diagonal.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge7d5] Developing and addressing White's threat, which was [Nd5].} 8. Na4 $6 {White's play is very risky. Instead of developing their pieces, our opponent is going for the pair of bishops.} O-O 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Be2 d5 $1 {[%csl Re1] It is time to punish White for losing a lot of time in the opening.} 11. e5 (11. exd5 Rd8 12. c4 b5 $1 {∓ White's centre is collapsing.}) 11... Qh4+ 12. g3 Qh3 {[%cal Re1g1] No castling!} 13. Bf1 Qh6 $1 14. f5 g5 $17 {[%csl Re5,Rf5] Our position looks unusual, but White can't protect their central pawns.} *

