1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2,Gc3d5] By far the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5] and also [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. h4 {[%cal Gc1g5] White wants to develop with [Bg5], but by itself it is not a particularly dangerous threat for us. We should be much more careful when it is combined with [Nd5].} d6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge8c8]} ({One step closer to castling long. If instead} 8... h6 {, then White may consider playing} 9. g4 $5 {.}) 9. Nd5 {Very rare, but only a trade on [d5] and the opened e-file could make [Bg5] dangerous.} Nxd5 10. exd5+ Ne5 $1 (10... Ne7 11. Bg5 Qe5 12. Qxe5 dxe5 13. a4 {could lead to a slightly better endgame for White, but instead with this move Black is sacrificing a piece and gets good chances.}) 11. f4 (11. Bg5 Qg6 12. f4 $4 Bg4 {-+ White is just lost, wherever the queen goes, it will allow ...[Qe4]+.}) 11... Bg4 $1 12. fxe5 Qf5 {[%cal Rg4d1,Rb6g1] We have given up a piece, but White's king is going to face a very serious attack as our bishops are stopping White from castling.} 13. Qd2 O-O $1 {[%cal Gf8e8] Bringing a new attacker into the game.} 14. Be2 Qf2+ 15. Kd1 Qxg2 {Black is starting to gain material for the sacrificed piece.} 16. Re1 Rae8 {[%cal Ye5e6,Yf7e6,Yf8f2] It is better to bring the a-rook to the e-file. If White then tries to close the e-file by playing [e6], we can simply open the f-file for our other rook.} 17. Bxg4 Qxg4+ 18. Qe2 Qxh4 {[%csl Rd1,Re5][%cal Ge8e5] Capturing a second pawn for the sacrificed piece. We only need one more to have material equality, and White's king is still far away from reaching a safe position.} *

