1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2,Gc3d5] By far the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5] and also [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. h4 {[%cal Gc1g5] White wants to develop with [Bg5], but by itself it is not a particularly dangerous threat for us. We should be much more careful when it is combined with [Nd5].} d6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge8c8]} ({One step closer to castling long. If instead} 8... h6 {, then White may consider playing} 9. g4 $5 {.}) 9. Bg5 Qe6 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yc3d5,Ye7d5,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] This is a much more comfortable square for the queen than [g6] for now, since with this move we are prepared against [Nd5] jumps. The bishop wants to develop to [d7] anyway, and in case of going to [g6], we should also count on [h5] once the bishop is protected on [g5] or retreats somewhere.} 10. O-O-O {White is playing standard moves, there is not even an alternative to this move in practice, which shouldn't come as a big surprise, since after playing [h4], White showed that their intention is not to play with [O-O].} f6 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge6f7] Providing a retreat square on [f7] for our queen and also kicking back the annoying bishop from [g5].} ({According to the machine} 10... Bd7 {is fine as well, but I wouldn't wait for} 11. g3 $1 {with the threat of [Bh3].}) 11. Be3 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] We are going to castle on our next move.} 12. g3 O-O-O {It is very hard to say whether the current structure or the one with ...[axb6] is better for us after the eventual trade of the bishops, both look completely fine, so I decided not to hurry with the trade.} 13. Bh3 (13. Bxb6 axb6 14. Bh3 f5 {Black's position is completely fine, next we will bring the h-rook into the game and step away with the queen from the pin.}) 13... Bxe3+ 14. Qxe3 Qf7 $10 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gh8e8] We will play ...[f5] very soon, challenging White's slight superiority in the centre, and the position is around equal.} *

