1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2,Gc3d5] By far the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5] and also [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. Nd5 {Only the third most popular move in this position, but it is the most challenging one.} Nxd5 {We obviously have to take, otherwise White just gets a free tempo and a strong knight.} 9. exd5+ Ne7 ({Again the only move,} 9... Ne5 $4 {is losing a piece to} 10. f4 {.}) 10. h4 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Rc1g5,Gh4g5,Gh1h3,Gh3e3,Gh3f3] The only dangerous continuation for White. They prevent ...[O-O] due to [Bg5]!, and also open up the way for the rook to join via the third rank.} (10. a4 {Another way to reach the main lines, since Black has to play} a5 $1 {and after} 11. h4 h6 {we transpose.}) 10... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5] Preventing [Bg5] is very important.} 11. Rh3 {[%cal Gh3f3,Rf3f6] Since [Bg5] is not possible, White tries to attack our queen with the rook and prevents us from castling.} d6 {[%cal Rc8h3]} 12. Rf3 Bf5 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge8c8] This move completely refutes White's plans. Black can now comfortably finish development on the next move with ...[O-O].} 13. g4 {The only question.} Bxg4 {But we can just accept this pawn.} 14. Qb5+ (14. Rxf6 $4 Bxe2 {-+}) 14... c6 $1 15. Rxf6 (15. dxc6 Qxf3 16. cxb7+ Bd7 17. bxa8=Q+ Qxa8 {-+ And Black was much better, with a huge lead in the development in Warzecha-Steinke, e-mail 2008. Black won a few moves later.}) 15... cxb5 16. Bxb5+ Kf8 17. Rf4 (17. Rxd6 $2 Bc7 {-+ The rook is trapped on [d6].}) 17... f5 $17 {[%csl Rd5,Yf4,Rh4] Black is much better due to White's misplaced rook on [f4] and the weak pawns on [d5] and [h4].} *

