o open up the way for the rook to join via the third rank.} (10. a4 {Another way to reach the main lines, since Black has to play} a5 $1 {and after} 11. h4 h6 {we transpose.}) 10... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5] Preventing [Bg5] is very important.} 11. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ra4a5,Ra5b6] The critical move, as White is threatening to trap our bishop and to include [a4]-[a5] is definitely in our opponents' favour.} ({•} 11. g4 {Looks logical, but the pawn on [g5] is not nearly as dangerous as the bishop would be.} d6 12. g5 Qf5 {⩱ It is not clear what White achieved besides weakening their kingside.}) ({•} 11. Bg5 $4 {Unfortunately for White it doesn't work.} hxg5 12. hxg5 {It is a huge tempo on the queen, but after} Qxf2+ $1 13. Qxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Rxh1 {-+ Black just wins the game.}) 11... a5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2a5] We have to stop White's pawn, but this move has a couple of problems. First of all, White can target the [a5]-pawn making any ...[O-O-O] plans for Black more difficult to execute. Also, we have removed one of the defenders of the [b6]-bishop, and if we play ...[d6], White will have ideas of [Qb5]+, and we will not be able to block the check with ...[c6].} 12. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3,Rc3f6] An interesting try from White, allowing [Bc3] for free is not really an option, but then it means that Black has to go for a journey with the queen.} Qxb2 13. Rh3 {[%cal Gd2c3] Bc3 is again a big threat.} Qxc2 {Looks greedy, but the main point is not to take the pawns, but to escape from the [Bc3]-tempo!} 14. Rc1 Qg6 {Finally the queen is back in our camp!} 15. Bc3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rh3g3,Yg3g7,Yc3g7]} d6 $1 {We have to give back some material in order to finish our development.} 16. Rg3 Qf5 17. Bxg7 Rg8 18. Bf6 {[%cal Re2e7,Rg3g8] White is threatening mate and also our rook on [g8]!} Be6 $1 {Saves the day for Black!} 19. dxe6 Qxf6 20. exf7+ Qxf7 $15 {Black is better with the extra pawn, but obviously the game is far from over.} *

