1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2,Gc3d5] By far the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5] and also [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. Nd5 {Only the third most popular move in this position, but it is the most challenging one.} Nxd5 {We obviously have to take, otherwise White just gets a free tempo and a strong knight.} 9. exd5+ Ne7 ({Again the only move,} 9... Ne5 $4 {is losing a piece to} 10. f4 {.}) 10. h4 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Rc1g5,Gh4g5,Gh1h3,Gh3e3,Gh3f3] The only dangerous continuation for White. They prevent ...[O-O] due to [Bg5]!, and also open up the way for the rook to join via the third rank.} (10. a4 {Another way to reach the main lines, since Black has to play} a5 $1 {and after} 11. h4 h6 {we transpose.}) 10... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5] Preventing [Bg5] is very important.} 11. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ra4a5,Ra5b6] The critical move, as White is threatening to trap our bishop and to include [a4]-[a5] is definitely in our opponents' favour.} ({•} 11. g4 {Looks logical, but the pawn on [g5] is not nearly as dangerous as the bishop would be.} d6 12. g5 Qf5 {⩱ It is not clear what White achieved besides weakening their kingside.}) ({•} 11. Bg5 $4 {Unfortunately for White it doesn't work.} hxg5 12. hxg5 {It is a huge tempo on the queen, but after} Qxf2+ $1 13. Qxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Rxh1 {-+ Black just wins the game.}) 11... a5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2a5] We have to stop White's pawn, but this move has a couple of problems. First of all, White can target the [a5]-pawn making any ...[O-O-O] plans for Black more difficult to execute. Also, we have removed one of the defenders of the [b6]-bishop, and if we play ...[d6], White will have ideas of [Qb5]+, and we will not be able to block the check with ...[c6].} 12. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3,Rc3f6] An interesting try from White, allowing [Bc3] for free is not really an option, but then it means that Black has to go for a journey with the queen.} Qxb2 13. Rh3 {[%cal Gd2c3] Bc3 is again a big threat.} Qxc2 {Looks greedy, but the main point is not to take the pawns, but to escape from the [Bc3]-tempo!} 14. d6 $1 {Before we can play ...[d6] ourselves, White slows down our development very with another pawn sacrifice.} (14. Rg3 $2 {This was tried in one game, but it is very slow.} d6 15. Qf3 Qf5 {-+ And Black is just up two pawns with a winning position.}) 14... cxd6 15. Rc1 Qf5 {[%cal Gf5e5,Gf5e6] We have ideas like ...[Qe5] or ...[Qe6].} 16. Be3 {[%cal Gh3e3] By offering the trade, White wants to bring the rook to [e3].} Bxe3 17. Rxe3 Qf6 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gd5d4,Gd7d6] Next, we want to push the d-pawns, enabling us to finish development and also to distrupt White's pressure on the e-file.} 18. g4 d5 $1 19. Bg2 d4 $17 {And Black is just better, since White can't keep the pressure on the e-file. A few possible lines follow.} (19... d4 {•} 20. g5 hxg5 21. hxg5 Qxg5 22. Nxd4 O-O {-+ And the knight is not hanging on [e7], since the rook on [c1] is unprotected.}) (19... d4 {•} 20. Re4 d5 21. Re5 Bxg4 {-+}) (19... d4 {•} 20. Nxd4 O-O $1 21. Rxe7 Qxd4 {-+ With two extra pawns for Black.}) (19... d4 {•} 20. Re5 d3 21. Qe3 d6 22. Re4 d5 {The d-pawns are very annoying!} 23. Re5 Bxg4 {-+}) *

