o open up the way for the rook to join via the third rank.} (10. a4 {Another way to reach the main lines, since Black has to play} a5 $1 {and after} 11. h4 h6 {we transpose.}) 10... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5] Preventing [Bg5] is very important.} 11. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ra4a5,Ra5b6] The critical move, as White is threatening to trap our bishop and to include [a4]-[a5] is definitely in our opponents' favour.} ({•} 11. g4 {Looks logical, but the pawn on [g5] is not nearly as dangerous as the bishop would be.} d6 12. g5 Qf5 {⩱ It is not clear what White achieved besides weakening their kingside.}) ({•} 11. Bg5 $4 {Unfortunately for White it doesn't work.} hxg5 12. hxg5 {It is a huge tempo on the queen, but after} Qxf2+ $1 13. Qxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Rxh1 {-+ Black just wins the game.}) 11... a5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2a5] We have to stop White's pawn, but this move has a couple of problems. First of all, White can target the [a5]-pawn making any ...[O-O-O] plans for Black more difficult to execute. Also, we have removed one of the defenders of the [b6]-bishop, and if we play ...[d6], White will have ideas of [Qb5]+, and we will not be able to block the check with ...[c6].} 12. g4 {The most common move in the practice, but not very scary, since it gives Black time to play ...[d6], and after that we have the option to play ... [Qe5] with a complex endgame, if nothing better.} (12. Bg5 $4 {Still doesn't work.} hxg5 13. hxg5 Qxf2+ 14. Qxf2 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Rxh1 {-+}) 12... d6 13. g5 Qg6 $1 ({Instead, both} 13... Qe5 {immediately or after 13...hxg5 14.Bxg5 Qe5 are fine and lead to very complex endgames. But after the text move, White has to play very accurately in order not to be worse. Our idea is to take on [g5] and then immediately attack the bishop with ...[f6].}) 14. h5 ({•} 14. gxh6 gxh6 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Qxc2 $1 17. Rc1 Qxb2 18. Rxc7 Qf6 {⩱ Next is ... [Kf8], and Black is up a pawn in a complex position. ( • 14.Rg1 hxg5 15.Rxg5 Qf6 ∓ White's h-pawn is very weak. )}) 14... Qf5 15. gxh6 gxh6 16. Rh4 $1 {It is very tough to find such moves.} Qxd5 17. Bd2 {White sacrificed a pawn, and calmly continues development.} Be6 18. O-O-O O-O-O $132 {With a very complex position, which looks good for Black. Also, White has to play like a machine to arrive here.} *

