1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nb3 {Recently, this is White's most dangerous attempt against the Classical Variation. White removes the knight from the centre, but gains a tempo on the bishop, so time is not an issue. Since they do not have to defend the knight on [d4], White very often aims to play [Qe2] and [O-O-O], which can obviously make the game pretty sharp.} Bb6 ({This is the most natural square for the bishop. The more obscure options are} 5... Bb4+ {or 5...Be7 , but Black has difficulties according to current theory.}) 6. Nc3 Qf6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d6,Ye8c8,Yc8e6]} ({The third most popular move in the position behind} 6... Nf6 {and 6...d6 . The point is to develop with ...[Nge7] but first develop the queen to a more active square, which also makes ...[O-O-O] possible later. We also have a mate in one threat. 🙂 Obviously the main moves are fine as well, I just don't like the pin which can happen in the 6...Nf6 7.Bg5 lines.}) 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2,Gc3d5] By far the main move for White, protecting [f2], preparing to play [Nd5] and also [O-O-O] is one step closer.} Nge7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye7d5] Continuing development and addressing the [Nd5] threat.} 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge1c1] By far the most common move in this position. White is continuing the development and preparing to castle long.} d6 {We are doing exactly the same!} 9. O-O-O Bd7 $1 {It is better to develop the bishop here than to [e6], since now after [Nd5] we can comfortably take it with the knight without getting a fork.} 10. Kb1 {A useful move, but White has other options available.} ({•} 10. f4 $6 {White wants to play this move in many cases, but now it is too early.} Bg4 $1 {Winning a pawn!} 11. Qxg4 Bxe3+ 12. Kb1 Bxf4 13. Bb5 Qg5 14. Qe2 O-O {⩱ White can possibly have some counterchances, but a pawn is pawn.}) ({•} 10. f3 {Way too modest, White can't really hope for any advantage after this move.} O-O-O 11. Qd2 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Qg6 {...[f5] is coming next, with an equal position.}) 10... O-O-O 11. Bxb6 axb6 12. g3 g5 $1 {Not a must, but when possible why not prevent [f4]?} 13. Bg2 Qg7 $10 {[%cal Gh8f8,Gd8e8,Yf7f5] We are bringing the rooks to the 'e and f'-files, and then playing [f5]. Or vice versa. 🙂} *

