1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. c3 $2 {Very slow! White does not develop their pieces and gives Black time to do so without problems.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Rf6e4,Gb1c3] Very effective development, and thanks to the pawn being on [c3], White doesn't have a very comfortable way to protect the [e4]-pawn.} 6. Nxc6 {So the bishop can protect the pawn from [d3], and White will not lose material on [d4] in the meantime.} bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5e4,Rf6e4] We are ahead in the development, so let's force the issue and try to open the position!} 8. exd5 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4d1] One more tempo!} 9. f3 (9. Be2 Qe7 {Stopping ...[O-O].} 10. h3 Ne4 $1 11. hxg4 Nxf2 12. Qa4 O-O {-+ With a rook coming to [e8], White is losing in this line as well.}) 9... O-O $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Re8e1] We sacrifice a bishop but bring the rook!} 10. fxg4 Nxd5 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8,Gd8d7] Even though we are not winning right away, we have a long-term compensation for the piece, since White's king can't castle.} *

