1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nf5 $2 {[%cal Rf5g7,Gf5e3,Ge3d5,Ge3f5] On paper this move doesn't look too bad, since White gains a tempo on the [g7]-pawn, and if it is kicked back by ... [g6], then from [e3] it controls both freeing attempts from Black, ...[d5] and ...[f5].} d5 $1 {[%cal Rc8f5] This strong move completely refutes White's idea. We can actually ignore the [g7]-pawn.} 6. Nxg7+ Kf8 7. Nh5 (7. Nf5 $2 {is very easy to meet,} Bxf5 8. exf5 Qh4 {With the rook coming to [e8], White's position is already lost.} 9. Qf3 Re8+ 10. Kd1 Nf6 {-+}) 7... Qh4 {[%csl Yh5][%cal Rh4f2,Rc5f2,Yg1f3,Yf3d4,Yd4f5,Yf5g7,Yg7h5,Yh5g3] Developing with a mate in one threat! White is very much behind in development and they are just about to make their 6th move out of 8 with their knight!} 8. Ng3 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Rf6e4,Rf6g4,Rg4f2,Re4f2] A new piece in every move!} 9. Be2 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd8e8] Black is not breaking the rule, bringing a new piece again, and opening the way for the rook!} 10. exd5 Bxd5 11. O-O h5 $36 {[%cal Gf6g4,Yh5g4,Rh8h2] Preparing ... [Ng4], and White will be almost forced to take the knight, opening up the h-file for our rook! Let's see what happens if White plays like an engine. 🙂} (11... h5 {•} 12. Qd3 $1 Ng4 13. h3 Rd8 $1 {All Black pieces are involved, the position is very scary for White.} 14. Nd2 Rd6 15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. Nf5 Qh5 17. Ng3 gxh3 $3 {Our attack is so strong, that we can even sacrifice a queen temporarily.} 18. Nxh5 Rxh5 {∓}) (11... h5 {•} 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 Rd8 14. Qe1 Ng4 {-+}) *

