1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {[%cal Yg1f3,Yf3d4,Yd4c6] White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {[%cal Gd8h4] This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bc4 $6 {White uses the fact that they don't have to protect the [e4] pawn so they put their bishop on a more active square. However, this very popular move is already a slight mistake as it allows Black to take over the initiative.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f2,Rh4e4] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. Qf3 $2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf3f2,Rf3f7] White replies in kind by defending [f2] and attacking [f7], but now Black can take advantage of the bishop on [c4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Yh4c4] A huge tempo on the bishop.} 8. Bd3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Rh4e4,Rd5e4] Putting pressure on [e4] and gaining time is key for Black.} 9. exd5 Ng4 {[%cal Rg4f2,Rc5f2,Rh4f2]} 10. g3 Qe7+ {[%csl Rf2] And White has to give back the material.} 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Ne5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] It is even better to have such a knight than taking back the material right away.} 13. Qg2 Rb8 $19 {[%csl Re3,Ge5][%cal Rb8b2,Yc8h3] White has a lot of problems in this position. They can't take the time to protect b2 because of the very nice move ...Bh3 trick. 14.b3 Bh3! 15.Qxh3 Nxd3+ 16.cxd3 Qxe3+ 17.Kd1 Qf3 + -+ and Black is picking up the rook on [h1].} *

