1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bc4 $6 {White uses the fact that they don't have to protect the [e4] pawn so they put their bishop on a more active square. However, this very popular move is already a slight mistake as it allows Black to take over the initiative.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f2,Rh4e4] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. Qe2 ({Better than} 7. Qf3 {, as it will be more difficult for Black to play ...[d5] since it can be captured with check, and also the bishop on [c4] is now protected.}) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Rh4e4,Rf6e4] Continuing the attack against the [e4]-pawn.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O d5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rf2,Rh2] With a combined attack against White's weak spots!} 10. exd5 Re8 $1 {It doesn't hurt to bring a new piece into the game!} 11. Qd3 Bd6 12. h3 (12. g3 $2 {This is weakening the light squares too much.} Qh3 13. Qf3 Bg4 14. Qg2 Qh5 15. h4 Bf3 16. Qh3 cxd5 {-+ With material equality and a horrible position for White's queen.}) 12... Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rd6h2,Yg4f2] The knight obviously can't be taken, and this way we can target the [f2]-square with the help of ... [Bh2]+.} 13. Bb3 Bh2+ 14. Kh1 Nxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Qxf2 16. Kxh2 Re1 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yc1,Rh2] White couldn't finish the development on the queenside.} *

