1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bc4 $6 {White uses the fact that they don't have to protect the [e4] pawn so they put their bishop on a more active square. However, this very popular move is already a slight mistake as it allows Black to take over the initiative.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f2,Rh4e4] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. Qe2 ({Better than} 7. Qf3 {, as it will be more difficult for Black to play ...[d5] since it can be captured with check, and also the bishop on [c4] is now protected.}) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Rh4e4,Rf6e4] Continuing the attack against the [e4]-pawn.} 8. e5 $1 {This should be the critical test of our approach as it looks like White can solve the issue of the [e4]-pawn while gaining a tempo.} O-O $1 {The sacrifice works excellently!} 9. exf6 d5 $1 {Normally we like to meet White's [e5] with ...[d5]!. Now we are a little bit late for it, but it is still effective. 🙂} 10. O-O ({•} 10. Bd3 $2 Bg4 {-+ White will lose a lot of material here.}) ({•} 10. fxg7 $6 {This move just gives an extra opportunity for Black.} Rd8 11. O-O Bg4 $1 {Since White forced the rook to [d8], now we will gain a tempo on the queen in the next move.} 12. Qd3 dxc4 13. Qg3 Qxg3 14. hxg3 Rab8 {⩱ Black is slightly better with the pair bishops, despite the less than ideal pawn structure.}) 10... Bd6 {Forcing White to weaken the light squares a little bit, making our [c8]-bishop more potent.} 11. g3 Qxc4 12. Qxc4 dxc4 $10 {[%csl Yc4,Yc6,Yc7,Gc8,Gd6] The endgame is balanced. Our bishops can be very strong, but White has the better structure.} *

