1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bc4 $6 {White uses the fact that they don't have to protect the [e4] pawn so they put their bishop on a more active square. However, this very popular move is already a slight mistake as it allows Black to take over the initiative.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f2,Rh4e4] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. O-O {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf1f2,Yh4e4,Yf1e1,Re1e8] This is the most common move, protecting [f2] and also [e4] since we can't take because of the pin.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] As usual, we are bringing the knight to [f6] in order to attack [e4], and also to have ... [Ng4] opportunities.} 8. Nd2 $1 {This continuation only happened in one game but this is the only move which gives White a reasonable position, so it is worth some examination.} O-O (8... Ng4 {This is not so clear.} 9. Nf3 $1 Bxf2+ {(9...Nxf2 10.Qe2 Ng4+ 11.Kh1 Qh5 12.e5 ∞ White has compensation for the pawn. )} 10. Kh1 Qh5 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Qd2 Qc5 13. Qd3 Qh5 14. Qd2 Qc5 {And after some engine supported play, the game is equal.}) 9. Nf3 $1 {Obviously no one plays like this, but still... at least we have a line against computer prep too.} Qxe4 {Looks like a free pawn, but White will have pretty good development, so it is not that easy.} 10. Bd3 Qd5 11. Bg5 Ne4 12. c4 Qe6 13. Bf4 d5 14. Rc1 Qe7 $13 {After playing brilliantly White is still down a pawn, but they have decent compensation for it.} *

