1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bc4 $6 {White uses the fact that they don't have to protect the [e4] pawn so they put their bishop on a more active square. However, this very popular move is already a slight mistake as it allows Black to take over the initiative.} Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4f2,Rh4e4] The queen uses the absence of the [f3]-knight and immediately attacks [f2] and [e4].} 7. O-O {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf1f2,Yh4e4,Yf1e1,Re1e8] This is the most common move, protecting [f2] and also [e4] since we can't take because of the pin.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] As usual, we are bringing the knight to [f6] in order to attack [e4], and also to have ... [Ng4] opportunities.} 8. g3 $2 ({By far the most common, but it is just very bad for White.} 8. Qf3 $2 {is also very bad.} d5 {∓}) 8... Qh3 {[%csl Rg1] The king's position is seriously weakened on the light-squares.} 9. Qf3 O-O 10. Nc3 d5 $1 {[%cal Yc8g4] We can speed things up and bring the bishop to [g4]!} 11. exd5 Bg4 12. Qg2 Qh5 $17 {[%cal Rg4h3,Rg4f3] With threats like ...[Bf3] and ...[Bh3], Black is much better here. Let's see a few possible continuations.} (12... Qh5 13. h4 Bf3 14. Qh3 cxd5 15. Bd3 Ne4 {-+ White can hardly move here.}) (12... Qh5 13. Re1 Bh3 14. Be2 Rfe8 $1 15. Be3 Rxe3 16. Bxh5 Rxe1+ 17. Rxe1 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Nxh5 {-+ And Black is up a piece at the end of the line.}) *

