1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the right approach from White. The bishop has to be on [d3] to protect the [e4] pawn, and they can safely castle on the next move.} (6. Nc3 Nf6 {transposes to the Four Knights.}) 6... Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rf3,Gh4][%cal Yh4f2,Yh4h2,Yh4e4] Our play is not changing, we want the queen on [h4] to put pressure on White's position, and it is pretty effective in the absence of the [f3]-knight.} 7. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Yf6g4,Rf6e4,Ge8g8] Usual square for the knight, preparing both to attack and also to castle.} 8. h3 $6 {White prevents the ...[Ng4]-idea, but gives a target for our light-squared bishop.} d6 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Yc8h3] Instead 8...[d5] is very tempting, but in case of correct play it can lead to a very quick draw. Of course, there is no guarantee that White can find all the correct moves. 🙂} (8... d5 9. e5 $1 Nh5 10. Nd2 $1 Bxh3 11. gxh3 Nf4 12. Qf3 $1 {And now Black has nothing better than a perpetual check.} Nxh3+ 13. Kg2 Nf4+ 14. Kg1 Nh3+) 9. Nd2 $2 ({Immediately losing.} 9. Qf3 {is correct, but Black retains a very good position, because White can't trade the queens on [g3].} Nd7 10. Be3 Ne5 11. Qe2 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 g5 {⇆ With both ...[Rg8]-[g4] and ...[Qf4] being legit ideas, Black is very comfortable.}) 9... Bxh3 $1 10. gxh3 Qg3+ 11. Kh1 Qxh3+ 12. Kg1 Ng4 $19 (12... Ng4 {White is losing their queen or getting checkmated. For instance,} 13. Nf3 Qg3+ 14. Kh1 Bxf2 {+ -+}) *

