trong.}) 9. c3 Ng4 $1 {A very important intermediate move. Unfortunately ...[Be5] works less well in this position.} (9... Be5 $6 10. g3 Qh3 11. Nd2 {⩲ With [Nc4] coming next, there is no really good square for our bishop.}) 10. Bf4 (10. h3 $6 Ne5 11. Qe2 Bb6 12. Be3 g5 $1 {Very strong, the attack can be dangerous.} 13. Nd2 g4 14. hxg4 Rg8 {⩱}) 10... Ne5 {Black wants to trade some pieces before retreating their dark-squared bishop.} 11. Qe2 (11. Bxe5 {Doesn't pose any serious problems for Black.} Bxe5 12. g3 Qe7 13. Nd2 g6 $1 {And the bishop will safely return to [g7].}) 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb6 {[%csl Gb6]} 13. Be3 {It looks logical to immediately trade Black's bishop pair.} O-O 14. Nd2 d6 $10 {[%cal Yf7f5,Gg8h8,Gc8d7,Ga8e8] We are not in a hurry to take on [e3], as if White trades on [b6] our structure would be very much improved. Our main idea is to play for ...[f5] and neutralise White's small space advantage. We can prepare for that by playing ...[Kh8], ...[Bd7], ...[Rae8].} *

