1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Game. White gains space advantage in the centre, but in return they move their knight for a second time, which can lead to issues with development in some variations. Black's main goals are connected with the [e4]-pawn, either to challenge it with ...[f5] or ...[d5], or just put pressure on it by playing ...[Nf6], ...[Re8] and similar moves.} Bc5 5. Nxc6 {White makes the third move with the knight, but at the same time weakens Black's structure.} bxc6 {This move should already come as little surprise to White, since the main line is the intermediate move 5...[Qf6]. Black aims for a more complicated game, with the queen often going to [h4].} (5... Qf6 {White has to react against the mating threat on [f2].} 6. Qf3 {The most popular choice for White. While the line seems to be okay for Black, it will be a pretty complex endgame, where it is not so easy to bring anything theoretically new. 6.Qd2!? is also an interesting line for White.}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the right approach from White. The bishop has to be on [d3] to protect the [e4] pawn, and they can safely castle on the next move.} (6. Nc3 Nf6 {transposes to the Four Knights.}) 6... Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rf3,Gh4][%cal Yh4f2,Yh4h2,Yh4e4] Our play is not changing, we want the queen on [h4] to put pressure on White's position, and it is pretty effective in the absence of the [f3]-knight.} 7. Qe2 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc1e3] This is the main line, White is preparing to exchange our strong bishop by playing [Be3], and there will be also a surprising line with [h3], which is obviously much better to play without castling.} Nf6 8. h3 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gg2g3] A very tricky move! White idea is to play [g3] therefore they take away the [h3]-square first and after ...[Qh5] not to trade, but play [g4] and and even [g5]!} d5 $1 {We strike in the centre against White's slow play on the kingside. After all, [h3] does not develop a piece!} 9. exd5+ Kd8 $1 {[%cal Gh8e8,Re8e1] The king is not ideally placed on [d8], but the position is very concrete and we have our own threats.} 10. O-O {White evacuates their king from the centre, but the kingside is not particularly safe either.} Bxh3 $1 11. Qe5 $1 {The queen has to help in the defense.} (11. gxh3 $4 {Just loses to} Qg3+ 12. Kh1 Qxh3+ 13. Kg1 Re8 14. Qd2 Re5 {-+}) 11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Bd6 {[%cal Rh4h2,Gd6h2] Looks very promising with ...[Qh2]+ next, but White can hold the draw here.} 13. Qf5 (13. Qg5 $2 {is losing to} Qh2+ 14. Kf3 h6 $1 {This extra tempo is difference compared to 13. [Qf5], now White will not have [Bg5].} 15. Qf5 Re8 $1 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Qh5+ 18. Kg2 Re5 {-+ And ... [Rg5] is decisive.}) 13... Qh2+ 14. Kf3 Re8 $1 15. Bg5 (15. Nc3 {This is also good enough for a draw.} Re5 16. Qf4 Qh5+ 17. Kg2 Re7 18. Qf5 Qh2+ 19. Kf3 Re5 {With a funny repetition. 🙂}) 15... Qh5+ 16. Kg2 Qh2+ $10 {And the game is drawn.} *

