!} 9. g3 Qh5 10. Qxh5 ({Of course not} 10. g4 $4 Bxg4 {-+}) 10... Nxh5 {We managed to avoid White's dangerous idea of pushing the g-pawn. We can now look forward to a normal endgame, where White has already weakened their kingside.} 11. e5 $2 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Yg3g4,Yg4h5] White wants to trap our knight, but in reality they'll be the ones losing material, not us!} Bd4 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Re5][%cal Rd4e5,Rd4b2] The weakness of the [b2]-pawn is White's problem!} 12. g4 Nf4 13. Bxf4 Bxb2 14. Kd2 Bxa1 $19 {[%cal Yd5d4,Ya1c3] And White can't trap our bishop, so we are just up a lot of material.} *

