1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nf5 $2 {A very dubious knight move, it is very easy to protect the pawn on [g7], so the knight will be just exposed on [f5].} O-O 7. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Rg5d8] By pinning the knight White is slowing down ... [d5]-ideas.} (7. Bd3 d5 $1 8. O-O {(8.exd5 Bxf5 9.Bxf5 Re8+ ∓ And White has to make some unpleasant decisions. )} Bxf5 9. exf5 Ne5 {∓ Black has a clear edge with the better structure.}) 7... d5 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Yc8f5] Or maybe not. 😀} 8. Nxd5 ({•} 8. exd5 Bxf5 9. dxc6 Qe8+ 10. Be2 Qxc6 {∓ With a symmetrical pawn structure, but Black is much better developed.}) ({•} 8. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 9. Nxd5 Qxb2 {-+ White's position is extremely unstable and weak on the dark squares.}) 8... Bxf5 $1 {Now White has to take on [f6], since recapturing on [f5] would drop the knight on [d5].} 9. Bxf6 (9. Nxf6+ $2 {Also drops a piece.} gxf6 10. Qxd8 Raxd8 11. Bxf6 Rd6 {-+}) 9... gxf6 10. exf5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Yf1e2,Ye1g1] White is missing a move or two to finish development.} Re8+ 11. Ne3 (11. Be2 $2 {is losing material to} Rxe2+ $1 12. Kxe2 Nd4+ 13. Kf1 Qxd5 14. c3 Qc4+ $1 {-+}) 11... Bxe3 12. Qxd8 Raxd8 13. fxe3 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c2]} ({This move decides the game, after} 13... Rxe3+ {White would have some chances to hold.}) 14. Bd3 Nxd3+ 15. cxd3 Rxe3+ 16. Kf2 Rexd3 $19 {[%cal Rd3d2,Rd2b2] Black is already up a pawn, with more to come.} *

