nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nb3 {Not a particularly bad move from White, but definitely not the one which could challenge the 5...[Bc5] line, since now our opponent is forcing the bishop to the 'correct' square.} Bb4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rf6e4,Yd4c6] If we had started with 5...Bb4 , White's move would have been 6.Nxc6 , which is not available now, so we can already consider the opening a success.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] Protecting [e4] and preparing to castle.} (7. Bg5 $2 {A serious mistake, White is either losing the pair of bishops or the [e4]-pawn.} h6 $1 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 {∓}) 7... a5 $5 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ya4a3]} (7... d5 {was already okay for Black, but I like the text move which was played by my legendary compatriot, GM Romanishin. The point is that if White reacts to this move by} 8. a3 {or 8.a4 then we can play ...[d5] under better circumstances, and if they don't, then we can push the pawn forward.}) 8. a4 d5 $1 {Challenging White's superiority in the centre.} 9. O-O Bg4 $1 ({Provoking some weaknesses. Instead,} 9... Bxc3 {looks tempting but after} 10. exd5 $1 {White has good chances for the advantage, because the bishops are going to be very strong.}) 10. f3 (10. Be2 {Leads to comfortable equality for Black.} Bxe2 11. Qxe2 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4+ Qe7) 10... Be6 {[%csl Rf3] f3 is not really a move White is happy to play, since it weakens the [g1]-[a7] diagonal.} 11. Bg5 dxe4 12. Bxe4 Qxd1 13. Bxc6+ {Looks like that White can get a slightly better endgame, but we have the strong,} Qd7 $1 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 $10 (14... Kxd7 {And the position is just equal. One possible continuation is} 15. Rfd1+ Kc8 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Nd5 Bf8 18. Nxf6 Bg7 19. Ne4 Bxb2 {⇆ And Black is doing well with very strong bishops.}) *

