nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nb3 {Not a particularly bad move from White, but definitely not the one which could challenge the 5...[Bc5] line, since now our opponent is forcing the bishop to the 'correct' square.} Bb4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rf6e4,Yd4c6] If we had started with 5...Bb4 , White's move would have been 6.Nxc6 , which is not available now, so we can already consider the opening a success.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] Protecting [e4] and preparing to castle.} (7. Bg5 $2 {A serious mistake, White is either losing the pair of bishops or the [e4]-pawn.} h6 $1 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 {∓}) 7... a5 $5 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ya4a3]} (7... d5 {was already okay for Black, but I like the text move which was played by my legendary compatriot, GM Romanishin. The point is that if White reacts to this move by} 8. a3 {or 8.a4 then we can play ...[d5] under better circumstances, and if they don't, then we can push the pawn forward.}) 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. O-O d5 $1 {Once we get this break in, we shouldn't have any problems.} 11. exd5 Qxd5 $10 {[%csl Ra3,Gc1,Yc2,Yc3,Gd3][%cal Yc1a3,Ya5a4,Gc8f5] The position is around equal, since our better structure is compensated by White's pair of bishops. You can see that having ...[a5]-[a3] included is pretty nice for Black, not only White can't bring the bishop to [a3], but sometimes Black can consider chasing the knight away by playing ...[a4].} *

