nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nb3 {Not a particularly bad move from White, but definitely not the one which could challenge the 5...[Bc5] line, since now our opponent is forcing the bishop to the 'correct' square.} Bb4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rf6e4,Yd4c6] If we had started with 5...Bb4 , White's move would have been 6.Nxc6 , which is not available now, so we can already consider the opening a success.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] Protecting [e4] and preparing to castle.} (7. Bg5 $2 {A serious mistake, White is either losing the pair of bishops or the [e4]-pawn.} h6 $1 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 {∓}) 7... a5 $5 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ya4a3]} (7... d5 {was already okay for Black, but I like the text move which was played by my legendary compatriot, GM Romanishin. The point is that if White reacts to this move by} 8. a3 {or 8.a4 then we can play ...[d5] under better circumstances, and if they don't, then we can push the pawn forward.}) 8. O-O a4 $1 {Chasing the knight to a more passive square.} 9. Nd2 O-O {An improvement over the game Areshchenko-Romanishin, Warsaw 2014, where Black took on [c3] right away. We definitely have that move as an option, but we can wait with it.} ({It is also important to note that even if} 9... a3 {looks tempting, it can be met by} 10. Nd5 $1 {and in exchange for the better structure, we are giving White a lot of development.}) 10. Nf3 {[%cal Gc1g5] Opening up the diagonal for the [c1]-bishop.} h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5] I like to play this move, rather than allowing [Bg5]. You can see throughout the whole course that, if possible, I prefer to avoid this pin from the bishop. The reason is pretty simple, there is no clear way to deal with it, and sometimes it can be pretty tough to understand whether ...[h6]-...[g5] is weakening or a completely safe way to break the pin.} 11. e5 {With taking the time to play ...[h6], we delayed pushing our pawn to [d6], so this move should be a question.} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rg4e5,Rc6e5] It is very important that we can get out from the attack with a tempo.} 12. Nd5 (12. Qe2 {Qe4 is a big threat, but Black is just in time with} d6 $1 13. Qe4 f5 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Qg6 Qe8 {White probably has to trade queens, and in the endgame it's Black who can fight for the advantage.}) 12... d6 $1 {[%csl Re5] We can give up the pair of bishops, since we will get very active pieces in return.} 13. Nxb4 Nxb4 14. exd6 Qxd6 $10 {[%cal Rb4d3,Gf8e8,Gc8f5] Black is fine, we are threatening to take on [d3], and if the bishop retreats then we can gain more tempi by easy developing moves.} *

