nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bg5 {[%cal Yf1d3,Ye1g1] Most likely will transpose to main lines, but it would be more important for White to finish development on the kingside before making this move.} h6 8. Bh4 O-O (8... O-O {And here White doesn't really have anything better than playing} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Bd4 {and transpose to 7. [Bd3] [O-O] lines.}) 9. e5 $2 {[%csl Re1] This is not a good idea with the king still being in the centre.} Re8 $1 10. f4 (10. Qe2 d5 11. O-O-O Qd7 $1 {⩱} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ne4 Be7 14. exf6 Bd6 {-+ Winning the knight on [e4].}) 10... d5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Yc8g4,Yg7g5,Yc3e4] Gaining some space in the centre, opening the bishop's diagonal, and also cutting out the [c3]-knight from the game.} 11. Be2 g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Yg5f4,Ye8e5] White's centre is falling apart.} 12. fxg5 (12. exf6 $2 gxh4 {-+ White is going to lose the game on the dark squares. Their king can't castle short, and if it goes to the other side, it can be attacked with ...[Rb8]. Of course, it doesn't help for White that they are going to lose both f-pawns in the next few moves.}) 12... Nd7 $17 {[%cal Re8e5,Rh6g5,Rd7e5] White is going to lose material in the next moves.} *

