1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bg5 {[%cal Yf1d3,Ye1g1] Most likely will transpose to main lines, but it would be more important for White to finish development on the kingside before making this move.} h6 8. Bh4 O-O (8... O-O {And here White doesn't really have anything better than playing} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Bd4 {and transpose to 7. [Bd3] [O-O] lines.}) 9. Bc4 $2 {[%cal Yd7d5] Walking into the ...[d5] tempo is a serious mistake.} ({•} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Bd4 {And we are back to this line. ( 10.Qf3? Pretty much loses on the spot, because of 10...g5! 11.Bg3 d5 -+ Where not only the [e4]-pawn, but the queen is in a danger as well, because of ...[Bg4]! )}) ({•} 9. Qf3 {This is maybe some extra option for White, instead of developing on the kingside at all, going for long castle. However, it is quite great news for Black, because we already have the b-file opened to attack there.} Bd4 10. O-O-O Be5 {∞ With ...[d6], ...[Be6] to follow, Black has decent chances in this completely untested position.}) 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 g5 11. Bg3 Re8+ 12. Be2 (12. Kf1 Bg4 13. f3 Bf5 14. dxc6 Qe7 {∓ With ...[Rad8] coming next, White is in a serious danger.}) 12... Nxd5 {There are other attractive options for Black, but aiming for the exchange of queens with White's king locked to the [e2] bishop seems a good choice.} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 cxd5 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ye8e2,Rc8a6,Gf7f5,Gf5f4] It will not be easy for White to neutralise Black's pressure.} *

