1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. e5 $6 {Too ambitious from White.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Re7e5]} 8. Qe2 {This is the correct way of protecting the pawn, but after this the main point of [e5] is gone, since our knight can comfortably jump to [d5].} ({•} 8. f4 $2 d6 9. Qe2 dxe5 10. fxe5 Ng4 {-+ White weakened themself and didn't achieve anything.}) ({•} 8. Bf4 $2 d6 9. Qe2 dxe5 10. Bxe5 Bxf2+ $1 {Winning material for Black.} 11. Kxf2 Ng4+ {+ -+}) 8... Nd5 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2d1,Rd1d5,Rc3d5]} 9. Ne4 (9. Nxd5 cxd5 {Black's centre is very strong, while White has problems with finishing the development.} 10. Bf4 Rb8 11. Qg4 g6 {∓ (11.O-O-O This is already winning for Black. 11...Ba3! 12.bxa3 Qxa3+ 13.Kd2 Qb4 + -+)}) 9... Bd4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Re7e5]} 10. f4 f5 $1 {There are no good squares for the knight.} 11. exf6 ({•} 11. Ng5 $2 Rb8 $1 {White is losing the game on [b2].} 12. c3 Nxc3 13. Qd2 Qc5 14. Nf3 Rb4 15. Nxd4 Ne4 $1 {-+}) ({•} 11. Nf2 $2 Qb4+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Bxb2 {-+}) 11... Nxf6 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gc7,Gd4,Gd7][%cal Ga8b8] Black is slightly better with the stronger centre and more active pieces.} *

