1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Rf6e4,Gc4d3,Gd3e4] Very risky move, since the bishop should rather protect the pawn on [e4].} O-O 8. O-O Re8 {[%cal Rf6e4,Re8e4]} ({Putting more pressure to the e4-pawn. Originally I wanted to recommend} 8... d5 9. exd5 Ng4 $1 {instead, where some of the lines are excellent for Black, but unfortunately there are a few ways for White to make a quick draw, so I decided against it.}) 9. Re1 $2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge1e4] White copies Black's move and supports the [e4]-pawn, but actually it is a big mistake, which highlights the issues with [Bc4].} d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] White is forced to take on [d5].} 10. exd5 Rxe1+ 11. Qxe1 cxd5 12. Bd3 Ng4 $1 {Black is taking over the initiative.} 13. Nd1 Bd6 14. h3 Ne5 $17 {[%csl Rd3,Gd6,Ge5][%cal Gd8f6,Yc8h3] Black is clearly better, White's pieces were forced to very passive squares in the previous moves.} *

