1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the most popular move for White, and correctly so, they are protecting the centre and preparing to castle.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {White could also start with this move, but after} Re8 {they will castle anyway, transposing to the main line.} 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 Bd4 {Transposes to the variation we're studying.}) 8... Re8 {[%cal Rf6e4,Re8e4,Yc5d4,Yd4c3] Bringing the rook to the game in order to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn. This plan can be and is continued many times with ...[Bd4], targeting one of the main defenders of that pawn.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White is not only strengthening the pawn on [e4], but threatens to play [e5]!} d5 $1 {This break tends to work well when our opponent's rook is on [e1].} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Re4d5,Yg5d8] White is putting more pressure in our centre by pinning the knight.} h6 $1 {We have to break the pin right away.} 11. Bh4 (11. Bxf6 $6 {Fortunately this is not working at all, since} Qxf6 {⩱ is a big tempo on the [f2] pawn, so White doesn't have the time to take on [d5].}) 11... g5 12. Bg3 {[%csl Yg5,Rg8,Yh6] We have weakened ourselves on the kingside, so we have to justify it in the next moves, otherwise we are just worse. Generally it is done by attacking or winning the [e4]-pawn, but now it is well protected, so we need something else.} Bg4 $1 13. Qc1 (13. Qd2 $4 {is losing a piece to} dxe4 {-+}) 13... Nh5 $132 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Yh5g3,Yc5f2,Yd8f6,Rf6f2] This is the point, we are going to take the bishop on [g3], and after that we are doing well with our strong dark-squared bishop.} *

