nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the most popular move for White, and correctly so, they are protecting the centre and preparing to castle.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {White could also start with this move, but after} Re8 {they will castle anyway, transposing to the main line.} 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 Bd4 {Transposes to the variation we're studying.}) 8... Re8 {[%cal Rf6e4,Re8e4,Yc5d4,Yd4c3] Bringing the rook to the game in order to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn. This plan can be and is continued many times with ...[Bd4], targeting one of the main defenders of that pawn.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White is not only strengthening the pawn on [e4], but threatens to play [e5]!} d5 $1 {This break tends to work well when our opponent's rook is on [e1].} 10. exd5 (10. e5 $4 Ng4 {-+ is already game over, since not only [f2] and [e5] is hanging, but ...[Qh4] is coming as well.}) 10... Bg4 {Developing with a tempo can't be too bad.} 11. Rxe8+ Qxe8 12. Qf1 cxd5 13. Bf4 Qd7 $10 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gc7c6] The position is around equal, White's structure is slightly better, but Black is very active.} *

