1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the most popular move for White, and correctly so, they are protecting the centre and preparing to castle.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {White could also start with this move, but after} Re8 {they will castle anyway, transposing to the main line.} 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 Bd4 {Transposes to the variation we're studying.}) 8... Re8 {[%cal Rf6e4,Re8e4,Yc5d4,Yd4c3] Bringing the rook to the game in order to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn. This plan can be and is continued many times with ...[Bd4], targeting one of the main defenders of that pawn.} 9. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Rg5d8] The most annoying move against our setup, but if we can deal with this pin well, then we are doing very well.} (9. Qf3 {In general, when the queen blocks the way from the f-pawn, we should be quite relieved because in such positions after [Bg5], it is much easier to play with ...[h6] and ...[g5], since White can't open the kingside quickly with [f4].} d6 10. Bg5 Bd4 11. Qg3 Qe7 {With ... [Rb8] or ... [Qe5] coming next, Black has good counterplay.}) 9... h6 {It is useful to start with this move, just to always have the option of immediately breaking the pin with ...[g5] later.} 10. Bh4 Bd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf6][%cal Gd4f6,Rd4b2,Ya8b8,Rb8b2] Quite an unusual square for a bishop, but it does a great job of defending and also puts pressure on the queenside, especially when it is combined with ...[Rb8].} 11. Re1 Rb8 {[%cal Rb8b2] It is already slightly tricky to protect the pawn on [b2].} 12. Rb1 (12. Na4 {This is really not an ideal square for the knight.} d6 13. Qd2 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 {⩱ Black is taking the bishop on [g3] and with that reaches a slightly better position with the pair of bishops.}) 12... g5 {The position is going to become sharp, so it is good to break the pin and have the ...[Nxe4] option available.} 13. Bg3 Rxb2 $1 {[%csl Rc3] A nice trick, but White can maintain equality.} 14. Rxb2 Bxc3 {[%cal Rc3b2,Rc3e1]} 15. Rb8 Bxe1 16. Qxe1 Nxe4 $1 {Another pawn.} 17. Bxe4 d5 $10 {Unfortunately the position is just equal, because our kingside is weakened and we also have many weak pawns.} *

