1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Nxc6 {One of the main lines, White is gaining a better structure and also a tempo for future development.} bxc6 {We are obviously not interested in trading queens and entering a horrible version of a Berlin-type endgame.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] This is the most popular move for White, and correctly so, they are protecting the centre and preparing to castle.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Bg5 {White could also start with this move, but after} Re8 {they will castle anyway, transposing to the main line.} 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 Bd4 {Transposes to the variation we're studying.}) 8... Re8 {[%cal Rf6e4,Re8e4,Yc5d4,Yd4c3] Bringing the rook to the game in order to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn. This plan can be and is continued many times with ...[Bd4], targeting one of the main defenders of that pawn.} 9. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Rg5d8] The most annoying move against our setup, but if we can deal with this pin well, then we are doing very well.} (9. Qf3 {In general, when the queen blocks the way from the f-pawn, we should be quite relieved because in such positions after [Bg5], it is much easier to play with ...[h6] and ...[g5], since White can't open the kingside quickly with [f4].} d6 10. Bg5 Bd4 11. Qg3 Qe7 {With ... [Rb8] or ... [Qe5] coming next, Black has good counterplay.}) 9... h6 {It is useful to start with this move, just to always have the option of immediately breaking the pin with ...[g5] later.} 10. Bh4 Bd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf6][%cal Gd4f6,Rd4b2,Ya8b8,Rb8b2] Quite an unusual square for a bishop, but it does a great job of defending and also puts pressure on the queenside, especially when it is combined with ...[Rb8].} 11. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] This move looks the most challenging to me. White is preparing to push [f4].} (11. Qf3 $2 {This is just a blunder.} g5 $1 12. Bg3 d5 {∓ Black is much better because of the ... [Bg4]-threat.}) 11... g5 $1 {Very concrete play starts from now on!} 12. Bg3 Bxc3 $1 {After ... [g5] we have to show something, and we are doing so by taking the pawn on [e4]!} 13. bxc3 Nxe4 14. Qh5 (14. f4 {This is very similar to 14. [Qh5], with chances to transpose as well.} Nxg3+ {(14...d6 15.Qh5 Bf5! This is another way to reach equality, there are a lot of forcing lines here, all ending with very drawish endgames. )} 15. hxg3 Qf6 $1 {Here} 16. Qh5 {would just transpose, but White can also try 16.fxg5 Qxg5 17.Qf3 Qd5! And Black seems to be doing okay. 18.Qg4+ Qg5 19.Qf3 Qd5=}) 14... Qf6 $1 15. f4 $1 ({White has to open the kingside.} 15. Bxc7 {White takes back the material, but with this allows for Black to close the kingside.} d6 16. f4 g4 $1 {Of course! We don't want to open the f-file.} 17. Rad1 Bf5 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Rxd6 Re6 {With the opposite-coloured bishops draw is a very likely result here.}) 15... Nxg3+ ({Instead} 15... Qg6 {is pretty much forcing a draw, since White can't avoid the trade of the queens, because then the kingside will be closed. However, after the text move it is rather White who has to prove equality, despite Black's position looking dangerous.}) 16. hxg3 Re7 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7,Yd7d6,Yc8d7] The key defensive move, the rook covers the [f7]-square.} 17. Rae1 (17. fxg5 Qxg5 18. Qf3 d6 19. Qxc6 Rb8 {The position is equal, and Black's king is not at all weaker than its colleague.}) 17... Rxe1 18. Rxe1 d6 19. Re8+ Kg7 {[%cal Yc8b7] White just doesn't have enough pieces to even create threats here.} 20. fxg5 Qxg5 21. Qh4 $1 {The only move to keep equality! Not an easy one!} Qxh4+ 22. gxh4 Bb7 23. Re7 Bc8 24. Rxc7 Be6 $10 {The material is very limited, with the draw being the most likely result. Let's see how the game might end.} (24... Be6 {•} 25. a4 a5 {Fixing the pawn on [a4], so the bishop can attack it later.} 26. Rxc6 Bd7 27. Rc4 Rc8 {The bishop endgame is also completely harmless for Black. ( • 25.Be4 a5 26.Bxc6 Rb8= The rook will be active either on [b2]. If White moves their rook, then it could go to [c8] as well. ) ( • 25.Rxc6 Bxa2 26.Rxd6 White has an extra pawn, but actually Black's a-pawn is the most dangerous one, since it is supported by the rook. 26...a5! White has to be careful to keep the balance. 27.Be4 Ra7 28.Rd1! Be6 29.Ra1 a4 30.Ra3 White is stopping the pawn before it could go too far. 30...Bd7= ...[Kf6]-[e5] is coming, and Black is not worse at all. )}) *

