[GameId "2160376117936043"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Bg5 $6 {White takes a page from our book, and moves the bishop for the second time. But this one is just really bad, since it is basically answering the 5...[Bb4] main line with 6. [Bg5], which already leads to advantage for Black.} h6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] Immediately asking the bishop, since there are problems with the [e4]-pawn.} 8. Nxc6 {[%cal Gf1d3] White has to include this move at some point, so the bishop can develop to [d3] and protect the pawn on [e4].} ({•} 8. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 9. Ndb5 Ba5 $1 {-+ With ... [a6] coming on the next move, Black is close to winning.}) ({•} 8. Bh4 O-O {...[g5] is a big threat now, followed by ...[Nxe4], and in order to develop with [Bd3], White has to take on [c6], transposing to 8. [Nxc6] lines.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to the current variation.}) 8... bxc6 9. Bd2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Yb4c3,Yd2c3,Rc3g7] White is 'protecting' the [e4]-pawn by preparing to recapture on [c3] with the bishop and then attack the [g7]-pawn.} Qe7 {[%cal Rf6e4]} 10. Qe2 ({•} 10. Bd3 $2 {This just drops the [e4]-pawn, because of discovered checks from the knight.} Bxc3 $1 11. Bxc3 Nxe4 {∓ And White can't take on [g7], because of ...[Nc3]+ winning the queen.}) ({•} 10. f3 d5 $1 {Increasing the pressure on [e4].} 11. Bd3 dxe4 12. Nxe4 {(12.fxe4 Ng4! ∓ The knight is coming to [e5], but there are also ...[Bc5] ideas against White's king. )} Nxe4 13. fxe4 Rb8 {⩱ Black is slightly better, now White has to solve problems with the [b2]-pawn, and then ...[Bc5] or ...[Qc5] is coming, making it tough for White to castle.}) 10... O-O {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg8g7,Rb4c3,Re7e4] The pawn is protected on [g7], so it means that White has to do something with [e4]-pawn.} 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga8b8] White is going to castle long most likely, and then it will be much easier to attack for Black, since the b-file is already opened for the rooks.} *

