nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Bg5 $6 {White takes a page from our book, and moves the bishop for the second time. But this one is just really bad, since it is basically answering the 5...[Bb4] main line with 6. [Bg5], which already leads to advantage for Black.} h6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] Immediately asking the bishop, since there are problems with the [e4]-pawn.} 8. Nxc6 {[%cal Gf1d3] White has to include this move at some point, so the bishop can develop to [d3] and protect the pawn on [e4].} ({•} 8. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 9. Ndb5 Ba5 $1 {-+ With ... [a6] coming on the next move, Black is close to winning.}) ({•} 8. Bh4 O-O {...[g5] is a big threat now, followed by ...[Nxe4], and in order to develop with [Bd3], White has to take on [c6], transposing to 8. [Nxc6] lines.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to the current variation.}) 8... bxc6 9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qf3 Qxf3 11. gxf3 O-O {∓ Black has the pair of bishops and the better structure in this endgame.}) 9... O-O {[%csl Re4][%cal Rg7g5,Yf6e4] The threat is ...[g5] followed by ...[Nxe4].} (9... g5 {This is possible and good, but we can be already more ambitious.} 10. Bg3 Nxe4 11. Qd4 $1 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Bd3 d5 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. h4 {∞}) 10. e5 $6 Qe7 11. Bxf6 (11. f4 g5 $1 {White's position is falling apart.} 12. Bg3 Ne4 {∓}) 11... gxf6 12. Qg4+ Kh8 13. Qh4 {White is giving up the pawn, but hoping for some counterplay on the kingside, unfortunately for them, there is not much.} Qxe5+ 14. Kd1 Qd6+ $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd6b4] Protecting the bishop with a tempo, and once the check is blocked...} 15. Bd3 f5 $15 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd6b4,Gd6h6] The queen is just protecting everything from [d6].} *

