 Bh4 O-O {...[g5] is a big threat now, followed by ...[Nxe4], and in order to develop with [Bd3], White has to take on [c6], transposing to 8. [Nxc6] lines.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to the current variation.}) 8... bxc6 9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qf3 Qxf3 11. gxf3 O-O {∓ Black has the pair of bishops and the better structure in this endgame.}) 9... O-O {[%csl Re4][%cal Rg7g5,Yf6e4] The threat is ...[g5] followed by ...[Nxe4].} (9... g5 {This is possible and good, but we can be already more ambitious.} 10. Bg3 Nxe4 11. Qd4 $1 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Bd3 d5 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. h4 {∞}) 10. Bd3 d5 $1 {Just before White could finish development Black is striking in the centre.} 11. e5 $2 Re8 {[%csl Re5] The [e5]-pawn or some other material is going to fall for White.} 12. f4 (12. Qe2 Qe7 13. f4 {(13.exf6? Qd8 -+ Wins the queen. )} Qc5 {∓ There is pressure on [c3], White can't castle, and also has no threats anymore, since the queen is out from the pin.}) 12... g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Yg5f4,Ye8e5] The key move, White can't keep the centre.} 13. Bg3 Bg4 {Bringing out the pieces with a tempo.} 14. Be2 d4 $17 {[%cal Rd4c3]} (14... d4 {...dxc3 is coming, White is close to losing. Of course,} 15. exf6 {doesn't work due to} Bxe2 $1 {-+}) *

