1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] A decent move, White is continuing the development.} Nxd4 $5 {A new move, with the aim of creating an imbalanced position.} 8. Bxd4 c5 $1 {[%cal Yd4e3,Rb4c3] This is the point, we are forcing away the bishop from protecting the knight on [c3], so we can create doubled pawns.} 9. Be3 ({•} 9. Be5 {White keeps the [c3]-square covered for the moment.} Qe7 10. Bf4 c4 $1 {One of the few ways to reach a decent position.} 11. Bxc4 Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 O-O) ({•} 9. Bxf6 {This is also possible, but completely harmless for Black.} Qxf6 10. Qd2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. O-O d6 {Black is completely fine here, we have a backward pawn on [d6], but White's queenside is also very weak.}) 9... d5 {First we want to bring the queen into the centre, and then take on [c3].} 10. e5 {Very ambitious, but also gives good chances for Black.} Ng4 {[%cal Rg4e3,Rg4e5]} 11. Bf4 (11. Bf4 {Black has different ways here, but since it was never played in practice, I suggest avoiding the huge complications which are arising after both} g5 {and 11...d4 .}) 11... c4 $1 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Yd3b5] The point is that, once Black plays ...[d4], White can't give [Bb5]+ which can lead to very dangerous positions for Black, since blocking the check with ...[Bd7] is not really possible, because we lose the knight on [g4].} 12. Be2 {[%cal Re2g4]} d4 13. Bxg4 (13. a3 {This can lead to a very weird endgame.} dxc3 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. axb4 cxb2 16. Rd1+ Ke7 17. h3 Rd8 $1 18. Rb1 Nxf2 $1 {With the idea of having very strong pawns for the piece.} 19. Kxf2 c3 {⇆ It looks very dangerous for White to play this position.}) 13... O-O $10 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Rb4e1,Gf8d8] We have time for this move, since White can't save the knight on [c3]. We are going to take on [c3] on the next move with a fine position.} (13... O-O {One possible line is} 14. Bd2 dxc3 15. bxc3 Bxg4 16. Qxg4 Qd5 $1 17. O-O Ba5 {And Black is taking the pawn on [e5] or [c3] on the next move.}) *

