nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] This is the most common move, and the one which White is going to play if they don't know the theory.} d6 {[%cal Yf6g4,Rg4e3]} ({A tricky moment for us, since} 8... d5 {or 8...O-O are extremely likely to transpose to the main ...[Bb4] lines after White eventually plays [Bg5] and loses a tempo. So, we need something different, and for that reason it is good that the bishop is on [e3] now and not on [c1], since our ...[Ng4] idea can come with a tempo.}) 9. Bg5 {With this we transpose to one of the sidelines of the 5...[Bb4] system, where Black is not playing ...[d5].} h6 {The pin is unpleasant, and with this move we give the ...[g5] option to ourselves.} 10. Bh4 Be6 {A clever waiting move, Black doesn't want to commit to ...[g5] before White castles.} 11. f4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg5][%cal Yf4g5,Ge1g1] Looks extremely unpleasant, before castling White prevents ...[g5] and gains more space in the centre.} g5 $1 {Without this, the line would be very dubious, but it just works very well.} 12. Bg3 (12. fxg5 Ng4 13. Qd2 Bc5 {With the huge threat of ...[Be3] and taking back the material.} 14. Nd1 Rg8 {⩱ Taking back the pawn on [g5] with a better position.}) 12... gxf4 13. Bh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4d8]} ({Again this pin!} 13. Bxf4 Ng4 {⇆ The knight goes to [e5] and Black is very stable.}) 13... Rg8 $1 {[%cal Gg8g4,Rg4h4] Black wants to play ...[Rg4] and break the pin.} 14. Be2 $1 Rg5 {There are many other options for Black, but this seems to be quite safe. Black would have a much better position if White takes the rook.} 15. O-O (15. Bxg5 $2 hxg5 {∓ With moves like ...[Rb8]-... [Nd7]-[e5] to follow, Black clearly has the upper hand, since the dark square are very weak in White's camp.}) 15... Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Qb8 $132 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rg4e3,Rb8b2] The position remains complicated, but Black is very active.} *

