1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] This is the most common move, and the one which White is going to play if they don't know the theory.} d6 {[%cal Yf6g4,Rg4e3]} ({A tricky moment for us, since} 8... d5 {or 8...O-O are extremely likely to transpose to the main ...[Bb4] lines after White eventually plays [Bg5] and loses a tempo. So, we need something different, and for that reason it is good that the bishop is on [e3] now and not on [c1], since our ...[Ng4] idea can come with a tempo.}) 9. Bg5 {With this we transpose to one of the sidelines of the 5...[Bb4] system, where Black is not playing ...[d5].} h6 {The pin is unpleasant, and with this move we give the ...[g5] option to ourselves.} 10. Bh4 Be6 {A clever waiting move, Black doesn't want to commit to ...[g5] before White castles.} 11. O-O g5 $1 {Once White castled, we not only break the pin, but start attacking on the kingside!} 12. Bg3 h5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yh5h4] The bishop is in a danger on [g3].} 13. f3 {Probably the most human move, the bishop should stand much better on [f2] than on [h2].} ({•} 13. f4 $6 {Positionally dubious, since after the trade of the pawns, the [e5]-square will be available for the knight.} Bc5+ 14. Bf2 Bxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Ng4 $1 {Going towards e5 with a tempo!} 16. Rf3 gxf4 {⩱ And White can't even take back on [f4] right away, because after} 17. Rxf4 Qh4 $1 18. h3 Qg3 {-+ is winning for Black.}) ({•} 13. h3 {Providing a retreat square for the bishop.} h4 14. Bh2 g4 $1 {We have to continue the attack.} 15. e5 $1 {(15.hxg4 Nxg4 ∓)} dxe5 16. Bxe5 Rg8 {⇆ Black has great counterplay on the g-file.}) 13... h4 14. Bf2 (14. Be1 $2 {This is not the right square for the bishop.} Bc5+ 15. Kh1 Nh5 {⩱}) 14... h3 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] It can be good to weaken the [f3]-square, since our knight eventually wants to reach [e5].} 15. g3 Bxc3 {It is time to take, since otherwise White plays [Ne2]-[d4] and it would just be a better piece than our bishop.} 16. bxc3 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gh8g8,Gd8f6] We want to play ...[Rg8] and ...[Ne5] in the next moves. It is tough to say where do we want to put our king, probably for now it will stay in the centre, but it is equally tough to say, how White should proceed in this position.} *

