1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Ge1c1,Gd4c3,Gd4e4,Rd4b4,Ye4e5] This move is the critical test of the whole 5...[Bc5], 6...[Bb4] line. White is using their extra move Be3 to speed up the development and castle long. Also, the queen is doing excellent defensive and attacking role in the centre. The good thing is that it only happened in 8 games! so far.} (8. Bg5 $6 h6 9. Bh4 O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to 7. [Bg5] [h6] lines.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ge7b4,Re7e4] Protecting the bishop and attacking the [e4]-pawn. Now, White has a wide choice, but in practice they played [O-O-O] in 6 out of the 7 games.} 9. e5 $6 {Poses zero problems for Black, the only good side of the move is that the pawn is not hanging on [e4] anymore.} c5 $1 ({Instead,} 9... Nd5 {is also fine for Black, but we can already play for the advantage.}) 10. Qf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] The only square for the queen, which is still protecting the [e5]-pawn.} (10. exf6 $6 cxd4 11. fxe7 dxe3 12. fxe3 c6 {⩱ Black is definitely better in this endgame with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Nd5 {[%cal Rd5c3,Rd5f4] Now this move comes with a tempo and double attack!} 11. Qe4 {[%cal Re4a8] White is protecting on [c3] by indirectly attacking our rook on [a8].} c6 12. Bd2 Nxc3 $1 13. bxc3 d5 $1 {The key move, Black gains a big tempo for free.} 14. Qf4 Ba5 15. Qa4 Qc7 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Re5][%cal Ge8g8,Gc5c4] With a much better structure, Black is doing excellently here.} *

