ishop and attacking the [e4]-pawn. Now, White has a wide choice, but in practice they played [O-O-O] in 6 out of the 7 games.} 9. e5 $6 {Poses zero problems for Black, the only good side of the move is that the pawn is not hanging on [e4] anymore.} c5 $1 ({Instead,} 9... Nd5 {is also fine for Black, but we can already play for the advantage.}) 10. Qf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] The only square for the queen, which is still protecting the [e5]-pawn.} (10. exf6 $6 cxd4 11. fxe7 dxe3 12. fxe3 c6 {⩱ Black is definitely better in this endgame with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Nd5 {[%cal Rd5c3,Rd5f4] Now this move comes with a tempo and double attack!} 11. Qg3 $1 {[%cal Rg3g7] White has to find counterplay, and it is against the [g7]-pawn.} (11. Qf3 $2 c6 {∓ With both [c3] and [e5] hanging, White is in trouble.}) 11... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] The plan is to meet [Qxg7] with ...[O-O-O]!} (11... Nxc3 12. Qxg7 $1 {Black doesn't have dangerous discovered checks.} Rf8 13. a3 Ba5 14. Bd2 $1 Bb7 15. Qf6) 12. Bd2 (12. Qxg7 $2 O-O-O {-+}) 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 f6 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge8c8] White has problems with the [e5]-pawn, and we can just castle long, where our king will be very safe.} *

