1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Ge1c1,Gd4c3,Gd4e4,Rd4b4,Ye4e5] This move is the critical test of the whole 5...[Bc5], 6...[Bb4] line. White is using their extra move Be3 to speed up the development and castle long. Also, the queen is doing excellent defensive and attacking role in the centre. The good thing is that it only happened in 8 games! so far.} (8. Bg5 $6 h6 9. Bh4 O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to 7. [Bg5] [h6] lines.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ge7b4,Re7e4] Protecting the bishop and attacking the [e4]-pawn. Now, White has a wide choice, but in practice they played [O-O-O] in 6 out of the 7 games.} 9. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ge1c1] White is keeping the options of castling either way.} O-O 10. e5 (10. O-O Ng4 $1 11. h3 {(11.Bd2?? is losing to 11...Bc5 12.Qc4 Qh4 -+)} Nxe3 12. Qxe3 Qc5 {Black is doing very well with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Nd5 {Black again can't play ...[c5], because at the end of the line the rook on [f8] is hanging.} 11. O-O {In general it is hard to believe that White can fight for anything serious if they give up the dark-squared bishop.} Nxe3 12. Qxe3 Re8 13. Rae1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] White is preparing to launch on attack on the kingside with [f4]-[f5].} d5 14. Kh1 {[%cal Yf2f4,Rb4c5,Rc5g1] Without the queen, attacking would be more difficult for White. 🙂} Bd7 $1 15. f4 f6 $1 {The right timing! White's attack is stopped before it could really get going.} 16. Qg3 fxe5 17. fxe5 Rf8 $13 {[%csl Re5] For now the position is balanced, but it is much more difficult to play as White, since they have to prove that the [e5]-pawn is not a weakness.} *

