nced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Ge1c1,Gd4c3,Gd4e4,Rd4b4,Ye4e5] This move is the critical test of the whole 5...[Bc5], 6...[Bb4] line. White is using their extra move Be3 to speed up the development and castle long. Also, the queen is doing excellent defensive and attacking role in the centre. The good thing is that it only happened in 8 games! so far.} (8. Bg5 $6 h6 9. Bh4 O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to 7. [Bg5] [h6] lines.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ge7b4,Re7e4] Protecting the b