1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {White is not putting immediate pressure on Black's position with this move but, strangely enough, this variation still gives the least options for Black in the 1. [e4] [e5] opening variations.} Nf6 ({The only decent move for Black. I really tried to make every other move work, but they simply don't. 🙂 The point is that we can't develop our dark-squared bishop, because} 3... Bc5 {is met by} 4. Nxe5 $1 {and then [d4], and 3...Bb4 can be answered by 4.Nd5! . And if we try some other 'clever' way, like 3...g6 or 3...Be7 , then White can play 4.d4! with a nice space advantage in the centre.After the text move we reach the Four Knights Variation, which is an extremely solid and stable one for White, and one of the toughest to create winning chances for Black.}) 4. d4 {One of 3 different approaches for White, and I would say it is the most difficult to handle, because after the exchange on [d4], White will have some advantage in the center with the [e4] pawn. The other major main line is 4. [Bb5], and there will also be a chapter with all the other possible slower and sometimes trickier options for White.} exd4 ({We have an alternative with} 4... Bb4 {, but the days when that move could be a surprise are long gone, and White has many ways to reach a good position.}) 5. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4] The real starting position of this line. White claims that with the pawn on [e4] and some space advantage they could be slightly better, but since that the [e4]-pawn is on a semi-open file, Black also should be able to create counterplay against it, or just challenge it by playing ...[d5].} Bc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc5d4,Yc6d4]} ({Not the most logical, and I have to say, most likely not the best move in the position, but the most fighting one. What could be more logical than playing} 5... Bb4 {, pinning the knight on [c3] and immediately attacking the [e4]-pawn? Well, nothing, and indeed 5...[Bb4] is a very reliable way for Black to play, but the theory is so far advanced in those lines and there seems to be so little room for improvement that I rather offer the text move, where objectively we can be maybe slightly worse in a few lines, but the chances to get a fighting game are much higher.}) 6. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Gd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd4c6] White is protecting the knight on [d4] and also have the [Nxc6]-threat since our bishop is loose on [c5].} (6. Nf3 $4 {Unfortunately not many people will play like this. 🙂} Ng4 $1 {And Black is getting a winning position straight out of the opening.} 7. Be3 Nxe3 8. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ (Bishop pair + an extra pawn.)}) 6... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Yd7d6,Rf6g4,Ye8g8,Yf8e8,Re8e4,Rf6e4] A very rare move, and it looks somewhat strange for sure. 🙂 We just developed our bishop to [c5] in order to avoid main lines after 5...[Bb4], and now once White developed their bishop to [e3], we are suddenly going to [b4] anyway. Besides losing a tempo, Black has other points too.It would be silly to say that the bishop is worse on [e3] than on [c1], but in some aspects it is. For example, once Black attacks this pawn with ...[Re8], then the bishop is on the way to protect the pawn, and if it happens with [f3], then after ...[d5] once our knight recaptures on [d5], it can be a tempo on the bishop. Another possible issue can be, that when Black plays ...[d6], then the idea of ...[Ng4] is also much more serious, since it is hitting the bishop with a tempo.} 7. Nxc6 {Similarly to the 5... [Bb4] main line, here also this capture is the correct move for White.} bxc6 8. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Ge1c1,Gd4c3,Gd4e4,Rd4b4,Ye4e5] This move is the critical test of the whole 5...[Bc5], 6...[Bb4] line. White is using their extra move Be3 to speed up the development and castle long. Also, the queen is doing excellent defensive and attacking role in the centre. The good thing is that it only happened in 8 games! so far.} (8. Bg5 $6 h6 9. Bh4 O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {Transposes to 7. [Bg5] [h6] lines.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ge7b4,Re7e4] Protecting the bishop and attacking the [e4]-pawn. Now, White has a wide choice, but in practice they played [O-O-O] in 6 out of the 7 games.} 9. a3 {This was never tried yet.} Ba5 (9... Bxc3+ $2 10. Qxc3 Qxe4 {White is getting huge play and an open e-file for just one pawn.} 11. Bd3 Qe6 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Rhe1 {± Black's position is very critical here.}) 10. e5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yb4a5,Yc6c5,Gb4c5] A move ago it was very bad for White, because we had ...[c5]!, now it is not available since the bishop is not guarding that square anymore.} (10. O-O-O O-O {This is the main line with [a3]-[Ba5] included.} 11. e5 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Nd5 13. Qd4 {(13.Qc5 Qxe5 ⇆)} Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Re8 15. f4 d5 {⇆ Having an extra [a3]-move may be some achievement for White, but overall the position shouldn't change much.}) 10... Nd5 {[%cal Rd5c3,Rd5e3]} 11. Bd2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 c5 {Eventually we can get this tempo in!} 13. Qe3 Bxc3+ 14. Qxc3 d5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5] Otherwise our position would be pretty passive, but now we have a decent centre.} 15. Bb5+ {This is the only issue with ...[d5]. 🙂} (15. O-O-O $2 c6 {⩱ We will castle and then start attacking on the b-file.}) 15... Kf8 16. O-O {[%csl Yc5,Yd5,Rf8] We have to play precisely here, since we have issues with our king, and also our centre is shaky at this moment.} (16. O-O-O {This is the less dangerous move.} d4 17. Qa5 h5 {⇆ With ...[Rh6]-[b6] and then ... [Rb8] coming, Black's position is fine.}) 16... Rb8 17. a4 (17. Bd3 c4 $1 18. Be2 c5 {If White does nothing, we just play ...[Be6] and ...[g6] with a very solid position.} 19. b3 cxb3 20. cxb3 d4 21. Qa5 g6 {The king is getting to [g7], Black is equal.}) 17... a6 18. Be2 {Not giving the ...[c4] tempo for Black.} d4 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Re5][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] White will lose either the [e5] or the [b2]-pawn, and even though they will obviously have compensation, ...[g6] followed by ...[Kg7] is not a long plan.} *

