1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1] The latest trend, played many times by GM Naroditsky. White is not interested in taking back the [d4]-pawn quickly, they rather prefer rapid development.} d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Continuing development and threatening to play ...[Bg4].} 7. O-O $6 Bg4 $1 {Black is easily solving their problems here, and for White it will be not easy to take back the pawn on [d4] and maintain equality.} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Ne5 {More trades are coming.} 10. Qg3 Nxd5 11. exd5 O-O $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ge7f6,Gc7c5] Black has good chances to keep the extra pawn.} *

