1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1] The latest trend, played many times by GM Naroditsky. White is not interested in taking back the [d4]-pawn quickly, they rather prefer rapid development.} d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Continuing development and threatening to play ...[Bg4].} 7. h3 $1 {The pin would be very annoying for White, so they have to take the time and play this move.} O-O 8. O-O (8. Nxe7+ $2 {This is not working at all.} Qxe7 9. Bg5 h6 {Black can easily break the pin.} 10. Bh4 g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 d5 {-+ White has no pieces to attack our king.}) 8... Nxd5 {There are other ways with more complicated positions, but that is what White is looking for, I guess.} 9. exd5 Ne5 10. Nxd4 Nxd3 {Very solid play.} 11. Qxd3 Bf6 {[%csl Gd5] White has some space advantage in the centre, but Black has no weaknesses in a symmetrical position.} 12. c4 Re8 13. Bd2 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf5 $10 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gb7b6] The position is completely equal, we can put our pawns on dark squares next, in order to restrict White's bishop.} *

