1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Nxd4 {This line doesn't pose any problems for Black, it just leads to early exchanges.} Nxd5 7. exd5 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O {White didn't manage to get anything out of the opening.} 9. Be2 Bf6 (9... c5 $5) 10. Qd3 d6 11. O-O Re8 $10 {[%csl Gf6,Gg5][%cal Yg7g6,Gc8f5] Black has zero problems, and if White is ambitious they can get into trouble, since after all Black is slightly ahead in development.} *

