1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Rd5c7] White has a big threat, but it is very easy to address.} d6 7. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4b5] It is not the pawn, which is important for White, but rather the option of going to [b5].} O-O $1 ({We can be ambitious here.} 7... Nxd5 {Trading pieces is still available and perfectly good for Black.} 8. exd5 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. O-O-O Bf6) 8. Nb5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Yg1f3,Yf3d4,Yd4b5] White is losing too much time with this knight.} (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {And White is losing the pawn on [e4], because} 10. f3 {is met by} Nxe4 11. Qe2 Re8 $1 12. fxe4 Qxe4 {-+}) 8... Nxd5 9. exd5 Ne5 {[%csl Gd5] White managed to get some space advantage in the centre, but in return Black is much better developed and can fight for the advantage.} 10. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Preparing long castle.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ya7a6,Yb7b5] An excellent move, the space White tried to control with the [d5]-pawn is gone.} 11. Be2 ({•} 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Nd4 c5 {∓ White is losing more time.}) ({•} 11. Bxe5 dxe5 12. d6 Bg5 13. Qd5 Qa5+ 14. c3 Be6 {∓ White is much worse with the lack of development and loose knight on [b5].}) 11... a6 12. Nc3 f5 $15 {[%cal Rf5e4,Rc5d4,Ge5g6,Gb7b5] Black is controlling the centre much better than White, and can start creating threats from the next move on.} *

