1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Rd5c7] White has a big threat, but it is very easy to address.} d6 7. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4b5] It is not the pawn, which is important for White, but rather the option of going to [b5].} O-O $1 ({We can be ambitious here.} 7... Nxd5 {Trading pieces is still available and perfectly good for Black.} 8. exd5 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. O-O-O Bf6) 8. Nb5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Yg1f3,Yf3d4,Yd4b5] White is losing too much time with this knight.} (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {And White is losing the pawn on [e4], because} 10. f3 {is met by} Nxe4 11. Qe2 Re8 $1 12. fxe4 Qxe4 {-+}) 8... Nxd5 9. exd5 Ne5 {[%csl Gd5] White managed to get some space advantage in the centre, but in return Black is much better developed and can fight for the advantage.} 10. Be2 Ng6 $1 {Asking some questions before White could castle.} 11. Be3 Bg5 $1 {This would be an excellent trade for Black, and also getting the control over the [f4]-square along the way.} 12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. g3 (13. Nxc7 $2 {The pawn is poisoned.} Qxg2 14. Bf3 Qg5 15. Nxa8 Re8+ 16. Be2 Nf4 {-+ And Black is going to take a lot of material.}) 13... Re8 $1 14. O-O (14. Nxc7 $4 {Still doesn't work,} Bg4 15. Ne6 Qe5 $1 {-+}) 14... Re7 $15 {[%cal Gc8h3,Ya7a6,Ga8e8] We will play ...[Bh3], then kick the knight back, and then double on the e-file with a better position.} *

