1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] White is strengthening the control over the [d5]-square.} O-O {It is always a good thing to castle against a gambit!} 7. O-O Nxe4 (7... d6 {is more common, but since we castled, I don't see any issue with taking this pawn.}) 8. Nxd4 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Yf6d5,Yc6d4] Offering trades.} 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 $1 {Anticipating the pin very nicely.} 10. Bg5 Ng6 $15 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Yh7h6,Yg6h4,Rg5h4] The knight is taking away the [h4]-square from the bishop, so after ...[h6] in the next move, Black is just a clear pawn up.} *

