1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] White is strengthening the control over the [d5]-square.} O-O {It is always a good thing to castle against a gambit!} 7. O-O Nxe4 (7... d6 {is more common, but since we castled, I don't see any issue with taking this pawn.}) 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Nxe7+ (9. Rxe7 $2 {Leads nowhere.} Nxe7 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 d5 $1 {∓}) 9... Nxe7 10. Bg5 d5 $1 11. Bxf6 gxf6 {Our kingside is weakened, but we have two extra pawns for it.} 12. Qxd4 (12. Bd3 Bg4 {⩱}) 12... dxc4 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rxe7 c5 $15 {Black has an extra pawn and excellent winning chances in this endgame.} *

