1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd7d5] The Belgrade Gambit can be a rather dangerous line in the hands of strong attacking players. Objectively it should not give White any advantage, but many times, even if the computer prefers Black, most people would take White in a heartbeat. The main point is that White prevents the move ...[d5], which, as we have seen in many other lines, is the ultimate development move for Black in 1. [e4] [e5] openings.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] The main line, and probably the most solid way to continue. Black doesn't want to compete with White in sharper lines and just wants to finish development with ...[O-O].} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] White is strengthening the control over the [d5]-square.} O-O {It is always a good thing to castle against a gambit!} 7. O-O Nxe4 (7... d6 {is more common, but since we castled, I don't see any issue with taking this pawn.}) 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Nxe7+ (9. Rxe7 $2 {Leads nowhere.} Nxe7 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 d5 $1 {∓}) 9... Nxe7 10. Qxd4 {White doesn't have anything immediate here, they are playing for long-term compensation with the pair of bishops.} d6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yf3e5,Yc8g4] I like this move better than the main line, which is 10... [d5], with the idea of restricting the knight on [f3], and ...[Bg4] can't be met by [Ne5] after this.} 11. Bg5 (11. b4 {it is not so effective now.} Bg4 $1 12. Bg5 Bxf3 {This is a forced line, which leads to a double-edged endgame.} 13. Bxf6 Nc6 14. Bxd8 Nxd4 15. Be7 Rfe8 16. gxf3 Nxc2 17. Rad1 Nxe1 18. Rxe1 d5 19. Bb3 c6 {Objectively it should be equal, but only Black can win such an endgame.}) 11... Nf5 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Rf5d4,Yh7h6,Rf5h4,Yg5h4] Hitting the queen with a tempo and preparing to play ...[h6].} 12. Qf4 (12. Qc3 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Re4 Ng7 {∞ White has compensation for the pawn, whether it is enough for a draw or not, is a good question.}) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. g4 {[%csl Rf5] Our knight is trapped, but we have the intermediate} g5 $1 15. Qe4 d5 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf5d6] Creating a square for the knight on [d6].} (15... Ng7 $4 16. Bd3 {+- And Black is losing.}) 16. Bxd5 (16. Qxd5 Nd6 {∓ White's position is very loose.}) 16... c6 $1 17. gxf5 (17. Bxc6 $4 Nd6 {-+ is winning a piece.}) 17... cxd5 (17... Bxf5 $4 {The 4th intermezzo in a row is just too much. 🙂} 18. Qd4 $1 Qxd4 19. Nxd4 {+-}) 18. Qxd5 Bxf5 $132 {[%csl Gg8] Black has the safer king, and good chances to reach a better position in the next few moves.} *

