1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nxe5 $6 {The Halloween Gambit, clearly a dubious opening variation. Black made no weakening move for such a large sacrifice to work, but if we are too eager to keep all the material advantage, we can find ourselves in trouble, especially in shorter time controls.} Nxe5 5. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rd4e5,Re4e5] White wants to gain a lot of tempi and control the centre, but yeah, a piece for only a pawn is too much.} Ng6 $1 {[%cal Ye5c6,Rd4d5] So this knight can't be chased again.} 6. e5 {White has managed to occupy the centre and force our knights to passive squares, but what is next?} Ng8 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Yg6,Yg8]} 7. Bc4 {[%cal Rc4f7] They are attacking the [f7]-pawn, maybe with [Qf3] to follow, so we have to prepare against that.} c6 {[%cal Yd7d5] Preparing to push ...[d5].} 8. Qe2 {[%cal Yd7d5,Ye5d6,Re2e8] Aimed against ...[d5], but the move is pretty slow, since White is down a piece after all.} Bb4 {We can continue the development, even though it gives back a pawn, we shouldn't be afraid to give back some material if it takes away the power from White's central pawns.} 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qc4+ d5 {[%csl Gb7,Gc6,Gd5] We are very solid now, if White is not taking en passant, then we can comfortably develop and play on the light squares.} 11. exd6+ Be6 12. Qxb4 Qb6 $19 {[%csl Rd4,Rd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gh8e8,Gf7g8,Ga8d8] White has 3 pawns now for the piece, but those pawns are separated, and rather weak than strong.} *

