1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nxe5 $6 {The Halloween Gambit, clearly a dubious opening variation. Black made no weakening move for such a large sacrifice to work, but if we are too eager to keep all the material advantage, we can find ourselves in trouble, especially in shorter time controls.} Nxe5 5. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rd4e5,Re4e5] White wants to gain a lot of tempi and control the centre, but yeah, a piece for only a pawn is too much.} Ng6 $1 {[%cal Ye5c6,Rd4d5] So this knight can't be chased again.} 6. e5 {White has managed to occupy the centre and force our knights to passive squares, but what is next?} Ng8 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Yg6,Yg8]} 7. Bc4 {[%cal Rc4f7] They are attacking the [f7]-pawn, maybe with [Qf3] to follow, so we have to prepare against that.} c6 {[%cal Yd7d5] Preparing to push ...[d5].} 8. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3f7,Rc4f7]} d5 $1 {This is how we wanted to protect [f7].} 9. exd6 Nf6 {[%csl Rd6,Gf6] Our knight is excellent now, but more importantly, we managed to break White's centre.} 10. Qe2+ Kd7 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gd7c7] Not a problem at all, after taking on [d6], the king will be perfectly safe on [c7].} 11. d5 {White is trying to open the position to attack our king.} (11. Bg5 Bxd6 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Qf3 Kc7 {-+ With a winning position for Black.}) 11... Bxd6 12. dxc6+ bxc6 13. Be3 Kc7 14. O-O-O {[%cal Rd1d8]} Qe7 $17 {[%cal Gh8d8] We will play ...[Rd8] next, and even though our king is not super-safe, White definitely doesn't have enough for the piece.} *

