1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Bxf7+ $2 {[%csl Gd7,Ge5] A very bad move, White is giving the full centre to Black in hopes of making Black's king weaker.} Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] White is already in the verge of losing.} 7. Neg5+ ({•} 7. Ng3 e4 8. Ng1 h5 $5 {A nice idea.} 9. Nxh5 Qh4 10. Ng3 Bg4 11. N1e2 Nd4 12. h3 Re8 {-+ White is completely pinned!}) ({•} 7. Nfg5+ $2 Ke8 $1 {The knights are hanging and falling.} 8. Qf3 Qe7 {-+}) ({•} 7. Nc3 e4 $1 {Now it is Black who is playing Halloween gambit, but with equal material. 🙂} 8. Ng1 Bf5 9. Nge2 d4 10. Ng3 dxc3 11. Nxf5 Qf6 {-+ With the knight hanging and ...[cxb2] being a threat, White is losing the game.}) 7... Kg8 {[%csl Rf3,Rg5,Gg8][%cal Rh7h6,Re5e4] Our king is very safe, and White's knights are horrible.} 8. d4 (8. d3 h6 9. Nh3 Bg4 {-+ With ...[Qf6], ...[Rd8] and ...[Bd6] to follow, Black has a winning advantage.}) 8... h6 9. Nh3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Yf3,Rh3][%cal Rg4d1]} ({Even better than the lines after} 9... e4 10. Ne5 {.}) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nf4 c6 $19 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gd8f6,Gf8d6,Ga8f8] White is about to lose material in the next moves.} *

