1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. O-O {White is sacrificing a pawn for quick development.} Nxc3 6. dxc3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rf3g5,Rg5f7] White has threats with [Ng5] now.} h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5]} ({With this move Black is trying to keep the material advantage and play for an advantage. If you feel it is unnecessary to learn these lines, or you feel it is risky, then just play} 6... Be7 {, when the game is completely equal after} 7. Qd5 O-O 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qxe5 Bf6 {.}) 7. Re1 {[%cal Rf3e5]} d6 8. Nd4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1f3] White is trying to create some play with [f4], but really the most they can hope for is equality.} Bd7 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd7c6] Protecting on [c6], since as you can see in the 8...[Be7] line, White can regain the material there.} (8... Be7 9. Qf3 $1 {Attacking [c6] and [f7].} O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bb5 Bd7 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Qxc6 Qc8) 9. f4 (9. Qf3 {This is nothing now, since c6 is protected.} Qf6 {∓}) 9... Qh4 $1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Rh4e1] By attacking the rook on [e1], White's queen is not so mobile.} 10. Bb5 Nxd4 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. cxd4 exd4 $15 {[%csl Gd4,Gd6,Rd7] White doesn't have enough for the 2 pawns, but we still have to put our king to safety.} *

