1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. O-O {White is sacrificing a pawn for quick development.} Nxc3 6. dxc3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rf3g5,Rg5f7] White has threats with [Ng5] now.} h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5]} ({With this move Black is trying to keep the material advantage and play for an advantage. If you feel it is unnecessary to learn these lines, or you feel it is risky, then just play} 6... Be7 {, when the game is completely equal after} 7. Qd5 O-O 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qxe5 Bf6 {.}) 7. Qd5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rd5f7,Rf3e5,Yd7d6,Yc4b5] This is the good move for White, not only targeting [f7] and [e5], but once we play ...[d6], they can also play [Bb5] and attack [c6].} (7. Nxe5 $2 Nxe5 8. Re1 Qe7 $1 {We can win a lot of material for the queen.} 9. f4 Nxc4 {(9...Qc5+? 10.Qd4!)} 10. Rxe7+ Bxe7 11. Qd4 d5 $1 12. Qxg7 Rf8 {-+ We will quickly go for ...[O-O-O] and have too much material for the queen.}) 7... Qf6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf7][%cal Gf6e5,Gf6f7]} 8. Re1 d6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf7][%cal Gd6e5] Everything looks very safe on [e5] and [f7], so White's only counterplay is against the [c6]-knight.} 9. Bb5 {[%cal Rb5c6]} Bd7 10. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gb5c6] Increasing the pressure on [c6].} Nd8 $1 {[%cal Rc7c6] it is not a big deal for the king to go to [d7], since it is well protected by the pawns.} 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nf3 {[%cal Rf3e5]} ({•} 12. Ne2 {Maybe [f4] is the plan.} g5 $1 {⩱}) ({•} 12. Nb3 c6 13. Qa5 Ne6 {∓}) 12... c6 13. Qb3 Kc7 $17 {[%csl Gc6,Gd6,Ge5][%cal Gd8e6,Gf8e7] ...[Ne6] and ...[Be7] are the next moves, it is not easy for White to find any counterplay.} *

