1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bb5 $2 dxe4 7. Nxe5 {[%cal Re5c6,Rb5c6] Doesn't look too bad, but it is already losing for White. 🙂} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5,Re5b5] Everything is hanging.} 8. d4 (8. Nxc6 Qxb5 9. Nd4 Qg5 {Black already has the pair of bishops, and White still has no good way to protect on [g2].} 10. g3 Bg4 11. f3 exf3 12. Nxf3 Qe7+ 13. Kf2 O-O-O {-+}) 8... Qxg2 9. Rf1 Bd6 $1 {Even better than the immediate ...[a6], which is also very good.} 10. Nxc6 a6 11. Ba4 Bd7 $19 {[%cal Rb7c6] Taking back the piece and keeping the extra pawn.} *

