1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {Now it is not only the centre, but Black also have the pair of bishops.} 7. Nc3 {(7.d3 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.Qe2 O-O-O ∓ )} Qa5 8. O-O Bg4 {∓}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge5] The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] chapter, when with Black we had positions like this, and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} 8. d4 {White wants to play it safe, and trade the [e5]-pawn which could give Black a long-term advantage.} exd4 ({Instead} 8... Nxd4 {is obviously fine, but Black can try to play for more here.}) 9. Nxd4 $2 O-O $1 {[%csl Re1,Gg8] Having a one-move advantage in a symmetrical position can mean a lot!} 10. Nxc6 ({•} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O Qf6 {∓ Our bishop pair gives us advantage in this completely open position.}) ({•} 10. O-O $4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxh2+ {+ -+}) 10... Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rh4e4] This is the point, White has big troubles with castling.} 11. Qe2 (11. Bf3 Re8+ {And White has to move the king.} 12. Kf1 {(12.Be3?? Rxe3 + -+)} bxc6 13. Be3 Rb8 {∓}) 11... Re8 $1 {[%cal Re8e4,Yh4e4] Bringing the rook with a huge threat.} 12. Bxh7+ Kf8 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gf8e8]} 13. Be3 bxc6 14. Bd3 Bg4 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Rh4h2,Rd6h2] And White's king is stuck in the centre.} *

