1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {Now it is not only the centre, but Black also have the pair of bishops.} 7. Nc3 {(7.d3 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.Qe2 O-O-O ∓ )} Qa5 8. O-O Bg4 {∓}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge5] The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] chapter, when with Black we had positions like this, and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. c3 $6 {Too slow, Black can already take over the initiative.} f5 $1 10. Bd5+ (10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 e4 12. Ne5 Qe8 {⩱ With ideas of undermining White's centre with ...[c5], and if needed twice!}) 10... Kh8 11. d3 Qf6 12. Ng5 {[%cal Rd1h5]} (12. Re1 h6 {⩱ Black easily keeps the space advantage, and prepares to make moves like ...[Ne7]-[Ng6].}) 12... Qg6 $1 {No [Qh5] for White!} 13. f4 {White is at least somewhat challenging our centre.} (13. Qb3 $2 Nd8 {∓ All threats are taken care of, and we will push back White with ... [c6] and ...[f4]/...[h6].}) 13... Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8e8] Black has at least a slight advantage with better pieces and more space.} *

