1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {Now it is not only the centre, but Black also have the pair of bishops.} 7. Nc3 {(7.d3 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.Qe2 O-O-O ∓ )} Qa5 8. O-O Bg4 {∓}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge5] The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] chapter, when with Black we had positions like this, and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 {[%cal Ye4c6,Yf7f5,Rf3e5,Re1e5] White is preventing ... [f5], by putting additional pressure to the [e5]-pawn.} (9. d3 $6 {White is not challenging our superiority in the centre.} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {⩱ Black is slightly better, and White has already count on ...[f5]-ideas.}) 9... Bg4 {[%csl Rd1,Yf3][%cal Yg4d1,Yf7f5] By pinning the knight ...[f5] is again very much a threat for White.} 10. h3 $6 {What we have tried with Black, breaking such pins with ...[h6] and ...[g5] is what White is doing now.} Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxe5 {[%csl Ya1,Yc1,Gf8,Rg4,Rh3][%cal Yf7f5] White has won the pawn, but in return their kingside is seriously weakened, and they are also very much behind in development.} Qh4 {[%cal Rh4h3]} 14. Qf3 f5 {[%csl Gd6,Gf8,Gh4][%cal Rf5g4,Ga8e8] Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.} *

