1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {Now it is not only the centre, but Black also have the pair of bishops.} 7. Nc3 {(7.d3 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.Qe2 O-O-O ∓ )} Qa5 8. O-O Bg4 {∓}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge5] The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] chapter, when with Black we had positions like this, and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 {[%cal Ye4c6,Yf7f5,Rf3e5,Re1e5] White is preventing ... [f5], by putting additional pressure to the [e5]-pawn.} (9. d3 $6 {White is not challenging our superiority in the centre.} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {⩱ Black is slightly better, and White has already count on ...[f5]-ideas.}) 9... Bg4 {[%csl Rd1,Yf3][%cal Yg4d1,Yf7f5] By pinning the knight ...[f5] is again very much a threat for White.} 10. c3 {[%cal Yf7f5,Rd1b3,Rb3g8] White is preventing ...[f5], aiming to meet it with a [Qb3]+ after taking on [c6], when they can take the pawn on [e5], but without weakening the kingside.} Kh8 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Yf7f5,Re5e4,Rb3g8] Stepping out of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Which means [Qb3] won't come with check anymore.} 11. Qa4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Re4c6,Ya4g4] Getting out of the pin and attacking on [c6], while also putting an X-ray on the [g4]-bishop!} f5 $1 {Of course, sacrificing on [c6] wouldn't be an issue at all, since we could play ...[e4] right away with a huge attack, but White wants to take on [e5]!} 12. Bxc6 {[%csl Re5]} e4 $1 {Easy to miss this move as White!} 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. d3 {[%csl Ga1,Gc1][%cal Rd3e4,Gb7f3] White is trying to involve new pieces into the defence, and in case of ...[exf3], they can still take back with the bishop on [f3].} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gh4][%cal Ra4h4] Because of the [e4]-pawn the 4th rank remains closed, and our queen can join the attack.} 15. gxf3 Qh4 {[%cal Rh4h2]} 16. f4 Bc5 $3 {[%csl Rf2]} (16... Rxb7 {is also better for Black, but not enough to win.}) 17. d4 (17. Be3 Qg4+ 18. Kf1 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 Rf6 {-+ (19.Ke2 Bxe3 20.fxe3 Rxb7 -+)}) 17... Bd6 $19 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Rb8b7,Rg7g5] Black managed to keep the centre closed, and now ...[g5] is a huge threat, with the computer already indicating that the attack is winning.} *

