1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bc4 $6 {The Italian Four Knights, played in thousands and thousands of games, but it is simply a dubious move, allowing Black to equalise on the spot.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yc3e4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4,Rd5e4] After this move it is rather White who has to be objectively careful to maintain the balance. White is losing their central pawn, while Black is keeping [e5].} 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd5c4,Rd5e4] Taking back the material while having an extra pawn in the centre.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 {Now it is not only the centre, but Black also have the pair of bishops.} 7. Nc3 {(7.d3 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.Qe2 O-O-O ∓ )} Qa5 8. O-O Bg4 {∓}) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge5] The position is similar to the Scotch Four Knights 4. [d4] chapter, when with Black we had positions like this, and wanted to attack White's [e4]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 {[%cal Ye4c6,Yf7f5,Rf3e5,Re1e5] White is preventing ... [f5], by putting additional pressure to the [e5]-pawn.} (9. d3 $6 {White is not challenging our superiority in the centre.} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {⩱ Black is slightly better, and White has already count on ...[f5]-ideas.}) 9... Bg4 {[%csl Rd1,Yf3][%cal Yg4d1,Yf7f5] By pinning the knight ...[f5] is again very much a threat for White.} 10. c3 {[%cal Yf7f5,Rd1b3,Rb3g8] White is preventing ...[f5], aiming to meet it with a [Qb3]+ after taking on [c6], when they can take the pawn on [e5], but without weakening the kingside.} Kh8 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Yf7f5,Re5e4,Rb3g8] Stepping out of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Which means [Qb3] won't come with check anymore.} 11. h3 (11. Qb3 $2 {This is just bad now, because after} Na5 $1 {-+ Black's next move is ...[f5] with a huge attack.}) 11... Bh5 {[%cal Yh5d1,Rf7f5] We are keeping the pin and have no interest in giving up the strong bishop.} 12. Qc2 {[%cal Yc2f5,Re4c6,Gf3e5] Controlling the [f5]-square and [Bxc6] followed by [Nxe5] also becomes an idea.} f5 $1 {Apparently the control on [f5] was not enough. 🙂} 13. Bxc6 (13. Bxf5 $2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qg5+ 15. Bg4 Qh4 {∓ For only one pawn, Black has a huge attack, with immediate threats like ...[h5].}) 13... e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5] Just like this! We can't give up our pawn on [e5].} 14. Bxb7 (14. Nd4 $2 bxc6 15. Ne6 {White is winning an exchange, but Black will have 4 pieces to attack White's king.} Qf6 16. Nxf8 Rxf8 {-+ The game is decided, let's see a possible continuation.} 17. d3 Bf3 $1 18. gxf3 {(18.g3 f4 -+)} Qg6+ 19. Kh1 exf3 20. Rg1 Qh5 21. Rg3 Re8 {-+}) 14... Bxf3 (14... exf3 15. Qd1 $1 {Seems to hold for White.}) 15. d4 (15. gxf3 Qh4 {-+ With ...[Qxh3] and ...[Rf6] coming, Black's attack is too dangerous.}) 15... exd3 16. Qb3 (16. Qxd3 $4 Bxb7 $1 {-+}) 16... Be2 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 {[%csl Ga8,Gd3,Gd6,Ge2,Rg1][%cal Yf5f3] Black's plan is to continue putting pressure on White by pushing the f-pawn forward.} *

