1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nd5 {An odd move, but not a bad one at all. In the worst case for White, the game can transpose to the Belgrade Gambit, which is a playable opening.} Nxe4 {This seems like the easiest line for Black. As I said, 4. [Nd5] is fine, so the task is to look for something reliable and not so chaotic.} ({•} 4... Bc5 {Obviously a good move, but White has two moves that can lead to a quite messy game.} 5. Bc4 $5 {or 5.c3 Nxe4 6.d4 ∞ With some unclear lines.}) ({•} 4... Nxd5 {Of course, this move should be enough for equality, but Black is struggling a bit to get it and this is not necessary after 4. [Nd5].} 5. exd5 Nd4 6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Qg4 {White may have a small pressure if Black is not precise.}) 5. d4 {This is White's main try for the advantage.} d6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] Not transposing into a line of the Belgrade Gambit!} (5... exd4 {It is a line of the Belgrade Gambit, which is not part of the repertoire. 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nd5 and here instead of 5...Nxe4 , we recommend 5...Be7!}) 6. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Yb5e8,Rd4e5] The only challenging move from White, putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} ({•} 6. dxe5 $2 dxe5 {-+ A healthy extra pawn for Black.}) ({•} 6. Bd3 $2 Nf6 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 {∓ Black's centre is very solid, and it is also possible to castle long.}) ({•} 6. Bc4 Be7 {This position was reached in the game J.Van Foreest-Deac, chess.com 2022. After some natural moves White managed to win back the pawn and equalised.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nf6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxe5 13. Rxe5 Bf6 {This all was played in the game and this is just a completely equal endgame.}) 6... a6 $1 {[%cal Yb5c6,Yb7c6,Rc6d5] Exploiting the fact that [Bxc6] is not really a move because of the [d5]-knight's unusual placement; ...[bxc6] would be tempo for Black.} 7. Ba4 b5 $1 {Breaking the pin, so the [e5]-square is stable.} 8. Bb3 Na5 {[%cal Ra5b3,Yc7c6,Rc6d5] Black had different options here, but this looks quite okay, not only threatening to take the bishop, but ...[c6] is a move as well.} 9. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Re2e4] White has to keep on attacking.} (9. O-O {This is too slow.} c6 10. Ne3 Be7 11. dxe5 O-O {⩱ Black will get the pair of bishops after ...[Nxb3] and can hope for a slight advantage in the open position.}) 9... f5 $1 {Since Black can take on [b3] anytime, this is not really a weakening move. The alternative is 9...[c6], but Black has to know more there to be fine.} 10. O-O (10. dxe5 $2 Nxb3 11. axb3 dxe5 12. Nc3 {White will win back the pawn, but Black has the pair of bishops.} Bb7 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Nxe5 Qf6 {⩱ Only Black can be better here with the bishop pair.}) 10... c6 {Kicking back White's knight.} 11. Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c6,Gb4d3] Putting the knight on this strange square is White's only good move. The knight keeps pressure on [c6] and also can return to [d3].} ({•} 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 e4 {∓ Black is much better with the extra pawn and the centre is closed.}) ({•} 11. Ne3 Qf6 {∓ Black is comfortably protecting [e5].}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Yb7c6,Gc6c5,Gb7e4] Covering the pawn on [c6], which can go to [c5] soon!} 12. Nd2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd4e5,Ye2e5,Rd2e4] Challenging the [e4]-knight, so White can have access to the e-pawn.} ({•} 12. dxe5 c5 {∓ White's minor pieces are in trouble.}) ({•} 12. Nd3 Nxb3 13. axb3 Be7 14. dxe5 O-O {∞ White has won back the pawn, but Black is comfortable with the pair of bishops.}) 12... Qe7 {Pretty much stopping the immediate [Nxe4].} 13. dxe5 (13. Nxe4 $2 fxe4 14. Qxe4 Nxb3 $1 15. axb3 d5 {-+ Winning a piece.}) 13... d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Gf5e4,Re7b4] Stabilising on [e4] and attacking on [b4].} 14. c3 g6 $132 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf8g7,Ge8c8,Yc6c5] With a complicated position where Black's chances look quite good.} *

