, not only threatening to take the bishop, but ...[c6] is a move as well.} 9. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Re2e4] White has to keep on attacking.} (9. O-O {This is too slow.} c6 10. Ne3 Be7 11. dxe5 O-O {⩱ Black will get the pair of bishops after ...[Nxb3] and can hope for a slight advantage in the open position.}) 9... f5 $1 {Since Black can take on [b3] anytime, this is not really a weakening move. The alternative is 9...[c6], but Black has to know more there to be fine.} 10. O-O (10. dxe5 $2 Nxb3 11. axb3 dxe5 12. Nc3 {White will win back the pawn, but Black has the pair of bishops.} Bb7 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Nxe5 Qf6 {⩱ Only Black can be better here with the bishop pair.}) 10... c6 {Kicking back White's knight.} 11. Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c6,Gb4d3] Putting the knight on this strange square is White's only good move. The knight keeps pressure on [c6] and also can return to [d3].} ({•} 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 e4 {∓ Black is much better with the extra pawn and the centre is closed.}) ({•} 11. Ne3 Qf6 {∓ Black is comfortably protecting [e5].}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Yb7c6,Gc6c5,Gb7e4] Covering the pawn on [c6], which can go to [c5] soon!} 12. Be6 $1 {[%cal Re6f5] Very difficult to play like this, but objectively this is the good line for White.} ({•} 12. dxe5 c5 {∓ White's minor pieces are in trouble.}) ({•} 12. Nd3 Nxb3 13. axb3 Be7 14. dxe5 O-O {∞ White has won back the pawn, but Black is comfortable with the pair of bishops.}) 12... Qf6 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Rf6e6,Yf6f5]} 13. d5 $1 Nc5 {[%cal Rc5e6] Attacking the [e6]-bishop, but White has a way to make the draw here.} (13... cxd5 $4 14. Nxd5 {+- Black is losing.}) 14. dxc6 ({•} 14. Bg5 Qg6 {∓ White has nothing.}) ({•} 14. Ng5 f4 $1 {Attacking the knight on [g5].} 15. Bf7+ Kd8 {⩱ White's pieces are all over the place and Black is still up a pawn.}) 14... Nxc6 15. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Rf6e6,Rd5c7] The queen can't take on [e6], because of [Nc7]+.} Qg6 16. Nf4 $1 {A weird repetition. 🙂} (16. Nc7+ $2 Kd8 17. Nxa8 Nd4 {-+ White is getting mated or just losing a lot of pieces.}) 16... Qf6 17. Nd5 Qg6 $10 {With equality and draw was agreed a couple of moves later in Denisov-Moreira, corr. 2022.} *

