1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. h3 {A tricky little move, basically White is giving us the honors of 'playing White'. 🙂 However, if we take the White side of the Scotch Four Knights, the [h3] move can be pretty useful for Black.} Bb4 {This is very comfortably equalising for Black. While White did waste a move for a trick, we just continue the development.} 5. Nd5 {Leads to a very equal position.} Nxd5 6. exd5 e4 $1 {[%cal Re4f3]} 7. dxc6 (7. Qe2 $2 O-O $1 {⩱}) 7... exf3 {And if White gets ambitious, they can only end up much worse.} 8. cxd7+ Bxd7 9. Qxf3 {White has won a pawn, but will have a very tough time to finish development.} O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Re8e1]} 10. Be2 Re8 11. O-O {White only needs one move to consolidate, but they are just not in time.} Bc6 $1 {[%cal Gf3e2] White's queen has to guard the bishop, but it can only be done by blocking the [c1]-bishop.} 12. Qd3 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Rd2d3]} ({•} 12. Qg4 $2 Re4 13. Qf3 Qe7 {-+}) ({•} 12. Qb3 $2 Rxe2 13. Qxb4 Qd5 14. f3 Rae8 {-+ And it is not so easy to move as White.}) 12... Qf6 {[%csl Yc1][%cal Ga8d8,Rb2b3,Rf6a1] ...[Rad8] is coming and [b3] is not possible for White.} 13. Bf3 Rad8 14. Qb3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Bxd2 $17 {[%csl Gd2,Gd8,Ge8,Rf2,Rf3,Rh3] Black is clearly better in this endgame, White will have to struggle a lot for the draw.} *

