1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. h3 {A tricky little move, basically White is giving us the honors of 'playing White'. 🙂 However, if we take the White side of the Scotch Four Knights, the [h3] move can be pretty useful for Black.} d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O {Basically we are playing the white side of the Scotch Four Knights, but with an extra move for Black that is [h3], and it is quite useful. I have found that in a couple of lines, Black has to be quite accurate to equalise.} 9. Re1 Qf6 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 h6 12. Rb1 {The computer evaluates it as equal, but it seems unnecessary to enter these kinds of positions.} *

