1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. h3 {A tricky little move, basically White is giving us the honors of 'playing White'. 🙂 However, if we take the White side of the Scotch Four Knights, the [h3] move can be pretty useful for Black.} Bb4 {This is very comfortably equalising for Black. While White did waste a move for a trick, we just continue the development.} 5. a3 {White continues playing provocatively, but if we want, we can just equalise straight away.} Bxc3 6. dxc3 Nxe4 ({This just forces more trades.} 6... d6 $5 {leads to a more complex game, so if you are in a must-win situation, this is the way to go.}) 7. Nxe5 Qe7 $5 ({The games are normally continuing with} 7... Nxe5 8. Qd5 {, but we can be a little bit tricky, and force White to work for the draw.}) 8. Nxc6 {[%cal Rc6e7] Our queen is attacked, so we don't have time for discovered checks.} dxc6 9. Be2 (9. Be3 Ng3 10. fxg3 Qxe3+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Be6 {We can claim a slightly better structure, but of course it is not enough for anything serious.}) 9... Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ra8d8,Rd8d1] And White may be slightly worse here! ...[Rd8] is a big threat.} 10. Qd3 ({•} 10. hxg4 $2 Rd8 {-+} 11. Bd2 (11. Bd3 Nxc3+ {-+ Black wins the queen.}) 11... Rxd2 12. Qc1 Qc5 {White can't castle, because then the [e2]-bishop is unprotected.} 13. Rf1 O-O {-+ ...[Re8] is next and White can't really move. ( • 10.O-O?? Would be a huge mistake. 10...Nxc3 -+ 11.bxc3 Bxe2 -+ Winning the exchange. )}) 10... Rd8 11. Qe3 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Rd6 $10 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd6e6,Ge8g8] The position still should be around equal, but we can definitely fight for more.} *

