1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. h3 {A tricky little move, basically White is giving us the honors of 'playing White'. 🙂 However, if we take the White side of the Scotch Four Knights, the [h3] move can be pretty useful for Black.} Bb4 {This is very comfortably equalising for Black. While White did waste a move for a trick, we just continue the development.} 5. Bd3 {A page from our course! 🙂} O-O 6. O-O Bxc3 {It is not a must to take, but since it is very unlikely to reach this position often, I just want to provide an easy way to play.} 7. dxc3 (7. bxc3 d5 $1 8. exd5 Qxd5 9. c4 Qd6 10. Re1 Re8 {⇆ With a double-edged fight ahead, I quite like Black's chances, with threats like ...[e4].}) 7... d6 {Of course, it was also possible to start with 7...[h6], but since [Bg5] is actually good for us, we can allow it.} 8. Bg5 (8. a4 a5 9. b3 Nd7 {∞ With ...[b6] and ...[Nc5] to follow, Black doesn't have problems.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g8] We can break the pin with the help of ...[Rg8], and then White's bishop is going to be very passive.} 10. Qd2 Rg8 $15 {[%cal Rg7g5,Yf6h5,Yd8f6] ...[g5] is next, and then maybe ...[Nh5], ...[Qf6].} *

