1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Be2 (4. Be2 {Similarly, like in the case of 4.h3, the main thing is not to play} Bc5 {in this position and allow} 5. Nxe5 $1 {On the other hand, [Be2] is not as useful as [h3].}) 4... d5 5. Bb5 {I guess playing the Scotch Four Knights as White is not something you've expected when you purchased a complete repertoire for Black! 🙂 This is what is happening here thanks to White losing a tempo with their bishop.} Nxe4 6. Nxe5 {Not quite working for White.} Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g2,Rg5e5]} 7. Nxc6 Qxg2 8. Rf1 (8. Ne5+ {Goes towards a worse endgame.} c6 9. Qf3 Qxf3 10. Nxf3 Nxc3 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. dxc3 f6 {∓ The bishops are clearly very strong here, as a pawn race is expected on both sides of the board.}) 8... a6 $1 {A thematic tactical idea. The point is that once the bishop goes to [a4], the knight is pinned by ...[Bd7] and can't jump from [c6].} 9. Ba4 (9. Nxd5 axb5 10. Nxc7+ Kd7 11. Nxa8 Kxc6 {-+ With ...[Bc5] and [Re8] to follow, White is in big danger.}) 9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qe4+ $1 {[%cal Re4a4,Re4e1] Going for a better endgame before playing ...[Bd7].} 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd7 $17 {[%csl Gf7,Gg7,Gh7] Black has a clear advantage, since the pawns on the kingside can be easily pushed, and also the [a4]-bishop is quite out of the game.} *

