1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Be2 (4. Be2 {Similarly, like in the case of 4.h3, the main thing is not to play} Bc5 {in this position and allow} 5. Nxe5 $1 {On the other hand, [Be2] is not as useful as [h3].}) 4... d5 5. Bb5 {I guess playing the Scotch Four Knights as White is not something you've expected when you purchased a complete repertoire for Black! 🙂 This is what is happening here thanks to White losing a tempo with their bishop.} Nxe4 6. Qe2 ({•} 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Nxe5 Qg5 $1 {transposes to the 4. [Bc4] [Nxe4] line.}) ({•} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Qe2 {White gets the pawn back and can play for equality. 🙂} Nxc3 8. Qxe5+ Qe7 {Black should be slightly better with the bishop pair.}) 6... Qd6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Ge5][%cal Gd6c6,Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Ye8c8] Covering the key squares in our position.} 7. Nxe4 ({•} 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. Nxe5 Qe6 {⩱ With some advantage because of the pair of bishops.}) ({•} 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Bc4 Qd6 9. Qxe4 Be6 {⩱ We will castle long and have the better chances because of more space in the centre.}) 7... dxe4 8. Qxe4 Bd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8c8] Preparing to castle long.} 9. O-O ({•} 9. d4 $4 {Drops the bishop.} Qb4+ {+ -+}) ({•} 9. Bxc6 $2 {A horrible trade for White, giving up the pair of bishops and making the position more open.} Bxc6 10. Qxe5+ Qxe5+ 11. Nxe5 Bxg2 12. Rg1 Bd5 {∓}) 9... O-O-O 10. Bxc6 {White has to try this, otherwise Black is simply better because of the [e5]-pawn.} (10. d3 f6 {∓ ...[Kb8] and then we can start attacking on the kingside by pushing the 'g' and h-pawns.}) 10... Bxc6 11. Qf5+ (11. Qxe5 Qg6 $1 {Targeting [f3] and [c2].} 12. Qg3 {(12.Qc3 Rd5 -+ With ...[Bd6] and ...[Rh5] to follow, Black's attack is very strong. )} Bd6 $1 {Even better than 12...[Qxc2].} 13. Qxg6 hxg6 {-+ Taking on [f3] and then on [h2] is winning for Black.}) 11... Rd7 $1 {Very important! It looks strange to self-pin, but it is a key that after [Nxe5], [Nxc6] will not come with a check.} (11... Kb8 $2 12. Nxe5 $1 {And the bishop can be taken by a check on [c6]!}) 12. Nxe5 $4 (12. Qxe5 Qg6 $1) 12... Qd5 $19 {[%cal Rd5g2,Rf7f6,Ye5c6]} (12... Qd5 {Since Nxc6 is not a check, White is losing material. For instance,} 13. f3 f6 {-+}) *

