1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Be2 (4. Be2 {Similarly, like in the case of 4.h3, the main thing is not to play} Bc5 {in this position and allow} 5. Nxe5 $1 {On the other hand, [Be2] is not as useful as [h3].}) 4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nxc3 7. bxc3 (7. dxc3 $6 {Gives the better structure for Black, for no reason.} Qxd1 8. Rxd1 f6 {⩱}) 7... e4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gd2d4] Just before White could have played [d4], we are sending the [f3]-knight away.} 8. Nd4 $6 {White can hope for some compensation for the pawn here, but definitely nothing more.} Nxd4 9. cxd4 Qxd4 10. c3 (10. Rb1 Bd6 $1 {Keeps the material advantage for Black, since it would be extremely risky to take on [g7] for White.} 11. Bb2 Qd5 {⩱ And Black is just up a pawn, since} 12. Bxg7 $4 {is losing right away to} Rg8 $1 13. Bc3 Rxg2+ $3 14. Kxg2 Qg5+ 15. Kh1 Qf4 {-+}) 10... Qd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5e4] The queen is well-placed on [e4], keeping the [d5]-pawn protected.} 11. d3 {[%csl Re8] White is trying to open up the position, since our king is still in the centre.} exd3 12. Re1 Be7 13. Bxd3 Be6 $15 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7][%cal Ye8c8,Ye8g8] Black is very solid and still can castle both ways.} *

