1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a3 (4. a3 {Another waiting move, which is called the Gunsberg variation, with the trick of meeting} Bc5 {with} 5. Nxe5 $1 {Luckily for us, it is also preventing 4...[Bb4], so we can't mess up our theory here. 🙂}) 4... d5 {Works well, [a3] is not a big deal for White in the Scotch, especially when it is compared to [h3].} 5. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] White is threatening with [Nxe5], but they have a pawn on [e4] hanging.} Nxe4 $1 (5... Nxe4 {Since as you will see,} 6. Nxe5 {is very dubious, there is no reason from refraining to take this pawn.}) 6. Qe2 Qd6 ({Instead} 6... Nxc3 7. Qxe5+ Qe7 {is just equal, so if you don't want to learn extra theory here, you can just go with that line. With the text move, we are still asking some questions from White.}) 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Bc4 {[%cal Re2e4,Gd5e4] Our queen can't keep the knight protected.} Qd6 9. Qxe4 Be6 10. Bb5 $1 Bd7 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Ge8c8] And with ...[O-O-O] next, Black would be just better, as it is the case in the lines after 4. [Be2], but here thanks to 4. [a3], White has} 11. d4 $1 {And we can't win the bishop with ...[Qb4]+ and actually we are also just transposing to 7. [Nxe4] line.} *

