1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a3 (4. a3 {Another waiting move, which is called the Gunsberg variation, with the trick of meeting} Bc5 {with} 5. Nxe5 $1 {Luckily for us, it is also preventing 4...[Bb4], so we can't mess up our theory here. 🙂}) 4... d5 {Works well, [a3] is not a big deal for White in the Scotch, especially when it is compared to [h3].} 5. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] White is threatening with [Nxe5], but they have a pawn on [e4] hanging.} Nxe4 $1 (5... Nxe4 {Since as you will see,} 6. Nxe5 {is very dubious, there is no reason from refraining to take this pawn.}) 6. Qe2 Qd6 ({Instead} 6... Nxc3 7. Qxe5+ Qe7 {is just equal, so if you don't want to learn extra theory here, you can just go with that line. With the text move, we are still asking some questions from White.}) 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Qxe4 Bd7 9. d4 $1 {[%cal Rd6b4] Since there is no [Qb4]+, White can equalise with this move.} (9. O-O $6 O-O-O 10. d3 {( After 10.Bxc6 Bxc6 , the lines are very similar to what we have already seen with 4. [Be2]. )} f6 {⩱ Even 10...f5 is good, but this looks easier, Black is very stable, and will start pushing the pawns on the kingside very soon.}) 9... O-O-O 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5 $4 {Drops a piece.} Nxe5 {-+}) 10... Nxe5 11. Bxd7+ {All 3 recaptures are fine on [d7].} Rxd7 12. O-O Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Qd5 $10 {[%cal Gf8c5] With symmetry and equality.} *

