1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a4 {This could be called the Kravtsiv Variation, named after the strong Ukrainian GM who played this line more than 50 times mostly in blitz, though.} (4. a4 {At the highest level, Abdusattorov has used this line with great success in shorter time controls. We must repeat that against waiting moves, we do not play} Bc5 $2 {, since it is met with} 5. Nxe5 {. The other criterion is to see how useful the move is in the reversed Scotch lines - well [a4], similarly to [h3], can be quite useful for White, so in these cases we also go by ...[d5].}) 4... Bb4 5. Nd5 {This is basically how the main line of the Spanish Four Knights, 4. [Bb5] [Nd4] goes, and it is completely fine for Black! Funny enough, the extra [a4] is bad for White in our position, since they can't hit our knight with [a3] in many of the lines!} Nxe4 6. Bc4 (6. Qe2 Nf6 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. Qxe5+ Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. Nd4 c5 $1 {⩱ And there is no [a3] for White!}) 6... Nf6 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. Nxe5 d6 $1 {And Black is doing extremely well.} 9. Nf3 ({•} 9. Bxf7+ $4 Kf8 {-+ Winning a piece.}) ({•} 9. c3 dxe5 10. cxb4 Qd6 {⩱ Black is slightly better since White's structure is not great.}) ({•} 9. Nxf7 $4 Qe7+ 10. Kf1 d5 11. Nxh8 dxc4 {-+ The knight will be trapped on [h8].}) 9... Qe7+ 10. Be2 O-O $15 {And White has difficulties to finish development, because of the [c2]-pawn.} (10... O-O {One possible line is} 11. O-O Nxc2 12. Qxc2 Qxe2 13. Re1 Qa6 14. Qxc7 Bg4 15. b4 $1 Rfc8 16. b5 Rxc7 17. bxa6 Bxf3 18. gxf3 bxa6 {⩱ And White is fighting for the draw in this endgame.}) *

