1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a4 {This could be called the Kravtsiv Variation, named after the strong Ukrainian GM who played this line more than 50 times mostly in blitz, though.} (4. a4 {At the highest level, Abdusattorov has used this line with great success in shorter time controls. We must repeat that against waiting moves, we do not play} Bc5 $2 {, since it is met with} 5. Nxe5 {. The other criterion is to see how useful the move is in the reversed Scotch lines - well [a4], similarly to [h3], can be quite useful for White, so in these cases we also go by ...[d5].}) 4... Bb4 5. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gc3d5] This is how White plays this line, for now protecting on [e4] and later going for [Nd5].} O-O 6. Nd5 {Too early to go for this.} Nxd5 7. exd5 e4 $1 {Black is completely fine after this.} 8. Bxe4 Re8 9. O-O Rxe4 10. dxc6 dxc6 $10 {[%csl Gb4,Gc8] If anything, it is rather Black who should be optimistic with the pair of bishops.} *

