1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a4 {This could be called the Kravtsiv Variation, named after the strong Ukrainian GM who played this line more than 50 times mostly in blitz, though.} (4. a4 {At the highest level, Abdusattorov has used this line with great success in shorter time controls. We must repeat that against waiting moves, we do not play} Bc5 $2 {, since it is met with} 5. Nxe5 {. The other criterion is to see how useful the move is in the reversed Scotch lines - well [a4], similarly to [h3], can be quite useful for White, so in these cases we also go by ...[d5].}) 4... Bb4 5. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gc3d5] This is how White plays this line, for now protecting on [e4] and later going for [Nd5].} O-O 6. O-O Bxc3 {The same approach as in the lines after 4.h3.} 7. dxc3 a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ya4a5,Yd7d6,Yf6d7,Yd7c5] Not allowing White to gain space on the queenside by playing [a5]-[b4]. If White did nothing, Black could just go for the plan of ...[d6] and ... [Nd7]-[c5].} 8. Bg5 {[%csl Gg1,Gg8] After both sides castled to the kingside, we should be happy to see this move, since it is easy to break the pin, and then the bishop will be sidelined.} h6 9. Bh4 d6 10. Nd2 g5 $1 11. Bg3 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Yd3,Yg3][%cal Gb7b6,Ge7g6] Black is very solid, and White's bishops are struggling in this structure.} *

