1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Glek variation. Mainly favoured by players who are not looking for some concrete advantage or forced lines from the opening, rather just want to get some playable position.} d5 (4... Bb4 {and 4...Bc5 are also good, but I like to go for ...[d5] against [g3]-setups.}) 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 {So far everything is normal, but here I would like to suggest a move which is only 8th! in popularity, even though of course we can transpose to some other lines and games later. The point is, as I already said in an earlier chapter, taking on [c3] is not something I like to do. It is the main line and the computer's top choice, but opening the b-file while giving White the option of playing [d4] right away, is not something I like.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge5] By not taking on [c3] we want to keep our space advantage in the centre, since it will be not so easy for White to go for [d4], or if they do, it can lead to a very equal game.} 7. O-O (7. d3 {Some players start with this move, but after} Bd6 {White will castle anyway.} 8. O-O O-O {transposes.}) 7... Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Gc6e5] Another rare move, the main line is 7...[Bc5]. While that move is more active, this one is extremely solid, Black is overprotecting on [e5]. The only issue is that this move allows [d4], but in my opinion getting an equal position out of the opening shouldn't be a problem.} 8. d4 O-O $1 {We shouldn't take on [d4] but rather finish the development.} 9. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Rg5d8] White is bringing a new piece, but we can break the pin right away.} (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Bxf4 12. Qxf4 c6 {Looks completely equal, White's bishop just has been neutralised by the [b7]-[c6] chain.}) 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {White needs something immediate to fight for an advantage, but neither I nor, more importantly, the machine can find anything.} 11. Ne4 Qe7 12. Nxd6 {At least creates some imbalance.} ({•} 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. c3 Rd8) ({•} 12. Re1 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Be5) 12... cxd6 13. Re1 Bg4 $132 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gg8h8,Yf7f5] Black has good pieces, and maybe in some day we can be ambitious by playing ...[f5].} *

