1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Glek variation. Mainly favoured by players who are not looking for some concrete advantage or forced lines from the opening, rather just want to get some playable position.} d5 (4... Bb4 {and 4...Bc5 are also good, but I like to go for ...[d5] against [g3]-setups.}) 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 {So far everything is normal, but here I would like to suggest a move which is only 8th! in popularity, even though of course we can transpose to some other lines and games later. The point is, as I already said in an earlier chapter, taking on [c3] is not something I like to do. It is the main line and the computer's top choice, but opening the b-file while giving White the option of playing [d4] right away, is not something I like.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge5] By not taking on [c3] we want to keep our space advantage in the centre, since it will be not so easy for White to go for [d4], or if they do, it can lead to a very equal game.} 7. O-O (7. d3 {Some players start with this move, but after} Bd6 {White will castle anyway.} 8. O-O O-O {transposes.}) 7... Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Gc6e5] Another rare move, the main line is 7...[Bc5]. While that move is more active, this one is extremely solid, Black is overprotecting on [e5]. The only issue is that this move allows [d4], but in my opinion getting an equal position out of the opening shouldn't be a problem.} 8. d3 (8. Re1 O-O 9. d3 h6 {transposes.}) 8... O-O 9. Re1 (9. Bg5 {Doesn't do much, Black can immediately break the pin.} h6 $1 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Ne4 Qd8) 9... h6 {It is just a useful move, we were not afraid of [Bg5], but now for example the bishop can go to [e6] and it can't be attacked by [Ng5].} 10. a3 {This is how Richard Rapport played, with the idea of pushing [b4]-[b5]. It is a matter of taste now if we want to stop that immediately or just later with ...[a6].} Re8 {Maybe I slightly prefer this, expanding with [b4] can make White's position less solid on the queenside.} 11. b4 a6 12. Bb2 Bf5 $10 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8] We will complete our setup with ...[Qd7] and ...[Rad8], and I like our chances with more space in the centre.} *

