1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d4 $6 {[%csl Gd6] A very illogical move, and something the [d6]-bishop is really happy about. White is basically opening up a diagonal and the [e5]-square for our silly bishop.} exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 {White's bishop is doing nothing on [b5], and the [d6]-bishop is just about to get active on [e5].} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Gd6e5,Gd6c5,Ye5c3,Re7e4,Rf6e4]} 8. O-O c6 9. Be2 O-O $13 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8,Gd6e5,Yb7b5,Yb5b4] Black has a great position, we can play ...[Re8], ...[b5]-[b4] and ...[Be5] at some moment, putting huge pressure on White's [e4]-pawn.} *

