1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d4 $6 {[%csl Gd6] A very illogical move, and something the [d6]-bishop is really happy about. White is basically opening up a diagonal and the [e5]-square for our silly bishop.} exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 {White's bishop is doing nothing on [b5], and the [d6]-bishop is just about to get active on [e5].} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Gd6e5,Gd6c5,Ye5c3,Re7e4,Rf6e4]} 8. Bg5 Be5 $1 {We can go for the [e4]-pawn right away.} 9. Qd2 Bxc3 (9... Qb4 $5) 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 $4 {Unfortunately for White, this is not working because of,} Nxe4 $1 11. Bxe7 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Kxe7 {-+ With a winning endgame for Black.}) 10... Qxe4+ ({If you find it risky, you can just play} 10... h6 {and force the trade on [f6].}) (10... Nxe4 $6 {This is not that clear now.} 11. Bxe7 Nxd2 12. Ba3 Ne4 13. O-O-O {∞}) 11. Kf1 {[%cal Ra1e1]} Qe5 {Looks very risky, but seems to work.} (11... O-O {This leads to a draw by force.} 12. Bxf6 Qf5 $1 13. Bxg7 Qxb5+ 14. c4 $1 Qxc4+ 15. Kg1 Kxg7 16. Qg5+ Kh8 17. Qf6+ Kg8) 12. Bd3 (12. Re1 Ne4 {Since the queen is attacking both bishops, White can't take advantage of the pin.} 13. Qd3 O-O {∓ Black is either taking on [g5], or saves the knight on [e4].}) 12... O-O 13. Re1 Qd6 {Black still has to finish development, but it is also tough to find enough play for White.} *

