1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. Bxc6 $6 ({Similarly to} 5. d4 {, this move just helps Black, and makes the bishop on [d6] a completely normal piece by opening up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.}) 5... dxc6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8g4]} 6. d3 {This line is not critical at all, but it can show some dangers White may face in such positions.} h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh6g5,Gc8e6] Covering the [g5]-square is typical when our bishop wants to develop to [e6], it can't be attacked by [Ng5] after this move.} 7. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yc8g4,Gh3g4,Re1g1,Yg7g5,Yg5g4] White is preventing ...[Bg4], but ironically, that move is only unpleasant if White's king is already castled, since then [h3]-[g4] is not available. So we could say that our opponent is preparing to castle, but now it is extremely dangerous for another reason, Black has the ...[g5]-[g4] idea to launch a quick attack.} (7. O-O $6 {Committing to the kingside too early.} Bg4 $1 {And it is tough to break the pin, because the usual,} 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 {is met by} Nxg4 $1 10. hxg4 Bxg4 {∓ And with ...[f5] and then pressure on the f-file coming, White is already much worse.}) 7... Be6 8. Be3 (8. O-O $6 Qe7 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] and ...[g5]-[g4] to follow.}) 8... Qe7 9. Qe2 {[%csl Ge1,Ge8] Both sides are developing normally, but it is more like a waiting game! If White would weaken their queenside, it is very possible that we keep our king in the centre, and start attacking instead!} O-O-O {This kind of situation can occur in several lines. It should not be assumed that the [a7] pawn is always poisoned, especially when the king is on the queenside.} 10. Bxa7 b6 11. d4 $13 {And this position is a big mess. Of course, White does not always have this chance with [d4], but the point is to make sure that ...[O-O-O] is safe.} *

