1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. Bxc6 $6 ({Similarly to} 5. d4 {, this move just helps Black, and makes the bishop on [d6] a completely normal piece by opening up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.}) 5... dxc6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8g4]} 6. d4 {Even a standard reaction, like ...[exd4] or ...[Nd7] is good for Black, but we have even better.} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Rf6e4] By counterattacking on [e4], Black is already fighting for more than equality.} 7. O-O exd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3 {Creating some weak pawns on the queenside.} 9. bxc3 c5 10. Nb3 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 b6 $10 {[%csl Ya2,Yc2,Yc3][%cal Gc8e6,Gf6d7,Ge8c8] The position is still around equal, but it looks much more pleasant for Black, with all those pawn weaknesses on White's queenside.} *

