1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. O-O {The slower and the less dangerous approach from White. We don't have to worry about [Bg5] or any type of kingside attack after this move, so we will have the time to put our bishop on [d6] to a normal square.} O-O 6. d3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rg5d8] White wants to play [Bg5] which is definitely slightly unpleasant for Black.} (6. Re1 {White can also start with this move, but eventually they are going to play [d3] in order to finish development.} Re8 7. d3 h6 {Transposes to the main lines.}) 6... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh6g5,Rc1g5] Preventing [Bg5] altogether! Now White has tried different moves in the practice, which pretty much can all transpose into each other, but if we have to put those into 2 groups, one is to play with [Ne2]-[g3] and then maybe [c3]-[d4], the other one is to bring back the bishop quickly to the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, and prevent Black's ...[d5] or even put the knight on [d5].} 7. Be3 ({A line which is likely to transpose to} 7. a3 Re8 {lines.}) 7... Re8 {[%cal Gd6f8,Yd7d6,Yd6d5,Gc8g4] Our standard regrouping plan, we protect the pawn on [e5], and leave the [f8]-square for the bishop, so then we can move our d-pawn and complete development.} 8. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4,Gc4a2] With the goal of having a retreat square for the bishop on [a2].} Bf8 {[%cal Yd7d6,Yd6d5] White has to watch out for ...[d5] as well, not only the more solid ...[d6]. Therefore in such situations the most common thing from White is to control the [d5]-square one more time.} 9. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2c4,Yc4d5] In OTB practice, Black continued here with ...[d6] most of the time, but allowing [c4] and then capturing with the c-pawn on [d5] looks unnecessary to me.} (9. Bc4 {This is the main move, and it transposes.} d6 10. h3 Be6 {transposes here.}) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne7 {[%cal Re7d5] Obviously if we can trade the [e5]-pawn for the [d5]-one, Black is just fine.} 11. Nxe5 (11. c4 c6 $1 12. Ba4 Nf5 {⩱}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxf7 $2 {We can't take back because of [Qh5], but the knight is actually trapped on [f7]!} ({•} 12. Qh5 $2 g6 $1 {The only move, but gives big advantage for Black.} 13. Nxg6 Nf6 $1 {Gaining a tempo with the loose piece!} 14. Qf5 d5 15. Qf3 fxg6 16. Bxe8 Nxe8 {∓ Black is ahead in material, and the rooks have no entry square on the only open file.}) ({•} 12. d4 c6 {Followed by ...[d6] and an equal position.}) 12... Qf6 $19 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Rf6f7] The knight is lost on [f7].} *

