1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. O-O {The slower and the less dangerous approach from White. We don't have to worry about [Bg5] or any type of kingside attack after this move, so we will have the time to put our bishop on [d6] to a normal square.} O-O 6. d3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rg5d8] White wants to play [Bg5] which is definitely slightly unpleasant for Black.} (6. Re1 {White can also start with this move, but eventually they are going to play [d3] in order to finish development.} Re8 7. d3 h6 {Transposes to the main lines.}) 6... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh6g5,Rc1g5] Preventing [Bg5] altogether! Now White has tried different moves in the practice, which pretty much can all transpose into each other, but if we have to put those into 2 groups, one is to play with [Ne2]-[g3] and then maybe [c3]-[d4], the other one is to bring back the bishop quickly to the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, and prevent Black's ...[d5] or even put the knight on [d5].} 7. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4] White wants to remove the bishop to [c4], but first they had to prepare a square for it to retreat, since Black had ideas with ...[Na5].} Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6f8,Ge8e5] Protecting on [e5] and preparing ...[Bf8].} 8. Bc4 (8. h3 Bf8 {And probably now [Bc4] transposing to the main line. Don't be surprised by any move, it is quite impossible to cover this line move by move, the main thing is to know our setup.}) 8... Bf8 9. h3 {[%cal Yc8g4,Yf6g4] A useful move against ...[Bg4] or ...[Ng4].} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] White made it easy to decide between ...[d6] and ...[d5], since they are strongly controlling the [d5]-square. After ...[d6] we want to develop the bishop to [e6], which will again ask some questions from White.} 10. Nh2 {[%cal Gf2f4] White is saying, that since nothing is happening in the centre no [d4] for White and no ...[d5] for Black they will try another pawn break, with [f4].} Be6 {[%cal Re6c4,Gd6d5] Maybe in some lines taking on [c4] can be unpleasant for White, but Black's main idea is to push ...[d5].} 11. Bxe6 {It is always a tricky question how to take back on [e6], but it is good that neither of the captures can be very bad generally. 🙂 If I would have to come up with a rule of thumb, then I would say, when you have excellent chances to get in ...[d5] very quickly, it looks more promising to take with the rook. On the other hand, when it is White who seems to be faster with playing [d4], or they can get some [Nd5]-[c4] for a while, then it is better to take with the f-pawn.} (11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 {Of course White has to take like this, at least they have the pair of bishops for the worse structure.} Ne7 13. Qf3 Ng6 {White's light-squared bishop is very passive, and Black can also play for ...[c6] and after the trade on [c6], try to go for ...[d5].}) 11... Rxe6 {[%csl Yh2][%cal Gf2f4,Gd6d5] Now, the knight on [h2] is missing from the fight for the centre, and our opponent wants [f4] anyways, and not [d4], so it looks like a good time to take with the rook.} 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] White wants ...[f5] and gain a lot of space on the kingside. Fortunately, we have learned how to meet [f4] in the early chapters, and now can use that knowledge.} (12. Nd5 {White can't stop ...[d5] for long.} Ne7 $1 {Challenging the knight and preparing ... [c6], ...[d5].} 13. Nxf6+ Rxf6 14. f4 exf4 15. Ng4 Re6 16. Bxf4 d5) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 (13. d4 $1 {White has to find this move in order not to be worse, but still, it is a pawn.} Re8 14. Rxf4 g5 $1 15. Rf2 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Rxe4 17. c3 d5 {∞ Our kingside is weakened, but we have a pawn for it.}) 13... d5 $1 {Takes and ...[d5]! As usual! 🙂} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6][%cal Ga8e8]} (15... Qxd5 {Black is already slightly better with excellent pieces, while} 16. Bxc7 $2 {is already close to lost after} Nd4 $1 {-+}) *

