nd prevent Black's ...[d5] or even put the knight on [d5].} 7. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4] White wants to remove the bishop to [c4], but first they had to prepare a square for it to retreat, since Black had ideas with ...[Na5].} Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6f8,Ge8e5] Protecting on [e5] and preparing ...[Bf8].} 8. Bc4 (8. h3 Bf8 {And probably now [Bc4] transposing to the main line. Don't be surprised by any move, it is quite impossible to cover this line move by move, the main thing is to know our setup.}) 8... Bf8 9. h3 {[%cal Yc8g4,Yf6g4] A useful move against ...[Bg4] or ...[Ng4].} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] White made it easy to decide between ...[d6] and ...[d5], since they are strongly controlling the [d5]-square. After ...[d6] we want to develop the bishop to [e6], which will again ask some questions from White.} 10. Be3 Be6 {[%cal Yd3d4,Gd6d5] Both sides are finishing development, now it is about [d4] or ...[d5].} 11. Bxe6 fxe6 $1 {White is ready to push [d4] right away, so we take with the pawn.} 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 (14. Bxd4 $6 e5 $1 15. Be3 c6 {And ...[d5] is coming on the next move, Black has an excellent position.}) 14... c6 $132 {[%cal Yd6d5,Ye6e5] We can play either ...[e5] or ...[d5] in the next move, depending on what White does, and it is just a complicated position with chances for both sides.} *

