1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. O-O {The slower and the less dangerous approach from White. We don't have to worry about [Bg5] or any type of kingside attack after this move, so we will have the time to put our bishop on [d6] to a normal square.} O-O 6. d3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rg5d8] White wants to play [Bg5] which is definitely slightly unpleasant for Black.} (6. Re1 {White can also start with this move, but eventually they are going to play [d3] in order to finish development.} Re8 7. d3 h6 {Transposes to the main lines.}) 6... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh6g5,Rc1g5] Preventing [Bg5] altogether! Now White has tried different moves in the practice, which pretty much can all transpose into each other, but if we have to put those into 2 groups, one is to play with [Ne2]-[g3] and then maybe [c3]-[d4], the other one is to bring back the bishop quickly to the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, and prevent Black's ...[d5] or even put the knight on [d5].} 7. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4] White wants to remove the bishop to [c4], but first they had to prepare a square for it to retreat, since Black had ideas with ...[Na5].} Re8 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6f8,Ge8e5] Protecting on [e5] and preparing ...[Bf8].} 8. Bc4 (8. h3 Bf8 {And probably now [Bc4] transposing to the main line. Don't be surprised by any move, it is quite impossible to cover this line move by move, the main thing is to know our setup.}) 8... Bf8 9. h3 {[%cal Yc8g4,Yf6g4] A useful move against ...[Bg4] or ...[Ng4].} d6 10. Re1 {One of the many such moves White can play. Our main interest is in how to take back on [e6].} Be6 11. Bxe6 (11. Nd5 Nd7 {With ...[Ne7] and ...[c6] coming, we can trade the knight on [d5].}) 11... Rxe6 {When White is ready to play both [Nd5] and [d4], it is best to take with the pawn on [e6].} (11... fxe6 $1 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Nd7 {∞ And we can continue with ...[c6] and ...[d5].}) 12. Nd5 Ne7 13. Nxf6+ Rxf6 14. c4 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4] White stops ...[d5] and prepares to play [d4].} *

