1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. O-O {The slower and the less dangerous approach from White. We don't have to worry about [Bg5] or any type of kingside attack after this move, so we will have the time to put our bishop on [d6] to a normal square.} O-O 6. d3 {[%cal Gc1g5,Rg5d8] White wants to play [Bg5] which is definitely slightly unpleasant for Black.} (6. Re1 {White can also start with this move, but eventually they are going to play [d3] in order to finish development.} Re8 7. d3 h6 {Transposes to the main lines.}) 6... h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh6g5,Rc1g5] Preventing [Bg5] altogether! Now White has tried different moves in the practice, which pretty much can all transpose into each other, but if we have to put those into 2 groups, one is to play with [Ne2]-[g3] and then maybe [c3]-[d4], the other one is to bring back the bishop quickly to the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, and prevent Black's ...[d5] or even put the knight on [d5].} 7. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3,Yc2c3,Yd3d4] White is transferring the knight to [g3], and then wants to play in the centre with [c3]-[d4].} (7. Bc4 Na5 $1) 7... Re8 {We are doing the usual, protecting on [e5] and then playing ...[Bf8].} 8. Ng3 Bf8 9. Re1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Yd7d5,Re4d5,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] Prepares well against Black's ... [d5]-break, but Black can get the light-squared bishop in the meantime!} a6 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2][%cal Yb5c4,Yc4a2,Yb5a4,Ya4c2] There are no retreat squares for the bishop.} 10. Bxc6 ({•} 10. Bc4 Na5 $1) ({•} 10. Ba4 b5 11. Bb3 Na5 $1) 10... bxc6 (10... dxc6 {is also completely good, but taking towards the centre is even more ambitious.}) 11. b3 d6 12. Bb2 c5 $10 {[%cal Gf6e6,Ge6f4,Ge6d4,Yf6h7,Yh7f8,Yf8e6] Black is completely fine; our next goal can be to transfer the knight to its ideal square, [e6].} *

