1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. g4 $2 {Yes, some strong players even tried to attack without any target! We should take [g4] very seriously, even when it is bad.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4b5,Rd4f3,Ye5d4] A typical reply to [g4], we are attacking at least for a trade two possible attackers from White, and if White takes on [d4], it can quickly open up the position in our favour.} 7. Bc4 $2 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Re1,Rg4][%cal Gd7d5] Introducing the threat of ... [d5]! and White is already lost here. You can't just play [g4] for fun.} 8. g5 d5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4,Rc8g4] Nice intermediate move!} 9. gxf6 Qxf6 {[%cal Rd5c4,Rf6f3] White can't keep the extra material.} 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. a3 dxc3 {[%cal Rc3b2]} 12. axb4 dxc4 13. bxc3 Bg4 $1 14. Qd2 (14. Qxg4 $4 Qxc3+ {+ -+}) 14... Qf3 15. Rg1 f5 $19 {Opening the centre is deciding the game.} *

