1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 {[%csl Ge5,Yf6][%cal Rg5d8,Gd6e5,Yd6e7] Very logical, White is creating an unpleasant pin, and uses the fact that it is not so easy to break it with ... [Be7], since the [e5]-pawn also needs protection.} h6 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yg5h6] It looks strange that Black is creating a target for the [g4]-[g5] advance, but this whole line lies on a very concrete idea.} 7. Bh4 Be7 $1 {Eventually Black can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. Qe2 $2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh1g1,Rg2g5] With the idea of castling long, and then prepare to go for [g4]-[g5].} Nd4 $1 {Not allowing White to execute their plans.} 9. Nxd4 exd4 {If the knight moves, we can go for ...[d5]!} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd5 Be5 12. f4 c6 $1 {And Black is much better after,} 13. fxe5 cxd5 $17 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Yd8a5] Because White has big problems with the bishop.} *

