 can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. O-O {Change of plans for White, but of course the bishop is not ideally placed on [h4], since it can be traded for our bad bishop quite easily.} d6 9. Bxc6 {The only real try from White. If they would play any other move, Black can already play ...[Nh7] and offer the trade of the bishops.} bxc6 10. d4 $1 {So far we have been following the games, Abdusattorov-Krassowizkij, Germany 2023 and Petkov-Hovhannisyan, Almaty 2022, where both Black players went with 10...[exd4] which leads to an okay, but slightly worse position.} Nh5 $1 {Black agrees to a worse structure for dangerous counterchances on the kingside.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. dxe5 dxe5 $13 {[%cal Gh5f4,Ge7f6,Ga8d8,Gc8g4] With ...[Nf4], ...[Qf6] and ... [Bg4] coming, Black is at least fine in this unclear position.} *

