1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 {[%csl Ge5,Yf6][%cal Rg5d8,Gd6e5,Yd6e7] Very logical, White is creating an unpleasant pin, and uses the fact that it is not so easy to break it with ... [Be7], since the [e5]-pawn also needs protection.} h6 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yg5h6] It looks strange that Black is creating a target for the [g4]-[g5] advance, but this whole line lies on a very concrete idea.} 7. Bh4 Be7 $1 {Eventually Black can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. O-O {Change of plans for White, but of course the bishop is not ideally placed on [h4], since it can be traded for our bad bishop quite easily.} d6 9. h3 {This move was suggested in the book “Squeezing 1.e4 e5 (a Solid Strategic Approach” by Khalifman and Soloviov, although with a different move order 8.h3 d6 9.O-O ) . White prevents ...[Bg4]. It has little relevance to our line.} Nh7 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gh7g5,Yg5f3] Offering the bishops' trade. Later, the knight can go to [g5] and fight for the centre by challenging the [f3]-knight.} 10. Bxe7 ({•} 10. Bxc6 {This exchange doesn't bring anything for White.} Bxh4 11. Ba4 Bf6 {The best White can do is to play [Nd5] and then take the bishop, so 10. Bxc6 is clearly not a success.}) ({•} 10. Bg3 Ng5 {Black is fighting for the [d4]-square with this trade.} 11. Nxg5 Bxg5 12. Bxc6 {Looks like the only try from White to unbalance the position.} bxc6 13. d4 Ba6 14. Re1 exd4 15. Qxd4 Qb8 $1 {∞ A famous plan to bring the queen into play via [b8], and Black should be doing okay with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Nxe7 {Rerouting the knight to [g6], from there it will support the [e5]-pawn and can sometimes jump to [f4]. Quite importantly, this maneuver makes the [b5]-bishop unemployed.} 11. d4 Ng6 $10 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gh7g5] Black will play ... [Ng5] next, and it is hard to see anything wrong with this position.} *

