1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 {[%csl Ge5,Yf6][%cal Rg5d8,Gd6e5,Yd6e7] Very logical, White is creating an unpleasant pin, and uses the fact that it is not so easy to break it with ... [Be7], since the [e5]-pawn also needs protection.} h6 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yg5h6] It looks strange that Black is creating a target for the [g4]-[g5] advance, but this whole line lies on a very concrete idea.} 7. Bh4 Be7 $1 {Eventually Black can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. Bxc6 $1 {Definitely the test for Black, White is going for the [e5]-pawn.} ({•} 8. g4 $2 {Not working at all.} Nxg4 9. Bxe7 (9. Rg1 d6 {-+}) 9... Nxe7 10. h3 Nf6 11. Nxe5 d5 $1 {∓ Black is much better, White's 'attack' didn't work out.}) ({•} 8. Qd2 $2 {is a blunder.} Nxe4 $1 9. dxe4 Bxh4 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe5 Rb8 {⩱ White has managed to win back the pawn, but with the bishops, Black keeps the advantage.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Re7h4] This is the tactical point of ...[Be7].} 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxe4 Bxh4 11. O-O Rb8 {And Black is doing very well with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Qxe7 {[%cal Re7e5]} 11. Nxc6 $1 {[%cal Rc6e7] Everything would be very easy, if not for this intermediate move!} (11. dxe4 Qxe5 12. O-O Rb8 {With ...[d6] and ...[f5] coming, it is White who has to be careful to keep the balance.}) 11... dxc6 12. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Re2e7] White pins the knight and even want to take it with the queen if possible.} (12. Nxe4 $4 f5 {-+}) 12... Bh3 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gf8] Yes, somewhat computerish, but connecting the rooks makes ...[Qb4] a huge threat.} (12... Qb4 {Playable, but not quite enough for equality.} 13. Qxe4 Qxb2 14. Kd2 $1 {⩲ White has the better structure, and the king is actually very safe on [d2].}) 13. gxh3 $2 Qb4 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gf8][%cal Re2e4,Rf8e8] And now the queen can't take the knight, because of the pin on the e-file.} 14. dxe4 {[%cal Yd8d1,Re1d2] Once White takes with the pawn, ...[Qxb2] can't be answered by [Kd2] anymore.} Qxb2 15. O-O Qxc3 $17 {[%csl Rg1] In heavy piece endgames king safety is the most important, well, it is not really a close call at this position.} *

