 can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. Bxc6 $1 {Definitely the test for Black, White is going for the [e5]-pawn.} ({•} 8. g4 $2 {Not working at all.} Nxg4 9. Bxe7 (9. Rg1 d6 {-+}) 9... Nxe7 10. h3 Nf6 11. Nxe5 d5 $1 {∓ Black is much better, White's 'attack' didn't work out.}) ({•} 8. Qd2 $2 {is a blunder.} Nxe4 $1 9. dxe4 Bxh4 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe5 Rb8 {⩱ White has managed to win back the pawn, but with the bishops, Black keeps the advantage.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Re7h4] This is the tactical point of ...[Be7].} 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxe4 Bxh4 11. O-O Rb8 {And Black is doing very well with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Qxe7 {[%cal Re7e5]} 11. Nxc6 $1 {[%cal Rc6e7] Everything would be very easy, if not for this intermediate move!} (11. dxe4 Qxe5 12. O-O Rb8 {With ...[d6] and ...[f5] coming, it is White who has to be careful to keep the balance.}) 11... dxc6 12. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Re2e7] White pins the knight and even want to take it with the queen if possible.} (12. Nxe4 $4 f5 {-+}) 12... Bh3 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gf8] Yes, somewhat computerish, but connecting the rooks makes ...[Qb4] a huge threat.} (12... Qb4 {Playable, but not quite enough for equality.} 13. Qxe4 Qxb2 14. Kd2 $1 {⩲ White has the better structure, and the king is actually very safe on [d2].}) 13. Qxe4 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Rf8e8]} 14. Qf3 {Maybe the most human move in the position.} ({•} 14. O-O $2 {Just a blunder.} Rae8 $1 15. Qc4 Qg6 {∓ And Black is winning the exchange.}) ({•} 14. O-O-O $6 Rae8 15. Qa4 Bxg2 16. Rhg1 Bf3 {⩱ The bishop should be superior to the knight in such position, where a pawn race is likely in the endgame.}) ({•} 14. Kf1 Rfe8 15. Qc4 Bf5 {∞ The king stays in the centre for a while, Black has at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({•} 14. Kd1 Rfe8 15. Qf3 Qxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bg2 17. Re1 Rxe1+ 18. Kxe1 Rb8 {⇆ Not only ...[Rxb2] but ...[Rb4]-[Rh4] is also a possibility.}) 14... Rfe8+ 15. Kd1 Qxf3+ 16. gxf3 Bg2 $132 {[%cal Rg2h1,Rg2f3] Black is taking back the pawn, and definitely shouldn't be worse in this endgame, where the play is going to happen in both sides of the board, and that is something the bishop likes better than the knight.} *

