1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 {[%csl Ge5,Yf6][%cal Rg5d8,Gd6e5,Yd6e7] Very logical, White is creating an unpleasant pin, and uses the fact that it is not so easy to break it with ... [Be7], since the [e5]-pawn also needs protection.} h6 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yg5h6] It looks strange that Black is creating a target for the [g4]-[g5] advance, but this whole line lies on a very concrete idea.} 7. Bh4 Be7 $1 {Eventually Black can leave the [e5]-pawn unprotected! Instead 7...[Nd4] looks fine according to my analyses, but there are some very difficult lines, and also some forced draws are available for White.} 8. Bxc6 $1 {Definitely the test for Black, White is going for the [e5]-pawn.} ({•} 8. g4 $2 {Not working at all.} Nxg4 9. Bxe7 (9. Rg1 d6 {-+}) 9... Nxe7 10. h3 Nf6 11. Nxe5 d5 $1 {∓ Black is much better, White's 'attack' didn't work out.}) ({•} 8. Qd2 $2 {is a blunder.} Nxe4 $1 9. dxe4 Bxh4 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe5 Rb8 {⩱ White has managed to win back the pawn, but with the bishops, Black keeps the advantage.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Re7h4] This is the tactical point of ...[Be7].} 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxe4 Bxh4 11. O-O Rb8 {And Black is doing very well with the pair of bishops.}) 10... Qxe7 {[%cal Re7e5]} 11. Nxc6 $1 {[%cal Rc6e7] Everything would be very easy, if not for this intermediate move!} (11. dxe4 Qxe5 12. O-O Rb8 {With ...[d6] and ...[f5] coming, it is White who has to be careful to keep the balance.}) 11... dxc6 12. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Re2e7] White pins the knight and even want to take it with the queen if possible.} (12. Nxe4 $4 f5 {-+}) 12... Bh3 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gf8] Yes, somewhat computerish, but connecting the rooks makes ...[Qb4] a huge threat.} (12... Qb4 {Playable, but not quite enough for equality.} 13. Qxe4 Qxb2 14. Kd2 $1 {⩲ White has the better structure, and the king is actually very safe on [d2].}) 13. dxe4 Qb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4b2,Rh3g2]} (13... Bxg2 $2 14. Rg1 Bh3 15. Qh5 {+- With both [h3] and [h6] hanging, Black is lost.}) 14. O-O ({•} 14. Qe3 $2 {Was played in the only game which reached this position, Vokhidov-Hovhannisyan, Almaty 2022, but this is just a blunder,} Bxg2 15. Rg1 Bxe4 {∓ And White can't take the bishop because of the pins, and then ...[Bg6] will completely stop White's attack on the g-file.}) ({•} 14. O-O-O $6 Rab8 $1 15. Rd3 Bc8 $1 {⩱ White can't prevent both ...[Ba6] and ...[Qxb2].}) 14... Qxb2 15. Qc4 {[%cal Rc4c6] There are many other queen moves, but maybe this is the most tricky, attacking [c6]. On any other move, we can play ...[Be6] and then bring the rooks to the open files, and even though our structure is worse, the bishop is clearly better than the knight, so overall it is around equal.} Be6 16. Qxc6 {According to the computer everything is equal here, Black is too active, so White can't do much with the extra pawn.} Rfd8 (16... Qxc2 17. Nd5 $1 Qxc6 18. Ne7+ Kh7 19. Nxc6 {⩲ This looks slightly unpleasant for Black, but the computer is not impressed.}) 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qb6 19. Qc4 c6 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8] And the position is completely equal, but of course we still have to defend a little bit if this position ever happens.} *

