1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4,Gc4a2,Yd6b4,Yd7d5] A very useful and somewhat also waiting move from White. They obviously still don't want to castle, and waiting for the moment to play [g4]. By creating a retreat square on [a2], they don't have to worry about ...[a6], ...[b5], ...[Na5] ideas to take the bishop, and also, since their king is in the centre for now, ...[Bb4] followed by ...[d5] could have been a decent idea for Black, which is also stopped.} (6. O-O h6 {transposes here.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd6c7,Yd7d5]} ({Our usual setup, when we are playing ...Re8 and then Bf8 is too passive here, and White can meet} 6... Re8 {with} 7. g4 $1 {. We have to find another way to remove the bishop from [d6], and still keep the [e5]-pawn protected, and ...[Nd4] is an excellent start for that, making ...[c6], ...[Bc7] available.}) 7. O-O {White gives up on the attack, so we can be already pretty satisfied here.} c6 $1 (7... Nxb5 $2 {Would be a big mistake, because after} 8. Nxb5 {± We will either have a bad structure, or lose the [e5]-pawn.}) 8. Bc4 Bc7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black is already threatening to play ...[d5] in the next move.} 9. Ba2 d5 {[%cal Rc8g4] ...[Bg4] is a very serious threat.} 10. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4]} Be6 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] And Black is slightly better with the space advantage. A few possible continuations.} (10... Be6 {•} 11. Bg5 Qd7 {⩱ and we are not afraid of [Bxf6]-[gxf6] at all, since it will be Black who can use the g-file after ...[Kh8] and ...[Rg8].}) (10... Be6 {Or} 11. Ng5 h6 {It is not a problem to give up the pair of bishops, as long as we have more space and the position is closed.} 12. Nxe6 Nxe6 {⩱}) *

