idea for Black, which is also stopped.} (6. O-O h6 {transposes here.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd6c7,Yd7d5]} ({Our usual setup, when we are playing ...Re8 and then Bf8 is too passive here, and White can meet} 6... Re8 {with} 7. g4 $1 {. We have to find another way to remove the bishop from [d6], and still keep the [e5]-pawn protected, and ...[Nd4] is an excellent start for that, making ...[c6], ...[Bc7] available.}) 7. O-O {White gives up on the attack, so we can be already pretty satisfied here.} c6 $1 (7... Nxb5 $2 {Would be a big mistake, because after} 8. Nxb5 {± We will either have a bad structure, or lose the [e5]-pawn.}) 8. Bc4 Bc7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black is already threatening to play ...[d5] in the next move.} 9. Bg5 $2 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Rg5d8] White wants to stop ...[d5] with this move.} ({•} 9. h3 d5 10. Ba2 Be6 {is the same as the 9. [Ba2] line.}) ({•} 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2 d5 {transposes here.}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 Nxf3+ $1 {[%cal Gg7g5] After trading the knights, ...[g5] is a very safe move.} 11. Qxf3 (11. gxf3 g5 12. Bg3 d6 {-+ Black has the better structure, and the bishop on [g3] is like a pawn.}) 11... g5 $1 12. Bg3 d5 $1 {[%csl Rf3] And Black is winning material, because of the unlucky placement of White's queen.} 13. exd5 Bg4 14. Qe3 cxd5 $19 {[%cal Rd5c4,Rd5d4] White can choose how to lose the piece.} *

