1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {The Spanish variation of the Four Knights Game.} Bd6 {[%csl Yc8,Rd6][%cal Gd7d6,Yc8g4]} ({This move seems extremely awkward, and I usually refrain from such moves. In this case, however, I am quite satisfied with this line, which in my opinion is the most fighting and also much less well known than the main theoretical lines. Black's main options are} 4... Nd4 {, which has a lot of forcing lines already analyzed up to the draw, but of course the biggest problem is} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 {which simply leads to a completely equal position - see the games of Top GMs when they settle for the draw. 🙂}) (4... Bb4 {is also extremely reliable, Black is doing well in these lines, but well, the positions can become very even, where it is difficult to show anything new for either side.}) ({Then there is} 4... Bc5 {which is also a decent line, although White has a chance to fight for the advantage. So here we are with our move, which allows no forced lines, but of course the bishop is horrible at [d6]; we must move it again as soon as we can, and then play ...[d6] or ...[d5] to open the other bishop at [c8].}) 5. d3 {The critical test of the 4...[Bd6] line, White delays castling, and very often wants to attack with [g4]! on the kingside, using the fact, that our pieces, especially bishops are struggling at the moment.} (5. a3 {One of White's two main ideas, but it will just transpose to 5. [d3] lines so it will be discussed there in detail.} Nd4 6. Bc4 c6 7. d3 O-O {Transposes. (7.O-O O-O 8.d3 Bc7 Transposes to the current line. )}) 5... O-O 6. a3 {[%cal Gb5c4,Gc4a2,Yd6b4,Yd7d5] A very useful and somewhat also waiting move from White. They obviously still don't want to castle, and waiting for the moment to play [g4]. By creating a retreat square on [a2], they don't have to worry about ...[a6], ...[b5], ...[Na5] ideas to take the bishop, and also, since their king is in the centre for now, ...[Bb4] followed by ...[d5] could have been a decent idea for Black, which is also stopped.} (6. O-O h6 {transposes here.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd6c7,Yd7d5]} ({Our usual setup, when we are playing ...Re8 and then Bf8 is too passive here, and White can meet} 6... Re8 {with} 7. g4 $1 {. We have to find another way to remove the bishop from [d6], and still keep the [e5]-pawn protected, and ...[Nd4] is an excellent start for that, making ...[c6], ...[Bc7] available.}) 7. Bc4 ({•} 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Ne2 c6 9. Bc4 Bc7 {transposes.}) ({•} 7. Bg5 c6 8. Bc4 h6 9. Bh4 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Be7 {transposes here.}) 7... c6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Yd7d5] Continuing the plan, preparing to play ...[Bc7] and then ...[d5] if possible. White has tried quite a few moves in this position, but none seems to pose serious problems for Black.} 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gf3d4] White is challenging our knight on [d4], and would like to force ...[Nxf3], so their queen can develop.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rd7d5] Black can temporarily sacrifice the pawn.} 9. Nxe5 d5 10. Ba2 Qe7 {[%cal Re7e5] Developing with a tempo, and actually the knight doesn't have any squares to go to!} 11. Na4 ({•} 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ {+ -+ With ... [d4] next, Black is winning.}) ({•} 11. f4 Nxc2+ 12. Qxc2 Bxe3 {-+}) 11... Nxc2+ $1 12. Qxc2 Bxe3 13. Nxc6 (13. fxe3 Qxe5 {∓}) 13... bxc6 14. fxe3 Ng4 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Re3][%cal Yd5e4] White is still far from equality here, with so many weaknesses.} *

