idea for Black, which is also stopped.} (6. O-O h6 {transposes here.}) 6... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd6c7,Yd7d5]} ({Our usual setup, when we are playing ...Re8 and then Bf8 is too passive here, and White can meet} 6... Re8 {with} 7. g4 $1 {. We have to find another way to remove the bishop from [d6], and still keep the [e5]-pawn protected, and ...[Nd4] is an excellent start for that, making ...[c6], ...[Bc7] available.}) 7. Bc4 ({•} 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Ne2 c6 9. Bc4 Bc7 {transposes.}) ({•} 7. Bg5 c6 8. Bc4 h6 9. Bh4 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Be7 {transposes here.}) 7... c6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Yd7d5] Continuing the plan, preparing to play ...[Bc7] and then ...[d5] if possible. White has tried quite a few moves in this position, but none seems to pose serious problems for Black.} 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gf3d4] White is challenging our knight on [d4], and would like to force ...[Nxf3], so their queen can develop.} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rd7d5] Black can temporarily sacrifice the pawn.} 9. Nxe5 d5 10. Na4 {A computerish defence from White, tried in a couple of correspondence games.} Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ra4] The refutation is also quite difficult.} 11. c3 Nc2+ 12. Qxc2 Bxe3 {[%csl Ra4] A lot of trades are happening, but White's knight remain awful on [a4], that is Black's main point.} 13. fxe3 dxc4 14. d4 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Gd4e5,Ga4c5] The line is already pretty long, but probably it is not the right time to stop when we are down a pawn, and have a difficult move to make.} (14. Nxc4 $2 Qg5 {-+ ...[b5] next is winning a piece!}) 14... b6 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ya4c5] Black is sacrificing one more pawn, in order to keep the knight completely useless on [a4].} 15. Nxc6 Qg5 16. Ne7+ Kh8 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 {[%csl Ra4] Black is down 2 pawns, but the [a4]-knight is completely out of the game.} (17... Raxc8 {Black is already better, the engine's top line for White goes like this:} 18. e5 Ng4 19. O-O-O f6 $1 {Opening the f-file for the rooks.} 20. exf6 Rxf6 21. Rdf1 Rcf8 22. Rxf6 Rxf6 23. Qe4 h6 {⩱ And the [a4]-knight is still doing nothing.}) *

