1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. c3 $2 {Somehow it was played in more than 600 games according to my database, but I failed to discover the point of this move, White just gives up the pawn on [e4].} Nxe4 {[%cal Gd7d5] It is not only a pawn, Black is already threatening to play ...[d5] in the next move.} 5. Qe2 (5. Bd5 {Relatively the best, but it just shows, how bad [c3] was.} Nf6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. d4 O-O {⩱ With ...[c5] to come in the next move, Black has the advantage of the bishop pair without doing anything.}) 5... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rd5c4,Gd5e4] With a tempo!} 6. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5]} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] It is very easy to deal with White's threats.} 7. d3 Nf6 8. Nxe5 O-O $1 {[%csl Re1,Re2][%cal Re8e1] White has won back the pawn, but our opponent is way behind in development, and also there could be unpleasant things on the e-file.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6,Gb6h6] The rook will be able to join the game via the 6th rank.} 11. O-O Rb6 12. Ba4 Bxh2+ $19 {[%csl Ya1,Ya4,Yb1,Yc1][%cal Gf6g4,Gd8h4] Since all of White's minor pieces are on the queenside, it is not a surprise that this typical tactical trick is already winning for Black.} *

