1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. O-O $6 {Another possible way to ignore defending the [e4]-pawn, and another dubious move. 🙂} Nxe4 5. d4 d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8g4,Gd5e4] Protecting the knight and opening up a diagonal for the bishop first, and later we can take on [d4].} 6. Bb5 exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 Bd7 {Transposes to the Scotch Gambit.}) 7... Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rc6d4,Gd7d5] Very unusual to break a pin with the queen, but it is necessary now, since the [d5]-pawn needs protection.} 8. Qa4 Nc5 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] With ...[Be7] and ...[O-O] to follow, Black is clearly better.} *

