1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. O-O $6 {Another possible way to ignore defending the [e4]-pawn, and another dubious move. 🙂} Nxe4 5. Qe2 d5 $1 {As usual!} 6. Bb5 {[%cal Gc2c4,Rf3e5] Sometimes White wants to undermine our knight by playing [c4], but more importantly the [e5]-pawn is hanging now.} Bg4 {[%cal Rg4e2] The pin is very unpleasant for White, and it also protects the [e5]-pawn.} 7. d3 (7. c4 Be7 8. d3 Nc5 9. Nc3 dxc4 10. dxc4 O-O {∓ Black easily keeps the extra material in this line.}) 7... Bxf3 $1 {Important, since if we would have moved with the knight somewhere, then White could play [Qxe5]+.} 8. gxf3 {[%csl Yf2,Yf3]} (8. Qxf3 Nf6 9. Qg3 Qd6 {⩱ With ...[O-O-O] to follow, Black is clearly better.}) 8... Nd6 {[%cal Rd6b5] Gaining a tempo on the bishop.} 9. Qxe5+ (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. f4 Be7 11. fxe5 Nf5 {∓ The material is equal, but White's king is very weak.}) 9... Qe7 10. Qxd5 {[%csl Yf2,Yf3,Rg1,Yh2] White even managed to win a pawn, but their position remains difficult with a broken position of the king.} Nxb5 11. Qxb5 O-O-O $17 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gc6d4,Ge7e6,Gf8d6] With excellent attacking chances for Black.} *

