1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. O-O $6 {Another possible way to ignore defending the [e4]-pawn, and another dubious move. 🙂} Nxe4 5. Re1 $2 {The most common move, and a very bad one as well.} ({•} 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 h6 {transposes to the Four Knights.}) ({•} 5. Bd5 Nf6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. d4 Be6 {⩱ Black can play very ambitiously and continue with ...[Qe7] and ...[O-O-O] but in any case we have the advantage because of the bishop pair.}) 5... d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd5e4,Rd5c4] Winning a huge tempo on the bishop.} 6. Bb5 Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rc5f2] For now we can ignore the defense of the [e5]-pawn, since we have a stronger threat on [f2].} 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 (8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Rxe4 Qd5 {∓ Black is comfortably keeping the extra pawn.}) 8... O-O 9. Bxc6 Nxf2 $1 {This is the fastest way to win the game.} 10. Kxf2 Qf6+ {[%cal Rf6f2,Rf6d4,Rc5d4]} 11. Kg1 Qxd4+ 12. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 13. Kh1 bxc6 $19 {Black is 2 pawns up and completely winning.} *

