ome tricks which actually can win the game for you quickly, if Black is not careful, so I expect to see this line online quite often in the future.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4e2,Rd4c2] This move completely refutes White's trick. We can ignore the threat on [f7].} 6. Bxf7+ (6. Qd3 d5 $1 7. exd5 Bf5 {-+ And Black is already winning a lot of material.}) 6... Kf8 {[%csl Yf7][%cal Rd4e2,Rd4c2,Rh7h6] White has many problems, [e2] and [c2] is hanging, and ...[h6] is also a threat.} 7. Qc4 (7. Qd3 h6 8. c3 hxg5 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Bb3 d5 {-+ White has managed to avoid losing material, but in return they couldn't finish the development.}) 7... Qe7 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Rh7h6,Ye7f7] ...[h6] is threatening to take the bishop on [f7].} 8. b4 Bb6 9. a4 a5 $19 {[%cal Rh7h6] We stopped White's desperate tries on the queenside and are about to win material with ...[h6].} *

