1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Qe2 {White is protecting the pawn on [e4], but in a somewhat unusual way. Our opponent will have to play [d3] most likely at some moment to develop the [c1]-bishop, so this queen move looks unnecessary in that sense. Maybe White is dreaming about a possibility to play [c3] and then [d4] at once, but as we will see, they just don't have the time for that.} ({•} 4. d4 exd4 {Transposes to Scotch Gambit.}) ({•} 4. Nc3 $6 {A typical mistake from White, which is discussed in another chapter.} Nxe4 $1 {transposes to Four Knights 4. [g3] and rare moves.}) 4... Bc5 $1 {Developing the bishop to the most active square.} 5. Ng5 $2 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7,Ge8g8] This move looks completely ridiculous, why wait a move and then attack on [f7], when Black can already protect there with castling? However, this is an excellent 'content' for streams and YouTube channels, to show some tricks which actually can win the game for you quickly, if Black is not careful, so I expect to see this line online quite often in the future.} O-O $2 6. Nxf7 Rxf7 (6... Qe7 $1 {And Black is still better according to the engine, but we don't need this of course.}) 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qc4+ {This is White's point waiting for the bishop to develop on [c5].} d5 9. Qxc5 $14 {Black has some tempi for the exchange, but White is obviously better.} *

