1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Qe2 {White is protecting the pawn on [e4], but in a somewhat unusual way. Our opponent will have to play [d3] most likely at some moment to develop the [c1]-bishop, so this queen move looks unnecessary in that sense. Maybe White is dreaming about a possibility to play [c3] and then [d4] at once, but as we will see, they just don't have the time for that.} ({•} 4. d4 exd4 {Transposes to Scotch Gambit.}) ({•} 4. Nc3 $6 {A typical mistake from White, which is discussed in another chapter.} Nxe4 $1 {transposes to Four Knights 4. [g3] and rare moves.}) 4... Bc5 $1 {Developing the bishop to the most active square.} 5. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2d4] Hoping for [b4] or [d4] at some moment, looks like the normal continuation for White.} (5. d3 O-O 6. O-O Re8 {This position is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [O-O] 6. [d3] [Re8] move order.}) 5... O-O 6. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5,Rb5c6,Rf3e5] White is gaining some space on the queenside and potentially [b5] can be an idea as well, to hit the knight at with that the [e5]-pawn too.} d5 $1 {A very nice counterattacking move, which pretty much refutes this line.} 7. exd5 $2 (7. bxc5 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Bg4 {White's position is very tough, Black is at least taking back the pawn with a much better position.} 9. Qe2 Nd7 {∓ With ...[Nxc5] or ...[f5] coming in the next move, Black is just much better.}) 7... e4 $1 {[%cal Rf8e8,Re8e1] One more counterattack, White can't let their knight to be taken, because it would open the e-file.} 8. Ng5 Bg4 {Every move is a tempo.} 9. Qf1 Ne5 (9... Nxd5 {is also working and very good.}) 10. bxc5 Re8 {[%cal Re5d3] Black is down a piece, but completely winning thanks to the unstoppable ... [Nd3]-threat.} 11. Be2 Nd3+ 12. Kd1 Qxd5 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Gd3,Gd5,Yf1,Yh1][%cal Rd5g5,Ga8d8] White almost can't move.} *

