1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Qe2 {White is protecting the pawn on [e4], but in a somewhat unusual way. Our opponent will have to play [d3] most likely at some moment to develop the [c1]-bishop, so this queen move looks unnecessary in that sense. Maybe White is dreaming about a possibility to play [c3] and then [d4] at once, but as we will see, they just don't have the time for that.} ({•} 4. d4 exd4 {Transposes to Scotch Gambit.}) ({•} 4. Nc3 $6 {A typical mistake from White, which is discussed in another chapter.} Nxe4 $1 {transposes to Four Knights 4. [g3] and rare moves.}) 4... Bc5 $1 {Developing the bishop to the most active square.} 5. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2d4] Hoping for [b4] or [d4] at some moment, looks like the normal continuation for White.} (5. d3 O-O 6. O-O Re8 {This position is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [O-O] 6. [d3] [Re8] move order.}) 5... O-O 6. O-O {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd2d4] Maybe with [Rd1] and [d4] to follow in a good day, but as we will see White is very far from it.} d5 $1 {[%csl Re2] Not really a sacrifice, but this is all possible now because the queen is misplaced on [e2], the rook would do a much better job attacking the [e5]-pawn after the trade on [d5].} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. d3 {This is the better move, but Black can achieve a very good position in different ways.} Bg4 {[%cal Rg4e2] Pinning the knight is a good start.} 9. Nbd2 (9. h3 Bh5 $1 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Qxe5 c6 {∓ Black has huge compensation for the pawn, White's king is very exposed.}) 9... Nf4 $36 {[%csl Gc5,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Rf4d3] With all the minor pieces being very active it is clear that Black is in the driver's seat.} *

