nd [d4] to follow in a good day, but as we will see White is very far from it.} d5 $1 {[%csl Re2] Not really a sacrifice, but this is all possible now because the queen is misplaced on [e2], the rook would do a much better job attacking the [e5]-pawn after the trade on [d5].} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxe5 $2 {This is the critical test of Black's play.} Nf4 $1 {[%cal Rf4e2] The queen is hanging with a check, so White doesn't have time for intermediate moves, and also have to keep guarding the [e5]-knight.} 9. Qe4 Qh4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rf4h3,Yh4e4] With the threat of ... [Nh3]+!} 10. d3 Nh3+ $1 {It still works!} 11. gxh3 Qxe4 12. dxe4 Nxe5 13. Be2 Bxh3 $19 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5,Rg1,Gh3][%cal Yf7f5] Black is much better developed and White's king remains very weak despite the queens being traded off.} *

