1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Qe2 {White is protecting the pawn on [e4], but in a somewhat unusual way. Our opponent will have to play [d3] most likely at some moment to develop the [c1]-bishop, so this queen move looks unnecessary in that sense. Maybe White is dreaming about a possibility to play [c3] and then [d4] at once, but as we will see, they just don't have the time for that.} ({•} 4. d4 exd4 {Transposes to Scotch Gambit.}) ({•} 4. Nc3 $6 {A typical mistake from White, which is discussed in another chapter.} Nxe4 $1 {transposes to Four Knights 4. [g3] and rare moves.}) 4... Bc5 $1 {Developing the bishop to the most active square.} 5. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2d4] Hoping for [b4] or [d4] at some moment, looks like the normal continuation for White.} (5. d3 O-O 6. O-O Re8 {This position is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [O-O] 6. [d3] [Re8] move order.}) 5... O-O 6. d3 d5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Re8e1] With the queen and also the king still being on the e-file, we absolutely don't have to worry about the [e5]-pawn, because of the potential pins.} 7. Bb3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] In general it is an excellent sign in 1. [e4] [e5] openings, that when Black plays ...[d5] White rejects to take it and Black is allowed to have the space advantage in the centre. This particular variation is no exception.} (7. exd5 Nxd5 8. O-O Bg4 {transposes to the 6. [O-O] [d5] line.}) 7... a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ra4b3] We can already be very ambitious, since it is clear that now Black is playing for the advantage. The goal is to force the light-squared bishop into a very passive square.} 8. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rg5d8,Rb3d5] By pinning the knight on [f6], White is putting pressure on the [d5]-square.} dxe4 9. dxe4 h6 $1 {It is good to include this move in most of the positions, since if White wants to keep the pin, then they have to count on ...[g5] later.} 10. Bh4 a4 11. Bc4 g5 $1 {We can safely break the pin, since the sacrifices are not working on [g5].} 12. Bg3 (12. Nxg5 hxg5 13. Bxg5 Qd6 {-+ With ...[Nh7] coming in the next move, White has no compensation for the piece at all.}) 12... Nh5 $17 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gg5g4,Gd8g5] With ...[g4] and ...[Qg5] to follow, Black is dominating the game.} *

