queen and also the king still being on the e-file, we absolutely don't have to worry about the [e5]-pawn, because of the potential pins.} 7. Bb3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] In general it is an excellent sign in 1. [e4] [e5] openings, that when Black plays ...[d5] White rejects to take it and Black is allowed to have the space advantage in the centre. This particular variation is no exception.} (7. exd5 Nxd5 8. O-O Bg4 {transposes to the 6. [O-O] [d5] line.}) 7... a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ra4b3] We can already be very ambitious, since it is clear that now Black is playing for the advantage. The goal is to force the light-squared bishop into a very passive square.} 8. a4 (8. O-O a4 9. Bc2 h6 {⩱ We have more active pieces, space advantage in the centre and easy development.}) 8... Be6 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Rd5e4,Re6b3] With the threat of ...[dxe4] and using the fact that White's bishop is undefended on [b3].} 9. Bc2 h6 {[%cal Rf3g5,Rc1g5,Yh6g5] We don't have to worry about [Ng5] or [Bg5] anymore.} 10. O-O Re8 $15 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gc5b6,Yf7f5,Gd8e7,Ga8d8] Black is definitely better with more space and has several plans. We can remove the knight from [f6] and play for [f5], or simply complete development with ...[Qe7] and ...[Rad8], then maneuver the knight via [d7] to [c5] to put more pressure on White's queenside and the [d3] pawn.} *

