1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. Bb3 $6 ({A better move than} 5. Bb5 {, but it is still Black who can fight for the advantage.}) 5... dxe4 $1 6. Ng5 {[%cal Rb3f7,Rg5f7,Yg5e4] This is the point behind 5. [Bb3], but we don't have to be afraid of this at all.} Be6 {We are up a pawn, so we can afford to give it back.} 7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. Bxe6 exd3 9. cxd3 (9. Qxd3 Qxd3 10. cxd3 Nb4 {∓ With an unpleasant double attack on [d3] and [c2].}) 9... Qd6 $1 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Ge8c8,Rd8d3] We want to play ... [O-O-O] next and attack the pawn on [d3].} 10. Bh3 Rd8 {Unfortunately it was not possible to castle, but White can't really protect the pawn on [d3] anyways.} 11. O-O Qxd3 $15 (11... Qxd3 {The bishop pair gives some compensation for the missing pawn, and it would be even more so if White could keep the queens on the board. Fortunately, however, they can't, since} 12. Qa4 {is met by} Rd4 {and White is losing more material.}) *

