1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Bb5 $6 {[%cal Rf3e5] This move at least addresses the key factor of the position, the [e5]-pawn. The problem is that White is moving the bishop for the second time, giving Black enough time to comfortably protect the pawn.} Bd6 7. Bxc6+ {Since White can't increase the pressure on [e5], it looks logical to take on [c6] and ruin Black's structure.} bxc6 {[%cal Ga8b8,Rb8b2,Yc6c5,Gc8b7,Rb7g2] It is important to know that this structure, in case it happens by White giving up their strong bishop for our knight, is just great for Black. Even though we have doubled c-pawns, it will not affect our space advantage and kingside play. Also, the opened b-file can be used potentially by the rook, and we also have ideas like ...[c5]-[Bb7], using the bishop on the long diagonal.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg8h8,Gd8d7,Ga8e8] We will start active play on the kingside with ...[f5] very soon.} *

