1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Ng5 $6 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Yf6d5,Rd1f3,Rf3f7,Rf3d5,Rf3h5,Rh5f7] Since our knight is missing from [f6], White is trying to take advantage of it and quickly attack the [f7]-square, just like in the Fried Liver variation. This is definitely a worse version for them though, since they lost an important tempo by playing [d3].} f6 $1 {A very important move, there is no more sacrifice on [f7]!} 7. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rc4d5] Was only tried in a couple of games, but it is pretty easy to go wrong here as Black.} ({•} 7. Ne4 $2 {No doubt, White is just losing a lot of time while Black has protected the [e5] pawn.} Be6 {∓}) ({•} 7. Qf3 $2 {This fails tactically.} Nd4 $1 8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. Bxd5 Nxc2+ 10. Kd1 Nxa1 {-+}) 7... Bb4 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rb4e1] Developing, protecting the knight on [d5] and preparing to castle!} (7... Nxc3 $2 8. Bf7+ $1 Kd7 {(8...Ke7 9.bxc3 ⩲ And White is better since we can't take on [g5]. )} 9. bxc3 fxg5 10. Qg4+ Ke7 11. Qf3 {+- Quite stunning position, White is down a piece, and they can make a quiet move just to protect the bishop, but Black is helpless against the threats of [Ba3]+ and [Bxg5]+.}) 8. Nge4 Be6 {Now everything looks safe for Black.} 9. O-O O-O $10 {[%csl Ge5] Black is at least equal, but with the potential to take over the game, because of the space advantage.} *

