n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Nc3 {Not a particularly dangerous move, since Black can just continue development without worrying about the [e5]-pawn.} Be6 7. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5e6] This leads to massive simplifications, but White doesn't have anything better.} (7. Bb5 f6 8. O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qd6 $1 {We can play very ambitiously and go for long castle.} 10. Be3 a6 11. Ba4 O-O-O {⇆}) 7... Nxc3 8. Nxe6 Nxd1 9. Nxd8 Rxd8 10. Kxd1 {[%csl Gc4] If we are not careful now, then White can be better because of the pair of bishops. However, we have a way to completely equalise the game.} Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ra5c4] White can't keep the bishop on the board.} 11. Bb5+ c6 12. Bd2 cxb5 13. Bxa5 Rd5 $10 {Black has no problems at all. Our structure is maybe slightly inferior, but in return for that, we can use the c-file with our rooks.} *

