1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yc8g4,Yh3g4] A very defensive approach, which is certainly not the way to punish Black for playing ...[d5] 'too early'. White takes away the [g4]-square from our bishop, but instead our opponent should attack us right away.} Bf5 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] Our plan is to continue the development with ...[Qd7] and ... [O-O-O].} (6... Be6 $6 {This is not the right place for the bishop, because it allows} 7. Ng5 $1) 7. O-O (7. Qe2 f6 8. O-O {(8.d4 allows 8...Ndb4! with a double attack on [c2] and [d4]. )} Qd7 {And we have transposed to the current line.}) 7... Qd7 8. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re2e5] White is putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn just before we could castle; the game is getting very sharp now.} f6 9. d4 $1 {[%cal Rd4e5] Only move, otherwise Black just castles with a better position.} e4 ({It is also possible to play} 9... O-O-O {with a complicated game, but I prefer the text move.}) 10. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rc3d5] Hitting both [d5] and [e4] seemingly forces Black to take on [c3] and strengthen White's centre, but we have another way to play!} O-O-O $1 {[%cal Re4f3] A lot of things are hanging, but every line is fine for Black. 🙂} 11. Nxe4 {Pretty much a must, since if White had taken on [d5], then after ... [exf3] the [d4]-pawn would also fall with a tempo.} Re8 12. Bxd5 (12. Bd3 $4 {losing a piece to} Bxe4 $1 13. Bxe4 f5 {-+}) 12... Qxd5 13. Nxf6 $1 {[%cal Rf6d5,Re2e8] White is getting out from the pin by winning one more pawn.} Rxe2 14. Nxd5 Be4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Re4f3,Yc6d4,Re4d5] We want to take on [f3] and then on [d4].} 15. Nf4 Bxf3 16. c3 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Re2][%cal Gc3d4,Rg2f3,Rf4e2] Since we have two pieces hanging, White has time for this move.} ({•} 16. gxf3 Rxc2 {⩱ Black is better, since White's structure is very bad.}) ({•} 16. Nxe2 Bxe2 17. Re1 Bh5 18. c3 Bf7 {⩱ Materially speaking White is doing well, but it will be very difficult to push their pawns, and the dark-squared bishop is also restricted by its own pawns.}) 16... Bd6 17. gxf3 Bxf4 18. Bxf4 Rf8 19. Bg3 Rxb2 $10 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3][%cal Gc6e7,Ge7d5] White has an extra pawn, but that is doubled on the f-file, and also the queenside is far from perfect in our opponent's camp.} *

