n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Yc8g4,Yh3g4] A very defensive approach, which is certainly not the way to punish Black for playing ...[d5] 'too early'. White takes away the [g4]-square from our bishop, but instead our opponent should attack us right away.} Bf5 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] Our plan is to continue the development with ...[Qd7] and ... [O-O-O].} (6... Be6 $6 {This is not the right place for the bishop, because it allows} 7. Ng5 $1) 7. O-O (7. Qe2 f6 8. O-O {(8.d4 allows 8...Ndb4! with a double attack on [c2] and [d4]. )} Qd7 {And we have transposed to the current line.}) 7... Qd7 8. Nxe5 {Leads to complete equality.} (8. Re1 f6 9. d4 Nb6) 8... Nxe5 9. Qe2 f6 10. d4 Nf4 $1 {The easiest way to a fine position. There are other ways too, but those are somewhat more complicated.} 11. Bxf4 Qxd4 12. Bxe5 Qxe5 13. Qd1 {[%cal Rf1e1,Re1e8] The pin on the e-file looks scary, but Black will have threats also.} (13. Qxe5+ fxe5 {Black is completely fine with the pair of bishops.}) 13... Bd6 {[%cal Re5h2]} 14. Re1 Be4 {[%cal Re5h2,Rh2g2] Looks suspicious, but White doesn't have time to take advantage of the pinned bishop, because of the ...[Qh2]-threat.} 15. g3 O-O-O 16. Nd2 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d1,Re5g3,Yc5f2,Yd8d2] Counterpinning and also introducing the ...[Qxg3] idea, so White has to be very careful now.} 17. Nxe4 $1 {A nice way to make the draw.} Rxd1 18. Raxd1 {[%cal Re4d6,Rd1d5,Rd5e5,Rd5c5] With threats like [Nd6]+ and [Rd5], Black has nothing better than giving back the queen and going for a drawish endgame.} Be7 19. Nd6+ Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Bxd6 $10 {A draw is extremely likely in this game.} *

