1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. O-O {[%cal Gd3d4] White first castles and keeps the [d4]-option available.} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Rb6c4] Our knight is not loose anymore on [d5], and we are also gaining a tempo on the [c4] bishop.} (7... Bg4 {White can reply with the annoying} 8. Qe4 $1) 8. Bb5 Bd6 9. d4 {[%csl Rc6,Re5][%cal Yb5e8,Gd4e5] This is how White should play, putting maximum pressure in our centre.} (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 {As we have learned already, this structure is very nice for Black, so White can't wait but has to play} 10. d4 {and after} O-O {We just transpose to the current line.}) 9... O-O {We have to finish the development and get out of the pins with our king.} 10. Bxc6 (10. dxe5 {This allows Black to recapture on [e5] without compromising the structure.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Black has no problems, ...[Bf5] is next with an equal position.}) 10... bxc6 {This is a different story compared to the previous positions with [Bxc6]-[bxc6], since now White has the chance to further weaken our structure.} 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5][%cal Gf8f2,Gc8g4,Gb6d5] Well, if only pawn structure would matter, then we could start looking for a new variation. 🙂 Fortunately, this position is much more than that. Black can develop enough counterplay by using the activity of their pieces.} 12. Nbd2 (12. Nc3 {would be very similar or the same, since White's idea is to blockade [e4] with the knight.}) 12... Qe8 $132 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gc8g4] And Black already has very good play, since White's main idea, which is [Ne4] can be met by ...[Bg4]. Our next moves are very easy, ...[Bg4], ...[Nd5], ...[Qg6], then doubling on the f-file comes, and we are putting a lot of pressure on White's position.} *

