 is the usual route for the queen in this structure. It wants to reach the [g6]-square, and from there it can put pressure on the [e4]-knight, or, if that moves, the [c2]-pawn. It also helps with ...[Bh3] or ...[Bg4] ideas.} 13. Ne4 Qg6 14. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3e4] A normal move, which is not only stabilising the knight, but allows the [f1]-rook to move, since now ...[Bg4] and ...[Bf3] is not something White has to prevent anymore.} Nd5 {The knight was doing nothing on [b6], so it was time to bring it into the game.} 15. Nbc3 Nxc3 16. Nxc3 Bf5 $10 {[%cal Rf5c2] With a good position for Black, since White couldn't keep the perfect blockade on [e4]. Let's see a couple of possible continuations.} (16... Bf5 {•} 17. Ne4 $2 Bxe4 18. fxe4 Rxf1+ 19. Kxf1 Rf8+ 20. Kg1 Bc5+ {∓ And White is losing the pawn on [e4].}) (16... Bf5 {•} 17. Bd2 Bxc2 18. Qc4+ Kh8 19. Ne4 {(19.Qxc6? Allows 19...e4! With the threat of ...[Bxh2]+. )} Bxe4 20. fxe4 c5 {We have an extra pawn, but it doesn't really mean much here. 🙂}) *

