n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. O-O {[%cal Gd3d4] White first castles and keeps the [d4]-option available.} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Rb6c4] Our knight is not loose anymore on [d5], and we are also gaining a tempo on the [c4] bishop.} (7... Bg4 {White can reply with the annoying} 8. Qe4 $1) 8. Bb3 {[%cal Gb3g8,Ye8g8] It is quite problematic to play ...[O-O] in this position, so we have to develop our light-squared bishop and queen, and go for ...[O-O-O].} Bg4 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8,Gd8e7]} 9. c3 {[%cal Yc6d4,Gc3d4] White prevents ... [Nd4] jumps.} Qd7 {When we place the queen on [d7] or [e7], the main thing to anticipate is [h3], and how we can react to that. Obviously the more ideal square is [d7], not to close the [f8]-bishop and keep attacking the d-file, but sometimes it is not possible.} 10. h3 Bh5 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re2h5] White's trick is [Nxe5] in this position, but of course it doesn't work right away, since the queen on [e2] is not protected.} 11. Re1 O-O-O $1 {We are falling for [Nxe5], but thanks to the weakness of the [d3]-pawn, it works out for Black.} 12. Nxe5 Qe8 $1 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ge8h5]} 13. Ng4 Qxe2 14. Rxe2 Rxd3 $15 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gh8d8] Black is better developed and more active.} *

