n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. O-O {[%cal Gd3d4] White first castles and keeps the [d4]-option available.} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Rb6c4] Our knight is not loose anymore on [d5], and we are also gaining a tempo on the [c4] bishop.} (7... Bg4 {White can reply with the annoying} 8. Qe4 $1) 8. Bb3 {[%cal Gb3g8,Ye8g8] It is quite problematic to play ...[O-O] in this position, so we have to develop our light-squared bishop and queen, and go for ...[O-O-O].} Bg4 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8,Gd8e7]} 9. Be3 Qe7 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gg4h5,Rf3e5,Re5d7] No [Nxe5] tricks anymore, since our bishop will be safe to retreat to [h5].} (9... Qd7 {It is playable, but if possible I would keep the light-squared bishop on the board.} 10. h3 $1 Bh5 {(10...Bxf3 11.Qxf3 O-O-O ∞ Is apparently quite okay for Black, but I would prefer White with the pair of bishops. )} 11. Re1 $1 {Now [Nxe5] is a huge threat.} Bf7 12. Bxf7+ Qxf7 13. Bxb6 axb6 14. d4 $1 {⩲ And we have concrete problems to solve, but it is not easy.}) 10. a4 {At one moment, it is useful to include [a4]-[a5] for White, because it will make the [b5]-square available for their knight.} a5 {We are planning to go for ...[O-O-O], so can't allow moves like [a5]-[a6] from White.} 11. Nc3 O-O-O 12. Bxb6 cxb6 13. Nb5 Qe8 $13 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g6,Gc8b8] With a balanced position, but I like Black's chances. We are going to play ...[Bc5] and ...[Kb8], and then we can start looking for aggressive play on the kingside.} *

