n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rf3e5] Very direct play from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4e2] The only way to keep the [e5]-pawn!} 8. Qe4 {[%cal Re4g4,Re4d5] White is forcing us to give up the light-squared bishop, but it is not a problem for us if we can win material with it.} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 (9. gxf3 Nb6 10. Bb5 Qxd4 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Kf7 {⩱ Black is better, it will be tough for White to find some safe place for their king.}) 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd5 Qxd5 11. Bxd5 Nxc2+ 12. Ke2 Nxa1 13. Be4 Bc5 $15 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gc5d4,Yg7g6,Yf6f5,Ya1c2] It will be not easy at all to take the knight [a1], since Black has the defensive resources ...[Bd4] and ...[g6]-[f5].} *

