1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rf3e5] Very direct play from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4e2] The only way to keep the [e5]-pawn!} 8. dxe5 Nxe5 {Black is very comfortably equalising here.} 9. Qe4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nb6 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yf3f4] Very important tempo on the bishop, otherwise [f4] could have been unpleasant.} 11. Bb3 {[%cal Re4b7,Rf3f4] White has 2 threats now, and the solution is obviously to ignore both.} (11. Be2 Qd5 $1 {And Black is at least equal with having the much better structure.}) 11... Qd7 $1 12. Qxb7 (12. f4 O-O-O $1 {⩱ Black rescues the knight because of the checkmate threat on [d1].}) 12... Bb4+ 13. Nc3 c5 $1 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {[%cal Rc5c4,Rc4b3,Re5f3,Gh8e8] With an excellent position for Black. White has to defend against many threats.} *

