n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rf3e5] Very direct play from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4e2] The only way to keep the [e5]-pawn!} 8. Bb5 {White is doing the same trick as we did by pinning our knight. But perhaps more importantly, they also open the way for [c4]-[d5] ideas, so the game is getting very sharp.} Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Preparing to castle long and hoping that the complications will work out in our favour.} 9. dxe5 O-O-O 10. O-O Ndb4 {[%cal Gd7f5,Yg4f3,Ye2f3,Yb4c2] With threats like ... [Bxf3] and then ...[Nxc2]. Also, getting out from pin with ...[Qf5] and potentially playing ...[Nd4] is very unpleasant for White.} 11. Nc3 Qf5 {[%cal Rc6d4] ...[Nd4] is a huge threat now.} 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 13. exf6 Qxf6 $15 {Even though White has an extra pawn, they are clearly struggling here; we can anytime take on [f3] and then play ...[Nd4].} *

