n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rf3e5] Very direct play from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4e2] The only way to keep the [e5]-pawn!} 8. Bb5 {White is doing the same trick as we did by pinning our knight. But perhaps more importantly, they also open the way for [c4]-[d5] ideas, so the game is getting very sharp.} Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Preparing to castle long and hoping that the complications will work out in our favour.} 9. c4 {[%cal Rc4d5,Gd4d5] White is attacking the knight and also ready to exploit the pin in the next move by playing [d5].} Bb4+ $1 {[%cal Yb1d2,Yc1d2,Yd5f4] Very important intermezzo! White can't block this check, since in that case ...[Nf4] would come with a tempo, and the whole [c4]-[d5] plan is refuted.} 10. Kf1 ({•} 10. Nbd2 $4 Nf4 11. Qe4 Bf5 {-+}) ({•} 10. Bd2 $4 Nf4 11. Qe4 Bf5 {-+}) 10... O-O-O $1 {Since we are way ahead in the development and White's king is in the centre, we will have great compensation for the piece.} 11. cxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Rc6d4,Re5e4] Both ...[e4] and [Nxd4] are huge threats now.} 12. Qc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qxf3 14. Qe6+ {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge6g4] In order to control the important [g4]-square.} (14. Bxc6 $4 {Is just losing to} Qd1+ $1 15. Kg2 Qg4+ 16. Kf1 Rxd4 {-+ And White is losing the queen.}) 14... Kb8 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rg1 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1] Since White's pieces are not taking part in the game, Black can reach a winning position here.} Qd3+ 17. Kg2 Qe4+ 18. Kf1 Rxd4 $19 {[%cal Rd4d1] White has to give back the material in order to stop ...[Rd1]+.} *

