1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. Qe2 {[%cal Rf3e5] This is one of the two challenging continuations for Black. White is immediately attacking the [e5]-pawn.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Very important! It is tempting to protect the pawn by pinning the [f3]-knight, but it just leads to a pretty bad position for Black.} 7. d4 {[%cal Rd4e5,Rf3e5] Very direct play from White.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Yg4e2] The only way to keep the [e5]-pawn!} 8. Bb5 {White is doing the same trick as we did by pinning our knight. But perhaps more importantly, they also open the way for [c4]-[d5] ideas, so the game is getting very sharp.} Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Preparing to castle long and hoping that the complications will work out in our favour.} 9. c4 {[%cal Rc4d5,Gd4d5] White is attacking the knight and also ready to exploit the pin in the next move by playing [d5].} Bb4+ $1 {[%cal Yb1d2,Yc1d2,Yd5f4] Very important intermezzo! White can't block this check, since in that case ...[Nf4] would come with a tempo, and the whole [c4]-[d5] plan is refuted.} 10. Kf1 ({•} 10. Nbd2 $4 Nf4 11. Qe4 Bf5 {-+}) ({•} 10. Bd2 $4 Nf4 11. Qe4 Bf5 {-+}) 10... O-O-O $1 {Since we are way ahead in the development and White's king is in the centre, we will have great compensation for the piece.} 11. h3 {Attacking one more piece, but it is still not a developing move.} Nf4 $1 12. Bxf4 Bxf3 $1 13. gxf3 (13. Qxf3 Qxd4 {-+ Everything is hanging in White's position: the bishop on [f4], the [b2]-pawn and [Qd1] is also a threat, since it is winning the rook on [h1].}) 13... exf4 14. d5 Rhe8 $19 (14... Rhe8 {And White is completely lost, one possible line is} 15. Qc2 Re1+ 16. Kg2 Rxh1 17. Kxh1 Qxh3+ 18. Kg1 Ne5 {With the machine indicating that it is a checkmate in 10 moves.}) *

