1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb3 {[%csl Gc6]} ({I believe it is easier to handle than} 7. Bb5 {, since after all the main problem of our position is the [e5]-pawn, which now will be easier because the knight on [c6] can't be pinned.}) 7... Bg4 ({Of course! We shouldn't fall for the} 7... Bd6 $4 8. Ng5 $1 O-O 9. Qh5 {+- line.}) 8. h3 (8. Re1 {At one moment White most likely will play [h3], so this move doesn't have much of an independent value, it just gives an extra opportunity for Black.} Qe7 {I recommend going with this move, since the transposition is extremely likely.} 9. a4 a5 10. h3 Bh5 {transposes. However, we have an interesting alternative with 8...Qf6 , since now we can meet 9.h3 by 9...Bxf3 and have a decent position.}) 8... Bh5 9. Re1 Qe7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e5,Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Of course, this is not the ideal position for the queen, but it is not only protecting the pawn on [e5], but also prepares ... [O-O-O], which is very important for Black.} (9... Qf6 $2 {Now it is not working, because after} 10. g4 $1 Bg6 11. Nc3 {± We have problems with castling, since [Bg5] would win an exchange in that case.}) 10. a4 {[%cal Ya4a5] It looks like the right moment to insert [a4], since Black normally has to reply with ...[a5], and then the knight can still go towards the weakened [b5]-square from [b1].} a5 {We can't allow White to gain a lot of space on the queenside by playing [a5].} 11. Nc3 {[%csl Gb5,Ge5][%cal Gc3b5] The knight will have a nice square on [b5], but this slower approach also means that the [e5]-pawn is not in danger. When this is the case, Black is pretty much always fine.} O-O-O 12. Nb5 f6 $132 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5,Yg7g5,Yg5g4] Supporting the centre, but also preparing a ...[g5]-[g4] expansion on the kingside.} *

