n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb3 {[%csl Gc6]} ({I believe it is easier to handle than} 7. Bb5 {, since after all the main problem of our position is the [e5]-pawn, which now will be easier because the knight on [c6] can't be pinned.}) 7... Bg4 ({Of course! We shouldn't fall for the} 7... Bd6 $4 8. Ng5 $1 O-O 9. Qh5 {+- line.}) 8. h3 (8. Re1 {At one moment White most likely will play [h3], so this move doesn't have much of an independent value, it just gives an extra opportunity for Black.} Qe7 {I recommend going with this move, since the transposition is extremely likely.} 9. a4 a5 10. h3 Bh5 {transposes. However, we have an interesting alternative with 8...Qf6 , since now we can meet 9.h3 by 9...Bxf3 and have a decent position.}) 8... Bh5 9. Re1 Qe7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e5,Gc6e5,Ge8c8] Of course, this is not the ideal position for the queen, but it is not only protecting the pawn on [e5], but also prepares ... [O-O-O], which is very important for Black.} (9... Qf6 $2 {Now it is not working, because after} 10. g4 $1 Bg6 11. Nc3 {± We have problems with castling, since [Bg5] would win an exchange in that case.}) 10. d4 {Nobody has tried it in practice yet, since it looks like that ...[O-O-O] will solve all of Black's problems. Still, the position is more tricky.} O-O-O 11. c3 {[%csl Gd4,Ye5][%cal Re1e7,Rd8d1,Gc3d4] With both queens pinned, the situation in the centre is weird. It is not easy to clarify the situation.} Qd6 $1 {Getting out of the pin is very natural.} 12. Na3 h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yd6f6,Yh6g5] By covering the [g5]-square, Black is preparing for an eventual ...[Qf6].} (12... exd4 {It is better not to take here, since after} 13. Nb5 $1 {Black is experiencing problems with the queen's placement.} Qg6 14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 {⩲ (With [g4] being a threat, and still no comfortable place for the queen on ...[Qd6] there is [g3] with the idea of [Bf4] White is better here.)}) 13. g4 {Wins a pawn, but weakens the king, which will give excellent compensation for Black.} Bg6 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Qd7 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8d6,Gh6h5] With moves like ...[Bd6] and ...[h5] coming, I really like Black's chances here.} *

