2 {Now it is not working, because after} 10. g4 $1 Bg6 11. Nc3 {± We have problems with castling, since [Bg5] would win an exchange in that case.}) 10. Nbd2 {The main move so far in practice, but of course we are not talking about a big sample size.} O-O-O 11. Ne4 {[%csl Ye7][%cal Ye7d6,Ge4g3] A better version of the [Nf1]-[g3] idea, now Black's queen doesn't have the [d6]-square available.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5,Gh5f7] We react in the same way, protecting the pawn on [e5], and also opening the [f7]-square for our bishop in case of [Ng3].} 12. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc6d4,Gc3d4,Gd3d4] White stops ...[Nd4] ideas and also prepares to push [d4] themselves at some moment.} Kb8 {A typical improving move after long castling, moving the king into a safer square out of the [h3]-[c8] diagonal.} 13. Ng3 Bf7 14. d4 {[%csl Yd1,Ye7] We have a very interesting position, with both queens misplaced and pinned, as well as big tension in the centre. It is not easy to improve the position for either side, so don't be so surprised about our next move. 🙂} a6 $13 {A slightly improving but mainly waiting move. The point is that once White's dark-squared bishop is developed, then Black can play ...[Nc4] and White can't kick that knight out immediately with [Qe2].} (14... a6 {One possible continuation is} 15. Qe2 Bxb3 16. axb3 exd4 17. Qxe7 Bxe7 18. Nf5 Nd5 19. N3xd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Rhe8 {And we reached an equal endgame.}) ({Instead, after} 14... Nc4 15. Qe2 $1 {± White is out from the pin with a tempo.}) *

