1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. d4 {Leads to forcing play, which is just fine for Black, but it is not easy, so it is an important line to know.} e4 $1 {We have no other move, otherwise we just lose a pawn or our structure will be very bad.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Re1e4]} f5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4] Again, we have no choice but to protect the pawn on [e4].} 10. Bg5 (10. c4 {This is also possible, but not dangerous for Black at all.} O-O 11. c5 exf3 12. Qb3+ Rf7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Qxf3 Nd5 {After massive exchanges we arrived at an equal position.}) 10... Qd7 ({Apparently} 10... Be7 {is also fine for Black, and it 'only' involves a pawn sacrifice. Still, after the text move, it is very easy to go wrong with either side. It also is somewhat more forcing, so it should be easier to remember the lines.}) 11. c4 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gc4c5,Yd5c6,Rc5b6,Rc5d6] White has now 2 different ways to attack our pieces and potentially win material.} (11. d5 $4 {This is just a blunder, the d-pawn is not protected because of a small tactical trick.} h6 $1 {Not so important, just a small finesse from the engine.} 12. Bh4 Nxd5 {∓ This is the key move. 🙂 White can't recapture, because of ...[Bxh2]+.}) 11... O-O $1 {[%cal Re4f3] By going out from the pin, we are threatening to take the [f3]-knight.} 12. c5 $1 {[%cal Rc5b6,Rc5d6] The chaos starts. 🙂 It is really tough to navigate such positions without the help of the machine I refer to analyses, don't use it in your games!. 🙂} (12. d5 $4 {This is still very bad.} exf3 13. Qxf3 Nd4 $1 {-+ And Black remains a piece up.}) 12... exf3 13. cxb6 {[%cal Yd4d5,Rd5c6] It is much more critical to take here, since now if Black recaptures, the [d5]-threat would still be there.} h6 $1 {Forcing White's bishop to a worse square, or we can just take it on the next move.} 14. Bh4 f4 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Yg7g5,Yd7g4,Rg4g2] With the threats of ...[g5] and ...[Qg4].} 15. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Yd4d5] In order to meet everything with [Nxf3], and then go for [d5] and win back the material.} (15. d5 $4 {White doesn't have time for this.} Qg4 {-+ Black is winning material.}) 15... fxg2 16. d5 (16. bxc7 Qxc7 {∞ The position is very complex, but I like Black's chances, White's position looks pretty tough to play.}) 16... f3 $1 17. Nxf3 (17. dxc6 $4 {It's mate in 3.} Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 Qh1#) 17... Rxf3 $1 18. Qxf3 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4f3,Rd4b5] This is the point, Black is doing very well.} 19. Qd3 Nxb5 $17 *

