n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. d4 {Leads to forcing play, which is just fine for Black, but it is not easy, so it is an important line to know.} e4 $1 {We have no other move, otherwise we just lose a pawn or our structure will be very bad.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Re1e4]} f5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4] Again, we have no choice but to protect the pawn on [e4].} 10. Bg5 (10. c4 {This is also possible, but not dangerous for Black at all.} O-O 11. c5 exf3 12. Qb3+ Rf7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Qxf3 Nd5 {After massive exchanges we arrived at an equal position.}) 10... Qd7 ({Apparently} 10... Be7 {is also fine for Black, and it 'only' involves a pawn sacrifice. Still, after the text move, it is very easy to go wrong with either side. It also is somewhat more forcing, so it should be easier to remember the lines.}) 11. c4 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gc4c5,Yd5c6,Rc5b6,Rc5d6] White has now 2 different ways to attack our pieces and potentially win material.} (11. d5 $4 {This is just a blunder, the d-pawn is not protected because of a small tactical trick.} h6 $1 {Not so important, just a small finesse from the engine.} 12. Bh4 Nxd5 {∓ This is the key move. 🙂 White can't recapture, because of ...[Bxh2]+.}) 11... O-O $1 {[%cal Re4f3] By going out from the pin, we are threatening to take the [f3]-knight.} 12. c5 $1 {[%cal Rc5b6,Rc5d6] The chaos starts. 🙂 It is really tough to navigate such positions without the help of the machine I refer to analyses, don't use it in your games!. 🙂} (12. d5 $4 {This is still very bad.} exf3 13. Qxf3 Nd4 $1 {-+ And Black remains a piece up.}) 12... exf3 13. cxb6 {[%cal Yd4d5,Rd5c6] It is much more critical to take here, since now if Black recaptures, the [d5]-threat would still be there.} h6 $1 {Forcing White's bishop to a worse square, or we can just take it on the next move.} 14. d5 hxg5 15. dxc6 bxc6 {A very forcing line, and it looks just great for Black, but White has a strong move now.} 16. Qxf3 $1 {[%cal Rb5c6] Otherwise White would be in trouble.} (16. Bc4+ Kh7 17. Qxf3 g4 {∓ And Black is just much better with the pair of bishops and soon extra pawn.}) 16... cxb5 $1 {We don't have a choice here, our king is in danger, so we have to sacrifice an exchange.} (16... Bb7 $4 17. Bc4+ Kh7 18. Qh5# {is not good.}) 17. Qxa8 cxb6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8b7]} ({Instead} 17... c6 {is also fine for Black, but the text is easier to remember and play. Materially speaking we are not doing too bad, with having the pair of bishops and a pawn for being down an exchange, and White's queen is also in danger currently.}) 18. Qd5+ ({•} 18. Nc3 $4 {Loses the game and the queen on the spot.} Bb7 $1 19. Qxa7 Qc6 20. f3 Ra8 {-+}) ({•} 18. Qf3 $6 {Too slow, Black can develop the initiative easily.} Bb7 19. Qb3+ Kh7 20. Qh3+ Kg6 {The king is very safe on [g6]!} 21. Nd2 g4 22. Qh4 Re8 $1 {⩱ An excellent move. Now Black not only has the ...[Qc6] threat, but in case of a trade, the queen can also enter White's position on the e-file.}) 18... Kh7 {[%cal Rd6h2] White has to address the ... [Bxh2]+ threat.} 19. Rd1 (19. Nc3 $4 {is losing material.} b4 20. Rad1 Rd8 {-+}) 19... Rf6 {[%cal Gf6h6,Rh6h2] The rook is coming to [h6], to attack White's king.} 20. Nc3 Rh6 21. h3 {Looks safer than 21. [g3], which seriously weakens the light squares.} (21. g3 b4 22. Nb5 Bb7 23. Qc4 Ba6 24. Rd5 Bxb5 25. Qxb5 Qxb5 26. Rxb5 Bc5 {Black is winning back the exchange, but the arising rook endgame is just a draw.}) 21... g4 22. Nxb5 (22. Qxb5 Qe7 {∞ Black's attack is very dangerous.}) 22... Bb7 23. Qc4 Ba6 $1 {Winning a tempo for ...[gxh3].} 24. Rd5 gxh3 25. Qd3 Bxb5 26. Qxb5 Qe6 {Black's attack is still very dangerous. White should probably just take the bishop and steer the game towards a drawish endgame.} *

