1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Rb5e8,Gf3e5,Ge1e5] By far the most popular move, White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] The only way to protect the pawn.} 9. d4 {Maximum pressure on the [e5]-pawn!} O-O 10. Bxc6 {White is completely ruining our pawn structure, but what we get in return is the pair of bishops and dynamic potential.} bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5] We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. Nbd2 $6 {[%csl Ge4,Rf3][%cal Gd2e4,Yc8g4,Yg4f3] The knight is going towards [e4], but even if it reaches it, we have ...[Bg4] and an annoying pin on the other knight.} Bg4 {Ne4 doesn't look too tempting anymore, since it allows doubled f-pawns.} 13. Qe2 Bh5 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gb6d5,Ye2c4,Yc4g4] A nice prophylactic move! Black prepares to play ...[Nd5] and then the queen can't hit our bishop with a tempo in the form of [Qc4]. This move also demonstrates that it is not so easy to improve White's position.} 14. Qd3 Nd5 $36 {[%csl Ya1,Yc1,Yd2][%cal Yd5f4,Gg8h8,Gd8f6,Ga8e8] Black has very good play. We can continue with ...[Qf6] and ...[Rae8], and it is still not so easy to mobilise White's queenside.} *

