n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Rb5e8,Gf3e5,Ge1e5] By far the most popular move, White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] The only way to protect the pawn.} 9. d4 {Maximum pressure on the [e5]-pawn!} O-O 10. Bxc6 {White is completely ruining our pawn structure, but what we get in return is the pair of bishops and dynamic potential.} bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5] We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. Ng5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gg5e4,Yc8g4,Yg4d1] This is one of the better moves which White has; they want to blockade the pawn from [e4], and not allowing the ...[Bg4]-pin anymore.} Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4] Black is also controlling the [e4]-square, not making it very easy for White to occupy it.} 13. Nc3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gg5e4,Gc3e4] Nge4 is available again, since White can recapture with the knight.} ({•} 13. Ne4 $4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 Bc5 $1 {-+ White is losing the game on [f2]!}) ({•} 13. Qe2 Nd5 14. Ne4 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Bc5 $1 {Again the [f2]-square is the problem!} 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Rb8 {Black is very active and White's structure also got worse.}) 13... Bb4 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rb4e1] Stopping [Ne4]!} 14. Qe2 Bxc3 {Ruining White's structure.} 15. bxc3 h6 16. Ne4 Qd5 $10 {[%csl Ya2,Yc2,Yc3,Gd5,Ye5,Gf5][%cal Ga8d8] White's queenside is at least as vulnerable as the [e5]-pawn, which gives Black decent counterchances.} *

