n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Rb5e8,Gf3e5,Ge1e5] By far the most popular move, White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] The only way to protect the pawn.} 9. d4 {Maximum pressure on the [e5]-pawn!} O-O 10. Bxc6 {White is completely ruining our pawn structure, but what we get in return is the pair of bishops and dynamic potential.} bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5] We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. Bg5 {Probably White's most serious try for an advantage, first bringing out the bishop and only then trying to blockade on [e4].} Qe8 {[%cal Ye8g6,Yg6h5] In this type of structure the queen have nice squares on [g6] or [h5], putting pressure on White's queenside.} 13. Nbd2 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 $1 {Normally we don't want to give up this bishop so easily, but now we can follow-up with ...[e4]!} 15. Nxf3 e4 {[%cal Ye8e5,Re5g5,Re5h2] If the knight moves anywhere, the queen comes to [e5] and Black is winning material.} 16. Bh4 (16. Qd4 Rxf3 $1 17. gxf3 Qg6 18. h4 h6 19. Qxe4 Qxe4 20. Rxe4 hxg5 21. hxg5 Rf8 {∓ Because of White's poor structure on the kingside, Black has a serious edge with the minor pieces.}) 16... Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5f4] The knight is coming closer to White's king.} 17. Qd4 $1 {Only move to save the game for White.} Rxf3 18. gxf3 Qg6+ 19. Kf1 (19. Kh1 $4 {loses to} Qe6 {-+}) 19... Nf4 20. Bg3 Qf5 $10 (20... Qf5 {It looks scary, but unfortunately we only have a perpetual check.} 21. Bxf4 Qxh3+ 22. Ke2 {(22.Kg1?? Bxf4 -+ ... [Bh2]+ followed by ...[Be5]+ will win the queen. )} Qxf3+ 23. Kf1 Qh3+ 24. Ke2 Qf3+) *

