n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Re1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Rb5e8,Gf3e5,Ge1e5] By far the most popular move, White is bringing a new piece to attack the [e5]-pawn.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] The only way to protect the pawn.} 9. d4 {Maximum pressure on the [e5]-pawn!} O-O 10. Bxc6 {White is completely ruining our pawn structure, but what we get in return is the pair of bishops and dynamic potential.} bxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ye5] We are not going to win any type of beauty award with our pawn structure, but if we can activate our pieces, maybe we can win in an ugly way. 🙂} 12. Bg5 {Probably White's most serious try for an advantage, first bringing out the bishop and only then trying to blockade on [e4].} Qe8 {[%cal Ye8g6,Yg6h5] In this type of structure the queen have nice squares on [g6] or [h5], putting pressure on White's queenside.} 13. Bh4 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gh4g3] White has to bring the bishop to [g3], where it will attack the [e5]-pawn, and much more importantly, defend the king.} (13. h3 $2 {A very bad move, gives a target for the [c8]-bishop.} Qg6 $1 {Both ... [e4], ...[h6] and ...[Rxf3] is a threat, so White is already losing material.} 14. Nbd2 h6 15. Bh4 Bxh3 16. Bg3 Bg4 {∓}) 13... Bg4 14. Nbd2 Qg6 {[%cal Ya8e8,Ye5e4] We are making our usual aggressive moves.} 15. Bg3 Rad8 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Yd8d1]} (15... Rae8 {is equally good according to the engine, but I prefer to set up an X-ray with the rook.}) 16. Re4 {The rook looks strange on [e4], this wasn't White's original plan.} ({•} 16. Bxe5 $4 {It is not working.} Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxd1 19. Nxg6 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 hxg6 {-+ This is just a piece for Black.}) ({•} 16. c3 Bxf3 {As we have seen previously, we only take like this, if we can follow it up with ...[e4]!} 17. Nxf3 e4 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Nd4 Nd5 {∞ We can play for ...[e3] now, in order to destabilise the bishop on [g3].}) 16... Bxf3 {Now we can't play ...[e4] in the next move, but White's structure is getting spoiled.} 17. gxf3 Nd5 $13 {[%cal Gg8h8,Yd5f6,Yd5f4] With a very unclear game, but Black's position with the safer king should be at least easier to play in a practical game.} *

