n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 9. Nxe5 {According to the machine, this is White's main try for an objective advantage against the 4...[d5] variation. It is hard to argue with it, but the good thing is that it is very far from common knowledge at this point.} (9. Re1 f6 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 fxe5 {transposes to 8. [d4] lines.}) 9... Bxe5 10. Re1 Qe7 {Only 11 games have reached this position so far, and here both 'normal' continuations are quite okay for Black.} 11. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4e5] Fantastic move, but without knowing this, not many people can find it, I guess. 🙂 The point is the White wants to take our dark-squared bishop, which was not possible in the lines after the immediate [f4].} O-O 12. f4 (12. d4 {Only can lead to problems for White.} Rd8 13. Qd3 Qh4 14. Rxe5 f6 15. Re4 Qxf2 {⇆ Black has good counterplay.}) 12... f6 {[%cal Gf6e5,Yf8f2] Not only we don't want to lose a pawn, but we also want the f-file open.} 13. fxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ge4,Ye5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] So, finally we have our normal structure 🙂 In this line it is not so easy to find enough play for it, because White has a relatively easy way to reach the [e4]-square with their knight.} 14. Nd2 {This line can obviously transpose to 14. [Nc3] if White would go to [e4] with the knight, but our opponent can also try to attack the [e5]-pawn right away.} Nd5 {We need the knight in the game, as usual.} 15. Nc4 (15. Nf3 $2 {It is not good to attack the pawn from this square.} Bg4 $1 {⩱}) 15... Rf5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf5e5,Ya8f8] An unusual way to protect the pawn on [e5], but we are preparing to bring the other rook to [f8], so it is fine.} 16. b3 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2e5] The bishop is joining to the attack of the [e5]-pawn.} (16. Bd2 Ba6 $1 17. Ne3 {(17.b3 Raf8 18.Re2 Qf6= ∞ Black has excellent pressure. )} Nxe3 18. Bxe3 Raf8 {We can continue with ...[c5] and [Bb7], and we are certainly not worse.}) 16... Bb7 {[%cal Yc6c5,Gb7g2] Right now the bishop is not looking good, but if once we can play ...[c5], it can become a beast in the long diagonal.} 17. Bb2 Raf8 {We couldn't protect the [e5]-pawn anymore, so we are trying to find play on the f-file.} 18. Rxe5 $1 {White should take like this and trade a pair of rooks, to lessen the pressure on their position.} Qg5 19. Rxf5 Qxf5 {[%cal Gc6c5,Yd5f4,Rb7g2] Our next move is ...[c5] and organise an attack against the [g2]-pawn.} 20. Qg1 (20. Qf3 {This is safe for White, but they are not better in this endgame.} Qxf3 21. gxf3 Rxf3) 20... Nf4 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 21. Qxa7 Nxd3 $1 {Securing the draw for Black.} 22. cxd3 c5 $10 {[%cal Rb7g2,Rf5f1]} (22... c5 {The key. Besides the back-rank checkmate, ...Bxg2+ is the threat with a perpetual check.} 23. Rg1 Bxg2+ 24. Rxg2 Qf1+ 25. Rg1 Qf3+) *

