1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4] This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. d3 d5 $5 {The most direct move of the position, with which we are dictating the direction of the game. It certainly won't be a slow fight!Of course things will not be easy, because in this case everyone would play like that. Normally the Italian's goal is to play for ...[d5] after long maneuvers and waiting for the right moment, and if Black could do it right away without any problems, then the Italian would not be a good opening. 🙂} 5. exd5 Nxd5 {We have already arrived at one of the critical positions in the line. It is quite rare for this to happen at move 5 in any opening, especially if we are talking about the Italian Game. 🙂 The key factor in the position is the [e5]- pawn. From it derive the advantages and disadvantages for us. Obviously, since the e-file has just become half-open, it can and should be a target for White. On the other hand, if in the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 9. Nxe5 {According to the machine, this is White's main try for an objective advantage against the 4...[d5] variation. It is hard to argue with it, but the good thing is that it is very far from common knowledge at this point.} (9. Re1 f6 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 fxe5 {transposes to 8. [d4] lines.}) 9... Bxe5 10. Re1 Qe7 {Only 11 games have reached this position so far, and here both 'normal' continuations are quite okay for Black.} 11. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4e5] Fantastic move, but without knowing this, not many people can find it, I guess. 🙂 The point is the White wants to take our dark-squared bishop, which was not possible in the lines after the immediate [f4].} O-O 12. f4 (12. d4 {Only can lead to problems for White.} Rd8 13. Qd3 Qh4 14. Rxe5 f6 15. Re4 Qxf2 {⇆ Black has good counterplay.}) 12... f6 {[%cal Gf6e5,Yf8f2] Not only we don't want to lose a pawn, but we also want the f-file open.} 13. fxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ge4,Ye5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] So, finally we have our normal structure 🙂 In this line it is not so easy to find enough play for it, because White has a relatively easy way to reach the [e4]-square with their knight.} 14. Be3 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4,Ge3f2] A very decent developing move, White is also controlling the [f2] potential entry square.} c5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7g2,Yc5c4] Not only opening up the long diagonal for our bishop, but sometimes we can also play ...[c4] and get rid of one of our weaknesses.} 15. b3 $1 {[%cal Gb3c4]} Nd5 {Bring the knight back into play, before [Nc3].} 16. Qd2 {Preparing [Nc3].} Bb7 17. Nc3 {Now Black must decide which minor piece to take, but it is not that difficult, since the [e3] bishop puts strong pressure on the [c5] pawn and also covers the [f2] square.} Nxe3 18. Qxe3 {White is pressing a little bit, but Black should hold with correct play.} Qh4 {Seeking for counterplay on the [f2]-square.} 19. Kg1 {Probably the most serious attempt on White's part. The king covers the [f2] square and also prepares against back rank problems in the upcoming endgame.} ({•} 19. Qxe5 {Leads to an immediate draw.} Bxg2+ $1 20. Kxg2 Qf2+ 21. Kh1 Qf3+ 22. Kg1 Qf2+ {With perpetual check.}) ({•} 19. Qxc5 {The other pawn grab is also a draw.} Bxg2+ {.} 20. Kxg2 {Qg4+ 21.Kh1 Qf3+ 22.Kg1 Qg4+= Perpetual check.}) ({•} 19. Ne4 {If Black can get active in the heavy piece endgame, then there is not much to worry about.} Bxe4 $1 20. Qxe4 Qxe4 21. Rxe4 Rf2 {Here it is!} 22. Rc4 e4 $1 {Trying to open the way for the other rook.} 23. Kg1 Raf8 24. dxe4 Re2 25. Rxc5 Rff2 {Black will easily make a draw here.}) ({•} 19. Re2 {White covers the [f2]-square and is ready to take the pawns on [c5] and [e5].} Qd4 $1 {It is a must, but it works!} 20. Qxe5 {(20.Qxd4 exd4 21.Na4 Rae8 There is no [Rae1] now, since White has issues with the back rank. That's why 19. [Kg1] is the main line. 22.Rxe8 Rxe8 23.Nxc5 Bc6= ∞ The rook is coming to [e2] in the next move, Black is completely fine. )} Qxe5 21. Rxe5 Rf2 {Black is winning back the pawn.} 22. Re2 Bxg2+ 23. Kg1 Rxe2 24. Nxe2 Re8 {White has the better structure, but the rook+bishop is stronger than the rook+knight, so overall it is around equal.}) 19... Rf6 {With the plan of ...[Raf8] and ...[Rf2].} 20. Re2 {[%cal Re3e5,Re3c5] Threatening the pawns on [e5] and [c5], since there is no ...[Qf2] or ...[Bxg2] anymore.} Qd4 {The only move to keep the material balance.} 21. Qxd4 cxd4 {Very important! In the 19. [Re2] lines Black could take on [d4] with the e-pawn, only because of White's weak back rank!} (21... exd4 $2 22. Na4 Rf5 23. Rf1 {+- Black has only weak pawns and no counterplay.}) 22. Na4 Rc6 {[%cal Rc6c2] The attack on [c2] indirectly defends the [e5]-pawn.} 23. b4 {[%cal Ga4c5] The knight is coming to [c5] and that could easily be a lost endgame for Black, because the c-file will be blocked and White can take the pawn on [e5].} (23. Rc1 Re8 {Black has counterplay with ...[e4].}) 23... e4 {This excellent move gives Black equality.} 24. dxe4 (24. Nc5 Rb6 25. Nxe4 Rxb4 {Black should hold without major problems.}) 24... a5 {Active play!} 25. b5 (25. Nc5 axb4 $1 26. Nxb7 Ra7 {Traps the knight and leads to a very drawish endgame.}) 25... Rc4 26. Nb2 Rb4 $10 {[%cal Rb4b5,Rb4b2] Black is catching up with the material and will have a nice endgame. This line has had more coverage because of the clash with another Chessable course. So, it's just to show that it is theoretically sound. However, there is no need to worry about being in these endgames too often.🙂} *

