Only can lead to problems for White.} Rd8 13. Qd3 Qh4 14. Rxe5 f6 15. Re4 Qxf2 {⇆ Black has good counterplay.}) 12... f6 {[%cal Gf6e5,Yf8f2] Not only we don't want to lose a pawn, but we also want the f-file open.} 13. fxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ge4,Ye5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] So, finally we have our normal structure 🙂 In this line it is not so easy to find enough play for it, because White has a relatively easy way to reach the [e4]-square with their knight.} 14. Be3 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4,Ge3f2] A very decent developing move, White is also controlling the [f2] potential entry square.} c5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7g2,Yc5c4] Not only opening up the long diagonal for our bishop, but sometimes we can also play ...[c4] and get rid of one of our weaknesses.} 15. Nd2 Nd5 16. Bg1 c4 $1 {A very nice pawn sacrifice, with the point of weakening White's control over the [e4]-square and the long diagonal.} 17. Nxc4 Nf4 18. Nd2 (18. Rxe5 $2 Bb7 $1 {And Black is already better.}) 18... h5 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8b7] With threats from both sides, Black has interesting play for the pawn.} *

