n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 9. Nxe5 {According to the machine, this is White's main try for an objective advantage against the 4...[d5] variation. It is hard to argue with it, but the good thing is that it is very far from common knowledge at this point.} (9. Re1 f6 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 fxe5 {transposes to 8. [d4] lines.}) 9... Bxe5 10. Re1 Qe7 {Only 11 games have reached this position so far, and here both 'normal' continuations are quite okay for Black.} 11. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4e5] Fantastic move, but without knowing this, not many people can find it, I guess. 🙂 The point is the White wants to take our dark-squared bishop, which was not possible in the lines after the immediate [f4].} O-O 12. f4 (12. d4 {