n the next 5-10 moves nothing happens with that pawn, it can give us a space advantage in the center and better chances in the long run. From this moment a direct confrontation begins and we have to be very precise, but so does White!} 6. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5] By far the most common and best move. White is getting their king to safety and is getting ready to attack our [e5]-pawn with [Re1].} Nb6 $5 {[%cal Rb6c4,Yc4b5,Yc4b3]} ({This is only the fourth most popular move, but I believe that it is the one that may give Black the best chances of fighting for more than equality in many lines.At the highest level,} 6... Be7 {is the main move, but many lines basically lead to an endgame in which Black tries to hold the draw. With the text move, we force White to make a decision: he can keep the [f7]-pawn under attack, but in this case it will be easier for us to protect [e5], since we no longer have to worry about any [Bb5] ideas. Or, he can play [Bb5] immediately, but this will take the pressure off of the [f7] pawn.}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Rf3e5] This should be the critical test of our line. White is immediately putting more pressure on the [e5]-pawn.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] We have to castle quickly and get rid of the annoying pin on our knight.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 9. Nxe5 {According to the machine, this is White's main try for an objective advantage against the 4...[d5] variation. It is hard to argue with it, but the good thing is that it is very far from common knowledge at this point.} (9. Re1 f6 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 fxe5 {transposes to 8. [d4] lines.}) 9... Bxe5 10. Re1 Qe7 {Only 11 games have reached this position so far, and here both 'normal' continuations are quite okay for Black.} 11. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4e5] Fantastic move, but without knowing this, not many people can find it, I guess. 🙂 The point is the White wants to take our dark-squared bishop, which was not possible in the lines after the immediate [f4].} O-O 12. f4 (12. d4 {Only can lead to problems for White.} Rd8 13. Qd3 Qh4 14. Rxe5 f6 15. Re4 Qxf2 {⇆ Black has good counterplay.}) 12... f6 {[%cal Gf6e5,Yf8f2] Not only we don't want to lose a pawn, but we also want the f-file open.} 13. fxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6,Yc7,Ge4,Ye5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] So, finally we have our normal structure 🙂 In this line it is not so easy to find enough play for it, because White has a relatively easy way to reach the [e4]-square with their knight.} 14. Nc3 Nd5 {Our knight was doing nothing on [b6], so it is better to have it on [d5].} 15. Ne4 Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yf5e4] White has achieved a nice blockade, but we are immediately challenging it and very possibly take the knight in the near future.} 16. Bg5 ({•} 16. Ng3 {Black shouldn't be too worried when the knight moves, since it gives up the control over the [f2] entry square.} Bg6 17. Qe2 Qc5 {Black wants to play ...[Rf2] next with good counterplay.}) ({•} 16. Qe2 Bxe4 $1 {Forcing White to either spoil their superior structure, or to allow the rook on [f2].} 17. dxe4 {(17.Qxe4 Rf2= Black is completely fine with such an active rook on the 2nd rank. )} Nf4 18. Qc4+ Qe6 {The doubled c-pawns only provide a symbolic edge for White, since the bishop can't really attack those pawns. ( 18.Bxf4 Even though White can win a pawn with this move, Black should have no problems in the heavy piece endgame. 18...exf4 19.Qc4+ Kh8 20.Qxc6 Qe5!= ∞ Attacking [b2] and also threatening [f3], Black should be completely fine here. )}) 16... Qb4 {[%cal Rb4b2] Trying to create some targets on the queenside.} 17. b3 Qd4 18. Rc1 Bxe4 $1 {The right moment to take on [e4]!} 19. dxe4 (19. Rxe4 $4 {Looks very strong, but loses to} Nc3 $1 20. Rxd4 Nxd1 {-+ The rook is hanging and ...[Rf1] is also a threat.}) 19... Qxd1 20. Rcxd1 Nc3 21. Rd7 {So far we have been following the only game which has been played in this line, So-Mamedyarov, chess.com 2022. And here instead of taking on [e4], Black can just play ...[Nxa2].} Nxa2 22. Rxc7 Nb4 $10 {[%cal Rb4c2,Ya7a5,Ya5a4,Gf8f7] And the position is equal; even our structure is only a little bit worse now. 🙂} *

