[PlyCount "28"]
[GameId "2160376123342948"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me, the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by computer evaluation. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. d3 ({White's only alternative to} 6. Bb5+ {. The point is that it is still not possible to take on [d5].}) 6... h6 {[%csl Rg5] Sending back the knight to a more passive square.} (6... Nxd5 $4 7. Qf3 $1 {+-}) 7. Nf3 e4 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Re4f3,Yd3e4,Ya5c4] One more tempo on the knight, since the [d3]-pawn has to protect the bishop on [c4], it can't take on [e4].} 8. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4,Ye4][%cal Re2e8,Ge2c4] White is not only pinning the pawn and therefore protecting the knight, but the queen is also protecting the bishop after [dxe4], so we can't wait and protect on [e4], but have to react.} ({•} 8. dxe4 $2 {Nevertheless, some players tried to prove that White has enough for the piece here.} Nxc4 9. Qd4 Nb6 10. c4 Nbd7 {White's center is really impressive, but we have an extra bishop. 🙂} 11. e5 Bc5 {Black wins a nice tempo!} 12. Qf4 g5 {It attacks White's queen, but it is mainly directed against the center.} 13. Qf5 {Moving the queen to [d2] and [g3] could be met by ...[Ne4]!} g4 {Chasing away the knight, so the e-pawn will be weaker.} 14. Nh4 (14. exf6 gxf3 {-+ White loses the [f6]-pawn on the next move.}) 14... Qe7 {-+} 15. Bf4 Nh5 $1 16. Qxh5 Nf6 $1 {Black is trapping the queen, so White has nothing better than} 17. Nf5 Nxh5 18. Nxe7 Nxf4 19. Nxc8 Nxg2+ 20. Kf1 Nf4 {-+ Black takes on [c8] next, with a completely winning position.}) ({•} 8. Nd4 {Black can easily regain the material against this move, and keep the lead in the development.} Bc5 9. c3 O-O 10. O-O exd3 11. Bxd3 Qxd5 {⩱ ( 11.Qxd3?! This is even worse, since White is losing the bishop pair. 11...Nxc4 12.Qxc4 Qxd5 ∓ Black has the bishop pair in an open position. )}) 8... Nxc4 {Black is getting the pair of bishops and the lead in the development for a pawn.} 9. dxc4 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc5d4,Rf3d4] The bishop is very active on [c5] and very importantly it doesn't allow White's knight to jump to [d4].} 10. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4,Yh3g4,Gf3h2,Gc1f4] ...[Bg4] is often an unpleasant move for White with the pawn on [e4], so they are preventing this option. Also, the knight can retreat to [h2], with the idea of not blocking the bishop's diagonal from [d2].} O-O {[%cal Re4f3] The pin is over, the knight is hanging!} 11. Nh2 {[%csl Re1,Yh2] White is behind in development and the king is still in the centre, therefore it is time for Black to open the position.} (11. Nfd2 $2 {Doesn't make much sense here.} e3 $1 12. fxe3 Bxe3 {-+ White is in big trouble, since they can't castle.}) 11... c6 $1 {[%csl Gd5] First, we are undermining White's strong central pawn.} 12. dxc6 e3 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Re8e1,Rd8d1] The [c6]-pawn doesn't matter; we have to open more files!} 13. Bxe3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Ne4 $17 {[%cal Re4g3,Rd8h4] With threats like ...[Qh4]+ or ...[Ng3], White is in serious trouble.} *

