ry active on [c5] and very importantly it doesn't allow White's knight to jump to [d4].} 10. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4,Yc3d4] White wants to put the knight on [d4].} b5 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Yc4,Yd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4,Gc3b5] Black is undermining White's centre and opening the position for the bishops. Now you can see that White wouldn't mind a knight on [c3] instead of a pawn.} 11. b4 (11. cxb5 O-O 12. Nd4 Nxd5 13. O-O Re8 {∓ Black has excellent play. We can try to make the position more open by playing ...[a6] in the near future, but placing our queen on [h4] and going for an attack against the king is also very tempting.}) 11... O-O $1 12. bxc5 Bg4 $17 {[%csl Yc4,Yc5,Yd5][%cal Rb5c4,Re4f3,Gf8e8] White is in a lot of trouble. Black will not only take back the material on [f3], but with that will also spoil White's kingside structure. White's centre is not very stable either.} *

