ifficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. d3 ({White's only alternative to} 6. Bb5+ {. The point is that it is still not possible to take on [d5].}) 6... h6 {[%csl Rg5] Sending back the knight to a more passive square.} (6... Nxd5 $4 7. Qf3 $1 {+-}) 7. Nf3 e4 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Re4f3,Yd3e4,Ya5c4] One more tempo on the knight, since the [d3]-pawn has to protect the bishop on [c4], it can't take on [e4].} 8. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4,Ye4][%cal Re2e8,Ge2c4] White is not only pinning the pawn and therefore protecting the knight, but the queen is also protecting the bishop after [dxe4], so we can't wait and protect on [e4], but have to react.} ({•} 8. dxe4 $2 {Nevertheless, some players tried to prove that White has enough for the piece here.} Nxc4 9. Qd4 Nb6 10. c4 Nbd7 {White's center is really impressive, but we have an extra bishop. 🙂} 11. e5 Bc5 {Black wins a nice tempo!} 12. Qf4 g5 {It attacks White's queen, but it is mainly directed against the center.} 13. Qf5 {Moving the queen to [d2] and [g3] could be met by ...[Ne4]!} g4 {Chasing away the knight, so the e-pawn will be weaker.} 14. Nh4 (14. exf6 gxf3 {-+ White loses the [f6]-pawn on the next move.}) 14... Qe7 {-+} 15. Bf4 Nh5 $1 16. Qxh5 Nf6 $1 {Black is trapping the queen, so White has nothing better than} 17. Nf5 Nxh5 18. Nxe7 Nxf4 19. Nxc8 Nxg2+ 20. Kf1 Nf4 {-+ Black takes on [c8] next, with a completely winning position.}) ({•} 8. Nd4 {Black can easily regain the material against this move, and keep the lead in the development.} Bc5 9. c3 O-O 10. O-O exd3 11. Bxd3 Qxd5 {⩱ ( 11.Qxd3?! This is even worse, since White is losing the bishop pair. 11...Nxc4 12.Qxc4 Qxd5 ∓ Black has the bishop pair in an open position. )}) 8... Nxc4 {Black is getting the pair of bishops and the lead in the development for a pawn.} 9. dxc4 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc5d4,Rf3d4] The bishop is very active on [c5] and very importantly it doesn't allow White's knight to jump to [d4].} 10. Nfd2 O-O 11. Nb3 {[%cal Gc1f4] It is good to include this move as soon as possible, in order to open up the diagonal for the bishop and stop [e3]-ideas from Black.} Bg4 $1 {Very important! The queen's only good square is [f1], but it will make short castle impossible for quite a few moves.} 12. Qf1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ge1g1]} (12. Qd2 $4 {Going into} e3 $1 {will lead to a quick loss for White.} 13. fxe3 Ne4 14. Qd3 Bb4+ {+ -+ Next is ...[Qh4]+, winning a lot of material.}) 12... Bb4+ $1 {Another very important move. Black is going away from the attack with a tempo, and if White doesn't want to lose time, then they have to play [c3] and take away that square from the knight.} 13. c3 ({•} 13. Bd2 $2 Bxd2+ 14. N1xd2 Re8 {∓ With ...[e3] coming in the next move, Black is much better. ( • 13.Nc3 c6! ⩱ White is under big pressure. )}) 13... Be7 {[%csl Rd5,Ge7][%cal Rb1c3,Ge7f6,Yf6d7,Yd7e5,Yb7b5,Yd8d5] Looks somewhat surprising to put the bishop on [e7], but the point is that White is not going to castle short, so the bishop's role on [d6] would be limited. It can be more useful from [f6], and also it allows the queen to keep attacking [d5], making ...[b5]-ideas stronger.} 14. h3 Bh5 {[%cal Rh5d1] If White wants to castle long, they have to weaken themselves more.} 15. g4 Bg6 {[%csl Rd3,Rf3][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] The knight has very nice targets on [d3] and [f3].} 16. Be3 Nd7 17. N1d2 Ne5 18. O-O-O {White just managed to castle before ...[Nd3]+, but the position remains very difficult.} b5 $40 {[%cal Ge5d3,Ga8b8,Ge7f6]} (18... b5 {Black has excellent play. The only positive thing for White is the extra pawn, but even the computer is not impressed with that. One possible line is} 19. Nd4 Nd3+ {The knight on [d3] is very unpleasant for White.} 20. Kb1 bxc4 21. Nc6 Qd7 22. Nxc4 Bf6 {The [d5]-pawn is hanging and White doesn't really have any counterplay.} 23. f4 {White is trying to do something, but it opens the [g6]-bishop.} exf3 24. Rxd3 Qxd5 {Both knights and the rook are hanging!} 25. N4e5 Be4 26. Ka1 Qe6 27. Bf4 f2 {-+ Black is not taking anything, just attacking everything in White's position. 🙂}) *

