sl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gh3g1,Gg1f3] White controls the [e4]-square, opens the diagonal for the bishop, and also prepares [Ng1]-[f3], since Black's ...[e4] is not dangerous anymore.} (10. O-O $4 g4 {-+}) 10... Qb6 ({(After 10 moves, we are already in unexplored territory 1 OTB game! Pretty much everyone plays)} 10... Bg7 {in this position, but keeping the option of playing with ...[g4] and then ...[Bc5] could become the new main line in one day. 🙂In any case, bringing the queen to attack on [f2] and [b2] can't be too bad.}) 11. Nc3 {White wants to develop and this move is also very useful against ...[Bc5], because of [Na4]-threats.} Nb7 {[%csl Ya5,Gb7][%cal Gb7d6,Gb7c5] Since the aggressive ...[g4] doesn't work, we just slightly improve our position, while keeping the option of playing ...[Bc5] at some moment. Therefore, the usual route for that knight ...[c5]-...[Nc6] is changed. Obviously, the move looks very slow for a position where we are down a pawn, but we already have decent positional compensation with space advantage in the centre, with White's knight being an issue on [h3], and our opponent still has to develop somehow on the queenside.} 12. Ne4 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Ge1g1,Yg5g4] White wants to trade off our pieces that are supporting ...[g4], and doing so allows them to prepare to castle short.} Nxe4 13. dxe4 {[%csl Gd1,Ge2][%cal Ge1g1,Yg5g4,Ge2g4,Gd1g4] Now White wants to castle, since ...[g4] is not trapping the knight anymore, because it can be just taken.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8d8,Rd8d1] And Black has an excellent position with ...[Rd8] coming. It is important that White can't play 14. [O-O], let's see why.} 14. O-O $4 Rd8 $1 15. Qe1 g4 $19 {[%csl Rh3] Black is winning the knight.} *

