sl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gh3g1,Gg1f3] White controls the [e4]-square, opens the diagonal for the bishop, and also prepares [Ng1]-[f3], since Black's ...[e4] is not dangerous anymore.} (10. O-O $4 g4 {-+}) 10... Qb6 ({(After 10 moves, we are already in unexplored territory 1 OTB game! Pretty much everyone plays)} 10... Bg7 {in this position, but keeping the option of playing with ...[g4] and then ...[Bc5] could become the new main line in one day. 🙂In any case, bringing the queen to attack on [f2] and [b2] can't be too bad.}) 11. Nc3 {White wants to develop and this move is also very useful against ...[Bc5], because of [Na4]-threats.} Nb7 $10 {[%csl Ya5,Gb7][%cal Gb7d6,Gb7c5] Since the aggressive ...[g4] doesn't work, we just slightly improve our position, while keeping the option of playing ...[Bc5] at some moment. Therefore, the usual route for that knight ...[c5]-...[Nc6] is changed. Obviously, the move looks very slow for a position where we are down a pawn, but we already have decent positional compensation with space advantage in the centre, with White's knight being an issue on [h3], and our opponent still has to develop somehow on the queenside.} 12. Bd2 {White is offering us to win a pawn in two different ways, but either way we would completely give up the pressure. Thus, it is better not to do so.} Be6 {A very similar move to ...[Nb7]. Black is just developing normally and is still waiting for White to show what they want, since it is not clear what exactly [Bd2] does.} ({•} 12... g4 $6 13. Ng1 Bc5 14. Na4 $1 Bxf2+ 15. Kf1 Qd8 16. Kxf2 Qd4+ 17. Ke1 Qxa4 18. c4 {⩲ White is better with the pair of bishops and many weaknesses in our position.}) ({•} 12... Qxb2 $6 13. Rb1 Qa3 14. Ng1 {⩲ With [Nf3] and [O-O] coming, it is White's position that will appear normal first. 🙂}) 13. Ng1 {Leads to a decent version for both sides of the ...[Bc5], [Na4] lines.} Bc5 14. Na4 Bxf2+ 15. Kf1 Qd8 16. Kxf2 Qd4+ 17. Kf1 Qxa4 $132 {[%csl Gf1,Gg5,Gh6][%cal Ge8c8] The position is very unclear, with decent chances and many possibilities for both sides.} *

