sl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Gh3g1,Gg1f3] White controls the [e4]-square, opens the diagonal for the bishop, and also prepares [Ng1]-[f3], since Black's ...[e4] is not dangerous anymore.} (10. O-O $4 g4 {-+}) 10... Qb6 ({(After 10 moves, we are already in unexplored territory 1 OTB game! Pretty much everyone plays)} 10... Bg7 {in this position, but keeping the option of playing with ...[g4] and then ...[Bc5] could become the new main line in one day. 🙂In any case, bringing the queen to attack on [f2] and [b2] can't be too bad.}) 11. Nc3 {White wants to develop and this move is also very useful against ...[Bc5], because of [Na4]-threats.} Nb7 {[%csl Ya5,Gb7][%cal Gb7d6,Gb7c5] Since the aggressive ...[g4] doesn't work, we just slightly improve our position, while keeping the option of playing ...[Bc5] at some moment. Therefore, the usual route for that knight ...[c5]-...[Nc6] is changed. Obviously, the move looks very slow for a position where we are down a pawn, but we already have decent positional compensation with space advantage in the centre, with White's knight being an issue on [h3], and our opponent still has to develop somehow on the queenside.} 12. Rb1 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb1b2,Gc1e3] Looks like a pretty human move, protecting on [b2] and preparing to play [Be3], in order to solve the problem of the [f2]-pawn as well.} Be6 {[%csl Ra2] The most flexible developing move, and White sometimes can have problems with the [a2]-pawn as well.} (12... g4 {We can't win a pawn like this anymore, because of} 13. Be3 $1) 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Ng1 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1] Finally White can bring the knight to [f3] and then castle.} Bg7 15. Nf3 (15. h4 $6 {Would be too ambitious, since after} g4 $1 {White again has serious problems with developing on the kingside.}) 15... Nd5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Yf7f5] We switched to positional compensation mode, and with so much space, we are doing quite well in that regard.} 16. O-O (16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. c4 d4 18. Bc1 a5 $1 {∞ Securing the [c5]-square for the knight and after castling we can start pushing for ...[f5] and ...[e4].}) 16... O-O 17. Bd2 f5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gg5][%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8,Gb7d6] We can still bring the rooks into the centre, and play ...[Nd6], and then see how can we increase the pressure. It looks very uncomfortable to play this as White, without having a clear way to lessen the pressure or trade pieces.} *

