ifficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the center with the [e5] pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 {This looks like the most natural square for the bishop, so it is not a surprise that this move is the most common in the current position.} h6 $1 {We don't have an alternative at this point; we gave up a pawn for time and development, so we should use it!} 9. Nf3 e4 {[%cal Re4f3] This is the issue with the knight on [f3] —Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d4,Rd4e5,Rd4f2] We have the huge threat of ...[Qd4] now, attacking the knight and [f2] as well.} 11. O-O Qd6 {Continuing to gain time against White's loose knight and also eyeing the [h2]-pawn!} 12. Nc4 $4 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ye2c4,Yf6g4] White loses the control from the [g4]-square with this trade.} Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rc5f2,Rg4f2,Rd6h2,Rg4h2] White already has no defence here.} 14. g3 Nxf2 15. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qd4+ 17. Kg2 Qxc4 $19 {[%csl Rg2] Black is just up an exchange, and White's king remains weak.} *

