1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me, the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by computer evaluation. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the center with the [e5] pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 {This looks like the most natural square for the bishop, so it is not a surprise that this move is the most common in the current position.} h6 $1 {We don't have an alternative at this point; we gave up a pawn for time and development, so we should use it!} 9. Nf3 e4 {[%cal Re4f3] This is the issue with the knight on [f3] —Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d4,Rd4e5,Rd4f2] We have the huge threat of ...[Qd4] now, attacking the knight and [f2] as well.} 11. O-O Qd6 {Continuing to gain time against White's loose knight and also eyeing the [h2]-pawn!} 12. Ng4 $2 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Rd6h2]} Bxg4 $1 13. Bxg4 h5 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yf6g4,Rd6h2] With ...[Ng4] coming next, Black's queen on [d6] is really well-placed.} 14. Be2 Ng4 15. g3 (15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. g3 Qe6 $1 {Black has the time to castle long and then just win the game on the h-file. (16...f5 17.d4! Black is still better, but this is a huge tempo for White, with the bishop covering the [h6]-square. )} 17. d3 O-O-O {-+ White's position is full of weaknesses.}) 15... Nxh2 $1 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Rh5h4,Rh4g3] Once the rook can join, White is in huge trouble.} 16. d4 {[%cal Gc1f4] White opens up the bishop with a tempo, it should help the defence.} (16. Kxh2 Bxf2 $1 17. Rxf2 h4 {-+ Black's attack is decisive.}) 16... exd3 17. Bf4 {White brings the bishop with a tempo, so White is not losing the game on [g3].} Qe6 $1 {[%cal Rd3e2,Rh2f1]} 18. Re1 {It looks like that White is escaping with this move.} O-O-O $1 19. Kxh2 ({•} 19. cxd3 Qh3 {-+ With ...[Ng4] or ...[h4] next, Black is winning.}) ({•} 19. Bxd3 Qxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Nf3+ {+ -+ Black is just up an exchange.}) 19... dxe2 20. Qxe2 Qxe2 21. Rxe2 Rd1 $19 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gd1a1] White didn't get checkmated, but they will lose in the endgame instead.} *

