ifficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the center with the [e5] pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 {This looks like the most natural square for the bishop, so it is not a surprise that this move is the most common in the current position.} h6 $1 {We don't have an alternative at this point; we gave up a pawn for time and development, so we should use it!} 9. Nf3 e4 {[%cal Re4f3] This is the issue with the knight on [f3] —Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d4,Rd4e5,Rd4f2] We have the huge threat of ...[Qd4] now, attacking the knight and [f2] as well.} 11. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4,Rb2b4] White is preventing ...[Qd4] and also introducing the [b4]-idea to the position.} O-O ({Black is doing very well in the main line as well, which is} 11... Bd6 {, but I prefer the text move, which 'prevents' White from going to lines with [f4], since it would be weird to protect a knight which is not hanging and stop [O-O] possibilities.}) 12. d4 $2 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yc2c3] Very suspicious. Once White played [c3], the knight will be not stable at all on [d3].} exd3 13. Nxd3 Bb6 14. O-O Re8 {[%cal Re8e2,Yc8a6,Yc8f5] White has very unpleasant pressure on their position.} 15. Nd2 (15. Bf4 Ba6 $1 {-+ Black is pretty much winning with the threat of ...[Rxe2].}) 15... B