1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some tricky options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me, the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by computer evaluation. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop. Black is also better in the center with the [e5] pawn and has a much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Be2 {This looks like the most natural square for the bishop, so it is not a surprise that this move is the most common in the current position.} h6 $1 {We don't have an alternative at this point; we gave up a pawn for time and development, so we should use it!} 9. Nf3 e4 {[%cal Re4f3] This is the issue with the knight on [f3] —Black can gain more tempi.} 10. Ne5 Bc5 {[%cal Rd8d4,Rd4e5,Rd4f2] We have the huge threat of ...[Qd4] now, attacking the knight and [f2] as well.} 11. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc3d4,Rb2b4] White is preventing ...[Qd4] and also introducing the [b4]-idea to the position.} O-O ({Black is doing very well in the main line as well, which is} 11... Bd6 {, but I prefer the text move, which 'prevents' White from going to lines with [f4], since it would be weird to protect a knight which is not hanging and stop [O-O] possibilities.}) 12. O-O Qc7 $1 (12... Re8 {would be a better move if we look at the lines after} 13. d4 exd3 14. Nxd3 {, but the problem is that it can be met by 13.Nxf7! Kxf7 14.b4! and the position is rather messy.}) 13. d4 ({•} 13. b4 $6 Qxe5 14. bxc5 Be6 {⩱ Black has a nice advantage because of the [e4]-pawn and lot of space. It is tough for White to put their pieces on normal squares.}) ({•} 13. Nxf7 $4 {Now this doesn't work at all.} Rxf7 14. b4 Bd6 15. bxa5 Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 Qf4 {-+ White is getting checkmated.}) 13... exd3 14. Nxd3 Bd6 {[%csl Rh2] Attacking [h2] with tempo is pretty important.} 15. h3 $2 {[%csl Gh2][%cal Yd6h2] It may even look more logical and less weakening than the correct move, which is 15. [g3], but in some lines it allows ...[Bh2]+, which makes it a mistake.} Bf5 16. Nd2 ({•} 16. Qa4 Rfe8 $1 17. Be3 Nd5 {-+ White is losing material.}) ({•} 16. b4 {Trying to solve the problem of the loose [d3]-knight.} Nc4 17. Nc5 Rad8 $1 {...[Bh2]+ is the threat.} 18. Qb3 Na5 $1 19. Qa4 Qe7 {-+ With ... [Qe5] coming, White is close to lost here.}) 16... Rad8 17. b4 (17. Nf3 c5 18. Qa4 Rfe8 19. Be3 Bd7 {-+ Next is ...[Nc4], winning material.}) 17... Bxd3 18. Bxd3 {Here White would be okay, if not for ...[Bh2]!.} (18. bxa5 Bf5 {-+}) 18... Bh2+ $1 19. Kh1 Rxd3 20. bxa5 Bf4 21. Qe2 (21. Qc2 Qd7 {-+ With a double attack on [d2] and [h3].}) 21... Qd7 {[%cal Rd3h3,Rf4d2]} 22. Nf3 Re8 23. Be3 Bxe3 24. fxe3 Ne4 $19 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Ye4g3,Gd7d6] White is losing material.} *

