1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some 'tricky' options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by the computer. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {[%csl Ra8,Gf3][%cal Yf3a8] White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here, there are many continuations with around equal value, I tried to choose one which is more human.} Rb8 {Bringing the rook into play and renewing the threat on the [b5]-bishop.} 9. Bxc6+ $2 {White is taking another pawn, but Black's lead in the development is going to be even more serious and the position is opening up for the bishops.} Nxc6 10. Qxc6+ Nd7 $1 {[%cal Rd8g5] We even win a tempo by blocking the check!} 11. Nf3 Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb6g6] The rook will be great on the 6th rank, and then we can develop the bishop to [b7].} 12. Qe4 (12. Qa4 Rb4 13. Qxa7 {One more pawn, but basically no development for White.} Bc5 14. Qa8 e4 {-+}) 12... Be7 13. O-O Bb7 $17 {[%cal Gb6g6,Ge8g8,Yf7f5] Black is much better. The next move is ...[Rg6], putting serious pressure on the long diagonal, and then after castling we can start pushing the f-pawn.} *

