1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some 'tricky' options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by the computer. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {[%csl Ra8,Gf3][%cal Yf3a8] White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here, there are many continuations with around equal value, I tried to choose one which is more human.} Rb8 {Bringing the rook into play and renewing the threat on the [b5]-bishop.} 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yg5e4,Yd3e4,Gd3f5] This is the main move. In case of a trade on [e4], White wants to take back with the bishop. Also, in general, we already saw that ...[f5] is a very dangerous idea for Black. Thus, the bishop tries to fight against it.} Bd6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rc8g4,Yf3g3,Re5e4,Rd6g3] Besides being a developing move and preparing ...[O-O], the bishop also targets the [g3]-square, highlighting the fact that White's queen doesn't really have a lot of squares to go to.} 10. O-O $2 {[%csl Rg4] White ignores the threat of ...[Bg4].} Bg4 $1 11. Qg3 (11. Qe3 Nd5 $1 12. Qg3 f5 $1 {Even stronger than 12... [Qxg5].} 13. f3 e4 14. Qh4 h6 15. fxg4 O-O $1 {-+ With ...[hxg5] or ...[exd3] coming, Black is much better.}) 11... e4 {[%cal Rd6g3]} 12. Qe3 O-O {[%csl Ge4] Even though it is risky to take on [e4], White doesn't really have an other choice, since the [e4]-pawn takes too much space and controls too many squares.} 13. Nxe4 (13. Bxe4 h6 14. Nf3 Re8 15. d3 Nd5 16. Qd4 Nb4 {∓ c2 is hanging and also ...[f5] is coming, White is in very bad shape.}) 13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {[%cal Re4g4,Re4h7]} (14. Bxe4 Re8 15. h3 Bh5 {-+ ...[f5] is the threat, and if the queen goes to [d3], then ...[Rb4]!}) 14... f5 $1 15. Qe6+ Kh8 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Re6][%cal Gf8e8,Gb8b7] The queen is close to being trapped, and White's pieces decided not to take part in this game.} *

