is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {[%csl Ra8,Gf3][%cal Yf3a8] White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here, there are many continuations with around equal value, I tried to choose one which is more human.} Rb8 {Bringing the rook into play and renewing the threat on the [b5]-bishop.} 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yg5e4,Yd3e4,Gd3f5] This is the main move. In case of a trade on [e4], White wants to take back with the bishop. Also, in general, we already saw that ...[f5] is a very dangerous idea for Black. Thus, the bishop tries to fight against it.} Bd6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rc8g4,Yf3g3,Re5e4,Rd6g3] Besides being a developing move and preparing ...[O-O], the bishop also targets the [g3]-square, highlighting the fact that White's queen doesn't really have a lot of squares to go to.} 10. Nc3 $2 {The most common move in the position, but it already gives a big advantage for Black.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3]} 11. Qg3 {[%cal Rd6g3] It looks extremely risky to put the queen into the dark-squared bishop's diagonal.} e4 12. Qe3 {[%cal Re3e8] For now White is avoiding material losses because of the pin on the e-file.} O-O 13. Ngxe4 (13. Be2 Re8 {-+ With ..