is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Qf3 {[%csl Ra8,Gf3][%cal Yf3a8] White is protecting the bishop by 'pinning' the pawn on [c6]. Black has a wide choice here, there are many continuations with around equal value, I tried to choose one which is more human.} Rb8 {Bringing the rook into play and renewing the threat on the [b5]-bishop.} 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yg5e4,Yd3e4,Gd3f5] This is the main move. In case of a trade on [e4], White wants to take back with the bishop. Also, in general, we already saw that ...[f5] is a very dangerous idea for Black. Thus, the bishop tries to fight against it.} Bd6 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rc8g4,Yf3g3,Re5e4,Rd6g3] Besides being a developing move and preparing ...[O-O], the bishop also targets the [g3]-square, highlighting the fact that White's queen doesn't really have a lot of squares to go to.} 10. Bf5 {White stops ...[Bg4], but keeps moving around with their pieces a lot.} h6 11. Bxc8 (11. Ne4 {This is very similar to the immediate 10. [Ne4].} Nxe4 12. Bxe4 O-O 13. g4 $1 {Without this move, the situation was very bad for White, since ...[f5] was coming.} Nb7 {∞ The knight is coming back, and Black has full compensation for the pawn. ( 12.Qxe4? This loses material. 12...Rb4! The queen has to find squares to protect the [f5]-bishop. 13.Qd3 (13.Qf3?? Rf4 -+ Immediately winning the bishop. ) 13...Rd4 14.Qh3 As already shown, the [f3] square is not an option. 14...Rh4 15.Qd3 e4! The key move. 16.Bxe4 Qe7 Pinning and winning the bishop. 17.Nc3 f5 -+ Black is winning with the extra piece. )}) 11... hxg5 {[%csl Rc8] White's bishop already made 5 moves, and there is more to come.} 12. Bf5 (12. Ba6 e4 $1 13. Qe2 O-O {∞ ...[Re8] and then ... [c5]-...[Nc6] are our next moves.}) 12... g6 {One more tempo on the bishop.} 13. Bd3 g4 {[%csl Gg4] Gaining some space on the kingside, and our rook is pretty active on [h8].} 14. Qe2 Kf8 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gc6c5,Ga5c6,Gc6d4,Gf8g7] The rook will stay on [h8], making [O-O] impossible. Our next step is to bring the knight back into the game by playing ...[c5] and then ...[Nc6].} *

