is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Ne4 {[%cal Yf7f5] This is risky in general when Black can push for ...[f5], and this position is no exception.} Nf4 {[%cal Rf4g2,Rf4d3] White has to retreat with the bishop to [f1], if they want to keep the extra pawn.} 10. Bf1 ({•} 10. Qf3 $2 f5 {∓ The queen is badly placed on [f3].}) ({•} 10. O-O Nxd3 11. cxd3 Be7 {∞ There are similar lines when White allows the doubled d-pawns, but it is a pretty good version for Black, since the knight on [e4] is defending the [e5]-pawn instead of attacking it.}) 10... f5 11. Nec3 Bc5 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Yc2c3,Yd2d4,Gc5f2] Now the knight blocks [c3] and then [d4], so the bishop can safely go to [c5] and target [f2].} 12. d3 {[%cal Yd8d4,Gc1e3] It is still not easy to do anything with the knight on [f4], since taking it would just open the e-file. However, at least ...[Qd4] can be met by [Be3]! now.} O-O 13. g3 Re8 $1 {[%csl Re1,Gf4] Keeping the knight on [f4], since taking it is just too dangerous for White.} 14. Qd2 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Rg3f4,Ge1d1] Very awkward, but White wants to take the knight and play [Kd1].} ({•} 14. Be3 Bd6 $1 {∓ We can continue with ...[Rb8], and then ...[c5], followed by ... [Nc6]-[d4] or ...[Bb7].}) ({•} 14. gxf4 exf4+ 15. Be2 {(15.Kd2 Nc4#)} f3 16. O-O fxe2 17. Nxe2 Bd6 {∓ And Black is much better, since White's king is very weak.}) 14... Nd5 $15 {[%cal Re5e4] This is good for the advantage, Black pretty much wants to play ...[e4] against any move.} (14... Bb7 $1 {The computer's way, showing very well in which style we can play in this opening line.} 15. gxf4 Qh4 16. fxe5 Rxe5+ 17. Kd1 Bxf2 18. Ne2 Nc4 $1 19. Qc3 c5 {∓ We are down a piece, and a lot of things are hanging now, but according to the engine it works out well.}) *

