1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some 'tricky' options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by the computer. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. h4 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh4g5,Gd1f3,Rf3f7,Rf3h5,Rh5f7,Gd3h7] This is just a crazy line. 🙂 White wants to keep the knight on [g5], then play [Qf3] or [Qh5], which are not so easy to meet. Even taking on [h7] can be an option sometimes.} Bd6 {Almost a novelty, which was only played in one game. The idea is to be ready to meet both [Qf3] and [Qh5].} ({•} 9... Be7 10. Qf3 $1 {Now Black can't protect the pawn on [f7], since the bishop is blocking the queen's way, whilst ...[O-O] would just drop the [h7]-pawn.} f5 11. Bxf5 Rf8 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Bxg6+ hxg6 14. Qxg6+ Kd7 {∞ With a complete mess. We will have something similar to this, but I believe it will be somewhat less chaotic.}) ({• Instead} 9... f5 {is met by} 10. Be2 $1 {and it is very tough for Black to play for ...[h6], while White is ready to go with [d4] in the next move.}) ({•} 9... h6 {is another main line, but I didn't like that after} 10. Qh5 Qf6 11. Ne4 Qe6 12. Ng5 {we can't really avoid the draw, not speaking about 11. [Nh7]!?, which also can lead to crazy positions.}) 10. Bxh7 {Hard to believe that this move is playable, but it is. White is breaking all opening principles and is still okay.} g6 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd5f6] We have to trap the bishop.} 11. d3 Nf6 12. h5 $1 {[%csl Gh1]} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf5g6,Yf6h7] It was too early to take on [h7], since after [hxg6], White would be just better. Now Black wants to take back with the bishop on [g6], protecting the knight eventually.} 13. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rf3c6] Creating counterplay against [c6] now.} Qe7 14. hxg6 Bxg6 15. Bd2 $1 Bc7 $132 (15... Bc7 {The position remains a huge mess. However, Black will be a piece up, so it can't be too bad. One possible way is} 16. Nc3 Nxh7 17. b4 e4 18. Ngxe4 Nb7 19. O-O-O O-O-O {∞ All three results are certainly possible. 🙂}) *

