is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. h4 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh4g5,Gd1f3,Rf3f7,Rf3h5,Rh5f7,Gd3h7] This is just a crazy line. 🙂 White wants to keep the knight on [g5], then play [Qf3] or [Qh5], which are not so easy to meet. Even taking on [h7] can be an option sometimes.} Bd6 {Almost a novelty, which was only played in one game. The idea is to be ready to meet both [Qf3] and [Qh5].} ({•} 9... Be7 10. Qf3 $1 {Now Black can't protect the pawn on [f7], since the bishop is blocking the queen's way, whilst ...[O-O] would just drop the [h7]-pawn.} f5 11. Bxf5 Rf8 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Bxg6+ hxg6 14. Qxg6+ Kd7 {∞ With a complete mess. We will have something similar to this, but I believe it will be somewhat less chaotic.}) ({• Instead} 9... f5 {is met by} 10. Be2 $1 {and it is very tough for Black to play for ...[h6], while White is ready to go with [d4] in the next move.}) ({•} 9... h6 {is another main line, but I didn't like that after} 10. Qh5 Qf6 11. Ne4 Qe6 12. Ng5 {we can't really avoid the draw, not speaking about 11. [Nh7]!?, which also can lead to crazy positions.}) 10. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3f7]} (10. Qh5 $6 {Without ...[h6], this move is just very bad.} g6 11. Qf3 O-O {⩱ With ...[f5] and ...[e4] coming, Black is just better.}) 10... Qe7 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7] This is the difference compared to 9...Be7 lines, Black doesn't have to go for ...[f5] immediately, and enter crazy complications.} 11. O-O f5 $1 {[%csl Yg1] This looks like a better version for Black, since the king can go to [d8]. Also, White's king doesn't necessarily feel safe on the kingside.} 12. Bxf5 Rf8 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Bxg6+ hxg6 15. Qxg6+ Kd8 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gd5f4,Gd8c7] It looks much easier to play with Black; we have obvious moves like ...[Bf5], ... [Kc7] coming, and then we can attack on the kingside.} *

