is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd3e2,Gd2d3] A rare line, but quite playable. White quickly wants to regroup their pieces and be in time to play [d3], slowing down the ...[f5]-...[e4] plan from Black.} O-O (10... Nf4 {and 10...f5 are good alternatives.}) 11. Be2 (11. O-O $2 f5 $1 {tranposes here.}) 11... f5 {[%cal Re5e4] ...[e4] is a big threat, but White is just in time.} 12. d3 Qc7 {[%cal Ye1g1,Ye5e4,Rd6h2] Putting pressure on the [h2]-pawn, making [O-O] more difficult for White.} 13. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gd2c3,Rd2a5] White wants to take back with the bishop on [c3], and more importantly this move is also eyeing the [a5]-knight.} Rb8 {[%cal Rb8b2] Black would like to weaken the dark squares on the kingside before switching to the plan of ...[Nf6] and ...[e4].} 14. O-O $1 {White will have to protect [b2] eventually, but this move order sets a trap.} ({•} 14. Rb1 Nf6 15. O-O c5 {∞ 15...e4 was also possible, but this looks even more unpleasant for White, who seriously lacks space.}) ({•} 14. b3 $6 Nf6 {⩱ If White is not castling, we can improve our position with ...[c5] and ...[Nc6]-[d4].}) 14... Nf6 {[%cal Re5e4]} (14... Rxb2 $2 {Would be a serious mistake, White could gain a lot of tempi here.} 15. Na4 $1 Rb8 16. c4 {Suddenly Black's position is pretty loose and there is no good square for the knight.} Nf4 17. Bxf4 exf4 {This is not the structure that Black wants. ...[e4] is not a move anymore.} 18. d4 {± White has returned the extra pawn, but it actually looks like they still have one. 🙂 ( 16...Nf6? 17.c5! Be7 18.Bxa5 Qxa5 19.Nxe5 ± White is taking an important pawn and even attacking [c6] with tempo. Black has no compensation here. )}) 15. Kh1 {So Black can't take on [h2] with a check.} c5 {[%cal Ga5c6,Gc6d4,Rb8b2] ...[Nc6]-[d4] is coming and Black has full compensation for the pawn with a huge space advantage.} (15... Rxb2 $6 {Still not so good, because after} 16. Qe1 $1 {⩲ The knight on [a5] has problems.}) *

