is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line, Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here, we are building on ... [f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Nc3 $2 {Allows ...[f5] for free.} f5 {[%cal Re5e4]} 12. Nxd5 (12. Be2 e4 13. Nd4 Be5 {Forcing the knight further away from the kingside.} 14. Nb3 Qh4 $1 15. g3 Qh3 {∓ With ideas like ...[f4] or ...[Nf4], Black's attack is extremely dangerous. For example,} 16. Nxa5 {loses to} Nf4 $1 17. Bf3 {(17.gxf4 Bxf4 -+)} Rf6 $1 {And ...[Rh6]-...[Qxh2] is unstoppable.}) 12... cxd5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5,Gf5]} 13. b4 $1 {The only move which is not completely losing according to the engine.} (13. Be2 e4 14. Nd4 f4 {∓ And ...[f3] is a huge threat.} 15. f3 {If White prevents it like this, Black can at the very least win back the material with a much better position after} Qb6 16. c3 Nc6 {-+}) 13... Nb7 {[%csl Gb7,Yc6][%cal Rd3b5,Rb5c6,Ya5c6] White anyway wants to get out from the fork with [Bb5], so it is better not to allow it with tempo.} 14. Bb5 e4 15. Bc6 {White is trading Black's centre for a piece.} exf3 16. Bxd5+ Kh8 17. Qxf3 Rb8 $15 {[%cal Gd8h4,Yb7d8,Yd8f7] Black's attacking prospects are more dangerous than White's pawns.} *

