is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line, Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here, we are building on ... [f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Rf3e5,Re1e5] Attacking on [e5], and sometimes it can be very important that the bishop can retreat to [f1].} Bg4 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye5e4]} ({A relatively rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on e5, but} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. Nc3 $2 {A bad move, Black is taking over the initiative.} f5 $1 {[%cal Re5e4]} 13. Be2 e4 14. Nd4 Nf4 $1 {Bringing the knight closer to the king, and if White takes on [g4], the f-file is opening up as well.} 15. Bxg4 (15. d3 Nxg2 $1 16. Kxg2 Qh4 17. f4 exf3+ 18. Nxf3 Qh3+ 19. Kf2 Bc5+ 20. d4 Rad8 {-+ White's king is too weak here.}) 15... fxg4 {[%cal Rf8f2]} 16. Nxe4 (16. Qxg4 h5 {The queen has to retreat, since on [g3] it would be exposed to discovered attacks.} 17. Qd1 Qg5 {-+}) 16... Nxg2 $1 {Creating a lot of weak squares around White's king.} 17. Kxg2 (17. Rf1 {Not really a serious alternative, since Black is going to attack with even material in this line.} Nf4 {∓ Without the [g2]-pawn White's king is very weak.}) 17... Qh4 {[%cal Rh4h2,Rh4h3,Rf8f2,Rd6h2]} 18. Rh1 Rae8 $1 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Re8e4] Bringing a new piece into the game and attacking the defender of the [f2]-square.} 19. Ng3 Nc4 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Yc4e5,Yc6c5,Ye5f3] White can't really move, and Black will just play ...[Ne5], ...[c5] and then ...[Nf3], and the position wins by itself.} *

