1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some 'tricky' options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by the computer. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line, Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here, we are building on ... [f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Rf3e5,Re1e5] Attacking on [e5], and sometimes it can be very important that the bishop can retreat to [f1].} Bg4 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye5e4]} ({A relatively rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on e5, but} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. Be2 $6 {[%cal Ge1e5] Playing such moves after [Re1] is clearly not what White should do.} e4 $1 13. Nd4 f5 $1 {Tactics are working out nicely for Black.} 14. Ne6 {[%cal Re6f8,Re6d8]} (14. Bxg4 fxg4 15. Qxg4 Bc5 16. c3 Qf6 17. Rf1 Rae8 {∓ White has no development, and Black can either bring the knight in with ...[Nc4]-[e5] or play ...[h5] and ...[Re5]. White shouldn't be able to defend such a position.}) 14... Bxh2+ $1 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Rf6 {[%cal Rf6h6,Rh4h1] Almost looks like mate, but White can still defend.} 17. g3 (17. d3 e3 $1 {Closing the bishop's diagonal, so ...[Rh6] can be played.}) 17... Qh3 18. d3 Bxe2 19. Ng5 $1 {Forces the trade of the queens.} Bxd1 20. Nxh3 Bxc2 $15 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5] Black is up a pawn and more active in this endgame.} *

