is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line, Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here, we are building on ... [f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Rf3e5,Re1e5] Attacking on [e5], and sometimes it can be very important that the bishop can retreat to [f1].} Bg4 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye5e4]} ({A relatively rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on e5, but} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. Bf1 {Quite passive, but since White is in time for [d3], it is playable.} f5 13. d3 $1 {[%cal Gd3e4] ... [e4] has to be stopped.} Qb6 {[%cal Gd6c5,Rc5f2,Rb6b2,Ga8e8,Ye5e4] Black has many ways to play here, this one looks decent to me, the queen puts pressure on [b2] and [f2], while frees the way for the rook towards [e8].} 14. Nbd2 (14. Nc3 {I don't really like this move. White should keep the option of playing [c3] and then at some moment [b4], which is both good for defense, since the bishop can't go to [c5]. This also helps with the development of the queenside.} Rae8 {∞ One possible way to continue for Black is ...[Bb8] followed by ...[Qc7], targeting White's king.}) 14... Rae8 {[%cal Gd6c5,Ye5e4] Black is bringing the last piece into the game the [a5]-knight is at least preventing [Nc4], which is pretty important, and will go to attacking mode starting next move.} 15. c3 {[%cal Rd2c4,Gb2b4] White also has threats of playing [b4] and then [Nc4], so Black shouldn't wait here.} (15. Nc4 $2 Nxc4 16. dxc4 Bc5 $1 17. cxd5 Bxf2+ 18. Kh1 e4 $1 {-+ And Black is taking more than just an exchange here.}) 15... e4 $1 16. dxe4 Bc5 {[%cal Rb6f2]} 17. Re2 Bxf2+ $1 18. Rxf2 fxe4 {Black is winning back the piece.} 19. Nxe4 {White has to take, otherwise ...[e3] would come.} Rxe4 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Rb6g1,Ga5c4] Black has full compensation for the pawn. Still, White is also okay here, even though the position is not much fun for them.} *

