 rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on e5, but} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. h3 {By far the most common and most logical, White wants to break the pin, and unfortunately they can.} Bxf3 (12... Bh5 $6 {Unfortunately doesn't work, because White has the very strong} 13. Bf5 $1 {± And when needed, they can just break the pin by playing [Bg4], without weakening the kingside at all.}) 13. Qxf3 f5 $1 {[%cal Re5e4] As usual, if we can play ...[e4] for free, then Black is just better.} 14. Bxf5 $1 (14. Bf1 e4 15. Qd1 Bc7 {∞ ... [Qd6] and ...[Rae8] is coming, Black's position is much easier to play.}) 14... Qe7 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ye7e6,Rg7g6]} ({Covering the e6-square, so now ...g6 is a big threat. On} 14... g6 $2 {, White has} 15. Be6+ {with a winning position.}) 15. Qh5 {White gives up the bishop, but will have 4 pawns for it.} g6 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. Qxg6+ Qg7 $1 {White can't take on [d6].} 18. Qxg7+ ({•} 18. Qxd6 $4 {Taking back the piece loses on the spot.} Nf4 $1 19. g3 {The only way to prevent immediate mate.} Nxh3+ 20. Kh1 Nxf2+ 21. Kg2 Qg4 {-+ And it is checkmate in a few moves. ( 20.Kg2 Allows checkmate. 20...Rxf2+ 21.Kxh3 Qh7+ 22.Kg4 Qf5+ 23.Kh4 Rh2#)}) ({•} 18. Qe6+ $6 Kh7 19. Re4 Nf4 {⩱ And White will eventually have to play [Qg4] and try to trade the queens.}) 18... Kxg7 $13 (18... Kxg7 {With a very double-edged Endgame. White is doing materially okay, but Black's strange pawn structure makes it quite difficult to create 3 or 4 connected passers. One possible line is} 19. d3 Bc5 20. Be3 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Rab8 22. b3 Nb7 {The knight is coming to [f5] to target some weak pawns and squares.}) *

