1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The introductory move to the Italian Game. It is maybe less aggressive than the 'main line' 3. [Bb5], which immediately puts pressure on Black's [e5] pawn by attacking its defender on [c6].In recent years, the Italian Game or Giuoco Piano which would occur in the event that Black responded with 3...[Bc5] is becoming increasingly popular, thanks to the fact that Black has found very solid defenses against 3. [Bb5], such as the Marshall or Berlin Defense. White's goal is to avoid a very elaborate theory and keep many pieces on the board.} Nf6 {This variation is called the Two-Knights Defense. Instead, the more popular 3...[Bc5] would lead to the so-called Giuoco Piano.Our goal in this repertoire is to avoid those slow positions that are very difficult to understand even for the best players in the world, with so many move order tricks and subtleties that it would be possible to write a huge separate course on this line alone.Our first move against the Italian already shows our intentions; instead of 'only' developing the bishop on [c5], we immediately attack the pawn on [e4].} 4. Ng5 {[%cal Rg5f7,Rc4f7] White's most aggressive way of playing against our repertoire. Although the theory is rather advanced in these lines, I don't mind it at all, as it is still much easier to understand than a slow Italian game. 🙂} d5 ({Practically the only move for Black. There are some 'tricky' options for Black, such as} 4... Bc5 {or 4...Nxe4 , but they are not good, to say the least. We cannot allow our opponent to take on [f7].}) 5. exd5 (5. exd5 {Now we are at a crossroads, but for me the choice was quite easy.} Nxd5 6. Nxf7 $1 {is the famous Fried Liver Attack, which is not only very dangerous for Black, but is even supported by the computer. 5...b5 , the Ulvestad Variation is becoming quite popular recently, thanks to some new discoveries, and although it is probably theoretically less demanding than my choice, it is also much less fun and White's task is not that difficult. 5...Nd4 , the Fritz Variation is also playable, but White seems to be doing well.}) 5... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] The Polerio Defense. We are forcing White's bishop away from the [f7]-pawn with a tempo.} 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 {is a decent alternative, but the text move leads to sharper positions.}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is basically the starting position of this aggressive 4. [Ng5] line. White has won a pawn, but for that they have given up a lot. The knight has already moved twice and will have to move at least one more time in the near future. The same can be said of the bishop.Black is also better in the centre with the [e5]-pawn and has much easier development. In addition, there is no clear objective in White's position. So, to sum up, several pros and cons in one of the most unclear lines in modern theory.} 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Yg5e4,Gd3e4,Yg5f3] The main line nowadays, and certainly the most challenging continuation for Black. The bishop is awkward on [d3], but it prevents Black from pushing ...[e4] easily, which is very important for these type of positions, as we have seen earlier.} Nd5 {[%cal Rd8g5,Yf7f5]} ({Attacking the knight on g5 and freeing the way for the f-pawn. This is clearly the main line for Black, since for example} 8... h6 {can be met by} 9. Ne4 $1 {and White is doing pretty well there according to theory.}) 9. Nf3 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd3e4,Ge5e4] The bishop on [d3] is not good, but stopping ...[e4] is very important for now.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Ge8g8] Protecting the pawn and preparing to castle and push ...[f5].} 10. O-O O-O ({This is more aggressive than} 10... Nf4 {, which is the other big main line, Black is taking on [d3] there and has decent compensation for the pawn. Our plans are completely different here, we are building on ... [f5] and ...[e4].}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Rf3e5,Re1e5] Attacking on [e5], and sometimes it can be very important that the bishop can retreat to [f1].} Bg4 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye5e4]} ({A relatively rare line, especially since Black figured out that it is not a must to protect the pawn on e5, but} 11... f5 12. Nxe5 Qf6 {is playable. Originally I wanted to recommend those lines, but I simply found them too crazy and too long.}) 12. h3 {By far the most common and most logical, White wants to break the pin, and unfortunately they can.} Bxf3 (12... Bh5 $6 {Unfortunately doesn't work, because White has the very strong} 13. Bf5 $1 {± And when needed, they can just break the pin by playing [Bg4], without weakening the kingside at all.}) 13. Qxf3 f5 $1 {[%cal Re5e4] As usual, if we can play ...[e4] for free, then Black is just better.} 14. Bxf5 $1 (14. Bf1 e4 15. Qd1 Bc7 {∞ With ...[Qd6] and ...[Rae8] coming, Black's position is much easier to play.}) 14... Qe7 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ye7e6,Rg7g6] Covering the [e6]-square, so now ...[g6] is a big threat.} ({On} 14... g6 $2 {, White has} 15. Be6+ {with a winning position.}) 15. c4 $1 {By far the best move for White, but not an easy one! The point is that by giving back one pawn, White wants to speed up the development of the queenside.} ({•} 15. Qg4 $2 {Logical, but doesn't work.} Qf6 $1 16. Be6+ Kh8 {Even though White gained a tempo for organising some defence, it is still not possible.} 17. Rf1 Nf4 18. Bb3 h5 19. Qf3 e4 $1 {-+ Black's attack is decisive.}) ({•} 15. Qd3 $2 Qf6 $1 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Rf1 e4 $1 {All the pieces are ready to attack the king.} 18. Bxe4 Nf4 {-+ The engine already wants to sacrifice the queen, as White's pieces are simply doing nothing.}) 15... g6 (15... Nxc4 16. d3 $1 {and then [Qe4] is what White wanted. Those positions are still far from clear, though, but I prefer the text move.}) 16. cxd5 Rxf5 17. Qe4 Qf7 $1 {[%cal Rc6d5,Rf5f2] Attacking on [d5] and [f2].} 18. dxc6 (18. Nc3 Bc5 $1 19. d4 Bxd4 20. Be3 Bxc3 21. bxc3 cxd5 {Finally the material is equal, and Black is fine.}) 18... Rf4 $1 {The queen is very well-placed on [e4], so we need this intermezzo.} (18... Rxf2 $2 19. Nc3 $1 {± And White is very solid.}) 19. Qe3 {[%cal Rd6c5,Ye3c5] Stopping ...[Bc5] is necessary.} Rf8 20. Nc3 ({•} 20. f3 e4 $1 {-+ Black is easily winning here.}) ({•} 20. Rf1 Nxc6 21. Nc3 Nd4 {And according to the engine, the game should end after,} 22. Ne4 $1 Qe6 23. Nxd6 Nf3+ 24. gxf3 {(24.Kh1? Qxd6 -+)} Qxh3 {And White will have to give perpetual check, since there is no other way to checkmate after ...[Rh4].}) 20... Rxf2 21. Ne4 {[%csl Ge4]} Rf1+ 22. Kh2 Bc7 {[%cal Rc7b6]} (22... Bc7 {And Black has enough compensation for the pawns. The computer comes up with all sorts of draws. One line is} 23. d3 Bb6 24. Qe2 Bg1+ 25. Kh1 Be3+ {And White has to repeat now.} 26. Kh2 {(26.Rxf1?? This is losing, because of 26...Qxf1+ 27.Qxf1 Rxf1+ 28.Kh2 and Black has the time to take on [c6]. 28...Nxc6 -+)} Bg1+) (22... Bc7 23. b3 $6 Bb6 {↑}) *

