[White "21) Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation - 5.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C68"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2160376126111903"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. Nxe5 $6 {This is the first important question. Isn't this pawn hanging?} Qd4 $1 {[%cal Rd4e4,Rd4e5] This position is normally the first one you have to know in the Ruy Lopez. Black is immediately taking back the pawn and enters a better endgame with the bishop pair.} 6. Nf3 ({•} 6. Ng4 $6 {White can keep the queens on the board, but it is probably even more dangerous than the endgame.} Qxe4+ 7. Ne3 Be6 {Black is going to castle long.} 8. Nc3 Qg6 9. O-O O-O-O {∓ We have excellent attacking chances by pushing the h or f-pawn.}) ({•} 6. Nd3 $6 {The knight is much worse here than on [f3], it is just blocking the d-pawn.} Qxe4+ 7. Qe2 Bf5 8. Nc3 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 O-O-O {∓ Black is a lot better here with the bishop pair.}) 6... Qxe4+ 7. Qe2 ({Quite a few players tried} 7. Kf1 {here, which is mysterious to me.}) 7... Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 Ne7 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Yc8d7,Yd7g4] Out of the 550 games that reached the position with [Kxe2], this was only played once! It wouldn't have won the novelty of the year anyway, but it is a pretty nice move, with the idea of delaying the bishop's development from [c8], since sometimes it goes just to [d7], but sometimes it can go to [g4] as well.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge2f1] White wants to remove the king to [f1].} (9. d3 c5 10. Nc3 {If White is developing on the queenside, the bishop shouldn't go to [g4], since it could be met by [h3].} Bd7 11. Be3 b6 12. Rhe1 O-O-O {⩱ ...[f6] is next, and then ...[Nc6].}) 9... f6 {One more useful waiting move. Our king doesn't necessarily have to castle long, it is also very good on [f7].} 10. Kf1 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Rg4f3] This was the whole point of waiting, now ...[Bxf3] is a threat, and it is not easy to find good squares for the knight.} *

