1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. h3 $6 {This move is surprisingly popular, especially in online games. ...[Bg4] is not nearly this dangerous that White should waste a full tempo to prevent it.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5]} 6. O-O {When White is playing this slowly, we should consider playing by ...[c5], and make the [d4]-break much tougher for our opponent. Or rather, we can get rid of our doubled pawns once they push [d4].} (6. d4 {Of course it is possible, we will see many similar positions later.} exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7) 6... c5 7. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc5d4] White has to go for [d4], there are not many other plans for them.} (7. d3 Ne7 {⩱ The knight goes to [c6], the bishops to [e7] and [e6], and playing both short and long castle is possible. Since White already played [h3], it looks quite tempting to go for ... [g5]-[g4] as well.}) 7... Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3] The queen is very unpleasant on [d3], it slows down [d4].} 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e3]} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7c6] The knight is going to [c6].} 9. Re3 {White has to kick out the queen and play [d4].} Qd7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Ge8c8] Better than [d8], since it leaves the option to go for ...[O-O-O].} 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Qxd4 ({•} 12. Nxd4 $4 c5 {-+}) (12. Re1 $1 {With this move, White manages to hold the position.} b6 {(12...c5?! 13.b4! ⩲)} 13. Nxd4 Bb7 14. Nc3 O-O-O) 12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Bd7 $15 {[%csl Ga6,Gb7,Gc7,Gd7,Gf8][%cal Ge8c8] Our structure is great on the queenside, so we just have the advantage of the pair of bishops.} *

