1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. d3 {[%csl Ge4,Re5][%cal Gf3e5,Gd3e4] By protecting the pawn on [e4], and also covering the [g5]-square, the pawn on [e5] is finally hanging. Nxe5-[Qg5], attacking on [g2] and [e5] is something which also protects the pawn on [e5]. However, the move absolutely doesn't fit the Exchange Variation, since White should go for [d4] at some point.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5,Yc6c5] Protecting the pawn and aiming to go for ... [c5] later to make [d4] from White much less effective.} 6. Be3 (6. Nbd2 $6 {Looks like a terrible move order, Black's knight is in time to reach [c6].} Ne7 7. Nc4 c5 {⩱ With the usual developing moves to follow, and then we can decide in which side to castle.}) 6... Ne7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7g6,Yf2f4,Gc6c5,Gf8c5]} (6... c5 {was also possible, but developing the knight first to [g6] is even better. The knight is doing well there, covering the [f4]-square, which could be another potential break for White, and also after playing ...[c5] too early, it is a little bit tricky to develop, since the bishop has to protect it from [f8].}) 7. Nc3 Ng6 8. Ne2 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gf2f4] White is aiming for some quick regrouping with [Nd2] and [f4].} Bd6 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd6f4] Already anticipating White's plan.} 9. Nd2 Be6 10. O-O a5 {[%cal Yd2c4,Yb7b5] Gaining some space on the kingside, and often we can kick out White's knight from [c4] with ...[b5], and it can't go to [a5].} 11. Nc4 (11. f4 $2 {Just drops a pawn now.} exf4 12. Nxf4 Bxf4 13. Bxf4 Qd4+ 14. Kh1 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 Qxb2 {-+}) 11... Be7 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7][%cal Yf2f4,Ye6c4] Keeping the bishop pair, and [f4] is not working currently, because we can take on [c4] and spoil White's structure.} 12. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4] In order to take back with the b-pawn on [c4], but of course Black is not so interested in taking anymore.} (12. f4 Bxc4 13. dxc4 exf4 14. Nxf4 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 Bd6 {⩱}) 12... a4 13. f4 exf4 14. Nxf4 Nxf4 15. Bxf4 O-O $132 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7][%cal Yb7b5,Yd8d7,Ya8a6,Yf8a8] White has managed to play [f4], but it is not clear what is next. Black is very solid with the bishop pair, and we can continue with kicking the knight out with ...[b5] and maybe later doubling on the a-file.} *

