1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. d3 {[%csl Ge4,Re5][%cal Gf3e5,Gd3e4] By protecting the pawn on [e4], and also covering the [g5]-square, the pawn on [e5] is finally hanging. Nxe5-[Qg5], attacking on [g2] and [e5] is something which also protects the pawn on [e5]. However, the move absolutely doesn't fit the Exchange Variation, since White should go for [d4] at some point.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5,Yc6c5] Protecting the pawn and aiming to go for ... [c5] later to make [d4] from White much less effective.} 6. Be3 (6. Nbd2 $6 {Looks like a terrible move order, Black's knight is in time to reach [c6].} Ne7 7. Nc4 c5 {⩱ With the usual developing moves to follow, and then we can decide in which side to castle.}) 6... Ne7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7g6,Yf2f4,Gc6c5,Gf8c5]} (6... c5 {was also possible, but developing the knight first to [g6] is even better. The knight is doing well there, covering the [f4]-square, which could be another potential break for White, and also after playing ...[c5] too early, it is a little bit tricky to develop, since the bishop has to protect it from [f8].}) 7. Nbd2 Ng6 8. Qe2 c5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc8e6,Yf8c5,Yd3d4,Yf2f4] And Black is very comfortable, while White has no clear plans here.} 9. O-O-O $6 Be6 $15 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4] The king can even get into trouble on the queenside.} *

