1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White is waiting to see how Black is going to protect the pawn on [e5], before going for [d4]. Actually the pawn is still not really under attack, because [Nxe5] can be met by ...[Qg5], but Black doesn't really have a useful waiting move.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] This is the main line, and indeed ...[f6] looks like a good option for Black, since it fits to the endgame, which is likely to happen after [d4].} 6. d4 {White has to go for this now, because ...[c5] was already a threat.} (6. O-O c5 $1 7. d3 Ne7 {⩱ Black is getting the ideal setup, and White is just struggling.}) 6... exd4 7. Qxd4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc6c5,Gc3d5] It is generally not dangerous for Black, when the queen trade happens without us having had to play ...[c5]. With that move, we weaken our structure a little bit, and [Nd5] can be slightly unpleasant sometimes.} Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] A huge advantage here, when compared to the Berlin endgame, is that we can castle and easily bring the rook into play.} 9. Be3 O-O-O 10. O-O-O Ne7 $132 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge7g6,Yh7h5,Gb7b6,Ga6a5] There were still over 100 OTB games for this position, but if you know the usual moves, you'll be fine here. Putting the rook to [e8] and the knight to [g6] comes first, to put pressure on White's centre and make it very difficult to do anything with that extra pawn on the kingside. If they go [h4], we pretty much always answer with ...[h5], not to let White to gain more space. Otherwise we can slowly improve our position on the queenside, by playing moves likes ...[b6] and ...[a5].} *

