1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White is waiting to see how Black is going to protect the pawn on [e5], before going for [d4]. Actually the pawn is still not really under attack, because [Nxe5] can be met by ...[Qg5], but Black doesn't really have a useful waiting move.} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] This is the main line, and indeed ...[f6] looks like a good option for Black, since it fits to the endgame, which is likely to happen after [d4].} 6. d4 {White has to go for this now, because ...[c5] was already a threat.} (6. O-O c5 $1 7. d3 Ne7 {⩱ Black is getting the ideal setup, and White is just struggling.}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gc3d5] These positions are tougher to play at least in my opinion compared to those when the pawn is on [c6]. We give up the [d5]-square, and sometimes White can quickly attack our pawns with [Nd5] and [Bf4]. However, in this current position, White first has to go backwards, since they are missing [O-O], so can't recapture with the rook on [d1].} 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gh1d1] Rxd1 would be ideal now.} 9. Nxd1 {[%csl Yd5] The knight has to go further away from the [d5]-square, and Black can use these additional tempi to develop and have a good position.} Be6 10. Bf4 O-O-O {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc8c7] Comfortably protecting [c7].} 11. Ne3 Ne7 {[%cal Yg7g5,Yf6f5] Black already has options to go for ...[g5] and ...[f5] and open up the position for the bishops.} 12. Rd1 (12. h4 {White is preventing ...[g5], so Black will go towards the queenside.} Nc6 {∞ We want to continue with ...[c4]-...[Bc5] and then probably ...[Rhe8], with an active position, where our bishops are doing pretty well.}) 12... Rxd1+ (12... Re8 {is also an option, and not a bad one.}) 13. Kxd1 g5 {[%cal Rf6f5]} 14. Bg3 f5 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gf8g7] Black should have no problems in an open position with the pair of bishops.} 15. Be5 (15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 {⇆}) 15... Rg8 16. Nc3 b5 $132 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Rb5b4,Rf5f4] The position is double-edged, since White still has the better structure, but long-term, it looks like a great position for the bishops.} *

