1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. d4 {White immediately goes for the pawn structure with the kingside majority, but it is better for White to wait until Black has to initiate a queen trade after ...[c5].} exd4 {Ideally, White should only play [Nxd4] after [O-O], so when Black is chasing away the knight with ...[c5], the rook is ready to recapture on [d1]. Therefore, 5.O-O is the mainline nowadays.} 6. Qxd4 (6. Nxd4 $2 {This is just bad, since the king has to recapture on [d1].} c5 7. Nf3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Be6 9. Nc3 O-O-O+ 10. Ke2 f5 {∓ Opening the position around White's king. Black is already much better.}) 6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {[%csl Yc5,Gc6,Ge4,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Gb1c3,Yc3d5] White has achieved the desirable structure, but Black should be very satisfied, since with the pawn on [c6], the position on the queenside is very safe and if White's knight goes to [c3], then it will be restricted by the same pawn.} Bd7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ge8c8,Gc8c7] Preparing to play long castle and bring the rook into the game. Black struggles a lot with this in the Berlin endgame, but here it is very easy. The king's position on [c8] is also ideal, it protects the pawn on [c7].} 8. Nc3 {[%csl Yc3,Gc6,Gd5][%cal Yc6d5] Basically White has to make 2 decisions, whether to put the knight to [d2] or [c3] and to castle long or short. Everything looks very similar and quite comfortable for Black.} O-O-O 9. Be3 Re8 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Re8e4] This move is pretty much always a part of our setup. The rook is excellent on [e8], putting pressure on the [e4]-pawn, and making it really difficult for White to start pushing the kingside majority.} 10. O-O-O (10. O-O Ne7 11. Rad1 Ng6 12. Rfe1 h5 {⩱ Completing our setup, we can continue with improving moves, such as ... [b6] and ...[a5], playing ...[h4] followed by ...[Rh5] is also possible, besides those, we can ask some question with ...[Bb4] and ...[Ne5]-[c4] as well.}) 10... Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6,Yg6f4,Yg6e5] The knight is going to ...[g6], which is a great square, since it controls [f4] and [e5], which are once again very important squares for White, regarding the advancement of the pawns.} (10... Nf6 11. f3 $1 {The knight is not so good on [f6].}) 11. Rhe1 Ng6 12. f4 (12. f3 h5 13. Nde2 Bd6 {⩱}) 12... Bb4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Re8e4,Rg6f4,Gd7g4] White's pawns are under attack in the centre, Black is already better, that's why White has to be careful to push [f4].} 13. f5 Ne5 $15 {[%csl Ye4,Ge5][%cal Yg7g6] White is struggling to equalise here.} *

