1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. d4 {White immediately goes for the pawn structure with the kingside majority, but it is better for White to wait until Black has to initiate a queen trade after ...[c5].} exd4 {Ideally, White should only play [Nxd4] after [O-O], so when Black is chasing away the knight with ...[c5], the rook is ready to recapture on [d1]. Therefore, 5.O-O is the mainline nowadays.} 6. Qxd4 (6. Nxd4 $2 {This is just bad, since the king has to recapture on [d1].} c5 7. Nf3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Be6 9. Nc3 O-O-O+ 10. Ke2 f5 {∓ Opening the position around White's king. Black is already much better.}) 6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {[%csl Yc5,Gc6,Ge4,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Gb1c3,Yc3d5] White has achieved the desirable structure, but Black should be very satisfied, since with the pawn on [c6], the position on the queenside is very safe and if White's knight goes to [c3], then it will be restricted by the same pawn.} Bd7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ge8c8,Gc8c7] Preparing to play long castle and bring the rook into the game. Black struggles a lot with this in the Berlin endgame, but here it is very easy. The king's position on [c8] is also ideal, it protects the pawn on [c7].} 8. Be3 O-O-O 9. Nd2 {[%cal Yf8b4,Gc2c3] It is hard to say whether the knight is better on [d2] than on [c3], but at least it can't be pinned or attacked so easily by ...[Bb4].} Re8 $1 {[%cal Re8e4] We are making the same moves.} 10. O-O {[%csl Yd2,Yd4,Gd5] Since White's knights are miles away from the [d5]-square, and our king is already there to protect [c7], we can safely kick out White's knight from the centre.} c5 11. Ne2 (11. N4b3 b6 {∓ The [b3]-knight is awful. Black can continue with ...[a5]-[a4] or ...[f5].}) 11... b6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gb6c5,Gg8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] It is useful to protect the pawn. We can now develop with ...[Ne7] or with ...[g6]-...[Bg7] as well.} 12. Rfe1 g6 13. Rad1 Bg7 14. c3 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Yd2,Ye2][%cal Yf7f5,Ga6a5,Ga5a4] We can continue with gaining space on the queenside with ...[a5]-[a4], but ...[f5] is also an idea White has to watch out for. The knights are struggling a lot in White's position.} *

