1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3e5]} (5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on e5, which can be defended in innumerable ways. The two main lines are} f6 {, which would lead to the endgame after} 6. d4 {, and 5...Bg4 , which usually leads to sharper positions. Both moves are obviously good, but since endgames with the pawn on [c6] seem so convenient for Black, with the move in the text we will try to get there, even with the loss of a tempo.}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ye6g4,Ge8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. h3 Be6 {Basically giving two extra moves for White in the endgame, but it doesn't matter at all, we are easily in time to employ our setup, while moves like [h3] are not changing anything.} 7. d4 exd4 8. Qxd4 (8. Nxd4 $4 O-O-O 9. c3 c5 {-+ Winning the piece.}) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4e6]} Bd7 $10 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gd8e8,Gg8e7,Ge7g6] There is no reason to give up the pair of bishops, and we are just playing our usual endgame.} *

