1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3e5]} (5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on e5, which can be defended in innumerable ways. The two main lines are} f6 {, which would lead to the endgame after} 6. d4 {, and 5...Bg4 , which usually leads to sharper positions. Both moves are obviously good, but since endgames with the pawn on [c6] seem so convenient for Black, with the move in the text we will try to get there, even with the loss of a tempo.}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ye6g4,Ge8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4] White wants to play [Nbd2] and [Nc4], but since [Na3] would immediately threaten [Nc4], this seems like a step backward for White.} Ne7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7g6,Yg6e5] There are other good moves for Black, but developing and bringing the knight to [g6], where it is going to protect the pawn on [e5], looks pretty good.} 7. Be3 {Also possible, but doesn't look like an improvement over 7. [Nbd2].} Ng6 8. Nbd2 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Yg8][%cal Gf8c5,Yg8e7,Ye7g6] Our knight is already developed, so we don't have issues with the [c5]-pawn. Allowing the knight to [c4] is not a problem at all, in fact it makes it more difficult for White to play [d4] or sometimes even [b4].} 9. Nc4 Qe6 {We are making a couple of moves with our pieces, but it pretty much doesn't matter at all in a closed position, which is not getting open anytime soon.} 10. Ng5 Qg4 11. Qxg4 (11. f3 Qh4 {⩱ And the knight on [g5] is in a danger.}) 11... Bxg4 $132 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gb7b6,Ge8c8] We will kick back the knight with ...[f6] in the next move, and then start slowly improving our position.} *

