 lines, because of the extra move [O-O], but as you will see it means pretty much nothing.} exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 {Let's see what White can do with that extra tempo.} 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4c7]} O-O-O 10. Nc3 Re8 {Fortunately, we don't have to change anything in our setup.} 11. Rad1 Ne7 12. f3 Ng6 13. Bg3 h5 {With exactly the same moves, Black is reaching a comfortable position,} 14. h3 f6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b6,Ga6a5] The computer likes to evaluate these positions as ⩱, which is rather unusual. White's position seems quite normal, and apart from the gain of space on the queenside, it is hard to find anything more concrete for Black. I think the assessment is for long-term prospects, thanks to the bishop pair and the fact that if White starts to do anything, it will only make their position worse.} *

