1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3e5]} (5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on e5, which can be defended in innumerable ways. The two main lines are} f6 {, which would lead to the endgame after} 6. d4 {, and 5...Bg4 , which usually leads to sharper positions. Both moves are obviously good, but since endgames with the pawn on [c6] seem so convenient for Black, with the move in the text we will try to get there, even with the loss of a tempo.}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ye6g4,Ge8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. d4 {White can gain an extra tempo compared to 5.d4 exd4 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 lines, because of the extra move [O-O], but as you will see it means pretty much nothing.} exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yc8d7,Ge8c8] This is what I like about ...[Qd6]! We can comfortably continue the development behind the queen.} 8. e5 $2 {[%csl Re5] Just a bad, weakening move! Additionally, Black's queen is forced to a better square.} Qg6 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf8c5]} ({Of course not} 8... Qd5 {now, since it would be met by} 9. Nc3 $1) 9. Be3 O-O-O 10. Qe2 Ne7 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Ge7d5,Ge7f5] Going for the weak squares which the e-pawn gave us.} 11. Nc3 Nf5 $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7f5,Gf8e7,Gh8e8] Black is clearly better, White will have serious problems with the e-pawn.} *

