1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3e5]} (5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on e5, which can be defended in innumerable ways. The two main lines are} f6 {, which would lead to the endgame after} 6. d4 {, and 5...Bg4 , which usually leads to sharper positions. Both moves are obviously good, but since endgames with the pawn on [c6] seem so convenient for Black, with the move in the text we will try to get there, even with the loss of a tempo.}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ye6g4,Ge8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. d4 {White can gain an extra tempo compared to 5.d4 exd4 6.Qxd4 Qxd4 lines, because of the extra move [O-O], but as you will see it means pretty much nothing.} exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yc8d7,Ge8c8] This is what I like about ...[Qd6]! We can comfortably continue the development behind the queen.} 8. Be3 (8. Nc3 O-O-O {And White has nothing better than} 9. Be3 Nh6 {and we are transposing to 8. [Be3] [O-O-O] lines.}) 8... O-O-O 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gb1c3] White is delaying the decision of where to develop their knight.} Nh6 $1 {[%cal Yf7f5,Rh6g4] Supporting ...[f5] and threatening with ...[Ng4].} 10. f3 (10. h3 $6 Qg6 $1 {With a double attack on [h3] and [e4].} 11. Qf3 f5 {∓}) 10... f5 11. Nd2 (11. Nc3 f4 $1 {Transposes here.}) 11... Qg6 {[%cal Gf8d6] Vacating the [d6]-square for the bishop.} 12. e5 {[%csl Yd7,Yf8] Stops ...[Bd6], and in general tries to close the position against the bishop pair.} (12. Bxh6 $2 {Weakening the dark squares.} Qxh6 13. exf5 Bd6 14. g3 Bxf5 $1 15. Nxf5 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Rxd2 17. Nxh6 Rxe2 {-+ With a winning endgame for Black.}) 12... Re8 {[%cal Re8e5]} 13. f4 {[%csl Ge3] If White could keep the dark-squared bishop, it would be a pretty decent position.} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rg4e3] They can't!} 14. N4f3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Kb8 $15 {[%csl Rd2,Rf3][%cal Gf8e7,Gg6f7,Yh7h6,Yg7g5,Yc6c5,Yd7c6] We will play for the ...[g5] break, but White also has to watch out for ...[c5]-...[Bc6]. Even though the position is relatively closed now, White's knights' have no squares to go to.} *

