 lines, because of the extra move [O-O], but as you will see it means pretty much nothing.} exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yc8d7,Ge8c8] This is what I like about ...[Qd6]! We can comfortably continue the development behind the queen.} 8. Be3 (8. Nc3 O-O-O {And White has nothing better than} 9. Be3 Nh6 {and we are transposing to 8. [Be3] [O-O-O] lines.}) 8... O-O-O 9. Nd2 c5 (9... Nh6 {is still pretty good, but we can be even more aggressive when the knight is on [d2].}) 10. N4b3 {[%cal Re3c5,Rb3c5]} (10. Ne2 Bc6 11. Nc3 Qg6 {⩱ With ...[Bd6] and ...[f5] coming, and then the knight can go to [f6], since there is no need to support [f5] here.}) 10... b6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yb6c5,Gd7c6,Gc6b7] Not only protecting the pawn, but also preparing the [b7]-square for the bishop, which is very good against potential [Na5] attacks.} 11. a4 a5 $1 {Of course, there is no need to allow anything on the queenside.} 12. Qe2 Bc6 $15 {[%csl Yb3,Gc6,Yd2][%cal Gc6b7,Gd6e6,Gg8f6,Yf2f3,Yg7g5,Yg5g4] White's knights are struggling a lot here, we should just finish the development in the next couple of moves, and since it is likely that at some point White should play [f3], we can consider attacking by ...[Rg8] and then ...[g5]-[g4].} *

