1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5c6,Gc6e5,Rf3e5] The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation. White doubles our pawns on the queenside, and ideally wants a 4 vs 3 majority on the kingside. A long time ago, entering these types of positions for White was deemed very promising, but currently, such an approach isn't considered to be so dangerous. Basically, all White can realistically achieve is to obtain a position similar to those seen in the Berlin endgames. I would argue that this version is an improvement for Black since their king can still move, and castling long, for example, is frequently a good option.} dxc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d4,Ye5d4,Gd1d4]} 5. O-O {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3e5]} (5. O-O {This is by far the main line. White attacks the pawn on e5, which can be defended in innumerable ways. The two main lines are} f6 {, which would lead to the endgame after} 6. d4 {, and 5...Bg4 , which usually leads to sharper positions. Both moves are obviously good, but since endgames with the pawn on [c6] seem so convenient for Black, with the move in the text we will try to get there, even with the loss of a tempo.}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yc8d7,Yd7e6,Ye6g4,Ge8c8] Not the most natural way to protect the pawn by any means, but it makes possible for Black to finish the development with ...[Bd7] or some other bishop move, and castling long.} 6. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4,Rc4d6,Rc4e5] This is the main test of the 5...[Qd6] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} (6. b3 {Quite a risky move, if we can play ...[f6] and ...[c5], White's bishop will not have much to do on [b2] or [a3].} c5 {And we can!} 7. Bb2 f6 {⩱ We have easy moves to make, and it is not clear what White should do.}) 6... f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy and in some cases they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. d4 ({Not nearly as popular as} 7. Nc4 {, but maybe the critical move against 6...[f6]. Black is behind in the development, so White wants to open the position right away.}) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 c5 $1 {We have to force the endgame immediately!} (8... Bd7 $2 9. Nc4 Qe7 10. Bf4 $1 {± And Black is in big trouble, for example} O-O-O 11. Qd3 c5 12. Bxc7 $1 Kxc7 13. Qg3+ {+- is already winning for White.}) 9. Ne2 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 {[%csl Ya3][%cal Ga3c3] Even though we played ...[c5] now, and I'm not happy about it, we are still completely fine, because White's knight is misplaced on [a3].} Bd7 11. Bf4 O-O-O {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc8c7] Still in time to protect on [c7].} 12. Nc4 Ne7 13. Nc3 (13. f3 g5 $1 14. Bg3 Bg7 {⩱ With ...[f5] on the next move.}) 13... g5 $1 14. Bg3 Bg7 $10 {[%cal Yf6f5,Gd7e6] And next is ...[f5] or ...[Be6].} *

