] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} (6. b3 {Quite a risky move, if we can play ...[f6] and ...[c5], White's bishop will not have much to do on [b2] or [a3].} c5 {And we can!} 7. Bb2 f6 {⩱ We have easy moves to make, and it is not clear what White should do.}) 6... f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy and in some cases they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. d4 ({Not nearly as popular as} 7. Nc4 {, but maybe the critical move against 6...[f6]. Black is behind in the development, so White wants to open the position right away.}) 7... exd4 8. Nc4 ({Another very critical continuation.} 8. Qxd4 $2 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {⩱ The knight on [a3] doesn't help with this endgame.}) 8... Qd7 {[%csl Gd7] This square looks like the most optimal for Black, still protecting the pawn on [d4], which means that if White takes it, we can force an endgame.} ({•} 8... Qc5 9. b3 $1) ({•} 8... Qe6 9. Qxd4 $1) 9. Nxd4 {The only game which reached the position after ...[Qd7], went like this.} c5 $1 {Of course! We want the endgame with such poor development.} 10. Nf5 (10. Ne2 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Be6 12. b3 {(12.Ne3 Bd6= Followed by ...[Ne7] is also equal. )} Bxc4 13. bxc4 Bd6 14. Bf4 O-O-O 15. Bxd6 Rxd6 16. Rxd6 cxd6 {Black shouldn't have problems, since White's structure is very bad.}) 10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Be6 12. b3 g6 13. Nfe3 Ne7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye6d5,Ye7d5] The [d5]-square is under control.} 14. Bb2 Bg7 $10 {With more or less equal chances, in Grobler-R. Szabo, e-mail 2021.} *

