] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} (6. b3 {Quite a risky move, if we can play ...[f6] and ...[c5], White's bishop will not have much to do on [b2] or [a3].} c5 {And we can!} 7. Bb2 f6 {⩱ We have easy moves to make, and it is not clear what White should do.}) 6... f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy and in some cases they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. d4 ({Not nearly as popular as} 7. Nc4 {, but maybe the critical move against 6...[f6]. Black is behind in the development, so White wants to open the position right away.}) 7... exd4 8. Nc4 ({Another very critical continuation.} 8. Qxd4 $2 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {⩱ The knight on [a3] doesn't help with this endgame.}) 8... Qd7 {[%csl Gd7] This square looks like the most optimal for Black, still protecting the pawn on [d4], which means that if White takes it, we can force an endgame.} ({•} 8... Qc5 9. b3 $1) ({•} 8... Qe6 9. Qxd4 $1) 9. e5 Qd5 $1 {[%cal Rd5c4] Winning a tempo and getting one move closer to long castle.} 10. exf6 gxf6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({Covering the e5-square is very important.} 10... Qxc4 $4 11. Re1+ Kd8 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Bg5+ Nf6 14. Ne5 Qd5 15. c4 {+- It is not a surprise that once White is getting all the tempi, we are just losing.}) 11. Qxd4 {White has nothing better than going for the endgame.} Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Yc1f4,Ye7d5] We have to be a little bit careful, since White has good development, but once we are protecting the pawns we are just fine.} 13. Bf4 c5 14. Nb3 Nd5 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd5c7,Rd5f4] This is a key move for Black, protecting and winning a tempo.} 15. Bg3 Be6 16. Rfe1 Kf7 $10 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gh8g8,Ga6a5] And Black is safe