] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} (6. b3 {Quite a risky move, if we can play ...[f6] and ...[c5], White's bishop will not have much to do on [b2] or [a3].} c5 {And we can!} 7. Bb2 f6 {⩱ We have easy moves to make, and it is not clear what White should do.}) 6... f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy and in some cases they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. Nc4 {[%cal Rc4d6] The most human move, the knight was not blocked out, so they can bring it to [c4] with a tempo. This position was still reached in 36 games, but now we go into really rare waters.} Qe7 (7... Qe6 {is the main move, but I didn't like it so much. The text move is risky, because it gives a free move to White, instead of attacking the knight. However, I couldn't find anything which would refute this extremely rare move.}) (7... Qe6 8. Qe2 {d4 is a threat.} c5 9. c3 {And now the computer wants to play ... [b5], but I don't like it too much, we want to castle long after all.} b5 10. Ne3 {⩲}) 8. d4 {The most aggressive move.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Re6c4] Everything else is very bad according to the engine, but okay, we want long castle, and now we could develop with a tempo.} 9. Na5 O-O-O $1 {And we castled! The computer approves, and I like this position for Black.} 10. c3 Qe8 {[%cal Gg8e7] Preparing the [e7]-square for the knight.} 11. Qe2 Ne7 $5 {It is not a must to sacrifice the pawn, but since if White wants to keep the extra pawn, they have to open the g-file, which is not bad for Black.} 12. dxe5 Ng6 13. exf6 gxf6 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gf8d6] Black has good compensation for the pawn, with dangerous play on the kingside.} *

