] line. White is immediately threatening to play [Nc4] and win the pawn on [e5].} (6. b3 {Quite a risky move, if we can play ...[f6] and ...[c5], White's bishop will not have much to do on [b2] or [a3].} c5 {And we can!} 7. Bb2 f6 {⩱ We have easy moves to make, and it is not clear what White should do.}) 6... f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf6e5]} ({The main lines are} 6... Be6 {and 6...b5 , with the obvious goal of keeping White's knight on [a3]. I have looked at both options, but the lines are not so easy and in some cases they are too complicated. If we know our theory, we can get decent positions there as well, but I like this much rarer approach, where White still has to be very energetic to get somewhere.}) 7. Nc4 {[%cal Rc4d6] The most human move, the knight was not blocked out, so they can bring it to [c4] with a tempo. This position was still reached in 36 games, but now we go into really rare waters.} Qe7 (7... Qe6 {is the main move, but I didn't like it so much. The text move is risky, because it gives a free move to White, instead of attacking the knight. However, I couldn't find anything which would refute this extremely rare move.}) (7... Qe6 8. Qe2 {d4 is a threat.} c5 9. c3 {And now the computer wants to play ... [b5], but I don't like it too much, we want to castle long after all.} b5 10. Ne3 {⩲}) 8. d4 {The most aggressive move.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Re6c4] Everything else is very bad according to the engine, but okay, we want long castle, and now we could develop with a tempo.} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2c4,Rd4e5]} exd4 10. Nxd4 Bxc4 $1 ({Looks very risky, but we don't have a choice.} 10... Bd7 $2 11. Bf4 O-O-O 12. Nb3 {+- Once White can use their knight for the attack, it is already over.}) 11. Qxc4 Qxe4 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] Against pretty much every move we want to play long castle.} 12. Bf4 $3 {White has to find this in order to keep equality. 🙂} (12. f3 {Was played in the only game after ...[Qxe4], but it is not good enough.} Qd5 $1 13. Re1+ Kf7 {∓ The king is actually very safe on [f7], and we have a clear way of finishing the development with ...[Bd6] and ...[Ne7]. Mikkelsen-Bedia, Serpukhov 2004.}) 12... Qxf4 {[%csl Re8] For now, White's compensation is that they managed to keep the king in the centre for a couple more moves.} (12... O-O-O $4 {is unfortunately losing to} 13. Rad1 $1 Qxf4 14. Nxc6 $1 {+- Pretty flashy!}) 13. Rfe1+ (13. g3 Qg4 14. h3 Qxh3 15. Rfe1+ Ne7 {is transposing to the main line.}) 13... Ne7 14. g3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rf4c4] White has to get the knight out of the pin.} Qg4 ({Still keeping the pin.} 14... Qd6 15. Ne6 $1 b5 16. Qb3 Rd8 17. c3 $1 {With [Rad1] next, is very dangerous for Black.}) 15. f3 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rf8c5] This is imprecise, because it weakens the king a little bit.} Qh3 16. Ne6 Rd8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gd7c8] The only move, the king can escape via [d7]-[c8] if White would take on [c7].} 17. Nxd8 Kxd8 18. Qf7 b5 $1 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gc8b7] The king needs a hiding square.} 19. a4 Qd7 $1 {These are only moves, but the line is great for Black.} 20. axb5 Nd5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] Forcing the trade of the queens and entering a better endgame.} 21. Qxd7+ Kxd7 22. bxa6 Bc5+ $17 {[%cal Gh8a8] Black has good chances to win this endgame.} *

