1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yc4d5,Ye4d5] After this move it would be pretty tough to play for ...[d5], but there is another way of challenging White's centre.} Ng6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8] The plan is ...[Bc5] and castle, and then Black is very comfortable, since White created a weak square on [d4].} 6. d4 {White shouldn't let the bishop arrive on [c5].} exd4 7. Nxd4 {[%cal Ye4f5,Yd4f5,Yf7f5] For now the [f5]-square is well controlled by White, but when we can't play for ...[d5], ...[f5] is our other break to undermine the [e4]-pawn and equalise the situation in the centre.} Bb4+ 8. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gd7d6,Yf7f5] The next step is to go for ...[d6] and ...[f5].} 9. O-O Nxd4 {It is a good trade. We couldn't play ...[d6], because of the pressure on [c6], and the [d4]-knight way nicely controlling the [f5]-break.} 10. Qxd4 d6 {[%cal Yf7f5]} 11. Nd5 Bc5 12. Qc3 c6 {We have to kick back the knight first.} (12... f5 $6 13. b4 $1 Ba7 14. c5 {With [Bb2] next, things can get somewhat uncomfortable.}) 13. b4 Ba7 14. Ne3 Nf4 $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gd8g5] White has managed to stop ...[f5] for now, but we have ideas like ...[Qg5] with ...[Re8] and putting a lot of pressure on White's position.} *

