1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. d3 {This is way too slow to pose any problems for Black.} Ng6 6. Nc3 ({•} 6. O-O Be7 7. Nc3 {White has to develop like this to prepare against ...[d5].} O-O {Black has 2 different ideas here though!} 8. Nd5 b5 $1 {( We could have played 8...d6 and then ...[f5], but when we have the chance to go for the light-squared bishop, we should do so. )} 9. Bb3 Na5) ({•} 6. h4 {As we will see many times later in the chapter, this move should be just answered by} h5 $1) 6... Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] Not even allowing for White's knight to reach [d5].} 7. O-O {[%cal Gc3d5] Nd5 is coming next, so Black has to take the knight immediately.} Bxc3 8. bxc3 {[%csl Ga4,Gc1,Yc2,Yc3] White has the bishop pair, but Black has the better structure, since the doubled c-pawns are problematic for our opponent.} O-O 9. h3 {[%cal Yc8g4] Avoiding some future ...[Bg4] followed by ...[Nh4] ideas.} d6 {[%cal Gf7f5] Playing for ...[f5].} 10. Be3 b5 {Black is taking the light-squared bishop, so White won't even have the bishop pair.} 11. Bb3 Na5 $10 {[%cal Ra5b3,Yf7f5] And Black had no problems in F.Svane-Kozak, Cala Gonone 2022. After taking on [b3], ...[f5] is a good plan for Black.} *

