1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Bb3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5] White is targeting the [f7]-pawn, and they have ideas like [Ng5].} d5 $1 {[%cal Yb3a4,Ya4e8] Since White already moved the bishop for the 3rd time, and even more importantly, they removed it from pressuring the [c6]-knight, we can afford to go for ...[d5] this early.} ({The alternative is} 5... Ng6 {, but it allows quite a few dangerous lines for White, such as} 6. h4 $5 {or 6.d4 exd4 7.O-O which I didn't like.}) 6. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5] White has to act very quickly, otherwise Black can easily be better with the space advantage in the centre.} 7. O-O {[%cal Gf1e1,Rf3e5] Re1 is coming with attacking on [e5].} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Yf3][%cal Rg4d1] By pinning the knight we make it very difficult for White to attack or win the [e5]-pawn without weakening their kingside with [h3]-[g4].} 8. h3 Bh5 9. d4 {[%csl Re8]} ({White is trying to open the position before Black could castle.} 9. Re1 Be7 {transposes to 8. [Re1] [Be7] lines.}) 9... Nxd4 10. g4 {Breaking the pin and getting back the pawn, since taking on [f3] is not possible.} Nxb3 $1 {An important intermezzo! Taking White's most dangerous piece solves all the problems for Black.} (10... Nxf3+ $4 11. Qxf3 {+- White is winning a piece.}) 11. axb3 Bg6 12. Nxe5 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Black is only one move away from castling.} 13. Qf3 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Rd1d5] White prepares to play [Rd1] and create some problems for Black by pinning the [d5] knight.} Qd6 {Showing some ambition; we can also castle long!} 14. Nxg6 {White is taking back the bishop pair, but opening the h-file is quite nice for Black - the [h3]-pawn can be a target.} hxg6 15. Rd1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yf3d5,Yd1d5]} O-O-O $13 {[%cal Gd6f6]} (15... O-O-O {Black is absolutely fine, and if White tries to win a piece with} 16. c4 Qf6 {then they just weakened their position on the queenside, and Black will be better in this endgame.}) *

