... [Ng6].} 5. Bb3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5] White is targeting the [f7]-pawn, and they have ideas like [Ng5].} d5 $1 {[%cal Yb3a4,Ya4e8] Since White already moved the bishop for the 3rd time, and even more importantly, they removed it from pressuring the [c6]-knight, we can afford to go for ...[d5] this early.} ({The alternative is} 5... Ng6 {, but it allows quite a few dangerous lines for White, such as} 6. h4 $5 {or 6.d4 exd4 7.O-O which I didn't like.}) 6. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rb3d5,Re4d5] White is putting more pressure to the [d5]-pawn.} Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Ge7d5]} (6... d4 $4 {is losing the game very quickly. 6...dxe4 is similarly bad.} 7. Ng5 $1 dxc3 8. Bxf7+ Kd7 9. dxc3+ {+-}) 7. Ng5 ({Pretty much the only move for White.} 7. O-O $2 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bxb3 9. axb3 f5 {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, as White lost the battle for the centre.}) 7... Qd7 (7... Nd4 {is also okay, but the lines are way too crazy. 🙂 It is usually not good to give up our light-square bishop for a knight, especially when White still has this bishop. However, it works thanks to quick ...[Nd4]-ideas. Also, in case White takes on [e6], we can restrict that bishop by taking back with the pawn.}) 8. Nxe6 fxe6 $1 {[%csl Yb3,Ge6][%cal Ye6d5] With the help of the [e6]-pawn, our centre is well-supported and the [b3]-bishop is not that strong.} 9. O-O d4 {[%cal Yc6a5,Ra5b3]} ({Going after the b3-bishop.} 9... O-O-O {is also very playable, leading to a sharper game.}) 10. Ne2 (10. Nb1 {The knight would be better on [d2] than on [e2], but Black has the strong} d3 $1 {and White's queenside is blocked.} 11. Nc3 Nd4 12. cxd3 O-O-O {-+ With ... [Nec6] and ...[Bc5] coming, Black is completely dominating.}) 10... Na5 11. d3 Nxb3 12. axb3 Nc6 $10 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has no problems and will finish the development with ...[Be7] and [O-O].} *

