1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Bb3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5] White is targeting the [f7]-pawn, and they have ideas like [Ng5].} d5 $1 {[%cal Yb3a4,Ya4e8] Since White already moved the bishop for the 3rd time, and even more importantly, they removed it from pressuring the [c6]-knight, we can afford to go for ...[d5] this early.} ({The alternative is} 5... Ng6 {, but it allows quite a few dangerous lines for White, such as} 6. h4 $5 {or 6.d4 exd4 7.O-O which I didn't like.}) 6. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rb3d5,Re4d5] White is putting more pressure to the [d5]-pawn.} Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Ge7d5]} (6... d4 $4 {is losing the game very quickly. 6...dxe4 is similarly bad.} 7. Ng5 $1 dxc3 8. Bxf7+ Kd7 9. dxc3+ {+-}) 7. Ng5 ({Pretty much the only move for White.} 7. O-O $2 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bxb3 9. axb3 f5 {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, as White lost the battle for the centre.}) 7... Qd7 (7... Nd4 {is also okay, but the lines are way too crazy. 🙂 It is usually not good to give up our light-square bishop for a knight, especially when White still has this bishop. However, it works thanks to quick ...[Nd4]-ideas. Also, in case White takes on [e6], we can restrict that bishop by taking back with the pawn.}) 8. exd5 {This looks critical, since White is getting the bishop pair without our pawn being on [e6].} (8. O-O d4 9. Nxe6 fxe6 {tranposes to 8.Nxe6 fxe6 9.O-O d4 line.}) 8... Bxd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 10. Ne4 {⩲ This is certainly not good.}) 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6d4,Rd4b3,Gf7f6] White's lack of space in the centre is compensated by the bishop pair, but I couldn't find a way for them to pose any problems.} 10. O-O f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf6e5] Stabilising the centre, and avoiding any tricks from the knight.} 11. Qh5+ (11. Nf3 O-O-O {This is already very dangerous for White, since Black has ideas like ...[g5]-[g4] and White has simply no play.} 12. d4 $1 {Basically giving up a pawn.} Nb6 13. c3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Qxd4 {⩱ The bishop pair gives compensation, but White is down a pawn.}) 11... g6 12. Qf3 {[%cal Rb3d5,Rf3d5,Rf3f6] It looks like that Black is in trouble.} O-O-O $1 {Sacrificing a pawn. However, we will win it back, because White will have to save their knight.} 13. Bxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxf6 Be7 $1 {[%cal Re7g5] Forcing [Qe6].} 15. Qe6+ Qxe6 16. Nxe6 Rd5 {[%csl Re6]} 17. d3 h6 $15 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ye6g5,Ye6f4,Ye6d4,Yd3d4] And White will have to give back the pawn, most likely with [d4] in order to escape with the knight.} *

