1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Bb3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5] White is targeting the [f7]-pawn, and they have ideas like [Ng5].} d5 $1 {[%cal Yb3a4,Ya4e8] Since White already moved the bishop for the 3rd time, and even more importantly, they removed it from pressuring the [c6]-knight, we can afford to go for ...[d5] this early.} ({The alternative is} 5... Ng6 {, but it allows quite a few dangerous lines for White, such as} 6. h4 $5 {or 6.d4 exd4 7.O-O which I didn't like.}) 6. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rb3d5,Re4d5] White is putting more pressure to the [d5]-pawn.} Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Ge7d5]} (6... d4 $4 {is losing the game very quickly. 6...dxe4 is similarly bad.} 7. Ng5 $1 dxc3 8. Bxf7+ Kd7 9. dxc3+ {+-}) 7. Ng5 ({Pretty much the only move for White.} 7. O-O $2 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bxb3 9. axb3 f5 {∓ With a clear advantage for Black, as White lost the battle for the centre.}) 7... Qd7 (7... Nd4 {is also okay, but the lines are way too crazy. 🙂 It is usually not good to give up our light-square bishop for a knight, especially when White still has this bishop. However, it works thanks to quick ...[Nd4]-ideas. Also, in case White takes on [e6], we can restrict that bishop by taking back with the pawn.}) 8. exd5 {This looks critical, since White is getting the bishop pair without our pawn being on [e6].} (8. O-O d4 9. Nxe6 fxe6 {tranposes to 8.Nxe6 fxe6 9.O-O d4 line.}) 8... Bxd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 10. Ne4 {⩲ This is certainly not good.}) 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yc6d4,Rd4b3,Gf7f6] White's lack of space in the centre is compensated by the bishop pair, but I couldn't find a way for them to pose any problems.} 10. Qf3 {[%cal Rb3d5,Rf3f7,Rf3d5] White is putting pressure on our weak squares and therefore prevents us from castling long. However, ...[Nd4] could win a huge tempo against this move, so it wins time now, but overall not really.} Rd8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Rd4b3,Rd4f3] ...[Nd4] is a big threat now.} 11. c3 f6 {Starting to kick back White's active pieces.} 12. Nh3 {[%cal Yc6a5,Gb3c2,Gc2f5]} (12. Nh3 {Weird move, but the point is that after} Na5 {, White has} 13. Bc2 $1 {with excellent control over the light squares. From [e4] the knight would block that diagonal.}) 12... g5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g4]} 13. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 14. Qxf6 Qe4+ $1 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Ge4h7] With the point of protecting on [h7].🙂} 15. Kf1 (15. Kd1 Qxg2 16. Qe6+ Be7 17. Rg1 Qf3+ {+ -+ Black is winning with the much safer king.}) 15... Be7 $1 16. Qxh8+ (16. Qf3 Qg6 $1 {-+ ...[g4] is next and then ...[O-O], Black is winning because White has no development.}) 16... Kf7 {[%csl Rh8] And the queen is trapped on [h8]!} 17. Qxd8 Nxd8 $19 {[%csl Ya1,Yc1,Rf1,Yh1,Yh3][%cal Gd8e6,Yg5g4] White has more than enough material for the queen, but all of their pieces are bad, and the king is weak.} *

