1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. d4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yg8f6,Yf6e4] Quite logical, Black didn't attack White's centre, so White immediately tries to get a space advantage.} exd4 6. c3 {[%cal Yd4c3,Gb1c3] Could be some sort of a dangerous gambit line, but Black is definitely not taking on [c3].} d5 $1 {Black is immediately at equalizing with this move.} ({•} 6... dxc3 7. Nxc3 Ng6 8. h4 $1 {is what White wants with 6. [c3].}) ({•} 6... Ng6 {transposes to 5.c3 Ng6 6.d4 exd4 lines, but we don't have easy equality there right away, so it is better to play 6...[d5]! here.}) 7. exd5 (7. Nxd4 dxe4 {...[Bd7] is next, and Black has zero problems.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Qxd4 (8. cxd4 $2 Bg4 $1 9. Nc3 Qh5 {∓ And with ...[O-O-O] coming next, Black was already a lot better in Naroditsky-Bernadskiy, Wijk aan Zee 2011.}) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 b5 $1 {Gaining the pair of bishops or creating an isolated pawn.} 10. Bb3 (10. Nxc6 bxa4 11. Nd4 Bd7 {⩱ this is also slightly better for Black, because of the pair of bishops.}) 10... Nxd4 11. cxd4 Nf5 $15 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gc8b7,Rf5d4,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Ge8c8] Black has the better chances in this endgame with the healthier pawn structure.} *

