[GameId "2160376127287501"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. d4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yg8f6,Yf6e4] Quite logical, Black didn't attack White's centre, so White immediately tries to get a space advantage.} exd4 6. Nxd4 (6. O-O Ng6 {transposes to 5. [O-O] [Ng6] main lines.}) 6... Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Ge7c6,Rc6d4] After the trade, we can speed up our development.} 7. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gf8c5] White has a lot of options now, but none seem to be very dangerous for Black.} 8. Qd3 Bc5 9. Nc3 (9. Be3 {The position is quite equal after this move.} Bxe3 10. Qxe3 b5 11. Bb3 O-O 12. a4 Rb8 13. Nc3 d6 14. axb5 axb5 15. O-O Be6) 9... O-O 10. Qg3 {[%cal Yc1g5,Yg5h6] With some ideas like [Bg5] or [Bh6].} d6 11. Bg5 (11. Bh6 $6 {Actually, doesn't achieve anything because after} Qf6 12. Bg5 Bxf2+ $1 {-+ Black is winning a pawn.}) 11... f6 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf6f5] Not really a weakening move, since Black is playing for ...[f5] many times in this line.} 12. Bh6 Qe7 13. O-O-O Be6 $132 {[%cal Gg8h8,Yb7b5] With a complex game where Black's chances are not worse at all. We can play ...[Kh8] or start pushing the queenside with ...[b5] right away.} *

