1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. d4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yg8f6,Yf6e4] Quite logical, Black didn't attack White's centre, so White immediately tries to get a space advantage.} exd4 6. Nxd4 (6. O-O Ng6 {transposes to 5. [O-O] [Ng6] main lines.}) 6... Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Ge7c6,Rc6d4] After the trade, we can speed up our development.} 7. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gf8c5] White has a lot of options now, but none seem to be very dangerous for Black.} 8. Qe3 $5 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ge3c5] If White decides to move the queen, this looks like the square to go to. Black's bishop wants to go to [c5] in general, but now it is prevented.} Bd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yb7b5,Yc8b7] Not as awkward as in the Spanish Four Knights. 🙂 Here we can quite easily develop our other bishop by playing ...[b5] and ...[Bb7] so that the dark-squared bishop can even stay on [d6].} 9. e5 $2 {[%cal Re3e8] Trying to use the pin on the e-file and gain a huge tempo on the bishop.} O-O $1 {[%cal Rf8e8,Re8e1] Black is doing the same! 🙂} 10. f4 Bxe5 $1 {[%cal Rd8h4,Rh4a4] The bishop is unprotected on [a4]!} 11. Bxc6 (11. fxe5 Qh4+ 12. Qg3 Qxa4 13. Bh6 Qe4+ {+ -+ With taking on [e5] in the next move, Black is completely winning.}) 11... Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Yf8e8]} 12. Be4 d5 $19 {[%csl Gc8,Re1,Re3,Gf6][%cal Gf8e8] Black is much better with or without an extra pawn.} *

