1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Nc3 {I struggled against this move the most. White is making it very difficult to play for ...[d5] and also once the knight goes to [d5] it is not so easy to deal with it. Besides these things, White also didn't give up on the [d4]-idea, so Black has to be ready for a lot of things.} d6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yb7b5,Ya4b3,Yc6a5,Ra5b3] By protecting the pawn on [e5], Black is ready to go after White's bishop with ...[b5] and then ...[Na5].} (5... Ng6 {I didn't really like because of the line} 6. h4 $1 h5 7. d4 $1 {and Black is struggling there. I was also looking at 5...[g6], but not only I didn't like it too much, I would really prefer to play with ...[Ng6] in all the lines.}) 6. d4 $6 {Strangely enough this is the second most popular move from White, but this is just not good.} b5 $1 7. Bb3 Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Yc7c5,Yc5c4] White's bishop on [b3] can easily get into danger.} 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Qh5 {[%cal Rh5f7,Rb3f7] This move saves White from a worse position.} ({•} 9. Qxd4 $4 c5 $1 {-+ And with ...[c4] next, Black is winning a piece.}) ({•} 9. Qf3 Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Ne2 c5 {⩱ White has some compensation, but not nearly enough for a full pawn.}) ({•} 9. Nd5 c5 $1 {Protecting the extra pawn.} 10. Nxe7 Bxe7 11. Bd5 Rb8 {∓ Black is just much better here.}) 9... Ng6 (9... g6 10. Qf3 Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Qf6 {White is taking back the pawn with a normal game.}) 10. Nd5 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Yb8b6,Gc7c6] Covering the [b6]-square and, with that, preparing to play ...[c6].} (10... c6 11. Bg5 $1 {And it is just a draw after ...[Qa5]+, because if} f6 {White has} 12. Nf4 $1 {± And Black is in trouble. (11...Qa5+ 12.Bd2 Qd8=)}) 11. O-O c6 12. Bg5 Qd7 $17 {[%cal Yb8a8,Rd5b6,Rb6a8,Rb6d7] With the rook on [a8], this move wouldn't be available.} *

