... [Ng6].} 5. Nc3 {I struggled against this move the most. White is making it very difficult to play for ...[d5] and also once the knight goes to [d5] it is not so easy to deal with it. Besides these things, White also didn't give up on the [d4]-idea, so Black has to be ready for a lot of things.} d6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yb7b5,Ya4b3,Yc6a5,Ra5b3] By protecting the pawn on [e5], Black is ready to go after White's bishop with ...[b5] and then ...[Na5].} (5... Ng6 {I didn't really like because of the line} 6. h4 $1 h5 7. d4 $1 {and Black is struggling there. I was also looking at 5...[g6], but not only I didn't like it too much, I would really prefer to play with ...[Ng6] in all the lines.}) 6. a3 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ga4b3,Gb3a2,Gd2d4] One of the two dangerous lines, White is preparing the [a2]-square for the bishop, so Black's main plan is not working now. It is also important that we have to be ready for [d4] as well, since we can't trap the bishop with ...[c5]-[c4] anymore.} Bd7 {This looks like a decent preparation against [d4], by breaking the pin on the knight, and not chasing the bishop to a better diagonal with ... [b5], but potentially trading it later.} (6... Ng6 {I still didn't like this move, because after} 7. d4 b5 8. Bb3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bd5 $1 {⩲ Thanks to this move, we can't even restrict the bishop with ...[c5]-[c4].}) 7. O-O Nd4 $1 {This novelty seems to solve Black's problems.} 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge2d4] It looks like that Black is worse with the inferior pawn structure, but there is the nice} d5 $1 {and everything is just fine for Black.} 11. e5 (11. d3 dxe4 12. dxe4 O-O-O {⇆ ...[Nc6] is next, and Black is doing well.}) 11... Nc6 12. f4 f6 $1 {Undermining White's centre.} 13. exf6 d3 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Yd2,Yd3][%cal Yc2d3] Slowing down White's development and creating a bad pawn structure.} 14. cxd3 O-O-O $132 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1,Ye2] We are down 2 pawns for now, but White is behind in development with a pretty bad pawn structure.} *

