1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. Nc3 {I struggled against this move the most. White is making it very difficult to play for ...[d5] and also once the knight goes to [d5] it is not so easy to deal with it. Besides these things, White also didn't give up on the [d4]-idea, so Black has to be ready for a lot of things.} d6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yb7b5,Ya4b3,Yc6a5,Ra5b3] By protecting the pawn on [e5], Black is ready to go after White's bishop with ...[b5] and then ...[Na5].} (5... Ng6 {I didn't really like because of the line} 6. h4 $1 h5 7. d4 $1 {and Black is struggling there. I was also looking at 5...[g6], but not only I didn't like it too much, I would really prefer to play with ...[Ng6] in all the lines.}) 6. O-O (6. d3 {Not a good move, since it allows Black to go after White's light-squared bishop.} b5 7. Bb3 Na5 {In such cases, when we are getting the pair of bishops, but lose a bit of control over the centre, White's best try is to go for [d4].} 8. O-O Nxb3 9. axb3 b4 10. Ne2 Ng6 {Black has a good game with the bishop pair.}) 6... Rb8 {Not a huge surprise that this move was only played once before. 🙂 Probably the most mysterious move of the whole repertoire, but it is just crucial not to allow White to play [Bd5] with a tempo in some lines, so we can continue the development with ...[Ng6].} 7. h3 {[%cal Yd2d4,Yc8g4,Gh3g4] A useful move for White, since once they go for [d4], they don't have to worry about ...[Bg4] anymore.} Ng6 8. Nd5 (8. d4 b5 9. Bb3 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 {⩱ And now you can see the point of ...[Rb8], there is no [Bd5]! with a tempo.}) 8... b5 9. Bb3 Na5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Ra5b3] We get rid of the bishop. However, since White is pretty strong in the centre, we still have to fight for equality.} 10. d4 Be7 11. Bd2 Nxb3 12. axb3 {[%cal Gd2a5] White has the threat of [Ba5].} Bb7 13. c4 O-O $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gd5,Ge4][%cal Yc7c6,Yf7f5,Yg8h8] I'll not question the computer's evaluation here, that White is slightly better, but I can see decent counter chances for Black, by kicking back the knight with ...[c6] or playing for ...[f5].} *

