... [Ng6].} 5. Nc3 {I struggled against this move the most. White is making it very difficult to play for ...[d5] and also once the knight goes to [d5] it is not so easy to deal with it. Besides these things, White also didn't give up on the [d4]-idea, so Black has to be ready for a lot of things.} d6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5,Yb7b5,Ya4b3,Yc6a5,Ra5b3] By protecting the pawn on [e5], Black is ready to go after White's bishop with ...[b5] and then ...[Na5].} (5... Ng6 {I didn't really like because of the line} 6. h4 $1 h5 7. d4 $1 {and Black is struggling there. I was also looking at 5...[g6], but not only I didn't like it too much, I would really prefer to play with ...[Ng6] in all the lines.}) 6. O-O (6. d3 {Not a good move, since it allows Black to go after White's light-squared bishop.} b5 7. Bb3 Na5 {In such cases, when we are getting the pair of bishops, but lose a bit of control over the centre, White's best try is to go for [d4].} 8. O-O Nxb3 9. axb3 b4 10. Ne2 Ng6 {Black has a good game with the bishop pair.}) 6... Ng6 {This line shows why we 'need' to play ...[Rb8] first.} 7. d4 b5 8. Bb3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Bd5 {[%cal Yc7c5] Otherwise we would be completely fine, but now it will not be possible for Black to advance ...[c5]-[c4] with tempo.} Rb8 11. Bc6+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd4a7,Gd4f7,Gf2f4,Yf8e7,Ra7b8,Ra7a6] White is clearly better here; they have targets on the queenside, and [f4] is already possible as well.} *

