1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. h4 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Gh4h5] Played only in a few OTB games, but it is always important to know how to react against this pawn push, which is clearly targeting the placement of our knight on [g6].} Be7 $1 {This is the best move! The inclusion of [h4]-[h5] before playing [d4] would clearly favour White as our kingside has now been weakened and the knight can jump to [g5].} 7. g3 h5 $1 {But now ...[h5] is well-timed! We have better development than on the previous move, so we can react aggressively against [d4].} 8. d4 d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] As usual, if we can play this move then we are doing great.} 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg4 12. f3 Be6 {∞ White has won a pawn but their position is extremely loose. Our bishop pair is very strong and we have at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Ngxe5 10. dxe5 b5 $1 11. Bb3 $2 Nxe5 $1 12. Qxd5 {[%cal Yc8g4,Yg4d1,Rd5e5,Rd5a8] Quite importantly, the queen is going away from the ...[Bg4] tempo.} Bg4 $1 {It still works!} 13. Qxe5 {This is practically the only move to consider, otherwise Black will have very significant compensation for the pawn.} Qd3 $1 {[%cal Rd3e2] Mate in 1 threat!} 14. f3 Qxf3 $1 {[%cal Rf3h1,Rf3e2]} 15. Rh2 O-O-O $1 {Not an easy line, it is easy to go wrong with both colours.} 16. Bf4 {[%cal Re5c7] White is also creating their own threats.} (16. Qxe7 $2 Rhe8 {-+ is quite easy.}) 16... Rd1+ $1 17. Bxd1 Qxd1+ 18. Kf2 Qe2+ 19. Kg1 Qe1+ 20. Kg2 Bd6 $1 {We have more than just perpetual check.} 21. Qd5 Bxf4 22. gxf4 Rd8 23. Qa8+ Kd7 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Rg2]} 24. Qd5+ Ke8 25. Qe5+ Kf8 $19 {[%cal Ge1e2,Yd8d3,Yd3d1] Black escaped from the checks, and White has no defence.} *

