 we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. h4 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Gh4h5] Played only in a few OTB games, but it is always important to know how to react against this pawn push, which is clearly targeting the placement of our knight on [g6].} Be7 $1 {This is the best move! The inclusion of [h4]-[h5] before playing [d4] would clearly favour White as our kingside has now been weakened and the knight can jump to [g5].} 7. g3 h5 $1 {But now ...[h5] is well-timed! We have better development than on the previous move, so we can react aggressively against [d4].} 8. d4 d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] As usual, if we can play this move then we are doing great.} 9. Nxe5 (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg4 12. f3 Be6 {∞ White has won a pawn but their position is extremely loose. Our bishop pair is very strong and we have at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Ngxe5 10. dxe5 b5 $1 11. Bc2 ({•} 11. Qxd5 $6 Qxd5 12. exd5 Nxe5 13. Bb3 Bf5 {∓ The engine already indicates a big advantage for Black as there are many weak squares in White's position, and it is also unlikely that they can keep their extra pawn.}) (11. exd5 $4 {Big mistake, it takes away the [d5]-square from the queen. 12...Nxe5 12.Bb3 Bg4 There is no good square for White's queen. 13.Qc2 Qd7 -+ White's king is horribly weak.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Bf4 (12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. exd5 Bb7 {⩱ Black is taking back the pawn with a more developed position.}) 12... Ng6 (12... Bg4 {Is not so dangerous now, because White has} 13. Qxd5 $1) 13. Be3 Bb7 $10 {Black has at least equal chances here, White's position is quite loose on the kingside.} *

