1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. h4 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Gh4h5] Played only in a few OTB games, but it is always important to know how to react against this pawn push, which is clearly targeting the placement of our knight on [g6].} Be7 $1 {This is the best move! The inclusion of [h4]-[h5] before playing [d4] would clearly favour White as our kingside has now been weakened and the knight can jump to [g5].} 7. d4 Nxh4 $1 {Why not? White doesn't have the [h5]-threat anymore.} 8. Nxh4 Bxh4 9. d5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh1h7] White definitely has good compensation, but it is only enough for an unclear game.} Na5 $1 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Yb7b5,Ya5b3] The goal is to play ...[b5]! and then bring the knight back in to play via [c4] or [b7]. All other ideas were not good at this point. Controlling the [b3]-square will be vital in the future if White plays [d6].} (9... Na7 $2 10. d6 $1 cxd6 11. Bb3 {± White is much better here. Our pieces are misplaced and it will be very tough to finish development. White can just bring the queen to [h5] and then the knight to [c4].}) 10. Nd2 (10. d6 {(Once the bishop can't go to [b3] and the knight to [c4] this idea is not so dangerous.)} cxd6 11. Qd5 O-O {∞ White still has enough compensation according to the engine, but it doesn't look that scary, we can continue with ...[Rb8] and ...[b5]. (11.Qxd6 Qf6! is a huge tempo on the [f2]-pawn. )}) 10... Bg5 11. b4 b5 $132 {[%cal Yg5d2,Ga5c4] Black can take on [d2] and then play ...[Nc4] and we are completely fine.} *

