1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. h4 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Gh4h5] Played only in a few OTB games, but it is always important to know how to react against this pawn push, which is clearly targeting the placement of our knight on [g6].} Be7 $1 {This is the best move! The inclusion of [h4]-[h5] before playing [d4] would clearly favour White as our kingside has now been weakened and the knight can jump to [g5].} 7. h5 Nf4 $1 {[%cal Rf4d3,Rf4g2]} 8. d4 {A typical pawn sacrifice, but the knight doesn't have to return to [f4].} Nxg2+ 9. Kf1 Nh4 (9... Nf4 $2 10. d5 {± Followed by [Nxe5], and Black is in a very bad shape.}) 10. d5 {If the [c6]-knight moves, White takes the pawn on [e5].} Nxf3 11. Qxf3 (11. dxc6 $2 {Isn't dangerous at all.} Ng5 {-+ Everything is protected, White is just a pawn down.}) 11... Na5 {A very important move! Everything else would be rather bad for Black. The knight from [a5] can re-enter the game much more easily than from [b8] or [a7], and also takes away the bishop's [b3]-square.} 12. Rg1 ({Pretty logical, White is putting pressure on the g-file.} 12. Qg3 {Attacking [g7] and [e5].} Bf6 $1 13. Nd2 b5 14. Bc2 Nc4 {∞ It doesn't look too dangerous for Black.}) 12... g5 {If Black is in time to play ...[f6], then even ...[O-O] is safe, as White can't open the kingside.} 13. h6 {Freeing the [h5]-square for the queen.} O-O 14. Nd2 Kh8 $13 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga5c4,Gf7f6] If necessary, ...[f6] is available. We also plan to bring back the knight by playing ...[b5] and ...[Nc4]. The position is very unusual, but it is not obvious how White should compensate for the missing pawn.} *

