1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Yf7f5,Gd4f5,Yd7d5,Yd4c6] This capture does not look very logical, as White prepared [d4] with [c3], but actually the move is not bad at all. The point is that if Black exchanges knights on [d4], then their chances for counterplay are seriously reduced. If they don't exchange on [d4], then the knight is well placed, controlling both of our breaks, pressurising [c6] and covering the [f5]-square.} Bc5 (7... Nxd4 $2 8. cxd4 {±}) 8. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd4c6] With the threat of [Nxc6], since our bishop is not protected on [c5].} (8. O-O O-O {transposes here.}) 8... Nce5 $1 {[%cal Yf7f5,Yd7d5,Ge5c4,Yc4e3,Ge5g4,Yg4e3] If ...[f5] and ...[d5] are not possible, we should look for counterplay with our pieces. The knight wants to attack the [e3]-bishop from [c4] or [g4].} 9. Nf5 ({Not bad, but our task is nevertheless easier than against the main line,} 9. Qe2 {.}) 9... Bxe3 10. Nxe3 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ye3d5,Ye3f5] The knight has moved around quite a lot, but in return it arrived to its best square in this structure, from where it controls both [f5], and [d5]-squares.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] We would like to develop our bishop to the [b7]-square.} 11. Bc2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2e4] Protecting the [e4]-pawn in advance.} (11. Bb3 $6 Bb7 12. O-O {This is better than protecting the pawn on [e4], but in any case, Black can accept it!} Bxe4 $1 13. f4 Nd3 14. Bd5 $1 ({This was White's point, since} 14. f5 {leads nowhere, because of} Qg5 $1) 14... f5 $1 {Only this nice sacrifice gives advantage to Black.} 15. Bxa8 Qxa8 {∞ The knight on [d3] and the bishop on [e4] are dominating.}) 11... Bb7 12. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4] We have to be very careful now, as [f4] is a big threat.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Yg6f4,Yf6f4]} 13. Nd2 O-O 14. g3 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf2f4] This is the way to push for [f4], but is also weakens White's kingside.} Qb6 $132 {[%cal Yb6g1,Yb7h1,Ga8e8,Gg6e7,Yf7f5] The bishop and the queen are very nicely putting pressure from the diagonals, so it is not so easy for White to play [f4].} (14... Qb6 {A possible continuation is} 15. Qe2 d6 16. Rae1 {Overprotecting the knight on [e3], so Black doesn't have ...[Ng4] ideas anymore.} (16. f4 {It's still not a problem, because Black has} Ng4 $1) 16... Nd7 $1 {Avoiding [f4] with tempo, and getting ready to attack the [e4]-pawn, in case White starts pushing the f-pawn.} 17. f4 Rfe8 18. Qf2 Nf6 {⇆ White has more space, but Black has good counterplay against the [e4]-pawn.}) *

