1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Yf7f5,Gd4f5,Yd7d5,Yd4c6] This capture does not look very logical, as White prepared [d4] with [c3], but actually the move is not bad at all. The point is that if Black exchanges knights on [d4], then their chances for counterplay are seriously reduced. If they don't exchange on [d4], then the knight is well placed, controlling both of our breaks, pressurising [c6] and covering the [f5]-square.} Bc5 (7... Nxd4 $2 8. cxd4 {±}) 8. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd4c6] With the threat of [Nxc6], since our bishop is not protected on [c5].} (8. O-O O-O {transposes here.}) 8... Nce5 $1 {[%cal Yf7f5,Yd7d5,Ge5c4,Yc4e3,Ge5g4,Yg4e3] If ...[f5] and ...[d5] are not possible, we should look for counterplay with our pieces. The knight wants to attack the [e3]-bishop from [c4] or [g4].} 9. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ye2c4]} b5 {[%cal Ge5c4]} 10. Bb3 {White is controlling the [c4]-square.} (10. Bc2 Nc4 {⇆}) 10... Qf6 {[%cal Yf2f4,Yg6f4] Not only stopping [f4], but we can also play [Nf4] sometimes!} 11. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ge1c1] With the option of castling long now, and [f4] would then be a much more serious threat.} (11. O-O {Not a good move, because White should use the fact that the king still could castle in the other way. With the king on [g1], it is much more difficult to go for [f4]-[e5], since the king can be exposed.} Nf4 $1 12. Bxf4 Qxf4 {⇆ And Black is in a good shape, since against the bishop on [c5] and soon on [b7], it doesn't look like a good plan to play [g3]-[f4].}) 11... d6 {[%cal Ye5g4,Rg4e3] With ideas of ...[Ng4] attacking the bishop.} 12. h3 {[%cal Yh3g4]} O-O 13. g3 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] Preparing to push [f4].} (13. O-O-O {This allows Black to start counterplay immediately on the queenside.} b4 $1 {⇆}) 13... Bxd4 {Giving up the pair of bishops and creating the centre that White wanted doesn't exactly look logical, but we need to create some counterplay. And apparently, we can do it like this.} 14. cxd4 (14. Bxd4 c5 $1 15. Be3 c4 16. Bc2 Bb7 17. f4 Nd3+ 18. Bxd3 cxd3 19. Qxd3 Qe6 20. f5 Ne5 {∞ And Black has decent counter-chances because of the weak light squares in White's position.}) 14... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Rc6d4]} 15. Nf3 ({•} 15. Bd5 $2 Nge7 $1 {⩱}) ({•} 15. Qd3 a5 {⇆ With ...[a4] and then maybe ...[b4] or ...[Ba6]/[Bb7] coming, the position is not so clear.}) 15... h6 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Ge3g5,Rg5f6,Gh6g5] Better to avoid [Bg5] tricks.} 16. g4 (16. O-O-O a5 $1 {The computer already prefers Black with serious attacking chances on the queenside.}) 16... Nf4 17. e5 $1 {White is winning a piece, but just temporarily.} dxe5 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Bxf4 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Rc8b7,Rb7h1] ...[Bb7] is an unpleasant threat.} 20. Be5 Qc6 21. O-O Bb7 22. Rfc1 {White has nothing better than going for the endgame.} Qxf3 23. Qxf3 Bxf3 24. Bxc7 Rac8 $14 {White is slightly better with the pair of bishops, but Black should be able to hold this position, especially if we manage to trade the light-squared bishops.} *

