1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] An interesting line, White wants to force Black to play ...[h5], and only then take back on [d4], which of course would be highly beneficial for our opponent, since our kingside position would be weakened, and it would be difficult to meet [Ng5].} d3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3] It is better to give back the pawn than to speed up our opponent's develpoment!} 8. h5 Nge5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. f4 b5 $1 {[%cal Ga4b3,Ye5c4] A very important intermezzo! Black is forcing the bishop to [b3] before playing [Nc4].} (10... Nc4 $2 11. Qxd3 b5 12. Bc2 $1 {± And the bishop is much better on [c2] than on [b3], when it is not blocked by the knight on [c4].}) 11. Bb3 Nc4 12. Qxd3 {[%csl Gc4] Black will have to sacrifice a pawn now, but we will have very good compensation for it. We will have the pair of bishops, and White's position is somewhat overextended.} d5 $1 (12... Bb7 {, played already in 2 OTB games, is also decent.}) 13. exd5 (13. Qxd5 Qxd5 14. exd5 Bb7 $1 {Black is regaining the pawn, and has very good chances in this endgame.} 15. Nd2 Nb6) 13... Bc5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e8] Keeping White's king in the centre.} 14. Qe2+ $1 {The only move for White to keep the balance.} Kd7 {[%cal Gh8e8] Better than to [Kf8], since now ... [Re8] is a threat.} 15. Qg4+ Ke7 $10 (15... Ke7 {A draw is very likely now, as White has nothing better than repeating moves.} 16. Qe2+ Kd7) (15... Ke7 {•} 16. Qg5+ $2 Kd6 {(16...f6 is also winning, but going for the endgame looks easier. )} 17. Kd1 Qxg5 18. fxg5 Bg4+ 19. Kc2 Bf5+ 20. Kd1 Kxd5 {-+}) (15... Ke7 {•} 16. Qxg7 $4 Rg8 17. Qxh7 Re8 $1 {-+ And White's king is very weak.}) *

