1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Bd2 {A rare, but tricky line, played amongst others by GM's Wesley So and Peter Svidler.} O-O $1 9. d5 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 b5 (10... Nce5 {would probably lead to the same thing.}) 11. Bb3 (11. Bc2 Nce5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O f5 $1 {Challenging White in the centre.} 14. exf5 d6 {With ...[Bxf5] next, Black is completely fine.}) 11... Nce5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4] f4 is already a big threat, so Black has to act quickly.} a5 $1 {[%cal Ya5a4]} 14. f4 a4 {Black is just in time to avoid a very passive and bad position.} 15. Bc2 (15. fxe5 axb3 {This is a very good trade for Black.} 16. a3 Qe7 17. Qf4 b4 18. Rf3 f5 $5 {Weakening White's centre.} 19. exf5 Bb7 {⇆ With a messy position, but the bishop is very strong.}) 15... Nc4 16. Qd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge4,Gf4] White has good central control which we need to challenge.} Qf6 $1 17. e5 (17. Qxf6 gxf6 {∞ The engine slightly prefers White here, but it looks very double-edged to me.}) 17... Qb6 $10 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8b7,Gc4b6,Yf7f6] And Black is completely fine, we can target the [d5]-pawn, and also have the chance to undermine the centre with ... [f6].} *

