1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Bd2 {A rare, but tricky line, played amongst others by GM's Wesley So and Peter Svidler.} O-O $1 9. Bxb4 {Played by both So and Svidler.} Nxb4 10. a3 (10. Nc3 $6 {This is too slow.} d5 $1 {Black is already fine here, since} 11. a3 {can be met by} dxe4 $1 {∓}) 10... Nc6 11. d5 b5 {Asking the bishop whether it wants to go to [c2] or [b3].} 12. Bb3 (12. Bc2 Nce5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 {⇆ And we have the [c4]-square for the knight.}) 12... Na5 $1 {[%cal Ra5b3] This is the difference! We don't have to go to [e5] now.} 13. Ba2 c5 $15 {[%csl Ya2][%cal Gd7d6] And Black is already slightly better, since White's bishop on [a2] is very passive.} *

