 we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Bd2 {A rare, but tricky line, played amongst others by GM's Wesley So and Peter Svidler.} O-O $1 9. Bxb4 {Played by both So and Svidler.} Nxb4 10. a3 (10. Nc3 $6 {This is too slow.} d5 $1 {Black is already fine here, since} 11. a3 {can be met by} dxe4 $1 {∓}) 10... Nc6 11. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] White prevents ...[d5] before castling.} (11. O-O d5 $1) 11... d6 {[%cal Yf7f5] Fortunately we have the alternative plan of challenging White's centre with ...[f5]!} 12. h4 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge1g1] This is always a possiblity for White if they have not castled yet.} b5 13. Bc2 (13. Bb3 {Loses a tempo to} Na5 $1 14. Ba2 Nc4 {⇆}) 13... Bg4 14. Qd2 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qf6 $132 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gg6f4] With strong control over the [f4]-square, Black is doing fine.} *

