1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Nc3 d5 $1 ({We have to strike in the centre right away!} 8... O-O 9. O-O {would just make our position clearly worse.}) 9. O-O dxe4 $1 {We should avoid getting tricked into a bad line.} (9... Bxc3 $2 10. exd5 $1 Qxd5 11. Bb3 $1 {is shown in the 9.exd5 illustrative line.}) 10. Ng5 {[%csl Rb4,Rf7][%cal Ya4c6,Yb7c6,Yd1b3,Yb3b4,Yb3f7] There are now some tactical tricks based on [Qb3], but we want to castle anyway.} O-O {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8f7] No more problems on [f7].} 11. Qh5 (11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ngxe4 a5 13. a3 Be7 {⇆ This was played in Pichot-G.Pap, chess.com 2023, and the computer already slightly prefers Black because of the bishop pair and potential ...[f5]-[f4] ideas.} 14. Qa4 f5 15. Nc5 Rb8 {⇆} 16. Qxc6 Qxd4 17. Be3 Qf6 {⩱}) 11... h6 12. Nxf7 {We are a pawn up, so we can decide when to return the material.} Rxf7 13. Bxc6 (13. Qxg6 Nxd4 {...[Bf5] is coming and we also prevented [Bb3].}) 13... bxc6 14. Qxg6 Qxd4 $10 {[%csl Gb4,Gc8] White can take the pawn on [e4] or [c6], but with the pair of bishops we are fine.} *

