1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Nc3 d5 $1 ({We have to strike in the centre right away!} 8... O-O 9. O-O {would just make our position clearly worse.}) 9. O-O dxe4 $1 {We should avoid getting tricked into a bad line.} (9... Bxc3 $2 10. exd5 $1 Qxd5 11. Bb3 $1 {is shown in the 9.exd5 illustrative line.}) 10. Nxe4 O-O {[%csl Yb4,Yc6,Yg6][%cal Yd4d5] White does have an isolated pawn, but unfortunately our pieces are not so well positioned to blockade it.} 11. d5 Nce7 12. Bb3 (12. a3 Bf5 $1 {Gaining a nice tempo for developing the bishop.} 13. Ng3 Bd6 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 15. Bc2 Qd7 {∞ White has the pair of bishops, but we have the better structure.}) 12... h6 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gf3g5,Yh6g5] An important defensive move. As our knight is on [g6] and not [f6], both [Bg5] and, more importantly, [Ng5] could have created unpleasant threats on [h7] and [f7].} 13. a3 Ba5 (13... Bd6 {would give White a free hand to develop their initiative, since we remove the bishop from covering the [e1]-square and also block the attack towards the [d5]-pawn.}) 14. Ba2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2,Ya5e1,Gf1e1] White wants to bring the dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal, and also provide the [e1]-square for the rook.} (14. d6 {Only leads to simplifications.} Nf5 $1 15. dxc7 Qxc7 {Black is completely fine in this symmetrical position.}) 14... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] Our bishop goes to [b7].} 15. b4 Bb6 16. Bb2 Bb7 $132 {The game can get very sharp in the next few moves in different ways, but Black seems to be doing fine everywhere.} *

