1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Yc3d4] One of the most popular options against our setup, White is playing for [d4] and intends to recapture with the pawn.} Ng6 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is trying to occupy the centre with their pawns, but as we will see, things are not so simple.} (6. O-O d5 $1 {is analysed via the 5. [O-O] [Ng6] 6. [c3] [d5] move order.}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] We have to develop quickly and then challenge White's centre, otherwise we are just worse.} 8. Nc3 d5 $1 ({We have to strike in the centre right away!} 8... O-O 9. O-O {would just make our position clearly worse.}) 9. exd5 Bxc3+ $1 {An unusual move order, but we have to force White to take back on [c3].} 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. Ba3 {Although it prevents Black from castle, it is not a very challenging move, since Black can castle on the queenside as well. It was tried against me recently, Marson-Valkova, Spilimbergo 2024.} Bg4 ({I played} 11... Qe4+ {, which is also good, but creating doubled f-pawns is maybe even better.}) 12. h3 {White has to neutralise the pin immediately.} ({•} 12. O-O O-O-O {∓ This is just bad, since Black can continue with ...[Nh4].}) ({•} 12. Qe2+ Kd8 $1 {The pin on the f-knight is more problematic than the position of Black's king.} 13. O-O Re8 {∓ White has to find very difficult moves in order not to lose quickly.}) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 O-O-O $13 {White has the bishop pair, but their structure is extremely weak, so Black has good chances in this endgame.} *

