1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc3d5] White is stopping ...[d5], but on the other hand they are delaying [c3]-[d4], which gives Black the time to prepare against it.} Bc5 7. Nd5 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gd2d4] White idea is to play [c3] next, and then [d4].} Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc7c6,Yc6d5] Preparing to play ... [c6] and chase away White's knight from the centre.} 8. Nxd4 (8. c3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 c6 10. Ne3 O-O {Black is completely fine, we can play for both ...[f5] and ...[d5] later.}) 8... Bxd4 9. c3 {[%cal Yc7c6] White still can play [c3] and [d4], but having the ...[c6] resource is just great for Black.} Ba7 10. d4 O-O 11. dxe5 c6 $1 (11... Nxe5 $6 {This would allow a much improved version for White, when the bishop is not closed by the knight on [e3].} 12. Be3 {⩲}) 12. Ne3 Nxe5 13. Qd6 Re8 $10 {[%csl Yc1,Ye4][%cal Ga7b8,Ge8e6] We can easily kick out the queen from [d6], and then organise some counterplay against the [e4]-pawn or on the kingside.} *

