1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. Re1 {[%cal Ye4d5,Ge1e5] This move is very good against ...[d5], but doesn't help much with [c3]-[d4].} Bc5 7. c3 Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Yd2d4,Yh4f3] The knight from [g6] sometimes can even fight against the [d4]-break!} 8. d4 (8. d3 {Does not pose any problems for Black.} O-O 9. Nbd2 d6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 Bb6 {⇆ Now Black has the worst structure, but has chances for breaks like ...[f5] or ...[c5].}) 8... Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 exd4 10. e5 $1 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gf3g3,Gd2e4] White is hoping for some kind of attack on the kingside with the space advantage the [e5]-pawn provides.} O-O 11. Nd2 (11. Qg3 f6 $1 {⩱ And White has to trade the [e5]-pawn.}) 11... dxc3 12. Ne4 Be7 13. Qxc3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] We have to give back the material, but don't have any defending to do.} 14. exd6 cxd6 $10 {White can take back the pawn on [c6] now, or a move later, with an equal position.} *

