1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The most common move, White is pushing for [d4] right away.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg6e5] It is extremely rare that Black can play ...[d5] so early in the Ruy Lopez. And it is not even bad! This is all possible, because the main defender of the [e5]-pawn is not the [c6], but the [g6]-knight.} 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. d4 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8,Yg4f3,Ye5d4] Putting pressure on the knight and the [d4]-pawn, while also preparing to castle long.} 9. Bb3 Bxf3 $1 {We should go for an equal endgame, retreating with the queen would be pretty dangerous.} (9... Qd7 $6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {⩲ White is better with the strong bishop on [b3].}) 10. Bxd5 (10. gxf3 $2 {This is just very bad.} Qd7 {∓ Black castles long next, with a big advantage.}) 10... Bxd1 11. Rxd1 (11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Rxd1 O-O-O 13. Be3 Bc5 {We can double on the d-file, or just take on [d4] and create an isolated pawn, the chances are equal.}) 11... O-O-O $1 {[%cal Rd8d4] Giving up [f7] for [d4].} 12. Bxf7 (12. dxe5 Ngxe5 {White has the bishop pair, but it is hard to play around this pin on the d-file.}) 12... exd4 13. cxd4 (13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Ngxe7 {After trading the bishop pair, Black has really nothing to worry about.} 15. Nd2 Rhf8 16. Be6+ Kb8 {⇆}) 13... Nxd4 {[%cal Rd4e2]} 14. Nc3 Ne2+ $1 {[%cal Re2c1] Taking the [c1]-bishop and completely equalising the game.} 15. Kf1 Rxd1+ 16. Nxd1 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 Ne5 $132 {[%csl Ga6,Gb7,Gc7,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2] There are pawn majorities on the different sides of the board, so still a lot can happen, but it is just an equal position for now.} *

