1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4] White is preventing the trade on [d4], since we don't want to give such strong central pawns to our opponent.} O-O 9. Be3 Nce5 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5,Ge5g4,Ge5c4] Now, we can create counterplay with a similar idea as before.} 10. Bb3 {This was played in Arizmendi Martinez-Bartel, Spain 2022, and here Black could have tried ...[d5]!} d5 $1 {[%cal Re5g4] Sacrificing a pawn, but renewing the threat of ...[Ng4].} 11. Bxd5 Ng4 12. Nd2 (12. Qe2 c6 13. Bb3 Qc7 14. g3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Ba7 $1 {∞ With threats like ...[c5]-[c4] and ...[Ne5]-... [Bg4], Black has excellent compensation.}) 12... c6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Rc7h2] We don't have to rush with taking on [e3].} 13. Bb3 Qc7 (13... Nxe3 $5 14. fxe3 Qg5 {∞ The doubled e-pawns give Black sufficient compensation.}) 14. N2f3 Ba7 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gc6c5,Gc5c4,Re8e4] Keeping the pressure, and it is not so easy to play White's position.} *

