y ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. c3 {White is preventing the trade on [d4], since we don't want to give such strong central pawns to our opponent.} O-O 9. Be3 Nce5 {Now, we can create counterplay with a similar idea as before.} 10. Bb3 {This was played in Arizmendi Martinez-Bartel, Spain 2022, and here Black could have tried ...[d5]!} d5 {Sacrificing a pawn, but renewing the threat of ...[Ng4].} 11. Ne6 $2 {[%cal Ye3c5,Re6d8] Positionally entirely justified, as White gets the bishop pair, but with the best development Black can initiate a dangerous attack against White's king.} Bxe6 12. Bxc5 {[%cal Rc5f8,Re4d5] With threats on [f8] and [d5]. The position looks great for White.} Nf4 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Ge6,Gf4][%cal Yd8g5] The three minor pieces, with the help of the queen, are launching a strong attack.} 13. exd5 Bg4 $1 14. f3 {White must play this, otherwise ...[Nf3] or ...[Bf3] were just too dangerous.} Bh3 $1 {[%cal Rh3g2,Rf4g2] White can't take the bishop, as ...[Qg5] is decisive.} 15. g3 (15. gxh3 Qg5+ 16. Kf2 Qg2+ 17. Ke3 Rfe8 {-+ With a mating attack. (17.Ke1 Ned3 + -+ Picks up the queen and more. )}) 15... Ned3 $1 {[%cal Yd3c5]} 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8c5,Rh3f1] ...[Qc5] is unstoppable, White has no defence.} *

