1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc1e3,Gf5e3,Rf5g7] The most annoying move for Black, White wants to play [Be3], trade the bishops, and the the knight reaches its ideal square on [e3], controlling both [f5] and [d5].} O-O 9. Qh5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gh5c5,Rf5g7] Tempting, but we should be happy if White is not going with [Be3].} d6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd6c5,Gc8f5] Opening the [c8]-bishop and protecting the [c5]-bishop against discovered attacks.} 10. Nc3 (10. Kh1 {Preparing [f4] is too slow.} Bxf5 $1 11. exf5 Qh4 $1 12. Qxh4 Nxh4 {∞ Black has no problems without queens.}) 10... Kh8 {[%csl Gh8] The king is much safer there, once we go ... [f5]/[f6].} 11. Bb3 (11. Kh1 {White's king is going away from the [a7]-[g1] diagonal, so [f4] is an option now.} Nce7 {Black wants to trade the strong knight on [f5]. The plan is ...[Nxf5] followed by ...[Qh4]! and then the knight doesn't have to go away from [g6], so White is not winning a tempo with [exf5].} 12. Bb3 {Without the knight on [c6], the bishop really had nothing to do on [a4].} c6 {Further preparing the ...[Nxf5]-idea, once the pawn is going away from [e4], Black can restrict White's knight and bishop by playing [d5].} 13. f4 $2 {Allows Black to execute the plan in a very good version.} Nxf5 14. exf5 Qh4 $1 15. Qxh4 Nxh4 {⩱ Black takes the pawn on [f5] on the next move, or play ...[d5] with a great position. ( 13.Rd1 This keeps the position equal. 13...Nxf5 14.exf5 Qh4! 15.Qxh4 Nxh4 16.Ne4 Nxf5 17.Bf4 White will win back the pawn on [d6] with a pretty drawish position. )}) 11... Nge5 {[%cal Rg7g6] ...[g6] is a threat.} 12. Nd5 f6 {[%cal Rg7g6] ...[g6] is again a threat.} (12... g6 13. Qh6 {And we can't play} gxf5 {, because of} 14. Nf6 {.}) 13. Nxg7 $5 {Leads to a crazy position.} Kxg7 14. Nxc7 {Black cannot take the knight, because then the rook [f8] would no longer be protected.} Rb8 (14... Qxc7 $4 15. Qh6+ Kh8 16. Qxf8#) 15. Bh6+ Kh8 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc8d7,Gf8g7,Gb8g8] White has a rook and 2 pawns for 2 minor pieces, but now it is Black's turn to attack the king.} *

