1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc1e3,Gf5e3,Rf5g7] The most annoying move for Black, White wants to play [Be3], trade the bishops, and the the knight reaches its ideal square on [e3], controlling both [f5] and [d5].} O-O 9. Be3 $1 Bxe3 10. Nxe3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge3,Gf5][%cal Ge3f5,Ge3d5]} b5 $1 {Since we can't challenge White's centre anytime soon, we need some compensation for less space, and taking the bishop is a good start.} 11. Bb3 Na5 12. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] Very aggressive, White wants [f5]-[f6].} Nxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 14. f5 Qg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Rg5e3] The queen is really needed there before [f6] could be played.} (14... Ne5 15. f6 $1 {is indeed very dangerous for Black.}) 15. Qe1 (15. Rf3 Ne5 16. Rg3 Qe7 {...[f6] is next, Black is completely fine with the strong knight on [e5].}) 15... Rae8 $1 {Accepting the piece is very dangerous for White.} 16. fxg6 Rxe4 17. Rf3 (17. gxf7+ $2 Rxf7 18. Rxf7 Kxf7 19. Qf2+ Kg8 20. Nf1 Re1 {-+ And White can't move.}) 17... f5 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Ge4,Gg5][%cal Rf5f4] And Black is even better here, quite surprising.} 18. Nc3 Ree8 19. Rg3 Qh6 {[%cal Rf5f4] White can even get out from the [f4]-threat, but Black is still better.} 20. gxh7+ Kh8 21. Rh3 Qe6 22. Qd2 f4 $1 23. Nf1 Rf5 $17 {[%cal Rf5g5,Rg5g2] And White has nothing against ... [Rg5]-[Rxg2].} *

