1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez, the traditional main line against 1...e5 . Black has found some reliable defenses, particularly the Berlin, which has driven players to move to 3.Bc4 or other lines, but overall it is still White's No. 1 option. Our opponent continues to put us under pressure; we have just protected the pawn on [e5] with the knight, which is under attack.} a6 {A useful move, since once White's bishop retreats to [a4], we can always force it onto another diagonal by playing ...[b5], and sometimes following it up with ...[Na5] and taking that important bishop.} 4. Ba4 Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Yd7d5] The 3...[Nge7] variation is called the Cozio Defense, so although I have not found it as the official name of the current line, we can refer to it as the Deferred Cozio. Instead of the much more popular 4...[Nf6], Black's knight is going to [g6].What are the advantages and disadvantages? From [f6], the knight controls 2 important central squares, [e4] and [d5], also immediately attacking a pawn. With [Nge7], the knight will move 2 times, controlling only the square [e5]. With protection on [e5], however, Black can aim for an early ...[d5], which is only possible in a couple of lines after 4...[Nf6], and almost always involves sacrificing a pawn the most famous example is the Marshall Attack.So, we lose a time, we put a knight in a less ideal square, but we have an extremely ambitious strategic goal, for if Black can play ...[d5] without immediate problems, it should mean that we are okay.After 4...[Nf6], there is obviously much more theory and elaborate lines, but even after 4...[Nge7] there are many different attempts for White, as Black gives a kind of free hand for one or two moves. The difference might be that very often here we can follow our own theory and not something established. The surprise value can also be considered positive: White players will not be surprised by 4...[Nge7], because this line was quite popular when followed by ...[g6], but we will always play ... [Ng6].} 5. O-O Ng6 ({Here we deviate from the main lines of} 5... g6 {, and play this much more rare move. The idea is to protect on [e5] and get ready for a quick ...[d5], if White is playing in the usual, [c3]-[d4] way.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 $5 {Unfortunately, I found the main line somewhat unpleasant for Black, so I would rather go for this rare line.} 8. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc1e3,Gf5e3,Rf5g7] The most annoying move for Black, White wants to play [Be3], trade the bishops, and the the knight reaches its ideal square on [e3], controlling both [f5] and [d5].} O-O 9. Be3 $1 Bxe3 10. Nxe3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge3,Gf5][%cal Ge3f5,Ge3d5]} b5 $1 {Since we can't challenge White's centre anytime soon, we need some compensation for less space, and taking the bishop is a good start.} 11. Bb3 Na5 12. Nc3 Nxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 {White has the space advantage, but Black is very solid. Normally White's way to attack here is with ...[f4], but that would give additional power to the [b7]-bishop.} 14. Qd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga1d1]} ({•} 14. b4 {Blocking the queenside, but we can undermine it quite quickly.} d6 15. Qd2 c5) ({•} 14. f4 f6 $1 {Preventing White's pawn from reaching [f6].} 15. Qd4 d6 16. Ncd5 Ne7 {⇆ White is slightly better, but it will be really tough to do anything against Black's setup.}) ({•} 14. Qd2 d6 15. Rad1 Nf4 {∞ Maybe it can be followed by ...[Qg5] or ...[f5].}) 14... Nf4 {[%cal Gd8g5,Yf7f5] Black is looking at some tactical ideas, connected with ...[Qg5] or ...[f5].} 15. Rad1 f5 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gb7g2,Gf4g2,Gd8g5] Attacking against the [g2]-square.} 16. Qxd7 ({•} 16. Nxf5 $4 Rxf5 17. exf5 Qg5 {-+ White is checkmated.}) ({•} 16. Ned5 Bxd5 $1 17. exd5 Qg5 18. g3 Nh5 {⇆ Black is not worse at all, the space is irrelevant now, since we can play on the kingside and e-file.}) 16... fxe4 $13 {Most likely White will trade the queens, and we will get an equalish endgame.} *

