1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bc5 {[%cal Re4f2]} 6. d4 Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ye4c3,Yb4c3]} 7. Bd2 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Nxc3 $1 {Not an obvious move, but the queenside weaknesses are a long-term problem for White.} 12. bxc3 {[%csl Yc2,Yc3]} c4 $1 {[%csl Rb5,Yf3][%cal Gc6e7,Ya7a6,Yb7b5] Forcing [Bxc6]. White's knight doesn't really have any good squares in this structure.} 13. Bxc6 (13. Qd2 $4 {or any other move is losing to} Ne7 {-+ with ...[a6] and ...[b5] trapping the bishop.}) 13... bxc6 14. Rb1 Qe7 {[%cal Re7a3] Immediately targeting the weak a-pawn.} 15. Qc1 h6 $1 {This move just highlights that White can't really do much here, and then it is useful to open the back rank.} 16. Rb4 Qc7 $2 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] Black wants ...[a5] without allowing [Rb6], but that wouldn't really be a problem.} (16... Bf5 {allows} 17. Nh4 $1 {Once White can trade the knight for the bishop, the drawing chances are much better.} Be4 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. Rxf5 {⩱ Black is still better, but trading the knight which was not doing anything is a great achievement.}) (16... a5 $1 {This was the correct move order.} 17. Rb6 Qc7 18. Qb1 Ra7 {Not allowing any [Rb7] once the bishop is developed. Importantly,} 19. Nh4 $2 {is not working now because of} Qe7 $1 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. Rxf5 Qxa3 {-+ and the a-pawn should decide the game.}) 17. Qb1 (17. Nh4 $1 {This was a good chance for White.} a5 18. Rb1 {with [Nf5] next.}) 17... a5 18. Rb6 (18. Rb6 {This transposes to the suggested line with 16...a5, and here,} Ra7 {looks easier.}) 18... Bf5 19. Rb7 Qc8 20. Re7 $2 {[%cal Rb8b1] Giving up the b-file.} (20. Qb6 $1 {White could have got some counterplay here.} Bxc2 21. e6 $1 {Again, the key for White to have something is to include the knight in the game. (( 21.Rc7 Qg4 22.Qxc6 Bd3 -+ ))} Qxe6 22. Ne5 {∞ It is still Black who is fighting for the advantage, but it is not clear anymore.}) 20... Rb8 21. Qc1 Qd8 {[%csl Re7] The rook is also far from ideal on [e7].} 22. Ra7 Be6 {It was not necessary, but just shows that White can't really do anything.} 23. a4 Qb6 {[%cal Rb6b2]} 24. Re7 Qb2 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Rb2c3,Rb2a3] White is losing either the [c3] or the [a4]-pawn.} 25. Qxb2 Rxb2 26. Rc1 Ra2 27. Kf2 Bf5 28. Ne1 Rxa4 $19 {[%csl Ga5,Ye1,Gf5] With the extra pawn and a better minor piece, the endgame is winning for Black.} 29. Ke3 Ra2 30. Rc7 Ra8 31. Rxc6 Rb2 32. Kd2 a4 $19 33. Rd6 a3 34. Ra1 a2 35. Kc1 Rb5 36. Nf3 Be6 37. Rc6 Rb7 38. Rd6 g5 39. h3 Kg7 40. Nd2 h5 41. Nf3 Kg6 0-1

