1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Be7 4. Nc3 Bh4+ {[%csl Gf1][%cal Ge1f1,Re1e2] In general, these lines are very risky for White when the king can't go to [f1] but has to block the bishop from [e2].} 5. Ke2 d5 {[%cal Gc8g4,Rg4d1] The pawn doesn't matter; it is even good that by taking it, White opens the position even more. The bishop going to [g4] is Black's plan.} 6. Nxd5 Bg4 7. d4 $6 {[%csl Yd4,Re2,Ye4] Too loose! With the king in the centre, White should play more cautiously.} (7. d3 Nf6 $1 {You can find more details about this position in the course.}) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Rf6d5] Targeting the knight and the [e4]-pawn as well.} 8. Nxf6+ {[%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5,Yd5f6] Very good trade for Black! 3 moves vs 1 moves with the knights, so it is 2 extra tempi!} Qxf6 9. e5 $2 {The same mistake as in move 7. White should play much more solid with the king in the centre.} (9. c3 O-O {∓ Black is still much better, but the game is not over yet.}) 9... Qb6 {[%cal Rb6d4,Rb6b2]} 10. Bxf4 $2 {Very optimistic!} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Ge8c8,Rc6d4] Of course! Finishing the development and attacking [d4] is much more important than the [b2]-pawn.} 11. c3 Qxb2+ {Okay, if it can be taken with check, it is not so bad. 🙂} 12. Bd2 Nxd4+ {It is good but somewhat unnecessary since White didn't really have a move.} (12... O-O-O $1 {and ...[Nxd4] will be even stronger like this.} 13. Rb1 Nxd4+ 14. cxd4 Qxd4 {-+ Black has a huge extra tempo compared to the game.}) (12... Nxd4+ {g3 Nxe5 dxe5 Bg5 -+ three different pins!}) 13. cxd4 Qxd4 (13... O-O-O $1 {was still better.} 14. g3 Rxd4 15. gxh4 Rhd8 {-+ Black sacrificed 2 pieces, but will start taking back the material.}) 14. g3 O-O-O $1 {Finally!} (14... Be7 {This is not how you are supposed to play, and White already has a decent defense here.} 15. Bf4 Qb2+ 16. Qd2 $1 Qxa1 17. Bg2 $1 {Already Black should save the game somehow.} Bb4 18. Rxa1 Bxd2 19. Kxd2 {⇆}) 15. gxh4 Qe4+ $2 {Too materialistic, and therefore wrong!} (15... Rhe8 $1 {Keeping the threats and the king in the centre was much better!} 16. Bg2 Rxe5+ 17. Kf1 Rf5 {-+ Black can take much more material this way.}) 16. Kf2 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Rxd2+ 18. Be2 Qxh4+ 19. Kf1 (19. Qg3 $1 {This was even better, and Black doesn't really have anything better than a perpetual check.} Qe4 20. Qe3 Qh4+ {but not 20...Qf5+? 21.Kg3 ±}) 19... Rd4 20. Kg2 Qg5+ $2 21. Qg3 $16 {Black has run out of threats, and White is already much better here.} Qd2 22. Rhe1 Re4 23. Kf1 (23. Kh1 $1 Rxe2 24. Qg4+ {+-}) 23... f5 24. Rac1 $2 Rxe2 25. Rxc7+ Kxc7 26. Qxg7+ Kc6 27. Rxe2 Qd1+ 28. Kf2 Qd4+ 29. Kf3 Qd3+ 30. Kf2 Qd4+ 31. Kf3 Qd5+ 32. Kf4 Qd4+ 33. Kxf5 Qd3+ 34. Re4 Rd8 35. Qh6+ Kb5 36. Qe3 Qf1+ 37. Rf4 Rf8+ 38. Ke4 Qg2+ 39. Qf3 Qc2+ 40. Ke3 Qc1+ 41. Ke4 Qb1+ 42. Kd5 Qxa2+ 43. Kd6 Qd2+ 44. Ke6 Rxf4 45. Qxb7+ Kc4 46. Qc7+ Kb3 47. Qxa7 Qa2 48. Qb6+ Kc3+ 49. Kd6 Rd4+ 50. Ke7 Qa3+ 51. Kf7 Rd7+ 52. Ke6 Qe7+ 53. Kf5 Qf7+ 54. Kg5 Qg7+ 55. Kf5 Rf7+ 0-1

