1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 h6 7. Ne2 Re8 8. c3 Bf8 9. Ng3 a6 10. Ba4 d5 {As usual, when Black is playing ...[d5] without any problems, the opening problems are solved, and it is even possible to reach a better position.} 11. exd5 {After this trade, it is very easy to end up worse as White, thanks to less space and somewhat weak [d3]-pawn.} (11. h3 {It is better to keep a pawn on [e4].} b5 12. Bc2 dxe4 13. dxe4 Be6) 11... Qxd5 {[%csl Yd3,Ge5]} 12. Bb3 Qd6 13. Qe2 Be6 $15 {It is clear that only Black can fight for the advantage here.} 14. Ne4 Qd8 $1 {Good move! White tried to have a pawn on [e4], but Black keeps the space advantage.} (14... Nxe4 15. dxe4) 15. Be3 Bxb3 16. axb3 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] Avoiding trades and preparing to push ...[f5].} 17. b4 f5 18. Nc5 Bxc5 (18... Qc8 $1 {Was probably even better, since after ...[b6], it is not clear where White's knight should go.}) 19. bxc5 Qe7 20. Qc2 f4 21. Qb3 Red8 22. Bd2 Qxc5 {Black has won a pawn, but White has counterplay against the [e5]-pawn.} 23. Rfe1 Qd6 24. Re2 Kh7 25. Rae1 Qg6 26. d4 exd4 27. c4 Ne3 $1 {Very nice! Allowing [Re6] was not good.} (27... Nb6 28. Re6 Qf5 29. c5 {⇆}) 28. fxe3 fxe3 29. Bxe3 (29. Bc1 {White can keep the extra piece, but the next moves are very unclear since Black's passed pawns are completely blocking the position.} Rf8 30. Kh1 b6 {∓}) 29... dxe3 30. Rxe3 b6 31. Qc3 Re8 $15 {Not an easy extra pawn to convert, and White was defending very well, just missing some chances at the end to make the draw.} 32. Nh4 Rxe3 33. Rxe3 Qg5 34. Qd3+ Kg8 35. Qe4 Rd8 36. h3 Rd4 37. Qe6+ Kh7 38. Nf3 Rd1+ 39. Kh2 Qf4+ 40. g3 Qf6 41. Qxf6 gxf6 42. g4 Kg7 43. Re8 Rd7 44. Nh4 Ne7 45. Ra8 Rd2+ 46. Kg3 Rxb2 47. Ra7 Rb3+ 48. Nf3 f5 49. Rxc7 Kf6 50. gxf5 Nxf5+ 51. Kf4 Ne7 52. Ra7 Rb4 53. Rxa6 Rxc4+ 54. Ke3 Rb4 55. Ra8 Nf5+ 56. Kd3 Rf4 57. Ke2 Re4+ 58. Kf2 Rb4 59. Ke2 Re4+ 60. Kf2 Re6 61. Ra7 Re7 62. Ra4 Rc7 63. Ke2 Re7+ 64. Kf2 Nd6 65. Rh4 Ne4+ 66. Ke3 Nd6+ 67. Kf2 Kg6 68. Rg4+ Kh