1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 h6 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 Bc5 11. c3 O-O 12. O-O Qc7 13. d4 exd3 14. Nxd3 Bd6 15. g3 Bf5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] Black just wants to bring the rooks to the centre and put pressure on White's position.} (15... Bh3 $1 {This is the course, but the game continuation is good as well.}) 16. Na3 $2 {This is already a serious mistake. Since the bishop on [d6] is restricted by the pawn on [g3], this trade is very good for Black.} (16. Nd2 Rad8 17. b4 Nb7 {∞ With ...[Rfe8] and ...[c5] in the next moves, Black has great compensation.}) 16... Bxa3 $1 17. bxa3 Rad8 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Yc3c2,Gf8e8] With the pawn on [c2], the position wouldn't be this horrible.} 18. Bf4 Qc8 19. Re1 (19. Qa4 {Unfortunately for White, going out from the pin is not working.} Bxd3 20. Bxd3 Rxd3 21. Qxa5 Qh3 $1 {This is the problem! ...[Ng4] is the threat.} 22. f3 g5 23. Bc1 Re8 {-+ There is nothing against ...[Re2], while 23.Bxg5 Rd5 -+ wins the piece.}) 19... Rfe8 {[%cal Re8e2] Increasing the pressure and threatening ...[Rxe2].} 20. Be3 Nc4 {[%cal Rc4e3]} 21. Bd4 Ne4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] All the black pieces are really good.} 22. Rc1 Ned2 $1 {[%cal Yf5d3,Ye2d3,Ye8e1,Yd1e1,Rd2f3] Black wants to trade everything and then go ...[Nf3]+ and win the queen.} 23. Nc5 Rxe2 $1 {[%csl Yf3,Yg2,Yh3] Eliminating the best defender; the light squares are horribly weak now.} 24. Qxe2 (24. Rxe2 Nf3+ 25. Kh1 Bg4 26. Qd3 Nfe5 {-+ and ...[Bf3] and ...[Qh3] is coming.}) 24... Bg4 25. Qd3 Nf3+ 26. Kh1 Nfe5 27. Rxe5 Nxe5 {The material is equal, but Black's attack continues.} 28. Qf1 Nf3 29. Qd3 Re8 {[%cal Rf3e1]} 30. h3 Ne1 $1 {[%cal Gg4f3]} 31. Rxe1 (31. Qd2 Bf3+ 32. Kh2 Bg2 {-+}) (31. Qf1 Be2 32. Qxe1 Qxh3+ 33. Kg1 Re5 $1 {One of the ways to win.} 34. Bxe5 Bf3 {-+ There is no check on [e8], so this is checkmate. ( 33...Bf3?? would blunder the game. 34.Qxe8+ Kh7 35.Qe4+ ±)}) 31... Rxe1+ 0-1

