1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Be3 Nce5 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc6 $6 {[%csl Rc5] This looks very good since White is getting the bishop pair, but normally Black has a standard trick against this plan.} dxc6 11. Bxc5 Qg5 $1 {[%cal Rg6h4,Rg6f4] With threats like ...[Nh4] or ...[Nf4], White has no time to take on [f8].} 12. Be3 (12. Bxf8 $4 Nh4 13. g3 Nhf3+ 14. Kh1 Qh5 15. h4 Qg4 {-+ is just checkmate.}) 12... Nf4 (12... Qh4 $5 {This is also good.} 13. f3 f5 $1 {Black has good play on the kingside.}) 13. Bxf4 $2 (13. g3 {White should have tried this move.} Nh3+ 14. Kh1 Qe7 15. Nd2 f5 {⇆ The light squares are pretty weak, but objectively, this is not so bad for White.}) 13... Qxf4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge5g4] White has problems with the [e4]-pawn, and ...[Ng4] is also unpleasant.} 14. Qd2 (14. Bc2 Ng4 15. g3 Qh6 16. h4 Be6 {White can either play with a weak king and queens on the board or trade and give up the d-file.} 17. Qc1 Qxc1 18. Rxc1 Rad8 19. Rd1 Ne5 {∓ and ...[Bg4] can be next.}) (14. Qe2 Rd8 {Stopping [Nd2].} 15. f3 b5 16. Bb3 a5 {-+ The bishop can come to [a6] or the knight to [c4] after ...[a4]. ( 15.Rd1? Bg4 16.f3 Nxf3+ is just winning material. 17.gxf3 Bxf3 -+)}) 14... Qxe4 $17 {This is just a pawn, which was later converted.} 15. Bc2 Qh4 16. Re1 Nc4 17. Qe2 Be6 18. Nd2 Nxd2 19. Qxd2 Rad8 20. Qe3 g6 21. Bb3 Rfe8 22. Rad1 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Rd8 24. Re1 Rd6 25. g3 Qd8 26. Kg2 Bxb3 27. Qe8+ Qxe8 28. Rxe8+ Kg7 29. axb3 Rd2 30. Rb8 b6 31. Rb7 Rxb2 32. b4 Rb3 33. Rxc7 Rxc3 34. Rb7 b5 35. Rb6 Kf6 36. Rxa6 Rc4 37. f4 Ke6 38. Kf3 h5 39. h3 f5 40. Ke3 Kd5 41. Ra8 Re4+ 42. Kf3 Rxb4 43. Rg8 Rb3+ 44. Kf2 b4 45. Rxg6 Rc3 46. Rf6 b3 47. Rxf5+ Kd4 48. Rf8 Rc5 49. Rd8+ Rd5 50. Rb8 Rb5 51. Rd8+ Kc3 52. Ke3 b2 53. Rd3+ Kc4 0-1

