1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {So far it has been standard theory, and now it is the first important move for Black to know.} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Playing ...[d5] quickly is one of the goals of the Deferred Cozio.} 9. exd5 Bxc3+ $1 {Yes! For the queen to be able to go to [h5], this intermediate check is a must.} 10. bxc3 Qxd5 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gd5h5]} 11. O-O O-O {Till this moment the players were not using much time; this is one of the main positions of the Deferred Cozio.} 12. h3 $6 {White prevents ...[Bg4], but the move is a little bit slow, so Black can improve the situation on the queenside.} (12. Bb3 $1 {This is the main line for White.}) 12... Na5 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4][%cal Ya5b3,Ya4b3,Gb7b5] Excellent move by Angelika; the bishop can't reach [b3] anymore for free, and after a move like ...[b5], Black has White's hanging pawns under control.} 13. Bb3 (13. Re1 b5 $1 14. Bc2 Bf5 {Black is trading the bishop pair anyway, and White has very weak squares on the queenside.}) 13... Nxb3 {After taking the bishop pair, Black has no problems at all.} 14. axb3 {[%cal Gc3c4]} (14. Qxb3 $2 {would leave White with weak light squares and the hanging pawns are well blockaded.} Be6 $1 15. Qxd5 Bxd5 {⩱ With ...[f6] next, Black is slightly better.}) 14... b5 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yb5c4,Gc3c4,Gc8b7,Rb7g2] Very good, stopping ...[c4]. Sometimes, the bishop can be developed to [b7] as well.} 15. Be3 Be6 $1 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Re6b3]} ({Instead,} 15... Bb7 $5 {was also good, but this is even better. White will really have a tough time to push [c4] in good circumstances.}) 16. Rb1 $6 (16. Nd2 {This was better, but probably White didn't like} Nh4 $1 {and Black can create threats on the kingside as well.} 17. f3 Qh5 {↑ with ideas of ...[Bxh3] and ...[Qg6] to follow.}) 16... Bf5 $2 {Wins a tempo to bring the bishop to the long diagonal, but Black should have played elsewhere!} (16... a5 $1 {Basically Black wants to push the pawn till [a2]!} 17. Nd2 {White is again ready to push [c4], but Black can switch to the kingside.} Nh4 18. f3 Qf5 {∓ With threats like ...[Qg6] or ...[Qd3], and going away from the [c4]-tempo.} 19. c4 $2 Qg6 {-+ Either winning a pawn on [h3], or White has to play [g4]...}) 17. Rc1 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc3c4] The rook is better on [c1], supporting [c4].} Be4 18. Ne1 (18. c4 $1 {was already good for White.} Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 c6 {With a more or less equal endgame.}) 18... Qe6 (18... a5 $1 {It was still better to push the pawn, although the bishop was of course better on [e6] for this purpose.} 19. c4 bxc4 20. bxc4 Qd6 {⇆ It is still rather White who has to fight for equality.}) 19. c4 c6 $6 {Too slow but also logical, Black didn't want to allow [d5].} (19... bxc4 20. bxc4 a5 {⇆}) 20. Nd3 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd3c5] The knight is going to be very strong on [c5], while the bishop is loose on [e4] in case the attack doesn't work out, so Black should have taken here.} Qf5 $2 (20... Bxd3 21. Qxd3 bxc4 22. bxc4 a5 {∞}) 21. Nc5 $1 Nh4 22. f3 Qg6 23. g4 {Black has to give up two pieces for the rook and pawn, which was not enough here. White was much better, but later the game ended in a draw in the time trouble.} Bxf3 24. Rxf3 Nxf3+ 25. Qxf3 Rfe8 26. Bf2 $16 h5 27. Kg2 hxg4 28. hxg4 a5 29. Nd7 f6 30. cxb5 cxb5 31. Qd5+ Qf7 32. Qxf7+ Kxf7 33. Nb6 Rab8 34. d5 Re2 35. Rc7+ Kg6 36. Nc8 a4 37. bxa4 bxa4 38. Kf3 Rd2 39. Be3 1/2-1/2

