1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nb6 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Re1 f6 9. d4 O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 {So far this is the line which is consider the most likely to happen in the Deferred Cozio. Here, presumably because she was afraid of the open f-file, White decided to stop ...[Bg4].} 11. h3 {[%csl Yg4][%cal Yc8g4,Yh3g4]} exd4 $1 {[%csl Yc6,Yc7,Gc8,Gd6] Now, Black's only problem is the double-pawns on the c-file, but it is easily compensated with the pair of bishops.} 12. Qxd4 (12. Nxd4 {Objectively it was probaby better, but White is just trying to equalise.} c5 {and} 13. Ne6 $4 {doesn't work because of} Bxe6 14. Rxe6 Bh2+ {+ -+ Instead, 13.Nc6 Qd7 14.Ne7+! With this move White can greatly simply the position, and make the draw in the endgame. 14...Bxe7 15.Qxd7 Bxd7 16.Rxe7 Rae8=}) 12... Bf5 $5 {[%cal Rf5c2] Interesting move; it is tough to say whether this or ...[c5] followed by ...[Bb7] was better for Black.} (12... c5 $1 13. Qe4 Bd7 {or 13.Qd3 Re8 14.Nc3 Rxe1+ 15.Nxe1 Qe8 16.Be3 Bb7 ⩱}) 13. Qc3 {Logical. Again, only the computer would come up with 13.Bf4 and trying to get equality after a less than obvious sequence.} (13. Bf4 $1 Bxc2 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Re6 c5 16. Qd2 {White will win back the pawn on [d6] with an equal position. (16.Qxd6?! Bf5 17.Qxd8 Raxd8 18.Re1 Nd5 ⩱ Black has better development, White is still struggling here a bit. )}) 13... Re8 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1] Angelika is playing very well, developing with every move and creating problems for White.} (13... Qd7 $1 {This was even better probably, because depending on what White does, the rook from [a8] can go to [b8] or [e8]. Defending the pawn on [c6] also wouldn't have been a problem. 🙂} 14. Be3 Nd5 $1 {Just like the game, but White can't take on [c6].} 15. Qc4 Rfb8 $1 {Very unpleasant, attacking on [b2] and the rook can join the kingside attack via [b4].} 16. b3 Bxh3 $1 17. gxh3 Qxh3 {-+ With the threat of ...[Rb4]!}) 14. Be3 (14. Qxc6 Rxe1+ 15. Nxe1 Qe7 {∞ With moves like ...[Re8] and ...[Be4] to come, Black has more than enough for the pawn here.}) 14... Nd5 {The move is okay, but it was not necessary.} (14... Qd7 $1 15. Nbd2 Nd5 16. Qc4 Kh8 {⩱ Of course, it is not the pawn itself which is so important, but rather that White's queen is not getting to [c6].}) 15. Qxc6 Kh8 $6 {This is too slow. Black should have taken the bishop and guaranteed decent compensation with the bishop pair.} (15... Nxe3 16. Rxe3 Rxe3 17. fxe3 Qe8 $1 {Just to show that queen trade is an option even when down a pawn!} 18. Qxe8+ Rxe8 19. Nd4 Bg6 20. Kf2 c5 21. Ne2 Be5 {∞ The bishops are really strong.}) 16. Nd4 Bg6 17. Nc3 Nxe3 18. Rxe3 Rxe3 19. fxe3 {[%csl Gd6,Gg6]} Qe8 $6 {Basically entering the endgame shown at move 15; just White has developed her knights and the king went to [h8]. These are not good developments for Black.} (19... Rb8 {∞ And next is ...[Qe7]; Black has a decent position.}) 20. Qxe8+ Rxe8 21. Kf2 $14 {The position is probably still holdable for Black, but it is not easy.} a6 22. Rc1 Rb8 23. b3 Kg8 24. Nce2 Ba3 25. Re1 c5 26. Nc6 Re8 27. c3 c4 28. b4 Be4 29. Ncd4 Bb2 30. Rd1 a5 31. b5 Ba3 32. Nf3 Bd3 33. Nf4 Rb8 34. Nxd3 cxd3 35. Nd4 Bc5 36. a4 Bxd4 37. cxd4 Rc8 38. Rxd3 Kf7 39. b6 Rc2+ 40. Kf3 Rb2 41. Rc3 Rxb6 42. Rc5 Ra6 43. e4 h6 44. Ke3 Rb6 45. Rxa5 Rb2 46. Ra7+ Kg6 47. Kf3 Rb3+ 48. Kf4 Rb2 49. g3 Kh5 50. Rxg7 Rb4 51. d5 f5 52. g4+ 1-0

