1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. Nc3 d6 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5][%cal Yd6e5]} 6. h3 $6 {This is a move you can expect to happen a lot after ...[d6], because of the 'threat' of ...[Bg4]. While that is indeed many times an option for Black, the main thing is that the [e5]-pawn is protected now, so Black actually wants to do something on the other side of the board!} b5 $1 7. Bb3 Na5 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Ra5b3] Black already solved the opening problems. It is White who has to be careful after giving up the bishop pair so easily.} 8. Ne2 $2 {Extremely slow; in this way White is really just losing the bishop for nothing.} (8. d4 $1 {White should somehow use the better development to compensate for the loss of the strong bishop.} Nxb3 9. axb3 {and instead of} exd4 10. Nxd4 {⩲ with some space advantage for White, 9...Bb7 10.dxe5 dxe5 11.Qxd8+ Rxd8 12.Nxe5 b4= Black is completely okay here.}) 8... Nxb3 9. axb3 Bb7 {Of course, this is good, but Black could also try more aggressive moves.} (9... f5 $5) (9... d5 $5) 10. Ng3 g6 $6 {[%csl Yg3][%cal Yg6f5,Yg6h5] This is a great move in general against a knight on [g3], but Black already had a big advantage, so there were more aggressive ways available.} (10... d5 $1 {would have already given a big advantage. Just opening the position for the bishops.} 11. exd5 Qxd5 12. O-O Nc6 {∓}) (10... g6 11. Qe2 {dxe4 Nxe4} Nc6 {∓ With ...[Be7]-...[O-O] and then ...[f5] coming, White is in big danger here.}) (10... g6 11. d3 {Maybe this is what White should do, but it is quite a bad endgame after dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 Ng6 ∓ With ...[O-O-O], ...[Bc5] and ...[Nf4] to follow, Black is much better.}) (10... g6 11. Nxe5 {dxe4 -+ The knight is very loose on [e5].}) (10... h5 $5 {Gaining more space and planning to kick back the knight with [h4].}) 11. d4 $1 {This may look counterintuitive, but if followed up correctly, this move is actually not opening but rather closing the position. In any case, this move makes ...[d5] or ...[f5] from Black more difficult to achieve.} Bg7 12. Be3 $6 (12. dxe5 $1 {Closing the long diagonal!} dxe5 13. O-O Qd6 {⩱ Black is still preferable with ...[O-O-O] and ...[f5] to follow, but it is not that bad for White.}) 12... d5 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7] Great move! Opening the position fully for the bishops.} (12... f5 $1 {was also good, but more complicated.} 13. exf5 Nxf5 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Ng5 Kd7 $1 {Not too easy to find. 🙂 Going away from [Qh5]+, covering the [e6]-square and also preparing to refute [Nf7].} 16. Nf7 Qe8 $1 17. Nxh8 exd4 {-+ Black will first take on [e3] and then on [h8].}) {16.dxe5 Bxe5 ∓} 13. exd5 (13. Nxe5 dxe4 {-+ The knight is completely misplaced on [e5] and can be trapped very easily.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Bg5 $6 {Losing more time, but the endgame also looked bad.} (14. dxe5 $1 Nxe3 15. Qxd8+ Rxd8 16. fxe3 O-O {⩱ White has chances to fight for the draw here.}) 14... f6 $1 15. Bc1 $2 {After making three moves with it, the bishop goes back to [c1]. It can't be good. White probably wanted to keep the option of taking back with the queen on [d4] as well.} (15. Bd2 exd4 16. Nxd4 Qd7 17. Qe2+ Kf7 {∓ With ...[c5] or ...[Rhe8] next, White's minor pieces are really bad.}) 15... O-O $6 {A big chance missed by Angelika!} (15... exd4 $1 {This move is pretty much winning for Black. There is no good way to recapture, and if White is not taking, then Black just protects the extra pawn with [c5].} 16. Nxd4 Qe7+ 17. Qe2 Qxe2+ 18. Ngxe2 {when} Kf7 {is also good for a big advantage. 18...O-O-O 19.Ne6 Nb4 -+ with big problems on [c2].}) (15... O-O {Qxd4? Qe7+ With ...[f5] and [O-O-O] next, this is already -4 for Black. White can't finish the development without losing material.} 16. Ne2 {O-O-O -+}) (15... O-O 16. O-O c5 17. Re1 Kf7 {-+ The king is perfectly safe on [f7]. 17...Ne7? would be a mistake, allowing 18.b4!}) 16. O-O Nf4 $2 {This is a mistake. Black still should have opened up both bishops.} (16... exd4 $1 17. Nxd4 Re8 18. c4 c5 {∓ Without central pawns, the bishop pair should give a nice advantage for Black.}) 17. Re1 (17. c4 $1 {Preparing [d5] and keeping the position as close as possible.}) 17... Qd5 $2 {Misjudgement of the position after 18.Bxf4.} (17... f5 $1 {This is much more difficult than any previous options for Black, but this was the way to keep the bishops open.} 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Ne2 g5 {∓ Contrary to the game, here Black is in time to push the kingside pawns and open the [g7]-bishop.}) (17... Qd5 18. dxe5 Qxd1 19. Rxd1 Nxh3+ $1 20. Kf1 {f4! Ne2} g5 {(( 21...Bxf3 22.gxf3 Bxe5 23.Kg2 Ng5 24.Rd5 Rf5 25.Bxf4 Bxf4 26.Rxf5 gxf5 27.Nxf4 The endgame is around equal.)) Ned4 Rae8 Crazy line from the machine.} 21. gxh3 c5 {∓ Immediately winning back the knight. 23.Nh2 Nxf2 24.Kxf2 h5= ∞ Really nice position, for now Black has only a pawn for the piece, but the kingside majority is dangerous and the bishops are very strong as well.}) 18. Bxf4 $1 exf4 19. Ne4 {[%csl Yb7,Gf3,Rg7][%cal Yb7f3,Ge4c5] Black is just not in time to push the pawns on the kingside, and especially the [g7]-bishop has become really bad.} g5 20. Nc5 $16 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ge1e7,Gd1d3] Now White is much better, and it was not really possible to save this game for Black.} Bc8 21. Qe2 g4 22. hxg4 Bxg4 23. Rxa6 Rae8 24. Qxb5 Bxf3 25. Rxe8 Qg5 26. Rxf8+ Bxf8 27. Qf1 Qg4 28. Nd7 Kg7 29. Nxf6 Qg5 30. Nxh7 Qg4 31. Nxf8 Kxf8 32. Rh6 Be2 33. Rf6+ Kg7 34. Rxf4 Qxf4 35. Qxe2 Qc1+ 36. Kh2 Qf4+ 37. Kh3 Qh6+ 38. Kg3 Kf7 39. Qf3+ 1-0

