1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nb6 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. Re1 f6 9. Nbd2 $6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6] Very slow. If White does not challenge the centre immediately, then Black just has more space there.} O-O 10. Nc4 $6 {[%cal Yc4d6,Yc4b6] None of the trades are particularly threatening for Black, while this move allows ...[Bg4].} (10. h3 {is at least stopping ...[Bg4], but obviously, it is now Black who is fighting for advantage.} Bd7) 10... Bg4 $15 {[%cal Rg4d1,Yg4f3,Gc6d4,Rd4b5,Rd4f3] The pin is very unpleasant and Black has threats with ...[Nd4] either immediately or after ...[Bxf3] as well.} 11. Nxb6 $6 {[%cal Yb1d2,Yd2c4,Yc4b6] White lost three tempi to trade the knight, which was not so good.} axb6 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf6f5,Ga8a2]} 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. h3 Bh5 {Of course, there is no reason to take on [f3].} 14. Bd2 (14. g4 {Weakening White's position quite a bit.} Be8 {∓}) 14... Nd4 $2 {Even though this move is forcing ...[g4], without the knights and with the symmetrical structure, White's king will not be that weak.} (14... f5 $1 {There is no [g4] for White, and it is very difficult to see how the pin can be stopped.} 15. Bc3 Rf6 {There is a regrouping plan of ...[Qf8] followed by ...[Re8]. Black can also consider ...[g5] later.} 16. Bd5 $2 {Trying to attack the [e5]-pawn by taking the knight doesn't work.} Ne7 17. Bxb7 Ra7 {-+ The bishop is trapped. 17.Bb3 Ng6 -+ The knight is again protecting [e5] and joining the attack via [f4].}) 15. g4 $1 Be8 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Qe2 Bc6 {[%cal Gf8e8]} 18. f4 $1 {[%cal Ge2f2] Preparing the [f2]-square for the queen.} Re8 19. Qf2 Qd7 20. Kf1 {[%cal Rf2d4,Gd6c5,Rc5g1] White is going away from the [g1]-[a7] diagonal, so the pawn on [d4] is hanging now.} b5 21. Bb3 Bh1 $5 {[%cal Rd7c6,Gc7c5] An incredible move! I doubt that many players would even see it. Angelika wants to protect the pawn with ...[c5] or bring the queen to [c6].} (21... Bf8 {With an equal position. Some trades are coming on the e-file, and a draw is likely.}) 22. Qxd4 {White accepts the pawn.} Qc6 {[%cal Rc6g2]} 23. Qf2 Bc5 {[%csl Gd4,Rf1] Black has lost a pawn, but White's king has become much weaker.} 24. Qg3 $2 (24. Be3 $1 {This was the only way for White to keep equality, but even this looks somewhat risky.} Rxe3 25. Rxe3 Bxe3 26. Qxe3 Qg2+ 27. Ke1 Qh2 28. Rd1 $1 {White is just in time with organising a defence.} Bc6 29. Rd2 Qh1+ 30. Kf2 Re8 31. Be6 $1 {Even though the bishop is pinned, it can be protected with [f5], so Black has nothing more than a perpetual check.} Qg2+ 32. Ke1 Qh1+) (24. d4 $4 Bxd4 {-+}) 24... b4 $4 {After the more difficult moves, somehow the easier was missed.} (24... Bf3 $1 {with the threat of ...[Be2] followed by ...[Qh1] and checkmating.} 25. a3 Be2+ 26. Rxe2 Qh1+ 27. Qg1 Qxg1# {White has to block the e-file in order to avoid checkmate. 25.Be6 Be2+! 26.Kxe2 Rxe6+ 27.Kd1 Rae8 -+ Black is likely to win the game in the next few moves, since the rook on [a1] is out of the game and the king is very weak.}) 25. Rxe8+ Rxe8 26. Re1 Rxe1+ 27. Bxe1 Bd6 28. Ke2 g5 29. Bd2 h6 30. Qf2 {Apparently, this position is still holdable, because it is difficult to create a passed pawn for White on the queenside. However, it is losing after the trade of the queens.} Qg2 $2 (30... Kg7 {⩲}) 31. fxg5 fxg5 32. c3 $18 bxc3 33. Bxc3+ Kh7 34. Be6 Bg3 35. Qxg2 Bxg2 36. Bf5+ Kg8 37. Be4 Bxh3 38. Kf3 Bh2 39. Bxb7 h5 40. gxh5 g4+ 41. Ke2 Bf4 42. Bd4 g3 43. a4 Bg4+ 44. Bf3 Bc8 45. Be3 Bd6 46. Bd5+ Kf8 47. h6 Bg4+ 48. Bf3 Bf5 49. a5 Bc8 50. Bd4 Kg8 51. Be4 Bg4+ 52. Kf1 Bh3+ 53. Kg1 1-0

