1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. d3 $6 {Black should already be happy after such moves. This is never the test of the Cozio.} Ng6 6. c3 d5 $6 {This is a mistake, which is quite surprising. 🙂 White is playing very slowly and an early ...[d5] doesn't work here...} (6... Be7 $1 {Basically White can't stop ...[d5] anyway, so it is better to first develop the bishop, stop [Ng5] and then go for ...[d5].} 7. O-O d5 {transposes to the course.}) 7. O-O (7. Bb3 $1 {This would have been unpleasant, because normally Black should play ...[dxe4] or ...[Be6] in such position, but those moves are met by [Ng5]!} Be6 8. Ng5 $1 Bc5 9. Nxe6 fxe6 {⩲ The engine claims slight advantage for White, but practically this is still quite okay for Black. There is decent chance for some attack on the kingside later on. 7...dxe4 8.Ng5! f6 9.Nf7 Qxd3 10.Qh5! Black has problems after this move. 10.Qxd3? exd3 11.Nxh8 Nxh8 ∓ A knight + 2 pawns are better than the rook.}) 7... Be7 8. Re1 Bg4 {It is unclear to me whether forcing [h3] is good for Black or not. It doesn't look like a particularly bad move for White, but later some sacrifices are possible there.} (8... O-O {This is more standard.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. exd5 Qxd5 {⩱}) 9. h3 Be6 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Nf1 b5 {Black is obviously playing for more than just equality.} (11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Rfd8) (11... d4 $5) 12. Bc2 (12. Bb3 Na5 {Preparing to gain more space with ...[c5].} 13. Bc2 d4 {⩱ With ...[c5] next, Black has good play on the queenside. 13.Bxd5 Bxd5 14.exd5 Qxd5=}) 12... f5 $6 {This is one of the ideas for Black, but it is somewhat early. It was better to first finish the development, since the position is quite slow anyway.} (12... Qd7 {With moves like ...[Rad8] and ...[Kh8] next and depending on what White does, ...[f5] is very possible later.}) 13. exd5 $1 Bxd5 14. Ne3 $1 {White has reacted very well to ...[f5] so far.} Be6 15. Bb3 $2 {This shouldn't be a problem for Black. Now, it is just more space for nothing.} (15. d4 $1 {This could have been problematic for Black.} exd4 16. cxd4 {± Obviously, the move Black would like to make here is ...[e4], gain a tempo and attack on the kingside, but it is just not working. 15...e4 16.d5! is a problem. 16...exf3 17.dxe6 ± The light squares are really weak in Black's position, and the [e6]-pawn is unpleasant as well.}) 15... Bxb3 16. Qxb3+ Kh8 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gg6f4,Gd8d7,Ga8d8]} 17. Rd1 Nf4 $5 ({Not bad, but maybe again} 17... Qd7 $1 {followed by ...[Rad8] was better.}) 18. Qc2 Qd6 {[%cal Gd6g6,Ga8d8]} 19. Nf1 {Angelika didn't play one of her favourite moves here. 🙂} Ne6 (19... g5 {∓ (Since the centre is essentially closed, on [d4], Black has ...[e4] Black can start taking aggressive measures on the kingside.)}) 20. a4 b4 $1 {[%csl Ya1][%cal Ya4b5] Not allowing any activity for the [a1]-rook.} 21. Ne3 Rad8 $1 {Finally!} 22. Qe2 $2 {This is just a blunder, but White's position was already very difficult.} Nf4 23. Qc2 Nxd3 $19 {[%cal Ge5e4] Black has an extra pawn and is completely winning.} 24. Nc4 Qd5 25. Ne3 Qd6 26. Ne1 (26. Nc4 Qd5 27. Ne3 Qe4 {-+}) 26... e4 27. Bd2 f4 28. Nc4 Qc5 29. Nxd3 Rxd3 30. cxb4 Qd5 31. Bc3 Bxb4 32. Rxd3 exd3 33. Bxb4 0-1

