1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 d5 9. exd5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. Ba3 {[%cal Ra3f8,Ge8c8] Not a particularly dangerous line, since Black can also castle long without any problems.} Qe4+ 12. Kd2 {[%cal Gh1e1] Quite ambitious from White.} (12. Qe2 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Bg4 {Black is comfortably equal.}) 12... Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8] Black is prepared to castle long.} 13. Re1 Qf4+ 14. Kc2 b5 (14... O-O-O {This was also just fine for Black.} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 {White is pretty weak on the light squares.}) 15. Bb3 O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc8] The king is safe.} 16. Bxe6+ fxe6 17. Qe2 (17. Rxe6 $4 {Of course, this was not possible.} Qf5+ {+ -+}) 17... e5 $1 {Trying to open the position against White's king.} 18. Bc5 $2 {[%csl Rc2,Gc8] Too optimistic; White's king is clearly weaker, so the queens should have been traded.} (18. dxe5 $4 Qa4+ 19. Kb2 Nf4 {-+ With the tempo on the queen, ...[Nd3] is winning a lot of material in the next move.}) (18. Nxe5 $4 {loses to} Ngxe5 19. dxe5 Qa4+ 20. Kb2 Nxe5 {-+ and ...[Nc4] or ...[Nd3] is next.}) (18. Qe4 $1 {White should have traded queens immediately, since the king is very weak.} Qxe4+ 19. Rxe4 exd4 20. cxd4 Rd5 {⇆ This is a fairly complicated endgame, but Black's queenside looks more dangerous than White's potential passed pawn on the other side.}) 18... Rhe8 $1 {[%cal Ye8e2]} 19. Qf1 $2 (19. Qe4 $1 {Even here, this was White's best try to save the game.} Qxe4+ 20. Rxe4 exd4 21. Rxe8 d3+ $1 {A big difference compared to the 18.Qe4 lines.} 22. Kd2 Rxe8 {∓ It is not so easy for White to take back the pawn, but at least there is no checkmate.}) 19... Qf5+ $1 {[%cal Gg6f4] Preparing the [f4]-square for the knight.} 20. Kb2 Nf4 $19 {[%cal Rf4d3,Ge5e4] With the threat of ...[Nd3] or ...[e4] followed by ...[Nd3], Black is winning material.} 21. Rad1 e4 22. Nh4 Qf6 23. g3 Nd3+ 24. Kc2 Qf7 25. Ra1 Nxe1+ 26. Qxe1 Qc4 27. Qe3 b4 28. Kb2 bxc3+ 29. Qxc3 Qe2+ 30. Ka3 Qd3 31. Kb2 Nxd4 32. Rc1 Qb5+ 33. Bb4 c6 34. Ng2 a5 35. a3 axb4 0-1

