1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 7. Bxc6 $6 {Too early!} (7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nxe5 {This is how the main line goes.}) 7... bxc6 8. Nxd4 (8. Qxd4 Be7 {⩱ White's queen and knight are both misplaced.}) 8... Nxe5 $1 9. O-O Bd6 10. f4 Ng4 $1 11. Re1+ Kf8 {[%csl Gf8,Rg1][%cal Rd6c5,Rc5g1,Rd8h4] Even though it is Black's king who didn't manage to castle, White's king is much weaker because of the [f4]-move.} 12. h3 h5 $1 {This is not the course, but this is how Angelika plays. 🙂 The [h8]-rook joining the attack is easily worth a piece sacrifice.} 13. hxg4 $2 (13. Nd2 {The computer recommends such moves... but already being down a pawn and sacrificing another pawn on [f4] is not how humans play.} Qh4 {(13...Bxf4)}) 13... hxg4 {[%cal Rd8h4]} 14. g3 {White slows down a queen a little bit, but not that much.} Qf6 $19 {[%cal Rf6h6]} 15. Kg2 c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7g2] Opening the long diagonal for the bishop.} 16. Nb3 d4 {[%cal Rb7g2,Gc8b7] ...[Bb7]+ is a winning threat.} 17. Na5 {[%cal Ya5b7,Rc8b7] Here there were a couple of easier ways to win than what Angelika chose, but it was always winning for Black.} c4 {[%cal Gf6f5,Rf5a5] Black wanted to play ...[Qf5] with a tempo.} (17... Qf5 $1 {with the threat of ...[Qd5].} 18. Nd2 Qd5+ 19. Ne4 Bf5 {-+ White is losing material on [e4]. 18.Qe2 Be6 19.c4 Qh5 -+ White is losing on the h-file now.}) 18. Qe2 {[%cal Re2e8]} Be6 {[%cal Re6d5] White has to stop ...[Bd5] now.} 19. Qe4 Re8 {[%csl Re1][%cal Re6d7,Ye8e1]} 20. Bd2 (20. Nd2 Bd7 {-+ wins the rook on [e1].}) 20... Rh5 21. Kg1 c3 22. bxc3 dxc3 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rd6c5] The other bishop is opened up now.} 23. Bxc3 Bc5+ 24. Kf1 Qh6 25. Nd2 Bd7 26. Be5 Rh2 {[%cal Rh2d2,Rh6h3]} 0-1

