1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 f6 6. Be3 c5 {[%cal Yc2c3,Yd3d4,Rc5d4,Re5d4,Gg8e7,Ge7c6] When White plays slowly, it is good to include this move, since now if anytime White wants [d4], Black can trade the doubled pawn on the c-file. Ideally, the knight can also go to [c6], but it is a little bit more difficult with the bishop on [e3].} 7. Nbd2 Be6 (7... b6 $1 {This was probably the correct way for Black, protecting the pawn on [c5] and preparing ...[Ne7]-[c6]/[g6].}) 8. Qe2 Qd7 9. O-O O-O-O (9... Bd6 $1 {is safer than the game continuation.} 10. c3 Ne7 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb5) 10. a3 {[%cal Gf1b1,Gb2b4] After playing so slowly in the opening, White shouldn't have gotten such serious chances for the attack.} g5 11. Rfb1 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gb2b4] White's attack is somewhat faster here; Black doesn't really have targets on the kingside.} Qc6 $2 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Yc6c5] Protecting [c5] so the knight can be developed, but this was already too slow.} (11... Ne7 $1 {This is very nice! Basically, Black would rather give up the [c5]-pawn for free, since it means that the b-file is not opening up!} 12. b4 $1 {White shouldn't take the pawn, but insist on opening up some files.} Nc6 13. bxc5 {(( 13.b5? is not working. 13...axb5 14.Rxb5 Nd4 -+ ))} g4 14. Nh4 Nd4 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 {⇆ with a complicated position. Black's king is much safer now than it could have been in the game.}) (11... Qc6 12. Bxc5 $2 {Instructive mistake. Ng6 Despite being up a healthy extra pawn, White is already worse, according to the engine! Black's attack is much faster now, while White hasn't managed to open files on the queenside. Bxf8 Rhxf8= ∞ or 13.Be3 g4 14.Ne1 h5 ∓ Black is attacking, while White is doing nothing.}) 12. Ne1 {There was no reason not to play [b4]; Black could hardly take on [c2].} (12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Qxc2 $4 14. d4 {+- The position is fully opening up, but Black's kingside pieces are still on their initial squares.}) 12... Ne7 13. b4 Ng6 14. bxc5 $2 {Not causing any problems for Black.} (14. c4 $1 {White wants to play [b5]!} h5 15. b5 axb5 16. cxb5 {± The knight is coming to [c4], and then the a-pawn's marching forward}) 14... Nf4 15. Qd1 Bxc5 $15 {The game has completely turned around. White has nothing on the queenside anymore, so Black just should be better with the pair of bishops. Given that it is a 3+1 blitz game, the rest of the game is not too interesting. The same will apply to all other blitz games.} 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. Qd2 f5 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Na5 Bxa5 20. Qxa5 Rd5 21. Qb4 a5 22. Qe7 Qe6 23. Qxe6+ Nxe6 24. f3 b6 25. h3 h5 26. g4 Bg6 27. Ng2 Rd7 28. Re1 Rf7 29. Rf1 hxg4 30. hxg4 Rh3 31. Ne1 Rg3+ 32. Kh2 Rxg4 33. fxg4 Rxf1 34. Kg2 Rf8 35. Nf3 e4 36. Ne5 Be8 37. dxe4 Nf4+ 38. Kg3 Ne2+ 39. Kg2 Nc3 40. Bxg5 Nxe4 41. Be3 Ba4 42. Rc1 Nc3 43. g5 Re8 44. Bf4 Ne2 45. Re1 Nxf4+ 46. Kg3 Ng6 47. Kg4 Nxe5+ 48. Kf5 Bd7+ 49. Kf6 Rf8+ 50. Kg7 Rf5 51. g6 Nxg6 52. Kxg6 Rc5 53. Rc1 Bf5+ 54. Kf6 Bxc2 55. Ke7 b5 56. a4 b4 57. Re1 b3 58. Rg1 b2 59. Rg8+ Kb7 60. Rg1 b1=Q 61. Rg6 Bxg6 0-1

