1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. O-O Ng6 6. c3 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. d4 Bg4 9. dxe5 Bxf3 {I messed up this line like at least 30 times in my online games, and even when I once checked it, I kept on messing it up. Then, in one rapid game, finally White took with [gxf3]! which just looks so counterintuitive, since the trade of the queens is not a given yet. In any case, I was struggling in that game, but you can easily try this move even in OTB games. The upside is very big compared to the risk. Nevertheless, it is not the course's recommendation because after 11.gxf3, White has some pressure.} 10. Qxf3 $2 (10. gxf3 $1 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ngxe5 12. Bf4 {⩲}) 10... Qxf3 11. gxf3 Ngxe5 $15 {Compared to the line with 10.gxf3!, White is missing one move, which is [Rd1], and that would be stopping ...[O-O-O]. This is what you will get in online games 95% of the time in this line. Black is already better.} 12. Bf4 (12. Kg2 O-O-O 13. Nd2 Nd3 14. Ne4 Be7 {⩱ Black is clearly better; it is tough for White to develop the [c1]-bishop.}) 12... O-O-O {[%cal Re5f3,Re5d3,Yd3f4,Yd3b2] With threats like ...[Nxf3] and ...[Nd3], White has no good defence here.} (12... Nxf3+ $2 13. Kg2 Nh4+ 14. Kh3 {∞ White is taking back the pawn on [c7].}) 13. Bxc6 (13. Nd2 Rxd2 $1 {Winning two pieces for the rook.} 14. Bxd2 Nxf3+ 15. Kg2 Nxd2 {-+}) (13. Kg2 Nd3 {-+ Double attack on [f4] and [c1].}) 13... Nxc6 $17 {[%csl Yf2,Yf3] Black has a much better structure.} 14. Nd2 Bd6 (14... Ne5 $1 {This was even better.} 15. Bxe5 Rxd2 {and ...[Bc5] is next.}) 15. Be3 Ne5 16. Rad1 Rhe8 {It is good to stop here. The mistakes are coming soon. 🙂} 17. Kg2 Re6 18. Ne4 Rg6+ 19. Ng3 Rf6 20. Bg5 Rxf3 21. Bxd8 Kxd8 22. Rfe1 Rd3 23. Nf5 Kd7 24. Nxd6 cxd6 25. Rxd3 Nxd3 26. Rb1 Ke6 27. Kf3 Ke5 28. Ke3 Nf4 29. Rd1 Ne6 30. a4 f5 31. a5 g5 32. b4 g4 33. Re1 Ng5 34. f4+ gxf3 35. h4 Ne4 36. Kxf3 d5 37. Ke3 Nxc3 38. Kd3+ Ne4 39. Rc1 f4 40. Rc7 f3 41. Rf7 f2 42. Ke2 d4 43. Rxh7 d3+ 44. Kf1 d2 45. Re7+ Kd5 46. Rd7+ Nd6 47. Kxf2 