{Actually, there is not much interesting in this game; it is mainly interesting because of the opponent. 🙂} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nb6 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. d4 {This was not prep from Kramnik; he spent like 10 seconds on this move.} e4 9. Re1 f5 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. c4 O-O 12. c5 exf3 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. d5 {This is all in the course, but I didn't know it at all, so I was spending time in all the moves after move 8. I spent already almost 2 minutes here, and he was also spending quite a bit of time.} Qg6 {Also completely fine for Black.} (14... h6 $1 {is the course.}) 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Qxf3 (16. Bd3 {This was probably somewhat better, but in any case, White doesn't have more than just compensation for the pawn.} Qxg5 17. Qxf3 {∞}) 16... cxb5 17. Be7 $6 {The bishop is somewhat misplaced here.} (17. Bf4 c6 18. Nc3 Bd7 19. a4 {∞ Black's extra pawn is almost meaningless. White is okay here.}) 17... Rf7 18. Nc3 Bd7 19. Bc5 Bc6 20. Qg3 Qxg3 $2 {It is a bad move, of course, but it was still a huge achievement to lose this game from an extra pawn endgame. 🙂} (20... Qh5 {⩱ This was the way to pose more problems for Black. ...[f4] is the threat.}) 21. hxg3 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Bxe8 23. b3 a6 24. Re1 Bc6 25. f3 h6 26. Kf2 Nd7 27. Re8+ Kh7 28. Bd4 Nc5 29. Re3 Nd7 30. Re6 Bb7 31. b4 Nf8 32. Re8 Nd7 33. a3 Nb6 34. Bxb6 cxb6 35. Ne2 Rc7 36. Nd4 Bd5 37. Nxf5 Rc2+ 38. Re2 Rc3 39. Re7 Kg6 40. g4 Kf6 41. Rxg7 Be6 42. Rb7 Bxf5 43. gxf5 Kxf5 44. Rxb6 Rxa3 45. Rxh6 Ra4 46. Rh5+ Kf6 47. Rh4 a5 48. Rf4+ Kg5 49. Rg4+ Kf6 50. bxa5 Rxa5 51. Rb4 Ke5 52. g4 Kd5 53. Kg3 Kc5 54. Rb1 b4 55. g5 Kc4 56. Kg4 b3 57. f4 Ra2 58. g6 Rg2+ 59. Kf5 b2 60. Kf6 Kd5 61. g7 Ke4 62. Rxb2 Rxb2 63. g8=Q Rf2 64. Qc4+ Ke3 65. Kf5 Rf3 66. Qe4+ Kf2 67. Qxf3+ Kxf3 68. Kg5 1-0

