1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. d3 h6 {Just didn't know the line! [Bg5] looked threatening.} (5... O-O $1 {is the course.}) 6. a3 a6 7. Ba4 (7. Bc4 Bc5 {is another line.}) 7... Bc5 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Be3 Bd6 {Even though it is logical to keep the bishop pair, it is too slow here.} (9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qe7 {Black doesn't have too many problems with options of castling either side.}) 10. h3 (10. d4 $1 {Since Black has lost quite a bit of time, this move would have been strong.} Ng4 11. dxe5 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Be7 {∞ Black should have compensation, but maybe not enough for equality. 10...exd4 11.Qxd4 Be7 12.Qxd8+ Bxd8 ⩲ This is clearly a much worse version of the usual Exchange Ruy Lopez endgames for Black, since the normal setup is far away.}) 10... c5 {[%cal Yc5d4,Ye5d4] Now it is quite okay for Black.} 11. Qd2 Be6 {Mainly put this game into this selection because of this position. With potential targets on both sides the [h3] and [a3]-pawns castling is not so easy for White!} 12. g4 {[%cal Rh6h5] Leading to a sharp position, with missed opportunities for both sides.} (12. O-O-O $6 b5 $1 {Black's attack can be very quick with ...[a5]-...[b4].}) (12. O-O $6 Qe7 {Black will castle long and then start attacking with ...[g5]-...[g4].}) 12... Qd7 13. Nh4 h5 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. O-O-O hxg4 16. hxg4 Rxh1 17. Rxh1 Nxg4 18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. Rh8+ Bf8 20. Nxg7+ Ke7 21. Qg5+ Kd6 (21... f6 $4 22. Qg6 Kd6 23. Nf5+ $1 Bxf5 24. exf5 {+-}) 22. Nf5+ Bxf5 23. Rxf8 Rxf8 $4 (23... f6 $1 24. Qg8 Be6 {-+}) 24. exf5 Qc6 25. Ne4+ Kd7 26. Qxg4 f6 27. Qg7+ Ke8 28. b4 b6 29. Kb2 Rf7 30. Qg6 Kf8 31. Ng5 Re7 32. Nh7+ Rxh7 33. Qxh7 Qd6 34. Qh8+ Kf7 35. Qc8 b5 36. Qb7 Ke7 37. Kb3 Kd8 38. Qe4 c6 39. Kc3 a5 40. f4 axb4+ 41. axb4 exf4 42. Qd4 Kc7 43. Qa7+ Kd8 44. Qa8+ Kc7 45. Qa7+ Kd8 46. Qd4 Kc7 47. Qa7+ 1/2-1/2

