1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 d5 9. exd5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bb3 Qh5 13. Ng5 ({My opponent spent a lot of time here, probably because of the} 13. Ba3 {option, which is not working for White but very tempting.}) 13... Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Na5 15. Bc2 Re8 16. f3 {Around this time I also started to use a lot of time. Black has a lot of similar moves and it was not easy to decide where to go.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7b5,Gb5c4]} (16... b6 {looks somewhat better, but maybe more difficult to play for the win.} 17. Kf2 h6 18. Ne4 Bb7 {⇆}) 17. a4 {[%cal Rd7a4] The bishop has a target on [a4] now.} (17. Ne4 b6) 17... Rad8 18. Kf2 Bc6 {[%cal Gc6d5]} (18... h6 19. Ne4 b6 {⇆}) 19. Bxg6 $6 {Probably because of being short on time, White decided to simplify things a bit.} (19. Ne4 Bd5 20. Rb1 {It was better to play like this and see if Black can come up with anything.}) (19. Bxg6 {Ne7?! Nc5 Nd5 Bd2} Nc4 {Bb3 Nxd2 Bxd5 Rxd5} 20. Rd2 {⩲}) 19... hxg6 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ga5b3,Ga5c4] The [a4]-pawn is really weak, and the knight has some squares too.} 20. Bf4 Nb3 21. Ra3 $6 {The position is pretty complicated, and I don't really remember what I saw from the next lines not much most likely I prefer not to comment on them. 🙂} (21. Rab1 $1 Bxa4 22. Ne4 $1 {but not 22.Bxc7? Rc8 ∓}) 21... Nc5 (21... f6 $1 22. Rxb3 $2 fxg5 23. Bxg5 Rd5 {-+}) (21... Nc5 22. Bxc7 Rd7 23. d5 $1 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 Bxd5 25. Ne4 {⩱}) (21... Nc5 22. Nh3 Bd5 23. Bxc7 Rc8 24. Nf4 {∞}) 22. Bxc7 (22. Rd2 $1 Nxa4 23. d5 Bd7 24. Bxc7 Rc8 25. d6 f6) 22... Rd7 23. Bf4 f6 $1 24. Nh3 $2 (24. Ne4 Bxe4 25. fxe4 Nxe4+ 26. Kf3 g5 {⩱}) 24... Nxa4 25. d5 Nb2 $19 {[%csl Rd5] Black is winning the pawn and the game.} 26. Rd4 Rxd5 27. Rxd5 Bxd5 28. Ra5 Nd1+ 29. Kg3 Nxc3 30. Bd2 Nb5 31. Nf4 Bf7 32. h4 Re5 33. Ra1 g5 34. hxg5 Rxg5+ 35. Kf2 Rc5 36. Rc1 Rxc1 37. Bxc1 Kf8 38. Ke3 Ke7 39. Ne2 Kd6 40. Nd4 Nxd4 41. Kxd4 Kc6 42. g4 Bd5 43. f4 Bf3 44. g5 fxg5 45. fxg5 g6 46. Kc4 a5 47. Be3 b5+ 48. Kb3