1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 $6 {Completely understandable. If you don't know the line, it is more logical to first protect the pawn on [e5] and then take on [c6].} (8. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 9. Nxd4 {is the critical line.}) 8... O-O 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 Nb8 {[%cal Rc6c5]} 11. f4 $6 {[%csl Ye1][%cal Ge1f1] It is logical to push this pawn, but since it can't get farther, it is rather a weakening move.} (11. Qf3 $1 {This is correct, to prepare [Nf5].} c5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 {⇆ Black has obviously no problems and is probably the side fighting for more than just equality.}) 11... c5 12. Nf3 Bf5 $6 {Very strange! I remember spending a lot of time here, since it was the first time I had this structure in a longer game. The bishop from [c8] is doing exactly the same as from [f5]. Of course, it can be developed later, but why not the knight first?} (12... Nc6 $1 {Way more normal.} 13. Nc3 d4 14. Ne4 c4 {⩱ Black is just pushing the pawns on the queenside, while White's majority is going nowhere.}) 13. Nbd2 $6 (13. Nc3 {I expected this move and wanted to attack the knight immediately.} d4 14. Ne4 Qd5 15. Ng3 Bg4 {This is what I was aiming for, but it is not even clear how much of a problem ...[Bxf3] is for White.} 16. c4 $1 {This is a nice move from the computer.} Bxf3 17. Qd3 $1 Qc6 18. Nf5 Re8 19. gxf3 {∞ or 16...Qxc4 17.h3= ∞ White has great compensation, and [f4]-[f5]-[f6] is finally possible.}) 13... Nc6 14. Nf1 Qd7 15. Ng3 Bg4 {[%cal Rc6d4]} (15... Be6 {This was probably better.} 16. c3 d4 {⩱ or 16.Qd3 f5 ⩱ This is a much better way to stop the pawn on [f4]. If White takes on [f6], then the bishop is coming there, while if not, then Black just has a 4 vs 3 on the queenside.}) 16. Qd3 (16. c3 $1 d4 17. h3 Be6 {⩱}) 16... Nb4 (16... h5 $1 {I didn't see this move at all.} 17. h3 Nb4 $1 18. Qe2 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Bh4 {-+ or 19.Qxf3 Nxc2 20.Rd1 h4 ∓}) (16... f6 $5 {DidnI dt see this either, but trading the [e5]-pawn and opening the position further looks quite good.}) 17. Qd1 Bh4 $2 {Very strange again. I wanted to prevent [h3], but the bishop is very strange there.} (17... Bxf3 18. gxf3 Nc6 {∓}) 18. a3 $6 (18. c3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nc6 20. Be3 {∞ The position is not obvious at all.}) 18... Nc6 19. Be3 Bxg3 20. hxg3 d4 $17 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gd7d5,Ga8b8] Now the bishop is safe on [g4], White's majority is blockaded, so Black has the free advantage on the queenside.} 21. Bf2 Rab8 22. Rb1 Qd5 23. Rf1 Rfd8 24. Qe1 Bxf3 25. gxf3 Qxf3 26. e6 Re8 27. exf7+ Kxf7 28. Qd1 Re2 29. b4 cxb4 30. axb4 Rb5 31. Rb3 Qe4 32. Qd3 Rxb4 33. Qa6 Rxb3 34. cxb3 d3 35. Qc8 h6 36. Qxc7+ Kg8 37. Qd7 d2 38. f5 Ne5 39. Qe6+ Kh7 40. Qa6 Nf3+ 0-1

