1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. h4 {My opponent prepared this dangerous line. I didn't know pretty much any theory here, but we discussed with Angelika that in such positions, ...[d3] and slowing down White can be played.} d3 8. h5 Nge5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. f4 b5 $1 {Luckily, I played this move, since the bishop would be much stronger on [c2] than on [b3].} (10... Nc4 $2 11. Qxd3 b5 12. Bc2 $1 {Both [b3] and [Nd2] can be problematic for Black.}) 11. Bb3 Nc4 12. Qxd3 Bb7 13. Bc2 $6 {My opponent played this quite quickly, but he just confused some lines in his preparation.} f5 $1 {[%cal Rb7g2,Yd8e7,Ye7h4,Ge8c8] White's position is overextended, and Black only needs two moves to castle long, so this move looked quite promising.} 14. exf5 $2 {My opponent spent around 45-50 minutes for this move. He clearly disliked his position a lot.} (14. Qe2 $1 {White had clearly more aggressive plans for this game, but it was already time to play more solid and try to equalise.} fxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4+ Qe7 17. Qxe7+ Bxe7 18. Nd2 $1 {White should be able to hold the balance here.}) (14. e5 Bxg2 15. Rh2 Be4 16. Qh3 Bxc2 17. Rxc2 Bc5 {⩱ White's position is quite strange and Black has an extra pawn.}) (14. Nd2 fxe4 15. Nxe4 Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O {⩱ White's king is clearly the weakest one here.}) 14... Qe7+ 15. Kf2 (15. Qe2 Bxg2 16. Rh2 Bc6 {∓ The endgame is also pretty bad for White. 15...Qxe2+ 16.Kxe2 O-O-O ∓}) 15... O-O-O 16. b3 Qc5+ $1 {First bringing out the queen and the knight can retreat later.} 17. Kg3 (17. Be3 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Qc6 {-+}) 17... Qc6 {[%cal Rc6g2]} 18. Rh2 (18. Qf3 Qf6 19. Be4 d5 {-+}) 18... Nd6 {[%csl Ya1,Yb1,Yc1,Rg3] White should somehow try to bring the pieces from the queenside, but the king is too weak.} 19. Nd2 Re8 20. Kh3 (20. Nf3 $4 Ne4+ 21. Kh4 Be7+ 22. Ng5 h6 {-+ winning the knight.}) 20... g6 {Opening up the kingside even more.} 21. Nf3 Bg7 22. Nd4 Qd5 23. Bd2 Ne4 {[%cal Re4f2]} 24. Be3 gxh5 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd5f5] Rather the queen should take on [f5].} 25. Bd1 c5 26. Bxh5 cxd4 27. Bxe8 (27. Bxe8 Qxf5+ 28. g4 Ng5+ {+ -+}) 0-1

