1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. d4 exd4 6. O-O Ng6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 {These endgames are harmless for Black even when it is like +2 tempi for White, but here it is -1.} 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Be3 Re8 {[%cal Rf8b4] This is the standard setup. Black already has a threat with ...[Bb4].} 12. a3 h5 {This is fine, but since Black has such a good version of the endgame, it was even possible to play more aggressively and not to allow White to restrict the knight.} (12... c5 $1 13. Nf3 f5 {∓ Opening the position for the bishops. Or 13.Nf5 Bxf5 and Black can win a pawn here. 14.exf5 Nh4 15.f6 gxf6 ⩱ or 15.g4 h5 16.h3 Bd6 -+ White's king is weak.}) (12... Ne5 $1 {Threatening ...[Nc4] and sometimes ...[Ng4] as well.} 13. b3 h5 {The difference compared to the game is that now [f4] is very bad, because of ... [Ng4]. (( 13...g6 is also possible; Black wants to play ...Bg7 and later ...f5.))} 14. h3 f6 $1 {And Black is doing extremely well, since} 15. f4 $2 {is just weakening now, because} Nf7 {∓ It is like the game, but the knight can go to [d6] and attack the [e4]-pawn.}) 13. f4 h4 14. Rae1 f6 15. h3 Rh5 (15... c5 16. Nb3 b6 {⩱}) 16. Nf3 Bd6 17. Nd2 b5 {It was a more or less an okay game up to this moment, and here both sides made a mistake.} 18. b4 $2 (18. f5 $1 Ne5 19. b4 {Black doesn't have ...[c5] here.}) 18... c5 {[%cal Gh5c5,Gd6c5] Trading the doubled pawns is obviously great for Black.} 19. f5 cxb4 20. axb4 Ne5 $2 {It is unclear why the free pawn was not taken. 🙂} (20... Bxb4 $1 21. Nd5 Bxd2 22. Bxd2 Ne5 {∓}) 21. Nd5 Bc6 22. Nf4 Rhh8 23. c3 Kb7 24. Bd4 Nd7 25. Ng6 Rh5 26. Nf4 Rh7 27. Ng6 Bg3 28. Re2 Rh5 29. Nf4 Rh7 30. Ng6 Nf8 31. Nxf8 Rxf8 32. Nb3 Bd6 33. Na5+ Kc8 34. Nxc6 Kd7 35. Na5 Rg8 36. e5 fxe5 37. Bxe5 Rf8 38. Bxd6 cxd6 39. Nb3 Rh5 40. Nd4 Rh6 41. Re3 Rf7 42. Rfe1 Rhf6 43. Re8 g6 44. fxg6 Rxg6 45. Ra8 Rfg7 46. Ra7+ Kc8 47. Re8# 1-0

