1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bc5 6. Be3 Bb4 7. Bd3 Nxd4 8. Bxd4 c5 9. Be3 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 $2 {Mixing up the lines!} (10... O-O $1 {and taking the d-pawn later is the course.}) 11. O-O $2 (11. Qd2 $1 {This is the refutation of Black's move. Black can't create doubled pawns anymore and then the queen has to move, losing more time.} Qxg2 $2 {is way too dangerous and bad.} 12. O-O-O {+- Black can't really castle short with the g-file open.}) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O {Things are back to normal now.} 13. h3 (13. c4 $1 {It was very important to include this move for White. It simply makes it much more difficult to trade the bishop pair.} Qe5 $2 14. Qf3 {± Black is under pressure, because the bishop can't be developed. 13...Qc6 14.f3 Stopping both ...[Ng4] and ...[Bg4]. 14...Re8 ⇆ with a complex game. It is not clear how White should make progress, but at least the immediate ...[Bf5] was avoided.}) 13... b6 (13... Bf5 $1 {This was already good.}) 14. Be2 (14. c4 $1 {This was still the move to play. However, things are not so simple anymore, since [h3] is completely unnecessary if White wants to play with [f3], and probably they have to after ...[Bb7].} Qc6) 14... Bf5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Yf5c2] Even though it is not a trade, targeting the weak [c2]-pawn is also good fo Black.} 15. Bf3 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Rad8 $6 (16... Bxc2 $1 {was just a free pawn for Black.} 17. Bxa8 Bxd1 18. Bc6 Bc2 {⩱ or 17.Rd2 Be4 ⩱}) 17. Rdc1 Be4 {The trade would be quite good for Black.} 18. Be2 Nd5 19. Bd2 Nb4 $2 {[%cal Rd8d2] Not good, but won the game.} (19... Rfe8 {Black still could have slowly improved, since White is pretty passive.}) 20. cxb4 $2 (20. Bg5 $1 {This leads to equality.} Rd5 21. cxb4 Rxg5 22. f3 Bb7) 20... Rxd2 21. Bd3 Bxd3 22. cxd3 cxb4 $19 {The rook endgame should be easily winning for Black.} 23. Rc7 a5 24. Rb7 Rxd3 25. Rxb6 Ra3 26. Rb7 h5 27. Kh2 Kh7 28. Rb5 Kg6 29. h4 Rd8 30. Rc1 Rd4 31. Rg5+ Kh6 32. g3 Rxa2 33. Rc8 g6 34. Kg2 Rdd2 0-1

